<HEADLINE>
NRC FAULTS '97 INSPECTION AT N.Y. REACTOR  
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ In blunt language that was one part mea
culpa, one part warning, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission accused
both Consolidated Edison and its own staff Thursday of mishandling
a 1997 inspection of the Indian Point 2 nuclear plant, saying that
structural weaknesses should have been detected well before last
month's radiation leak.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's statements represented the boldest comments to date
in its evaluation of what went wrong before, during and after the
Feb. 15 leak, in which a corroded tube in one of the plant's steam
generators cracked, allowing radioactive water to mix with clean
water. That crack forced Con Edison, the plant's owner, to issue an
alert _ the second-lowest of four levels of nuclear emergency _ for
the first time since the plant opened in 1974, and prompted a rash
of criticism from nearby residents and public officials who said
that they should have been notified sooner.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Con Edison and the commission have both said
that the problem stemmed from a corroded tube in a steam generator.
But today, the commission cast a critical eye on Con Edison's most
recent inspection of the generators, in 1997, saying that the
utility had done a ``weak and incomplete'' job and that its
assessment of how much the tubes had degraded was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that a more thorough operational assessment,'' said
one document released by the commission, ``would have predicted an
increased probability of tube leakage or rupture.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandums did not say that there was a direct relationship
between the sloppy inspection and the Feb. 15 emergency. That kind
of determination will have to wait for at least a few weeks, as
both Con Edison and the commission wrap up more detailed reports,
said Neil Sheehan, a spokesman for the federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   What the memorandums did suggest, though, was that there was
less wiggle room, now, for both the utility and the NRC to say that
nothing could have been done to prevent the leak. And even more
important, perhaps, the memorandums raise the question of whether
the shoddy inspection work at Indian Point 2 was an isolated case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this falls into the category of self-criticism,''
Sheehan said. ``We need to look at the generic implications and
whether or not the lessons learned here can be applied to other
plants with steam generators.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday might, Con Ed said that it did not have an immediate
reaction to the commission's findings, which were released on the
agency's Web site. ``We are in the process of reviewing it, and
it's too soon for us to comment on it,'' said Joseph P. Petta, a
Con Ed spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdogs of nuclear power, meanwhile, offered mixed reviews.
While some had suspected all along that the inspection process was
slipshod _ and that the NRC had functioned only as a rubber-stamp
of that process _ others were heartened by the fact that mistakes
were caught sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you show that you can be self-critical and learn from that,
over all, the public trust goes up,'' said David Lochbaum, a
nuclear safety engineer with the Union of Concerned Scientists, in
Washington. ``The bad part of it is, Con Ed didn't do a good job,
and the NRC staff didn't do a good job and allowed the mistakes to
go on uncorrected. ''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandums emanated from a Feb. 28 request by the
commission for an independent review of the 1997 inspection process
at Indian Point, in Buchanan, about 35 miles north of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The leak released radioactivity _ too small an amount to be
measured, officials said _ into the atmosphere. There were no
injuries. Still, it was the worst accident in the plant's 26-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   And a memorandum dated March 16 from Ashok C. Thandani, director
of the NRC's Office of Nuclear Regulatory Research, spelled out
just how unsatisfactory the inspection process was in 1997 _ as
well as the subsequent request by Con Edison in 1999 to delay
inspection until this year.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC also criticized its own staff, albeit more obliquely,
for failing to scrutinize Con Edison's analysis more rigorously. As
a result, the commission suggested that the entire basis for
granting Con Ed the delay in 1999 rested on faulty analysis.
</P>
</TEXT>
