<HEADLINE>
MEMBERS OF HOUSTON R&AMP;B GROUP BLAST MANAGER IN LAWSUIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
and JEFF CHARLES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two members of Destiny's Child _ a local
rhythm-and-blues group that currently has the nation's top pop
single _ have filed a lawsuit accusing their manager and the other
singers of taking their money and kicking them out of the group.
</P>
<P>
   LeToya Luckett and LaTavia Roberson, both 18, say in their state
district court lawsuit that manager Mathew Knowles ``made money
from the girls while the girls themselves made virtually no
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowles is the father of the lead singer, Beyonce Knowles, 18,
and the legal guardian of singer Kelly Rowland, also 18, both of
whom are named as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The Grammy-nominated group's second album, ``The Writing's on
the Wall,'' has sold more than 3 million copies and is currently
the seventh-best selling album on Billboard's pop charts. The song
``Say My Name`` tops the current pop and rhythm-and-blues charts in
Billboard.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims that Mathew Knowles tried to ``gain complete
control'' over Luckett when she was a minor by trying to persuade
her to accept him as her legal guardian. He also allegedly tried to
coerce Luckett and Roberson ``to live at his house and conform
everything from their diets to their relationship with their
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was all up in my personal business, telling me who I can
and who I can't date,'' Roberson said Wednesday. ``He told me if I
wasn't a virgin, I'd have to resign from the group. He told me I
made the rest of the girls look like sluts. He was totally
controlling.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, owner of Music World Management, did not return a call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Luckett and her mother, Pamela Luckett, also sued Knowles in
1998 in Harris County, claiming he intended to kick LeToya out of
the group. In that lawsuit, Pamela Luckett said in an affidavit
that she has tried in vain since 1993 to get an audit of the
group's finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I joined the group in Baton Rouge, La., and got on the
bus, Mr. Knowles had me removed from the bus by calling the
police,'' Pamela Luckett wrote of her attempt to be with her
daughter in 1998, when LeToya was battling asthma.
</P>
<P>
   LeToya submitted an affidavit in that suit saying Mathew Knowles
had tried to kick her out of the group since 1997 and once
``knowingly gave instructions that would have left me stranded and
alone in Tulsa, Okla.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas attorney Gerald Conley, who represents Roberson and
LeToya Luckett, said Luckett had dropped the first suit on the
condition that her legal claims were preserved. The current suit
seeks unspecified actual and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   He said his clients have earned significantly less than $100,000
in total, much below what members of a group with a top pop song
should have earned. He said Mathew Knowles drew up a contract
giving himself 20 percent of gross earnings instead of net, as is
common in such contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Conley said it is unclear how much money is at stake because his
clients have had no access to financial records.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also claims the two other singers have received
preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In Dec. 14 letters, Luckett and Roberson told Knowles that since
they were now legal adults, they had the right to terminate a
contract they had signed as minors in 1997. They said they intended
to exercise this right but still wanted to stay in the group.
</P>
<P>
   After the letter, the suit claims, Mathew Knowles, Beyonce
Knowles and Rowland ``went on a rampage to destroy LeToya and
LaTavia and their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathew Knowles allegedly kept Luckett and Roberson in the dark
about their performances and replaced them with Farrah Franklin and
Michelle Williams, also named as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Franklin and Williams appear in a
recently released video of ``Say My Name`` even though they ``had
nothing whatsoever to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckett and Roberson said the defendants intended for Franklin
and Williams to replace them in the February Grammy Awards in Los
Angeles and the Soul Train Music Awards in April. The defendants
falsely said that Luckett and Roberson left the group over
``creative differences,'' the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed Knowles did not send them tickets for the Grammy
Awards, but ``had learned to anticipate Mr. Knowles and had
previously made arrangements'' for tickets. However, they said they
missed the Soul Train Awards because they received no information.
At the ceremony, Franklin and Williams performed with the group,
the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   LeToya Luckett said Wednesday she and Roberson are important
members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't see TLC without Chilly, Left Eye or T-Boz,'' she
said of the veteran R&AMP;B group Destiny's Child is modeled after.
``That's because all of them were in the spotlight. Even though me
and LaTavia didn't sing lead, up onstage, everyone was up there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
