<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES STRAIN RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Ahmed Mohammad Jawad dreamed of life in America when
his family was being persecuted by Iraq's Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in January, a refugee eager for a fresh start. A week
later, though, an explosion blew off part of two fingers and broke
other bones in his hand. Doctors aren't sure if he'll ever be able
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   No hand and no English means no job.
</P>
<P>
   Jawad's case isn't the kind that Phoenix area refugee agencies
are designed to handle, and they're increasingly feeling the
strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program works for those who can work,'' said Robin Dunn
Marcos, regional director of the International Rescue Committee in
Phoenix. ``For those who can't work, there's no safety net, at
least in Phoenix. If we don't help them, they go to a homeless
shelter. And they don't speak English. So, what do we do?''
</P>
<P>
   IRC set aside $5,000 for the year for the occasional critical
refugee cases that need extra help. It spent twice that amount in
just three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have them, the ones that really take a great deal of
time and a lot of resources,'' said Craig Thoresen, director of
refugee resettlement for Lutheran Social Ministry of the Southwest.
What they don't have, he said, is a reserve fund for special needs.
</P>
<P>
   So, the agencies depend on the public to help meet those needs,
which are many. More than 3,000 refugees arrived in Arizona last
year.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Cuban refugee with diabetes whose leg had to be
amputated because it was infected and hadn't been treated before
she arrived.Or another refugee from Cuba who suffered a broken
pelvis and other injuries when hit by a car in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   There are families from Kosovo who need mental health counseling
to deal with what they have seen _ ``ghosts that need to be
exorcised,'' Thoresen said.
</P>
<P>
   Or the single mother from Somalia who is being evicted from her
Phoenix area home. The government won't reimburse the agency for
moving a refugee into a new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet can we have this woman be evicted? Of course not,''
Thoreson said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee agencies can't simply turn away those whose situations
are too trying, Dunn Marcos agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a program to save lives. These are people who have been
persecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, 757 refugees - defined as people fleeing racial,
religious or ethnic persecution or conditions of war - came into
Arizona, accounting for less than 1 percent of those entering the
United States. By 1998, more than 2,800 arrived in the state, about
4 percent of the nation's refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Al-Asady sees the demands every day as a caseworker for IRC.
He handled 27 families in February, from Iraqis to Cubans to
Vietnamese. He was a refugee himself in 1995, from Saudi Arabia .
</P>
<P>
   He says the aid to refugees usually is not enough to cover rent.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a family of three that arrives through IRC. They get
$348 per month in assistance (usually for a month or two), plus
food stamps. Yet rent for a small apartment is often more than
$350. And they generally must pay an additional $80 or so in
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are diapers, quarters for the washing machine, money
for the bus or for dish soap or basic medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department gives refugee agencies a one-time payment
of $740 per person - and that is for everything from rent to paying
for mileage to drive refugees to doctors appointments. The rest is
up to the agencies, which rely heavily on fund-raising and help
from the public.
</P>
<P>
   IRC's Phoenix area office, for example, received about $50,000
last year in cash and donated items. According to national watchdog
groups, 93 cents of every dollar donated to IRC goes directly to
the refugees. But because of the demand from the unique cases,
money is tight.
</P>
<P>
   Many churches play an important role, picking up the slack by
essentially adopting refugee families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some churches are amazing with what they can bring to the
table,'' Thoresen said. ``The resources, yes, but also the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Such help is especially critical for refugees who arrive and
don't have relatives here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View Lutheran Church in Ahwatukee, for example,
``adopted'' a family from Kosovo. Church members found a job for
the husband. They drive the children to karate practice and have
arranged for free dental care.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees will keep coming, and they will keep hoping to find
the American Dream. Some will, said Al-Asady, the caseworker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They start from zero, they make their way up,'' he said.
``They are moving up in jobs. They are going to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like a determined Jawad, will struggle but hope that
things improve.
</P>
<P>
   His wife is pregnant, and they already have a 14-month-old son
who needs diapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think the United States is the mother of the world and
everything is nice and easy,'' he said through an interpreter.
``Then you get here and reality hits. It's hard and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   He stared at his mangled hand, wrapped in a partial cast with
pins where his bones used to be. He looked to his pregnant wife and
young son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made everything difficult,'' he said of his injury. ``It
makes it difficult to take care of the family, to do the daily
things the house man would do for the family. I have to deal with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm alone, and I'm responsible for my family. I'm not sure
what I can do.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Chris.Fiscus(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-7942. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
