<HEADER>
A6541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-24 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BRACKETTVILLE _ Taking the scenic route on the way to the NCAA
South Regional in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in the sweet smell of mesquite, marveling at the rolling
tumbleweed and standing knee-deep in the mulberry and cacti that
cover the landscape as far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Brackettville.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the real Brackettville, the one that has been here _
220 miles southwest of Austin between Mexico's Ciudad Acuna and
Uvalde _ long before Nike founder Phil Knight ever uttered the
words, ``What about trying a waffle iron?''
</P>
<P>
   This is as remote a place as there is in Texas, tucked quietly
amid rugged South Texas terrain and more than 100 working ranches
of at least 5,000 acres apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `Is there a McDonald's there?''' said assistant
municipal district manager Kathryn Letsinger. ``No. `Is there a
Pizza Hut?' No. `Are there (movie theaters)?' No. `Then what's
there?'''
</P>
<P>
   This is where you find pure Texas at its throwback, cowboying
best.
</P>
<P>
   This is where John Wayne once burned the house down, literally,
after a long night of poker and partying while filming the movie
The Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Wyatt Earp once lived, Mexican bandidos engaged in
legendary battles with Texas freedom fighters, four Seminole Native
Americans won the Congressional Medal of Honor in Civil War-era
battles with renegades, Texas icon Judge Roy Bean reportedly had
romantic liaisons, Will Rogers kept a ranch home, World War II
generals George S. Patton and George Marshall trained tank
battalions and former President Lyndon Johnson went bird hunting
every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of history here,'' said Zack Davis, a
veterinarian by profession who also owns the local hardware and
general store and whose great-great-grandparents helped found the
town in 1852.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing you will not find in Brackettville, pop. 1,872: a
place to buy Nike shoes.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most intriguing of phenomena about the only namesake
town in America for Nike's popular ``Bracketville'' television
slogan, which has become a catch phrase for the 2000 NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you count the Internet,'' Letsinger said, ``you have to
drive to Del Rio or Uvalde for anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   You also won't find Dick Vitale, any of the coaches featured in
the commercials or lush green lawns like the ones on TV.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, around here about the only things cropped as carefully
as the yards in the ads are sheep. Every fall, Brackettville
immerses itself in, well, shear madness.
</P>
<P>
   Sheep and goat farming are among the longtime traditions of
Brackettville, although it is anything but a big moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``During World War II, wool and mohair used to bring 65 cents a
pound,'' Davis said. ``Right now it's hard to get 35 cents a pound.
It's just gone way down.''
</P>
<P>
   Brackettville's biggest industries today are hunting and
tourism, with some 30,000 people a year pulling off U.S. 90 long
enough to catch a tour of the 10,000-acre Shahan Ranch, where The
Alamo was filmed in 1959 and a replica of the Alamo mission and Old
San Antonio still stand.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy John Wayne belt buckles at the Alamo Village general
store. You also can buy John Wayne prints, John Wayne dominoes,
John Wayne buck knives, John Wayne videos and John Wayne bandannas.
You can even buy the ever-popular ``Alamo Crackers.''
</P>
<P>
   You just can't buy Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   Several other movies and commercials have been filmed in
Brackettville and Alamo Village, but not Nike's ``Bracketville''
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Approach anyone in Brackettville about the Nike commercials, and
you'll probably get a blank stare in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it college or pro?'' said the proprietor of the Alamo
Village general store. Roughly 50 percent of the citizenry polled
Thursday did not realize Nike was giving Brackettville a whole new
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have satellite TV out here,'' Letsinger explained.
</P>
<P>
   A hoops mecca this is not, although Brackett Tigers coach Jimmy
Thomas worked a small miracle with these ranching kids this season
by taking the high school team to a 16-9 record, its best in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the commercials, and some of the kids have, too,''
Thomas said. ``My first impression was, man, that's a lot nicer
than in real life. This really isn't a big basketball area, but
it's nice they're mentioning Brackettville.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis first found out about the spots two weeks ago, when an
overnight package with an Oregon return address arrived at his
store. Inside was a video of the commercials, a letter outlining
the ``Bracketville'' storyline and some T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch basketball to a degree, but I hadn't seen them,''
Davis said. ``When I saw the videos, I said, `Well, that's kind of
interesting.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Davis has begun receiving calls from friends asking,
``Is that your store in the commercials?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not. And it is unclear whether Nike marketers even knew of
the real Brackettville when it launched the promotion. But last
week a video crew arrived in town to take various pictures for
research. And Thomas also received a package from Oregon last week,
as Nike donated 10 dozen basketballs, baseballs, softballs and
footballs to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never received the type of publicity we've gotten
lately,'' Brackettville city manager David Luna said. ``When you
talk about an old cowboy flick compared to a Nike commercial,
there's a real big difference there. Hopefully, you're not going to
have to explain anymore where Brackettville is. Maybe some people
around here haven't seen the commercials, but everyone else has.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't come here looking for Dick Vitale or to buy the
latest Air Jordans.
</P>
<P>
   As Thursday's regional semifinals were tipping off, no one at
the Krazy Chicken Cafe was watching. At the other restaurant in
town, Barbara's Table, a handful of patrons sat on the patio
listening to country music on the radio and telling the proprietor
she outdid herself on the chile relleno casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road at the ice house/hunting outfitter, patrons leaned
against the bar talking about deer corn and the front that's
supposed to be moving in.
</P>
<P>
   This is the real Brackettville, where the front door almost
always is unlocked, the butter rolls are to die for, some 30
percent of the population is 60 or older and the only Duke usually
mentioned is The Duke, not Mike Krzyzewski's team.
</P>
<P>
   It is quaint and pretty in all its ruggedness. It is boots and
belt buckles, limestone buildings and screen porches.
</P>
<P>
   The only big game is the kind you hope to see while sitting in
one of the thousands of deer blinds that sprout from the
countryside like beacons of life for a town that could have died
decades ago if not for its world-class hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ranchers were down on their luck for a long time,
until they started leasing their land for hunting,'' Letsinger
said. ``They'll tell you they're still ranchers, but hunting season
is what tides them over for the rest of the year. During hunting
season, (out-of-towners) stick out like a sore thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of them come through here with their outfits, their
jacked-up trucks, their guns. They come through here and buy a
bunch of liquor, ammo, groceries and gifts for their wives so they
can prove they were here. It's what keeps us going.''
</P>
<P>
   Brackettville is all about quail, white-tailed deer, turkeys and
hogs _ not Spartans, Cyclones, Blue Devils and Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   The only big dance you'll hear about is the one over at Fort
Clark, the former cavalry post built in 1852 that thrived through
five wars before converting into a retirement community. It was at
Fort Clark where Wayne stayed during filming of The Alamo in 1959
and was notorious for his long nights of poker and partying.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Dean Martin visited Wayne on the movie set and the party
didn't stop until somehow Wayne's house burned to the ground at
daybreak. The gutted building still stands in the middle of Fort
Clark, a testament to The Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The only road to the Final Four you'll find here is Highway 90.
In fact, it's just about the only road you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   Brackettville was founded in this remote spot in 1852 only
because wagon trains needed a place to stop to rest horses and
sleep for the night. But it's the real thing. It's old-time Texas,
and now suddenly it has been thrust unknowingly into the nation's
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of Brackettville,'' Luna said. ``It's a good, safe
city with a lot of history. What Nike has done, it gives us
something else to talk about and to be proud of. Everyone knows
about Brackettville now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like people around here always say, with Highway 90 right
here, sooner or later almost everyone has to go through
Brackettville to get somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Including the Final Four. Just don't come here to buy a pair of
Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
