<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MULLIGANS NOT GIVEN TO PLAYERS AT No. 17  
 (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ The wind was tricky, the greens were
treacherous, and for many, the day was torture.
</P>
<P>
   Only 13 players completed sub-par rounds Thursday at the TPC at
Sawgrass, and they played terrific golf in extremely trying
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult was the opening round of the Players Championship?
Phil Mickelson was 10 over par after nine holes. Sergio Garcia shot
82. Colin Montgomerie, John Daly, Bob Tway and Craig Stadler all
had at least one triple bogey. And did anyone mention the famous
par-3 No. 17, featuring its island green, where a long list of
players could have used a mulligan? Forty-one balls sailed into the
water at No. 17, and unless conditions improve dramatically, many
more will follow.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Hal Sutton was alone and relieved on the top
of the leader board. Shooting a three-under-par 69, and showing
resiliency on a day that tested his skill and patience, Sutton held
a one-stroke lead when the first round was suspended by darkness,
with 21 players still on the course. First-round play will be
completed Friday morning, with second-round action as well on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players were tied for second place at 70 _ Lee Janzen,
Bernhard Langer, Brad Fabel, Billy Mayfair, Len Mattiace, Joe Ozaki
and Kenny Perry. Meanwhile, Tiger Woods was just two strokes off
the lead at 71, tied with Tom Lehman, Justin Leonard, Craig Barlow
and Greg Chalmers. Omar Uresti was at two under par through 16
holes when play was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   With the wind gusting to 26 miles an hour, with heavy rough
lining the fairways, and with the greens fast enough to turn any
lengthy putt into a nightmare, the tournament looked and felt like
a major, and the scores resembled a U.S. Open. But Sutton squeezed
the most out of his round, like someone squeezing all the juice out
of an orange. After a bogey on the first hole, Sutton bounced back
with an eagle at No. 2, then he played smartly the rest of the day,
capitalizing on opportunities and minimizing the damage when he
made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But even for Sutton, the day was a constant test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course was showing its teeth,'' said Sutton, after a round
that included four eagles, five birdies and four bogeys. ``You
couldn't go through without making some bogeys. So you needed to
make some birdies whenever you got the opportunity. That is what
makes this golf course so great. - When conditions get difficult on
a great golf course, you have to be smart enough to know where to
take those risks.''
</P>
<P>
   For many players, it was a day of high risk with no reward.
Nineteen players shot in the 80s, including Garcia, Stadler (83)
and Mickelson (83). David Duval, the defending champion, shot 75,
despite starting his day with two birdies. Duval made one only more
birdie, and his round also included six bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   That was still better than Stadler, who began to unravel in the
deep rough at the par-4 No. 12. First Stadler missed the ball
completely on an attempted pitch shot, then on his next shot, he
accidentally double-hit the ball, leading to a double bogey. Then
at No. 16, the rough got the best of Stadler again, when his
attempted pitch shot out of a buried lie traveled only about 5
feet. That ignited Stadler's legendary temper.
</P>
<P>
   He angrily took a hockey-like-slap shot swing at his next
attempt, and the ball rolled through the green and into the water,
resulting in another triple bogey.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Stadler reached No. 17, people were expecting a full
volcanic eruption if his tee shot found water. Fortunately,
Stadler's tee shot landed safely on the green, and he derisively
tipped his hat to the crowd. Stadler still three-putted for a
bogey, but at least he finished his round without breaking a club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have shot 90,'' Stadler said. ``Good thing I made some
putts early. It was a good day until I teed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods hit his 9-iron tee shot into the water at No. 17,
leading to a double bogey that cost him a share of the lead. Woods
went to the drop area after his penalty stroke, then hit his next
shot onto the green. His first putt at No. 17 from 60 feet rolled
10 feet past the hole, forcing Woods to make a 10-footer to save
double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely is Woods happy with a double bogey. Thursday was
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal making a double bogey under these
conditions,'' said Woods, who has only made two double bogeys all
year. ``That's why I wasn't upset at all when the ball went in the
water.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
