<SLUG> BC-COELHO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPT. PURSUES INQUIRY OF GORE CAMPAIGN CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (rk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department is pursuing an investigation
of Tony Coelho, Vice President Al Gore's campaign chairman, after
an inquiry found questionable spending by U.S. participants in the
1998 World Exposition in Portugal, a project Coelho championed, his
lawyer and others said today.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Stanley Brand, said in an interview that Coelho, a
former Democratic congressman from California, had received a
subpoena from the State Department's inspector general late last
year and had responded with a written statement and other
documents.
</P>
<P>
   An initial report by the inspector general, Jacquelyn L.
Williams-Bridgers, last fall found that U.S. officials involved in
the U.S. exhibition at the fair may have violated federal rules by
hiring Coelho's niece and that a Portuguese bank made a personal
loan of $300,000 to Coelho for a private foundation to build a
memorial at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said that the investigation had continued in the months
since the report.
</P>
<P>
   If investigators for the inspector general found evidence of
wrongdoing, the investigation would normally be handed over to the
Justice Department for possible criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the continuing investigation were first disclosed
Thursday by The National Journal. A spokeswoman for the inspector
general's office, Linda Topping, would not comment on the status of
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, who is of Portuguese descent, has been accused by the
Center for Public Integrity, a public watchdog group, of using his
connections on Capitol Hill and in the administration to get
taxpayer money to finance much of the U.S. participation in the
World Exposition in Lisbon, known as Expo 98.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about Coelho have dogged Gore's presidential
campaign. But the vice president had repeatedly stood by his
campaign manager, describing the issue as ``inside baseball'' of
little interest to voters. Chris Lehane, Gore's campaign spokesman,
referred calls on the issue Thursday to Brand.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's original report cited mismanagement by
the U.S. Information Agency, which oversaw U.S. participation in
the fair in Lisbon, its contractors and Coelho. U.S. organizers for
Expo 98 had hoped to obtain significant private contributions. But
the report estimated that 80 percent of the cost of U.S.
participation came from government money. The total cost may have
exceeded $10 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
