<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCFOOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER SAYS HE'LL STAY A TROJAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC quarterback Carson Palmer will begin his third
year of college next fall, but he stressed Thursday that nothing
could cause him to turn pro following the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be here for sure,'' said Palmer. ``I want to play college
football as much as possible. It's the chance of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said even if the Trojans exceeded expectations this
season, it would not affect his decision to remain in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll still have two years (of eligibility) left,'' Palmer
said. ``I'm not thinking about anything else except playing college
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer will be a sophomore in eligibility next season, after
redshirting following a broken collarbone in the third game of the
season against Oregon. Even after he announced last November that
he would redshirt, there was speculation he would leave USC after
one season to enter the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Palmer said. ``I'm enjoying college football.''
</P>
<P>
   So far in spring drills, Palmer is just about where USC coach
Paul Hackett expected of someone who hasn't played since September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's rusty,'' Hackett said. ``He's herky-jerky. I
don't think he's smooth, but did you see his long pass to Kareem
Kelly?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Secondary shuffle: It's too soon to say what will happen with
USC's secondary. Junior college transfer Chris Cash has been
impressive and it was assumed that junior Kris Richard would move
to free safety next season, so Cash could start at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard has probably been the best cornerback in the first
three practices, and Hackett wants to hold off making a decision as
long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newcomers, however, Cash has made the quickest impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without pads so far, the best surprise has been where Chris
Cash is,'' Hackett said. ``Probably, at some point, somebody will
have to move. I don't know. Maybe it will become obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard, who started last season at cornerback, hopes to remain
at the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely prefer to stay at corner,'' he said. ``(Changing
positions) was mentioned to me. But I'll play wherever I'm
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Denmon hurt: Center Eric Denmon suffered a concussion last
week in a car accident. He will be out at least a week. In his
absence, freshman Lenny Vandermade is the No. 1 center, and
freshman Norm Katnik is also working at the position. Hackett said
guard Trevor Roberts might also work at center.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans will have more depth in the fall, when Carlos Acosta
of Moorpark College joins the team.
</P>
<P>
   __ Who's No. 1? One position Hackett is watching closely this
spring is tailback, where Sultan McCullough and Malaefou MacKenzie
are getting most of the practice time. Freshman Chris Howard
doesn't arrive until the fall, and senior Petros Papadakis is
recovering from a broken foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malaefou and Sultan will be in quite a battle for the next 13
days,''Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ First scrimmage: USC will have its first scrimmage session on
Saturday. Hackett said he expects to scrimmage for 20-30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back from track: Wide receiver Marcell Allmond and defensive
back Darrell Rideaux returned to the football team Thursday after
missing the first two practices to participate in track.
</P>
<P>
   They joined fellow sprinters Kareem Kelly, Sultan McCullough and
Miguel Fletcher, who participated in the opening practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was great today was we had all the track guys,'' Hackett
said. ``The speed dimension is so different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
