<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MCCAIN-GIULIANI-NY     03-24 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCAIN-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN TO CAMPAIGN AGAIN, THIS TIME TO SUPPORT GIULIANI  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. John McCain has yet to announce whether he will
endorse Texas Gov. George W. Bush for president now that he has
abandoned his own campaign. But the Arizona Republican is
displaying no such reticence when it comes to New York's U.S.
Senate race. Aides to McCain and New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Thursday that they were negotiating the final details
of a swing by McCain on behalf of Giuliani in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to doing it,'' said Todd Harris, a spokesman
for McCain. ``We want to go up there and show our strong support
for Mr. Giuliani as a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce J. Teitelbaum, said the mayor
embraced the prospect of campaigning with McCain at his side. ``The
mayor welcomes John McCain's support,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   There is reason to believe that Giuliani may be more
enthusiastic at the prospect of campaigning with McCain than with
Bush. The mayor kept a distance from Bush during the Republican
primary contest in New York and was critical of the hard-edged
tactics he used to defeat McCain in the state.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Giuliani, who endorsed Bush, described McCain as a
friend and praised his campaign during the primary. His ability to
present himself as one of Bush's supporters without joining in the
attacks on McCain paved the way for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican primaries, McCain appealed to independent and
some Democratic voters, almost precisely the same voters Giuliani
is pursuing in his contest with Hillary Rodham Clinton, his
Democratic opponent. In New York, McCain was popular among
Republicans as well: he received 44 percent of the votes cast for
delegates in the March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the trip remain to be worked out, though aides to
McCain and the mayor said McCain would be likely to campaign with
Giuliani mainly in New York City and the suburbs, where he proved
particularly popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do whatever he asks us to do, except raise soft
money,'' Harris said, referring to the largely unregulated source
of campaign contributions that McCain has proposed outlawing. Both
Giuliani and Clinton have been aggressively seeking those
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever benefit the visit brings Giuliani, it will be something
short of a happy return for McCain. He dropped out of the race two
days after the Super Tuesday primaries, which included contests in
New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   McCain lost 9 of 13 states that day, though he has singled out
the campaign run against him in New York as the most unfair. It
included a Bush radio advertisement that portrayed McCain as an
opponent of financing for breast cancer research and a television
advertisement financed by a Bush supporter that attacked his
environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said McCain's relationship with Giuliani outweighed any
bad feelings he had about New York. ``McCain is a strong supporter
of the mayor,'' he said, adding, ``he looks forward to the mayor
joining him in the United States Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
