<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-CAVALIERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAVALIERS DUMP LETHARGIC MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.1996 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Dallas Mavericks put themselves in another hole
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Tuesday night when the Mavericks rallied from a
double-digit deficit to claim a victory, Cleveland was able to
withstand any comebacks from the Mavericks in a 104-98 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a poor first-half performance that doomed the Mavericks
against the Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks shot 31 percent from the field, missed all eight
of their 3-point attempts, and committed 10 turnovers for the half.
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter might have been a sign of things to come, when
the Mavericks scored a season-low 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug ourselves a hole,'' said Mavericks center Shawn
Bradley, who scored eight points. ``You can't expect to do that
every night and come back to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks trailed by 23 points at halftime and many of those
in the crowd of 13,043 at Reunion Arena booed the team as it walked
off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mavericks made a rally in the second half by outscoring
Cleveland 65-48, and cut the Cavaliers lead to six points after a
3-pointer from Dirk Nowitzki late in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws from Cedric Henderson with 1:07 left pushed
Cleveland to a 101-93 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing,'' Mavericks guard Steve Nash said.
``I think we have a pretty proud group. For us to come out and play
like that in the first half was terrible. We were awful and we
deserved what we got, and that was a loss. We certainly didn't
deserve to win the way we played in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bright spot was Michael Finley's 29 points, but he
missed 10 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback was spirited if anything else, especially when the
Mavericks fought back from a 22-point deficit to beat San Antonio,
97-96, on a buzzer- beating basket from Erick Strickland on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer for you,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson
said. ``We didn't come out the way we were supposed to. I suppose
its human nature after an emotional win like that. It was hard to
get it cranked up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Mavericks' past four games against teams with losing
records, they have lost three times.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night against the Cavaliers, the Mavericks were beaten
inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers scored 52 points inside and outrebounded the
Mavericks, 52-44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland moved the ball very well,'' Mavericks forward Sean
Rooks said. ``They ran their plays and executed, Brevin (Knight)
got to the inside and caused problems. If they weren't scoring,
they were getting offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight had 12 points and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Kemp scored 22 points and grabbed 12 rebounds. Henderson
came off the bench and added 15 points as Cleveland made 48 percent
of its shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was pretty bad,'' Nowitzki said. ``We didn't
execute very well; we only had 33 points in the first half. That's
terrible. It was one of our worst games.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
