<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POKEMON' POWER HITS THE SHELVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: An accent mark is needed over e in Pokemon) 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `POKEMON: THE FIRST MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   How long before the Pokemon craze goes the way of the Teenage
Mutant Ninja Turtles or Tiffany?
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is still out. But for now the Japanese ``pocket
monsters'' rule, and Warner is banking on their first film being a
top-selling video.
</P>
<P>
   The animated fantasy made a respectable $87 million in theaters
last fall, but video should be the real gold mine if just a
fraction of kids who paid $4-$5 per ticket shell out up to $26.98
for videos.
</P>
<P>
   Then another Pokemon movie will invade us from Japan during the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   New tapes and DVDs offer sneak previews of it, along with an
exclusive new Mewtwo game card from Wizards of the Coast. They also
have the shorts ``The Story of Mewtwo's Origin'' and ``Pikachu's
Vacation,'' which preceded the movie in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs also have the first film's theatrical trailer, a music
video for M2M's ``Don't Say You Love Me,'' an instructional feature
on playing Nintendo's Pokemon Stadium Game and commentary by the
film's director and producer.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to mention such DVD-ROM features as game guides and
Internet archives.
</P>
<P>
   VHS buyers won't get any of that, but they can look for one of
five ``Golden Tickets'' inserted randomly into the tape boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Find one, and a kid can score a trip for two to Japan, a meeting
with Pokemon's creators, a $1,000 Pokemon Center shopping spree and
a first-edition starter set of Team Rocket game cards.
</P>
<P>
   Does life get any better?
</P>
<P>
   That depends on whom you ask. Pokemon mania is like a kids'
clubhouse with the hand-painted sign ``No grown-ups allowed.'' This
is not for adults, but then, it's not meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it taps into the most consistent kid appeal in popular
culture since the '30s origin of Superman: adolescent power
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon's kid heroes for television and film don't wield much
power of their own. Rather, they fight by proxy with cutesy little
fire-breathers and energy-wielders springing from tiny pocket-size
orbs.
</P>
<P>
   In ``First Movie,'' Pokemon masters Ash, Misty and Brock _ who
seem to be on an eternal camping trip _ visit an island in search
of still more power battles. There, they tangle with the cloned
Mewtwo, a bitter, whining Pokemon, and hear sermonettes about
self-reliance and brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of like the old Billy Jack movies, which preached
tolerance and nonviolence while wallowing in good, old-fashioned
rump-kicking.
</P>
<P>
   The animation is far from Disney quality, but it does have a
trippy playfulness. As in much Japanese anime, weird creatures
sprout writhing tentacles, and humans have huge eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So will many kids when they find this in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Review: C (plus)
</P>
<P>
   1999, G, Warner, CC, VHS and DVD $26.98 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`THE ABYSS SPECIAL EDITION' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years before he made ``Titanic,'' director James Cameron got his
feet wet with another watery movie, and it's back on video this
week with ``The Abyss Special Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time on tape, you can see an extra 28 minutes of
scenes, making ``The Abyss'' a 171-minute epic.
</P>
<P>
   DVD, of course, offers much more. You don't just watch this
film: You study it, via 440 minutes of video and almost 6,000
screens of stills, story boards and text about cast, crew, script,
set construction and other stages of the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron made this shoot both wildly ambitious and notoriously
rigorous, but he got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Abyss'' is slick yet real, fanciful yet gripping, and
truly an eye-popping adventure, as a deep-sea crew (led by Ed
Harris) goes to rescue a crashed sub and makes an amazing
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   A supplemental disc features two making-of documentaries (one 10
minutes, the other an hour _ which VHS consumers can purchase by
mail); three ``Abyss'' trailers; detailed cast profiles and studies
of sets and hardware; and hype about how the film is about human
interaction, not special effects.
</P>
<P>
   The other disc includes the original 143-minute cut, as well as
the expanded edition, with extra scenes identified (but not
readily) in chapter-stop descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Most DVD extras have been on laserdisc, but not all. New
elements include a 20-minute Academy Award special-effects reel,
pitched to Oscar voters, who then gave the film an award for best
visual effects.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs also have three new DVD-ROM games and a computer-animated
``drill room'' for exploring various features.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A
</P>
<P>
   1989, PG-13, Fox, CC, VHS full-screen $14.98, VHS wide-screen
$19.98, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
