<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-II-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA STATE AND FIZER ARE JUST TOO STRONG FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ UCLA was deep, athletic, winners of eight
games in a row and supposed to be the hottest team in the
tournament. What about Iowa State? They were the Big 12 regular
season and tournament champions, had a starting five short of star
power and was the No. 2 seed nobody knew much about.
</P>
<P>
   But after an 80-56 victory _ their 10th in a row, the Cyclones
are the hottest team in the tournament. They play hard, they play
ugly and now they play a team a lot like them, Michigan State, in
the final of the Midwest Regional here at The Palace on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For every stunning lob pass the Bruins threw halfway down the
court, the Cyclones answered with three easy layups as they mocked
UCLA's full-court pass.
</P>
<P>
   Behind back-to-back 3-pointers by Michael Nurse, the Cyclones
tossed off a 10-3 run that appeared to put the No. 2 seed in firm
control with a 17-point lead, 50-33. But free throws and Jerome
Moise helped the Bruins scratch back into the game. The center had
11 of the Bruins first 15 points in the second half as UCLA made 6
of 7 free throws to cut Iowa State's lead to 54-43 with 11 minutes
left.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the Bruins even got that close was because Iowa
State's all-American Marcus Fizer was on the bench with three
fouls. Once he came back, the Bruins never got closer as the best
player know one ever heard of finished with 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones pounded their way to a 40-28 halftime lead by
bullying the deeper more than athletic Bruins. Iowa State's
backcourt of Nurse and Jamaal Tinsley hounded UCLA's Earl Watson
and never let him get the Bruins in the running rhythm that
decimated Maryland, 105-70. Against the Terrapins, the Bruins shot
62 percent as Watson dished out a school record 16 assists and was
5 of 6 from the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who had laser surgery Monday for a punctured retina in
his left eye, was merely human early against Iowa State. He had
eight points and three assists, but instead of highlight-friendly
alley-oop passes, he was forced to punch the ball inside to the
6-foot-10-inch tandem of Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric. The pair,
however, fumbled the ball _ Moiso had four turnovers _ and were
moved around like chess pieces by the 6-8, 265-pound Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa State all-American pulled down seven rebounds and
scored 10 points in the first half, but just as impressively kicked
the ball out to Tinsley, who was 5 of 10 from the field and led the
Cyclones with 13 first-half points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-IOWASTATE-UCLA-TE     03-24 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-IOWA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYCLONES START QUICKLY, ROAR PAST BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-UCLA-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Explaining the primary method through
which UCLA had come down the stretch with eight consecutive
victories and an improbable berth in the NCAA Tournament, Bruins
forward Sean Farnham laid out an intriguing plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to play several different games, at different
speeds,'' he said. ``It's very confusing to our opponents, because
we can adjust to whatever they're doing _ we can run the court,
take it inside, or slow it down and play half-court and shoot
threes. The other team usually has trouble adjusting and has to
alter its game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   To which, super Cyclone Marcus Fizer offered a succinct
rejoinder: ``We don't change our game plan for anyone ... not UCLA,
not the Los Angeles Lakers. We make teams change their plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer's method prevailed easily Thursday night at The Palace, as
the second-seeded Cyclones (32-4) rolled to an 80-56 victory,
setting up a championship battle between top seeds at 6 p.m.
Saturday with Michigan State, which defeated Syracuse earlier in
the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Bruins (21-12) tried to shift gears, they veered
off the freeway. Iowa State assumed command with a 40-28 halftime
lead, and UCLA seldom managed to get any closer during a ragged
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, when you've won 31 games coming in, it probably means
you're doing something right,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said. ``They
are a very talented team that is having an awesome season, and they
are playing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, whose season was barely above .500 a month ago,
seemed rejuvenated down the stretch with the return of forward
JaRon Rush, who sat out most of the season under NCAA mandate. When
he returned, he hit a clutch last-second shot to beat Stanford, and
UCLA had came in at 8-0 with Rush in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But legendary coach John Wooden couldn't have saved this one for
the Bruins, who were rolled under by 46 per-cent shooting by the
Cyclones in the first half and achieved little in the comeback
attempt beyond accumulated a large collection of fouls.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer from Michael Nurse and a bucket by Fizer stretched
the lead to 15 early in the second half, and the Cyclones coasted
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a dangerous team that can hurt you in a lot of ways,''
said ISU coach Larry Eustachy, who grew up in Los Angeles, once
aspired to be a Bruin, and said earlier in the week he thought UCLA
was ``playing the best ball of anyone left in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   That designation might now fall to the Cyclones, who won easily
in the opening Sweet 16 round while top-seeded Michigan State
struggled.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     03-24 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GEEKS _ AND GENIUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Vasgersian, the host of the new Fox Sports Net game show
``Sports Geniuses,'' tapped his pen on the table as he pondered a
question that he went back to try to answer again.
</P>
<P>
   __ In 1977, first-round draft pick Ricky Bell was joined in the
Tampa Bay backfield by what fellow USC tailback?
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I should know that,'' said Vasgersian, a 32-year-old
Trojans alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   He took a few more moments, and the name finally popped into his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Who was it? Take the quiz of sample questions from the show
yourself (see the graphic box) before peeking at the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't so easy, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Vasgersian, the current TV play-by-play voice for the Milwaukee
Brewers, got better than half, and admitted that on a similar
20-question quiz given to potential contestants, he came up with 11
right which is the cutoff when you're asked back for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   No disrespect to him or co-host Lisa Guerrero, the KTTV Channel
11 sportscaster whose tight-fitted athetic gear poses a definite
distraction to the players, but when the show debuts Monday at 6
and 11 p.m., the mind-bending questions could be the main
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   In the short history of game shows geared toward
sports-unconscious viewers, few have really combined the challenge
and play-along entertainment that this one promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a completely different target audience, like the
difference between those who like Trivial Pursuit and magnetic
football games,'' said Vasgersian, asked if this is just another
attempt at a network trying to capture some of the
game-show-revival fever going around.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's previous try at sports game shows, ``The Ultimate Fans
League,'' turned out to be minor league. ESPN has made several
attempts, including one hosted by Chris Berman called ``Boardwalk
and Baseball'' back in the '80s that had a decent run, and the
network has another in the planning stages. But between those and
Dick Enberg's campy ``Sports Challenge'' that originally aired in
the late '60s and now runs daily on ESPN Classic, the sports quiz
show genre hasn't been able to maintain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of networks get on the game-show bandwagon but fall off
because they forget the golden rule, which is the play-along
factor,'' said ``Sports Geniuses'' executive producer Gregg
Sherman. ``I'm not a sports genius, but I have a good sense and
when I'm editing the tapes of the shows, I'm shouting out the
answers and my wife doesn't understand it. `You already saw the
show,' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you just become driven to play along.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, who once worked on the Comedy Central hit ``Win Ben
Stein's Money,'' wants the comedic twist of that series combined
with the strategy and intensity of ``Jeopardy!'' to drive this
three-segment show that also includes an Internet player element.
The format works, climaxing with the faceoff between the top two
contestants who volley answers to a question such as ``Name a
member of baseball's 500 home run club'' until someone is stumped.
</P>
<P>
   The series recently finished taping 65 episodes that will run
through June (ending in a nine-player championship week). Each show
also has a sports celebrity guest who asks questions. And for a
program that couldn't possibly pitch the celebs by its reputation,
it attracted a great number of big names, including Pete Rose, Cal
Ripken Jr., Carl Lewis, Sugar Ray Leonard, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar,
Nadia Comaneci and Bart Conner.
</P>
<P>
   As for prizes: Winners get weekend vacations, runners-up get
flat-screen TVs and La-Z-Boy chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude for the show starts with the title, which Sherman
admits is an oxymoron, and continues with the wisecracking
Vasgersian.
</P>
<P>
   ``We considered the name `Sports Geeks' but thought it would be
more fun to make it reverential when, all in all, it's for guys
with way too much time on their hands,'' he said. ``The show backs
up that smarmy attitude with the category titles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Studs'' might be the title Vasgersian would go with.
</P>
<P>
   In the same league with Joe Buck, Chip Caray and Thom Brennenam
as the future stars of sportscasting, Vasgersian admits he always
wanted to host a game show since he was a kid actor with his SAG
card. He sorta got that when he hosted ``Toughman World
Championship'' boxing series with Lawrence Taylor for FX, although
that probably falls under the category as a show that just smelled
a little too gamy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted something like Mark DeCarlo had with a dating show,''
said Vasgersian, who admits to once being a contestant on ``The
Dating Game'' and ``Supermarket Sweeps.''
</P>
<P>
   As viewers get hooked on this and start planning their days
around it, Vasgersian will have his wish. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Graphic: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOW IS YOUR SPORTS GENIUS QUOTENT? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On ``Who Wants to be a Millionare?'' answer 15 questions
correctly and, well, you become one. Answer these 15, and you'll
not only feel like a million bucks but you'd do pretty darn well on
``Sports Geniuses,'' the new sports quiz show debuting on Fox
Sports Net (Monday at 6 and 11 p.m.):
</P>
<P>
   __ 1. In 1977, first-round draft pick Ricky Bell was joined in
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers backfield by what fellow USC tailback?
</P>
<P>
   __ 2. Christian Laettner ranks second on Duke's all-time scoring
list behind what guard?
</P>
<P>
   __ 3. With what team did Steve Sax end his career in 1994?
</P>
<P>
   __ 4. In Game 1 of the 1990 Stanley Cup finals against Boston,
what Edmonton player scored the triple-overtime game winner?
</P>
<P>
   __ 5. When he was named the Houston Oilers' head coach in 1975,
Bum Phillips replaced what AFL coaching legend?
</P>
<P>
   __ 6. In a 1980 game against the Cardinals, what bruised and
battered Colts quarterback was sacked a then-record 12 times?
</P>
<P>
   arrow!7. Colorado won a share of the 1990 national title by
beating what team in the Orange Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   __ 8. Chosen with the eighth overall pick in 1977, what Sonic
ranks first on the team's all-time rebounding list?
</P>
<P>
   __ 9. Who coached the Phoenix Suns to the 1976 NBA finals?
</P>
<P>
   __ 10. After winning only seven games as a Yankee, what pitcher
won the 1990 Cy Young Award for the Pirates?
</P>
<P>
   __ 11. In the first round of the 1992 draft, the Denver Broncos
wasted a pick on what UCLA quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   __ 12. In 1948, Willie Mays began his professional career as an
outfielder with what Negro League team?
</P>
<P>
   __ 13. Long before he coached the Lakers, Phil Jackson was a
two-time All-American at what school?
</P>
<P>
   __ 14. Frank Gifford made headlines in 1997 when he was caught
in the upright and locked position with what flight attendant?
</P>
<P>
   __ 15. Found with a girl in his dorm room, Ted Turner was booted
out of what Ivy League school in 1960?
</P>
<P>
   (open boxes)
</P>
<P>
   __ Answers: 1. Anthony Davis; 2. Johnny Dawkins; 3. Oakland A's;
4. Petr Kilma; 5. Sid Gillman; 6. Bert Jones; 7. Notre Dame; 8.
Jack Sikma; 9. John MacLeod; 10. Doug Drabek; 11. Tommy Maddox; 12.
Birmingham Black Barrons; 13. North Dakota; 14. Suzyn Johnson; 15.
Brown University. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
