<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE AGREES TO THREE-YEAR CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ With the start of the regular season just 11
days away, the Dodgers avoided a messy situation Thursday by
agreeing to a three-year, $5.05 million deal with Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time in five months, the Dodgers' third-base
situation is settled.
</P>
<P>
   The deal _ which will keep Beltre in a Dodgers uniform for the
next five years _ wipes out the $330,000 contract Beltre had this
season. Instead, Beltre _ who gets a $1.5 million signing bonus _
will make $500,000 this season and $750,000 next year. Beltre is
guaranteed $2.3 million in 2002, but a provision allows him to void
that year if he has 800 total plate appearances during the 2000 and
2001 seasons or he has 400 plate appearances in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Beltre can take the Dodgers to salary arbitration before
the 2002 season. He will be eligible for salary arbitration for
2003 and 2004 and be eligible for free agency after the 2004
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers for the last five months had a cloud over (them)
about who's our third baseman,'' said Dodgers managing partner and
CEO Bob Daly. ``This was the right way to settle this. This is not
a three-year deal, it's a five-year deal because he's committed to
the Dodgers for five years. The down side was we could have lost
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, peace of mind exists for everyone involved, especially
Beltre. Commissioner Bud Selig ruled in December the Dodgers signed
Beltre before his 16th birthday in 1994 and fraudulently altered
documents to make the signing appear legal under baseball rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Selig declined Beltre's request that he be made a free
agent. Subsequently, the Major League Baseball Players Association
filed a grievance _ which was to be heard by an arbitrator _ over
Selig's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little anxious because I wanted it to be over with,
but it takes time,'' said the 20-year-old Beltre. ``I appreciate
they want me here. They showed respect to me. I spoke with Daly and
he showed me he's a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Beltre became frustrated about the slowness of the
process, though the Dodgers said they were impressed with Beltre's
conduct throughout. Scott Boras, Beltre's agent, and Daly met 18
times to resolve the dispute. The final time was late Wednesday
night, and in the early hours of the morning it was settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a sense of security and Bob didn't have to pay market
value prior to performance,'' Boras said. ``We thought Adrian could
make $8 million in this deal, and the way he can make it is if he
performs like we think he's going to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said it was difficult projecting what Beltre would be
worth in his first arbitration year. That projection was made more
difficult because Beltre has only one full season at the major-
league level. Beltre hit .275 with 15 homers and 67 RBI last
season. He's batting .238 with three homers and five RBI this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern was how Major League Baseball would react to the
contract, and enormous pressure was put on the Dodgers not to
overspend and change the pay structure for players in the second
and third year of service. A baseball official said MLB should be
pleased with this contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief for me,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson,
``and I know it is for Adrian and the rest of the team. Now, maybe
we can start concentrating on some more important goals and getting
our act together.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of the dispute also means sanctions levied by Major
League Baseball against the Dodgers begin. Selig fined the Dodgers
$50,000, ordered the team to close its Campo Las Palmas training
facility in the Dominican Republic for one year, forbade them to
sign any player residing in the Dominican Republic for one year and
ordered the team to pay Beltre $49,500 in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The money the club owes Beltre is wiped out by the signing, but
the rest of the sanctions remain. Club officials said the team is
waiting for baseball to set a date when Campo Las Palmas must be
closed. The Dodgers have asked baseball to reverse its ruling on
closing the facility, but that's considered a long shot, so the
club has made plans for players to train elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because of the signing, the Dodgers designated backup
Kevin Orie for assignment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
