<SLUG> BC-BKC-WISCONSIN-LSU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN'S DEFENSE SMOTHERS LSU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ The temperature has been unseasonably chilly
this week in the valley west of the Sandia Mountains, where it
snowed off and on for two days before play began in the West Region
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten weather.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was entirely fitting that Wisconsin joined conference
partner Purdue in Saturday's West championship game by bumping off
No. 4 seed Louisiana State, 61-48, Thursday night. The Badgers'
defense and patient offense proved more stout than the Tigers'
obvious talent edge.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-seeded Badgers, who finished sixth in the Big Ten
race, can now add their first appearance in the Elite Eight to
their initial advance into the round of Sweet 16. Wisconsin
previously defeated No. 9 Fresno State and top-seeded Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin took charge late in the first half and held off the
explosive Tigers, who made a late run but couldn't get over the
hump.
</P>
<P>
   Whether confounded by the Badgers' persistent defense or just
not sharp, LSU committed 14 turnovers and made only 33 percent of
its shots in the first half and trailed at the break, 22-14.
Compounding a poor shooting percentage, the Tigers only got off 15
shots _ half as many as Wisconsin, who also shot poorly by making
only nine. Both teams shot eight treys, Wisconsin's two converts
twice as many as LSU's.
</P>
<P>
   Smith (one) and Swift (two) combined for only three shots in a
half played at the Badgers' pace. LSU surrendered the ball without
a shot on six of their final eight possessions of the half and did
not score in the last five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were up 14-11 when Lamont Roland hit one of two free
throws at 5:03. Wisconsin scored 11 consecutive points, including a
driving layup by Julian Swartz five seconds before the halftime
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin opened the second half by pushing to a 31-18 lead by
the first television timeout at 15:58. Maurice Linton scored the
first two buckets on an 18-foot jumper and an inside follow jam on
a feed from Mark Vershaw. LSU hit inside and then Jon Bryant nailed
a trey and came back for a steal and breakaway layup.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers completed a 10-0 run as Linton hit another jumper
and Duany Duany dropped in a three at 13:46 for a 36-18 Wisconsin
edge. After a two-for-one free throw exchange, UW posted its
biggest lead of 38-19 with 12:21 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Jabari Smith then sparked an LSU awakening, scoring nine of 12
points as the Tigers got to 40-29. But Bryant hit a 15-footer,
Vershaw popped a trey and Charlie Wills scored inside on Bryant's
pass to put Wisconsin back up 47-29 with five minutes remaining. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
