<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FATHER-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FACTORS CONSIDERED IN YOUTH'S MURDER AND FATHER'S SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the Social Security number written in black
marker on a human skull found Tuesday in Alley Pond Park in Queens,
detectives had little trouble concluding that 19-year-old Steen
Fenrich had fallen victim to a twisted murderer.
</P>
<P>
   But when the young man's stepfather shot himself to death
Wednesday after an eight-hour standoff in Dix Hills, police were
left with an even grimmer realization about who might have
committed the murder and why.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn Wednesday, shortly after police told the stepfather,
John D. Fenrich, that they had found his stepson's body, he picked
up the phone and called News 12, the Long Island television
station, to suggest a motive. He said he wanted to discuss ``his
stepson's dismembered body that was found in a Queens park,'' News
12 said, and suggested that he was ``murdered because he was gay.''
</P>
<P>
   That may well have been the reason, investigators said Thursday,
and Fenrich could have been the one to know because several signs
point to his role in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   After the phone conversation with News 12, Fenrich met with
police officers who came to his home after being alerted by the
station, then bolted onto his roof, fired guns in the air, begged
officers to shoot him and eight hours later, shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   As detectives in Queens continued to piece together the events
leading to the rooftop suicide, officials cautioned that while
dental records confirmed that the bones in the park belonged to
Steen Fenrich, the medical examiner still had not been able to
determine the cause of death. Until then, the case cannot be
classified as a homicide, though officers are assuming that will
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is being investigated as a homicide and every angle is
being investigated and every part of his life is being looked
into,'' said Deputy Chief Patrick Timlin, commander of Queens
detectives. Among the possible reasons, he said, ``bias would be
one of the motivating factors.'' Chief Timlin suggested that
Fenrich had a fractious relationship with his stepson, but would
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   During its evening news broadcast Thursday, Channel 12 said that
New York detectives had told the station that they never informed
Fenrich that his stepson's body had been found in pieces,
suggesting that he had incriminated himself by describing the
condition of the body that way.
</P>
<P>
   When police first visited the Fenrich home at 75 Oakfield Ave.
on Tuesday night, Fenrich, 36, and his wife, Wanda, 52, said that
they had not heard from their oldest son since September. But
Timlin said no one had ever filed a report that Steen Fenrich was
missing, either in Queens, where he had been living, or in Suffolk
County, where his parents lived with his 14-year-old stepbrother,
John David.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, a man strolling through Alley Pond Park near
Oakland Lake found two plastic food containers, one of which
contained human bones, part of a foot, part of a pelvis and part of
a skull. Racial and anti-gay epithets were written on the skull in
marker along with a social security number. ``It was very clear,
leading us to believe somebody wanted us to identify that body,''
Timlin said.
</P>
<P>
   In its evening broadcast, News 12 reported that New York police
detectives told the station that Steen Fenrich was gay and had
posed for gay pornographic photographs. Gay rights advocates,
including the New York City Gay and Lesbian Anti-Violence Project,
City Councilwoman Christine Quinn and state Sen. Tom K. Duane,
urged the police Thursday to give the case high priority.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin said that detectives had interviewed Mrs. Fenrich and
planned to question her again. Thursday afternoon, she pulled into
the driveway of her house in a white pick-up truck. ``All I can say
is, there are a lot of inconsistencies,'' she said as reporters
peppered her with questions.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials, meanwhile, continued to search through the
Queens park where the remains were found. The New York City Police
Department's scuba team scoured Oakland Lake and officials said the
search would continue Friday. The Fenrich home, a brown split-level
ranch, was also searched.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were also looking into the details of federal mail and
insurance fraud charges that were filed against the Fenriches in
April. The charges accused them of schemes to defraud more than a
dozen insurance companies of more than $300,000 from October 1992
through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Blessinger, an investigator with the National Insurance
Crime Bureau, who helped compile the federal charges against the
Fenriches, said he interviewed the couple two years ago and
remembered the case because of the way Mr. Fenrich ``appeared to be
mutilating himself for insurance money.'' The charges accused him
of basing false insurance claims on a number of self-inflicted
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said those injuries included the fracture of his
left wrist; a laceration of his left ear and his penis; neck and
back sprains; and the loss of the tip of his left finger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
