<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-THERON-HNS &LR;      03-24 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THERON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLIZE ANGEL: ACTRESS TO BE A REGULAR CINEMA FIXTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In most luxury hotels in Houston, you can't open the
windows. In this town, you can, which is why it's downright chilly
in Charlize Theron's suite.
</P>
<P>
   Theron seems to like it, which is odd since she's from South
Africa and has been complaining about all the cold weather she's
had to deal with recently on movie locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told my assistant that she can now only read scripts
that take place in warm climates,'' Theron says with a laugh. ``I
always make movies in such ridiculous temperatures.''
</P>
<P>
   The cold doesn't seem to faze her at the moment. She's barefoot
and sleeveless. Shoulderless, in fact, because she's wearing a
bizarre top that can only be described as a halter sweater crossed
with a turtleneck. It buttons up the back _ what there is of the
back.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, Charlize, w-w-would you like that w-w-window closed?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm totally fine, actually,'' she says, running a hand
down her leg. ``I have my leather pants on.''
</P>
<P>
   Theron, 24, is often referred to as Hollywood's latest It Girl,
due to both her memorable appearance and her strong sexual presence
in movies. She's warming the screen in the multi-Oscar-nominated
``The Cider House Rules''and the action thriller ``Reindeer
Games.``
</P>
<P>
   She's going to be a regular cinema fixture as the year unfolds.
She's already finished ``The Legend of Bagger Vance`` for director
Robert Redford (co-starring with Matt Damon and Will Smith); ``Navy
Diver`` with Cuba Gooding Jr. and Robert DeNiro; and ``The Yards``
with Mark Wahlberg, Joaquin Phoenix, James Caan and Faye Dunaway.
All are due in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   She's currently shooting ``Wakin' Up in Reno,'' with Billy Bob
Thornton, Patrick Swayze and Natasha Richardson. Earlier this year,
the film shot for a week around Amarillo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about two couples traveling from Arkansas who take a
vacation road trip to Reno. We're just going for a motor jamboree
show. I'm married (in the movie) to Patrick Swayze.''
</P>
<P>
   And then she has ``Sweet November,'' with Keanu Reeves, and
perhaps the musical ``Chicago`` down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Because of her role in ``Wakin' Up in Reno,`` Theron no longer
has the short, natural-looking blond hair she sported in ``The
Cider House Rules`` and ``Reindeer Games.'' Instead she's pushing
long, straight tresses in a harsher blond hue over her bare
shoulders. The color and a cigarette give her a hard look, but
that's offset by a high-voltage smile and a loud, ready laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She's excited about ``The Cider House Rules,'' which is up for
seven Oscars Sunday night, including best picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a hit before, that's really the god's
honest truth,'' she says. ``So the support it's been getting from
critics, that to me was more than enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Cider House Rules,'' set during World War II, Theron
plays Candy, a mature young woman who takes emotional and physical
comfort in a romance with a naive youth (Tobey Maguire) working on
an apple farm. This is after she learns that her fiance has been
badly injured overseas and won't get home for a long time, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard film to make,'' Theron says. ``Thank goodness
for (Swedish director) Lasse Hallstrom, because he automatically
brought magic to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just so much of the story to be told and just so
little time to build such a huge relationship, especially between
my character and Tobey's character.''
</P>
<P>
   Theron has been thrilled with her directors of late, including
Hallstrom, John Frankenheimer (``Reindeer Games'') and especially
Redford on ``The Legend of Bagger Vance.'' She found that
experience memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' she says. ``Frightening, very frightening, in the
sense that it was the first time that somebody (Redford) that I
find to be such a legend to this industry, completely just offered
me the part _ just trusted me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one meeting with him. I never read anything to him. We
talked about 20 minutes. The next day I got this offer, and before
I knew it I was working on the film. It was frightening because I'm
so used to having to go in and prove myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Theron has kept busy since she made her first big impression on
the screen four years ago in a small but eye-catching part as the
sexual and murderous Helga in ``2 Days in the Valley.'' It was only
a few films before she moved into leading roles (``The Devil's
Advocate,`` with Al Pacino and Reeves; ``Mighty Joe Young`` with a
giant ape; and ``The Astronaut's Wife,`` with Johnny Depp).
</P>
<P>
   Her face has made her a frequent magazine cover subject, which
adds to the belief that she was a supermodel before coming to
Hollywood. In fact, she had not done a lot of modeling but was
actually aiming for a career as a ballet dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Theron, born and raised on a farm near a small suburb of
Johannesburg, trained in ballet from a young age. She did some
modeling as a teen in Milan, but soon headed to New York to work
with the Joffrey Ballet. But that didn't last long, either, due to
a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Family tragedy struck in Theron's mid-teens: Her mother shot and
killed her father. The incident was ruled self-defense by
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Theron is close to her mother, frequently mentioning her during
interviews and often traveling with her.
</P>
<P>
   Theron, who spends most of her time in the United States, was
involved in a South African controversy last year. While back on a
short visit, she did an anti-rape commercial (South Africa has a
high incidence of rape) that was banned there as discriminatory
against men. However, the decision was later overturned, and the ad
ran.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Theron was ``discovered'' for the movies is a
classic Hollywood tale. When a bank cashier would not cash a check
for her, Theron created enough of a scene to catch the eye of a
talent agent in line behind her. He gave her a card, and soon after
she was in ``2 Days in the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   As busy as Theron has been, she insists she could have been a
lot busier if she had taken all the roles she has been offered
instead of holding out for chances to work with high-profile
directors. She's convinced that decision has helped move her along
the path from movie It Girl toward recognized actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody once told me _ and it's always stayed in the back of
my head _ that Mick Jagger once said that he made a career out of
saying `no,''' Theron says. ``Something about that I liked. And I
have said `no' many times, especially early in my career when a lot
of people thought I was completely out of my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky in that the work I really wanted came my way, even
though I was never thought of (first). I had to go in and prove
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can only make the decision if you have the options in
front of you. I've been lucky to have a lot of interesting material
come my way and make a decision on what will make me grow as an
actress and make me feel challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
