<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE NARROWLY PASSES SPENDING PLAN WITH $150 BILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House adopted a Republican budget plan on
Friday morning that would cut taxes by at least $150 billion over
the next five years, provide more money for the military and
education and cut spending on most other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 211-207, largely along party lines, and came after
Republican leaders scrambled to avert defections by a bloc of
conservatives who said the plan would allow too much spending.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the plan, a nonbinding blueprint that sets the
broad parameters for tax and spending bills, was a balanced
approach that provided enough money for national priorities while
restraining the overall growth of government and returning a
substantial portion of the projected federal budget surplus to
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which because it is not a law is not subject to
veto, calls for total government spending authority next year of
$1.85 trillion, an increase of 3 percent over this year. It would
increase Pentagon spending by 6 percent, to $307.3 billion, and
would effectively require cutbacks in most other categories of
general government operations after taking account of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether we're going to advance the reform
agenda in Washington,'' said Rep. John R. Kasich, the Ohio
Republican who is chairman of the House Budget Committee, picking
up a theme from his party's expected presidential nominee, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that the plan would force unacceptable cuts in
programs from Head Start to the Drug Enforcement Administration,
that it did nothing to secure the long-term solvency of Social
Security and Medicare, and that it also risked plunging the budget
back into deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican budget sacrifices fiscal responsibility on the
altar of massive tax cuts,'' said Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
the Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob J. Lew, the White House budget director, said in a letter
to congressional leaders that the Clinton administration believed
the House budget was ``fundamentally flawed and fails to provide a
balanced and workable economic plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The House defeated five alternative budget plans, including one
backed by the Democratic leadership and another offered by a group
of conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties supported using the surplus generated by the Social
Security system _ estimated at $2.3 trillion over the next decade _
only to reduce the part of the national debt held by the public in
the form of Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways the debate was a replay of last year's budget
battle, when Republicans passed a $792 billion, 10-year tax cut
that was vetoed by President Clinton. And just like last year,
Republican leaders in the House struggled to hold their slim
majority together for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal conservatives said the measure did too little to guard
against end-of-session surges in spending. Republican members of
the appropriations committees that draw up spending bills warned
that the spending levels contained in the budget might be
unrealistically low.
</P>
<P>
   The internal problems Republicans faced in the House were
mirrored in the Senate, where a group of conservatives led by Sen.
Phil Gramm of Texas continued to block a vote in the Senate Budget
Committee on the Senate's own version of the budget. Gramm wants
the budget to contain less spending and more tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the House also found themselves in the awkward
situation of passing a budget that calls for a smaller tax cut than
the one advocated by Bush in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would cut taxes by $483 billion over the five years
starting in 2002, and by about $300 billion during the five-year
period, starting next year, covered by the House budget plan. The
House plan calls for at least $150 billion in tax cuts, and as much
as $240 billion if the projected surplus continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats used the unwillingness of the House leadership to
embrace the Bush tax plan to buttress their argument that the Texas
governor's proposal is excessive even by the standards of his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the partisan wrangling was over the one-sixth of the
budget that goes to general domestic spending outside of Social
Security, Medicare and the Pentagon. The Republican plan would hold
that so-called nonmilitary discretionary spending to $289.2 billion
next year, less than a billion dollars more than this year and not
nearly enough to keep up with the effects of inflation. Democrats
proposed $309 billion in nonmilitary discretionary spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would increase spending in a few categories,
like education, where spending would rise to $56.8 billion next
year, an increase of 27.6 percent. But there would be deep cuts in
most other categories after accounting for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John M. Spratt Jr. of South Carolina, the senior Democrat
on the House Budget Committee, said the Republican plan would hold
non-defense discretionary spending $114 billion below what is
needed to keep pace with inflation over the next five years. And he
said the entire Republican approach was unrealistic because it
failed to acknowledge that even the Republican-led Congress had
ultimately passed spending bills each year that increased spending
above the rate of inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
