<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-I-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS STAGE RALLY AND DEFEAT SYRACUSE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Michigan State's sharpshooters, Charlie
Bell and Morris Peterson, combined for eight points in the first
half, and the scoreboard showed that Syracuse was poised to upset
the top-seeded Spartans in the Midwest Regional Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But all it took after intermission were flicks of their left
wrists and the omnipresent A.J. Granger to put back their misses to
turn a 10-point halftime deficit into an impressive 75-58 victory
over the fourth-seeded Orangemen and a trip to the regional final
here at the Palace, which is only an 80-minute drive from their
East Lansing campus.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, the senior from Flint, showed Bell, the junior from
the same industrial hometown, how to beat back the Syracuse
challenge _ by shooting often and confidently. The 6-foot-8-inch
forward's 16 second-half points _ including 4 of 6 from the 3-point
arc _ twice earlier had trimmed what once were runaway leads for
the Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
   But with 6 minutes 11 seconds remaining, Bell hit a 24-foot
3-pointer to tie at 58-58 and and followed it with a 16-footer to
give the Spartans their first lead since the opening moments of the
game, 60-58. When Peterson, who finished with 21, dropped his own
bomb from 3-point land to make it 63-58 the Spartans were off and
running _ scoring the last 17 points of the game and sending the
Orangemen home.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Orangemen (26-6) withstood an early
Spartan scoring outburst only have to do it again midway through
the second half. Trailing by 40-26, the Spartans (29-7) hit four
consecutive 3-pointers in the span of 1:56 _ two of them by Mateen
Cleaves who was blanked in the first half _ to cut Syracuse's lead
to 44-38. The Orangemen, however, extended their zone to disrupt
Michigan State's hot shooters and built their lead back to 49-41.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson hit a 3-pointer and Cleaves followed it with an
18-footer to pull to 49-46. Allen Griffin, a defensive specialist
having the offensive night of his career, answered with a slashing
drive. He did it again the next time down the floor, was fouled and
hit his 13th and 14th points of the night on the free throws.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:04 left to play, the Spartans pulled to 56-55, when
Cleaves found Granger beneath the basket with a no-look pass. What
had been a difficult play all night with the shot-blocker Etan
Thomas lurking in the middle was suddenly easy, the Orangemen's
6-foot 9-inch center was on the bench after he committed his fourth
foul 47 seconds earlier. Moments later, the Spartans had taken
their first lead since the opening minutes of the game, when Bell
hit a 3-pointer and brought the sold-out crowd of 21,214 to its
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State's penchant for attacking inside with everyone
from skittering the 6-foot-2-inch point guard Cleaves to the
bullying 6-foot 8-inch and 6-foot 9-inch muscle men Andre Hutson
and Granger is what made Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim pick them to
win a national title long before the NCAA tournament began.
</P>
<P>
   Boeheim's team had followed a 19-0 start by going 5-5 down the
stretch, including an embarrassing opening-round loss to Georgetown
in the Big East tournament. But as the No. 4-seeded team in the
region, the Orangemen found their way again by going back inside
and keeping their opponent outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is expecting us to get past this round,'' Syracuse
guard Preston Shumpert said before Thursday night's game. ``But
they've had trouble with zone defenses in the past. We definitely
can play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans came into the tournament allowing only 59.4 points
a game _ the 11th-best scoring defense in the nation. In their
73-61 second-round victory over Utah, the Utes were only the third
team this season to shoot better than 50 percent against Michigan
State.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, in taking a 34-24 halftime lead, Syracuse looked
intent on becoming the fourth and perhaps final team to master
Michigan State's vaunted attack man-to-man defense. The Orangemen
shot 53.8 percent and their compact zone forced the Spartans to
struggle to 33 percent from long range.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans, however, bolted to the fast start much to the
delight of the almost completely green-and-white clad Michigan
State faithful. Peterson needed just seven seconds to drill a
3-pointer from the left wing. Then Cleaves stripped Jason Hart in
the open court and got the ball inside to Andre Hutson.
</P>
<P>
   When the Orangemen turned the ball over three consecutive times,
including Hart's stepping over the line on an inbounds pass, the
Spartans were off to an 11-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orangemen answered with an 18-3 run over the next 7
minutes to take a 21-14 lead and showed the Spartans that hostile
crowd or not they intended to battle. Then they pounded the ball
inside and dominated one of the nation's best rebounding teams,
18-12. With Thomas and Ryan Blackwell plugging the middle, Hart and
little-used Griffin sparked a 11-0 run that that put Michigan State
in its biggest hole of the tournament at 32-19.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, a junior from Brooklyn, was nearly flawless, scoring 10
first- half points on 4-of-5 shooting to lead Syracuse. He and Hart
combined for three steals and limited Cleaves and Bell to a
combined 1-for-9 shooting from the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
