<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-MANAGEMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS BOSS WANTS DON NELSON TO RETAIN GM TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mark Cuban answered three of the most frequently asked
questions about the Mavericks' organization when he announced
yesterday that he wants Don Nelson, Terdema Ussery and Donnie
Nelson to return.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, the Mavericks' owner pending NBA approval, said Don
Nelson will return as the Mavericks' general manager and not as
president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not be named president of basketball operations,''
Cuban said. ``As GM, I would like to have him come back. But it's
as much his decision as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is under contract for two more seasons, and liked what he
heard from Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under contract, but I didn't know I was going to stay
on,'' Nelson said. ``It's nice to know. I was just going to conduct
my business the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was my position to ask him how I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban also said he likes what Ussery _ the Mavericks' president
and chief executive officer _ has done. Ussery helped lobby for the
referendum on the new American Airlines Arena, which passed by
fewer than 1,700 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``T is staying here; I love T,'' Cuban said. ``There's no
decision to make. He's here, and he's going to be here as long as
he wants to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   That was inspiring news for Ussery, who also has two years
remaining on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love working with Mark, because he's been an incredible
breath of fresh air,'' Ussery said. ``I think we're going to do
great things together _ all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goals are the same, and that is to fill the building and
bring a championship to Dallas. And there's no doubt in my mind
with him leading the point, I'm going to be wearing a championship
ring in the not too distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Nelson is in the final year of his contract as the
Mavericks' top assistant coach and director of player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Donnie back,'' Cuban said. ``In what capacity, we don't
know yet. But Donnie will definitely be part of the organization,
unless he decides not to be.''
</P>
<P>
   As for asking his players on who the team's next head coach will
be, Cuban said that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking for names of coaches,'' he said. ``I'm looking
for qualities that are important to the players when it comes to
selecting a coach. I want to know if they want a younger guy or an
older guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to make the decision; I just want their
feedback. I want them to be part of the decision process, so when
the decision is made they won't get turned off. Do they want
somebody that works them hard like Pat Riley? Again, it's not going
to drive the decision, but it's feedback that I need.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Cuban will be polling his front office about the
players. Don Nelson said he wants to re-sign forward Gary Trent,
who has been out since re-injuring his strained left groin Jan. 22
against New Jersey. Trent can option out of his contract on July 1,
but that's unlikely, because he has no leverage on the free-agent
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll sign a one-year deal next year and then he'll be our
\RLarry\S Bird exception,'' Nelson said, referring to NBA rule that
allows teams to exceed the salary cap to sign free agents already
on their roster. ``Then we will sign him to a long-term deal after
we get our free-agent stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are $6 million over the salary cap for next
season. Unless they are able to move players such as Shawn Bradley,
Steve Nash, Robert Pack, Sean Rooks or John ``Hot Rod'' Williams,
they won't get any cap relief until the summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban has said he wants to sign an impact free agent this
summer. While salary-cap restrictions make such a move unlikely,
the Mavericks' roster could change. Cuban said no player is
untouchable, including Michael Finley and Dirk Nowitzki.
</P>
<P>
   ``In business there's no such thing as an untouchable,'' Cuban
said. ``But it'll take one hell of a deal to get me to pry any one
of those guys away from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've fallen in love with a lot of guys, but business is still
business. I thought the world of Dennis Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman was released by the Mavericks after a short stint with
the team. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
