<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-REWARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCARS' FINDER INVITED TO ATTEND AWARDS SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Junk salvager Willie Fulgear's rock 'n' roll
dreams came true Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After days of anticipation, the 61-year-old former singer
finally got his $50,000 reward for finding 52 of the 55 stolen
Oscar statuettes near a trash bin and returning them in time for
the awards ceremony Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences also told
Fulgear that he and his son will be going to the Oscars - riding in
a limousine and wearing tuxedos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say honesty don't pay,'' Fulgear said, as a mob of
reporters listened intently. ``Those are the rich people. I don't
know what it's like to be rich. I'm a poor man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come across gold, you know what I mean, and I gave it back
where some people wouldn't do that. My mother didn't raise me that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Since finding filmdom's golden idols Sunday, Fulgear has been
deluged with offers - one up to $10,000 - from reporters who want
to ride with him to the event and walk down the red carpet.
</P>
<P>
   This brush with fame and fortune couldn't have come at a better
time for Fulgear, who was being evicted with his 22-year-old son
from their home.
</P>
<P>
   While sprucing up Thursday at his favorite barber shop, Fulgear
pondered the prospect of going to the ceremony and getting fitted
today for a tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that,'' he said. ``Yeah. I love it. I'd like to have a
book made of me, my life. My story. I would love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulgear said he hopes to meet Billy Crystal and Denzel
Washington at the ceremony. He plans to use the reward money to put
a down payment on a home, which he could leave to his son after
he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of my father,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulgear came from Chicago to Los Angeles in the 1960s to pursue
a singing career. But he didn't make much money singing so he got a
job as a mechanical engineer at various Los Angeles bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the mid-1980s, he lost his job, his wife died and he was
left to raise his son alone.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he got his reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to local hero Mr. Fulgear, we were able to recover 52
of the 55 missing statuettes,'' said Los Angeles police Cmdr. David
Kalish. ``Along with our recovery came a quite sizable reward. As
we said earlier, now the show can go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Academy officials said he also gets a coveted seat at the
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize his role in the recovery of the Oscar statuettes
and we're looking forward to him being in attendance at our show,''
said Leslie Unger, a spokeswoman for the academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he'll have a wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulgear walked up to the Parker Center police headquarters with
his arm around his son's shoulders and was escorted inside the
building, wearing a dark jacket and a porkpie hat.
</P>
<P>
   He reappeared wearing a jacket and cap from Roadway Express,
which had shipped the Oscars from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. O'Connor, vice president of the western division of the
shipping company, thanked him for finding the stolen Oscars and
took note of his dream to buy a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this goes a long way to helping that dream come true,''
said O'Connor, handing Fulgear a $50,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
