<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGY WORKED ONCE BEFORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; AUBURN HILLS, Mich.  &UR; _ &LR;  To defend Iowa State All-American
Marcus Fizer, UCLA grabbed a page from one of its most successful
playbooks in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins defended Fizer as they defended Arkansas All-American
Corliss Williamson in the 1995 NCAA title game. Both Fizer and
Williamson are power forwards in the classic sense  &UR; _ &LR; 
thick-bodied, physical, mobile, with playing styles similar to
Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Marcus Fizer is as dominant as anyone in the
country,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``He's very versatile,
like Barkley. He can step away from the basket and create for
himself. But he can also post you up down low and go to work on
you. He's a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer is a 6-8, 265-pound junior from Arcadia, La. He entered
Thursday's Sweet 16 showdown averaging 23.2 points and 7.8 rebounds
while shooting 38.9 percent from 3-point range. He's a leading
candidate for national player of the year and has five 30-point
games in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a bigger guy on him, he'll go outside and take you
off the dribble,'' said UCLA assistant Steve Spencer, who oversees
the defense. ``If he has a smaller guy on him, he posts up.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing UCLA's big men have that Fizer doesn't is length.
Jerome Moiso is 6-10, Dan Gadzuric is 6-11, and both have long
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Bruins successfully forced the 6-7 Williamson to
shoot over 7-foot center George Zidek  &UR; _ &LR;  Williamson scored just 12
points  &UR; _ &LR;  so did they try to force Fizer to shoot over Moiso and
Gadzuric. When Fizer got the ball in the low post, the Bruins
backed off, played a perimeter-style defense that emphasized
lateral movement and tried to deny him a direct path to the basket.
They did not use the body-to-body style that allows Fizer to
overpower opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a 6-8 guy shoot over a 7-footer's hands, you have
a chance,'' Spencer said. ``You have to do a good job keeping
yourself between him and the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Return trip: UCLA freshman forward Jason Kapono played in
The Palace last spring in the Magic Johnson Roundball Classic, a
high school all-star game. He recalled scoring 20 or 22 points in a
victory. Cincinnati's DerMarr Johnson and Kentucky's Keith Bogans
also participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing here should help me,'' Kapono said before Thursday's
game. ``I know the floor and the rims and the surroundings. This
actually seems smaller because the Metrodome (where UCLA played
last weekend) was so huge. This seems like a high school gym.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Games to remember: Lavin was asked Wednesday to name the
greatest victories of his four-year tenure. He mentioned six:
</P>
<P>
   The `97 victories over Duke (late in the regular season) and
Iowa State (Sweet 16).
</P>
<P>
   The `98 upset of No. &UR;  &LR; 3 seed Michigan in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   This year's victories over Purdue (he is close friends with
Boilermakers coach Gene Keady), North Carolina and, of course,
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Nice bump: Talk about commitment. Iowa State coach Larry
Eustachy recently signed a 10-year, $9-million contract that could
be worth in excess of $1 million annually with incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the Big 12, when you look at the Big 10, when
you look at the Pac-10 and other conferences across this country,
it's competitive relative to Larry's experiences and where he is in
his life,'' ISU athletic director Gene Smith told the Ames Tribune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
