<SLUG> BC-SHARK-TOOTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, 11, DISCOVERS ANCIENT SHARK TOOTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chatsworth, Calif. _ Eleven-year-old Adam Sadinsky was walking
to class at Chatsworth Hills Academy recently when he spied what he
thought was an acorn. Like any curious kid, he dug it up and
discovered not an acorn but what appeared to be a two-inch-long
tooth.
</P>
<P>
   On a class field trip to the Museum of Natural History this
week, the young boy learned it was a fossilized mako shark's tooth,
believed to be 12 million to 15 million years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first words were, oh my God,'' Adam recalled. ``And my
second words were how much is it worth?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, nothing - aside from its educational value, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   The school plans to keep the tooth, much to Adam's
disappointment, and display it in the library with some locally
found Indian artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Howell Thomas, head of the museum's fossil preparation lab,
identified and dated Adam's find in consultation with his
colleagues. It dates from the middle of the Miocene period, which
was roughly 5 million to 24 million years ago, he said, when the
entire region as far east as the Sierra Nevada range was
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   The shark itself was probably about 12 to 15 feet long, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chatsworth and the Simi area are marine sediments, so it's not
uncommon to find things out there,'' Thomas said. ``Not everyone
stumbles onto a shark's tooth, of course. There's older stuff out
there, like 50 million-year-old crabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Academy director Laura Bell said the school is located on a
Chumash Indian site, so artifacts such as arrowheads and mortars
and pestles have been found before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found, over the years, different artifacts from the
Native Americans, and we have found fossilized plant life, but
something of this nature is a first for us,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the second-graders are going to the museum on a
field trip today and plan to bring other artifacts for Thomas to
identify.
</P>
<P>
   The display in the library will credit Adam with the find and
include some text to educate students about its significance, Bell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam said he would have liked to keep the tooth, but he
understands, and his mother said they don't plan to dispute the
school's possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to argue with teachers, but I'm sure
disappointed, because I found it,'' Adam said.
</P>
<P>
   For Adam, the find was particularly exciting not just because of
its age.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves sharks,'' said his mother, Beverly. ``He watches the
Discovery Channel all the time with his dad. He did a book report
on sharks. He's fascinated with them.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
