<HEADLINE>
FETTERS A PLEASANT SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The Dodgers found relief in an unlikely place
in lefty Pedro Borbon last season and they're hoping to have done
the same with right-hander Mike Fetters.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters, the onetime Milwaukee closer who has pitched hurt for
much of the last three seasons, saw his career plummet.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers gave him a chance to resurrect it and the San
Fernando Valley product is on target after making the club as a
nonroster invitee.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters' spot in the bullpen became official Thursday when the
Dodgers added him to their 40-man roster. It came after his fourth
outing of the spring, in which he was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed Fetters to a minor-league contract, we thought
he was going to be good,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``Just not this good.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetters, 35, allowed one hit in a shutout inning against
Atlanta. It's the only hit he's allowed this spring while striking
out three and not walking a batter.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Nuys native and former Pepperdine star credited surgery
last June to remove bone chips in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked my butt off to get in shape so I could be pitching
well,'' said Fetters, who saved 71 games for the Brewers from
1994-96. ``I came back at the end of last season to prove to
everyone I could still pitch and I was healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sheffield eyes return: For the first time since cutting his
left pinkie Friday, Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield hit off a
tee and said he could return to the lineup Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't have full range of motion, but it feels
better,'' Sheffield said. ``It didn't hurt that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield needed three stitches to close the gash, and he said
one of them fell out earlier in the day. But he didn't think that
would set him back.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Righty Kevin Brown pitched six shutout innings
against the Braves to lower his spring ERA to 1.23. He allowed
three hits and threw 84 pitches. . . . The Dodgers optioned
left-hander Jeff Williams to Triple-A Albuquerque, where he'll join
the starting rotation. Catcher Adam Melhuse was reassigned to
minor-league camp. . . . After signing third baseman Adrian Beltre,
Dodgers managing partner and CEO Bob Daly left Dodgertown and won't
return this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
