r a BC-FRUITFLY-GENOME-SFCHR     03-24 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUITFLY-GENOME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUIT FLY'S GENES MAY PROVIDE AN DISORDERS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Two research teams composed of hundreds of scientists described
Thursday how they have determined the nearly complete genetic
design of the lowly fruit fly _ a tiny creature that has proved
vital to understanding basic human biology over the past 90 years.
<P>
   Decoding the cryptic genetic sequence of the fruit fly, whose
scientific name is Drosophila melanogaster, was termed a
``phenomenal milestone'' that could lead experimenters to new clues
about human genetic disorders.
</P>
<P>
   It also marks a major step in the effort to decipher the entire
human genetic code, which comprises about 3 billion molecular
``letters`` making up the 100,000 or so genes that direct human
inheritance, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit fly achievement is described in a series of nine
detailed reports appearing in Friday's issue of the journal
Science. Leaders of the teams are Dr. Gerald M. Rubin of the
University of California at Berkeley and J. Craig Venter, founder
of the Celera Corp. Their first complete report Friday counted 195
co-authors.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Rubin described how the teams reached
the climax of their work by calling in scores of the world's
leading genetics researchers from five countries for a closed-door
meeting last November at the Celera Corp. headquarters in
Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The teams ``holed up'' for two weeks at Celera, Rubin said, and
shared all their data in a day-and-night marathon with researchers
catching moments of sleep at all hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived on Chinese take-out, we talked and talked and talked
and we didn't sleep. What we had was a regular Woodstock for
science nerds,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit fly, he said, ``provides a dictionary'' for learning
much about human genes because some 60 percent of the fruit fly's
13,600 genes are identical to those in humans. By studying the
genes of fruit flies during decades of experiments, scientists have
already acquired powerful insights into genetic disorders that
afflict millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a century, the tiny big-eyed fly has been an
important laboratory tool for studying the mechanisms of heredity,
in part because it produces new generations in a matter of weeks.
Now that researchers know the sequence of nearly all the fruit
fly's genes, they can work to determine the precise function of
those genes.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit fly is the third organism whose genetic code has been
almost completely deciphered. Scientists have deciphered the genome
of a single microscopic yeast strain called Saccharomyces, as well
as the common roundworm known as C. elegans.
</P>
<P>
   Government scientists, as well as those working for private
companies like Celera Corp., are working furiously to resolve the
greatest puzzle of all _ the complete decoding of the entire
genome.
</P>
<P>
   But simply learning the sequence of molecular letters of these
genes is only part of the challenge. Scientists will then use
supercomputers and their own brains to pin down the function of all
the genes they have decoded.
</P>
<P>
   By comparing human genetic code with that of yeast, the
roundworm C. elegans and the fruit fly, scientists hope to better
understand the function and origin of human genes and gain a deeper
knowledge of how human bodies are designed.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the reports Thursday, Dr. Thomas B. Kornberg of the
University of California at San Francisco and Dr. Mark A. Krasnow
of Stanford called the fruit fly achievement a ``monumental feat,''
leading to a better understanding in medical fields like cancer
biology, diabetes, kidney disease, parkinsonism, nerve disorders
and drug interactions.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Francis Collins, director of the National Human Genome
Research Institute at the National Institutes of Health, declared
Thursday that decoding the genetic makeup of the fruit fly is ``a
phenomenal milestone because of the fruit fly's pivotal role in
research, ranging from aging and cancer to learning and memory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
