<HEADLINE>
S.F. A LEADER ON GLOBAL WARMING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Break out the shorts and sunblock. The National
Weather Service low-frequency radio station KHB49 in S.F. provides
24-hour weather, read by the suave-voiced guy who sounds like
Ricardo Montalban but is really a robot sound machine dubbed Igor.
<P>
   Thursday at 10 a.m., Igor reported that the temp in downtown San
Francisco was 552 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   As Granny used to say, hot enough to fry your eyeballs like corn
fritters.
</P>
<P>
   -- That's good, but Carl Nolte's favorite weather report was in
The Chronicle a few years back, a forecast for ``snot in the
foothills.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The St. Francis Theater on Market, observes Yanni, is either
offering knockoff versions of popular movies or can't spell.
``Isn't She Graet?'' played recently. Now playing is ``Gril,
Interrupted,'' some kind of barbecue horror flick.
</P>
<P>
   -- With the widespread bemoaning of the loss of local landmarks,
notes history buff Buffy Footnote, ``I'm expecting soon a Doggie
Diner Bar &AMP; Grill with de rigueur gruff Irish bartender serving
Irish coffee in dice cups.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Let's hear it for the fifth-graders at E.R. Taylor Elementary
in the Portola neighborhood. The kids sewed a dozen beautiful
sleeping bags from scrap material to give to local homeless folks.
And today San Francisco is a warmer place.
</P>
<P>
   -- On the other hand: A woman is moving some boxes of stuff, and
a very expensive bike, to an apartment in the Castro. She's
unloading her car when another car swerves around corner, nicks her
car, knocks her to ground, speeds off.
</P>
<P>
   A young man and woman dash to assist, offer to watch her stuff
while she goes inside to call police. When she comes back out,
couple is gone, so is bike and all the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   File under: Slimy Samaritans.
</P>
<P>
   -- James Smith, teenager, discussing capital punishment with his
dad, finally says OK, he can see that it's not a good idea, but:
``If I don't have cable TV, they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Happy cabbies? Maybe because they've been to the Nikko Hotel
Friday, where VP/GM John Hutar has declared ``Taxi Appreciation
Day.'' The Nikko is giving each cabbie who pulls up on Mason St.
(8-10 a.m. and 2-4 p.m.) a free takeaway meal and a gift.
``Underappreciated tourism ambassadors,'' Hutar calls 'em.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oscars FYI: Aaron Smith, part of the team that is up for a
special-effects Oscar for ``Stuart Little,'' is the son of Robert
Graysmith, longtime political cartoonist for The Chronicle and
author of several true-crime books, e.g.: ``Zodiac.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A group of Marin fathers take their tykes on hikes every few
weeks. One dad was talking about the scorn he gets for letting his
1-year-old watch ``Teletubbies'' because this will cause his son to
talk baby-talk. Said the dad, ``He  &UR; is  &LR; a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   You gotta love the name of the group: The Grateful Dads.
</P>
<P>
   -- Big Babs fan: Thursday at the Mansions Hotel garage sale in
Pacific Heights (all this weekend), someone wrote a check for
$33,000 for the contents of the room where Barbra Streisand slept.
</P>
<P>
   -- They're steamed at P.J. Mulhern's in North Beach, where Bob
Mulhern says Howard Cummings, GM of the 24 Restaurant at the
Giants' new ballpark, pulled a daring dining-room raid, recruiting
a P.J.'s waiter and bartender in mid-shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unwritten rule,'' Mulhern says, ``you do not go into a
restaurant and start hustling people. The war is on.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Equal time for alleged raider Cummings: ``Absolutely not
true. I don't do that.'' Cummings swears he did not initiate the
contact with the P.J. barkeep, and all dealing was done outside the
restaurant, fair 'n' square.
</P>
<P>
   -- Yuks to raise bucks: ``North Beach Reunion'' Saturday and
Sunday at S.F. State's McKenna Theater reunites Jonathan Winters,
Shecky Greene, Phyllis Diller, Gary Owens, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Owens says, ``When Steven Spielberg's kidney came out, first
four days it did a hundred million at the box office.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Lawrence Ferlinghetti, S.F.'s first poet laureate, passes his
title to Janice Mirikitani on Sunday at 4 p.m. at City Lights. In
honor of the occasion, S.F. limerickist laureate, e.e. goings,
composed the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``Beat poet supreme Ferlinghetti/ from the 'hood known for wine
and spaghetti/gave us two nutty years /then 'midst huzzahs and
cheers/ passed the torch, but we will not forget he.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, that's lovely.
</P>
</TEXT>
