A6587 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-SHARPSHOOTER-ERADICAT     03-24 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPSHOOTER-ERADICATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$14 MILLION TO FIGHT SHARPSHOOTER, A THREAT TO STATE'S VINEYARDS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Gov. Gray Davis Thursday committed $14 million over
two years to eradicate the glassy-winged sharpshooter, a nefarious
bug threatening vineyards up and down the state.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpshooter, which transmits Pierce's disease, has settled
in the Temecula region of Riverside County and has been found
recently in the San Joaquin Valley. Experts in California's $33
billion wine industry fear it will spread statewide if left
uncontrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased by the personal pledge of the governor,
his leadership and the resources of his departments,'' said John
DeLuca, president of the San Francisco-based Wine Institute, which
represents 90 percent of the state's wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's disease already has caused $33 million in damage in
Napa, Sonoma and Mendocino counties. The glassy-winged sharpshooter
is considered the most destructive carrier of the disease, which
has been around for a century.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of wineries, including Kendall-Jackson, Gallo
and Beringer, and other industry experts met Thursday with Davis
and William Lyons Jr., secretary of the California Department of
Food and Agriculture, to discuss the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that not only affects wine, but also almonds,
citrus, peaches and other products,'' Lyons said. ``We are taking
it as a serious threat and are marshaling a statewide task force to
work on the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' support will speed passage of a Senate bill by Democratic
Sens. John Burton of San Francisco and Wes Chesbro of Arcata that
includes the $6.9 million funding each year for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also is working on an appropriations bill
of $14 million to combat the disease, and the industry will
contribute 25 percent for research funds, DeLuca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for wiggle room when it comes to
cost-sharing,'' he said. ``The agriculture industry will pay its
fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   The money will be used for both short-term and long-term
solutions. The most immediate goal is to stop the insect from
spreading, said Karen Ross, president of the California Association
of Winegrape Growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term goal is to stop the disease,'' she said.
Immediate efforts include surveying every California county to look
for the pest, notifying farmers of the risks and ways to combat the
disease, and continuing research into better ways to kill the
insect.
</P>
<P>
   The glassy-winged sharpshooter was detected in California in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The insect is known to feed on hundreds of species of plants,
using its needle-like mouth to tap into the water-conducting
tissues of a plant. In addition to its mobility and its varied food
sources, it is dangerous because of its sheer thirst: equal to, in
relative terms, a 150-pound human drinking 4,300 gallons of water a
day.
</P>
<P>
   As the insect drinks, it deposits the bacteria that cause
Pierce's disease into the center of the plant, clogging the flow of
water through the plant's system.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found some pesticides and natural predators
that kill the insects, and they are continuing to look for even
better natural enemies of the bugs that can be safely introduced to
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
