r a BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2Takes-L     03-24 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR WHO FOUGHT TO CHARGE RAMPART COPS REASSIGNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT, GREG GITTRICH AND RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A top veteran prosecutor who aggressively pushed
to file criminal charges against Rampart Division anti-gang
officers was abruptly removed from District Attorney Gil Garcetti's
LAPD corruption task force and reassigned to low-level work, the
Los Angeles Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney George Rosenstock repeatedly told his
supervisors that by working with LAPD investigators he had obtained
enough evidence to file a solid criminal case against disgraced cop
Brian Hewitt and possibly other officers involved in an infamous
station-house beating.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenstock never got the chance to indict the cops.
</P>
<P>
   After two months of meetings and memo exchanges, he was yanked
from the task force and ``exiled'' Feb. 7 to a nondescript post in
Long Beach, far away from the high-profile, elite corruption
investigative team downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstock, who refused to comment on his transfer, now handles
only routine cases, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got rid of him,'' said a source close to the
investigation. ``He was ready to file cases. He wanted to move on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney's Office spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons declined to
discuss the rationale for Rosenstock's transfer, saying it was the
prerogative of Deputy District Attorney Dan Murphy to select his
own team when he took over the task force handling the police
scandal in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was given authority to put together his own team and that's
exactly what he did,'' Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons described Rosenstock as an experienced and ``excellent
trial attorney. He has handled some big cases for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the District Attorney's Office and Los Angeles Police
Department said Rosenstock's banishment was a significant flash
point in the acrimonious relationship between Garcetti and LAPD
Chief Bernard C. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti has resisted Parks' demands to move swiftly against
corrupt cops, insisting his office has a better chance of winning
convictions on conspiracy and other serious charges that take time
to put together.
</P>
<P>
   Not buying the argument, Parks contends there is a better chance
of getting cops to talk if they face prison time now, even on
relatively minor offenses like perjury and evidence tampering.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Murphy to kick Rosenstock off the team has
essentially put the law enforcement agencies at a standoff for the
past five weeks. During the feuding, little, if any collaboration
has occurred, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   As revealed by the Daily News in a Feb. 14 article, the District
Attorney's Office rejected two requests from top LAPD officials to
indict Hewitt. Senior prosecutors contended the case was too weak,
despite compelling evidence gathered by Internal Affairs officers.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstock took up the case late last year. After reviewing the
evidence - including samples of the victim's blood splattered on
the station house walls, a swatch of carpet soaked with the
victim's bloody vomit and testimony from an emergency room doctor
who treated the victim - he was convinced it was strong enough to
win a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt was fired for the February 1998 beating, but has not been
charged with any crimes. In fact, no police officers involved in
the worst police corruption scandal in the city's history, other
than Rafael Perez, the central figure in the turmoil, have been
arrested or indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Resisting mounting criticism about his prosecutorial decisions,
Garcetti has said he will not charge corrupt cops with perjury,
falsifying evidence or other crimes merely to appease Parks or the
public. In sworn statements made since last September, Perez, the
corrupt cop turned key informant, has told task force investigators
that he and other cops waged a thuggish and criminal war on
suspected members of the 18th Street Gang.
</P>
<P>
   According to Perez, the cops routinely framed suspects and then
lied in court to send them to prison. Most egregiously, at least
one unarmed man was shot by police, confidential transcripts of
Perez's testimony reveal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rosenstock's exile, pressure has been steadily mounting on
the District Attorney's Office to move more quickly on prosecuting
dirty cops. The most vocal critics have been LAPD officials who
publicly maintain the disgraced men in blue should be put behind
bars, not just brought up on administrative and disciplinary
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, tension between the LAPD and District Attorney's
Office has increased dramatically and publicly in a war of words
and blatant news leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The questions raised by the Rosenstock affair resonate with
issues brought up by recent Daily News articles about whether the
District Attorney's Office shares responsibility for the extent of
the police scandal and whether Garcetti has been vigorous enough in
going after dirty cops.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti has been vigorous enough in going after dirty cops.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN SECOND TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, tension between the LAPD and District Attorney's
Office has increased dramatically and publicly in a war of words
and blatant news leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The questions raised by the Rosenstock affair resonate with
issues brought up by recent Daily News articles about whether the
District Attorney's Office shares responsibility for the extent of
the police scandal and whether Garcetti has been vigorous enough in
going after dirty cops.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Michael Kraut, for instance, sounded
alarms about Perez on two occasions in 1997, more than a year
before Perez was nabbed for stealing about $1 million worth of
cocaine from a police evidence room.
</P>
<P>
   While Perez's supervisor was verbally notified about one of
Kraut's suspicions, the District Attorney's Office failed to
officially inform the LAPD for more than a year or even warn other
prosecutors about the dirty cop. During that span of time, at least
17 people were convicted on bogus charges concocted by Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti's office has responded to the criticism by saying it is
``absurd'' that prosecutors share any blame or responsibility for
the Rampart scandal. Garcetti has said the scandal is the LAPD's
``mess.'' He has refused to conduct an investigation into how
dozens and possibly hundreds of people could be convicted by his
office on tainted evidence and testimony without arousing
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Parks declined on Thursday to discuss the Rosenstock situation.
</P>
<P>
   But an LAPD source said the chief has repeatedly railed against
the decision of the District Attorney's Office to pull Rosenstock
off the Hewitt case. In private conversations, Parks has pointed to
Rosenstock's exile to explain the problems his detectives are
having with Garcetti's office, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you had a deputy D.A. who got it _ who understood the
seriousness of the case and said he could win the case,'' a source
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, all of a sudden Rosenstock was transferred.''
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews, three sources close to the widening
corruption probe said Rosenstock repeatedly told them beginning in
late November that he was prepared to file charges against Hewitt
for the vicious 1998 jail-house beating of Ismael Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said Rosenstock told the heads of the LAPD and
D.A.'s investigative teams that the case against Hewitt was solid
and should be filed promptly.
</P>
<P>
   In Rosenstock's opinion, Hewitt wouldn't be a sacrificial
prosecution; he believed other cops involved in the beating of
Jimenez were indictable, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He indicated to us it was a fileable case and ready to go,
that he had discussed it with his bosses in mid-December,'' said
one source, who said he spoke directly with Rosenstock on the
matter in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was full speed ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his removal from the task force, Rosenstock was respected
by the LAPD for his willingness to leave his office in the downtown
Criminal Courts building to accompany LAPD detectives as they
walked through potential crime scenes described by Perez.
</P>
<P>
   When his calls for indictments were ignored by his superiors,
Rosenstock told several high-ranking officials he was frustrated
that his bosses weren't backing him in his efforts to get key
information, including audio tapes from LAPD investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In late December, Garcetti named Murphy to head the task force
and he took over in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Murphy on board, it was over; that became real evident,''
one source said. ``They didn't like Rosenstock because he was
aggressive. Still, he tried to convince Murphy that the case was
ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In early February, as Garcetti prepared for a tough political
fight in the March 7 primary, Rosenstock again pushed for charges
to be filed. On Feb. 7, he was reassigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly there was no (District Attorney's Office) contact in
the Hewitt case,'' a source added. ``There was no activity in the
Hewitt case for five weeks. A case that we were led to believe had
a tremendous amount of merit ... sat there for five weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators were left in the dark on the status of the
Hewitt case until last week when prosecutors called with a series
of requests for information, complaining they had been denied
potential pieces of evidence. Some of that information already had
been turned over to prosecutors before the shake-up in the team, a
source said.
</P>
<P>
   The request was part of Garcetti's plan to accuse Parks of
refusing to cooperate with the District Attorney's Office, a source
added.
</P>
<P>
   An original team of five prosecutors was set up in October to
examine Perez's allegations of police corruption. It was recently
expanded by Garcetti to include 30 prosecutors and support
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 23, six FBI agents were added to the probe at Parks'
request. Attorney General Janet Reno has said the Department of
Justice will continue to review the corruption scandal from an
independent point of view, providing assistance where it can.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, civil rights activists and city officials have
stepped up calls for the Department of Justice to take over as the
lead agency in the task force. Cries for an officewide review of
the District Attorney's Office also have intensified.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
