<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCKPIT-DOORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONGER DOORS SOUGHT FOR COCKPITS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARSHALL WILSON 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five airlines and a pilots' association are investigating ways
to strengthen doors to the cockpit after two recent incidents of
passengers assaulting the flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an airline industry group issued a guide this week on
how to prosecute unruly passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got people trying to open the cabin door in
flight, that's a dangerous situation,'' said John Mazor, spokesman
for the Air Line Pilots Association, speaking from his home in
Virginia last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were designed for privacy and to keep people from
wandering in, not for passengers going berserk and breaking into
the cockpit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a passenger aboard an America West flight to Phoenix
allegedly entered the cockpit and struck the co-pilot. Last week,
witnesses said a man lunged for the controls on a San
Francisco-bound Alaska Airlines jet and fought with the crew before
being subdued with the help of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Airliners that carry more than 22 passengers are required only
to have a lockable door, with no rules about strength, said Mitch
Barker, spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the door is locked, if there's nothing to prevent
people from pushing through it like a piece of cardboard, that
defeats the purpose,'' said Michael Barr, director of the Aviation
Safety Program at the University of Southern California. ``It
reminds me of the door to the bathroom. It's almost tissue-paper
thin.''
</P>
<P>
   American, Alaska, Northwest, Delta and TWA said Thursday they
are looking for ways to reinforce cockpit doors, especially folding
doors on DC-9s and MD-80s.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots association, which represents 55,000 pilots at 51
airlines, is talking with manufacturers about ways to build
stronger doors in new aircraft, including bulletproof doors and
bulkheads, Mazor said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong doors would act as a barrier to protect the flight crew.
But pilots also worry, Mazor said, that doors allow the flight crew
to escape or be rescued in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers who break through the doors can face federal charges
for interfering with the flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bradley, a burly 39-year-old Missouri carpenter, is due in
court Friday in San Francisco for a detention hearing after being
charged in the Alaska Airlines incident.
</P>
<P>
   On a March 16 flight from Mexico, Bradley allegedly threw his
shoulder against the locked cockpit door of the MD-80, shouted,
``I'm going to kill you,'' and dived for the controls.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, there were 90 reports of passengers interfering with a
flight crew, according to the FAA. The numbers rose to 301 in 1998
and to 302 in 1999, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry is pressing for stiffer penalities for such
``air rage'' incidents. The Air Transport Association issued a
52-page handbook Tuesday to help federal officials prosecute
disruptive passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation before President Clinton, the civil penalty
for interfering with a flight crew would rise from $1,100 to
$25,000, Barker said.
</P>
<P>
   One American Airlines pilot at SFO, who declined to give his
name, said last night that stronger doors would not stop all
passengers intent on causing havoc.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to steal your car, they're going to steal
your car,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr recalled that airlines once routinely let children into the
cockpit. Some international carriers still leave the cockpit door
open, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (airlines) never thought in a million years that our
society would get to the point where people would be crashing
through the doors to get to the pilots, which if they do would
ensure their own death,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Tom Zoellner and Chronicle wire services
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
