<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-VOA-PLAINTIFF-SFCHRON     03-24 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOA-PLAINTIFF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 23 YEARS AFTER FILING SUIT, PLAINTIFF FINALLY TASTES VICTORY  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolee Brady was awakened early Wednesday morning by a phone
call she'd been waiting for for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer had called to tell her that after decades of appeals,
stalling and resistance, the federal government had finally agreed
to settle a sex discrimination lawsuit that she filed in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The payment was a record-shattering $508 million to 1,100 women,
including Brady, who were refused jobs at the now-defunct U.S.
Information Agency because of their gender. It was the largest
award in a sex discrimination case in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Brady packed a bag, said goodbye to her boyfriend and her cats
at her San Francisco home, and flew off to Washington, D.C., to
take part in a nationally covered press conference.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, after seeing her face on the front page of
newspapers and on television, she was back at work in her tiny
office in Pacific Heights, savoring the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 15 minutes of fame,'' said Brady, a psychotherapist
studying to get her license. ``It's great. It's exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, she had tried to get women's rights groups involved
but they said they didn't want to step into continuing litigation.
She wrote to reporters but with no luck. ``It wasn't sexy,'' she
said. ``It was a bunch of women filing a sex discrimination case.''
It was only when women starting receiving money judgments that the
media showed some interest.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, she is a funny, self-assured, and, as the federal
government learned, tenacious woman who stood up for what she
believed was right.
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1977, she was a relatively naive 29-year-old writer
working in the public information office of the Department of
Labor's Occupational Safety and Health Administration. The feminist
movement was in full bloom but Brady wasn't involved.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in Mississippi's Bible Belt, got married at 19 and
had no wild ambitions for a career. ``I was raised to be Miss
America,'' she said with a smile that showed off a row of braces on
her teeth. ``I learned to make tea, tap dance and play piano.''
</P>
<P>
   She also was used to being told that as a woman she wasn't good
enough. When she was in high school, she wanted to pole vault, but
her mother told her that girls aren't athletic and shouldn't get
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she was startled by the reception she received when
she went in to interview for a magazine writing job at the U.S.
Information Agency, which, with its subsidiary Voice of America,
disseminated news about the United States throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   The man who interviewed her, Robert Korengold, told her that the
magazine was modeled after Life magazine and would cover a range of
topics, including soccer. Did she know anything about soccer, he
asked skeptically. ``We need to hire a man for this position,'' she
recalls him saying.
</P>
<P>
   She went away stunned and puzzled. But days later, after talking
to her husband and friends, she got angry. ``He said it
straight-out, flat out, to my face, without a smile or
hesitation,'' Brady recalled grimly.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she went through the administrative maze, hoping at
most to get a job and maybe even an apology.
</P>
<P>
   But when the agency officials resisted, she decided to take them
to court. ``What happened was not right,'' she said in summing up
why she decided to sue the government. ``I felt like I had been
discriminated against, taken advantage of, and a number of other
women had also.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to resolve it with them in a nice way, and they
wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband at the time, who is a lawyer, wrote the complaint
for her _ it was filed under her married name, Carolee Brady
Hartman. Through one of his friends, she got a young lawyer named
Bruce FredricksonCQ &LR;  to take her case.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson was able to track down other women who had received
the same treatment at the agency, which had a reputation of being
mired in tradition and bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's suit became a class action, representing 1,100 women who
had been turned down for jobs as writers, reporters and technicians
in favor of men who were frequently less qualified. In 1984, a
federal judge found the agency liable for sex discrimination. But
the litigation dragged on for 16 more years while the agency filed
appeals and insisted on individual trials for each of the class
members.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Brady got depressed and thought about
giving up. ``It's like having a relative on death row,'' she said.
``It's frustrating. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   But she and the women pressed on with their case, sensing that
the government was hoping that they would get tired and go away.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Brady went on with her life, earning a Ph.D. in
English, getting divorced and falling in love with a new man. She
and her partner moved to San Francisco, where she is now studying
to be a psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
   She has a few clients who she sees in an office so small that it
barely fits a sofa, a bunch of big pillows and a couple of soft
teddy bears in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   After trying out an assortment of careers, she says she has
finally found what works for her. ``This is a room where people can
come in and sit down and say what they feel and what's really going
on,'' she said. ``I really love that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the money she expects to receive from the settlement _
$461,818 _ she plans to help clients who otherwise couldn't afford
to see a psychotherapist. As a personal splurge, she wants to buy a
big television and indulge in her love of the small screen.
</P>
<P>
   As much as she savors her victory, Brady firmly believes that
the discrimination she and scores of other women faced still
exists.
</P>
<P>
   Although women are far better off now, she said they still face
a subtle bias that is often hard to prove in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an inherent, ingrained idea in many people that a
woman can't be president, a woman can't do a traditionally male
occupation,'' she said. ``I think it's better, but (discrimination)
is still possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
