<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6592 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCSIDE-LADN-(SLAN     03-24 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCSIDE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FUTURE BRIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Every time he thinks about the future,
UCLA coach Steve Lavin scans the roster and smiles. There is only
one senior, Sean Farnham, and he isn't a major contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two, three, four years,'' Lavin has said several
times, ``UCLA basketball has a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. In the aftermath of UCLA's 80-56 Sweet 16 loss to
Iowa State on Thursday, several players said they will consider
their options before committing to another season in Westwood:
</P>
<P>
   __ Sources close to sophomore forward Jerome Moiso expect him to
enter the NBA Draft in June, but it's not the slam dunk many
thought when the season began. Moiso's February struggles _ he
reached double figures in two of nine games _ caused him to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's a lottery pick, he's leaving,'' a source said. ``If
not, he might come back.''
</P>
<P>
   If Moiso isn't a lottery pick, he's at least a first-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'll leave school, Moiso looked at his feet and
mumbled: ``I need time to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor could influence Moiso: He is struggling
academically.
</P>
<P>
   __ Forward JaRon Rush, who probably isn't much better than a
high second-round pick, did not commit to returning for his junior
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea right now,'' Rush said. ``I have to talk to my
family, then I'll decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Money could be a factor. Rush owes the NCAA $6,525 for
violations that resulted in a 24-game suspension. (The money
actually goes to a charity of UCLA's choice.) He also must pay
legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll come back,'' said Rush's mother, Glenda.
``Another year will do him good because he missed so much time this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Barnes, who was unhappy with playing time behind
Moiso and Dan Gadzuric, said he plans to return next season _ but
not necessarily to the basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up in the air,'' Barnes said. ``I'm thinking about
playing football. I have to talk to my family and coach (Bob)
Toledo, but that's a big option for me this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was a talented receiver in high school. With Brad Melsby
and Danny Farmer graduating, there's playing time available.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might transfer, Barnes said: ``I don't think so. I'm
going to stick it out here.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Gadzuric also is considering a jump to the pros, but he's
considered less likely to leave than Moiso. Two reasons: Gadzuric
enjoys school more than Moiso, and his skills are not as refined.
NBA scouts consider him an awesome athlete with few moves and
tendinitis-plagued knees.
</P>
<P>
   Would he be a first-round pick? Probably.
</P>
<P>
   Would he be a lottery pick? Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Another year to develop his low-post game would help his draft
status immensely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll stay in school, but the word is that his
(European) advisers are thinking hard about the NBA,'' an NBA scout
said.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Jason Kapono said he expects to return for next
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
