<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-24 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ This is how they beat you.
</P>
<P>
   Not with a hammer, but with a jolt of electricity that zaps down
your legs, up your spine, leaves your hair standing on end and your
brain scrambled like a dish of yesterday's eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Not by methodically drumming you out of the building, but by
frantically and relentlessly running you down until your breath is
going to give out, your heart is going to explode and you simply
roll over and surrender in the way a rabbit does to a hungry
cheetah.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the scene in the movie where Indiana Jones is sprinting
through the temple ahead of the giant boulder?
</P>
<P>
   Well, this time Michigan State was the boulder and Syracuse
couldn't get away fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Orange crushed, 75-58. Nothing left but the pulp.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the Spartans won the game but how they won it
that made you rub your eyes in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   By playing the second half like a runaway tractor-trailer going
down the side of a mountain. By tearing through the last six
minutes like Olympian Michael Johnson with a rocket on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally played our game,'' said All-America point guard
Mateen Cleaves. ``We sank our teeth into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, like Hannibal Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tie ballgame when Jason Hart twisted through the lane
to hit a tough bucket for Syracuse with 5:55 left on the clock. It
was nothing but Michigan State the rest of the way. If there hadn't
been a second game scheduled between Iowa State and UCLA, the
Spartans might still be out there on the floor of the Palace
scoring again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State outscored Syracuse 49-18 over the last 18 minutes
of the game and finished with a 17-0 burst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got aggressive,'' Cleaves said. ``We finally got
all of us into the game with the kind of intensity that we needed
and starting cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   They cooked like popcorn inside a microwave, exploding in every
direction all at once. They were Morris Peterson suddenly finding
the range on his 3-point shooting as if he were merely trying to
toss tennis balls through a hula hoop, finishing with 21 points.
They were Cleaves bouncing back from an 0-for-6 first half to slice
down the lane and slither through the cracks in the defense for 10
points and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   They were center Andre Hutson winning a night-long wrestling
match with his counterpart Etan Thomas. They were Charlie Bell
playing through the pain of a balky knee to get his hand on so many
passes and come up with all of those loose balls down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought that all of those second-chance NCAA
Tournament pools were going to be turned into more office confetti,
up popped a No. 1 seed that finally played like a No. 1 seed, and
the madness of this March was temporarily, at least, brought to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   All of this after trailing by 10 at halftime and by 14 early in
the second half as Cleaves, Peterson and Bell, the so-called
Flintstones, were looking like rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Where does it come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it fear,'' said Cleaves. ``It's more a sense
of urgency for the seniors, knowing that this could be the last 20
minutes you'll ever play in this uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   It came from a halftime speech by Cleaves that was part Vince
Lombardi and part Papa Smurf for its combination of inspirational
message and blue language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it was my best speech ever,'' Cleaves said.
``But I did say some of the worst stuff I've ever said right to the
faces of some of the guys. I don't mind if you go out there and
miss shots or you try to make plays and don't get them done. But I
had a feeling at halftime that a lot of our guys weren't into the
game and giving it their best.''
</P>
<P>
   They are a team that seems to need a little adversity poured
into its gas tank to make the engine run. Of the teams left
standing in the Tournament, they are now the slight favorite to win
it all at the Final Four in Indianapolis. But at 29-7, they are by
no means an awe-inspiring bunch.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until Cleaves kicks them in the pants and then the
Spartans kick it into another gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why Mateen and I get along so well,'' said Michigan State
coach Tom Izzo. ``If I don't do my job, he does it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And they lift off faster than the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans hit six straight 3s, including a trio of killers by
Peterson. They brought the home crowd to life and used their own
rush of adrenaline to swamp Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to keep the train rolling,'' said Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   And the Orangemen tied to the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
