<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HAMPTON-ASTROS-HN     03-24 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HAMPTON-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ It's one of the biggest mysteries in the
history of Houston sports.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is Mike Hampton, after winning a franchise-record 22 games
in 1999, now wearing a New York Mets uniform? All sorts of theories
exist, ranging from the thought-provoking to the ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Was it all about money? Probably not, since the two sides didn't
discuss terms of a possible contract extension before the National
League Cy Young Award runner-up was traded to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Were there personal problems? Hampton says some of his best
relationships were made in the Astros organization and that he
didn't leave any burned bridges. And it certainly didn't seem he
had left enemies in Houston as he traded hugs with several of his
former teammates before Thursday's exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   All comments on the parting point to philosophical differences
regarding the direction of the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: The Astros were interested in extending
Hampton's contract beyond the 2000 season, after which he could
have become a free agent. But the winds of change began blowing
after an offseason meeting with Hampton, his agent Mark Rogers and
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make sure that the direction we were going in
was going to be the right way,'' Hampton said Thursday. ``We never
talked any terms. We had a meeting, and I decided that I was going
to wait until after the (2000) season to make my decision. It was
their option to either wait for my decision or to try to do
something, and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously concerned about the possibility of losing Hampton on
the free-agent market without compensation, Hunsicker engineered a
trade that sent him and outfielder Derek Bell to New York for
pitcher Octavio Dotel, center fielder Roger Cedeno and pitching
prospect Kyle Kessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would have been there this year, but I didn't want
to make a decision if I wasn't sure which direction we were going,
and after that meeting I was still unsure about their plans,''
Hampton said. ``I was just making sure we were going to have a
chance to win a World Series for years to come, not just a one-year
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I signed somewhere it was going to be a five- or six-year
deal, and that's a long time to play somewhere, and if you don't
have a chance to win that can be pretty miserable. That's what it
all boils down to. I want to play somewhere where I'm going to have
a chance to win every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade, Hunsicker's stance has been to keep
confidential the details of his meeting with Hampton and his agent,
as well as other factors that might have led to the trade.
</P>
<P>
   But he defended the Astros' record in response to Hampton's
assessment of the team's chances to win a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find those comments disheartening because we've been pretty
successful around here, and I'm committed to continuing to be
successful here,'' said Hunsicker, whose moves have helped the
Astros compile the third-best record in the majors since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have the money to keep an All-Star at every
position, but I fully expect to compete, and I fully expect to be
successful here,'' Hunsicker said. ``If a player chooses to have a
different opinion because we don't spend lavishly, and comes to the
conclusion that we're not going to have a competitive team, I take
exception to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton pointed to two moves that helped form his opinion: the
trade that sent catcher Brad Ausmus to Detroit prior to the 1999
season and the deal that shipped center fielder Carl Everett to
Boston this past winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it, we probably got rid of the best catcher
(Ausmus) in the organization's history, and then we got rid of the
guy (Everett) who was probably our MVP last year,'' Hampton said.
``How many more good players can you get rid of before you have no
chance?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want the trend to continue, and when I saw it
going that way I was like, `Man, if we continue to get rid of these
type of players
</P>
<P>
   then what's next? Is it going to be me, Shane (Reynolds) and
Jose (Lima) surrounded by a bunch of Triple-A players, just trying
to make a profit?' I don't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will begin the 2000 season with a payroll about $9
million lower than it was at the end of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hunsicker and owner Drayton McLane Jr. have said they
have the flexibility to add to the payroll during the season and
have indicated the final total could be similar to 1999's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I take exception to (comments) that we're not going to
do everything we can to win,'' Hunsicker said. ``If part of the
definition is spending a lot of money, that's not going to happen
around here, but that is not my definition of being committed to
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Hampton also has declined the Mets'
attempts to work out a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where they get all of this stuff from,'' Hampton
said. ``My agent hasn't said it, and the Mets haven't said it. I
don't care to be the highest-paid player in baseball. I just want
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait and weigh the offers after the season, and
I'm going to base my decisions the same way I would have if I had
been in Houston. I'm going to wait and see where these guys (the
Mets) are going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go to a place that has the most money; I'm
going to go to the place that has the best chance to win. I haven't
made an incredible amount of money, but I've made good enough money
to where I don't have to worry about it. I haven't won that ring
yet, and that's why I'm going to go where I have the best
opportunity to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a great irony, Hampton said Houston still is a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't rule anything out,'' said Hampton, who still plans to
reside in Houston. ``If I feel they're going to do the right things
and that they're going to have a chance to win, I don't have a
problem going back there. I don't think I've worn out my welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of baseball's tampering rules, Hunsicker declined
comment on the possibility of Hampton returning to Houston. The GM
did acknowledge that no bridges have been burned.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
