<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA SEASON FINISHED BY LOPSIDED LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ It began a month ago, quietly and without
warning. It gathered steam as February faded to March, then turned
awesome last weekend. But UCLA's late-season charge ended Thursday
night with a resounding thud, as the Bruins wilted in the face of
an opponent that was quicker, tougher _ much, much tougher _ and
immaculately prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State's Cyclones took away everything the Bruins did in
building their eight-game winning streak, and because of that, UCLA
departed the NCAA Tournament with an 80-56 loss before 21,214 in
The Palace of Auburn Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was nearly as thorough as UCLA's 35-point victory
over Maryland in the second round. The Bruins trailed by 12 points
at halftime and 17 early in the second half. With four minutes
left, the Cyclones were in complete command 70-49 and UCLA's
cheering section was silent.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones shot 51.7 percent from the field and held UCLA to
33.9 percent. They also outrebounded the taller Bruins 43-32 and
allowed only one UCLA player, forward Jerome Moiso (15 points), to
score in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State All-American Marcus Fizer was good but not great,
scoring 16 points and grabbing nine rebounds. But the best player
on the floor was Cyclones point guard Jamaal Tinsley, who
penetrated at will, controlled the tempo and got the Cyclones easy
baskets just when they needed them most. He finished with 14
points, 11 assists and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a victory for Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy and
his staff, which watched the Bruins devastate Maryland and built a
game plan to nullify everything UCLA likes to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones challenged every pass and every shot. Their
defenders shadowed Earl Watson the moment he crossed midcourt, thus
preventing the open 3-pointers Watson used to bury Maryland. Stocky
and low to the ground, the Cyclones also grabbed every loose ball.
And their transition defense was superb, allowing UCLA just two
alley-oop dunks and a meager seven fast-break points. Forced to
work for every shot, the Bruins struggled. They took a few wild
shots and had the ball ripped from their grasp several times.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was taut and brisk. The teams exchanged baskets
for 10 minutes, then Iowa State made the first spurt of the game.
It started when Brandon Hawkins, of Fontana, scored from the lane
to give the Cyclones a 22-18 lead. Hawkins pushed the lead to six
when he converted an errant Moiso pass into a layup. Matt Barnes
responded with a wild shot from the left wing (he was removed from
the game immediately) and Kantrail Horton buried a 3-pointer to
give the Cyclones a 27-18 advantage with eight minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins countered with two quick baskets: Dan Gadzuric made a
layup, then Jason Kapono buried a 3-pointer from the right wing,
trimming the deficit to 27-23. The Bruins would score two baskets
in the next seven minutes as Iowa State took control.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones botched several opportunities to expand their
lead,but Michael Nurse's 3-pointer with five minutes left sparked a
surge. AJaRon Rush turnover became a Fizer jumper on the fast
break, and Tinsley drained a 3-pointer. Suddenly, Iowa State had a
36-25 lead with just over three minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for 12 scoreless possessions, until Tinsley
hit two free throws for a 38-25 lead. Stevie Johnson tipped in a
Tinsley miss for a 15-point advantage, but Watson's 3-pointer at
the buzzer made it 40-28 when halftime arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The second half began as the first ended. Nurse hit a 3-pointer,
then ripped the ball from Watson, leading to a Fizer turnaround and
a 45-30 Iowa State lead. Billy Knight hit a 3-pointer for the
Bruins, but the Cyclones kept coming. Nurse hit another 3, then
Johnson's free throws with 17:30 left gave them a 17-point lead at
almost the exact moment Iowa State held a 16-point lead against
UCLA in the 1997 Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   That UCLA team responded with a furious charge. This one did
not. Moiso's short jumper slowed the Cyclones, but only for a
minute. Tinsley slashed into the lane and found Johnson for a
layup.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' best chance came with 12:33 left, when Fizer
committed his third foul and departed. The Bruins trailed 54-41 at
the time but could get no closer with the nation's best player on
the bench. Their problems had little to do with defense _ Iowa
State scored just three points _ and everything to do with offense.
They simply could not score. No open jumpers. No penetration. When
Fizer returned four minutes later, the Bruins had scored just two
points and Iowa State had increased its lead by one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
