<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LSU-WISCONSIN-HNS     03-24 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LSU-WISCONSIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Oxygen, anyone?
<TEXT>
<P>
   LSU was obviously hurting, but it was unclear whether it was the
altitude or Wisconsin's attitude that hurt the Tigers most.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   LSU, a team designed for a track meet, found itself in a
wrestling match with Wisconsin and had the breath squeezed out of
it by the Badgers' choke-hold defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin forced 23 turnovers and held the Tigers to a
season-low point total in claiming a 61-48 win in the nightcap of
the NCAA Tournament's West Regional semifinal doubleheader Thursday
before 16,004 at the Pit.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin (21-13) will face Big Ten rival Purdue on Saturday for
a berth in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, the Tigers (28-6) were dragging and
everyone could see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That confused look is almost a sense of frustration,''
Wisconsin forward Andy Kowske said. ``Coming into the game,
(opponents) know our defense is going to be tough, but it is
probably tougher than they think when they go up against it. (LSU)
knew we were going to double the post, and it worked (anyway).''
</P>
<P>
   LSU's inside tandem of Stromile Swift and Jabari Smith topped
the Tigers with 12 points each, but Swift could get just five shots
from the field against the smothering Badgers defense and Smith
went 5-for-12 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defensive scheme was great,'' Smith said. ``I give their
defense a lot of credit. They took away the things we like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers, who controlled the game from the start with their
stingy defense, took over on the scoreboard late in the first half
and held on in the second despite a couple of LSU runs.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 38-19 with 12 minutes remaining, LSU put together its
best run of the game. But the 10-2 burst was the next-to-last gasp
of a fading team.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was the key, following a Colis Temple 3-pointer with two
buckets inside for seven straight Tigers points. Kirk Penney broke
the string with jumper, but the 6-11 Smith answered quickly with a
long 3-pointer to get LSU within 40-29 with 9:24 to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers would not score again until there was just over four
minutes left, as Wisconsin ran off seven straight points to build
an 18-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers had one more spurt in them, but it would not be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Nine consecutive points, capped by a steal and layup by Jermaine
Williams, cut the lead to 47-38 with 2{ minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Bryant, who led Wisconsin with 16 points, drilled a
3-pointer for the Badgers, and LSU resorted to launching off-target
3-pointers in a futile attempt to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game got out of hand and we got down by 15, 16, they
started running their offense with nine or 10 passes and we
couldn't get back into the game,'' Swift said. ``We just didn't
compete like we are used to, but they had a lot to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   LSU played like it was running around in a Louisiana swamp in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers scored a measly 14 points and committed almost as
many turnovers (14) as they attempted shots (15).
</P>
<P>
   The five field goals made and the 14 points were the worst in a
half for LSU this season. At one point LSU did not attempt a shot
in a 4:52 span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed because I knew we were a better team than
we showed,'' Swift said. ``We just didn't come out and play LSU
basketball in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Wisconsin was lighting up the scoreboard on the
other end.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers were worse from the floor than the Tigers, with
their 9-for-30 start (30 percent). But Wisconsin had only three
turnovers, and that accounted for the difference in field-goal
attempts (30-15).
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers kept grinding away until they put together a closing
spurt to take control.
</P>
<P>
   After LSU took a 14-11 lead on a Lamont Roland free throw with
5:03 left, Wisconsin scored the final 11 points of the period to
take a 22-14 margin into the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shook a lot of balls loose (in the first half), and there
weren't many openings,'' said Wisconsin coach Dick Bennett, who
believed his team's defensive effort in the first half was its best
all season. ``We were about as active as we've been.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into a game and you see you've got a team, that
just feeds your defensive confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
