<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUNOTES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ABLE TO BOTHER FIZER
</HEADLINE>
 THIS REPLACES UCNOTE (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ To defend Iowa State All-American Marcus
Fizer, UCLA grabbed a page from one of its most successful
playbooks in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins defended Fizer like they defended Arkansas All-
American Corliss Williamson in the 1995 NCAA title game. Both Fizer
and Williamson are power forwards in the classic sense _ thick
bodied, physical, mobile, with playing styles similar to Charles
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Marcus Fizer is as dominant as anyone in the
country,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said before the 80-56 loss to
Iowa State on Thursday. ``He's very versatile, like Barkley. He can
step away from thebasket and create for himself. But he can also
post you up down low andgo to work on you. He's a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing UCLA's big men have that Fizer doesn't is
length.Jerome Moiso is 6-10, Dan Gadzuric is 6-11, and both have
long arms.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Bruins successfully forced the 6-7 Williamson to
shoot over 7-foot center George Zidek _ Williamson scored just 12
points_ so did they try to force Fizer to shoot over Moiso and
Gadzuric.
</P>
<P>
   When Fizer got the ball in the low post, the Bruins backed off,
played a perimeter-style defense that emphasized lateral movement,
and tried to deny him a direct path to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Fizer scored just 16 points and grabbed nine
rebounds. Half his points came in the opening five minutes. After
that, he was relatively quiet.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins could not contain Iowa State point guard Jamaal
Tinsley, who had 14 points, 11 rebounds, nine assists and four
steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real crafty point guard,'' Lavin said. ``It was the
biggest concern we had, keeping the point guard in front. He still
had theability to break down our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Return trip: UCLA freshman forward Jason Kapono played in The
Palace last spring in the Magic Johnson Roundball Classic, a high
school all-star game. He recalled scoring 20 or 22 points in a
victory. Cincinnati's DerMarr Johnson and Kentucky's Keith Bogans
also participated.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono hoped the experience would help his shooting touch
Thursday night, but it did not. He was 1-of-4 from 3-point range
and scored eight points. His misfires were contagious. Five days
after their hot-shooting game against Maryland, the Bruins hit just
23.5 percent of their 3-pointers against the Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of rhythm,'' Kapono said. ``I couldn't find the
rhythm of the game. They played pressure defense, and it got to
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
