<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-24 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET LESSON FROM PROFESSOR FIZER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ This doesn't have to be the end. To the
contrary, the UCLA basketball team's NCAA Tournament run, which was
halted by Iowa State 80-56 Thursday night in a Midwest Regional
semifinal game, could be the start of something extra special.
</P>
<P>
   But only if Bruins sophomores Jerome Moiso, Dan Gadzuric and
JaRon Rush learned anything from Iowa State's stellar center Marcus
Fizer. Every time the junior fleeced Moiso, frisked Gadzuric or
fettered Rush, it was as if he was sending the trio a message:
</P>
<P>
   Stay in school. Concentrate on upper-division college basketball
before graduating to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   Fizer last year bore only a slight resemblance to the goliath
who stoned the Bruins in a very public flogging at The Palace. He
didn't have the muscles he flexed against UCLA. Or the serviceable
outside shot that put would-be defenders back on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   He was prone to passiveness, like Moiso. His body was an
unfinished sculpture, like Gadzuric's. He sometimes forced things,
like Rush, instead of letting the game come to him.
</P>
<P>
   In his sophomore season, Fizer didn't always bear down like a
cyclone. His focus, like his waistline, was diffused. He was good
enough to be a first-team All-Big 12 selection and probably good
enough to be a mid-to-late first-round NBA draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   But Fizer wasn't a phenomenon by any stretch of the definition.
His collegiate career to that point had been perfectly fine, but it
wasn't fabled.
</P>
<P>
   He grew into a legend by staying put. Fizer, 21, forsook his
summer for an intense conditioning regimen that added 17 pounds to
his frame and shrank his body fat from 16 percent to nine percent.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't working on his body, the 6-foot-8 player worked
on his outside shot. Through sweat and seasoning he turned himself
into arguably the best player not only in his conference but in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, in the same span Iowa State evolved from a
.500 team to an NCAA Tournament Elite Eight participant. Fizer put
the Cyclones directly in the path of local favorite and No. 1 seed
Michigan State with a 16-point, nine-rebound performance against
the Bruins (21-12), who have no reason to hang their heads.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it took a giant to snap UCLA's winning streak at
eight.
</P>
<P>
   The hope here is Moiso, Gadzuric and Rush, before deciding their
futures, will ponder how it is Fizer and Iowa State came so far so
fast.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA's 8-1 stretch run proved anything, it's that the Bruins
are bearing down on college basketball's summit. They could get
there as soon as next year, but only if Moiso, Gadzuric and Rush
stay put. With those three and incoming recruit T.J. Cummings, too,
the Bruins would be a popular choice to rule Bracketville in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If the vacillating Bruins leave, UCLA will weather their
departures (under coach Steve Lavin, the Bruins have shown
themselves to be nothing if not resilient). And besides, Duke did
all right in year 1 AD (after underclassmen defections).
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for the trio to see the common sense for all the
dollars, but Moiso, Gadzuric and Rush would help themselves more by
staying than going. The NBA money is enticing, to be sure,
especially to someone facing a pile of legal bills as is Rush.
</P>
<P>
   However, the four-games-in-seven-nights treadmill can wear down
one's spirit quickly. It's more exhausting than trying to stop
Fizer. A few months at that unforgiving pace can make a player
yearn for the relatively carefree days of fall and winter and
spring quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, Gadzuric and Rush can afford another year of maturing. It
would behoove Moiso to work on his consistency, his focus and his
defense; Gadzuric, his post moves and fundamentals; and Rush, his
patience and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   JaRon rushed his shots against the Cyclones; he put up quick
3-pointers instead of using the clock and his teammates to optimal
advantage and finished with a very quiet six points.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, who gave up 30 pounds to Fizer, couldn't get around him,
so he tried, in vain, to shoot over him. The result? The only thing
worse than Moiso's shooting in the first half (he misfired on 6 of
8 attempts) was his passing. He had as many turnovers (four) as
points as Iowa State bolted to a 12-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old from the West Indies showed some moxie in the
second half, making three of four shots in what could have been a
harbinger for next year. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric fearlessly called for the ball and was the Bruins'
go-to guy in the first half. But he played only five minutes in the
second as UCLA went to a smaller, quicker lineup in an effort to
slow Iowa State's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   If they return for another year of college ball, Moiso, Gadzuric
and Rush can make themselves better and their team, too. Just as
Fizer did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a thousand times better than he was last year,'' Cyclones
coach Larry Eustachy said. ``He dictates the game, as opposed to
the way the game dictated him last year.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Fizer was fine if he started fast. If not, he tended
to struggle. In other words, he was just like Moiso. He was just
like Gadzuric. He was just like Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping the vacillating Bruins all decide to try to be
just like Fizer. The fact is, they could do a lot worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
