<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TAKES PLACE IN KINGS SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PHILADELPHIA _ Forty-eight seconds into the third period
Thursday night, the Kings' Nelson Emerson went down and Craig
Johnson stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson suffered a broken right index finger when he was
struckby Philadelphia's Daymond Langkow.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, usually confined to a checking role on the Kings third
unit, moved into Emerson's spot alongside Jozef Stumpel and
assisted on both of his goals in a 3-2 overtime victory over the
Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see him use his speed, you know how much he can
helpus,'' Luc Robitaille said of Johnson ``He gave us a real lift
tonight when we really needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, who had a goal in four games since coming over from
Atlanta with Kelly Buchberger, went to a local hospital to have his
fingerset. Instead of accompanying the team to Boston, where the
Kings play Saturday afternoon, Emerson returned to Los Angeles to
be examined by a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson entered the game with nine goals and 18 points, but
hisoffensive skills came out on the Kings tying goal just 2:15 into
the third period. He got the puck in front and Stumpel did the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was swarming their net the whole third period,'' Stumpel
said of Johnson. ``We got down 1-0 and 2-1 and we needed a spark.
He gaveit to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson clearly was pumped in overtime when he went out for
thefour-on-four. On the winning goal, scored 1:20 into OT, Johnson
touchedthe puck three times during the sequence before getting a
pass to Jere Karalahti, who fed Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to contribute,'' Johnson said. ``This was
a huge win for us, starting a road trip and moving closer to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fiset returned: Goaltender Stephane Fiset, sidelinedalmost
two weeks with a strained right groin, returned Thursday and
stopped 22 of 24 shots. Fiset was told by Kings coach Andy Murray
that if he played well in the morning workout, he would be in the
lineup. Jamie Storr had started the previous five games.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset allowed goals to Jody Hull and Gino Odjick, but his
biggest play of the night came late in regulation when he made a
dramatic save on a blast by Mark Recchi after the Flyers had a
two-on-one with Mark Greig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matty (Norstrom) did a great job directing the play,'' Fiset
said. ``He allowed me to set up. After (Recchi) took the shot just
seem to keep going after the stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
