<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-IOWAST-UCLA-HNS &LR;      03-24 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-IOWAST-UCLA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Iowa State's defensive pressure never
permitted UCLA to run and gun as the Cyclones advanced to their
first NCAA Elite Eight with an impressive 80-56 victory over the
Bruins on Thursday night in the Midwest Regional semifinals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In gaining a Saturday meeting with No. 1 seed Michigan State,
the second-seeded Big 12 champions won for the 29th time in their
last 31 starts and 10th in a row after taking charge late in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones (32-4) staged a 13-2 run as the sixth-seeded Bruins
(21-12) went scoreless for nearly four minutes. Iowa State then
built on its 40-28 halftime margin with a deliberate offense that
stung the Bruins for backdoor layups or opened the way for close-in
shots by Marcus Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA never whittled the margin to single digits, even when Fizer
spent several minutes on the bench in foul trouble. The Bruins kept
trying the lob passes inside like those that led to 14 alley-oop
baskets in their 105-70 drilling of Maryland last week in the
second round. But Stevie Johnson, Kantrail Horton, Jamaal Tinsley
and Fizer steadily derailed the strategy by deflecting the lobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA caught us at a bad time,'' Cyclones coach Larry Eustachy
said. ``Our goal was not to let them dunk, and I think we gave them
one for the entire game.''
</P>
<P>
   After Fizer went to the bench with his third foul with 12:33 to
play, UCLA's Jerome Moiso fashioned a three-point play, then was
fouled again several seconds later and made two free throws that
pulled the Bruins within 54-43.
</P>
<P>
   But Horton sank two free throws, Tinsley another, Fizer added
two more foul shots after he broke clear for a long inbounds pass
and Johnson got loose inside for a slam that widened the lead to
61-43.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the usual brand of Iowa State defense held the
Bruins to 33.3 percent shooting in the second half (33.9 percent
for the game). The Cyclones shot 60.9 percent in the second half
and 51.7 percent for the game in advancing past the regional
semifinals for the first time in their 11 NCAA appearances. It also
was Iowa State's first victory over UCLA in seven meetings, the
most recent an overtime loss to the Bruins in the regional
semifinals in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley barely missed a triple double, with 14 points, 11
assists and nine rebounds plus four steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one in the nation who can guard Jamaal one on
one,'' said Fizer. ``Jamaal can do about anything he wants. A lot
of times he decides not to play defense, but he's totally unselfish
in getting us the ball in position to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer added 16 points, eight rebounds and two blocked shots.
Johnson and Michael Nurse scored 16 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso (15 points) was the only Bruin in double figures after ISU
snapped UCLA's eight-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson, whose spectacular 17-point, 16-assist, no-turnover
performance keyed the Bruins' demolition of Maryland, fouled out
with 4:50 to play after scoring eight points with five assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't used to people getting into them defensively,''
Fizer said. ``We saw the defensive mistakes that Maryland made
against a great UCLA team, and we tried to make sure that didn't
happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State more than held its own despite a considerable height
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable that we could outrebound (43-32) a team as
athletic as that,'' Eustachy said. ``We wanted to keep them out of
transition and keep them in a half-court offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 6-4, Johnson added eight rebounds to the nine gathered by
the 6-3 Tinsley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we would be outsized,'' Horton said. ``I knew we could
fight with them tonight. We've been going against bigger teams all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
