<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS CURE A SEVEN-YEAR ITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PHILADELPHIA  &UR; _ &LR;  So many times the Kings had come here to die,
trailing late in a game with nowhere to go but down.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday seemed like one of those nights, but the Kings clearly
are not one of those teams, shaking off a four-game winless streak
to defeat the Philadelphia Flyers 3-2 in overtime and win here for
the first time in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game you measure yourself against,'' said
Craig Johnson, who had assists on the tying and winning goals by
Jozef Stumpel. ``A team like Philadelphia tests you. We needed to
pass and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel's goals, the first with 2:15 left in regulation and the
second 1:20 into OT, decided the game, but there were plenty of
players who made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Johnson, seldom heard from as a scorer, did more than
assist on both Stumpel goals. As the Kings' fastest skater, he
created havoc around the net after newcomer Nelson Emerson left the
game 48 seconds into the third period with a broken right index
finger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Stephane Fiset returned after missing almost two weeks with
a strained groin and won his third overtime game of the season.
Even though the Flyers were playing without Eric Lindros, who is
sidelined at least a month with a severe concussion, Philadelphia
had a chance to win it in the final minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But Fiset gloved a blast by Mark Recchi after Philadelphia drove
in on a two-on-one break. The Flyers also lead the league with 62
power-play goals but went 0 for 4 against the Kings with the man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Luc Robitaille scored his first goal in 10 games midway
through the third period. The Flyers regained the lead less than a
minute later on a goal by Gino Odjick, but that only added to the
Kings' resolve. Robitaille also ended a 1-for-20 slump on the power
play with his 34th goal. In the previous 10 games, the Kings were 3
for 47.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to score that goal,'' said Robitaille, one of the
few players left from the Kings' last victory here in 1993 when the
team reached the Stanley Cup Finals. ``It's great to score any goal
but especially this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Kings (35-30-9) 83 points in the tight
Western Conference playoff race. It keeps them in second in the
Pacific Division and fifth overall in the Western Conference
heading into upcoming road games against beatable Boston (Saturday)
and expansion Atlanta (Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   But maybe just as important, they beat the Flyers at their own
physical game, something they will see down the stretch and in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Kings lost top scorer Ziggy Palffy for the final
three weeks of the regular season, opposing teams were having
success pounding them. Emerson's broken finger came on a slash by
Daymond Langkow that wasn't called.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, the Kings set the tone, mixing it up in
front of Flyers goaltender Brian Boucher after falling behind 2-1
midway through the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing football out there,'' Odjick said. ``They
got away with it so good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way was Stumpel, who has been criticized in the past
for playing soft.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is a regular in front of the opposing net and it paid off
against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The tying goal came on a pass from Johnson, the winner from Jere
Karalahti and Johnson. Both were from short range. After going four
games without a goal, Stumpel now has five game-winners this season
and three in OT this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were devastated when they retook the lead,'' Johnson said.
``But Stumpy kept us alive. When he gets down low like that, he
gives us a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
