<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-EDMONDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS GET EDMONDS FOR BOTTENFIELD, KENNEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz.  &UR; _ &LR;  Only five days after Anaheim Angels general
manager Bill Stoneman told Jim Edmonds to ignore the rampant rumors
he would be traded, Edmonds was traded Thursday to the St. Louis
Cardinals for pitcher Kent Bottenfield and second baseman Adam
Kennedy, a former Cal State Northridge star.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ends months of speculation, negotiation and uncertainty
regarding Edmonds' status with the team, and also ends Edmonds'
12-year stay with the organization based in Anaheim, only a few
miles south of his hometown in Diamond Bar.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds was pulled from Thursday's game against the A's at Tempe
Diablo Stadium after the sixth inning and told to go to the
clubhouse. It was there that Stoneman gave him the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was in a little bit of shock,'' Stoneman said.
``This has been his only club. His home is in the area, he's from
the area. This is something that's a little different for him. At
the same time, it seems to be a relief in the sense that the little
cloud that's been following him hopefully will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kennedy, the Angels get the Cardinals' 1999 minor-league
player of the year. He finished the season in the big leagues,
hitting .255 in 33 games, but he wasn't going to start for the
Cardinals because they acquired Fernando Vina to play second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty excited,'' said Kennedy, who has a 7 a.m. flight
this morning and is expected to be in Angels camp today. ``It's a
great opportunity. I'm really looking forward to it. I'm leaving
behind my best friends, but they understand my situation and what's
best for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds is eligible to become a free agent after this season,
but his agent, Paul Cohen, said the Cardinals were one of the nine
teams Edmonds listed as teams to which he'd prefer to be traded.
Cohen said it's too soon to say whether or not Edmonds will sign an
extension with the Cardinals. Bottenfield also is eligible for free
agency after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the trade didn't come as a surprise to many in the
Angels clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everybody heard Bill Stoneman a couple of days ago, to a
lot of the players, we figured something would happen,'' Angels
shortstop Gary DiSarcina said. ``It was the kiss of death.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stoneman said he wasn't going back on his word to Edmonds.
His talks with the Yankees, A's and Mariners had hit a dead end, so
Stoneman did what he could to stop the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the general managers of the clubs who had been
calling about Jim,'' Stoneman said. ``It became pretty obvious that
we weren't going anywhere. . . . The Cardinals were not one of
them. This is something that came together very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it started to become apparent we might be able to fill
two of our needs, it made a lot of sense. After I spoke to the GMs
and told them he was off the market, I told Jim that. I was dead
serious when I told him I pulled him off the market. But something
new came up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are excited about the deal because they filled two
holes: starting pitching and second base. In Bottenfield, they get
a 31-year-old right-hander who went 18-7 with a 3.97 ERA last
season. Bottenfield was originally drafted by the Expos when
Stoneman worked in their front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of him last year and the pitcher I saw was very
different than when I first knew him,'' Stoneman said. ``The
blazing fastball is gone, but this guy can throw to a dime and hit
it. He's like a Greg Maddux  &UR; _ &LR;  he's not a particularly hard
thrower, but he understands pitching and has control.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield became available because of the development of
Garret Stephenson, who is 1-0 with a 0.53 ERA in camp and will take
Bottenfield's spot in the St. Louis rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no intention of trading a starting pitcher,'' said
Cardinals general manager Walt Jocketty. ``This came up, and when
you get an opportunity to get a guy of Edmonds' stature, you can't
pass it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had talked with the Angels about a Bottenfield-
for-Edmonds deal earlier in the winter, but Stoneman wouldn't make
the deal one-for-one. But on Sunday, Stoneman talked with Cardinals
scout Bob Gebhardt, who was scouting the Angels in Arizona.
Stoneman brought up the possibility of adding Kennedy to the deal,
and it was consummated quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A talent like Jimmy is not going to be replaced, it's like
when Chuck (Finley) left,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said.
``Fortunately for us, the impact won't be as great offensively, and
we've got G.A. (Garret Anderson) to step in to play center field.
Overall, this gives us more balance than we had. Obviously, the
balance came at a huge cost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
