<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOS </SLUG>
 
PURDUE BEATS GONZAGA &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE _ Purdue is well-established as the Best Friend Who
Never Gets The Girl, which is why coach Gene Keady hasn't even
purchased a ring, let alone booked a hall for the reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty minutes is a long time,'' said the ever-pragmatic
Boilermaker mentor after his squad advanced to the West Regional
final with a 75-66 victory over Gonzaga Thursday night at The Pit.
``We don't have anything to celebrate yet. We've won three games in
the NCAA tournament, and that's nice. But you're judged on whether
or not you get to the Final Four, in the final analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   As he's been hearing ad nauseum for years and years, the
respected Boilermaker mentor has never taken any team to the Final
Four. Now a Purdue team that operated with its usual national
anonymity all season, and which exited the Big Ten tournament in
unpleasant fashion (a 78-66 loss to Wisconsin), is indeed 40
minutes away from the Promised Land after not just outscoring, but
truly punishing, the Zags.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing standing in Keady's way is the aforementioned
Wisconsin, which stifled LSU, 61-48, in the West's other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Is Keady excited?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says I need to do this to fill out my resume,''
Keady said with a shrug. ``I don't need that. I'd rather sink a
20-foot putt against my buddies. But I'd be happy for these kids if
they could go back and play in front of our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Don't forget this year's Final Four will be played at
the RCA Dome in Indianapolis, which is no more than an hour and a
half by car from the Purdue campus.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Gonzaga, the lovable team from the 4,500-student
Jesuit school in Spokane?
</P>
<P>
   They will at least know there weren't any great what-ifs? The
Zags were outplayed for a good 35 minutes. They were outshot,
outdefended, outhustled, and, most of all, unmercifully
outrebounded. Purdue helped itself to 20 offensive rebounds, good
for 23 second-chance points. All other things being equal, that was
the old ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been one of our strengths all year,'' said the
relentless Brian Cardinal, who twice back-tapped missed free throws
to set up bonus Boilermaker points. ``We offensive rebound as hard
as we can, because we know we have an edge on most teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding is the primary adjunct to defense, and if the
Boilermakers got an A in board work, they had to get an A-plus in
defense. They wrapped up Gonzaga's 1-2 offensive punch of Matt
Santangelo and Richie Frahm, who combined to shoot a dismal 9 for
30, including 2 for 13 on their patented 3-pointers. Many of
Santangelo's wounds were self-inflicted, but Frahm was simply
dominated by the Purdue defenders, most notably senior Mike
Robinson, who entered school as an offensive whiz kid and who will
exit it as a nice all-around, and, incidentally, quite humble
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up Richie Frahm at the 3-point line and tried not to
give him any easy looks,'' said Robinson. ``During the course of
the game I wanted to make him work, tire him out, and push him
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga had an early 10-4 lead via a 10-0 run. At this point
Keady called time and ordered more ball pressure to stop some easy
high-low lobs underneath to the likes of Casey Calvary and Axel
Dench. Ask, and the coach shall receive. The Purdue defense
inspired its offense, and soon the Boilermakers were off on a 22-7
run. Purdue led by 13 (35-22) at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga whittled the lead to 37-32, but it wasn't exactly panic
time on the Purdue side. With bench performers Rod Smith and Chad
Kerkhoff _ the Last of the One-Hand Set-Shooters _ making big
hoops, Purdue responded with a run of 7-0. Gonzaga never really
threatened again, never getting closer than 8 (61-53, 3:37) and
never rattling the Boilermakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having five seniors helps,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again . . . and again . . . and again . . . Purdue got
what it needed via second shots. ``We've had a stretch of seven or
eight games where we've outrebounded people,'' said Gonzaga coach
Mark Few. ``I've never seen us outrebounded like that, especially
on missed free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Superior depth also was a major factor. Gonzaga was down one
injured starter, anyway, and Purdue is more naturally deep. Keady
paid homage to the mile-high altitude by allowing his players to
substitute themselves out for a blow.
</P>
<P>
   The classy Gonzaga kids knew which team deserved to move on.
``They're not like St. John's, who want to force you into turnovers
and beat you by 40,'' said Santangelo. ``They contest every shot,
they rebound the heck out of the ball, they make you work hard for
everything, and they just want to beat you by 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, in this case, 9. Does anyone hear wedding bells in the
distance?
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin 61, LSU 48 _ It will be an All-Big Ten West Regional
final. Make that a rock 'em-sock 'em All-Big Ten West Regional
final. Wisconsin saw to that by humiliating LSU.
</P>
<P>
   If LSU doubted Wisconsin's defensive prowess before the game _
and there were indications that was the case _ what can the Tigers
say now after needing more than 35 minutes to break, ahem, 30? (It
was 22-14, Badgers, at the half.)
</P>
<P>
   Just getting off a shot was a major LSU achievement. At one
point in the second half, the No. 4 seed Tigers had a 1-to-1 ratio;
that is to say, they had 22 shots attempted _ and 22 turnovers.
Wisconsin, the No. 8 seed, led by as many as 19 (38-19).
</P>
<P>
   LSU star Stromile Swift didn't live up to his name, taking but
one shot in the first half en route to a 12-point evening padded by
garbage-time scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin has won 10 of its last 13, the only three losses
coming to consensus tourney favorite Michigan State. The Badgers
were 2-1 against Purdue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
