<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6609 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     03-24 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE EMBRACES SHAQ OVER WILT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We haven't clubbed together. We haven't discussed his favorite
philosopher Nietzsche together. We haven't even done lunch or
dinner together.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and I aren't exactly pals, with our only previ
ous contact with each other over the years coming during interviews
in the Lakers locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the other night at Staples Center after the Lakers had
impaled the Golden State Warriors, O'Neal warmly hugged me, even
bent over and laid his huge head on my shoulder, and feigned
weeping in a comical display that elicited laughter in his team's
dressing quarters.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like being touched by an angel, but I have to candidly
admit it was the first time in my life I've been embraced by a 7-
foot-1, 320-pound multimillionaire destined to be a unanimous
choice as the Most Valuable Player in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   What inspired O'Neal's impromptu display of faux emotion?
</P>
<P>
   It came after I told him, ``I think you're a better player than
Wilt Chamberlain was.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal vs. Wilt Chamberlain?
</P>
<P>
   Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   O'NealChamberlain
</P>
<P>
   The Shaquille O'Neal I've been watching dominate the NBA in
recent months is simply superior to the Wilt Chamberlain I once
covered as a beat writer for the Los Angeles Herald Examiner when
Chamberlain was a member of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Blasphemy?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly to those devout patrons of the late center whose
perceptions are hopelessly immersed in the mistiness of the past
and are mesmerized by Chamberlain's incredible numbers 100 points
in a game, 55 rebounds in a game, 50-point average for a season,
etc. that were achieved early in his career against inferior
opposition and often at the expense of his team winning games.
</P>
<P>
   But I've been seeing O'Neal dispense heroics this season like
that late-game, midcourt steal that recently saved the Lakers
against Orlando, or those four consecutive third-quarter blocked
shots against Alonzo Mourning the other evening, etc. etc., etc.
that have set him apart from Chamberlain in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Chamberlain might have been a better rebounder than O'Neal,
perhaps even a better PLEASE SEE DOUG / B7 DOUG: Shaq beats Wilt
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUEDFROMB1 shot blocker.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't nearly as good a passer, nor did he have the deft
footwork, or the variety of offensive moves that O'Neal has been
exhibiting with such devastating results this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coached Wilt and loved Wilt,'' says Bill Sharman, coach of
the Lakers during Chamberlain's heyday with the team. ``But he
never had the quickness inside that Shaquille has. Shaquille is
just such an awesome force. Right now Shaquille is playing better
than any center I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Shaquille keeps improving, I think he has a chance to go
down as the greatest center in the history of basketball,'' says
Bill Bertka, the Lakers' venerable assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt that Shaquille now compares favorably with all the
great centers who have been in the league,'' says Jerry West, who
played with Chamberlain, coached Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and was the
driving force behind the acquisition of O'Neal. ``When you consider
all the things he does and how well he does them he has to be
ranked among the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the scary thing is that there is so much room for
improvement. What upsets me most is when people say, `All he can do
is dunk.' People who say that don't know the game. Shaquille has a
nice feel for what he's doing out there. He makes the smart passes.
He gets good position. And his quickness for a man of his size is
what sets him apart from everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It definitely sets him apart from Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at old Laker film footage on the Sports Classic
network and I did the other night when the famous Willis
Reed-limping-onto-the Madison Square Garden-floor, Lakers-New York
Knicks Game 7 of 1970 was shown you can't help but notice how
Chamberlain maneuvers around almost in slow motion compared to what
you're accustomed now to seeing with O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not to demean Wilt Chamberlain, a legendary figure
who holds records that never will be broken and was the most
dominant player of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that Shaquille O'Neal has now evolved beyond Wilt
Chamberlain, and is playing at an unprecedented level that is
reflected graphically in the Lakers' 57-12 record. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It seems hardly a year passes without swimming great Susie
Atwood being elected into some sort of Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The latest honor came Thursday in Palm Springs, where the
two-time Olympian was inducted into the California Community
College Sports Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   She also is in the National Swimming Hall of Fame, the Century
Club Hall of Fame and the Long Beach City College Hall of Fame.
Alas, it's doubtful she'll ever make it in the Hall of Fame in
Cooperstown, although you never know for sure when it comes to this
fiercely ambitious lady.
</P>
<P>
   The advancement of women sports has been startling since 1973
when Atwood, and her former Millikan High classmate, An Simmons,
had no alternative but to compete on the LBCC men's swim team.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at the time, there were only three universities that
offered scholarships to women swimmers and Atwood would wind up
attending one of them, Hawaii, for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a silver and bronze in the 1972 Olympics in Munich
she also was a member of the 1968 Olympic team that competed in
Mexico City and after coaching at Ohio State, Atwood went into the
insurance business and has become a successful State Farm agent in
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband-in-waiting, former Secret Service agent Dave
Butler, have become popular figures on the local social scene. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Contreras, Dr. Robert ``Fighting Bob'' Maxson's bright,
energetic assistant, has lined up the USA Men's National Volleyball
team to perform against a Korean national team on April 14 at the
Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players on the American squad will be competing in
the upcoming Sydney Olympics and one of them, middle blocker Tom
Hoff, is a former Long Beach State star. . . .
</P>
<P>
   One of the nice guys in sports, Long Beach State men's
volleyball coach Ray Ratelle, will be honored Saturday evening
before his team's match against USC at the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Ratelle is retiring at the end of the season, and he's
determined to go out in a flourish as his 17-2 team is rated No. 1
in the nation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The least surprising statement of the week came out of Staples
Center Wednesday, when it was announced that tickets were going
briskly for the June 17 Sugar Shane Mosley-Oscar De La Hoya
welterweight title fight. Supposedly, 13,000 were peddled in a few
hours, but I don't believe it. You can be sure Bob Arum's roly-poly
propaganda minister, Mr. Bill ``Bozo'' Caplan, was busy playing a
behind-the-scenes role in such inflated figures calculated to give
the public illusion that Mosley-De La Hoya is an event of epic
proportions. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Gee, I'm not sure if I'll ever watch television again now that
Michael Jordan says he's no longer going to be a commercial
pitchman. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Listen, don't be too down on the foundering Dodgers. After all,
they've won more games in March than the Clippers. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I've had a lot of weird things happen to me in my life, but
Shaquille O'Neal ``crying'' on my shoulder ranks among the most
bizarre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
