<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6610 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     03-24 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIM PAYROLL IS GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first person I called Thursday after the Angels traded Jim
Edmonds was a friend named Bryon who is an Angels season-ticket
holder.
</P>
<P>
   After initially telling him the Angels had traded Edmonds for
Mark McGwire and Alan Benes, he said ``OK, who did they really
get?''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Bottenfield and Adam Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it!'' he screamed. ``I'm giving up my tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend may reconsider, because he's a big-time baseball fan
and his infant son Dakota gets a lot of face time on the Angels
video board. But his initial incredulous reaction was probably
typical of most long-suffering Angels fans.
</P>
<P>
   Even with an abundance of outfielders Edmonds on the roster, how
does a team let someone as talented as Edmonds go for so little in
return?
</P>
<P>
   Why would a team ever back itself into a corner over a player
with as much upside and value as Edmonds?
</P>
<P>
   And, why can't the Angels (and Dodgers, for that matter) ever be
on the receiving end of a blockbuster trade, the way the Cubs did
in getting Ismael Valdes and Eric Young from the Dodgers for a
middle reliever, or the way the Mariners picked Houston's prospect
pocket Bottenfield in the Randy Johnson trade?
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer is that this is the Angels' way. They've been
a reactionary, impatient and out of synch organization since birth.
</P>
<P>
   The organization that gave too much money to too many free
agents is the same organization that let Nolan Ryan walk. The
organization that didn't pull the trigger on trading for Mark
McGwire is the same organization that now sends Edmonds to become
his teammate.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, former G.M. Bill Bavasi nurtured the sensible
formula of building through the farm system and signing players
before they reached their early free agent years. It might have
worked if Bavasi had developed a few more pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The new regime has two mandates: Clear the clubhouse of
controversy and trim the payroll. Disney has adopted a we-can-lose-
92-games-without-you philosophy, and there would be some merit to
the concept if the team had an improvement plan to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   On that matter, the jury is still out. New Angels GM Bill
Stoneman says Kennedy and Bottenfield will make the team better.
Maybe. But they definitely cost less. Bottenfield made $800,000
last year and Kennedy is a rookie playing for the major league
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   That makes them a fit on a team that let Chuck Finley get away
without compensation and hired ex-Dodgers catcher Mike Scioscia as
manager because they could pay him less than anyone else on the
market. With the departure of Finley ($5.8 million) and Edmonds
($4.5 million), the Angels have cut more than $10 million in
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds was part of the clubhouse mess last year, not because of
anything he said as much ashis manner. In spite of his willingness
to dive on asphalt-hard turf, Jim Edmonds has laid-back body
language, and some fans and teammates believe that means he doesn't
care.
</P>
<P>
   But do these numbers say ``I don't care''? In a four-year span
(1995-98) before last year's injury- shortened season, Edmonds
averaged 27 home runs, 86 RBI, 97 runs scored and a .301 batting
average, and won two Gold Glove awards.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Bobby Bonilla we're talking about. Somehow, I'd find
a way to keep Edmonds in my lineup. And I certainly wouldn't deal
him for a rookie and a 31-year-old pitcher with one good year in
seven big league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is a line-drive hitter who doesn't strike out. He hit
.327 in AAA last year, and Baseball America ranked him the third
best prospect in the Cardinals farm system. But the Cal State
Northridge product is a former shortstop with a year of second-base
experience, and his minor league numbers (on-base percentage,
steals) don't project as a leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, 31, was the epitome of a journeyman pitcher until
last year, when he went 18-7 and made the N.L. All-Star team. The
Angels are his sixth team in eight seasons, and one of those teams
was Montreal, Stoneman's old haunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, he was a thrower, not a pitcher,'' Stoneman
said. ``He found himself last year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But the Cardinals didn't seem too keen on keeping him.
In trading for Darryl Kile and Pat Hentgen in the offseason, the
Cards were saying they weren't convinced Bottenfield could
duplicate his season. At best, he was the No. 4 or 5 starter in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Scouting reports say Bottenfield is a fly ball pitcher with
occasional control problems. With the Cardinals, he benefited from
run support of 6.1 runs per game, among the N.L. leaders. Stats
Inc.'s 2000 Major League Handbook said he tied for the N.L. lead in
cheap wins with six.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Cardinals actually gave up more (two good pitching
prospects) to get Kile than they gave up for Edmonds, which is just
another reason to believe the Angels are making plans on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many Angels fans are tuned in to the N.L.,
and I doubt many people other than neighbors know Adam. But I'm
pleased we were able to land an 18-game winner, and I envision Adam
having a long career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope fans will say `let's take a look at this team and see
if it can make a run.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At least those that haven't already ran off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
