<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-TONY-COELHO-COX     03-24 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-COELHO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore aide faces probe by State Department
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ The State Department is investigating Tony Coelho,
presidential campaign chairman for Vice President Al Gore, for his
role in organizing the World Exposition in Portugal in 1998,
Coelho's attorney said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Brand said his client was cooperating with the inquiry,
which arose out of a critical audit of the World Expo in September
1999. Coelho was the U.S. commissioner general to the expo.
</P>
<P>
   News of the investigation by the State Department's office of
inspector general is reported in today's National Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rehash of everything that's been reported and talked
about since September,'' Brand said of the Journal article.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said Coelho began cooperating with the investigation in
November and had provided bank records as recently as January.
</P>
<P>
   Brand accused Journal editor Michael Kelly, a frequent Gore
critic, of political motivations in publishing the report just
three weeks after Gore wrapped up the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why all of the sudden is this news?'' Brand said. Kelly could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho is credited with helping retool Gore's campaign after it
stumbled early against former rival Bill Bradley. But Coelho has
also been something of a lightening rod for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho resigned from Congress in 1989 after he failed to report
a loan from a troubled savings and loan institution. The Justice
Department investigated the loan but never filed charges.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho's latest legal problems arose from the nonpaid position
he took with the U.S. Information Agency to spearhead the United
States' exposition at the World Expo in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department audit found that the expo was mismanaged
and overbudget, resulting in U.S. government agencies absorbing 82
percent of the cost when private donations were in fact supposed to
foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   While the audit praised the expo for attracting millions of
visitors, Coelho was faulted for such internal management lapses as
putting his niece on the payroll at $2,500 a month, $900 more than
the office manager was receiving.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign issued a strong endorsement of Coelho when the
audit was made public last fall, and again praised Coelho Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is doing a great job, day in and day out,'' said Chris
Lehane, Gore's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 0859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
