<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush smart enough to lead country, but that's not all it takes
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Bush is getting a bum rap about his smarts.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Texas Gov. George W. Bush is smart enough to
be an excellent president.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean he would be an excellent president, just that
he is smart enough to be one.
</P>
<P>
   The is-Bush-smart-enough question comes from two primary
sources.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bush's political opponents have belittled him by saying
that his Yale grades were mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Bush admits that he reaped his share of ``gentleman Cs'' at
Yale. That doesn't mean he lacks the smarts to be president.
</P>
<P>
   The other primary source for the jokes and innuendoes about
Bush's brain power came when a Boston TV reporter ambushed the
governor with a pop quiz on the names of foreign leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush couldn't name the general who recently took control of
Pakistan, the president of Chechnya or the prime minister of India.
</P>
<P>
   He did recall the name of the president of Taiwan, ``Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Forewarned, the other presidential candidates refused to answer
current-events pop quizzes. But the damage was already done to
Bush. Everyone from TV comedians to serious pundits have made hay
with Bush's intellect.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons that make the is-Bush-smart-enough
question unfair.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, high grades in school do not translate into high
leadership qualities. Sometimes they do, but often they do not.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Bush's grades at Yale were higher than Al
Gore's grades at Harvard, according to the Washington Post and
historian David Maraniss.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has refused to release or talk about his grades. No wonder.
Gore placed in the lower fifth of his classes two years straight at
Harvard. His classmates remember him spending time shooting pool,
watching TV, eating hamburgers and smoking dope.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush graduated from Yale, he earned a graduate degree, an
MBA, from Harvard Business School. That's not shabby academic
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was an F-102 pilot for the Texas Air National Guard.
Not everyone has what it takes to fly high-performance combat jets.
That doesn't mean Bush would make a good president, but it shows
he's no dummy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, high intelligence is not a good predictor of a good
president.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter was a nuclear engineer. He had high grades and high
intelligence. He had very high ideals. All excellent qualities.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter micromanaged White House tennis court schedules and
repeatedly misfired on his big-picture initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was, and is, a good man. But he often was out of sync
with the American people. That's not good in a leader.
</P>
<P>
   Most political historians and observers agree that Richard Nixon
and Bill Clinton were among the most intelligent presidents ever
elected. They also both disgraced the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, by all accounts, was no great shakes in the IQ
department. But those same political historians and observers agree
that Reagan was a good president.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan was in sync with the sentiments of most Americans. He
inspired confidence even if he couldn't recall the names of world
leaders or thought trees caused air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30 years that I have been interviewing politicians and
political candidates, I have often felt that some of them were not
smart enough to handle the job. I did not get that feeling in
editorial board conversations with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   I also had a long conversation with Gore about offshore oil
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are smart enough to be president. Smarts should not be
a question.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
