<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIETITIAN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Effects of resveratrol are still unclear
 &HT;    By Karen Collins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the resveratrol found in wine available in any other
foods?
</P>
<P>
   A: Resveratrol is a naturally occurring substance found mainly
in grapes that may promote heart health and prevent the development
of cancerous cells. Researchers caution, however, that much of the
work regarding resveratrol's effects has been conducted only in
test tubes; we are just beginning to see how this compound may work
in animals or humans.
</P>
<P>
   Content varies with the type of grape, growing conditions and
stage of ripeness. Since resveratrol is found in the grape skins,
white wine (which is not fermented with the skins) has little of
the substance. Resveratrol is most readily found in red wine, but
it is wise to drink it in very moderate amounts. The health risks
of more than one or two small glasses of wine a day outweigh the
potential phytochemical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Grape juice (especially dark types) and table grapes provide
resveratrol in less concentrated amounts, but you can consume
larger portions without health risk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that honey is recommended because tooth decay is
caused by bacteria, which cannot live in honey.
</P>
<P>
   A: Tooth decay is caused by bacteria, but the bacteria that
cause it do not come from our food. Bacteria are always present in
our mouth. If there is carbohydrate present on our teeth, bacteria
ferment it. This produces an acid that damages tooth enamel,
leading to cavities. That is why the key to cavity prevention is
brushing and flossing teeth after eating whenever possible, and
avoiding the habit of eating or drinking carbohydrate snacks
constantly throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, honey is known to occasionally contain the bacteria
responsible for botulism food poisoning. Adults can tolerate the
small amounts that may be present, but because babies are more
sensitive, experts recommend that children under the age of two
never be given honey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any truth to the notion that cranberry juice can
cure bladder infections?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some studies have found that drinking a daily 10-ounce glass
of cranberry juice reduces the incidence of bacterial infections of
the urinary tract in elderly women by about 50 percent after four
to eight weeks. Evidence also suggests that cranberry juice could
help treatment of bladder infections.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry juice, however, is not a substitute for medication. If
you think you might have a bladder infection, see your doctor. It
is important that bladder infections be completely resolved. When
buying cranberry juice, if you have diabetes or glucose
intolerance, choose the artificially sweetened versions since
regular cranberry juice cocktail contains about three tablespoons
of sugar per cup.
</P>
<P>
   (These Ask a Dietitian questions were answered by Karen Collins,
M.S., R.D. of the American Institute for Cancer Research.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
