<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bunch of nekkid women will cause you nothing but trouble
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ The news office was invaded by a gaggle of
nekkid women Friday. Really. But, trust me, it isn't news of the
traditional sort.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Magazine sent us three copies of its latest College
Girls extravaganza and one of the models happened to be a poor girl
from Longview who was foolish enough to take her clothes off while
someone was snapping a camera. The few thousand dollars she got (I
hope she got at least a few thousand) may already be gone. Those
pictures are going to be around forever.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to sound too sanctimonious, however. If someone had
sent me that magazine 30 years ago I would have been overjoyed
beyond all belief and hidden the magazine in my most secret place
in the hopes that my mother would never find it.
</P>
<P>
   She would have.
</P>
<P>
   Even Friday, it took me several tries before my hand would
actually let the darn thing go into the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a hangover from my teen-age years. When I was 15, I
spent weeks trying to get just such a magazine in an episode that
will forever rank as one of my most embarrassing moments (or at
least I hope so).
</P>
<P>
   I walked to and from school every day. Yes, disbelieving young
people, once most high school students did actually walk to school
and many for several miles. I had a two-mile jaunt each way.
Fortunately, living in Texas, I never had to walk in snow. They
closed the school.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time I varied my walk, but most often it was right
down one of Fort Worth's main streets, Lancaster Avenue, and right
past a newsstand.
</P>
<P>
   And in the newsstand, there were nudie magazines. I knew this
because the place was also a convenience store and I would
frequently stop there to get a soft drink _ particularly after I
discovered they sold nudie magazines.
</P>
<P>
   I knew right where they were in the store, but I was always too
chicken to openly browse them. Instead I would pretend to be
looking at some of the other nearby magazines, sneaking a glance
now and then. It did not do me much good. They were all covered in
wrappers and showed no more than anyone could see at the tame
movies of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But I dreamed that there was more. So much more.
</P>
<P>
   After several months of this, I decided that I had to buy one of
those magazines. I saved up my lunch money until I had about $5. I
carried that money with me for two weeks trying to get up the
nerve. Finally, the day arrived.
</P>
<P>
   I walked into the store as fast as I could go, walked straight
to the adult section and, without even looking (thank goodness they
didn't sell those magazines with nude men back then) I picked a
magazine in a plastic wrapper, took it to the counter and plopped
it down.
</P>
<P>
   I kept my eyes downward while the clerk walked slowly over. I
put my crumpled, sweaty $5 bill on top of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk walked over. He looked at me and he looked at the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to buy this?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yessir,'' I said, hoping that my voice hadn't squeaked.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me and he looked at the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, but I'm going to have to see some ID.''
</P>
<P>
   It had never occurred to me that I would be asked to show my ID.
Still, I was quick on my feet. I told him I didn't drive and, thus,
didn't have a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you are 18, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I'm 20,'' I said. No need in limiting a good lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, then, great. Just show me your draft card.''
</P>
<P>
   I was had. During the Vietnam War, all 18-year-olds were
required to carry their draft cards at all times, proving, for one
thing, that you had actually registered for the draft. Of course, a
15-year-old boy didn't have a draft card.
</P>
<P>
   I told him I'd left it in my other wallet (looking back that is
the silliest thing I've ever heard, what man keeps two wallets?).
He didn't say anything and I didn't say anything. I walked out as
quickly as I'd walked in.
</P>
<P>
   My face was burning with embarrassment as I walked down
Lancaster Avenue, but I didn't yet know how bad it was going to
get.
</P>
<P>
   For in just a few seconds, the door of the store opened and out
came the clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonny!'' he shouted, ``Sonny, come here!''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny?
</P>
<P>
   I turned around and held up my hands, as if to ask what he
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   He held up my 10th-grade geometry book.
</P>
<P>
   ``You left your school books here. I'm sure you'll be needing
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And I never went in that store again.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
