r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN25-COX     03-24 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old-fashioned remedy
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of advantages of growing up rural and
countrified is I've never had the reputation of being a suave
Southern gentleman. This lack of certain social graces serves me
well in an era of new and complicated rules of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   I have often heard myself described as introverted, a bore and
even timid. Certainly, I've never been the life of a party.
</P>
<P>
   For several reasons, among them being the face I see in the
mirror when I shave and such deficiencies as an inability to match
neckties and socks to the rest of my attire, my relationships with
the opposite sex have generally and historically been rather
distant.
</P>
<P>
   I've never bothered to flirt with flight attendants and
waitresses, the favorite pastime of many American males whenever
they are beyond the range of domestic surveillance. Such an
expenditure of energy on my part would at best be a waste of time
and at worst an embarrassing rebuff.
</P>
<P>
   When I was gainfully employed in the work force, I was inclined
to steer away from water fountains whenever a pretty young thing
headed in that direction. Being well-trained at home, I certainly
never asked a female associate to bring me a cup of coffee, nor
have I been so indiscreet as to comment on a dress or a hairdo worn
by a female under the age of 85. I don't think I'd risk such
behavior even if my wife didn't have the antenna of a Scotland Yard
detective. In other words, I run scared.
</P>
<P>
   While it might be nice to be known as a suave Casanova _ or
better still, a rogue _ my natural reticence in relationships with
the opposite sex has paid off. I don't think I'm likely to be
accused of sexual harassment, although I'm not altogether sure what
it is.
</P>
<P>
   To be on the safe side, I've re-evaluated my demeanor whenever
I'm in the presence of any female other than my wife or
granddaughter. Not only do I observe Emily Post's rule of never
initiating a handshake, I take care to keep my hands clasped behind
my back. Although a dress may be a designer model from Saks or
Neiman Marcus, I never proffer a compliment. If it is either
low-cut or short-cut and displayed on a well-put-together body, I
don't merely refrain from comment. I head for the other side of the
room on the chance I might be caught looking.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clarence Thomas got in deep trouble with indiscreet
chitchat and almost didn't get confirmed to the Supreme Court, I
haven't taken chances in anything resembling sexual harassment.
Individuals can get into a lot of trouble. So can municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Fayetteville is being asked to shell out $125,000
because the city manager allegedly sexually harassed an employee.
We don't know the details because the city is being very secretive.
All we know is the city manager, since departed, got in trouble
with certain female employees at city hall, and now one of his
alleged victims is asking the city for $125,000 in lieu of a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   One reason you see more of these lawsuits cropping up is because
of other rules changes. In the old days, an irate spouse or
boyfriend would simply call on the offending party, black his eye,
or worse, and let him explain to his spouse or girlfriend as best
he could.
</P>
<P>
   The accused former city manager admits he said some things out
of line and claims other people at city hall, including some of the
complaining women, also made sex jokes. The versions are a piece
apart.
</P>
<P>
   This is a case I wouldn't mind seeing in court. It could help
clear up what sexual harassment really is, and if it's what I think
it is, maybe I can relax and be more sociable in company of
womenfolk. It must be more than bragging on a new outfit, even when
the skirt rides well above a shapely knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Have you ever been sexually harassed?'' I asked my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ''You mean by someone other than you?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Like someone you meet in business,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd say so,'' she answered. ''It happens.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't ask her if she'd be embarrassed to admit she never had
been.
</P>
<P>
   ''How would you define sexual harassment?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''It can be nothing much, or it can be really demeaning and
offensive,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is it when it's nothing much?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to call it flirting,'' she said. ''With women being so
much smarter than men, flirting is easy to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I know you don't have a boss, but if you had a boss, and he
got seriously out of line, and his bosses didn't do anything about
it, would you get a lawyer?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sure would,'' she said. ''We'd need one to keep you out of
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, we need to keep sexual harassment out of the
workplace. I wonder what happened to the old-fashioned remedy of
simply slapping an offender up-side his head.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
