r l BC-GAS-GALLON25-COX     03-24 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-GALLON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think gas is high? Try buying other items by the gallon
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Woe this world of high gas prices. A gallon of
regular unleaded costs anywhere from $1.38 a gallon to more than
$1.50 a gallon. Let's not even talk about super unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring price of fuel has hit all parts of the nation.
Truckers are lobbying Congress to address a problem they say is
crippling their industry. Airline companies are threatening to
raise ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday night at a department store perfume counter,
Michele Thompson looked over a display of exotic aromas, where the
meaning _ and cost _ of a gallon was something altogether
different. Far from the upwardly mobile digits at the local gas
pump, there were liquids of all varieties, from perfumes and body
lotions to cleaning supplies and shampoo, that carried their own
sort of sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how much it actually costs when you look at it
like that,'' Thompson said as she perused the display of perfumes.
``I guess people don't really think about it. It's not something
you use a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   We took a nonscientific survey of some popular products at local
stores to see what a gallon of the different liquids would cost,
not calculating any bulk-purchase discounts. Many of the products
we priced are not marketed or intended to be sold by the gallon,
but just in case you had a hankering for 128 ounces of your
favorite soft drink, four quarts of a name-brand toothpaste or 8
pints of Ralph Lauren's newest fragrance, we went ahead and did the
math.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren's Romance perfume, one of the more popular fragrances
around, comes in a 3.4-ounce container for $60. A gallon of the
sultry smelling potion would cost you $2,252.80. Think that makes
the price of premium unleaded sound a little better?
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder's Resilience Lift Eye Creme comes in half-ounce
containers for $42.50. Buying 128 ounces of the facial enhancer
would cost somewhere around $10,880.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing up your nails by the gallon could get a bit pricey, too.
OPI Nail Lacquer, which comes in half-ounce containers for $6,
would run about $1,536 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   At the grocery store, things get a little better. A 6.2-ounce
tube of Crest toothpaste sells for $2.98. A full gallon of it would
cost $62.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Healing Vaseline Intensive Care Lotion is $3.47 for an
11-ounce bottle. That comes to $40 per gallon. Suave Shampoo would
cost $11 a gallon; Clairol Herbal Essences about $40 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-pack of Coors Light costs $5.19. That's $9.23 per gallon. A
gallon of Coke Classic would cost $2.61 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   And what about water? Surely, it's cheaper than gasoline, you
say. Guess again. Ozarka Natural Spring Water sells for 69 cents
per 8 ounces. That's $11.04 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   For cleaning up, original Windex runs $10.68 per gallon. Ultra
Palmolive dishwashing liquid comes out to $12.29 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning on some work around the house this weekend,
here are some prices that might make you think twice.
</P>
<P>
   A gallon of Elmer's Carpenter Wood Glue costs $9.75. Clear
satin, fast-drying polyurethane costs $19.93 a gallon. A 128-ounce
container of paint thinner runs $1.84.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-ounce bottle of Homelite two-cycle engine oil cost $3.94.
That averages out to about 25 cents per ounce or $32 a gallon.
Real-Kill Home Insect Control is $5.68 a gallon. Flea and Tick
Shampoo is $30 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Roundup Weed and Grass Killer concentrate costs $76 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just pour gasoline on 'em,'' David Billy of Dallas said as
he shopped for lawn equipment Wednesday night. ``It's cheaper than
that stuff. But you have to watch out. It kills everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the next isle, a one-gallon gas can costs $2.98.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
