<HEADER>
A6739 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FEATURES-BJT25-COX     03-24 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, March 25
and Sunday, March 26, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-WHALES _ TIJUANA, Mexico _ To some, protecting the gray
whales that mate and give birth in a warm-water lagoon near here is
like a religion. It may
</P>
<P>
   sound a little wacky, but their passion was enough to cause the
Mexican government and Japan's Mitsubishi Corp. to suddenly scrap
plans to build a new
</P>
<P>
   salt mining factory on the lagoon _ despite the fact that an
environmental study showed that it would not harm the whales.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Thursday, March 23, in (i) International (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS _ ZIMBABWE _ In sub-Saharan Africa, 23.3
million people _ most of them women _ are infected with HIV/AIDS,
compared to less than 1 million in North America. There were 2.2
million deaths from AIDS in the region in 1999 ? representing 85
percent of the world's HIV-related fatalities, even though only 10
percent of the world's population lives in the region. The disease
is destroying entire villages, but beyond that is robbing these
countries of a whole generation of potentially productive people.
Perhaps the most grim by-product is the staggering fact that the
disease has created more than 10 million orphans a number that is
expected to soar to 13 million next year. The implications of this
are devastating. (Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS and
half-page color graphics prepared by Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Tues., March 21, in (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-CITY _ SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ A stay-at-home mom, Kathy
Verschoor sits down daily at the family computer to stay in touch
with her toddler's playgroup, scan upcoming events at the nearby
community center and keep up on neighborhood concerns. But
Verschoor is no nerd. She kew little about computers and the
Internet until she and her husband, Scott, moved last year to DC
Ranch, a high-tech housing development taking shape in the desert
foothills on the northern fringes of Phoenix's urban sprawl. Amid
the personal-computing boom, real-estate developers and architects
across the country are collaborating on new neighborhoods that
feature high-speed connections marrying the Internet, television
and telephone services. But DC Ranch is not intended as an
exclusive haven for the pocket protector crowd. The Arizona
developers, DMB Associates, have taken their technology a step
further by encouraging the use of computers to build personal
relationships among the suburbanites. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
