<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-PREVIEW (Undated) _ First the ballots get lost in a
postal snafu. Next a ``professional rummager'' finds 52 stolen
Oscars in the trash in L.A.'s Koreatown. We've graduated from
Oscarmania to vicarious enjoyment of the sabotage _ which I suppose
is merely a heightened strain of Oscarmania. The mood is
contagious. And with the NCAA tourney falling apart faster than
Bobby Knight's temper, Sunday night's Oscar awards show might be
all the March Madness anybody needs. Herewith: Predictions,
feelings. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-COMEDY (Undated) _ Hey, Oscar _ think you could lighten
up a touch? Death isn't all there is to life, you know. There are
other things. Chocolate, for instance. Chickadees. Jim Carrey
movies. Whoa _ sore subject for the Oscarooni. Oscar doesn't like
commedians, as anyone knows who has paid attention to the Academy
Award nominations, much less the actual awards, for the past two
years. By AMY BIANCOLLI. (For release Sunday, March 26.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-TITUS (Undated) _ ``Titus'' is a furious, bloody,
overindulgent, overcooked, maniacally entertaining Shakespeare
adaptation (nee ``Titus Andronicus'') from the crowned queen of
Broadway, Julie Taymor (``The Lion King''). By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-WHATEVER (Undated) _ You know ``Whatever It Takes''
is some kind of quaint high-school comedy/teen romance when a kid
actually uses ``smells like teen spirit'' to describe the vibe at a
party. Then, later, the Moby jam on the soundtrack is shut off so a
boy can eke out a version of ``I'll Melt With You'' on his
accordion for his girl. Hey, it brought a tear to her eye, and it
might bring one to yours, too. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-WAKING (Undated) _ On a college campus somewhere,
there blooms a love like Fielding and Sarah's. He wants to be
president and is on the Democratic fast track to Congress; she's an
activist who hates the U.S. government. It's 1971 or '72 and they
meet at a magazine run by Fielding's leftist brother and seem able
to put away their collegiate righteousness. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGES (San Francisco) _ As 88 gay and lesbian couples
held hands inside San Francisco City Hall and pledged their love to
each other, an unusual protest _ even for this city _ took place in
the plaza outside. By By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   DR.-LAURA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Dr. Laura Schlessinger is the Queen
of Contempt, a bully and a bigot _ the last at least when it comes
to homosexuals. That is her appeal. But gay and lesbian advocates
are running a very real risk of turning her into something else: a
martyr. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   EUCALYPTUS (San Francisco) _ Eucalyptus trees are like pigeons.
Some consider them pesky intruders, better dead than alive. Others
see eucalyptus trees as a gift from nature that add majesty to a
city taken over by asphalt and steel. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-APOLOGY (San Francisco) _ Sexual abuse victim Lorraine
Bruz won a cash settlement from the Santa Rosa Catholic diocese.
But on Saturday, Bruz will receive something more spiritually
symbolic than a monetary payment: a formal apology from the Roman
Catholic church. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   LADY-BIRD (San Antonio) _ Lady Bird Johnson, the oldest living
former first lady, returned to the San Antonio church where she was
married to visit with friends, including the college roommate who
was her maid of honor. Still chipper and gracious at 87, she
granted media interviews, signed autographs, ate lunch and enjoyed
the company of lifelong chums at St. Mark's Episcopal Church
downtown. By SUSIE P. GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   CAMEOS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Cameos not only make great jewelry, but
great works of art as well. Portraits and classical themes often
dominate the art of cameo cutting, which flourished in the first
half of the 1st century AD They are most often carved from
stratified stones or shells, which give the relief cut in the top
layer a background of a contrasting color. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEINS. (For release Sunday, March 26.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The Hearst Corp. has told a
federal judge that its plan to give the Fang family a $25 million
annual subsidy to publish The Examiner would create economically
competitive newspapers for the first time in 35 years. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAFFRON (Undated) _ Saffron is the world's most expensive spice
because of its labor-intensive harvest. The flower of the Crocus
sativus, a small purple crocus that blooms in the fall, bears only
three red-orange stigmas, which must be hand picked and dried. It
takes more than 14,000 of these tiny stigmas to produce 1 ounce of
saffron. Fortunately a little saffron goes a long way. By LISA
STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Yosemite, Tahoe, Shasta and
the Golden Gate may be the top outdoor destinations in California,
but not a one is the state's most popular getaway. You know what
is? That is, the No. 1 getaway for people not only from California,
but from throughout the world? I'll tell you what it is: It's
Disneyland, along with Universal Studios and Knott's Berry Farm. By
TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
