<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX     03-24 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't need same-sex marriage; we do need law to recognize
couples
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Social conservatives across the country stand at
the plate, hands tightly around the bat, waiting to knock a big fat
pitch from Vermont out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Vermont throws a butterfly knuckler.
</P>
<P>
   Holy hernia, batman.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, the Vermont Supreme Court ruled that
homosexuals were unconstitutionally denied the rights and benefits
of marriage. The court suggested strongly that the state broaden
marriage statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, the faxes and e-mails of the right were cranking
across the country plying the great political wedge issue of modern
times: homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont, the messages warned, was about to put every state in
the nation in the position of having to recognized gay and lesbian
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The wedge drivers weren't afraid. They were drowning in their
own saliva. They pictured the prospect of making same-sex marriage
an issue in campaign after campaign for statehouses. What better
way to ``out'' liberal agents of moral decay?
</P>
<P>
   But Vermont lawmakers may have left the mad faxers with a case
of cotton mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of passing a bill legalizing gay and lesbian marriage,
Vermont's legislature has sent to the governor a bill to create
``civil unions'' _ not marriages but arrangements that give
same-sex couples some of the same rights and obligations that
marriage does.
</P>
<P>
   That includes joint title to property, the right to sue over the
loss of a partner, the right to be joint beneficiaries in insurance
policies and to be treated similarly to a spouse in probate
matters. A civil union also would have to be dissolved in divorce
court.
</P>
<P>
   A marriage by another name? A duck called a goose? Vermont has
artfully dodged the name game.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to a 1993 ruling by Hawaii's Supreme Court that would
have cleared the way for same-sex marriages (later the voters
changed the state constitution to ban it), 30 states passed
pre-emptive laws saying they wouldn't recognize same-sex marriages
if legalized in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   In the Super Tuesday primary, California voters did the same.
(However, California does recognize domestic partnerships, as do a
host of municipalities and corporations.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, has Vermont laid all those pre-emptive laws to waste?
</P>
<P>
   It's a travesty that loving, committed lifelong couples cannot
be recognized as that in the eyes of the law. At its root is
nothing more than religion masquerading as law. ``In God's eyes''
is how marriage is commonly framed, end of argument. But government
is not a divine institution. Unfortunately, this barrier of illogic
will survive until the U.S. Supreme Court tears it down.
</P>
<P>
   A civil union has nothing to do with religion. It has to do with
contracts and commitments. Seemingly, everyone who values social
responsibility would encourage what a civil union represents.
</P>
<P>
   Heterosexuals who have no other stake in the matter, who have no
friends or relatives being discriminated against because of their
sexual orientation, should at least look at the civil-union option
in public health terms.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of AIDS, sexual monogamy is a life-or-death matter.
The irony of AIDS, with its prevalence among gay men, is that while
urging faithfulness to one partner as the best way to prevent it,
we make it illegal for the most at-risk population to ``make it
legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont has given other states a vehicle to end this argument in
the best possible way, leaving ``holy matrimony'' intact, or at
least extracting holiness from the debate in making civil law.
</P>
<P>
   Same-sex marriage is an unnecessary distinction. It's the union
that matters.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
