<P>
   Editors for publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; SATURDAY, March 25, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Korazim, Israel) _ Stepping into the pages of the
New Testament, Pope John Paul II on Friday sat on a lush,
rock-strewn hillside near where Jesus delivered the Sermon on the
Mount and asked young believers from across the globe to spread
Christian teachings of selfless love and forgiveness. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ Despite an outbreak of violence
at a Palestinian refugee camp and the sniping over Jerusalem that
ruined his inter-denominational gathering, the pope has managed to
present what some see as a model of brotherly discourse to
religious leaders here. He has also established a soothing tone
that made both Israelis and Palestinians feel endorsed by his
visit. A news analysis. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (Hyderabad)) _ President Clinton saluted India's
information technology industry on the last full day of his visit
to India. After having dealt with tricky strategic and political
questions, it seemed appropriate that the president should
concentrate on the economy, the area where there is probably most
commonality between the United States and India. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PAKISTAN (Islamabad) _ What may await President Clinton
when he visits Pakistan for five hours on Saturday. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TB (Dateline to come) _ How India is trying to conquer
tuberculosis among its poor. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECTION (Moscow) _ In an apparent effort to take votes
from Grigory Yavlinsky and ensure a first-round victory for
Vladimir Putin in Sunday's presidential election, Russian state TV
broadcast ``news'' reports on how Jews, gay men and foreigners
support Yavlinsky. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The Security Council meeting on
Iraq. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-POLITICS (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Saying he must bear
responsibility for the Nationalist Party's crushing defeat in last
weekend's presidential elections, Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-hui,
resigned Friday as chairman of the party that has ruled this island
for more than half a century. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-POLITICS (Belfast) _ A challenge to David Trimble's
leadership of the Unionist Party at a party conference Saturday
bodes ill for the peace effort. (Summary from wires.) By Warren
Hoge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-IDENTITY (Berlin) _ On the western facade of the
Reichstag is the inscription ``Dem Deutschen Volke'' _ ``To the
German People.'' That seems straightforward enough. But just how
complex, charged and divisive those words are has been revealed by
an outcry over a proposed work of art for the refurbished
parliamentary building. The problem, as usual in this country, is
who Germans are. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
</P>
<P>
   ILLEGAL-COHABITATION (Peralta, N.M.) _ In many places these
days, living together carries less of a moral stain than smoking,
but in New Mexico it is against the law. A journal. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   WWII-MUSEUM (New Orleans) _ When Stephen Ambrose decided to
found a museum on World War II, the first in the United States
dedicated to the entire war, he had no doubt about where to put it.
On June 6, the National D-Day Museum will open in Higgins'
hometown, New Orleans, La. The museum will focus on the Normandy
invasion but will tell the story of all the major amphibious
assaults undertaken by Americans during the war, including Pacific
engagements like Iwo Jima, Guadalcanal and Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES _ Politics &LR;  (Will move in `p' news category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTERS (Washington) _ Behind much of the political debate
in recent weeks, on issues from gun control to education, is an
intensifying struggle for the votes of women, particularly suburban
mothers. One of the first tests may come on the issue of gun
violence and gun control, which pollsters say is a far more
powerful issue among women than among men. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
