   &UR; UNITED STATES _ Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ The Pentagon is expected to release
a report on implementation of the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy
on gays in the military Friday. (Press conference scheduled for
1:30 pm EST. ) By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GAMES (Undated) _ The videogame business has been
redefined in just the last month. In Japan, Sony sold nearly 1
million Playstation 2 videogame consoles in the first three days on
the market. And in California, Microsoft jolted the industry with
the announcement of X-Box, a Windows PC masquerading as a videogame
console. But one should not forget the $4.2 billion industry's
greatest bit player of all: Game Boy, which engenders fierce
customer loyalty and has so far proven impervious to competition.
By Joe Hutsko.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC (Vienna) _ A curtain raiser to Monday's meeting of OPEC
ministers, where they will determine production increases and a
timetable. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BEER (Paris) _ European Union antitrust regulators raid
Heineken's offices in the Netherlands and Italy Friday as part of a
widening investigation into possible price collusion by the world's
No. 2 brewer and others. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OIL (Moscow) _ Lukoil, Russia's biggest petroleum
company, strikes oil in its section of the Caspian Sea, considered
one of the last remaining untapped reserves of oil. Lukoil's share
price rises 5 percent on the news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   COWBOY-POEMS (Undated) _ Ever since books of cowboy poetry began
to appear in the 1890s, the lyrical verses have evoked a sense of
lost romance and a disappearing way of life. On the history and art
of this poetry written by cowboys as they moved herds of cattle
from Texas northward. With excerpts. By Joyce Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-IDEAS-INTRO (Undated) _ A peek at several scholars' newest
works in progress.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   NEW-IDEAS-FLOWERS (Undated) _ Peter Bernhardt, a professor of
biology at St. Louis University, is looking at the similarities
between existing flowers and their extinct ancestors, whose fossils
are found in deposits of clay, sedimentary stone and amber from the
Cretaceous period. By Joyce Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-IDEAS-BALKANS (Undated) _ Karen Barkey, a sociologist at
Columbia University, argues that the region's history is much more
cooperative than many of the current explanations suggest. By Lynda
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-IDEAS-MONEY (Undated) _ Caitlin Zaloom, an anthropologist at
the University of California at Berkeley, wants to know how
technology is affecting the money managers who make decisions that
direct capital flow around the world. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-IDEAS-BOOKS (New York) _ Sometimes a bookstore is just a
bookstore. But sometimes, as today's Freudians should know, it is
also a publisher, a Website and a gathering place for readings and
lectures, like the newest venture by analyst, academic, editor and
psychoanalytic entrepreneur Michael Moskowitz.
</P>
<P>
   HIDDEN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ An air of desolation hangs over
``Hidden River,'' the feature film debut of Mercedes Garcia
Guevara, an Argentine director who shows herself an adept conjurer
of cinematic moods. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   ARGERICH-PIANIST (New York) _ Few people who have heard the
tempestuous, Argentinean-born pianist Martha Argerich perform ever
forget it. She is a colossal technician, a powerfully intuitive
musician, and an electrifying performer. But Argerich is the most
enigmatic figure in classical music today, by turns passionate,
disarming and chaotic. A profile. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
