<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-WHALES-$ADV26-     03-24 1761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-WHALES-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VICTORY FOR GRAY WHALES SIGNALS NEW POWER FOR MEXICO'S
ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS
 &HT;    (1400&AMP;ADD).
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGUNA SAN IGNACIO, MEXICO _ No place on earth exists like this
distant lagoon in the middle of Mexico's Baja California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Waves gently lap onto deserted shell-strewn beaches and stars
shine by the millions. And one of the sea's most enigmatic
behemoths, the gray whale, is willing to swim up to human beings
and allow a species that has killed them to caress their
barnacle-encrusted backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you scratch them they open their mouths. I even
touched a tongue once,'' laughed whale-watch guide Romualdo
Fischer, one of the local fishermen who used to fear and avoid the
whales until the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say they hope this magical relationship
between human and marine mammal will be preserved forever thanks to
a March 2 decision by Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo to scrap a
plan to build a salt-mining operation here in partnership with
Japan's Mitsubishi Corp.
</P>
<P>
   An isolated inlet 600 miles south of San Diego and three hours
from the nearest paved road, the San Ignacio Lagoon is the last
gray whale breeding habitat on Baja's coast that is untouched by
commercial development. Every winter, the whales, which were an
endangered species until five years ago, swim into the lagoon after
a 6,000-mile migration from the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Here they mate or give birth and train their young for the
rigors of life. Once hunted to the brink of extinction by Americans
who called them ``devil fish,'' the whales _ which can weigh up to
30 tons _ are now beloved by tourists who delight in the hiss and
spray of their powerful spouts. Hands reach out to pet the whales
as they cavort next to boats, curious to investigate the human
cargo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Mexico's president declared the San Ignacio Lagoon and
a vast 6.2 million-acre desert around it the Vizcaino Biosphere
Reserve, the largest such protected area in Latin America.
Zedillo's decision to call off the salt mine _ which would have
sucked water out of the lagoon and created miles of salt flats _
came after a five-year battle by Mexican and American
environmentalists that many consider the most significant victory
of their generation.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists forged a sophisticated model for action
they say could be replicated around the world to win similar fights
to save habitat.
</P>
<P>
   They filed a barrage of lawsuits in Mexican courts, and enlisted
the help of sympathetic scientists and celebrities like James Bond
movie star Pierce Brosnan.
</P>
<P>
   They used the Internet to link supporters in the Americas, Asia
and Europe, and convinced 43 California cities to adopt resolutions
against the plant and 15 U.S.-based mutual funds to pledge not to
invest in Mitsubishi. They started a consumer boycott of Mitsubishi
dealerships as well as other products, in California and bombarded
the company with more than 1 million protest postcards.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they embarrassed the Mexican government and
Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran this campaign like a modern political campaign, but
always with advice from the Mexicans,'' said Fred O'Regan,
president of the Massachusetts-based International Fund for Animal
Welfare.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 Mexican environmental groups joined the coalition
to stop the salt mine, and emerged from the experience stronger
than ever. The rule of law, always vulnerable in Mexico, received a
tremendous boost, said Alberto Szekely, the coalition's Mexican
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for all because we were able to make our
laws prevail,'' Szekely said. ``If the development had been
allowed, protections for all of Mexico's other reserves would have
crumbled.''
</P>
<P>
   Szekely filed repeated lawsuits in Mexico arguing that the
proposed salt mine violated this country's environmental laws and
the rights of fishermen living near the lagoon in a community
called Punta Abreojos. He had already won the suit on behalf of
fishermen in one hearing last October, and he expected his case to
be upheld if the fight had continued.
</P>
<P>
   Szekely also successfully sued Mexican environmental
authorities, forcing them to sanction the government and Mitsubishi
for infractions committed at an existing salt mine about 100 miles
to the north on the edge of another inlet, Scammon's Lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   That salt operation was found guilty of dumping batteries and
industrial discharge into a lagoon where whales also congregate.
Allegations of whether wildlife was harmed by these infractions
remain disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican writer and environmentalist Homero Aridjis was the first
person to signal the alarm over the second proposed salt factory.
Trying to protect animal habitat in Mexico, he said, is often a
frustrating exercise because laws are so frequently ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this time President Zedillo saw this had spilled out
beyond borders and that it might damage him politically,'' Aridjis
said with satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of this historic victory, however, environmentalists
now face the challenge of addressing the concerns of several
thousand fishermen in this isolated area who would like more stable
jobs and better education, health care and infrastructure here.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, environmentalists acknowledged, they now run the risk
of being seen as rich interlopers with little credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental community needs to demonstrate that it's not
just going to walk away from these people,'' said Robert F. Kennedy
Jr., a leading critic of the salt mine who flew to the lagoon this
month with other activists to celebrate Zedillo's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is a lawyer for the Natural Resources Defense Council,
an American environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   On the east side of the lagoon, residents must truck in their
drinking water from the nearest desert oasis, which is several
hours away. There is no high school, and only parents that can
afford room and board send their children away to study. Doctors
only visit the area every few weeks. And there is no power source
except for a few solar panels.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fishermen already are developing campsites and whale
watching for tourists here. But that activity only lasts for
several months out of the year. Most have to seek work elsewhere or
return to fishing full-time to make a living. Some initially
supported the salt mine, which would have provided construction
employment, 200 permanent jobs and cash for the area.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Peon, a fisherman who also owns a landing strip near the
lagoon, said most local residents turned against the project
because they feared it would spoil their fishing and nascent
whale-watching operations.
</P>
<P>
   But Peon offered a cautionary tale, explaining that people might
still be tempted to mismanage the lagoon if they face economic
hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Some years back, Peon said, fishermen in his cooperative had
such a dismal year they gave themselves permission to illegally
slaughter endangered sea turtles here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ate them and sold them,'' Peon said. ``I know if people in
the United States read this it will drop like a bomb . . . But
families were desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   To show they mean business with the fishermen, Mexican
environmentalists brought community development experts with them
on the victory tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next battle is to bring these people what they need and
what they deserve,'' said Melba Pria, director-general for Mexico's
National Institute for Indigenous Affairs. Experienced in
developing jobs in areas that are culturally and environmentally
sensitive, Pria personally opposed the salt factory.
</P>
<P>
   The village of Punta Abreojos, which sits on the ocean near the
mouth of the lagoon, could provide a model for well-managed fishing
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The village of 1,000 inhabitants has run a fishing cooperative
since the 1930s that exports abalone, lobster and other seafood to
Asia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperative is so prosperous, said Ana Maria Sandoval, that
she and her eight siblings were all able to attend schools of
higher education and become professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Punta Abreojos was almost solidly against the salt mine, which
would have placed an enormous ocean pier in the middle of sensitive
lobster habitat the community depends on.
</P>
<P>
   The town threw a feast and celebration for environmentalists
after Zedillo announced the salt mine's demise. Children sang songs
_ ``Pollution! No! No! No!'' _ and oysters and lobsters sizzled on
a beachside grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salt company tried to convince us by saying they would
pave our streets. They would bring us a big highway. said Brenda
Gayita, a university student home for a visit. ``But in exchange
for what?''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While the environmentalists assembled scientists who argued that
the salt plant would disturb the lagoon's sensitive ecosystem _ and
the whales _ Mitsubishi fought back with its own team of experts,
who contended that whales had co-existed well with the salt
operation on Scammon's Lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Wechselblatt, a vice president of public relations at
Mitsubishi International in New York, said the environmentalists
ultimately won by portraying themselves as ``David against
Goliath.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, President Zedillo saved face for the government and
Mitsubishi by declaring that the salt-mining operation probably was
compatible with the lagoon, but would certainly disturb the
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, some environmentalists suggested, may have also been
reluctant to allow a allow a controversial development in an area
that was designated a United Nation's World Heritage Site in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Rosental, Mexico's former ambassador to the United
Nations, also suggested that Mexican authorities are more attuned
to the demands of environmentalists now.
</P>
<P>
   Rosental _ who knows Zedillo _ was a powerful lobbyist against
the salt mine, enlisting the help of Mexican entrepreneurs who
donated space to put up billboards in Mexico City denouncing the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now,'' Rosental said, ``Mexico has had a reputation
for being easier to do business in than the United States or Canada
when it comes to environmental laws. But this now shows that the
government can't just plow ahead as it has done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
