<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SECURITY-$ADV2     03-24 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SECURITY-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. LOOKS TO RENEW, RESTORE RELATIONS WITH NEW RUSSIAN
PRESIDENT
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-AID-$ADV26.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. March 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Russians vote Sunday to chose their second
democratically elected president, the probable winner will be
Vladimir Putin, a man U.S. officials expect to strengthen ties with
Washington on national security issues like arms control, weapons
proliferation and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. relationship with the world's second-largest nuclear
power deteriorated drastically in the last two years, punctuated by
a high-pressure stand-off in Kosovo and anti-Western rhetoric by
the increasingly erratic former president, Boris Yeltsin, and
Russian generals.
</P>
<P>
   The slump was an embarrassment to the Clinton administration,
which counts U.S.-Russian relations as a cornerstone of its foreign
policy. Washington had sunk billions of dollars into the
post-communist economy, hoping to speed along democracy by
fostering capitalism. After years of money squandered on both
sides, the White House had little to show for the expenditure in
1999, both in terms of domestic Russian growth and international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with great relief for U.S. officials to hear Putin in
the months leading up to Sunday's(CQ) Russian presidential vote
make several overtures to Washington, including a surprising
statement in February that Moscow might consider joining NATO.
</P>
<P>
   This turnabout has triggered warm words from the White House
about Putin, despite alleged human rights abuses in Chechnya and
the mixed signals the Russian has given about how he'll treat
fledgling democratic institutions, like a free press.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see in Putin is a man who wants to leave the past in
the past and move ahead,'' said a senior U.S. official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, during a recent trip to Moscow. ``We see
the same way on many issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's major thoughts on foreign policy are summed up in
Russia's new national security doctrine, a document drafted last
summer while Putin was head of Russia's National Security Council,
refined after he became prime minister in August and then made
public after he became acting president on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the change of language in regards to use
of nuclear weapons, that it reflects a shift of strategic thinking
on the part of the Russians. However, the references to nuclear
weapons occupy only a small part of the document.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow-based defense analysts say the real development of the
doctrine is the weight given to internal threats _regional and
economic instability, and a ``critically'' ill-equipped army _ as
opposed to external threats, as the greater national security risk.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also point to the fact that the Russian security
document for the first time omits a section outlining which
countries fall within Russia's sphere of influence, and gives up
historic rights to military bases outside of Russia's territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great shift of thinking. It shows we are not concerned
with expansion any longer,'' said Alexander Zhilin, an ex-army
pilot who now works as a military affairs journalist with the
Moscow News newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the document does include harsh words about what Moscow
views as the development of a U.S.-dominated international system
of conflict resolution. The decision for NATO forces last year to
bomb Yugoslavia without U.N. approval is a symptom of this, Russian
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials say they have been
pleased with the tone set by Putin's seven-month-old government
concerning bilateral relations and security issues, especially the
revival of ties between Russia and NATO in March.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and NATO began cooperating after signing a May 1997
accord aimed at easing Russian fears about the alliance's eastward
expansion to Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, but relations
broke down in spring 1999 with the start of the 78-day Kosovo
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military officials insist that day-to-day working
relationships are more important than seeing eye-to-eye on every
international issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the closest friends can't always get along. What's more
important is consistency. We don't want another Pristina airport,''
said one U.S. diplomat, referring to the flare-up in tension after
a small group of Russian peacekeepers occupied the airport in
Kosovo's provincial capital in defiance of NATO orders.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's step towards the West came none-too-soon for the Clinton
administration and the budding presidential campaign of Vice
President Al Gore. White House officials say that renewal of ties
will go far in helping Gore against Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush when it comes to foreign policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first steps Putin will take toward enhancing
bilateral ties will come immediately after the Russian presidential
elections, when the Russian Duma is expected to vote to ratify the
START II arms control treaty, according to the deputy chairman of
the Duma Defense Committee, Georgy Arbatov.
</P>
<P>
   START II, signed in 1993 and approved by the U.S. Senate in
1996, lowers U.S. and Russian nuclear stockpiles to about 3,000
warheads each. After almost seven years of parliamentary bickering,
the Duma has consistently refused to vote on the issue. After
December elections, Putin now controls the largest Duma faction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the votes to finally push it through the Duma, thanks
to Putin's faction,'' Arbatov said in an interview this week after
heading closed-door meetings between parliamentary, Russian
Ministry of Defense and Foreign Ministry leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Both Russian ministries want to ratify the treaty, knowing their
cash-strapped country can ill-afford the upkeep on or security over
a massive stockpile of weapons. With internal terrorist threats now
a reality, as witnessed by the Chechen war, nuclear management has
become a priority for Putin, according to his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this hurdle out of the way, another divisive issue
lurks in the near future, namely President Clinton's decision this
summer about whether to commit the tens of billions of dollars to
developing a national missile defense system, a tool designed to
protect America from nuclear attacks from rogue states.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, besides the unanswered question of whether the
technology for such a defense is effective, is that the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, the cornerstone of arms control
agreements between Moscow and Washington, prohibits such a system.
Russia violently opposes it, saying it would disrupt parity between
the two countries and spark another arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Putin as prime minister made no hints Russia was willing to back
down from this position.
</P>
<P>
   Despite months of shuttle diplomacy by high-ranking U.S.
officials like Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Russia's
position remains staunch: that any amendment to the ABM would
signal the collapse of all weapons agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Arbatov said the START II ratification would likely include a
stipulation saying Russia would drop out of the treaty if the U.S.
violates the ABM pact.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overall upturn in bilateral relations, however, some
Russians fret over the support the United States has already
extended to Putin.
</P>
<P>
   They fear that the Clinton administration desire to sign arms
control agreements aimed at bolstering Vice President Al Gore's
chance at the White House this year will outweigh criticism in
human rights arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
