<HEADLINE>
COHEN ORDERS GAYS-IN-THE-MILITARY OVERSIGHT PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying incidents of gay harassment are ``more
widespread than I anticipated,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Friday he will appoint a special gays-in-the-military
oversight council to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen made the announcement in a breakfast meeting with
reporters and said the Pentagon will release a report in the
afternoon detailing a recent investigation that found a significant
amount of verbal abuse of suspected homosexual troops in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The council, said Cohen, will try to change the hostile
atmosphere that gay and lesbian troops often encounter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidents and use of abusive language (against suspected
gay and lesbian troops) are more widespread than I anticipated,''
Cohen said. ``I was surprised at the numbers of people who said
they saw some evidence of harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Benecke, co-executive director of the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Network, an organization that provides legal aid to
homosexual military personnel, said the findings confirm what the
group has said for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the Pentagon for six years that harassment and
abuse are a serious problem. I'm glad the Pentagon has finally
acknowledged it. But the key to stopping harassment is leadership
and accountability. We hope this oversight committee is not a
substitute.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said a major responsibility for the oversight council will
be to ensure that all military personnel are versed in new Pentagon
anti-harassment guidelines issued last month. The guidelines are
aimed at making sure the controversial ``don't ask, don't tell,
don't pursue'' policy on gays in the military is followed. The
policy allows homosexuals to serve as long as they keep quiet about
their sexual orientation and don't engage in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   The policy also is designed to ensure that troops who are
harassed can complain to their commanders without fear of setting
in motion an investigation into their sexuality. Gay rights leaders
have said that when troops report acts of alleged harassment, they
often are drummed out of the service.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon Inspector General's Office survey of personnel at
38 major military bases found that many troops simply were
unfamiliar with the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the survey findings underscore that ``we have a big
job to do in terms of really getting the instruction and training
out there and holding commanders accountable'' for preventing
harassment. He added, ``We still have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen said he was encouraged by one finding in the survey of
some 70,000 service members _ that many respondents said they felt
they could report harassment incidents without fear of reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen ordered the survey of the bases in the wake of the murder
last July of an Army recruit at Ft. Campbell, Ky., who was
suspected of being gay. The killing rekindled the debate over the
Clinton administration's seven-year-old policy on gays in the
