<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF PILGRIMS ATTEND POPE'S SEA OF GALILEE MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT OF THE BEATITUDES, Israel _ Standing where Jesus Christ
was said to have delivered the Sermon on the Mount _ telling his
disciples, ``Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the
earth'' _ Pope John Paul II on Friday warned a youthful multitude
against heeding the secular anti-Beatitudes lurking in the modern
Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the voice which says, `Blessed are the proud and
violent, those who prosper at any cost, who are unscrupulous,
pitiless, devious, who make war, not peace, and persecute those who
stand in their way,''' the pope said, speaking to thousands of
pilgrims from a platform overlooking the shimmering Sea of Galilee.
``And this voice seems to make sense in a world where the violent
are often triumphant and the devious seem to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Jesus called his first disciples together ``not far
from this very place,'' the pope said, ``his call has always
demanded a choice between the two voices competing for your
hearts.'' The pope described this as ``the choice between good and
evil, between life and death,'' and asked which voice the young
people would obey.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope asserted that Jesus' Beatitudes, recorded in the
Gospel of Matthew, continue to challenge Christians nearly 2,000
years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strange that Jesus exalts those whom the world generally
regards as weak,'' the pope said. ``He says to them, `Blessed are
you who seem to be losers, because you are the true winners. The
kingdom of heaven is yours.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who is making a weeklong spiritual pilgrimage to the
Holy Land, celebrated Mass outdoors before an estimated 150,000
pilgrims who had gathered, starting as early as 3 a.m., on grassy
slopes left muddy from an early morning rain.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-and-white Israeli flags fluttered near the Vatican's
yellow-and-white banners. In the crowd were also
red-white-and-black Palestinian flags and a banner that read, ``The
uprooted people of Kfar Bire'm welcome John Paul II.'' The banner
mentioning Kfar Bire'm, a village occupied by Israel in 1948, came
down halfway through the Mass, which started at about 11 a.m. and
was held under tight security.
</P>
<P>
   A semicircular black tent was pitched over the pope's altar and
platform, and he was shielded by bulletproof glass on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrims seemed to have traveled from everywhere. They
included not only Palestinians from Israel and the West Bank but
also Lebanese Christians, who were allowed to cross the tense
border from southern Lebanon, and a scattering of U.N. peacekeepers
recognizable by their blue berets. The pope's visit has been
enormously important to Christians who constitute a tiny minority
in Israel and had never been to an outdoor Mass like this.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nazrin Touba, 33, who works in an orphanage in Nazareth, arrived
in a bus with other Arab Christians at 3 a.m. Touba, who was pushed
up against a fence by the exuberant crowd, explained why she and
her friends had come to the Sea of Galilee, when the pope is
scheduled to come to Nazareth Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're afraid we might not be able to see him in Nazareth,''
she said. ``The security may be so strict that we won't be able to
go at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pilgrims came from as far afield as Romania, Guam, the
Philippines, Italy and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Marina Danese, 33, an Italian homemaker from Milan, said she had
left her family behind in Milan, Italy. ``I could see the pope
anytime I want in Italy,'' Danese said, ``but I could never again
see him in the place where Jesus lived.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though the Vatican has described the pope's visit to the Holy
Land as foremost a spiritual journey, he has been confronted by the
competing politics and tensions of the Middle East almost since his
arrival. Israeli officials have used the papal visit to assert
their claim to Jerusalem as a Jewish city according to the Bible.
And two days ago, Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat, as he greeted
the pope in Bethlehem, called Jerusalem the Palestinian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said that if such
problems are real, he could hardly avoid them. ``It would be a
fiction to walk on the clouds and not on the earth,'' Navarro-Valls
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      03-24 1676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEARST CORP. DETAILS EFFORTS TO SELL EXAMINER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hearst Corp. has told a federal judge that
its plan to give the Fang family a $25 million annual subsidy to
publish The San Francisco Examiner would create economically
competitive newspapers in San Francisco for the first time in 35
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst lawyers made the statement Thursday in a motion asking
U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker to dismiss former mayoral
candidate Clint Reilly's lawsuit to block Hearst's purchase of the
San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends the purchase would leave San Francisco with only
one daily newspaper and higher advertising and subscription rates.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contacted Walker's chambers Thursday to request a hearing
Monday seeking a temporary restraining order to bar Hearst's
purchase of the Chronicle pending a previously scheduled hearing on
his lawsuit set for April 13.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer, has said Reilly is concerned
Hearst's deal with the Fangs will not enable The Examiner to
continue as a viable newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst contended in court papers that its plan would promote
economic and editorial competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in decades, there will be direct economic
competition between two daily newspapers published in the city of
San Francisco,'' said Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer. ``The
contemplated sales of the Chronicle and Examiner will also promote
the diversity of editorial and reportorial voices that Mr. Reilly
claims to champion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs will preserve The Examiner's editorial voice, said
Halling, while Hearst builds the Chronicle into ``a world class
newspaper better able to compete in the Bay Area with other media
and major local and regional dailies owned by national
enterprises.``
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, Hearst's afternoon Examiner and the locally owned
morning Chronicle have been in a joint operating agreement, an
exception to federal antitrust laws that allows them to share
business operations while maintaining independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has been trying to complete a deal to buy the Chronicle
for a reported $660 million, which Reilly has opposed in court.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst argued in its papers that Walker should dismiss Reilly's
request for a preliminary injunction blocking its purchase of the
Chronicle, because Reilly is not likely to succeed on the merits of
his lawsuit and because the preliminary injunction would cause
Hearst irreparable harm.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst says it has only a fleeting chance to buy the Chronicle _
which a Hearst executive called a ``one of a kind opportunity in a
highly desirable market by reason of its demographics, affluence,
growth and geographical proximity to the world's technology center,
Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's agreement to buy the Chronicle could be terminated if
it does not close by May 2, the court papers say, although they
note that the deadline may be extended for as much as nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, the preliminary injunction Mr. Reilly seeks could
effectively kill the deal,'' Hearst said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst confirmed in the court papers that it had agreed to give
the Fang family, publishers of the thrice-weekly free Independent,
up to $25 million a year to help cover the cost of publishing The
Examiner as a daily sold by home subscription and news racks.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst did not disclose how much, if anything, the Fangs paid
for The Examiner. In court papers, Hearst characterized an earlier
offer from the Fangs as ``in effect . . . a negative purchase
price.''
</P>
<P>
   the court papers shed light on what Hearst described as its
exhaustive and daunting effort to sell The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Co. replied, ``definitely not interested . .
. good luck,'' according to the court papers. McClatchy Co.,
publisher of the Sacramento Bee, declined, saying, ``couldn't make
the numbers work.'' Times Mirror, publisher of the Los Angeles
Times, likewise passed, saying, ``can't see how to make money
there.'' Rupert Murdoch, chairman of the News Corp. Ltd., replied,
``too bloody difficult.'' The Unification Church, publisher of the
Washington Times, said, ``too hard to make (it) work,'' the court
papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst initially got only two offers for The Examiner, and both
demanded annual subsidies of up to $35 million and amounted to a
negative purchase price, the court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show Hearst's efforts to craft a deal that would
satisfy the U.S. Department of Justice, which was investigating
whether Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle would create an illegal
monopoly; local politicians, who had advocated maintaining multiple
editorial voices in San Francisco, and Reilly's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Through its New York City investment banker, Veronis, Suhler &AMP;
Associates Inc., Hearst contacted more than 80 prospective buyers,
the court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   They ranged from Internet giants like America Online and Yahoo,
to media heavies like the Tribune Company, Gannett Co. Inc., A.H.
Belo and CNET Networks Inc., to investment groups like Warren
Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway, Charles Schwab Corp. and the Saudi
Investment Financial Co.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little interest, Hearst said.
</P>
<P>
   Local real estate developers and wealthy individuals who might
have been ``trophy buyers'' also turned down the opportunity,
including Richard C. Blum and Doug Shorenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Unacceptable offers came from New Times Inc., publisher of the
SF Weekly and other weeklies around the country, and the Spanish
Broadcasting System, the papers say.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Hearst offered to sell The Examiner's editorial
assets, including its archives, subscriber and advertiser lists and
options to buy its editorial and news operations and a transitional
production and distribution agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But with no viable takers, and in response to concerns from
third parties not named in the court papers, Hearst expanded the
offer to a ``turn key'' operation, including a printing press on
Army Street, delivery trucks and offices.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there were potential offers from only four parties:
Pan Asia Venture Capital Corp. of San Francisco, the Fangs'
company; Leucadia National Corp., a New York-based firm involved in
insurance, manufacturing, trading stamps and purchasing properties
at attractive prices; Knight Ridder, owner of the San Jose Mercury
News and Contra Costa Times, and Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder was interested only if it could get Hearst's 50
percent share of its current joint operating agreement with the
Chronicle, under which the two newspapers split profits, Hearst's
court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Tony Ridder, chairman and chief
executive officer of Knight Ridder, said, ``We would only have been
interested if we could take the Hearst's position in the JOA, and
even then we don't know if we would have gone ahead with it.``
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's offer was not disclosed in the court filing, because,
Hearst said, it was part of confidential settlement negotiations
over his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Fangs and Leucadia initially demanded annual subsidies
of $25 million to $35 million, the court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   In their final offers, both still ``insisted on receiving annual
support payments from Hearst for at least $25 million over a
multiple year period,'' the papers say. ``Neither party expressed
any interest in purchasing the printing facilities or the other
additional newspaper assets for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst's exhaustive sales efforts demonstrated that no one was
willing to acquire The Examiner unless Hearst also provided tens of
millions of dollars to support The Examiner's operations for a
multiyear period,`` Halling said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, Hearst struck a deal to sell The Examiner to the
Fangs that included only the paper's name, archives, subscriber
list, examiner.com Web site, computers and office furniture,
delivery trucks and news racks. The staff and buildings were not
included.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst will publish The Examiner for four months after the deal
closes, which will be by the end of this month unless Reilly
obtains a court order blocking it.
</P>
<P>
   During the first eight months after the Fangs take over, Hearst
will contribute up to $16 million in publishing expenses. In the
next two years, Hearst will pay up to $25 million per year, the
papers say.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst said the sale arrangement should satisfy the concerns of
Reilly's lawsuit that Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle might mean
closing The Examiner and leaving San Francisco with one daily
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs have said they will publish The Examiner as ``a strong
local competitor,'' the court papers say, while continuing to
publish the Independent as a free paper three times a week. Alioto
told the Associated Press on Thursday that newspaper economics
experts have told him producing a viable daily metropolitan
newspaper competitive in advertising, circulation and news coverage
will cost $80 million to $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Reilly would drop his objections ``if the potential
buyer looked as if it were going to be a viable competitive
alternative to the Chronicle . . . but from the information we
have, that is not the case.``
</P>
<P>
   Halling argued in court papers that the continued publication of
The Examiner, along with many other media in the Bay Area, would
provide robust editorial and economic competition.
</P>
<P>
   Among newspapers, The Examiner now has a 7 percent share of the
market; the Chronicle has 27 percent; the Alameda Newspaper Group,
which publishes the Oakland Tribune, the Hayward Daily Review and
San Mateo Times, has 12.8 percent; and Knight Ridder's Mercury
News, Contra Costa Times, West County Times and Valley times
together have 29.5 percent, the court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   Other competition comes from radio, television, weekly papers
and the Internet. ``San Francisco is the most technologically
advanced and 'wired' community in the country,'' Hearst said in the
papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
