<HEADLINE>
SITE BRINGS PARTY TO THE STRIP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It should be a heck of a do this weekend, even by the sometimes
grandiose standards of Web start-ups. In this case, the online do
to do is the Hollywood Stock Exchange (at www.hsx.com) Oscar party,
which has also become the official celebration of the event for the
city of West Hollywood (where HSX just moved its headquarters).
</P>
<P>
   HSX has been around a few years now, functioning as a sort of
stock market simulator that tracks the ``value'' of about 1,800
Hollywood celebs and properties. You ``purchase'' shares in the
stars, hoping to realize gains as their value rises with their next
big hit, or in this case, Oscar win.
</P>
<P>
   From a purely sociological standpoint, watching the rise and
fall of stars, particularly leading into big events such as Oscar
night, is an engaging exercise, one of those zeitgeist-driven
experiences possible only through the hive mind of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, though, the site is going to be a little more
corporeal. It's taken over the south side of four blocks of the
Sunset Strip, from the Standard Hotel to the House of Blues. Even
the tattoo parlor and palm reader are renting out their joints for
themed transformations, and the whole stretch has been scrimmed and
lighted for dramatic effect, with bands performing tonight and
other special events going on all weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The big blowout is, of course, on Oscar night, when everyone's
favorite vegan dance-rock-blues-jazz-underground wizard, Grammy
nominee Moby, takes over the turntables at the House of Blues.
Earth, Wind and Fire will also be playing that night, and comedian
Rob Schneider will emcee.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck getting into the HOB that night without an invitation,
though _ not to mention getting through the chaotic Sunset Strip
traffic. But the party will be Webcast online, with 15 cameras
stationed around the House of Blues, and found online at
www.hsx.com/o2k.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's much smaller HSX event at the House of Blues drew
more than 1 million viewers, said HSX chief executive officer
Michael Burns. It should be an even more popular online event this
year. Plus, you don't have to worry about parking. &QL; 
POKE, AGAIN &QL; 
Warner Bros., knowing a good and fabulously profitable thing when
it sees it, will bring another Pokemon movie to U.S. screens this
summer, only about nine months after the first one blew through the
box office in record fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The cleverly titled ``Pokemon the Movie 2000'' will debut on
July 21.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest news for Pokemon fans is that the movie will debut
six new creatures, and once again, the new creatures will be on
special trading cards from Wizards of the Coast that will be handed
out at theaters. Here we go again. &QL; 
MIXED MESSAGE &QL; 
I know the U.S. Department of Justice is trying to stop illegal
hacking, but something tells me some of its campaign isn't always
working quite as intended. Exhibit A is the masthead of the winter
2000 edition of the magazine 2600:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hacking can get you in a whole lot more trouble than you think
and is a completely creepy thing to do,'' it says, quoting in large
type from a DOJ Web page (at www.usdoj.gov/kidspage/do-dont/reckle
ss.htm) aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   When quotes like this are put front and center of the magazine
that bills itself as ``the hacker quarterly,'' it's pretty obvious
at least some hackers !ital!like the idea of causing a little
trouble, however ``creepy'' it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of tweaking the legal beagles, 2600's cover features
what appears to be a screen capture from a video of
celebrated/notorious San Fernando Valley hacker Kevin Mitnick.
</P>
<P>
   He's pressing a ``Free Kevin'' bumper sticker against the window
of what appears to be the Metropolitan Detention Center in downtown
Los Angeles, in a nose-thumbing at federal prison regulations.
Mitnick recently finished five years behind bars for
computer-related crimes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloomearthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. This column and
related material can also be found all week at www.dailynews.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
