<SLUG> BC-WARRIOR-SPERM-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL SEA SPECIES ENGAGE IN SPERM WARFARE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MARCH 27, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By JON COPLEY  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life under the waves can get pretty crowded when you are a sea
squirt vying for space on the rocks. But these sea creatures have a
novel weapon _ they use their sperm to sabotage the eggs of other
kinds of sea squirt.
</P>
<P>
   According to a California marine biologist, this may be the
first example of sperm competition between species.
</P>
<P>
   Sea squirts spend most of their life clinging on to rocks, and
many are prolific spawners. Females and males release eggs and
sperm into the water, where they mix and fertilize. Any egg that is
fertilized by more than one sperm will not develop properly, so,
like other animals, sea squirts have evolved ways to prevent this
occurrence. Once a sperm binds to an egg, the egg releases an
enzyme that alters its surface, preventing other sperm from
attaching.
</P>
<P>
   Now Charles Lambert of California State University in Fullerton
has found that other species of sea squirts can subvert this
mechanism. Lambert studied two species, Ascidia nigra and Ascidia
sydneiensis, in the waters around Hawaii and Guam. Although the two
cannot cross-fertilize, the sperm of one still triggers the defense
mechanism in eggs of the other. This prevents the species under
attack from being fertilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one species can cause eggs of another species to die
without being fertilized, that takes a possible competitor for
space out of the game,'' Lambert says.
</P>
<P>
   This may explain why the males produce so many sperm.
</P>
<P>
   ``One function of the excess sperm may be to make some of the
other species' eggs infertile,'' Lambert says.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that germ-cell warfare between species may be more
common than anyone realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few people have looked to see if sperm that cannot fertilize
an egg can still render that egg incapable of fertilization,''
Lambert said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1304EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0088 </DOCNO>
