A6803 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-BENDING-LIGHT-NEW-SCI     03-24 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENDING-LIGHT-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENDING LIGHT OVER BACKWARDS  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MARCH 27, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By HAZEL MUIR  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ingenious new material appears set to turn everyday physics
on its head and open the way to entirely new kinds of electronic
components.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Russian physicist Victor Veselago worked out how an
imaginary material would behave if it had negative values for its
permeability and permittivity _ properties that measure how much a
material modifies magnetic and electric fields. Veselago showed
that the material would bend _ or refract _ a light beam
differently from a normal substance like glass. It would also
reverse the Doppler shift that warps the colors of very fast-moving
objects.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists couldn't test Veselago's ideas because, at the time,
no such material existed.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, David Smith, Sheldon Schultz and their
colleagues at the University of California in San Diego have made
such an object. It consists of arrays of copper rings connected by
wires. At a meeting of the American Physical Society in
Minneapolis, Schultz said his team plans to test Veselago's
predictions for microwaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're convinced it will work, and it'll be a dramatic
effect,'' Schultz says.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks such a scenario could provide exotic components for
uses such as satellite communication. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1304EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6804 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-MARS-GLACIERS-NEW-SCI     03-24 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-GLACIERS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ICE PLANET MARS  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MARCH 27, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By HENRY BORTMAN  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melting glaciers _ rather than flowing surface water _ could
have carved out the distinctive valleys of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Branching networks of small valleys have led many scientists to
conclude that rivers of running water once flowed freely across the
surface of Mars. But this would mean that the red planet once had a
much warmer climate than it does today and, apart from its valleys,
there is no evidence to suggest that Mars was ever warm.
</P>
<P>
   But Pascal Lee, a planetary scientist at NASA's Ames Research
Center in Mountain View, Calif., says the answer may be found on
Devon Island in the Canadian Arctic, where he is studying valleys
carved by glacial meltwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've been finding on Devon Island,'' Lee says, ``is a
wide variety of valley types _ from canyons to little networks of
small valleys _ that bear an uncanny resemblance to specific
counterparts on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he says, the Martian valleys ``cut through a
desert that otherwise has very little sign of water flowing
nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   The constant width and depth of Martian valleys over long
distances, their flat floors and steep walls are distinctive
features found on Devon Island, but uncommon on river networks.
</P>
<P>
   Lee believes that other Martian landforms, notably some large
canyons on the west end of Vallis Marineris, could actually have
been carved by flowing glacial ice. Devon Island also has canyons
like these, he told the 31st Lunar and Planetary Institute Science
Conference in Houston last week.
</P>
<P>
   If Lee is correct, Mars may have had a cold climate, in which
snowfall piled up to form glaciers that later melted in the heat
generated inside the planet. Mars expert Jim Head of Brown
University in Rhode Island welcomed Lee's work, saying the analogy
to Devon Island is helping him visualize how melting snow might
have produced valleys on Mars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
