<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of MON., MARCH 27, 2000,
and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BENDING LIGHT OVER BACKWARDS
</P>
<P>
   BENDING-LIGHT-NEW-SCIENTIST _ Researchers at the University of
California have set everyday physics on its head with the creation
of an ingenious new material that bends, or refracts, a light beam
in the opposite direction to a normal substance like glass. By
Hazel Muir. 200 words.
</P>
<P>
   THE ICE PLANET MARS
</P>
<P>
   MARS-GLACIERS-NEW-SCIENTIST _ The large canyons on the surface
of Mars could have been carved out by melting glaciers rather than
running surface water, Californian scientists say. By Henry
Bortman.
</P>
<P>
   RIVAL SPECIES ENGAGE IN SPERM WARFARE
</P>
<P>
   WARRIOR-SPERM-NEW-SCIENTIST _ Life is competitive for sea
squirts fighting for space on underwater rocks. Biologists in
California have found that rival species have a novel weapon to
take their competitor out of the game: They use their sperm to
disable the eggs of other squirt species. By Jon Copley. 300 words.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SYSTEM ALLOWS ANONYMITY ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FREESPEECH-NEW-SCIENTIST _ At what price freedom of
speech on the Internet? A new system designed to make publishers of
information on the Internet anonymous could make it virtually
impossible to investigate illegal material such as pornography. The
creators of Freenet say the risk is worth taking to maintain
freedom of speech on the Net. By David Cohen. 400 words.
</P>
