<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMINALIZING THE CLUMSY  

</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if life for the clumsy were not challenging enough, British
researchers have now come up with software that might make lack of
coordination a crime.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article in New Scientist magazine, unearthed by
News of the Weird connoisseur Chuck Shepherd, scientists have come
up with a way to assist police by rigging surveillance cameras with
a gizmo that electronically identifies people who are moving about
in suspicious ways.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, said one of the developers, someone ``awkwardly''
approaching a car is probably up to no good.
</P>
<P>
   As one of millions of Americans who are coordination-challenged,
I resent the implication that our awkward movements are a sign of
criminal intent or motivated by anything other than sheer
clumsiness.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it is amusing to watch us repeatedly drop our keys or bump
our heads as we get into and out of a car, but is that reason
enough to accuse of being car thieves?
</P>
<P>
   Although I have no research to back this up, I think it's fair
to say that 99 percent of the people who move about in an awkward
fashion are not criminals, at least not most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   (This is also an insult to people who ``are'' criminals most of
the time but are not awkward. These people may be a menace to
society, but is it necessary to strip them of all dignity?)
</P>
<P>
   People who cannot hand money to the drive-through cashier
without dropping a quarter and having it roll under the car are to
be pitied, not incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one might argue that awkwardness is a sign of superior
intelligence, not sociopathy. So deep in thought are we that we
sometimes forget to coordinate our bodies, with the result that we
step on rakes and smack ourselves in the face or drop slices of
pizza on our laps. (Topping-side down, of course. That may have
been one of the immutable laws of physics that we were
contemplating at the time of the accident.)
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is that in these days of political
correctness it is insensitive to refer to us as ``clumsy'' or
``awkward'' or ``klutzy'' or any of those other ugly words
including but not limited to ``gawky,'' ``oafish,'' ``bungler,''
``oaf,'' ``fumbler'' or the one that really gets under my skin,
``hobbledehoy.'' The disabled prefer to be called ``differently
abled.'' For us, ``coordination-impaired'' is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   What people need to remember is that the person who catches his
necktie in his trouser fly is not doing so intentionally; he is
merely a victim of one of those awkward moments that just happen to
occur much more often for the coordination-impaired than for
others. (Also be advised that while the person may look funny
walking around in that hunched-over manner, it is not polite to
laugh.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, just because a person is coordination-impaired does not
mean he or she cannot lead a full, rich, happy life. (Assuming he
or she can minimize the unintentional self-inflicted injuries along
the way.) Some of the most successful, influential Americans are
coordination-impaired. Take Al Gore, for instance. Here is a man
who cannot clap his hands and blink at the same time, yet he may
well turn out to be our next president.
</P>
<P>
   Would you assume that Gore was ``up to no good'' if he tries to
dance at his inauguration ball? Tipper might, if Gore accidentally
knocks her off the stage, but the rest of us, I think, need to be
more tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   Coordination-impairment may be amusing, but it's not a crime.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
