<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COL     03-24 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONGRESS HITS DEAD END IN TRYING TO SLOW PRICE JUMP AT THE PUMP
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Fearing voter road rage fueled by high prices at
the pump, members of Congress are scrambling for solutions to the
rising cost of gas. But oil is proving to be a slippery subject.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans first explored repealing a 4.3 cents-per-gallon
federal fuel tax only to encounter resistance from road builders
who might lose work funded by the levy. Democrat Sen. John Breaux
of Louisiana wants to open more coastal areas to oil drilling, but
he might have trouble finding many takers for that idea.
</P>
<P>
   House members were supposed to consider a measure that would
have cut foreign aid to nations that fix oil prices, but the
measure was gutted before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Republicans and Democrats agree on is that they
need to appear to be doing something about gas price hikes. ``I
don't think anybody on this floor wants to go home and face angry
people about the prices in this country,'' Rep. Karen Thurman,
D-Fla., told her House colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman, like some in the Clinton administration, wants tax
incentives to encourage uses of new energy technology such as solar
and wind power to decrease reliance on oil. Some Republicans are
skeptical to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``We doubt there is a breeze sufficient to fire the furnaces of
Bethlehem steel,'' GOP Sens. Jesse Helms of North Carolina and Paul
Coverdell of Georgia wrote to President Clinton this month. They
urged him to lean on Western Hemisphere oil producers such as
Mexico, Venezuela and Colombia to boost production.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the main Republican solution appears to be to blame
the Clinton administration for failing to see the price hike coming
and for not having a comprehensive energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great concern is that the United States government does not
really have an energy plan,'' complained Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss. ``There's not a short-term solution that's been
proposed by the administration. There's not a long-term proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKING A BITE OUT OF CRIME
</P>
<P>
   Countering the push for tougher gun control measures, a group of
House Republicans is offering a tough-on-crime measure that could
quickly funnel law enforcement money to Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rep. Bill McCollum, the Floridian who chairs a crime
subcommittee, the lawmakers are trying to enact a federal version
of a Virginia program that has led to a measurable drop in gun
crimes. Called Project Exile, the program imposes a mandatory
minimum five-year sentence on anyone convicted of carrying a
firearm during an array of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would make available $100 million in criminal
justice money to states that adopt such guidelines. McCollum said
Florida, Louisiana, South Carolina and Texas would already qualify
for the aid.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say such lock-em-up approaches simply pack offenders in
prison. McCollum conceded incarceration costs could rise under the
measure but he suggested the deterrent provided by his bill was
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is, if you commit a crime with a gun, you are
going to do a lot of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HELLO DOLLY
</P>
<P>
   Dolly Parton came to town to pick up an award for her endowment.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't another Washington scandal. The endowment in this
case is Parton's $7 million commitment to the Imagination Library,
a literacy program she founded and promotes.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of American Publishers honored Parton for her
efforts, and Education Secretary Richard Riley was on hand to
present the award.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting his own country roots as much as his education
credentials, Riley said that ``as somebody from the upcountry of
South Carolina,'' he was more than qualified to honor the country
music star.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the audience, Riley said, ``I do not see a lot of
people who know the tune to `I Don't Know Whether to Kill Myself or
Go Bowling.' Now, I can hum that tune. A few years ago when some
members of Congress wanted to eliminate my job I use to hum that
song every day. My staff got to the point that they decided to give
me a bowling ball as a present.''
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Republicans don't often praise decisions by the Supreme Court,
but they were happy with the recent ruling that the Food and Drug
Administration lacks the authority to regulate cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco-state lawmakers were especially thrilled, weary from
years of attacks on an industry critical to many Southern
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, said Rep. Howard Coble, ``is a victory for North
Carolina tobacco growers and cigarette manufacturers, along with
Congress' ability to decide who will regulate what products in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, most Democrats from tobacco-growing states and
districts had little to say about the decision, reflecting perhaps
their torn loyalties between tobacco farmers and President Clinton
who had pushed for the new FDA powers.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
