<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHO, WHAT WILL STEAL THE OSCARS SHOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ First the ballots get lost in a postal snafu.
Next a ``professional rummager'' finds 52 stolen Oscars in the
trash in L.A.'s Koreatown. We have graduated from Oscarmania to
vicarious enjoyment of the sabotage, which I suppose is merely a
heightened strain of Oscarmania.
</P>
<P>
   The mood is contagious. And with the National Collegiate
Athletic Association basketball tournament falling apart faster
than Bobby Knight's temper, Sunday night's Oscar awards show might
be all the March Madness anybody needs.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith: Predictions, feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BEST PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   Should win:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider''? Only if it's 1975 and there's no ``Nashville,''
``Shampoo,'' ``Cuckoo's Nest,'' ``Jaws,'' ``Barry Lyndon'' or ``Dog
Day Afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules''? Only if the four other nominees are
``The Cider House Rules,'' ``The Cider House Rules,'' ``The Cider
House Rules'' and ``The Cider House Rules'' - and as a promotional
tie-in, Planned Parenthood hands out apples and copies of the
Saturday Evening Post, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile''? You're kidding, right?
</P>
<P>
   And ``American Beauty''? Only if I'd never been to the suburbs
and had never read a John Updike or Philip Roth novel.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves ``The Sixth Sense,'' the only one of these movies
that actually improves upon a second or third encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: ``American Beauty.'' (``John or Philip who?'')
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Should Win: Russell Crowe. Heartbreak, rage and searing
vulnerability _ with a potbelly! (Or Denzel Washington, a galvanic
force on a disposable soapbox.)
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Kevin Spacey. Someone has been taking his Jack Lemmon
pills!
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Should Win: Hilary Swank. More than a sock in a crotch. Her
emotional investment goes so deep she can't fathom it.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Annette Bening. ``Boy, Warren's highly versatile, very
preggers wife sure was juicy in that glorified supporting role.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Haley Joel Osment. At last: A kid who's earned the
right to make us say all three of his names.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: I see a precocious Oscar speech.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Those are my hands thrown up. Chloe Sevigny showed
me how to love Swank. Toni Colette showed me how to love the
paranoid Osment. Catherine Keener showed me how to love Cameron
Diaz and John Malkovich _ acerbically, hilariously and at the same
time. So, her.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Angelina Jolie. She made crazy and emaciated
Academy-friendly. (Though I'm getting a Brenda Fricker-in-``My Left
Foot'' vibe about Colette.)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BEST DIRECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Spike Jonze. Was John Malkovich's head not the most
fascinating ride you got on last year?
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Sam Mendes, ``American Beauty.'' Emmy season comes
early!
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Charlie Kaufman, ``Being John Malkovich.''
Metaphorically sound, metaphysically amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Alan Ball, ``American Beauty.'' Yes, I've seen his ABC
show ``Oh Grow Up,'' but, still, that monologue about the plastic
bag was pretty beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ADAPTED SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Alexander Payne and Jim Taylor, ``Election.'' They
left all the raunch and ethical ambivalence in Tom Perotta's novel.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: John Irving. It's his book and, dude, it ``Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL SONG
</P>
<P>
   Should win: ``Blame Canada.'' PT Anderson leaned so hard on
Aimee Mann and her songs that she belongs in the supporting
category, but each vulgar tune in ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and
Uncut'' was a movie unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Will win: The race comes down to the cheesiest balladeer on
Earth (Diane Warren, ``Music of the Heart'') vs. the cheesiest
drummer on earth (Phil Collins, ``Tarzan''). Beat a snare: Collins
used Pamesano Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN LANGUAGE FILM
</P>
<P>
   Should win: ``All About My Mother``
</P>
<P>
   Will win: ``East-West.'' It has Catherine Deneuve, World War II
romance and, yes, World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL SCORE
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Gabriel Yared, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Rachel Portman, ``The Cider House Rules''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
