<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-WAKING-HN     03-24 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WAKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICS AND STRANGE BEDFELLOWS IN `WAKING THE DEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a college campus somewhere, there blooms a love like Fielding
and Sarah's.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be president and is on the Democratic fast track to
Congress; she's an activist who hates the U.S. government. It's
1971 or '72 and they meet at a magazine run by Fielding's leftist
brother and seem able to put away their collegiate righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   They go out to lunch, and in a matter of jump cuts he lays out
most of his political beliefs. She's attracted and repulsed. ``Can
I buy you dinner sometime?'' he asks. ``Can I talk?'' she retorts.
</P>
<P>
   A love is born, the glue of which is politics, ideology and some
metaphysics. It's not a romance so much as a dissertation with
feelings. But Keith Gordon's ``Waking the Dead,'' as adapted by
Gordon and Robert Dillon from Scott Spencer's elaborate mini-saga,
is sterile and unconvincing as a political-thriller love story.
Instead it relies on Billy Crudup and a wounded-looking Jennifer
Connelly to illuminate it, which they do hotly, like a pair of
halogen lamps that have been on all night.
</P>
<P>
   Since we are informed at the outset that Sarah has been killed
in a plane crash en route to Chile, she seems that much more
angelic in the flashbacks. Accordingly, things seem lighted by
halo, and Fielding's eventual suspicion that she's haunting him
only plays into the celestial dimensions. Fielding tells his sister
(Janet McTeer) he can still feel her when he is walking the New
York streets; she doesn't think that's something political
candidates ought to do.
</P>
<P>
   As involved as Crudup and Connelly beseech you to be with this
story, their very youthfulness, their nagging lack of adulthood,
keeps the film from being anything more credible than a tight
grad-school tryst. Convinced Sarah is still with him, Fielding
begins to lose it, circa 1985. But it's as though his inability to
pull himself together will cause him to fail his orals rather than
lose an election.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is still trying to parse out the contradictions of
adolescence and adulthood and infuse them with the same seriousness
and insouciance that he did with ``The Chocolate War'' and ``A
Midnight Clear.'' But he's never been able to make the twain meet.
In that thematic failure, he actually gets a grip on a handsome
love story.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most lived-in conversations between a movie couple
that I can remember, Sarah tells Fielding who she thinks he is and
about the guarantees of fate during a subway ride from a disastrous
fund-raiser. It's one of those indelible, all-too-real
confessionals college women have with their boyfriends in
candle-lit studio dorms with Joni Mitchell playing softly in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, Gordon happens to have the Joni queued. ``A
Case of You'' plays so many times, a floodgate opens and her entire
catalog threatens to come pouring in. ``Can't we think of this as a
wartime romance?'' Fielding asks Sarah early on. Only if the war is
over by the time classes start in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-24 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OUTDOOR ADVENTURE? TRY DISNEYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yosemite, Tahoe, Shasta and the Golden Gate may
be the top outdoor destinations in California, but not a one is the
state's most popular getaway. You know what is? That is, the No. 1
getaway for people not only from California, but also from
throughout the world?
</P>
<P>
   It's Disneyland, along with Universal Studios and Knott's Berry
Farm. That's right, the L.A. movie with a cast of thousands, make
that millions, 75-degree weather and where every visitor going
through the gate of the Magic Kingdom has stars in his or her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Especially kids, whose biggest fantasies come to life as you
watch.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy more accustomed to an ascent up the back side of Mount
Whitney than a frontal assault on Splash Mountain, I probably
looked like a man from Mars wandering around amid the crowds. After
all, I still thought they still sold ``E'' tickets for the best
rides at Disneyland. But my two kids, Jeremy, 12, and Kris, 8, were
more than willing to lead the way, acting as guides for my wife,
Stephani, and me.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a paradise for kids, and it doesn't take long for
them to become experts. The first stop always is Disneyland, coming
after the flight south, the terrorizing drive (via rental car or
shuttle bus) on the highways to Anaheim, and getting set in a
hotel. The first thing you notice is that spring has arrived,
temperatures are in the mid-70s daily, the happy crowds are up
early, walking to the entrance gates for the 7:30 a.m. opening (for
those paying an extra fee, and we'll get to that), talking in every
language imaginable, pointing at Matterhorn Mountain looming over
the park.
</P>
<P>
   This is the true United Nations. While walking to the entrance,
we heard people talking in Spanish, Japanese, Chinese, Indian,
German, French, Russian, even English. Everybody has the same silly
grins, myself included, something like Clark Griswold and family,
regardless of the culture. Disneyland is like religion: many paths,
one truth.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to figure out the magic of the appeal. The
best rides combine amusement-park thrills with Disney-type
production. The best, according to the experts _ kids _ are Splash
Mountain, Space Mountain and Indiana Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous moment, of course, is the head-long plunge at
Splash Mountain, where you sit in a boat-like ``log.'' First you
float along this ``river,'' with turns, rises and falls, in and out
of the mountain, then suddenly plunge in a heart-pounding surge,
what seems straight down into this pool, similar to a Class V rapid
at Hells Corner on the Klamath River. At the height of terror, a
remote camera snaps your picture _ they sell thousands of these
shots. If you've made the trip, you probably have one yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Close inspection of these photographs reveals the adults in
utter terror, yet youngsters with happy, excited grins. That should
tell you everything you need to know about the trip down here.
</P>
<P>
   You can have a similar encounter at Space Mountain, where you
climb into this spaceship-like car, then careen through space at
warp speeds, with unexpected drops, turns and rises. Let me tell
you, I have a pilot's license, am certified to fly high-power
aircraft, and have been charged by grizzly bears and swum Class V
rapids _ and nothing has ever scared me as much as this ride. This
was pointed out to me by my kids, who spent much of the week making
fun of me _ the ultimate bond between males _ simulating my howls,
screams and shouts of absolute horror, fright and panic.
</P>
<P>
   They said the ride was ``fun,'' of course, ``almost as good as
Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jurassic Park ride is not at Disneyland, but at Universal
Studios near downtown Los Angeles. Universal is part of the must-do
tour for every visitor to the region, and, unlike Disneyland, the
lines are far shorter and the waits minimal _ 5 to 10 minutes
instead of the 20 minutes to an hour that has become par for the
course at Disneyland. There is hope that the $2.1 billion expansion
of Disneyland, due to be completed early next year, will solve the
long lines and waits.
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park features sitting in a boat-like raft, then barely
eluding being eaten by a T-Rex followed by a drop-dead, horrifying
fall into water where everybody gets soaked. Because the lines were
so short, unlike Disneyland, some kids will repeat rides over and
over; they never blow a circuit on overload.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this park work is that you get to live through cinema
special effects in all kinds of scenarios, from time travel (``Back
to the Future''), riding a bike over L.A. (``E.T.''), an earthquake
(tram tour) and barely eluding being eaten by Jaws (tram tour),
among others, yet with no long delays. The tram tour through the
studio lots is like a trip into the past, the sites of creation of
thousands of movies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to complete the L.A. circuit, the other must-go is
Knott's Berry Farm. This is more like the ultimate amusement park,
featuring Ghost Rider, the highest roller coaster in the world, and
Log Ride, a kids' favorite for its simple thrills.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want overall shock, wait until you get the bill. The
entry price for adults at Disneyland is $76 for a three-day ticket,
plus an $8 surcharge for early gate privileges (7:30 a.m. instead
of 9 a.m., absolutely a must), with some hotels adding a $5
``surcharge'' for selling you the ticket, which is just a skim job.
Three-day tickets for kids 3 to 11 are $57, not including
surcharges. Universal charges $42 a day for adults, and Knott's
Berry Farm a little less than that.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels are booked near 100 percent nearly every day of the year
and commonly charge $100 and up per day for rooms with multiple
beds. Car rentals are the biggest gouge, $250 to $300 for a week.
The only flexibility is with airline tickets, with Southwest
offering fares as low as $56 (well in advance, a limited promotion)
to as high as $91 per seat. The cost of meals in the parks is
simply an outrage, often $25 to $40 for a family ordering
greaseburgers, fries and cokes.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a calculator for a brain to figure out that this
can turn into one pricey getaway.
</P>
<P>
   But do you know what? This is one of the few times when price
makes no difference. They could charge anything they want and
people would pay it. After all, there are no price tags on the
biggest smiles you've ever seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
