<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-OSCARS-COMEDY-$ADV26-     03-24 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-COMEDY-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHERE IS OSCAR'S SENSE OF HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 26)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, Oscar, think you could lighten up a touch? You're quite the
morose fellow, sitting there in your black turtleneck with your
dog-eared copy of ``The Bell Jar,'' always blathering on about
death and depression and death and catastrophe and death and failed
romance and death.
</P>
<P>
   Death isn't all there is to life, you know. There are other
things. Chocolate, for instance. Chickadees. Jim Carrey movies.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar doesn't like Jim Carrey, as anyone knows who has paid
attention to the Academy Award nominations, much less the actual
awards, for the past two years. Carrey turned in one of the most
praiseworthy, kudos-worthy, little-gold-man-worthy performances of
1998 _ as the titular television icon in ``The Truman Show'' _ and
turned in another last year, as Andy Kaufmann redux in ``Man on the
Moon.'' He deserved a nod from Oscar. But, no.
</P>
<P>
   The question, for those of us who fret over such movie-industry
bosh in advance of the handing out of the Oscars tonight, is: Why?
What is it about Jim Carrey that rankles the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences? Why can't they regard him as a Serious
Ac-TOR?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is, because he's not. He's a comic genius with
superhuman powers of mimicry and a dramatic well of surprising
depth. He can act, he can inhabit characters, he can do more
trickery with a line of dialogue than most heavy thespians, but
he'll probably never overcome his reputation as Butt-Talker first,
Actor second. All those vulgar antics during his stints as Oscar
presenter may have scotched his chances for good.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   MORBID SUBJECTS
</P>
<P>
   For if the Academy Awards do nothing else well, they take
themselves _ and the movie industry _ seriously. Most of the time,
films get nominated for tackling morbid subjects: murder, suicide,
the death penalty, mass human destruction, war, abortion, disease.
The grimmer the better, although the quintessential Oscar nominee
has a dose of uplift to boot; death often leads to redemption. And
if it makes us cry, perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the slate of this year's best-picture nominees.
``The Cider House Rules'' shocked a few critics (this one included)
when it earned a nod, but perhaps it shouldn't have. Besides
addressing a host of sober topics (abortion, drugs, death), the
film is triumphantly optimistic in tone and jerks buckets of tears.
Similarly, the damp ``The Green Mile'' entwines gruesome
electrocutions with miracles, a Christ figure of childlike
innocence and one heck of a cute mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' involves dead people and the depressed
little boy who sees them, but the movie is unflaggingly
compassionate _ even toward ghosts _ and manages to find closure
for everyone. Amend that: almost everyone. (``The Insider,'' on the
other hand, doles out neither death nor redemption, which doesn't
bode well for its chances tonight.)
</P>
<P>
   Even this year's most independent-minded best-picture nominee,
``American Beauty,'' conforms to the standard requirements. Death
is an unequivocal presence; the film is, after all, narrated by a
corpse. Yet Sam Mendes' bristling satire of consumerist ennui is
also shockingly, poetically spiritual, and its conclusion is filled
with hope. A nasty, funny piece of work it may be, but it's a
nasty, funny piece of work that makes us weep. If it wins tonight,
it'll win not on laughter, but on tears.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   None of this should surprise. Comedies do not generally win
major-category Oscars unless they're based on the Bard
(``Shakespeare in Love''), involve melodramatic death scenes
(``Terms of Endearment'') or are set in World War II prison camps
(``Stalag 17,'' ``Life is Beautiful''). Cynicism doesn't tell us
this; experience does.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions to the rule _ the odd ``Annie Hall'' or
``It Happened One Night'' (or even ``The Sting'') _ that wins on
funny bones alone. But by and large, Oscar prefers highbrow to
lowbrow, tragic to comic, Stanislavsky sturm-und-drang to air-light
verbal jousting (to say nothing of poop jokes).
</P>
<P>
   So it is, most years. And so it is in the individual performance
categories. As Emil Jannings proved to Charlie Chaplin at the first
Academy Awards in 1929, loud dramatic puffing wields the upper
hand. If the role involves death, disease, depression or disability
_ the four D's _ then the chances of winning become almost
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   By that reckoning Kevin Spacey should win for his performance in
``American Beauty'' _ he's funny, but he's dead _ as should Hilary
Swank for ``Boys Don't Cry,'' although Julianne Moore (``The End of
the Affair'') certainly qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   And when a purely comic performance does earn an Oscar, it's
most often in the supporting categories: Kevin Kline for ``A Fish
Called Wanda,'' Mia Sorvino for ``Mighty Aphrodite.'' Those who
score in the best-actor categories for a humorous role tend to be
either powerhouse dramatic types slumming in comedy _ Jack
Nicholson, Lee Marvinor total flukes. Roberto Benigni, who won last
year for ``Life is Beautiful,'' might qualify as the latter sort
were it not for the fact (spoiler!) that he dies at the end of the
film. Call it the Cruel End Dispensation.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   OVERLOOKED COMEDIANS
</P>
<P>
   Just think of the comic geniuses who haven't scored with Oscar:
Eddie Murphy, Buster Keaton, Steve Martin, Peter Sellers, Mae West.
Although Charlie Chaplin won in plenty of other categories, he
never earned an acting award. And Cary Grant, whom film historian
David Thomson once called ``the best and most important actor in
the history of the cinema,'' had to wait until he'd retired before
the industry got around to recognizing him with a consolation-prize
``Honorary Oscar'' in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Cranks and film buffs, take note: Grant was never even nominated
for a humorous role. He was tapped twice, once for being soppy
(``Penny Serenade''), once for being wooden (``None But the Lonely
Heart''). Never for being a charm.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the entire history of the Oscars, only two bona fide
comedians have ever earned acting awards. The most recent was
Benigni. The year before, Robin Williams received best supporting
actor for his bit as the kindly shrink in ``Good Will Hunting.''
Although Benigni's qualified (more or less) as a comic role,
Williams' did not _ his was more in line with the fuzzy-wuzzy parts
he's accepted of late.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' persona is, at least, cozier than Jim Carrey's, so the
Academy doesn't hold his funnyman roles against him. Still, it
speaks volumes about Hollywood's morose disposition that the
century's greatest comic actors haven't won Oscars for their
greatest comic performances. Decades from now, movie nerds will
still be watching (in some form or another) Keaton in ``The
General,'' Chaplin in ``The Gold Rush,'' Sellers in ``The Pink
Panther.'' The films will remain, embraced with belly laughs, eons
after everyone's forgotten who clutched the best-actor statue in
1935 (Victor McLaglen, ``The Informer'').
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   STARCHY CONSEQUENCE
</P>
<P>
   Awards are fun, but they're meaningless. Although a few brave
souls have suggested the Oscars follow the Golden Globes' lead and
split the major awards between comic and dramatic performances,
comic and dramatic films, the chances of that happening are just
shy of nil. Members of the Academy regard themselves and their
movies with too much starchy consequence to start passing out
awards for mere frivolity.
</P>
<P>
   You and I and Uncle Ed may take our movies as entertainment, but
in Hollywood they're serious business. They're art. And sometimes
they are, but often as not the films that get ignored by the
Academy boast the purest art of all: that which relieves us from
the quotidian pains of life. Good comedy is impossibly hard to pull
off, harder than melodrama, harder than shake-n'-bake camerawork or
egghead philosophizing.
</P>
<P>
   But when it works _ when that bubble of laughter begins its
unstoppable swell _ the result can be as transporting and
illuminating as the muddiest trek through Bergman. Yes, human
existence is fraught with grief and ends with death and the good
lord knows what's next. Too true, too true; we've seen it on bumper
stickers (``Life's a __ and then you die'') and in multiple
screenings of ``The Seventh Seal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a great film comes along that reminds us,
beautifully, of our mortality. Sometimes, a great film comes along
that doesn't. Oscar or no Oscar, three cheers for the ones that
don't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
