<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-SAFFRON-HNS &LR;      03-24 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFFRON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A PINCH OF SAFFRON IS WORTH THE PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA STEVENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saffron is the world's most expensive spice because of its
labor-intensive harvest. The flower of the Crocus sativus, a small
purple crocus that blooms in the fall, bears only three red-orange
stigmas, which must be hand picked and dried. It takes more than
14,000 of these tiny stigmas to produce 1 ounce of saffron.
Fortunately a little saffron goes a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Saffron was used by ancient civilizations in the eastern
Mediterranean, writes Jill Norman in ``The Complete Book of
Spices.'' The Romans and the Egyptians used it in food, wine, as a
clothing dye, in perfumes and as a drug. In the seventh century,
saffron was in demand in China for use as a drug and in perfume. In
the 10th century it was being grown in Spain, probably taken there
by the Arabs, Norman says. In the 11th century it reached Germany
and France; by the 14th century it was in England.
</P>
<P>
   Today the aromatic and pungent spice is used to flavor and color
food.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: The red-orange stigmas from a small purple crocus.
</P>
<P>
   FORMS: Threads, ground
</P>
<P>
   LOOK FOR: Blood-red threads with very few yellow threads. A
brown color means the saffron has lost its potency. It should have
a rich aroma and be very lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   STORE: In an airtight container in a cool, dark, dry place for
up to six months.
</P>
<P>
   USE IN: Fish, poultry, pasta, potatoes, breads, risotto and rice
dishes. In Spain it is a key ingredient in paella. In Britain it is
used to make saffron cakes. Turmeric, safflower petals and marigold
petals can all be used as substitutes for saffron because they also
produce the yellow color, although they do not yield the same
taste.
</P>
<P>
   COST: Threads $5 per gram
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   MONKFISH PARCELS WITH SAFFRON
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds monkfish, boned
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 3/4 teaspoon saffron threads
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 pound large spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the monkfish into cubes and season with salt and pepper.
Crush the saffron threads and soak in a little hot water for a few
minutes. Heat the wine and water in a skillet, add the saffron
liquid and stir.
</P>
<P>
   Add the monkfish and simmer for about 5 minutes. Drain
carefully; reserve the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Select enough large spinach leaves to make 3 or 4 parcels per
person. Wash the leaves, remove the stalks and blanch in boiling
water for 2 to 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the leaves, vein side up, and put some of the pieces of
monkfish at the stalk end. Wrap the parcels firmly, making sure the
sides are tucked in. Place them in a buttered gratin dish with the
end of the leaf underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the reserved cooking liquor over the parcels. Cover with
foil and bake for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Complete Book of Spices,'' by Jill Norman (Viking,
1990)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
