<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6825 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-GOLDMAN-LADN &LR;      03-24 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-GOLDMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIEW FROM THE TRENCHES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Goldman has won a couple of Oscars for his screenplays
(for ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' and ``All the
President's Men,'' to be specific), but if they handed out awards
for best anecdotes, he'd need a new trophy case. He's a raconteur
of the highest order, assembling his Hollywood horror stories into
a couple of eminently readable books: ``Adventures in the Screen
Trade'' and its sequel, the just-released ``Which Lie Did I Tell?''
</P>
<P>
   In the new book, he tells tales out of school (his take on Chevy
Chase working on ``Memoirs of an Invisible Man'' is priceless) and
offers an invaluable insight into screenwriters' minds by
submitting a script of his to some scribe pals, letting them rip
him to shreds and publishing the whole mess. His books are very
nearly as much fun as talking to him in person.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he's perhaps best-known for his quintessential
Hollywood axiom, ``Nobody knows anything.'' Which makes him, to our
mind, the perfect guy to handicap Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   We sat down with Goldman in his publisher's office and asked him
about the Oscars, particularly the screenwriting categories. He
made but one flat declaration, for the best actor category: ``I'm
hoping for Denzel Washington, because I thought that was one of the
major pieces of acting I've seen in a very long time.'' He added,
``How did `Boys Don't Cry' get away with being relatively
inaccurate, how did
</P>
<P>
   `The Insider' get away with being relatively inaccurate, and why
did they hammer 'Hurricane'?''
</P>
<P>
   Before turning to his predictions, Goldman noted, ``Miramax
changes everything. I don't know what they do, I don't know how
they do it, I don't think they just out-buy everybody. I don't
understand; it's magical. Of the five movies that are up, what is
'Cider House Rules' doing there? What is it (BEGIN ITAL)doing (END
ITAL) there? Premiere magazine prints a list of 100 movies rated by
critics, smart critics _ I think 'Cider House Rules' was 43rd out
of 100. So I can't predict anything. If any (other studio) had
'Cider House Rules,' I would think 'American Beauty' would do very,
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   One last thing: Like everyone else, Goldman thinks most of these
films were too long. He quotes George Roy Hill, who directed
``Butch Cassidy'': ``If you can't tell your story in an hour and 50
minutes, you better be David Lean.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true, says Goldman. ``'The Insider' was terrific, but why
was it two hours and 40 minutes? 'Magnolia' was 11 hours and 'Green
Mile' was eight. Here's my theory _ 10 years ago, this (BEGIN
ITAL)actor(END ITAL) _ '' in Goldman's mouth, the word sounds like
the worst expletive _ ``makes a western and it's a disaster and it
costs a fortune; he's risked his career and everything. And it's a
huge hit, it's Kevin Costner's 'Dances With Wolves.' And I think
the other directors, none of them immune to (proving their manhood,
Freudian-wise), say, `If that (BEGIN ITAL)(expletive) actor(END
ITAL) can do that, don't tell me I can't tell my story in two hours
and 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, here's Goldman's take on the 10 best screenplay
nominees, which includes all the best picture nominees. &QL; 
!folo!Best original screenplay:
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty:'' ``Terrific screenplay,'' Goldman enthuses
of Alan Ball's suburban satire. ``I have troubles with some of the
things _ this is not the screenwriter. In the screenplay, Kevin
Spacey's character has sex with the teen girl. In the movie, he
says, 'Cease and desist; you're a virgin, child.' Well, that's (a
naughty word meaning 'unlikely'). I don't know whose fault it is,
but that damaged the movie for me. You don't have to change
anything, you show them embrace, you dissolve; they're embarrassed,
she leaves. The original script, which I thought was brilliant, the
kids go to jail for that. I loved that. I also have trouble with
the 18-year-old drug pusher as God _ 'Come, child, you and I will
go to New York, I have $40,000 tucked away.' But it's a terrific
movie; I don't want to sound that critical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'': ``The one movie I have zero problem with is
'Sixth Sense,''' Goldman says of M. Night Shyamalan's supernatural
thriller. ``Solid, wonderful storytelling. And for me, the best
scene is not the ending, but the scene in the traffic jam toward
the end with the mother and the son where they talk about the
grandmother. That was just wonderful. But _ do you have any sense
of a great campaign for this movie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being John Malkovich'': ``I thought it was brilliant,'' the
writer says of Charlie Kaufman's Dada-esque comedy. ``It had two of
the great jokes of my life _ the seventh-and-a-half floor, and the
way people kept falling into New Jersey. I loved it! I felt, after
an hour, it got a little convoluted.'' Goldman adds that there were
three times he thought he was sitting through a near-perfect movie
this past year, only to have them go awry, to varying degrees,
after about an hour _ this one, ``Three Kings'' (which isn't even
nominated) and ``The Cider House Rules'' (its dropoff, he felt, was
most severe).
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'': Writer-director Paul Thomas Anderson is ``a very
brilliant kid,'' Goldman believes. That said, his criticisms:
``There are three stories intertwined, and two are of old guys
dying of cancer? And the moment when everybody in the cast starts
singing, and poor Jason Robards is singing in his bed _ come on!
There's some wonderful stuff in there, but I wish he'd had a great
producer. ... When the frog slides down the windshield, I thought,
'What a dopey-looking frog!' Some of it, like the game show, that's
terrific stuff. He deserves all the success that he's had _ I just
hope his next movie is not four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Topsy-Turvy'': ``I think Mike Leigh's really talented, and I
love Gilbert and Sullivan,'' Goldman says. That's the good news.
The bad: ``I wish all the critics who raved about 'Topsy-Turvy' got
on a desert island for the rest of their lives with only
'Tospy-Turvy' to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   His prediction: ``American Beauty.'' His preference: ``Beauty''
or ``Sixth Sense.'' &QL; 
!folo!Best adapted screenplay
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rule'': ``The first hour was wonderful, and
the second hour was not as wonderful,'' Goldman observes of John
Irving's adaptation of his own novel. ``I thought it was wonderful
when he was in the orphanage, and I thought it went off the cliff
when (Tobey Maguire's character) left the orphanage. I thought once
Michael Caine was gone, the interest was gone. But I wouldn't be
surprised if it won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'': ``Fun _ liked (Reese Witherspoon); liked the
script; wished it had done more business,'' Goldman says of the
script by Alexander Payne and Jim Taylor. ``People point to all the
great movies, but I don't think anything has changed that much.
None of (the truly acclaimed films) did a lot of business _
'American Beauty's' the shock; it's a great success. But the other
movies didn't take off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'': ``Solid work _ I didn't know why people didn't
want to go see it,'' Goldman says of Michael Mann and Eric Roth's
deconstruction of tobacco industry sleaze. ``You can sell it, and
Disney loved that picture and it's a quality film and Al Pacino's a
good selling tool and a brilliant actor, and they didn't want to
go. In all the years that I've been doing this, I (BEGIN
ITAL)never(END ITAL) ask myself, is this going to be a hit or a
flop, because I have no sense for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'': ``That's a wonderfully done
movie,'' says Goldman of writer-director Anthony Minghella's
follow-up to his Oscar winner ``The English Patient.'' ``I remember
the novel and the movie 'Purple Noon,' where Alain Delon, who was
the world's most beautiful human being, played Ripley. I would have
liked to have seen the movie with Matt Damon and Jude Law flipping
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile'': ``I was very moved with 'Green Mile,' but I
had a problem with the (framing sequence), which takes 20
minutes,'' he says. ``I cried at (writer-director Frank Darabont's)
screenplay. I read the book after and just thought some of those
moments hit me. Oh my God, when the (guard) kills the mouse, and
there's a great shot from behind that giant black hand saying,
'Bring me Mr. Jingles.' I just went.''
</P>
<P>
   His prediction: ``Cider House Rules.'' His preference:
``Insider'' or ``Green Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   And because he's just that kind of guy, Goldman offered a bonus
piece of prognostication for next year's race: ``I've read the 'Me
Myself and Irene' script (by Peter and Bobby Farrelly and starring
perennial snubbee Jim Carrey), and I think it's going to be bigger
than 'There's Something About Mary.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
