<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE MAKES IT EASIER TO TRACK ANCESTRY  
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new software program for genealogy _ the third most
popular hobby in the United States _ that's impressive in its size,
its depth and its weight.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, weight. Generations Family Tree Millennium Collection from
SierraHome tips the bathroom scales at a full 5 pounds, hefty by
any standards. It's part of the Generations series of genealogy
software from SierraHome.
</P>
<P>
   There are 21 CD-ROMs in the package _ another record in that
category for software that I've reviewed over the last 17 years.
They contain more than 200 years of records and resources with more
than 350 million names. There are links to more than 60,000
genealogy Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 19 million Americans are actively tracing their
roots and it's becoming more important than ever to preserve this
precious family history for information for future generations,''
said Mark Winters, senior brand manager for Generations.
</P>
<P>
   SierraHome has timed the release of the software for April's
unveiling of the Immigrant Wall of Honor by the Ellis Island
Foundation. The wall honors the 12 million immigrants who went
through that port. More than 40 percent of all Americans can trace
an ancestor through Ellis Island, a SierraHome spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   There are digital images of handwritten 1800 census data for the
ports of New York, Charleston and Philadelphia, along with an
extensive history of the Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   A video, ``Remembering Ellis Island, Everyman's Monument,''
running for an hour, is also part of the package, as is the book,
``American Naturalization Records 1790-1900,'' which tells how to
use naturalization records in searches.
</P>
<P>
   The CDs also contain marriage and land records for the United
States from 1560 to 1907 and information on 19th century immigrant
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Registered users of the program get a free month's access to
Ancestry.com, which has more than 500 million records; a free name
search by a professional genealogist with access to 2 billion
names; a photo editing program for repairing and restoring family
photos; and flexible carting capabilities for making family trees
using drag-and-drop editing.
</P>
<P>
   The software is available for Windows with a shelf price of
around $65-$70.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. The Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
