<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-NEWBORN-BRAIN-CAP-NYT     03-24 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBORN-BRAIN-CAP-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COOLING CAP' MAY MITIGATE NEWBORN BRAIN DAMAGE 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from The New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (A color photo is available electronically)
 &HT;    
 By JULIANNE REMINGTON  
 c.2000 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a difficult delivery Angela Douglas learned that her baby
had suffered extreme oxygen deprivation during birth and lacked
normal muscular reactions.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of a small percentage of newborns who become starved
for oxygen and are at risk to suffer brain damage and develop
neurological problems including cerebral palsy, mental retardation,
or epilepsy. Recent research offers hope for these babies if
physicians can identify them in time.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the infant's temperature by using a cooling cap for
approximately 72 hours seems to protect the delicate chemistry of
the developing brain.
</P>
<P>
   Cooling Angela Douglas's baby Jaydon seemed to work wonders. The
cascade of chemical reactions that can lead to brain damage
apparently stopped as the baby's temperature decreased a few
degrees. The cap that doctors put on his head was lined with tubes
circulating cool water. The experimental therapy is currently
undergoing clinical trials worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a little cycling cap,'' says Angela. ``When
they took it off Jaydon on the fourth day, and warmed him back up,
he started taking breast milk almost right away. He gripped my
finger and looked right at us.''
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic improvement in baby Jaydon's reactions continued,
and one week later he had a brain scan that appeared normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cooling procedure helps reduce swelling,'' says Dr.
Marianne Thoresen of St. Michael's Hospital in Bristol, England.
``Placing a cap on the head cools the brain and the whole body.
When the brain lacks oxygen, nerve cells get damaged in a process
that lasts about three days. We think that cooling during this
period stops or reduces those processes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoresen explains that the severity of oxygen starvation varies
a lot. ``We treat perhaps only 2 percent of newborns for oxygen
deprivation. It's a rare condition, but a devastating one because
babies may develop cerebral palsy, mental retardation, or epilepsy
later.''
</P>
<P>
   WARMING
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't run into any big problems with the cooling
procedure itself,'' says Thoresen. ``And we're pleased that so many
of the babies have done quite well. But until we have more results
from clinical trials, we cannot say that the cooling cap definitely
works.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the issue is the fact that babies who have been
starved for oxygen frequently show numerous side effects and
require intensive care. They can have low blood pressure and other
complex problems later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we warm the baby too fast, the baby's blood pressure may
drop,'' explains Thoresen. ``So we have to warm the baby very, very
slowly, not faster than a half a degree per hour. And we monitor
all the cardiovascular signs too.''
</P>
<P>
   MANY UNKNOWNS
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged by the results we're seeing with the cooling
cap,'' says Dr. John Wyatt of University Hospital in London. ``I
hope this becomes a significant advance in treating babies in
danger of brain damage.''
</P>
<P>
   It's often impossible to predict which babies will have
difficulties at birth. ``In about half the cases, we don't know why
the baby lacks sufficient oxygen,'' says Thoresen. ``Sometimes the
umbilical cord can be wrapped around the neck, but that's not
usually the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   With oxygen-starved infants, it's critical that doctors
intervene to prevent brain damage within the first six hours after
birth. ``We think that temperature is extremely important during
that time,'' says Thoresen.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians used to think that injury from lack of oxygen
happened instantaneously. ``We now think brain damage takes more
time before it becomes permanent,'' says Wyatt. One of the real
challenges is identifying these babies immediately after birth so
we can intervene in time.''
</P>
<P>
   IDENTIFYING BABIES AT RISK
</P>
<P>
   No reliable tests were available to help sort out the vulnerable
infants from the large portion of babies who are not at risk. But a
new test may be on the horizon, as reported in the July 29, 1999
issue of The New England Journal of Medicine. Researchers
discovered that urinalysis can help indicate which babies suffer
the highest risk.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently oxygen-deprived babies, who are most likely to suffer
brain damage, have a higher ratio of certain metabolic products
called lactate and creatine in their urine. The new test may
provide a relatively simple way to identify oxygen-starved newborns
prone to brain injury.
</P>
<P>
   A large proportion of oxygen-starved babies do not grow up to
have cerebral palsy or other neurological disorders. But one in
every 1,000 infants begins life with such a severe struggle for
oxygen that he or she may lose critical brain functions that govern
movement, posture and intelligence. The British team says effective
interventions are needed that can save these infants from
irreversible brain injury and permanent disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take about three years before doctors know for certain
whether the cooling cap makes a difference in the outcome for
oxygen starved infants,'' says Wyatt. ``We won't know for sure if
it's effective until the babies in the trials get older.''
</P>
<P>
   For Angela and her husband, the treatment couldn't have worked
out better. ``I don't think Jaydon would have made it if it wasn't
for the cooling cap,'' says Angela. ``He's just a miracle baby. He
didn't cry at all when he was born, which worried me terribly. Then
to see him four days later looking right at us, tightening his
fists, kicking his legs and crying, was just indescribable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt explains that researchers will need to study 200 babies
worldwide who have suffered acute oxygen deprivation before they
can draw clear conclusions. ``Some of the babies will receive the
cooling cap and intensive care. The other babies will receive
standard intensive care without the cooling cap. That's the only
way we'll know for certain if this treatment works.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site at http://healthsurfing.com
contains further information.)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
