<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-400&AMP;A     03-24 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S PRESIDENT QUITS AS HEAD OF DEFEATED NATIONALIST PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Saying he must bear responsibility for the
Nationalist Party's crushing defeat in last weekend's presidential
elections, Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-hui, resigned Friday as
chairman of the party that has ruled this island for more than half
a century.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee will remain president until May 20, when he is
succeeded by the opposition leader, Chen Shui-bian, his departure
as party boss greatly diminishes his power, effectively ending the
77-year-old politician's extraordinary career as the man who
brought democracy to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief valedictory speech to the Nationalist Party's top
officials Friday morning, Lee extolled that legacy, saying the
Nationalists had ``unshakable status'' as pioneers of democracy.
But he also acknowledged deep-rooted flaws in the party, which led
to its repudiation by voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must admit that because of the long history of this party,
there are long-running problems, which need to be eliminated,'' Lee
said. He did not elaborate, but added, ``This defeat is the right
time for the comrades of this party to do a full self-examination
and a total reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee flashed his trademark ear-to-ear grin as he entered the
Nationalist Party's imposing headquarters Friday morning. But it
was a humbling moment. Rolls of barbed wire still ringed the
building, after days of angry protests against him. Lee had
resisted calls for his departure, but he was drummed out by younger
members, who said his imperious style had contributed to the
party's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists named Lien Chan, their defeated presidential
candidate, as interim chairman. Lien promised to undertake a
wholesale reform of the party. The Nationalists now seem likely to
enter a turbulent period, in which younger leaders will battle
against the elders of Lee's generation for the soul of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old KMT is dead,'' said Chen Li-luan, a Nationalist member
of Taiwan's legislature, who led the campaign against Lee. He used
the initials to refer to the Nationalist Party. ``We are trying to
resurrect it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalist's internal struggle has profound implications
for Taiwan. Even without the presidency, the party remains a
ubiquitous presence here. It has a majority of seats in the
legislature, a vast grass-roots network and a business empire that
ranges from petrochemicals to media companies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some political analysts fear that these assets could be
liquidated or even plundered while the power struggle rages within
the party. Lien said Friday that he would press on with a plan to
place the properties in a trust, making them harder to
misappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   But that plan must await the passage of new laws by the
legislature. Chen's Democratic Progressive Party has said that it
wants to investigate the businesses and possibly seize those that
it determines were improperly confiscated by the Nationalists after
the party took control of Taiwan from Japan in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is a political conspiracy,'' said Darby Liu, the
secretary-general of the party's business management committee.
``They want to kick us while we are down. Our contention is that
these properties are legally owned and registered. Why should we
give them back?''
</P>
<P>
   Lee kept firm control over the party's businesses through his
close ally, Liu Tai-yin, who was chairman of the committee that
controls the assets. But Liu also resigned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For Lee, the resignation was a bittersweet end to a career in
which he had become the first native-born Taiwanese to run this
country. Trained as an agricultural economist at Cornell
University, Lee entered politics in 1972 as a Cabinet minister in
the regime of Chiang Kai-shek, who fled here from China with his
army in 1949 after being defeated by the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Lee served as vice president under Chiang Kai-shek's son, Chiang
Ching-kuo, and became president when he died in 1988. Chiang
Ching-kuo had initiated Taiwan's move to democracy by lifting
martial law and legalizing opposition parties in 1987. Lee built on
that by instituting direct elections of the president; in 1996, he
became the first popularly elected leader of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But while Lee opened the political system, he kept an iron grip
on the party. He dominated its weekly Wednesday meetings, setting
policies that were implemented when the Cabinet met the following
day. On some matters, he did not bother to consult anyone, such as
when he abruptly declared last July that Taiwan and China could
only negotiate on a ``state-to-state'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the more controversial part of his legacy,'' said Ma
Ying-jeou, the 49-year-old mayor of Taipei, who is regarded as one
of the party's rising stars. ``The party should have democratized
long ago,'' he added. ``But we have a tradition of strong
leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
