<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-TITUS-HNS     03-24 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TITUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FAST-PACED `TITUS' IS NOT TO BE IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To call ``Titus'' a visceral film isn't merely to call it raw,
or emotional, or as charged with madness and imagination as a
traveling freakshow. It's all those things and a few more
(``deranged'' springs to mind), but the word ``visceral'' has more
than a figurative meaning. It implies the presence of actual
viscera. Specifically, the slopping-full bowl of human intestines
that show up in the movie's first half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Which is as good entree as any into the world of ``Titus,'' a
furious, bloody, overindulgent, overcooked, maniacally entertaining
Shakespeare adaptation (nee ``Titus Andronicus'') from the crowned
queen of Broadway, Julie Taymor (``The Lion King'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' is Taymor's first feature, and it makes a noisy debut
_ a movie to watch or walk out on, but never to ignore. A film in
which the main character pulls ersatz pen ink from the blood of his
own handless stump won't win any congeniality awards, but it
certainly leaves a vivid impression.
</P>
<P>
   The film concerns the downfall and crack-up of a victorious
Roman general, Titus Andronicus (Anthony Hopkins), who returns home
from battle with some rather fateful booty: the Goth queen Tamora
(Jessica Lange) and her three sons. When Titus orders the eldest
son slain, Tamora pleads for his life. Titus ignores her; entrails
ensue.
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications of this little act don't become clear until
later on, when Tamora marries the Roman Emperor (Alan Cumming) and
with her remaining sons (Matthew Rhys and Jonathan Rhys-Meyers)
plots revenge on the aging Titus and his issue. What kind of
revenge? Rape, decapitation, hands chopped off, a tongue ripped out
_ the usual. No one's eyes are gouged (though there are shades of
``King Lear''), but Titus' climactic retaliation does involve a bit
of creative cuisine that dares one to laugh and barf
simultaneously. (You will laugh. You'll hate yourself afterward and
shower obsessively for weeks, but you will laugh.)
</P>
<P>
   Many an academic row has been devoted to the matter of ``Titus
Andronicus,'' namely, whether it is a wretched, gruesome play
written by a young William Shakespeare or a wretched, gruesome play
written (in whole or in part) by someone posing as a young William
Shakespeare. It was in any case an out-of-the-park hit for Will,
who wowed Elizabethan crowds with scenes of decapitation,
dismemberment and disembowelment that might ring a bell for anyone
familiar with ``Mortal Kombat.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, if you can get past all the sticky red stuff, is kind of
the point. Taymor uses the film's opening scene _ in which a
cherubic young boy goes ballistic with action figures on a kitchen
table _ to establish up front her deconstructive spin on the
violence that follows, drawing obvious parallels between
exploitative gore in the Bard's time and exploitative gore today.
This Is Us, she's saying. She might be right and she might be wrong
(next time visiting heads of state are served meat pies made from
their grown children, drop me a line), but at least she's adamant.
She doesn't putz around.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, Taymor sets her adaptation in neither ancient Rome
nor a modern discotheque, but at the junction of both and
everything between: characters dressed in (Oscar-nominated)
glam-rock outfits and encrusted metal armor sashay around the
Colosseum, Mussolini's ueber-Rome and a subterranean-dungeon video
arcade. In a Jazz Age orgy scene, a brassy band honks away while
nekkid couples writhe and moan.
</P>
<P>
   To which the skeptical viewer protests: how absurd. And it is
absurd. It is absolutely, unapologetically, patently ludicrous. Yet
the film's very absurdity _ along with its Grand Guignol
grotesqueness _ give it its mojo, tossing moments of agonizing
tragedy and clownish humor into the same sick salad. The result is
one of the fastest 162-minute films on record, an erratic visual
feast that fascinates and nauseates in equal measure.
</P>
<P>
   Taymor gets plenty of help from her cast, who seem to understand
the inherent wackiness of the material and act accordingly.
Literary critic Michael Stapleton once claimed the play ``only
succeeds when the title role can be given to an actor who carries
enough guns to sink a battleship, like Laurence Olivier,'' and
Hopkins surely qualifies. Indeed, he seems consumed by the part to
the point of coming unhinged; his proud warrior's slide toward
insanity has touches of Hannibal Lecter, but Titus is a much
messier and more honestly human fellow.
</P>
<P>
   Prostrate with grief, weeping into the stones for two condemned
sons (``In summer's drought I'll drop upon thee still''), he's as
wounded and ravaged as he has ever appeared on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Lange, in her Shakespearean debut, pulls off a performance of
snarling She-mother muscularity. There's no way we're messing with
her. Cummings slinks around in his fascist-chic leather cape and
comes off as a dissolute feline. Laura Frasier (as Lavinia, Titus'
daughter) and Angus MacFadyan (as Lucius, one of his sons) provide
able support, but it's Harry Lennixas Aaron, Tamora's scheming
slave _ whose gravity, delivery and thunderous charisma herald the
break-out of a major talent. Watch this guy.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you can, watch ``Titus.'' You might walk out; you might
feel ill; you might write hate mail to the nearest available
critic. But this hideous tale of vengeful parents proves once again
that the elemental power of Shakespeare, even this Shakespeare,
lies in its malleability. Tap it, pummel it or pound it into
tissue, it's still gold. Even when Taymor wields the hammer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
