<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6873 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-HEART-PAGER-NYTSF &LR;      03-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-PAGER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEART PAGER RECORDS RHYTHM DISTURBANCES AS THEY OCCUR 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from The New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (A color photo is available electronically)
 &HT;    
 By JULIANNE REMINGTON  
 c.2000 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new heart pager turns itself on at the first sign of trouble
and records irregular rhythms as they happen. Patients push a
button to transmit the data by phone to their doctor and the
receiving phone converts the data into an ECG, or wave pattern
reflecting the electrical activity of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   When 83-year-old George Welch suffered vague symptoms of
dizziness and shortness of breath, doctors thought he might have an
irregular heart beat, or arrhythmia. But they had no way of knowing
for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can have symptoms one day and be perfectly fine for
weeks or months,'' says Dr. Dennis Leahy, a cardiologist with the
Escondido Cardiology Association in California. ``Then the symptoms
can occur again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst time was when I went shopping in the grocery
store,'' says Welch. ``I stopped for about 10 seconds and felt like
I was going to pass out. I really thought I might be sailing off
into the great blue yonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors diagnosed Welch's arrhythmia two weeks after he started
wearing the heart pager, which is also called a looping event
recorder. His irregular heart rhythms triggered the pager, which
began recording the patterns of electrical impulses traveling
through his heart. When his doctor received the data by phone, he
used it to diagnose Welch's arrhythmia and determine the best
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   SYMPTOMS COME AND GO
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a challenge to try and catch a cardiac event that
is associated with sporadic symptoms,'' says Leahy. ``The event
recorder helps us determine what's causing the rhythm disturbance
so we can start appropriate treatment. In the worst of all worlds,
some of these rhythms can be associated with sudden death.''
</P>
<P>
   Most arrhythmias are treatable if properly diagnosed. Doctors
recommended a pacemaker for Welch, a small electronic device that
is implanted under the skin and generates electrical impulses to
improve the heart's rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   RECORDS CRITICAL EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine now,'' Welch says. ``But when my heart stopped, I
thought it might be all over. I feel better knowing I have the
recorder on.''
</P>
<P>
   A signal on the heart pager lets the patient know when it's
starting to record. The patient can also activate the device if he
or she feels symptoms coming on. The pager monitors the heart
rhythm continuously, but only stores the patterns for several
minutes before and after it's activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other causes of lightheadedness and dizziness,''
explains Leahy. ``Correlating the heart rhythms with the patient's
symptoms gives us valuable information. It's useful in ruling out
heart problems as well as pinpointing them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The device will freeze a segment of the heart patterns right
before it's activated and for several minutes after,'' explains
Kathleen Brooks of Alaris Medical Systems, which manufactures the
pager device. ``It allows the physician to see exactly what the
heart is doing at the time the symptoms occur.''
</P>
<P>
   ARRHYTHMIAS
</P>
<P>
   Many arrhythmias go unnoticed, but they can be extremely
serious. People with heart disease have a higher risk of suffering
arrhythmias, but irregular rhythms can effect people with normal
hearts too. Healthy individuals may suffer arrhythmias from
caffeine, smoking, drugs, alcohol or stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``An arrhythmia can manifest as the heart speeding up, skipping
beats or going too slow,'' says Leahy. ``People can have symptoms
like palpitations, shortness of breath or lightheadedness because
the heart isn't pumping blood around the body effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   When a 69-year old woman blacked out while wearing the device,
the recording allowed doctors to diagnose her specific kind of
arrhythmia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her heart rate went from normal, which is about 70 beats per
minute, to about 30 beats a minute,'' explained Leahy. ``That's
serious enough to cause lightheadedness or loss of consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association offers a quiz to help people
determine if they have any of the risk factors for heart problems.
Some of the risk factors include advancing age, (45 years for men
and 50 years for women,) heredity, high blood pressure, cigarette
smoking, high blood cholesterol, obesity, diabetes, a type A
personality, stress and a sedentary lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients attach several electrodes to their skin while wearing
the lightweight recording device,'' says Leahy. ``It gives us the
ability to monitor the patient for up to a month at a time. I would
say 30 to 40 percent of the event recorders we give patients yield
valuable information. The recorder also helps us monitor patients
with pacemakers and medications that slow the heart rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site at http://healthsurfing.com
contains further information.)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
