<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-WHATEVER-     03-24 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WHATEVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `WHATEVER IT TAKES': DATED ON ARRIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Whatever It Takes'' is some kind of quaint high-school
comedy/teen romance when a kid actually uses ``smells like teen
spirit'' to describe the vibe at a party. Then, later, the Moby jam
on the soundtrack is shut off so a boy can eke out a version of
``I'll Melt With You'' on his accordion for his girl. Hey, it
brought a tear to her eye, and it might bring one to yours, too.
</P>
<P>
   This is purely a matter of personal taste. At the same party,
Grace Jones' ``Pull Up to the Bumper'' is the 18-year-old tune that
has all the tail feathers shaking. And that was fun. But I spent 99
minutes with ``Whatever'' and not one character materialized who
might have been responsible for spinning that record.
</P>
<P>
   No one goes into these movies sniffing around for realism per
se, but in theory this movie's sense of nostalgia would add 15 to
20 years onto these kids. (Coincidentally, that's about how far
apart in age director David Raynr and writer Mark Schwahn are from
the interchangeable stars in their movie.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever It Takes'' is DOA _ dated on arrival. It serves as a
platform for its filmmakers to use shallow teen-agers to reflect
their own tastes. Accordion boy's name is Ryan (Shane West), and in
one of the film's more humiliating moments, he reveals his secret
joy _ his accordion _ while ``Play That Funky Music'' mocks him in
the background. Like friends or co-workers whose fashion sense and
pop sensibilities practically carbon-date them, ``Whatever'' joins
the roster of recent musty, moral-slinging co-conspirators in
teensploitation. (There's a reason none of these flicks has set a
lifestyle trend: They're hung up on trends set over a decade ago.)
</P>
<P>
   And like ``10 Things I Hate About You'' and ``She's All That,''
this one needs a previously existing text to justify its existence
_ as if every day of high school weren't already ``Taming of the
Shrew,'' ``Pygmalion'' or (in ``Whatever's'' case) ``Cyrano de
Bergerac.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan thinks he wants to be with the school ditz, Ashley (Jodi
Lyn O'Keefe). Meanwhile, Chris (James Franco), the school player,
wants to get next to Maggie (Marla Sokoloff), who happens to be
best friends with Ryan. Chris agrees to put Ryan on with Ashley,
provided Ryan do the same for Chris with Maggie. Makeovers and a
prom ensue.
</P>
<P>
   The signature ``Cyrano'' impersonation/seduction employs call
waiting. It feels so tampered with that the spontaneity is snuffed
out by arrhythmic cutting. But when a movie's title sequence
features makeup and hair accessories dancing in stop-motion,
there's no mystery where, if anyplace, it's taking you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever'' begins by showing us what it takes for a girl to
get pretty enough to go to fourth-period chemistry. It ends by
telling us that chemistry doesn't matter if you can see into the
bedroom of the girl you love. And throughout, the movie insists
that the way to a high school senior girl's heart in 2000 is by
loving ``Casablanca'' and old Cheap Trick.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Maggie starts hanging out with the vapid popular
girls, and Sokoloff wears that priceless look of demoralized horror
Lorraine Bracco had when she sees her fellow mob wives for the
first time in ``GoodFellas.'' It's an out-of-body moment: She knows
she's in a time warp, her life flashing before her eyes. Then she
snaps out of it, wearing the stung look of a girl who's just popped
a pimple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
