<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-COLOR-0325-COX     03-24 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-COLOR-0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON FINDS SIGHTS, PEOPLE OF INDIA 'IMMENSELY IMPRESSIVE'
 &HT;    (425&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With INDIA-CLINTON-0324.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ He's stood in the great legislative cathedral of
the world's most populous democracy and felt his heart quicken at
the site of a tiger in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   He's glimpsed the high-tech future of one of the world's oldest
civilizations and wandered the ruins of its distant past.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, it has been India's people that have moved
and inspired the world's most powerful man.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of its difficulties,'' said President Clinton, who
leaves India Saturday after a week-long visit, ``this is an
immensely impressive country.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible, certainly, to embrace the complexity and the
contrasts, the poverty and the promise, of this vast and ancient
land in any single journey, much less in a tour of only five days.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's passage through India, moreover, has been a carefully
scripted drama seen largely from Air Force One, presidential
helicopters, bilateral meetings and speeding motorcades.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents have done their best to keep the
presidential magic carpet from being soiled with the dust of
antiquity choking much of the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   He's slept in five-star hotel suites where the nightly rate is
three times what the average Indian makes in a year.
</P>
<P>
   And his political advisers have been so finicky that Clinton
couldn't even take a hoped-for elephant ride at the 16th Century
Amber Fort in Jaipur, lest photographers capture him astride the
symbol of his Republican foes.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, rays of India managed to filter through the screen,
reflected in the eyes of its people.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the black granite bier marking the spot where
Mahatma Gandhi was cremated in 1948, Clinton ruminated on the
impact that the father of Indian independence and the apostle of
non-violent civil disobedience had on the American South, where
Clinton was raised, and the civil rights movement that helped shape
his political career, even as it changed the face of his nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about Gandhi's life,'' he later told reporters,
``how he completely gave his life over to what he believed, and
how, if all of us just had one fraction of that commitment, we
could make peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a group of more than 1,000 executives at a high-tech
industrial park in Hyderabad, Clinton spoke to the irony of India's
exploding computer sector amid the continuing trauma of its
enduring poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of Indians are connected to the Internet, but
millions more aren't yet connected to fresh water,'' Clinton said.
``Our challenge is to turn the newest discoveries into the best
weapons humanity has ever had to fight poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with women at an innovative dairy co-op in the village
of Nayla, an impoverished hamlet at the edge of the great Thar
desert in the fabled state of Rajasthan, Clinton was taken by the
quiet dignity and fulsome pride summoned by some of the world's
poorest women, made rich by a belief that they might change the
world for themselves and their families, one warm and creamy gallon
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an edge to those women,'' Clinton later said. ``They
had something, it was special. They knew they'd done something.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Clinton addressed the Indian Parliament, seat of
the officials privileged to be elected by the most populous
democracy in the history of the world, a body politic of 620
million eligible voters
</P>
<P>
   And the next day, before touring the Ranthambhore Tiger
Preserve, he paid tribute to the grandeur of local government by
the people, dropping in on a village council. One member asked
Clinton whether he found India to be a backward country.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' came Clinton's reply.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But what I hope my trip will do is to help people all over the
world see India in a more complete way,'' he said. ``There are many
people here who are poor, but you are proving that democracy can be
used to lift the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton, who has devoted much of his nation's treasure and
prestige to fighting the fruits of ancient prejudice and modern
hatred around much of the world, told the villagers, and all of
India, what he's learned from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in India you can prove that people can lift themselves from
poverty, and, at the same time, end discrimination against women
and their girl children, and learn to work together across tribal
and caste lines because of democracy, you will give the world the
greatest gift it could have now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
