<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GAY-MARRIAGES-HNS &LR;      03-24 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GAY COUPLES DEFY CALIFORNIA'S MARRIAGE BAN WITH UNITY
CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ILENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As 88 gay and lesbian couples held hands inside
San Francisco City Hall and pledged their love to each other, an
unusual protest _ even for this city _ took place in the plaza
outside.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was the religious conservatives who angrily demonstrated
at last year's same-sex commitment ceremony officiated by Mayor
Willie Brown and other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth ceremony Thursday attracted Californians for Same Sex
Marriages, a small group that held signs bearing slogans like
``Marry Me!'' and gathered signatures on a petition to put a
measure on November's state ballot that would legalize marriages
between homosexuals and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about how far we've come,'' said a surprised Supervisor
Leslie Katz, who helped officiate the ceremony inside.
</P>
<P>
   Yet still not far enough, according to the demonstrators outside
and many couples inside, who are frustrated by the passage on March
7 of the ballot initiative banning marriage between same-sex
couples.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some couples said the passage of Proposition 22, which
defined marriage as only between a man and a woman, motivated them
to defiantly and proudly participate in Thursday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been just one disappointment after another,'' said
Richard Gibson, 54, of San Francisco, adding that he hoped that in
his lifetime there would be a law approving same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson exchanged vows with his boyfriend of five years, Paul
Porcher, 46, who popped the question to Gibson while they were
watching the movie ``Runaway Bride.'' The couple wore matching
green coats with white rose buds in their lapels for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the public affirmation is important,'' Porcher said.
</P>
<P>
   With Mayor Brown's instruction to ``say it loudly and proudly,''
Porcher, Gibson and the other couples said their vows together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do willingly take you to be my lifetime partner to love and
cherish forever,'' Brown said, leading the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating with the crowd was state Assemblywoman Carole
Migden, a San Francisco Democrat who launched the city's first
commitment ceremony in 1996 and helped create a new state registry
for domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy to bless our San Francisco families and we are
here to perform real marriage ceremonies and illustrate to America
that lesbians and gays are committed to each other,'' Migden said.
``We will have marriage and families and (we will) self-define them
and have them fortified and prevail. We will have them respected
and recognized everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the new century has held many ups and downs for
homosexuals and lesbians. Just three weeks after Proposition 22
passed in California, the Vermont House approved ``civil unions''
that offer them many of the benefits and responsibilities of
heterosexual marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Some domestic partners in San Francisco already can receive
similar rights, including health care, if they register with the
city. Domestic partners who work for the city benefit, and at least
one other major employer here, United Airlines, adopted a similar
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Carolin Forks, 36, and Lori Augustine, 30, of San Bruno work for
United and plan to register with the city soon to qualify for the
shared benefits. But that is not the main reason they participated
in Thursday' ceremony, Augustine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason is we love each other,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
