<HEADER>
A6905 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NATURE-EXPLOSIVES-NYT     03-24 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURE-EXPLOSIVES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSIVE PICTURES  
 FOR RELEASE: THU., MARCH 30, 2000
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NATURE news service clients. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement with the
Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By DAVID ADAM  
 c.2000 Nature News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers in India may have come up with a new way of
predicting when explosives might lose their fizz. Medical imaging,
it seems, could reveal an explosive's shelf life and sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbles or ``void spaces'' collapse under the high-pressure
shock waves of an explosion. Compression instantly forces up bubble
temperature and ignites the surrounding material. More and more
bubbles get converted into these hotspots as shock waves rush
through a detonating explosive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size and the number of bubbles is half the science of
making emulsion explosives,'' says Jack Hedger, technical officer
of the United Kingdom's Institute of Explosives Engineers. Only
bubbles below a certain size produce enough heat to drive an
explosion forward, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Explosives are given void spaces by filling them with porous
solid bits. Tiny glass balloons, mineral particles and even pieces
of corn all put crushable air pockets into the liquid. From the
size and number of these additions, manufacturers can calculate how
many void spaces, on average, a liquid explosive contains. This
figure gives a guide to what should happen when the plunger is
pressed.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing air and other gases into the explosive while blending the
emulsion is a cheaper alternative, but one that makes bubble
content difficult to regulate and quantify. Liquid density gives no
clues to void size and peering down a microscope is unreliable as
bubbles move around in the sloppy slurry.
</P>
<P>
   Promising images of gas bubbles mixed into emulsion explosives
can be produced with a technique called nuclear magnetic resonance,
according to P.K. Ghosh and his colleagues at the ICI India R&AMP;T
Center in Thane, India.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic resonance is used widely in medicine (under the
pseudonym medical resonance imaging or MRI) to map blood flow
around the body, and the brain in particular. It identifies the
distinctive magnetic fields around the nuclei of most atoms.
</P>
<P>
   The technique offers a way to check the bubble quality of
emulsion explosives that ``was hitherto not possible due to
nonavailability of noninvasive techniques for void measurements,''
the group reported.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosh and his colleagues used magnetic resonance to probe
samples of a water-in-oil concentrated emulsion explosive. Each
sample was divided into a grid of over 16,000 squares, which were
checked for signals or ''echoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest signals correspond to the explosive ingredients:
water, ammonia and paraffin oil. Void spaces do not produce signals
and so show up as holes.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures that Ghosh's group obtained are not perfect but
they do reveal bubbles, like a blurred black and white photograph
of Swiss cheese. Better picture resolution will help measure bubble
size, the team said.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic resonance imaging can only work with very small samples
of explosive. The technique will have to be improved before it can
analyze the cartridges of explosives used in mines. And, because
bubbles merge and expand over time until they are too flabby to go
out with a bang, it could help determine a ''best before'' date for
explosives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NATURE
news service and other features. &QL;
</P>
