<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURE-COSMIC-XRAYS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-RAYING THE UNIVERSE  
 FOR RELEASE: THU., MARCH 30, 2000
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NATURE news service clients. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement with the
Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By PHILIP BALL  
 c.2000 Nature News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Every day you play with the light of the universe'', said
Chilean poet Pablo Neruda. And there is plenty of light to play
with.
</P>
<P>
   As well as visible starlight (of which sunlight is a nearby
representative), the sky glows with radiation that we cannot see:
radio waves, microwaves, ultraviolet, X-rays and gamma rays. All of
it is produced by the astrophysical objects _ galaxies of stars,
gas clouds, black holes _ that pepper empty space. But sorting
through all of these sources is difficult and tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Now a team of U.S. astronomers has sifted through one of the
most interesting parts of the spectrum of the universe, the X-ray
region, to show where it comes from.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays bombard the Earth from all directions. X-rays are
extremely high-frequency radiation and carry a lot of energy. But
they are strongly absorbed in the upper atmosphere, and so do not
reach the ground. This is fortunate for life on Earth, as X-rays
are potentially damaging to living organisms. But it is a problem
for astronomers. It means that cosmic X-ray sources can only be
studied by orbiting satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Since the launch of the first satellite dedicated to X-ray
astronomy in 1970, their study has been a rich source of
information. In 1988, the French astronomer Jean-Pierre Luminet
said, ``High-energy astrophysics is arguably the branch of
astronomy that has most advanced our understanding of the universe
over the past 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmic X-rays are produced in very extreme environments. Objects
emit radiation of increasing frequency as they get hotter, which is
why a filament goes from red-hot to blue-hot when it heats up. But
to emit X-rays, such an object must have a temperature of millions
of degrees.
</P>
<P>
   When the background of cosmic X-rays was first discovered, some
suggested that it might be produced by a diffuse but tremendously
hot gas lodged between galaxies in all directions. During the
1990s, however, it became clear that the cosmic X-ray background is
the product of many individual point-like sources in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Hellish things are happening in these places. Black holes or
dense neutron stars are pulling matter apart. Some galaxies seem to
have very energetic events at their core (called active galactic
nuclei or AGN), where a huge, central black hole is thought to be
sucking up stars. But until now it has not been possible to match
the measured background ''spectrum'' of X-rays _ the way their
intensity varies with their frequency _ with the spectra of known
X-ray sources such as galactic nuclei.
</P>
<P>
   Len Cowie of the University of Hawaii and his co-workers have
helped to resolve much of the mystery of where the X-ray background
comes from. They have analyzed data from the Chandra satellite
launched last year, largely to investigate this question.
</P>
<P>
   The group has focused on the highest-energy _ the ``hard'' _
X-rays. At ``softer'' energies, much of the cosmic X-ray background
has already been resolved into individual sources such as galactic
nuclei, but the emission of hard X-rays from these sources doesn't
match that found in the background spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   To identify the X-ray sources, the researchers used the Chandra
data to pinpoint where the X-rays are coming from, and then used
ground-based optical telescopes (which measure visible light) to
detect astrophysical objects such as distant galaxies at those
points.
</P>
<P>
   They studied the Chandra results from a region of the sky
already thoroughly combed by optical astronomy, so that any
``candidate'' sources of X-rays would already have been seen. They
have thus found sources accounting for three-quarters of the hard
X-ray background in this part of the sky. These, say the
researchers, include ``a rich assortment of hard X-ray sources
which could not have been discovered by previous satellites.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are quasars. Others look like normal galaxies. And some are
so faint that it is hard to know exactly what they are. These faint
objects may be extremely distant quasars, formed very early in the
history of the universe. If so, they are some of the most remote
and oldest objects ever seen by astronomers, and could contain
X-ray-generating black holes formed in a different way from those
in closer, more recent galactic nuclei. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NATURE
news service and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
