<HEADER>
A6912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-DR.-LAURA-HNS &LR;      03-24 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR.-LAURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROTESTS AGAINST THE MEAN-SPIRITED DR. LAURA COULD BACKFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dr. Laura Schlessinger is the Queen of Contempt,
a bully and a bigot _ the last at least when it comes to
homosexuals. That is her appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But gay and lesbian advocates are running a very real risk of
turning her into something else: a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   In her daily radio show that is broadcast nationally,
Schlessinger dishes out instant, simplistic and acerbic advice to
masochistic callers. Her analysis often takes the form of moral
edicts delivered in a withering, mean-spirited fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Included in her heaping helpings of abuse are some pretty
vitriolic assertions about homosexuality: Gays are ``sexual
deviants,'' ``biological errors,'' unfit parents and more prone to
pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does deviant sexual behavior get rights?'' she asked on
her show.
</P>
<P>
   Now the good doctor (her degree is in physiology, not
psychology) has a syndicated television show slated for the fall
that has been picked up by 160 television stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Why, you ask, would anyone want her on the air?
</P>
<P>
   We'll give you 20 million guesses, one for each of her
listeners. That's more than Rush or Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is the hottest thing in the marketplace,'' Steve
Baboulis, general manager of WNYT, the NBC affiliate in Albany,
said of the upcoming television show. ``Obviously, it will be
controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's distributor, Paramount Television, has been hit with
protests, including an organized demonstration Tuesday in
Hollywood. Web sites have popped up decrying her television deal
(www.stopdrlaura.com might be the most comprehensive), while gay
rights groups have formally petitioned Paramount to drop her.
</P>
<P>
   Understandable, but worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the protests, Laura (let's forget the doctor
part: the title is misleading and irrelevant to what she does) and
her supporters cry ``fascism'' (patently false, because the state
is not involved), ``terrorism'' and ``censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullies often cry ``foul'' when someone punches back.
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger _ who at least decries violence against gays _ says
her beliefs and moral code are rooted in her Orthodox Judaism. She
denies the comparison between homophobia and racism, stating the
difference is between actions and skin color. This 53-year-old
model of morality is an advocate of ``reparative therapy'' that
``cures'' homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she issued an apology for some of her comments. It
didn't stick; she later called it a ``clarification.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of things. This is not a First Amendment issue. Yes,
you have a right to your beliefs and a right to express them. But
you do not have a constitutional right to your own television show,
radio show, or space in a newspaper. So don't even try that
argument.
</P>
<P>
   And vocal opposition to someone's beliefs does not amount to
censorship _ again, a dysfunction of the state _ or terrorism. That
rant is as well thought out as some of Laura's asinine remarks
about gays.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the woman is a twit. Fine. So why is this anti-Laura
push a concern?
</P>
<P>
   Because she is angling for victim status, and she just might get
it.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for John Rocker, the Atlanta Braves pitcher who, in
one Sports Illustrated article, made a fool of himself with bigoted
remarks (aimed at blacks, gays, Asians, single mothers _ pick a
minority), then got suspended from baseball. This knucklehead gets
support from some people because he's getting ``picked on.''
</P>
<P>
   The call for pulling Schlessinger's television show is
misguided. Pre-emptive strikes run a risk of making the aggrieved
minority look more like the bully. Plus, the most likely end result
will be heightened ratings. Look at how past protests against shows
like ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Married ... with Children'' fared.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, these advocacy groups should make a different point
clear to Paramount, and the show's sponsors: Go ahead, put Dr.
Laura on. We welcome it.
</P>
<P>
   And every time she says ridiculous, bigoted comments _ on radio
or television _ we will make these transgressions known widely and
loudly. This is the person with whom you want to be associated?
That's fine by us. We'll make sure everyone knows.
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger's comments should be given as much exposure as
possible. Silencing her doesn't remove the egregious beliefs that
she and others hold. Air them. Let everyone know how stupid she
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Schlessinger is a lot of things. ``Martyr'' should not be
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
