   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECTION (Moscow) _ In what looks like an effort to
ensure a first-round victory for Acting President Vladimir Putin in
Sunday's election by taking votes from challenger Grigory
Yavlinsky, the state TV channel has run ``news'' reports on how
Jews, gay men and foreigners support Yavlinsky. The gay segment is
a seemingly staged ``news conference'' at which effeminate men
declare their support for Yavlinsky. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ News Analysis: Despite an
outbreak of violence at a Palestinian refugee camp and the sniping
over Jerusalem that ruined his inter-denominational gathering, the
pope has managed so far to hover above the fray. In doing so, he
has presented what some see as a model of brotherly discourse to
religious leaders here. And he has established a soothing tone that
quieted most of the tensions and made both Israelis and
Palestinians feel endorsed by his visit.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Korazim, Israel) _ Stepping into the pages of the
New Testament, Pope John Paul II sat Friday on a lush, rock-strewn
hillside near where Jesus delivered the Sermon on the Mount and
asked young believers from across the globe to spread Christian
teachings of selfless love and forgiveness. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The Security Council meets on Iraqi
sanctions today. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N.-LIST (United Nations) _ A look at the greatly expanded
list of stuff Iraq can buy without seeking U.N. approval.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (Hyderabad) _ President Clinton saluted India's
information technology industry on Friday, the core of the
country's steady economic growth and the crucible for much of
Silicon Valley in California. This was the last full day of
Clinton's visit to India, and after having dealt with tricky
strategic and political questions, it seemed appropriate that the
president should concentrate on the economy, the area where there
is probably most commonality between the United States and India.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TB (Dateline to kum) _ On World Tuberculosis Day, a look
at India's efforts to conquer TB among the poor. By Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PAKISTAN (Islamabad) _ What awaits Clinton, who visits
Pakistan for five hours on Saturday. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-POLITICS (Taipei) _ Saying he must bear responsibility
for the Nationalist Party's crushing defeat in last weekend's
presidential elections, Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-hui, resigned
on Friday as chairman of the party that has ruled this island for
more than half a century. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-POLITICS (Belfast) _ A challenge to David Trimble's
leadership of the Unionist Party bodes ill for the Northern Ireland
peace effort. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-IDENTITY (Berlin) _ On the western facade of the
Reichstag is an old inscription: ``Dem Deutschen Volke'' _ ``To the
German People.'' Straightforward enough. But just how complex,
charged and divisive those words are has been revealed by an outcry
over a proposed work of art for the refurbished parliamentary
building. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ The Pentagon's inspector general
found in a survey of U.S. military bases that anti-gay speech and
harassment is widespread, and that many service members believe it
is tolerated by their leaders, the Pentagon said Friday. The
conclusions make clear that, ``We need to do more work on this
policy'' to protect gays, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said.
(Summary from wires) By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EMAIL (Washington) _ Developments on the criminal
investigation into whether White House officials illegally
suppressed large numbers of executive office e-mails subpoenaed in
investigations of the White House campaign fund-raising and other
activities. By Mark Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ A look at why House Republicans
pushed through a budget knowing full well they will break all the
limits once the tax and spending bills are finished. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   WWII-MUSEUM (New Orleans) _ When Stephen Ambrose decided to
found a museum on World War II, the first in the nation dedicated
to the entire war, he had no doubt about where to put it. On June
6, the National D-Day Museum will open in Higgins' hometown, New
Orleans, La. The museum will focus on the Normandy invasion,
commonly known as D-Day, but it will tell the story of all the
major amphibious assaults undertaken by Americans during the war,
including Pacific engagements like Iwo Jima, Guadalcanal, and
Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ILLEGAL-COHABITATION (Peralta, N.M.) _ In many places these
days, living together carries less of a moral stain than smoking,
but in New Mexico it is against the law. Few New Mexicans seem to
realize this, but Pitcher's ex-wife did, and in February she filed
a complaint. By Jim Yardley. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ the weekly Religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTERS (Washington) _ Behind much of the political debate
in recent weeks, on issues from gun control to education, is an
intensifying struggle for the votes of women, particularly suburban
mothers. Strategists in both parties say the presidential race may
well hinge on whether Gov. George W. Bush, who has framed his
campaign around a promise of ``compassionate conservatism,''
succeeds in holding his own among women, who since the early 1980s
have tended to vote Democratic. One of the first tests may come on
the issue of gun violence and gun control, which pollsters say is a
far more powerful issue among women than among men. By Robin Toner.
(1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
