<HEADER>
A6927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CAMEOS-$ADV26-HNS &LR;      03-24 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMEOS-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAMEOS MAKE GREAT ART ON OR OFF THE BODY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 26)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Cameos not only make great jewelry, but great
works of art as well.
</P>
<P>
   Portraits and classical themes often dominate the art of cameo
cutting, which flourished in the first half of the 1st century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   They are most often carved from stratified stones or shells,
which give the relief cut in the top layer a background of a
contrasting color. But they can also be carved from glass, onyx,
porcelain and ivory or made from molded plastic.
</P>
<P>
   The images are often very detailed _ from the facial expression
to curls in the hair. It's the larger amount of detailing in a
cameo that makes it more valuable. The material and age of the
cameo also contribute to its worth.
</P>
<P>
   Hard stone is much more difficult to carve than a softer shell.
But many of the cameos of the late 18th century are intaglios,
where the design is incised in, or hollowed out of, the top layer
of stone, rather than carved in relief.
</P>
<P>
   This period also produced a lot of copyists and forgers. In some
cases, older cameos from the 15th century have been reworked,
making dating rather difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Always look at a cameo carefully to check for any damage, such
as tiny cracks or chips. The high points of the carving are prone
to chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can place cameo pins in a velvet-lined case and hang them
on the wall,'' said William Vollbrecht, owner of Vollbrecht Jewelry
and Antiques in Guilderland, N.Y. ``This way, you can take one out
and wear it whenever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Framed cameos are often hung on the wall as a pair, or you can
create a whole wall grouping out of a collection.
</P>
<P>
   Wedgwood is best known for his porcelain and stoneware cameos of
the second half of the 18th century. His blue-and-white Jasper Ware
was a popular material.
</P>
<P>
   The background of a cameo comes in a variety of shapes, from
oval and round to rectangular.
</P>
<P>
   Vollbrecht said that cameos range in price from about $125 up
into the thousands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1455EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
