<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-940&AMP;ADD     03-24 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-940&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SPENDS LAST DAY IN INDIA FOCUSING ON ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(See also CLINTON-PAKISTAN, INDIA-TB) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ In a parting message, President Clinton
addressed a group of businessmen at the stock exchange here Friday
night, saying that he hoped his visit India over the last five days
would become the catalyst for a new relationship with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends don't have to agree on every issue,'' Clinton said.
``They just have to have an honest relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   He appealed again to India to reduce tensions on the
subcontinent with its neighbor, Pakistan, and to forswear nuclear
weapons, asking Indians to work for ``the proliferation of new
ideas'' and not ``dangerous weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to leave here for Islamabad on Saturday
morning to meet with the military leader of Pakistan, Gen. Pervez
Musharraf. The president will suggest that the confrontation with
India over the disputed Himalayan region of Kashmir holds dark
consequences for Pakistan, said Sandy Berger, Clinton's national
security adviser. Clinton is also expected to urge Pakistan's
leaders to move forcefully toward restoring democracy after the
October coup that brought Musharraf to power.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Clinton concentrated on the economy, the area where
there is probably the most common ground between the United States
and India. He saluted India's information technology industry, the
core of the country's steady economic growth and the crucible for
much of Silicon Valley in California.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture toward the potential for trade between India and
the United States, Clinton announced financing from the U.S.
Export-Import Bank for small business exports to India, guarantees
of rupee-dominated loans to Indian importers and financing for the
purchase of 10 Boeing passenger aircraft by Jet Airways of India, a
new domestic airline.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, trade between the United States and India is
relatively small: only $12 billion last year, compared to $94.9
billion between the United States and China. But it is the
potential for dramatic growth, especially with an expanding Indian
middle class that has a taste for U.S. consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is India's largest trading partner, but India,
because of its high tariffs and largely state-run economy, accounts
for less than 1 percent of U.S. global investments. Accompanied by
his commerce secretary, William M. Daley, throughout this trip,
Clinton made clear that he hopes that will change.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Hyderabad earlier Friday, the president spoke
at a software center, popularly known as Hi-Tec City, an acronym
for Hyderabad Information Technology-Engineering Consultancy City.
A number of U.S. computer companies, including Microsoft, Oracle
and Toshiba, have set up shop there, alongside new Indian giants
and smaller start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In extolling Indian achievements in information technology,
Clinton cited some of the world's computer superstars: Vinod
Khosla, who helped build Sun Microsystems, and Vinod Dahm, who
created the Pentium chip.
</P>
<P>
   India was ``fast becoming one of the world's software
superpowers,'' Clinton said, proving that ``in a globalized world,
developing nations not only can succeed, developing nations can
lead.'' The number of Internet users in India was set to grow 10
times in the next four years, he said. India's information
technology exports have catapulted from $150 million 10 years ago
to $4 billion today. The Indian government projects that by 2008,
those exports will grow to $85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly for India, Clinton said that the significant
impact of Indian computer engineers on the U.S. computer industry
was now beginning to pay back here in India. ``We're moving from
brain drain to brain gain,'' the president said. A group called
IndUS Entrepreneurs, whose members include the elite of Indian
software engineers in Silicon Valley, estimates that 30 percent of
the software engineers in the valley are of Indian origin.
</P>
<P>
   Most were educated at India's institutes of technology and came
to the United States to work in the valley. But now, with the
Indian economy growing at 6 percent annually and 10 percent growth
within site, some Silicon Valley veterans are beginning to return
to India.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also struck one of his favorite themes about the
Internet: that it can be used to lift the poor. India, he told his
audience, accounted for 30 percent of the world's software
engineers but also 25 percent of the world's malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the president said, India was in a special position to
show how its brains and inventiveness in the new technologies could
improve health care and education across the nation's villages.
</P>
<P>
   This was ``good economics,'' Clinton argued. If, for example,
villages had computers with educational software _ and printers _
there was a potential for a revolution in education in a country
where almost 50 percent of the population remains illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean among other things that the world's most
populous nation would have the world's largest number of educated
people and, therefore, in no time would have the world's largest
economy,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton chose to come to Hyderabad _ one of the three urban
centers that make up India's Silicon Triangle _ in part because of
Chandrababu Naidu, the chief minister of the state of Andhra
Pradesh, where the city is located.
</P>
<P>
   Naidu, 49, effusively introduced Clinton Friday before an
audience of Indian computer entrepreneurs gathered in the atrium of
the Hi-Tec City building. The kind of political leader that the
president admires, Naidu appeals to the growing urban middle class
of India with ideas like making his state another Singapore within
20 years. He favors cutting state subsidies, courting private
investment and spending more on education and rural development.
</P>
<P>
   His party is a powerful member of the Hindu-Nationalist-led
coalition that won the national elections last October, and
Washington believes that Naidu represents the next generation of
national leaders, and perhaps a future prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1456EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0124 </DOCNO>
