<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-W     03-24 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PENTAGON FINDS WIDESPREAD HARASSMENT OF GAYS IN UNIFORM  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG And STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon admitted Friday that there is
widespread harassment of homosexuals in the armed forces, reporting
that 80 percent of GIs questioned at 38 installations worldwide had
heard anti-gay remarks in the past year and that 37 percent had
witnessed or experienced harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen immediately launched an
emergency four-month effort to combat what he called ``harassment
based on perceived sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acted in response to a report by the Pentagon's deputy
inspector general, Donald Mancuso, who randomly surveyed more than
71,570 men and women in the nation's 1.4 million troops. The survey
gauged their experiences under the Clinton administration's
controversial ``don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue'' policy that
was inaugurated in 1993 to enable homosexuals to serve more freely
in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The report said 80 percent of the respondents ``stated that they
had heard offensive speech, derogatory names, jokes or remarks
about homosexuals in the last 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   It also found that 85 percent said they believed ``such comments
were tolerated to some extent.'' Of those surveyed 37 percent
``responded that they had witnessed or experienced an event or
behavior toward a service member that they considered to be
harassment based on perceived homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of those surveyed, 57 percent, said that they had
``not had training'' on the Pentagon's policy of tolerance toward
homosexuals. But the GIs said they felt free to report harassment
to superiors, with 78 percent saying that they would ``feel free to
report harassment of perceived homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen announced several hours before the public release of the
report that he was establishing a working group of senior military
leaders to map steps to combat the problem. He said the panel will
try to change the hostile atmosphere that gay and lesbian troops
often encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen told a breakfast meeting with reporters that ``the
incidents and use of abusive language (against suspected gay and
lesbian troops) are more widespread than I anticipated. I was
surprised at the numbers of people who said they saw some evidence
of harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Benecke, co-executive director of the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Network, an organization that provides legal aid to
homosexual military personnel, said the findings confirm what the
group has said for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the Pentagon for six years that harassment and
abuse are a serious problem. I'm glad the Pentagon has finally
acknowledged it. But the key to stopping harassment is leadership
and accountability. We hope this oversight committee is not a
substitute.'' Cohen said a major responsibility for the oversight
council will be to ensure that all military personnel are versed in
new Pentagon anti-harassment guidelines issued last month. The
guidelines are aimed at making sure the controversial
administration policy on gays in the military is followed. The
policy allows homosexuals to serve as long as they keep quiet about
their sexual orientation and don't engage in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   The policy also is designed to ensure that troops who are
harassed can complain to their commanders without fear of setting
in motion an investigation into their sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon survey found that many troops simply were
unfamiliar with the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen ordered the survey of the bases in the wake of the murder
last July of an Army recruit at Ft. Campbell, Ky., who was
suspected of being gay.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Army Pvt. Calvin Glover, 19, was sentenced to life
in prison for murdering the recruit, Pvt. Barry Winchell, 21, with
a baseball bat. During Glover's trial, soldiers testified that
Winchell was regularly taunted with anti-gay slurs and that
superiors did not intervene when he complained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
