<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WEB-RADIO-LADN &LR;      03-24 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-RADIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET AN EARFUL ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, your radio might pick up only 15 or, in a big
market like Los Angeles, maybe 50 stations, depending on the time
of day, which mountains were next to your house and how good your
antenna was.
</P>
<P>
   Despite improving technology, the choices seemed to shrink in
recent years. The loosening of federal restrictions has meant fewer
companies owned more stations and made them sound all the same,
concentrating on a few tightly controlled programming formats most
likely to attract larger audiences. If you weren't into mainstream
pop, Mexican country or a few other categories, you weren't going
to hear a lot of music you like.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no more. Thanks to the Internet, you can find virtually
any kind of music you like, using your computer. You can even
create your own niche, either by culling a custom playlist from a
site's thousands of selections, or becoming a DJ or talk-show host
yourself with virtually no equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has set off an explosion of sites that provide
``streams'' of music available on your computer _ or new Internet
radio players like those from Kerbango. For once, you won't be
stuck with a few, mostly uninteresting formats, but can turn on the
music you like.
</P>
<P>
   A quick check of the Web turns up thousands of radiolike sites,
including online versions of many broadcast stations. You can find
a ton of choices at search engines such as Yahoo!, or go to media
specialists such as Yack.com, which fancies itself a TV and radio
guide for the Net, or Tuneto.com and WebRadio, which let you pick
through stations that use its technology.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful alternative is the latest version of MusicMatch,
software that now has a button you can click on to pick from
hundreds of Web radio sites. The free program also lets you play
CDs on your computer, find and play MP-3 music files and even, with
the $30 upgrade, create custom CDs. RealNetworks' RealPlayer
Jukebox has somewhat similar capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   So what can you find out there?
</P>
<P>
   One good place to start is Santa Monica-based KCRW-FM, the
nation's biggest public radio station, which recently went from one
to three channels of its eclectic and influential music and public
affairs programming (KCRW.org), and cut a deal for HOB.com to carry
its programming there.
</P>
<P>
   HOB.com makes available a huge array of performances and other
music from the House of Blues chain of venues, to which HOB.com is
connected.
</P>
<P>
   The homesick or curious can hear plenty of commercial stations
as well, from WBCN in Boston to the BBC in Britain to B-92 in
Belgrade (when it's not shut down by the Yugoslav government). But
focus on the old- media entries and you'll miss all the new
companies busily busting paradigms.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, soundbreak.com mixes underground dance music with
strikingly offbeat animation, video feeds of the ``digital jocks,''
a DJ-run chat room, and information and fan ratings on each song.
The site expects to soon sell the music it plays.
</P>
<P>
   Soundbreak's vice president of music is Mark Goodman, one of
MTV's original five VJs, who once again feels like he's part of
something big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm jumping on a moving freight train,'' Goodman said. ``I
feel lucky to be aboard. The way you get music, the way you listen
to it, the way you buy it, is going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundbreak's digital jocks said their new gigs differ radically
from their broadcast past.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the most exciting part is the ability to interact with
the listeners,'' said Christian. ``I had 30 people in the chat room
last night and it was just going.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobi said listeners get upset when she steps away from the
microphone, and the chatroom keyboard, because they enjoy
constantly interacting with her. Like her colleagues, she's had to
become tech-savvy fast, and a much better typist.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes Internet radio so interesting is the control
fans have over what they hear, said Dave Goldberg, CEO of Santa
Monica-based Launch Media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody likes music, but they don't like everybody else's
music,'' Goldberg said. ``That's why you don't have any music on
MTV's cable broadcasts anymore. They play a Madonna video and
chances are, the people who want to watch a Metallica video don't
want to wait until that's over. We don't have that problem. We give
you control. You get the music you want, when you want it.''
</P>
<P>
   His company's Launchcast software lets listeners build their own
notion of what a station should be. Pick a genre, throwing out
those individual artists you don't like, then save the playlist, as
more than 200,000 people have done. You can share it with friends,
or try out someone else's mix. The software turns Joe Sixpack into
Joseph Tastemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Live365.com and Shoutcast take the notion of personal tastemaker
to its logical end, letting anyone become a station manager,
sending out their own talk show or music.
</P>
<P>
   Their software makes it easy to Webcast anything from
Republicans `R' Us to Led Zeppelin Forever to Clog Music Lovers,
and people do. But it isn't just amateurs using these services.
</P>
<P>
   Blues wunderkind Kenny Wayne Sheppard, for one, put his studio
outtakes, live songs and album cuts on two Live365.com channels,
then linked them to his own fan site.
</P>
<P>
   Enigma Digital doesn't even want to be called a music operation,
though music _ from hard rock to Christian contemporary _ is the
organizing feature around each of its sites, said co-founder Bob
Ezrin, a legendary record producer.
</P>
<P>
   Ezrin calls the sites ``Net-based, individually branded,
genre-specific lifestyle communities. We're creating safe havens
for people whose particular passion is a genre of music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ezrin's company is one of several using music to reach, and
eventually sell to, specific online communities. The Net, Ezrin
said, does a terrific job connecting people of like minds and
diverse geographies into a cohesive community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the world's first three-way medium: connecting
people to stuff, stuff to people and people to each other,'' Ezrin
said. ``It's a whole other animal.''
</P>
<P>
   And with visitors from as many as 58 countries at a time,
someone's listening, and closely: When Enigma's KNAC.com posted a
vintage live track by Guns N' Roses, 75,000 people downloaded it in
three weeks, Ezrin said.
</P>
<P>
   Another pair of pioneers _ Interscope Records founder Jimmy
Iovine and Universal Music Group head Doug Morris _ have rolled out
their own on/offline indefinable: Jimmy and Doug's Farm Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Farm Club is billed as a home where unknown artists could
essentially try out for the big leagues, maybe even sign with
Universal, the world's biggest music company.
</P>
<P>
   Since its announcement in November, Iovine said, Farmclub.com
has added an in-your-face USA Network TV show, record-label
operations and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug and I were sitting around and said, 'If we were going to
start a new record company, what would we do?''' Iovine said. ``It
would be online and offline, it would have cable distribution,
hence a TV show.''
</P>
<P>
   Pigeonholing a music company in one medium is ``an absurd
concept,'' Iovine said. ``The world isn't just on TV, it isn't just
on the Internet, it isn't just on radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Unknown bands can post their tracks online, find bandmates, get
advice from rapper Dr. Dre and other industry vets, and build a fan
base, Iovine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really involves getting the musicians and the community of
people who like music to interact and get closer in this world of
communications,'' said Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   Farmclub.com got off to a rocky start when some bands loudly
questioned how different it truly was from old-media predecessors.
Since then, the company reportedly has begun mending fences, and
amending problematic contract provisions.
</P>
<P>
   MusicBlitz is another paradigm-buster, combining traditional
record-promotion teams with genre-specific Web sites featuring
artists such as Taj Mahal, Presidents of the United States of
America and Aimee Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to take the best of both worlds,'' said CEO Kevin
Nakao. ``You can't just put music on the Web. People think in black
and white, but that's not what we do. We really create the push
behind an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to follow all this can feel like hearing a beginners'
violin recital with a hangover. But focus on where the music is
going, instead of where it used to be. Then dial in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the Net as the new medium,'' said Ezrin.
``It's entirely social. You're putting out information, you're
gathering information, and you're connecting people all at once.
It's something a record company (or radio station) can't do.'' &QL; 
________ &QL; 
To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloomearthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. Related material
can also be found at www.dailynews.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
