<HEADER>
A6956 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-LADY-BIRD-HNS &LR;      03-24 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADY-BIRD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LADY BIRD JOHNSON RETURNS TO CHURCH WHERE SHE MARRIED LBJ 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSIE P. GONZALEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Lady Bird Johnson, the oldest living former first
lady, returned Thursday to the church where she was married to
visit with friends, including the college roommate who was her maid
of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Still chipper and gracious at 87, she granted media interviews,
signed autographs, ate lunch and enjoyed the company of lifelong
friends at St. Mark's Episcopal Church in downtown San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city always will hold a place in my heart,'' Johnson said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance caused something of a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Farnes had taken her 5-year-old granddaughter, Spencer
Bobbitt, to participate in the church's ``Lenten lunch'' program
when she spied Johnson climbing the front steps, a cane in one hand
and the arm of a U.S. Secret Service agent in the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``See her?'' Farnes whispered to the wide-eyed child. ``She's
the lady responsible for planting wildflowers all over the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia ``Lady Bird'' Taylor and Lyndon Baines Johnson, the
future president of the United States who then was a congressman's
secretary, were married at St. Mark's on Nov. 17, 1934, after a
two-month courtship.
</P>
<P>
   Much of their dating took place via Depression-era phones, which
Mrs. Johnson described as ``not sophisticated contraptions.'' But
the conversations were enough to convince LBJ that Claudia Taylor
was the woman for him.
</P>
<P>
   The way Johnson remembers it, LBJ simply wouldn't take no for an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   She consulted an Episcopal prayer book, pondered the possibility
of letting him slip away, and said yes.
</P>
<P>
   The next question was where to marry. Since the bride was from
the East Texas town of Karnack and the groom had grown up in the
Texas Hill Country, San Antonio seemed an unlikely compromise for a
location.
</P>
<P>
   What brought them to the Alamo City to begin their 39-year
marriage was the woman who was to be Mrs. Johnson's maid of honor,
Cecille Marshall, and the best man, Dan Quill, who later became
postmaster here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would love to have Cecille in my wedding,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The two women were roommates while students at the University of
Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been a special person,'' said Marshall, who was
at St. Mark's on Thursday. ``She's not your run-of-the-mill
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall described Johnson as extremely dependable, loyal and
lots of fun. Because they were close friends, Marshall was not
surprised to be asked to take part in the hastily called nuptials
66 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on a Saturday,'' Marshall said. ``She called and said,
`I'm going to be married. Would you stand for me?'''
</P>
<P>
   LBJ dispatched Quill to find a wedding ring, which he purchased
for $2.98 at a Sears &AMP; Roebuck store that was open late, Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   She wore a purple dress, only to learn later that it was LBJ's
least favorite color. She had no ring to give her husband, and
there were no flowers. A 10-day honeymoon in Mexico followed.
</P>
<P>
   Was she happy to have said yes after all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes!'' Johnson said in her trademark drawl.
</P>
<P>
   She was a particular hit with children Thursday. In the church's
bustling cafeteria, 5-year-old Sterling Schrader presented a book
for Johnson to autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Without any hesitation, she signed it with her name and the
inscription, ``For a pretty young lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Chalk, rector of St. Mark's, was happy to have
the former first lady at his church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a great deal to us that Lady Bird, who was married
here, would come back and tell her story,'' he said. ``Their story
is so much a part of our parish.''
</P>
<P>
   The days are long gone when a couple could call him on a
Saturday morning to set up a wedding ceremony that evening, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The church now advises engaged couples to go through a certain
amount of counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priest at that time wanted them to have a waiting period,
too,'' Chalk said. ``But Lyndon was a pretty forceful fellow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
