<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-2TAKE     03-24 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VILLAGE SURVIVORS STRUGGLE TO RECOVER AFTER MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELA CRVKA, Yugoslavia _ There are no signs showing the way to
this small, dusty village tucked in the southwest corner of Kosovo,
but everyone knows where it is.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, people from surrounding villages point the
direction, then lower their eyes and bow their heads.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, 3,000 people lived in Bela Cvrka (pronounced Bella
Circa), but today there are only 2,000. Some walk around with the
dazed look of having survived something awful. A third left and
can't bear to return, so horrible are the memories buried in the
rich, dark earth where local farmers once grew the tastiest green
peppers in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilding that is taking place here is happening all across
Kosovo, where over the last nine months more than 1 million ethnic
Albanians have returned to villages destroyed by Serb forces in the
war that began one year ago. But the reconstruction of Bela Crvka
is more difficult, more poignant and more purposeful than most,
because it wasn't just buildings that were destroyed here.
</P>
<P>
   Last March 25, the day after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia, Serb
troops with blackened faces and even darker hearts surrounded the
village. As night fell the gunmen closed in, and terrified
villagers fled for their lives. The Serbs chased them down and
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, 65 villagers _ men, women, and six children _
were dead, their bodies sprawled in the fields or face down in the
Rimnik, a small river that snakes its way through the area. The
oldest child killed was a 13-year-old boy, the youngest a
2-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors at the International Criminal Tribunal
for the former Yugoslavia, what took place here last March 25 was a
war crime, and it was orchestrated by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic. The massacre is one of six cited in the indictment that
charges Milosevic with using systematic terror against ethnic
Albanians to crush support for independence from Serbia, and,
later, to punish them for NATO's intervention.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators from the war crimes tribunal at The Hague
visit here periodically, gathering evidence and firming up witness
statements, the residents try to put their lives, their homes, and
their community back together. It is a slow, sometimes agonizing,
process.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the local elementary school named Liria, or Freedom, children
laugh and play soccer during recess. The school was trashed by
retreating Serb troops, and villagers had to use wood-burning
stoves in each classroom to make it through the winter. But classes
resumed on schedule, and most of the 450 students seem remarkably
well adjusted. The walls have posters warning children about the
dangers of land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Blrta Fetoshi, 12, a thin, thoughtful girl with brown hair and
almond eyes, said she and other students had lived in terror for
two years before the war began. Serb police and paramilitaries
would cruise by, firing randomly at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers would tell us to dive on the floor,'' she
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the massacre, she hid and was able to flee on a
tractor with her parents and older brother to Albania. The week
after NATO troops liberated the village, her family returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was destroyed. My house was burned. Everything I
had was burned. All my books,'' she said, her eyes misting. ``I
loved my books the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Blrta, whose family is still living in a makeshift home while
repairs continue on their house, wants to become a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to help people,'' she said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The skeletons of charred cars, burned by Serb troops, lie
scattered through the village, some of them dumped in the river.
Children play on them. Before leaving, the Serbs bombed the mosque
and murdered the 29-year-old imam, Hajrulla Begaj. Villagers have
been too busy rebuilding the 300 homes that were destroyed here to
get around to restoring the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very beautiful mosque,'' said Aziz Popaj, 75,
standing in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many graves over there, young children,'' the old
man said, suddenly weeping. ``I survived because I am old. I wish I
died. I wish I died instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting cross-legged on the carpet of his partially rebuilt
farmhouse, his shoes set neatly outside in keeping with Muslim
tradition, Sabri Popaj still can't figure out why he didn't die. He
is 41 but looks 10 years older. His two sons, his only children,
were killed in the massacre. So were his two brothers and nephew.
In all, 22 members of his extended family died in the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On that fateful night last year, he was one of the last
villagers to flee, having stayed behind to release his cows into
the fields so the Serbs wouldn't kill them in their pens. In the
confusion, he got separated from his wife and sons, then sprinted
in the darkness before stumbling on 13 people from two families he
knew. They had stopped by the riverbank, the children too exhausted
and terrified to go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a blanket down and made the children sit,'' he recalled.
``I covered a 2-year-old boy with a blanket. I saw the Serbs
coming, six of them wearing bandannas, and I told everyone to hide,
to scatter.''
</P>
<P>
   Popaj hid in a nearby irrigation ditch. There was utter
confusion in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is NATO for you now!,'' he heard one of the gunmen yell
before the firing began.
</P>
<P>
   The boy under the blanket, Dibran Zhuniqi, miraculously escaped
uninjured. Everyone else, including his parents, was slaughtered.
War crimes investigators later found a needle and syringe nearby,
and suspect it was used by at least one of the killers to whip
himself into a killing frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   As he lay in the darkness, Popaj heard more shooting, more
screaming, as the Serbs mowed down civilians fleeing along the
river. He did not move for two days.
</P>
<P>
   When Popaj and some other villagers tentatively emerged from
their hiding places, he saw his shepherd dogs, Karabash and Trum,
standing over a group of bodies on the riverbank, whimpering
mournfully. He found his sons, Shendet, 17, and Agon, 13, lying
dead in shallow water.
</P>
<P>
   Popaj and his neighbors began burying the dead, 36 the first
night, 29 the next day. It was exhausting, numbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel dead, like they are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the riverbank, he found brightly colored rubber boots of the
dead children. He went to put them in the graves but found he
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the nearby village of Celine, where 74 people were
killed in a similar massacre. Again, he helped bury the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Celine, I buried a child, not even a year old,'' Popaj
said, staring at his whitewashed wall. ``She had a bottle, still
sucking on it in death. We wanted to take it out, but we couldn't
so we buried her with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, more than three months after the massacre, war crimes
investigators came and gingerly explained that the bodies had to be
dug up so they could examine them for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always the relatives who dig them up,'' Popaj said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
