<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-2ND &LR;  &UR;      03-24 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BELLA CRVYKA, Yugoslavia: ... Popaj said.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retrieving the decomposing bodies of his two sons from the earth
was simultaneously macabre and heart-rending. But there was a
sliver of mercy for Popaj: a roll of undeveloped film in his son
Agon's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   He had the film processed and now carries the photos around with
him _ snapshots of Agon's friends, a picture of Shendet smiling _
memories from the grave. It's not much, but the photos and a cheap
black watch he took from Shendet's wrist are all he has. He wears
his dead son's watch. The rest of the family's belongings were
destroyed by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others here, Popaj has what psychologists call
survivor's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday I ask, why did I survive?'' he said. ``Why did I
live?''
</P>
<P>
   He has no answers, and he sometimes wishes he hadn't lived, so
overwhelming, so visceral is the grief he shoulders. But more
often, Popaj is consumed by a sense of duty that keeps him going.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has been on this land for 350 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so determined. His cousin, Feim Popaj, 35, was
shot in the hip and chest by marauding Serbs but managed to get
away. Popaj used a primitive first aid kit to cut out one bullet
lodged just beneath his cousin's skin, then nursed him back to
health on a diet of only milk.
</P>
<P>
   As his neighbors flocked back here, Feim Popaj asked his cousin
to get him out. Sabri Popaj paid someone $2,000 to smuggle him to
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he will never come back,'' Popaj said, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   His nephew, Valdet Popaj, 25, had the opposite reaction. He had
been living in Switzerland, seeking asylum, for five years. After
the war ended, he volunteered to come home to help his uncle
resurrect the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost so many members of my family, the material destruction
I found here did not bother me,'' Valdet Popaj said, taking a break
from building a makeshift greenhouse for peppers.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the village, 43-year-old Sahit Zhuniqi sat on a
crate in Reshit Gashi's newly reopened grocery shop, drinking cheap
Turkish beer in the middle of the afternoon. Zhuniqi's eyes were
red, his speech slurred. Gashi nodded toward him, smiling
awkwardly, as if to say, ``Who can blame him?''
</P>
<P>
   No one does.
</P>
<P>
   ``They killed 13 members of my family,'' Zhuniqi said,
approaching a visitor unsteadily to shake his hand. ``They killed
my father, brother, four children. . .''
</P>
<P>
   His voice trailed off. Zhuniqi closed his eyes, shook his head,
then went back to his crate and can of beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is not so good,'' said Gashi, 57, glancing at his
tortured friend. ``I've had a shop here for more than 30 years. But
no one has money these days. I will try to stay open. Maybe things
will get better.''
</P>
<P>
   You hear that a lot in Bela Crvka.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers hope there will be more indictments, not just of
bigshots like Milosevic, but of the men who pulled the triggers.
Sabri Popaj's wife has identified one of the men who led villagers
away. He is a Serb who lived in a neighboring village.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew him before the war,'' Popaj said softly, almost as if
he can't believe it. ``I knew him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most others here, Popaj says he can never live with Serbs
again, not after what happened.
</P>
<P>
   His dogs, which loyally guarded the dead of Bela Crvka on the
riverbank, did not survive the year. Trum was shot by Serbs, and
Karabash was struck and killed by a NATO armored vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the war and the relative freedom it has brought was
worth it, Popaj pulled hard on a cigarette and exhaled slowly,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   He tried exile, 45 days in Germany. He hated it. He came home.
He will not leave again, he said. There are some things you can't
run away from.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I do?'' he said, his eyes glistening with tears or
hope or maybe both. ``I had two sons who are dead here. I will stay
with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
