<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TRUMP CARD ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his latest war of words with the National Rifle Association,
President Clinton has the ultimate trump card: the American people.
</P>
<P>
   This is the best time ever to speak for the people, given the
NRA's recent looniness and last week's concessions by Smith &AMP;
Wesson to agree to install safety locks on guns and refuse to
participate in gun shows that do not conduct background checks on
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there are some aspects of gun control that the American
people are reluctant to entertain. In different polls, only between
32 percent and 50 percent of Americans favor a nationwide ban on
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Only 28 percent of Americans support the Justice Department's
suing gun manufacturers as a way to recoup health care and law
enforcement costs due to gun violence. Forty-eight percent of
Americans think the Second Amendment guarantees the right to own
guns, compared with 38 percent who say ``not necessarily'' or
``don't know/no answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The polls show ambivalence on concealed weapons. In an April
1999 NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll, 73 percent of Americans
disapproved of new laws making it easier to carry concealed
weapons. But a September 1999 Washington Post/ABC News poll found
Americans split down the middle on banning them outright, with 49
percent in favor of a ban and 48 percent against a ban.
</P>
<P>
   Even the NRA, at least before its latest bombasts, had
credibility. Polls show that about 50 percent of Americans had a
favorable opinion of the NRA, compared with about 40 percent who
had an unfavorable opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans also do not want to continue to live in the wild,
wild West. There is much Clinton can do to pressure Congress into
action on gun control. The polls, all from 1999 and 2000, also
show:
</P>
<P>
   --Between 72 to 77 percent of Americans favor federal licensing
of handgun owners (Yankelovich Partners and ABC News/Washington
Post).
</P>
<P>
   --Between 73 and 79 percent of Americans favor registration of
all handguns (Gallup/CNN/USA Today).
</P>
<P>
   --Between 59 and 68 percent of Americans favor stricter gun
control laws (CNN/Time, ABC News/Washington Post, and Gallup).
</P>
<P>
   --Ninety percent _ 9 out of 10 Americans _ support background
checks on people buying firearms at gun shows (ABC News/Washington
Post).
</P>
<P>
   --Ninety-three percent favor a general mandatory waiting period
and background for all gun buyers (Newsweek).
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly 8 out of 10 Americans want a national ban on the sale
of assault weapons (ABC News/Washington Post and CBS News).
</P>
<P>
   --Only 4 percent of Americans are pleased about the way Congress
has handled gun control (ABC News/Washington Post).
</P>
<P>
   --Eighty-nine percent of Americans favor requiring child safety
locks on all new handguns (Newsweek).
</P>
<P>
   --Sixty-one percent of Americans favor requiring owners of
hunting rifles to register with the government (Newsweek).
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy two percent of Americans believe criminals should lose
their rights to a plea bargain when use a gun in their crimes
(CNN/Time).
</P>
<P>
   --Eighty-two percent believe the minimum age for handgun
posession should be 21 (Gallup/CNN).
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy-nine percent favor the registration of all firearms
(Gallup).
</P>
<P>
   --Sixty-eight percent favor banning high-capacity ammunition
clips (Gallup/CNN).
</P>
<P>
   --Between 77 and 84 percent think gun owners should have to take
an instruction course, similar to what drivers must do in order to
drive a car (Newsweek and Fox/Opinion Dynamics).
</P>
<P>
   --Sixty-one percent say they would be more likely to vote for
their congressional representative if he or she votes for tougher
gun control measures (Fox/Opinion Dynamics).
</P>
<P>
   --Sixty-five percent believe controlling gun ownership is more
important than protecting the right to own guns (Pew).
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy-five percent of African-Americans (who
disproportionately suffer from gun violence) and 75 perent of women
believe controlling gun ownership is more important than protecting
gun rights (Pew 1999).
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy percent of Americans believe stricter gun control laws
would reduce violent crime by either a little or a lot, compared to
26 percent who say more laws would not reduce violent crime ``at
all'' (Newsweek).
</P>
<P>
   With those numbers, Clinton cannot lose if he fights for some
forms of gun control. The NRA has the money, outspending Handgun
Control on a current media blitz, 3 to 1. The NRA has Congress
wrapped around its finger with cash and threats. But Clinton holds
the ace if he would only use it: the people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
