<HEADER>
A6963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-OSCARS-RICHARDSON-ART     03-24 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-RICHARDSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WINNING AN OSCAR WON'T MAKE ROBERT RICHARDSON ANY LESS INTENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURNE, Mass. _ He's jumped out of airplanes and filmed with
bullets whizzing by his head, but the thought of going to Sunday
night's Academy Awards, where he's nominated for an Oscar, fills
him with fear. So cinematographer Robert Richardson plans to hole
up at home on the Cape, watching the telecast with his family.
</P>
<P>
   This is not because he's already the jaded owner of one golden
trophy, the 1992 Oscar he won for the original camerawork on Oliver
Stone's ``JFK.'' It has nothing do with his conviction that he
won't win Sunday for his work on ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' Nor is
he a cameraman's version of the politically sensitive Marlon Brando
or George C. Scott, both of whom re-
</P>
<P>
   fused to accept their statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old director of photography (or DP) describes
himself as mischievous, a kind of evil prankster. And depending on
his expression, he can look the part, with his pointed beard,
devilishly arched eyebrows, and mane of prematurely white hair. But
he's not jesting about his phobic dread. ``It's too intense,'' he
says, comparing an on-site awards experience to something ``near
death.'' Attending the Oscars or other awards ceremonies when he's
a nominee makes him sick, Richardson says. After going to the
Oscars the first time he was nominated, for ``Platoon,'' Richardson
vowed: never again. Presenter Richard Gere accepted the ``JFK''
statuette for him.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is open and curious about his own psychology, and
this searching quality makes him a close observer of his creative
impulses. He has shot approximately 20 films, 13 with Stone, the
rest mostly with other top directors like Martin Scorsese, John
Sayles, Errol Morris, and Barry Levinson. But the word that often
comes to his mind as he reflects on his admirable body of work is
``panic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why I'm so vulnerable,'' he says, nursing a cup
of coffee. When shooting a film, he says, he suffers through the
nights, restively reliving yesterday's shoot and agonizing over
tomorrow's. He speaks of ``panic attacks all night long'' and
trying to ``numb'' his nerves with sleeping pills.
</P>
<P>
   Panic seems misplaced in the tranquil interview setting _ a
high-ceilinged sitting room in the comfortable if eccentric home
Richardson shares with his wife and two daughters. It's an
Italianate eight-bedroom ``cottage'' built by a Boston banker at
the turn of the previous century on a private island near Monument
Beach. As we talk, late winter snow swirls over Buzzards Bay and
frills the gray sky like a scene from ``Snow Falling on Cedars.''
It's hard to believe this gifted and acclaimed DP (four Oscar
nominations, among others honors) both harbors and frankly reveals
so much insecurity. Still, he values his achievements. He thinks
``Snow Falling on Cedars'' was a beautiful film, and credits the
vision of director Scott Hicks and then his own creative
contributions. But ``it's very rare that a film will win visually
that hasn't been nominated for best picture. Things are latched,
it's sad,'' he says. ``Cedars' '' only nomination was for best
cinematography, and, Richardson says, `` `American Beauty' is
running hot.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was filming ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' Richardson's
nocturnal uneasiness abated _ for the first time, he didn't agonize
every night. On the other hand, the subjects of his alarm were
``much larger issues,'' such as the fear of losing his creative
touch completely. Burnout will ``get me,'' he says, and he worries
about the eventual decline of the mature directors who employ him
and the advent of ``a much younger group.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes his sense of fragility is connected to his
creativity and that it feeds it. It ``keeps me constantly wanting
to change.''
</P>
<P>
   His fear, then, has a function. So perhaps it shouldn't sound
too paradoxical that Richardson is attracted to danger. He used to
parachute out of airplanes for fun. He operated a camera in the
face of live gunfire in the '80s, filming combat footage in El
Salvador for a PBS ``Frontline.'' (The experience prepared him for
his first job as director of photography, on Oliver Stone's intense
1986 fictional treatment of Central American strife, ``Salvador.'')
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of the fear is a kind of spell or ecstasy the
cinematographer says he experiences behind the camera.
``Extraordinarily concentrated emotion drives me forward,'' he
says, to a point where he virtually loses consciousness. It's a
``zone'' where the world falls away: ``With my eye up to the
eyepiece, I'm there.'' He can't describe it more precisely, he
says. ``I blank out. The closest thing I would say would be the
first time I jumped out of an airplane. There's a blank spot from
when I left the plane to when my parachute was open: Time doesn't
exist in that space.''
</P>
<P>
   Resisting scripts he considers less than first-rate, Richardson
shot ``Bringing Out the Dead'' a year and a half ago, right after
``Cedars,'' and hasn't done a feature since. So, as he often does
between films, he directs commercials, and recently filmed
campaigns for United Airlines and the US Army. He takes the work
seriously: ``I bleed to make these things as good as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He's away from home working far more often than he's on the Cape
with his wife, writer and independent filmmaker Monona Wali, and
their children. ``Monona has basically become a saint,'' he says.
Still, why does he insist on a base so far from the movie capital
of the world?
</P>
<P>
   As with other aspects of Richardson's life, there appears to be
a long braid of complex motives, his boyhood in Brewster, where his
parents operated the Cape Cod Sea Camps, being just a fraction of
the story. But one thing is certain: Much of what Richardson does
is determined by what, and how, he sees.
</P>
<P>
   After a near family tragedy seven years ago when they lived in
Los Angeles, the Richardsons scouted the Northeast for a home,
starting in Maine. The moment he saw the big stucco house on
Buzzards Bay, then unimproved and framed by thickets of brambles,
Richardson was sold. ``It was love at first sight, the drive up the
winding dirt road, the surrounding water.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he tends to view the world in cinematic terms,
Richardson describes his unique perspective. ``I put elements
together. Looking at you, I see the chair, the way you're pushed
against the windows, and I see the flowers behind your head. I
don't see them in one image: I see them in a whole series of boxes,
almost as if I were trying to put a story together.'' His
perception functions this way all the time, ``and I think it's
because my brain doesn't work in a linear fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was a Rhode Island School of Design film student in the
late '70s, he chose cinematography because he didn't think his mind
was developed enough to be a director. But recently, he's been
angling to bring his practiced eye to a movie of his own. In 1998,
he signed to direct the film version of author James Ellroy's
novel, ``White Jazz'' (Ellroy also wrote ``L.A. Confidential'').
The two have been conferring about Ellroy's script and hoping the
project, produced by Nick Nolte, who is slated to star in it, will
soon move forward. Richardson isn't optimistic. ``That's why
directors go absolutely crazy _ the development of a project is
highly unpredictable and doesn't make tremendous sense. It may
happen, but not in my time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to know better than Richardson that the moviemaking
life is a notoriously capricious, costly and nerve-damaging game of
chance. If he doesn't get a shot at directing a feature film,
``I'll survive,'' he says. Then he leaves the sitting room to
conduct a tour of his fine, solid old house while the wind lashes
the water and the snow continues falling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
