<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-HERE-ON-BOS &LR;      03-24 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HERE-ON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAUDLIN SCRIPT MARS `HERE ON EARTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HERE ON EARTH 
Directed by: Mark Piznarski 
Screenplay by: Michael Seitzman 
Starring: Chris Klein, Leelee Sobieski, Josh Hartnett, Michael
Rooker, Annie Corley, Bruce Greenwood, Annette O'Toole 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some sensuality and thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three appealing performers are lumbered with material that
doesn't measure up to them in ``Here on Earth.'' It's a tepid
tearjerker about young love bridging the traditional town-gown
divide in a farm town adjoining a flossy prep school. It asks us to
believe that Chris Klein's spoiled preppy isn't the shallow twit he
seems when he destroys the town's only diner with the new Mercedes
his rich dad got him for graduation. Leelee Sobieski, as the
daughter of the woman who owned the diner, senses he's a poetic
soul and proves it to herself by sneaking up on him in the woods
and hearing him recite Robert Frost to himself. So moved is she
that she drops the nice local boy (John Hartnett) she's known for
years to concentrate on the arrogant rich kid who's been sentenced
to stick around town and help rebuild the diner for which his
absent dad is paying.
</P>
<P>
   The preppies-on-parade stuff gives way to a prickly
getting-acquainted period, egged on by such clumsy devices as the
rejected guy's kid sister looking the rich kid over and saying, ``I
think he's hot.'' What's jarring is the contemporary ring of the
term because even though the car was new, too, the film has the
feel of something very dated, something immersed in the formulas of
the late '50s and early '60s. Of course, in one sense, the guy is
hot. His temperature goes up every time he thinks about himself,
and this self-styled babe magnet thinks about himself all the time.
Given her tender and perceptive attentions, he thaws, and begins
reciprocating her interest. Before it's all over, she accompanies
him back to his family mansion and learns what vulnerable piece of
personal history his facade _ she knew it was a facade _ is
concealing.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can tiptoe around the rich kid's sulks and not
embarrass himself in a scene in which he gets drunk and talks to
cows, it should be Klein, who played the nice-guy candidate in
``Election.'' He does intermittently reduce the animosity his
character generates. Sobieski has softly lyrical moments when she
makes us believe her character is experiencing first love. And
Hartnett affectingly projects raw pain as the jilted one. But the
prefab writing finally self-destructs in a cop-out ending that's as
convenient as it is sentimental. It's one thing to be retro,
especially given the film's smalltown setting (set in
Massachusetts, it actually was filmed in Minnesota). But the
predictability, calculation, and compromise that end up swamping
``Here on Earth'' would face losing odds in any time period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1545EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6965 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-WHATEVER-BOS &LR;      03-24 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WHATEVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECTLY FORGETTABLE TEEN COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WHATEVER IT TAKES 
Directed by: David Raynr 
Screenplay by: Mark Schwahn 
Starring: Shane West, Jodi Lyn O'Keefe, Marla Sokoloff, James
Franco 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The producers of ``Whatever It Takes,'' in the apparent belief
that it doesn't take much, settle for the most obvious load of
formula stuff in a numbingly cliched teen comedy pivoting on a lot
of plastic angst over who'll take whom to the prom. The best thing
in it is Marla Sokoloff, partly because her smart, secure,
straight-shooting character doesn't fit the cliched mold of the
kind of girl high-school guys chase. Still, she's the one who
catches the eye of the school's self-styled babe magnet, played
with suitable obnoxiousness by James Franco. In the film, the guy
may be a cliched jock, but he at least has taste.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligent, sensitive guy played by Shane West, on the
other hand, is crazy about Jodi Lyn O'Keefe's most popular (but not
most secure) girl. There are the usual nerdy sidekicks, the usual
boneheaded scheming, the usual physical comedy _ some involving a
girls' shower room, some a ``Titanic'' caper. The usual, the usual,
the usual. The spectacle of the guys sorting out their feelings,
and the girls killing time until they do, is less than
electrifying. Was high school really this dumb? Could be. But even
in a genre that aims low, ``Whatever It Takes'' is pretty lame
stuff. Already it seems to be passing with the speed of light into
the limbo of utterly forgettable who-will-I-take-to-the-prom?
movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1547EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
