u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-24 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTY' DISPLAYS HOLLYWOOD'S NEW CLICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps you missed it; sexagenarian movie critic Rex Reed was
arraigned last week on charges of shoplifting three CDs (Mel Torme,
Carmen McRae, and Peggy Lee) from a Tower Records. Bantering with
reporters outside Manhattan Criminal Court, Reed protested his
innocence and worked in his plug for best picture at this Sunday's
Oscar ceremonies: ``I hope `American Beauty' wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed's not the only one. The critics loved ``Beauty.'' ``A
quirky and disturbing take on modern American life energized by
bravura performances,'' wrote the LA Times' Kenneth Turan. Like the
movie itself, David Denby's New Yorker review was so over-the-top,
you had to wonder if he was kidding. ``By far the strongest
American film of the year . . . rich, brilliant, unnerving . . .
mesmerizing hyperreality . . . the editing discovers . . . the
hidden connections among things.'' Waiter! Something cool for Mr.
Denby, please . . .
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I pretty much hated it. Maybe I took it too personally, as
I am the object of contemporary tastemakers' contempt _ a married,
white, heterosexual suburban parent. But I have to ask _ is there
any dime-store banality that writer Alan Ball and director Sam
Mendes didn't stuff inside this two-hour celluloid whale?
</P>
<P>
   1. Heterosexual white couples who live in suburban homes with
white picket fences _ as opposed to cool places, like LA's west
side _ are sexually frustrated adulterers. Natch.
</P>
<P>
   2. The worker is alienated from Evil Capitalism. ``Beauty''
protagonist Lester Burnham works as a self-described ``whore for
the advertising industry,'' which Hollywood purports to disdain.
Except when it is used to promote sensitive, cutting-edge material
like ``American Beauty,'' that is. The film's producers are
reported to have spent $775,000 in trade industry ads alone,
puffing their product for an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   3. Capitalism Is Evil, the Sequel: Burnham's boss pays for sex
with the company credit card _ doesn't everybody? The script,
personally approved for production by Steven Spielberg, spends a
good 20 minutes mocking the commercialism of the hateful real
estate business. As opposed to the public-spirited movie business,
I guess.
</P>
<P>
   4. You're in the military? You must be queer. All those men
packed in together . . . those guns, with the long barrels. In the
character of Marine colonel Frank Fitts, the filmmakers have scored
a twofer _ he's a militaristic homophobe, and he's gay! So I guess
that makes him (see cliche number one) an adulterous parent. It
gets better still: He's a militaristic, gay, Nazi-loving homophobe.
He probably wears fur, too.
</P>
<P>
   The original script had a scene in which Colonel Fitts watched
his male lover die in Vietnam. That might have been useful to roll
in yet another Hollywood cliche _ you know, the Vietnam War/loss of
innocence thing. (Cf ``Rambo,'' ``The Rock,'' and everything in
between.) In case you missed the connection between guns and
psychotic behavior, as Burnham's wife starts to go off the deep
end, she shows up at a firing range.
</P>
<P>
   5. God/the Life Force is a white plastic bag blowing in the
wind. Yessiree, I think we've got Oscar on the line!
</P>
<P>
   Are there nice touches? Yes. The teenage Ricky Fitts and
Lester's daughter, Jane, are terrific characters. True, they hate
their parents and they loathe modern society, but they've got
options _ money, his unashamedly earned in the drug trade _ and
they've got each other. Their characters are as well written as
everyone seems to think the rest of the movie is.
</P>
<P>
   Onto Ricky's spindly shoulders has been loaded the film's tinny
Message. Has the boy really tuned in to ``this incredibly
benevolent force who wanted me to know that there was no reason to
be afraid''? Or is that just the G-13 _ the US government's
genetically engineered marijuana _ talking? I'll let you be the
judge of that.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is agog with this ``uncompromising'' portrayal of
American society. But, in fact, it is a highly compromised
Hollywood fantasy of what life must be like in the Forbidden Zone,
those horrid, soulless suburbs where no self-respecting director or
screenwriter would live. Essentially gay, essentially nihilistic,
informed by a penny-Zenny spirituality that would make a
Scientologist blush, ``American Beauty'' is big-budget, Technicolor
junk.
</P>
<P>
   Arty junk; probably Oscar-winning junk. But junk nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
