<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-NODOUBT-BOS &LR;      03-24 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NODOUBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DOUBT: BACK ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The public sheds no tears for a successful band trying to follow
up a top-selling album. Oh, are we supposed to feel sorry for them?
From the band's point of view, though, it can be a daunting task to
grab the brass ring again. Writer's block can creep in. So can
self-doubt, which the ironically named No Doubt has fought ever
since it began more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been interesting this time around because we've
never been in this position of having expectations,'' says No Doubt
singer Gwen Stefani. ``We did a press conference in New York and 50
people flew in from all over to listen to our record and ask us
questions. It still blows my mind that people care.''
</P>
<P>
   No Doubt jumped from obscure club act to amphitheater headliner
with its last album, ``Tragic Kingdom,'' which sold 6 million
copies and spun off three Top 10 hits in ``Don't Speak,'' ``Just a
Girl,'' and ``Spiderwebs.'' It also made a star of the videogenic,
navel-exposing Stefani, though it didn't make writing the new
album, ``Return From Saturn,'' any easier.
</P>
<P>
   The new disc _ an exciting progression that takes the band's
basic ska-rock sound and expands it in many directions _ comes out
April 11.
</P>
<P>
   The album climaxes two years of false starts and a switch in
producers. The low point came when No Doubt was in Stefani's home
in the Hollywood Hills, stumped for ideas, while having to listen
to the Red Hot Chili Peppers _ their onetime LA club idols _
perform reams of new music up the street, where Flea, the bassist
for Chili Peppers, lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were trying to write at Gwen's house, we could hear them
in their garage just bashing out all these new jams every afternoon
for a whole week,'' says No Doubt guitarist Tom Dumont. ``We just
felt so inadequate. We couldn't write anything and there they were,
jamming and having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But No Doubt got its act together, helped by a shift in
producers from Matthew Wilder (who did ``Tragic Kingdom'') to Glen
Ballard, who is best known for Alanis Morissette's ``Jagged Little
Pill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen was pretty much meant to be,'' says Stefani. ``It was
weird, because we had been working on the album for about a year
before we met him. We just really needed to find the right person,
and he was recommended. He didn't seem like the obvious choice to
us, but we had meetings with five different producers one day and
he was one of them. We all walked out saying, `That's the guy.'
He's just a really amazing person, a real kind of peaceful
personality. He's inspiring and hard-working. He pretty much
brought all our confidence back and helped us sort through the
songs we had at that point. We couldn't tell which ones were good
and bad, you know? But he helped pick the ones that stood out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, the band's former producer, had started working on the
new record, but ``first of all, we didn't have the songs,'' says
Stefani. ``And second of all, I think we were just too comfortable
with Matthew. We needed to get outside our comfort zone and kind of
push ourselves a little bit. Sometimes you need to do something
different to get something different.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is a greater depth in musical and lyrical
content, from the subtly sarcastic first single, ``Ex-Girlfriend''
(with Stefani singing, ``You know it makes me sick to know I'm on
that list, but I should have thought of that before we kissed'') to
high-quality rock, ska-rock, and funk, plus more love ballads than
before. One ballad, ``Too Late,'' has the playfully possessive
line, ``I just want to take you from everyone and keep you
stashed.''
</P>
<P>
   The album rocks enough to hold the interest of the teen audience
that craved the band last time but is also thought-provoking enough
to entice more adult fans. And Stefani, who writes most of the
lyrics, has kept her inimitable wit in songs like ``Artificial
Sweetener'' and ``Magic's in the Makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In No Doubt's past, before `Tragic Kingdom,' even maybe during
`Tragic Kingdom,' it was all about energy and having a really
pumped-up sound so people would get off on us live,'' says Dumont.
``It was almost the energy of punk with more of a melodic approach.
This time, the idea was not just trying to get things upbeat and in
your face, but to use a little more dynamics and worry less about
the tempo and more about what the lyrics were saying and how we
could best bring out their emotional content.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for Gwen, between recording `Tragic Kingdom' and this
record, she learned a lot,'' Dumont adds. ``Instead of singing on
10 the whole time, she was able to have a lot more subtlety.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefani shines most on ``Simple Kind of Life,'' the first tune
she has written entirely by herself. ``All I ever wanted was a
simple man . . . all I ever wanted was a simple life,'' sings
Stefani, who in real life has been dating heartthrob singer Gavin
Rossdale of the band Bush for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new album title, that's Stefani's idea as well. She
just turned 30 and was looking for a way to embrace that age rather
than run from it.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers say it takes Saturn 29 years to circle the sun, she
explains. ``So from the time you're born to the time it returns is
a time where you go through a confusion and you second-guess
everything in your life and clear away things that are holding you
back from growing and maturing and moving on and getting better. I
feel a lot clearer now. It's such a huge accomplishment for us to
be able to write this record and feel we have grown this much. It's
like the peak of our ongoing dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1550EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-USAIR-STRUGGLE-ART-BO     03-24 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAIR-STRUGGLE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 LOOMING LABOR DISPUTE DAMPENS AIRLINE'S CHEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TOULOUSE, France _ This should be the best of times for US
Airways.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the airline showed off its newest aircraft here, the
Airbus A330, which will become the backbone of the nation's 6th
largest airline, the dominant carrier in the Northeast. The
airplane will serve North Atlantic routes as US Airways expands its
three east coast hubs, Pittsburgh, Charlotte, N.C., and
Philadelphia, where the airline is also building a $350-million
international terminal and increasing its seven daily overseas
flights.
</P>
<P>
   But the flowing champagne and good cheer that accompanied the
unveiling of the Airbus A330 in the US Airways color scheme could
not mask the labor problem facing the nation's 5th busiest airline
with 55.8 million passengers last year. The carrier's more than
9,000 flight attendants have been working without a contract for
more than three years, and they threaten to begin random job
walkouts on busy routes beginning Saturday. Rather than subject
customers to the uncertainty of wildcat walkouts, management has
vowed to shut the airline down if an agreement cannot be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with the National Mediation Board continued
Thursday, but barring an agreement or continuation of talks past
the deadline, the airline will shut down unless President Clinton
intervenes. Boston's Logan International Airport will be
particularly hard hit, where US Airways controls about 20 percent
of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen M. Wolf, the airline's chairman, and chief executive
officer Rakesh Gangwal, who joined came to the airline in 1996
after running United, developed a plan to reduce the airline's
staggering operating costs by wringing concessions from labor
groups. In return, management promised they would spend billions
growing the airline. Otherwise, Wolf said, US Airways would shrink
to become a regional player.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said it would offer its workers ``parity plus one''
meaning they would get what workers at the big four _ United,
American, Delta and Northwest _ got, plus one 1 percent. Contracts
were reached with pilots and mechanics, but negotiations with the
Association of Flight Attendants have gone on, and a 30-day cooling
off period ends at 12:01 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   There are an array of issues at dispute beyond salary, including
management's desire to change work rules which would, among other
things, make scheduling more efficient, and limit sick leave. The
union wants better pensions and the airline to recognize the Family
Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   Because management reached parity plus one with pilots and
mechanics, it is unlikely it would budge with the flight
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   While in Toulouse to view the new A330, Wolf said the airline
was ``in active negotiations and we are committed to getting an
agreement.'' In an interview, however, he vowed to shut the airline
down rather than have passengers face the uncertainty of flight
cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very unattractive thing to do, but it is the better of
two options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After making more than $530 million in profit in 1998, the
airline made $197 million in 1999, but lost money in the last two
quarters. Wolf said the airline lost money in January, and it is
not likely it will make money in the first quarter, or second
quarter, since the threat of a shutdown has had an adverse affect
on bookings into the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming we get a resolution, we look promisingly toward the
second half of the year,'' said Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   But even with a flight attendant pact, it will not be a
turbulant-free flight for US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier has a cost-per-seat mile, an industry standard for
measuring cost, above 12 cents. Southwest Airlines _ US Airways
main low-cost competitor on the east coast _ has a cost above 7
cents, and Delta's cost is just under 9 cents.
</P>
<P>
   One reason costs are so high at US Airways is because it has one
of the most varied fleets, with seven different types of aircraft.
Training costs for cockpit crews, which must be certified in each
aircraft type, is exhorbitant. If a maintenance or scheduling
problem creates a delay, that problem can be compounded if the only
spare airplane is a different type, or another flight crew
certified to fly the airplane is not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   When US Airways reached an agreement with pilots in 1996, the
airline went ahead with a plan to convert its entire fleet to
Airbus aircraft. If all orders are realized _ more than 150 are
firm _ the airline will fly about 400 A320 aircraft and 30 A330
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in effect, a gamble of about $17 billion, but one airline
officials are confident will save US Airways more than $100 million
annually in operation and training costs. Airbus planes have the
same cockpit, so when a pilot is certified to fly an A320, they can
also fly the A319 and A321. With minimal training, they can fly the
A330 and A340. US Airways is using the A320 already on the shuttle
and main lines. For the shuttle, the new planes use half the fuel
of the Boeing 727s they replace and are so quiet that US Airways
can leave Washington, D.C. at 6 a.m. _ a full hour before curfew is
lifted on noisy planes. The airline will also save millions in
parts inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Jenkins, director of the Aviation Institute at George
Washington University, thinks buying all Airbus is a smart move,
but cautioned that US Airways still has its ``work cut out for them
because of their costs and they face so much competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Southwest, JetBlue, a low-cost start-up with more
than $130 million in venture capital has begun flying from New
York's John F. Kennedy International Airport to Florida and plans
on expanding throughout the east coast over the next two years. And
US Airways is restricted by its pilot contract to 35 regional jets
while other airlines, Continental especially, are moving to replace
their turboprops with so-called RJs (regional jets) which
passengers prefer. Wolf said the airline is negotiating with pilots
for another 35 regional jets, and wants many more.
</P>
<P>
   One way in which US Airways has responded is with its low-cost
MetroJet. After some tinkering, US Airways is focusing on using
MetroJet on Northeast-Florida routes, freeing up main line aircraft
to support hub operations.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways also faces stiff competiton from main line carriers,
especially Delta and United, which is building up a hub at Dulles
International Airport, a short distance from US Airways' corporate
headquarters in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the largest carrier on the east coast and very well
positioned, but we do face increasing competition,'' Wolf said.
``United is growing at Dulles and Delta has clear focus on us.''
</P>
<P>
   US Airways response is to win competitive labor agreements, reap
the savings from Airbus aircraft, improve hubs and grow
internationally, a huge profit center for airlines. The centerpiece
of that international strategy is the A330. US Airways is the first
American carrier to have the A330, and the only carrier to offer
on-demand video and audio at every seat, even in coach.
</P>
<P>
   But the airline is focusing on premium class service for
business travelers across the Atlantic. US Airways' award-winning
Envoy premium class has a menu developed with Philadelphia's
renowned Le Bec Fin restaurant. Flight attendants recieve training
from the Culinary Institute of America. And unlike Delta, which did
away with first class, US Airways will have six seats in a first
class section on the A330.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways officials view its Charlotte, N.C. hub as a
convenient, less-crowded alternative to Delta's fortress in
Atlanta. The airline is boosting its international service from
Charlotte, which now serves London, with daily flights to Paris
starting April 13 and daily flights to Frankfurt in May.
</P>
<P>
   The airline gave up its international service from Boston when
it applied for and failed to get Boston-Paris service. The
Department of Transportation awarded that service to American,
leaving US Airways only with Boston-Frankfurt service. Officials
decided to use the aircraft for international service from
Philadelphia, but want to return to Boston. At Logan, US Airways is
locked in fierce competition with Delta. Delta is building a new
terminal and US Airways completed one $30 million expansion that
added 100,000 square feet to Terminal B and is beginning another
$33 million expansion that will add 65,000 square feet and four new
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston remains a significant market for us and international
flying makes sense from there,'' said Lawrence M. Nagin, executive
vice president of US Airways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
