<HEADLINE>
PARKER GIVES SPENSER A CHANCE TO HORSE AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HUGGER MUGGER 
By Robert B. Parker. 
G. P. Putnam's Sons, 307 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert B. Parker has launched a couple of new mystery series
featuring Jesse Stone, North Shore policeman and recovering
alcoholic, and Sunny Randall, a feisty female shamus. But he
remains as loyal as loyal to Spenser as his readers do.
</P>
<P>
   Spenser's new adventure departs from Parker's patented formula,
but then most of the good ones have. Spenser doesn't cook this time
and doesn't spend much time in Boston restaurants. In fact, Boston
is not the primary venue: Most of the story takes place in
horse-raising country, Lamarr, Georgia, and the action also takes
Spenser to San Francisco, Atlanta, and Saratoga, N.Y. A few members
of the regular local supporting cast appear in walk-on or offstage
roles, but Hawk is absent _ he's flown to Paris with a professor.
</P>
<P>
   Susan is still around to be sensitive and sexy; she gives
Spenser somebody to think lustfully about and to talk dirty to.
Spenser chivalrously resists the advances of drunken Southern
belles, but it's probably a good thing that Susan flies in from
time to time for reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Hugger Mugger is a horse, a potential Triple Crown winner, and
he's in danger. Somebody is shooting horses down in the Three
Fillies Stables, so Walter Clive, owner of the stables, has come
looking for help, and he's come to the right man. Spenser's
attention is engaged by the situation _ and by the knees and ankles
of Clive's youngest daughter, Penny, who has been running the
business. Penny shows up in Spenser's office with eyes ``the color
of morning glories,'' and wearing pearls and white gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Down in Lamarr, Spenser meets the rest of Clive's family,
including Penny's sisters, SueSue and Stonie, and their husbands,
hard-drinking Pud and Cord, who looks like a polo player, although
Spenser confesses he's never met a polo player. Before very long,
Spenser feels he's stepped into a Tennessee Williams play. People
drink a little bit too much, and their sexual histories are very
complex and intertangled. Spenser must procede warily over mined
ground; the stable's official security firm is not exactly happy to
find him on its turf.
</P>
<P>
   Another horse gets shot, and then a human does. Penny
regrettfully removes Spenser from the case. Spenser returns to
Boston, and tackles another situation, a 5-chapter inset short
story about a nanny and her boyfriend-stalker. The situation, when
Spenser gets to the bottom of it, goes to show that nothing is what
it seems to be at first _ a lesson that will prove useful when
another member of the Clive family appears to hire him to look once
more into the trouble down south.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Spenser sorts it all through, with a little help from
his friends, and some shrewd character analysis from Susan. He
punches out a couple of guys, does a little breaking and entering,
visits a gay bar, reads Jonathan Lear on Freud, and seems to enjoy
letting good people surprise him; the bad guys never get the
chance. Spenser's moral compass is unerring, and it has nothing to
do with political correctness. Some of the rich and snobbish turn
out to have generous hearts, but not all of them. A heartless
fast-track single-mother career woman gets what's coming to her,
and so does a flower power hippie named Sherry Lark. Sherry takes
her seat in a San Francisco restaurant and orders herbal tea, as an
Spenser notes, ``It was unfortunately apparent that she was
braless.'' Susan has her work cut out for her: Spenser is
incorrigible.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Parker's gay characters turn out to be sympathetic; in
this area, as in many others, Parker breaks the mold of popular
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   There's some amusing banter in ``Hugger Mugger,'' a bit of
baseball lore (Spenser ponders the relative merits of Johnny Bench
and Roy Campanella), and a little more suspense than usual. Parker
has worked on this one, and he makes very few wrong moves.
</P>
<P>
   Spenser does swagger because he's wearing his Clubman after
shave, but Susan puts him in his place. `` `Are you wearing Club
Man again, or have they just painted the radiators?' `You fear Club
Man, don't you,' I said. `Because you're afraid that after just a
single whiff, your libido will jump out of your psyche and begin to
break-dance right here on the rug.' `That's probably it,' she
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if they'd just both learn that Pinaud uses one word to
identify Clubman, that aphrodisiac aroma that barbershops smell
like. . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
