<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS EYES A FITTING CAP TO HIS CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ When the topic of his future Hall of Fame millinery was
broached earlier this spring, Roger Clemens told reporters he hoped
to go to Cooperstown wearing a Yankees cap.
</P>
<P>
   All those years in Boston, measured against one championship
season in New York, and the Rocket wants to be immortalized in
pinstripes? Perhaps, it was suggested, Clemens might take a cue
from Carlton Fisk, who also harbored some bitterness against the
Sox for years but eventually opted for a ``B'' on his bust, a year
after Sox general manager Dan Duquette hired him as a special
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe the Duke has a front office job waiting for
Clemens, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt that, I really doubt that,'' Clemens said Thursday
morning. ``The guy didn't want me as a player, I don't think he'll
want me as an assistant. When the guy running the show doesn't want
you around, you won't be around.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens didn't close the door on having a change of heart. There
are a few things he feels obliged to do in New York, he said, to
seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to accomplish some more things in this uniform,''
he said. ``Maybe winning another championship, maybe winning 20
games, winning my 300th game, the Cy Young (Award) again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talking to some people close to me. Reggie (Jackson)
has been hammering me about it. We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   He has won his World Series ring _ he'll get it sometime in the
next month _ and while he wants another, Clemens admits that
winning 300 has become important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to push the pedal, push the envelope, see if it can
happen,'' he said. ``I hear every day that myself, (Greg) Maddux
have a shot at it. I know it's going to be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   With 247 career victories, he's 53 wins away. How long will it
take him to hit 300? ``I hope I can do it in about (2002),'' he
said. ``I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet that timetable, Clemens would have to average 18 wins
for the next three seasons, by which time he'll be 40. A tall order
for a guy who went 14-10 last year, had the highest ERA (4.60) of
his career, and was bothered for a good chunk of the season by a
sore hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens, who Thursday downplayed his leg problems, doesn't
see the same signs of slippage others did last season. ``Nobody
said that here,'' he said. ``I'll be happy to go 14-10 again if
they give me the ball again in postseason. I've won 20 games many
times, ERA titles, individual awards, but nothing (compares) to
having a big, shiny ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have a single thing to prove. I've just got to
be ready. That's half the battle. I have to do my work and be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens seemed amused when told about this week's Sports
Illustrated cover predicting the Red Sox will win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good, that's great,'' he said. ``New century. I'll have
to call up a couple of my close friends (in Boston). They're the
ones who'll shoot it down. They won't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Clemens who was shot down on his last appearance in
Boston, when his much-hyped duel of the century against Pedro
Martinez turned to dust when he was driven from the mound after
just two-plus innings in the Sox' 13-1 win in Game 3 of the
American League Championship Series last October. After the game,
Clemens's wife, Debbie, ripped Sox fans for the way they taunted
the man who once owned their town.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said he thought Debbie was just exchanging pleasantries
with Globe columnist Dan Shaughnessy after the game. ``That's the
way I left it,'' he said. ``He said hello to my mother and was
talking to my wife. Then she came and told me she thought she said
some things that might be in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists he was unaffected by the hostile reception. ``I know
it didn't get to me,'' he said. ``She was sitting there and heard
it . . . I take offense at that only if it carries over to my
family, and to my boys.''
</P>
<P>
   He paid as much attention to the negative vibes, he said, as he
did to the numbers Martinez put up last season for the Red Sox,
which eclipsed Clemens's spectacular 1986 season, when he went 24-4
with a 2.48 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know my numbers,'' he said. ``Why would I look at his?
That's not that important right now. That's something you look at
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was asked if he ever thought about wearing a Sox uniform
again. He shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to finish right here,'' he said. ``That's the
reason why we came here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
