<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS TYLER'S TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Suddenly, it's different for Elton Tyler. No
more wondering what it's going to take for the 6-foot-9-inch junior
from the University of Miami to develop some consistency in his
game.
</P>
<P>
   The maddening part for Tyler, who arrived at Miami from via
Boston College (albeit briefly), is that when you see performances
like the one he turned in against Ohio State Sunday in the second
round of the NCAA tournament, you ask why he can't do it every
time.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, who will be part of the Hurricane contingent facing Tulsa
in the South Regional semifinal, has a simple explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to get confidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The effort against Ohio State, a 75-62 victory, should have
taken care of that.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty points, nine rebounds, and the ultimate compliment from
Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien, who recruited Tyler while at BC but
then ran into an admissions snafu that set off a chain of events
that resulted in Tyler being at Miami and O'Brien at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elton Tylers are the type of guy you could spend 100 years in
this business coaching,'' said O'Brien. ``Miami was very fortunate.
He's a wonderful guy and I'm happy it's gone good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's succinct comment after Tyler helped send the Buckeyes
on an early vacation: ``We had no answer for him.''
</P>
<P>
   No one really has in the last part of the Miami season, which
has lasted longer than most expected.
</P>
<P>
   After playing up and down most of his junior season, Tyler has
picked it up in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It began with Miami's final regular-season game, a home win over
St. John's that earned the Hurricanes a share (with Syracuse) of
the Big East regular-season championship.
</P>
<P>
   During the five-game stretch that includes the St. John's game,
two Big East tournament games, and two NCAA tournament games, Tyler
has averaged 15.6 points and eight rebounds. He scored 20 or more
points twice and was in double figures four times.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Leonard Hamilton, who also has become a hot
commodity (he's on the short list of candidates to replace Bobby
Cremins at Georgia Tech), says it's just a matter of maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not step up every night,'' said Hamilton. ``But he's
making a more concerted effort to come as close as he can each
night in reaching his potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Tyler showed only sporadic signs of stardom as he
moved in and out of Hamilton's lineup and doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   This season was more of the same, especially at the start. Tyler
scored in double figures in the Hurricanes' first four games, but
could only manage double figures in three of Miami's next 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler agrees it is a matter of finding a comfort zone. It took a
while for him to get past the disappointment of not going to BC, of
adjusting to new friends and establishing his own identity.
</P>
<P>
   This season also has had its low points. In a regular-season win
over Connecticut, Tyler was doing so little on the court, Hamilton
pulled him aside and chewed him out with a tough-love speech that
apparently worked. Tyler went on a scoring binge with 22 points and
was one of the key figures in a 63-57 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's regular season wound up being productive, with averages
of 10.4 points and 5.6 rebounds. The postseason has been even
better, with 14.5 points and 8.5 rebounds per game. He has started
all 33 of Miami's games and leads the team in field goal percentage
(.524) and blocks (34).
</P>
<P>
   It's a dramatic upturn from Tyler's first season, when he didn't
start a game, and from last season, when he started only three
times and averaged 11 minutes. He was a part-time player, still
striving for his potential.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tyler and Miami are two wins away from the Final Four and
the confidence is starting to flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a good chance,'' Tyler said Thursday of his
team's prospects this weekend. ``As long as we work hard and stay
focused, we have a real good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he has tried to keep his team focused on what has
worked so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried very much not to change our approach on what we've
been doing all year,'' said Hamilton. ``You know it's a
one-and-done deal, but we feel we've been successful because we
haven't allowed ourselves to get too far ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   For Miami to advance against a Tulsa team that is every bit as
tough defensively as the 'Canes, Tyler will have to continue to be
aggressive and assertive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elton is such an unselfish kid,' said Hamilton. ``He just
wants to win and he's not looking for statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler said Hamilton hasn't played up the game to his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically said that we have to execute on defense and we
have to get our mental focus right,'' Tyler said. ``We know what we
have to do so it shouldn't be that hard to focus on those things. I
think if you're ready to play, you're ready to play. As long as we
have this opportunity, we want to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler is ready to do that and says he is also past any remorse
about what might have been at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to play together,'' Tyler said of O'Brien's
recruiting class that also included Jonathan DePina (UMass), Mike
Bradley (Kentucky and Villanova), and Adam Allensbach (Clemson).
``We wanted to play for Coach O'Brien and we wanted to go in there
and help BC. Unfortunately it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen at BC, but at Miami Tyler is doing what he, and
O'Brien, thought he could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1557EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
