<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKC-WILDCATS-BOS &LR;      03-24 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-WILDCATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BURST OF ENERGY FOR THE WILDCATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Wildcats were in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The University of New Hampshire had knocked off Wisconsin the
night before in the NCAA East Regionals in Albany, and now it was
in against top-seeded Boston University, a team it was still trying
to figure out how to beat in the big games.
</P>
<P>
   This was huge. Lose, and the season was over. Win, and it was on
to the Frozen Four, the lofty place BU knew well and UNH had not
been in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   They went to overtime. Boston University went on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, oh.
</P>
<P>
   Enter forward Mike Souza of Wakefield, Mass., and the UNH
penalty killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck turned over and Dan Enders got it and passed it up
the boards,'' Souza said. ``We were on a two-on-one shorthanded and
Mark Mowers went to the net. He kind of got behind the defenseman
and I just saw his stick. I didn't see him, only the blade of the
stick and I passed it, and it deflected off the stick and in. It
was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all that, and maybe more, said UNH coach Dick Umile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great moment, a fabulous moment,'' Umile said. ``The
place goes crazy in Albany. We were struggling at the end of that
season and, bang, all of a sudden we beat Wisconsin the night
before and Mike was great in that game. And then we played BU and
beat them in overtime. Shorthanded. It can't get any better than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Souza _ as he has been the last four years _ was smack dab in
the middle of it. UNH went on to the NCAA semifinals at the
FleetCenter and a string of unprecedented success.
</P>
<P>
   UNH lost that semifinal game to Michigan, but then came back
last year and won its first outright Hockey East regular-season
title. For the first time, the Wildcats made consecutive trips to
the Frozen Four and then also made it to their first championship
game, where they lost to Maine in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Wildcats are in the NCAA tournament for the fourth
straight year. Their quest for a first national title begins in
Minneapolis against Niagara, a team the Wildcats have never faced.
UNH (23-8-6) is the No. 3 seed in the West Regionals and Niagara
(29-7-4) is No. 6. The winner plays No. 2 seed North Dakota
(28-8-5) Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Souza, along with fellow UNH captain Enders, leads the chase.
``He's playing great,'' said Umile. ``He competing hard and he's
playing his best hockey of the season as he did in the latter part
of last year. He's playing with a sense of urgency, like there's no
tomorrow. I like the way he's playing.''
</P>
<P>
   For good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Souza's blast beat Merrimack in overtime in the first round of
the Hockey East tournament and sent UNH on to the FleetCenter. He's
had six goals and six assists in the last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Sense of urgency? Well, yeah. This is it for the UNH seniors,
who have already gone where no other UNH seniors have gone. And
want to go one giant step farther.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, individually, it's been a bit of an up-and-down
year,'' Souza said. ``I may not have met the goals I set for
myself, but in looking back I like to think I've contributed in
other ways. I'm very happy with the year we've had as a team. And
we still have some unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   Souza, who had 23 goals and 42 assists in 41 games last year,
has 15 goals and 25 assists in 37 games and is tied for the team's
scoring lead with sophomore Darren Haydar.
</P>
<P>
   UNH numbers were down across the board this year. The Wildcats
lost Hobey Baker Award winner Jason Krog and maybe more important,
three of their top defenseman. They were not nearly as explosive as
a year ago. Still, the Wildcats have been close to the top of the
national rankings all year, are in the tournament, and will
surprise no one if they go deep into it.
</P>
<P>
   And if they do, Souza _ who at 6 feet 1 inches and 208 pounds
looks like and plays the part of a power forward _ will likely be a
big part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday at practice, in UNH's first look at Mariucci Arena,
Souza was on a line with fellow seniors John Sadowski and Jason
Shipulski. He basically had swapped spots with freshman Lanny Gare,
who was with Darren Haydar and Matt Swain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of late, he's taken his game to another level,'' said UNH
assistant coach Brian McCloskey. ``He's probably relaxed a little
bit. There was a lot of pressure on this team to try and fill the
shoes of the departing seniors and live up to the expectations of
the fans. He's a goal scorer, he's a pretty good playmaker for his
size, and he's also a physical player. He does all three things
pretty well, which makes him a difficult player to play against.''
</P>
<P>
   BU coach Jack Parker _ who has known and liked Souza for years _
has noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a great kid,'' Parker said. ``He's the kind of kid
you're happy to have representing you in the uniform wherever he
goes. Add to that he can score goals, he can bang people, he
competes as hard as he competes. It's a pretty nice package.''
</P>
<P>
   A package Parker figures will transfer well to professional
hockey. Souza was a 1997 third-round pick of the Chicago
Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question he'll be able to play that
game as well as he plays our game,'' Parker said. ``He's got that
pro look, the stride. He just looks like a big, blocky, left wing
who will be in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Souza is keeping those thoughts in check _ hopefully for a few
more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few weeks that's been brought up all the time,'' he
said. ``I try to block it out for the most part. I'm real
determined to stay focused. That probably sounds like I'm blowing
smoke, but I'm being honest. How well you play in playoff
situations probably makes a difference in what people think of you.
But I'm not too concerned with that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He and the Wildcats are concerned with Niagara. If they get by
the Purple Eagles, they will worry about North Dakota for a third
straight trip to the Frozen Four.
</P>
<P>
   And try to match the feeling they had two years ago when Souza
passed across to Mowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the great moments in UNH hockey history,'' Umile
said. ``It's got to be one of the top three.''
</P>
<P>
   With a little room still left at the top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1558EST &QL; 
