<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (Bombay, India) _ President Clinton, completing
the Indian leg of his South Asian journey, moves on to Pakistan to
press its military ruler for a timetable for national elections and
a return to democratic government. ``We are worried about the
future of Pakistan,'' says Clinton's national security adviser,
Samuel R. Berger. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Saying incidents of gay harassment
are ``more widespread than I anticipated,'' Defense Secretary
William Cohen announces he will appoint a special
gays-in-the-military oversight council to combat the problem. The
Pentagon releases its inspector general's report detailing a
significant amount of verbal abuse of homosexual troops in the
ranks. By ERIC ROSENBERG and STEWART M. POWELL. (Will updated.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-BREAK (South Padre Island, Texas) _ Residents fed up the
traffic, trash and truculence of college-age merrymakers are urging
city officials to put the brakes on spring break in this Gulf of
Mexico getaway. By ALISON GREGOR.
</P>
<P>
   GENOCIDE-MINISTER (Laredo, Texas) _ Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a
retired Seventh-day Adventist minister who is accused of war crimes
in Rwanda, is deported to stand trial before a United Nations war
tribunal. The man, who had been living with a son in Texas, is
accused of leading attackers armed with machetes, grenades and guns
in a murderous April 1994 rampage that killed dozens of people who
were hiding in his church. By BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSH-EDUCATION (Washington) _ They're poles apart on most
education issues, but Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush do agree on one thing: having rigorous standardized tests
at key grade levels coupled with sanctions, including loss of
federal funds, for low-scoring schools that failed to show
improvement. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Directors Guild of America
made a terrible mistake when it removed the name of D.W. Griffith
from an award it gave filmmaker Steven Spielberg. Griffith was a
racist but he was one of the greatest pioneers in motion pictures,
and the removal of his name was an extreme example of political
correctness. The directors' action would be like judging the
presidencies of Lyndon Johnson, Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton only
by their mistakes. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
