<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-TB-500(TRIMS)-N     03-24 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-TB-500(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREATMENT HELPS INDIA BATTLE TB 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-INDIA, CLINTON-PAKISTAN) 
(HLW) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDERABAD, India _ For a year, 10-year-old Chaitanya Pusa
suffered from recurring fevers, a hacking cough and debilitating
weakness. She saw healers who chanted mantras over her and private
doctors who missed her real illness.
</P>
<P>
   Her family, which survives on a meager income from three milking
cows, sunk deeper and deeper in debt to pay the bills. The girl lay
bedridden. ``When she developed pain in her chest, we panicked and
took her to the hospital,'' said her grandmother, Sandamma Pusa.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors there promptly diagnosed Chaitanya as one of the 2
million people who develop tuberculosis each year in India, more
than in any other country.
</P>
<P>
   About 450,000 die from it _ more than from AIDS, malaria and
tropical diseases combined _ but Chaitanya, now 12, will not be one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, on World Tuberculosis Day, President Bill Clinton
gave this little girl with dark brown eyes and two long braids her
final dose of the medicines that will cure her, and he signed the
register that has documented each stage of her six-month long
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``TB kills more people around the world than ever before,
including one almost every minute here in India,'' Clinton said,
calling for intensified efforts to control the epidemic and to find
a vaccine that will prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   Chaitanya's is one of 40,000 lives that experts say have been
saved by the use of a popular treatment that is popular here. It
begins with an accurate diagnosis, then ensures that patients
complete a 6- to 8-month long regimen of drug taking by having an
observer literally watch them take their medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Trained paramedics monitor the patients' records to double check
that the treatment is proceeding properly.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a team of experts from the World Health
Organization, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and
the World Bank, working with India's leading tuberculosis
specialists, interviewed 1,000 patients and reviewed the records of
more than 10,000 patients to evaluate the strategy which has been
used in India since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   They discovered that this method, known as directly observed
treatment, short course, or DOTS, has doubled cure rates to 84
percent and cut death rates to 4 percent from 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a quarter of a million people with tuberculosis, which is
caused by a bacteria and spreads through the air when an untreated
patient coughs or talks, have been given the DOTS treatment in
India.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is available to only about 15 percent of India's
population of 1 billion _ and the challenge in this vast,
impoverished nation with its shaky public health system is to
expand the program, and fast.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say the strategy is too cumbersome, and the public
health systems in developing countries like India, too weak to make
the program work on a much larger scale.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents say that more than 5 million patients have
already been treated using DOTS _ and it's worked even in poor
countries like Tanzania, Vietnam and Peru.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We have a cure for TB,'' said Tom Frieden, a doctor who ran
New York City's tuberculosis program and now advises the Indian
government about TB on behalf of the World Health Organization.
``And it's cheap and cost effective. It's just not being applied as
widely as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   There are now more resources coming in to spread the treatment
to new parts of India. The World Bank, the largest contributor, has
given India a $142-million low-interest loan over five years. The
British government recently pledged $25 million over 5 years to
combat TB in this southern state of Andhra Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
   The United States contributes a relatively small amount _ $1
million for an applied research project in Tamil Nadu.
</P>
<P>
   India has a budget of $28 million to combat the disease, while
the United States, which had 17,528 new cases of TB last year,
spends more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The shoe-box sized box of drugs required to treat a patient in
India costs $10 to $15 _ and by saving the lives of young men and
women, who are not only the most likely victims, but their
families' breadwinners, TB treatment is also important to
preventing poverty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   First thing on Friday morning, here in Hyderabad, Mohammad
Jaffar, a social worker and father of six children 9 and younger,
and Mohammad Fakaruddin, a leather worker with a 3-year-old son and
a 4-year-old daughter, came into the Nampally treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   Both are in the early, intense phase of treatment. Jerripotula
Urmila, a pharmacist, gave them their foil packets of pills and
watched to be sure that they took them.
</P>
<P>
   People with the disease here in Hyderabad, where treatment is
available, seem confident that they will be cured. For them, the
stigma of the disease has lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Mahaboob, a 35-year-old auto rickshaw driver, got his
final treatment on Friday morning from the chief minister of Andhra
Pradesh, N. Chandrababu Naidu. ``I read in the newspaper that it is
very much curable, so I wasn't too worried,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Chaitanya, dressed in her favorite full-length, festival
dress made of a shimmery golden fabric, walked confidently up to
the president of the United States on Friday morning for the last
dose of medicine she would need to banish the disease.
</P>
<P>
   She stuck the pills on the back of her tongue, tilted her head
back and poured the water into her mouth, in the Indian way,
without touching her lips. She was done with TB. Her ordeal was
officially over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
