<HEADER>
A6983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0325-COX     03-24 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF JESUS: 'CHOOSE LIFE'
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORAZIM, Israel _ When the locals of this lakeside village
refused to believe in him, Jesus of Nazareth responded, ``Woe unto
thee.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2,000 years later, Pope John Paul II on Friday took the
message of Christ back to these hills overlooking the Sea of
Galilee, and this time was greeted enthusiastically by a crowd from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   More than 75,000 worshippers arrived by sunrise to wait for the
11 a.m. mass on the Mount of the Beatitudes _ the same mountain
where Christ is believed to have spoken the Sermon on the Mount.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mass aimed at young people but attended by people of
all ages. There were those who called John Paul(cq, second
reference without II) ``Papiez'' in their native Polish, ``El
Papa'' in Spanish, ``I-Baba'' in Arabic and ``Paus'' in the Bahasa
language of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried through the whole thing,'' Gregg Purcell, a
29-year-old seminary student from Denver, Colo., said.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the 2000-year-old image of Jesus as a lonely prophet,
the mass produced the most celebratory event so far in the pope's
six-day pilgrimage to Israel and the West Bank areas controlled by
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The pope had urged others to join him on the pilgrimage, and
they did. Thousands of local Arab Christians, a beleaguered Holy
Land minority, also came.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's trip is the highlight of his millennium effort to
foster better relations between faiths. It is only the second trip
here by a Roman Catholic pope and the first time a pope has
officially recognized the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   After the mass Thursday, the pope prayed quietly at lakeside
churches where tradition holds that Christ performed many of his
miracles. They included The Church of the Loaves and Fishes, where
he is said to have served 5,000 people with a couple loaves of
bread.
</P>
<P>
   He also met with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. Barak joked
that he was nervous that the meeting would run past sundown and
catch him working past the start of the Jewish Sabbath. Religious
government leaders have said they would find that offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's mass in a heavily-secured, wide, shelf on the Mount
of the Beatitudes was untarnished by the type of political
squabbling that has confronted much of the pope's visit.
Palestinians and Israelis have repeatedly sought to use episodes in
the pope's trip for vindication of their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was a day more of scenery than polemics.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening clouds held off their rain until after the mass was
well over. The overcast skies created a soft mist over the Sea of
Galilee and the coastal city of Tiberias. Occasionally, the sun
would crack through the clouds enough to shed light on the high
plain, still leaving the lowlands around it in shadow.
</P>
<P>
   On a large red and green stage with a black tarp covering it,
the pope sounded stronger than usual. After moving through the
crowd in his popemobile, John Paul II took his place in a simple
gray throne. He exhorted the crowd to avoid the temptations of
evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit on this hill like the first of the disciples, and we
listen to Jesus. In the stillness we hear his gentle and urgent
voice, as gentle as this land itself and as urgent as a call to
choose between life and death,'' the pope said.
</P>
<P>
   He reviewed the Sermon on the Mount, where Jesus urged love for
your neighbor and highlighted the righteousness of the poor. He
compared that guidance to the older Ten Commandments. He said the
Sermon fulfilled, rather than replaced, the commandments, leaving
listeners to understand a common ground between Christianity and
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   About half the crowd were from a 36-year-old Catholic
Neocatechumenal movement, which was started in the slums of Spain
by an artist and musician. The movement appeals to those who have
lost their faith and seeks to bring them into the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pilgrims with the pope,'' said Wojciech Dubinski, a
20-year-old computer technician who joined the movement from
Warsaw, Poland, which is the pope's home country.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign flags that the group waved relieved a sense of
isolation felt by thousands of local Christians in the crowd. Arab
Christians from Israel and the Palestinian areas make up just two
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wonderful. We have been waiting our whole lives to see
him in Palestine,'' said Palestinian Sylvia Kassiss, a 40-year-old
Catholic teacher from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
