<P>
   &UR; INDIA ISN'T PAKISTAN'S SIAMESE TWIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESPECT-INDIA-OPED-IHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ India resents being treated by U.S. policy as a
Siamese twin of Pakistan. It also frets at the respect accorded to
China, to the extent that Washington has let Beijing off the hook
on its nuclear and missile transfers to Pakistan. India would like
Washington to be on the side of the world's largest democracy, not
on the side of the world's largest autocracy....By Brahma Chellaney
for the International Herald Tribune &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., March 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON STEPS INTO THE KASHMIR QUAGMIRE HE HELPED CREATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; US-TREASON-KASHMIR-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DELHI _ Forty Sikh villagers have died to burn the message home
to visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton that the Kashmir problem
won't go away. Meanwhile, Pakistan's former leader, Nawaz Sharif,
sits in a Karachi jail string into the hangman's noose as a result
of repeatedly doing what America told him to do. And this week his
friend Bill Clinton arrives to bestow his blessing (that is how it
will play in Pakistan) on the man responsible....By Peter Popham,
The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 925 words; 1,275 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEN-ARMED CLINTON MAKES UP FOR 20 YEARS OF NEGLECT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MR.FIXIT-CLINTON-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Bill Clinton arrived in New Delhi Monday
to start a tour of the Indian subcontinent, presented in Washington
as the opening of a new chapter of diplomacy and trade. Seen in the
context of Washington's overture to Iran at the end of last week,
the president's week-long trip appears not just as an attempt to
address years of neglect, but as part of a much wider shift in U.S.
policy for the whole region _ from the bipolar to the multipolar
post-Cold War world....By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Monday, March 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
