<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-INDIA-CLINTON-0325-CO     03-24 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CLINTON-0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO URGE PAKISTAN, SYRIA BACK ON RESPECTIVE PEACE TRACKS
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With INDIA-COLOR-0325.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ President Clinton was hurtling toward a weekend
of whirlwind diplomacy Saturday, hoping for measured steps toward
peace on two fronts _ the Himalayan territory of Kashmir and the
fractious Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Journeying first to the Pakistani capital of Islamabad, Clinton
meets with Chief Army Gen. Pervez Musharraf. He seized power in a
coup last October, overthrowing the elected government of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants Musharraf to develop a blueprint for returning the
country to civilian rule, end Pakistani support for seccessionist
rebels in Kashmir, and move toward peace talks with India over the
disputed Himalayan territory.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday Clinton travels to Geneva, where he is scheduled
to meet Sunday with Syria's president, Hafez al-Assad. Clinton
hopes that meeting will lead to a near-term resumption of
Syrian-Israeli peace talks that broke off after a week of
negotiations in Shepherdstown, West Va., in January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tacked the Geneva summit onto the tail end of a
week-long swing through the Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   He wrapped up his tour of India Friday with visits to Hyderabad,
where he spotlighted India's burgeoning computer technology sector
and efforts to tame widespread tuberculosis. In Bombay, he touched
base with a new generation of up-and-coming Indian artists, doctors
and executives.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to several hundred executives at the Bombay Stock
Exchange Friday night, Clinton said American companies had signed
contracts during his visit this week that would ultimately be worth
$4 billion. He also announced about $1 billion in new financing for
small- and medium-sized businesses in India to export to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Hyderabad, Clinton visited Mahavir Hospital, which
runs one of 400 clinics around the country that provide medication
to cure tuberculosis. A staggering 20 million Indians suffer from
TB _ a disease for which inoculations were developed 118 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At a Hyderabad commercial center called HI-TEC City, Clinton
pledged $5 million in U.S. assistance to help wire impoverished
Indian villages to the Internet, bringing on-line health and
education opportunities to the doorsteps of some of the poorest
people in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could do that for every village in South Asia, in
Africa, in Latin America, in the Middle East, then, overnight, the
poorest place in the world could have access to the same learning
materials that only the richest schools offer their students
today,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean, among other things, that the world's most
populous nation would have the world's largest number of educated
people,'' he said, ``and, therefore, in no time, would have the
world's largest economy.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   India has become one of the world's leading centers of computer
and software technology. American companies have become
increasingly drawn to this country's rich talent pool, at wages a
fraction of those paid in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On-line technology is transforming such relationships, enabling
U.S. companies to employ Indians who work to develop software or
handle technical problems directly from India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, many of our leading companies _ from Apple to Texas
Instruments to Oracle _ are coming in waves to your shores,''
Clinton said in a speech to more than 1,000 technology executives
assembled at HI-TEC City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told that if a person calls Microsoft for help with
software, there's a pretty good chance they'll find themselves
talking to an expert in India, rather than Seattle,'' Clinton said.
``India is fast becoming one of the world's software superpowers,
proving that, in a globalized world, developing nations not only
can succeed, developing nations can lead.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton shifts Saturday from cyberspace to statecraft, aides
stressed that his missions to Islamabad and Geneva were both aimed
at sowing the seeds of future progress. Immediate breakthroughs
weren't expected on either front.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan is something of a wild card. U.S. influence there is
limited. Musharraf is contending with a strong element of radical
Muslims, whose political clout appears to be growing. And rhetoric
coming from Islamabad in recent days suggests that it could be
months before Musharraf moves to limit violence in Kashmir or sets
out a road map back to democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, moreover, has no plans to try to mediate the Kashmir
crisis, unless he's specifically sought by both parties to the
dispute. So far, India has rejected the idea of a formal U.S. role.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, little immediate action is expected from Clinton's
meeting Sunday with Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, this is a meeting to talk about the circumstances
required to reinvigorate Israeli-Syrian negotiations that
deadlocked two months ago over how to structure a mutually
acceptable formula for exchanging land for peace.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the most likely outcome of Sunday's
meeting would be that Assad would go home to Damascus to consider
the path ahead, as Clinton communicates with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, in the hope that both men would see it in their
interest to resume peace talks at some point in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best case result, I would say, is that we have a sense
after the meeting that there's enough common ground, they're close
enough, that if we actually resume negotiations that you could
envision them ending in success,'' White House National Security
Advisor Samuel Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's meeting would be the fourth between Clinton and Assad,
but the first since the American leader brought Syrian and Israeli
negotiators together at the White House last December.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting led to a week of negotiations in Shepherdstown,
W.Va., between Israel's Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the terms under which Israel would return to Syria
the strategic Golan Heights in exchange for security guarantees
from Syria. Israeli troops seized the Heights during the 1967
Israeli-Arab war.
</P>
<P>
   While the broad parameters of an Israeli-Syrian peace accord
have been known for years, a serious dispute persists over
precisely how to draw the new border between Israel and Syria.
Assad's position has been that talks can't go forward on myriad
substantive issues _ ranging from water rights to trade terms _
unless and until Israel agrees to return all of the Golan lands to
Syrian control.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has balked, instead offering to return most, but not all
of the Golan, which have become an important intelligence gathering
and monitoring platform for Israeli defense forces.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
