<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, March 26, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NUN-SISTER-KAROL (New York) _ If the nuns in ``The Sound of
Music'' couldn't figure out how to solve a problem like Maria, they
would be completely baffled by Sister Karol Jackowski, 53, who
lives in the East Village, has Margaritaville (cocktails, chips and
pizza) each week with her friends and calls chopped liver ``a major
food group for me.'' Karol has also written a book with the
improbable title, ``Ten Fun Things to Do Before You Die''
(Hyperion, $9.95). All things considered, she sounded like my kind
of sister. By Alex Witchel. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GREAT-DAMES (New York) _ Great dames _ flamboyant diva-women,
who came of age before 1960s feminism _ are never defeated by their
circumstances. Tenacity, flair and fun are the traits that define
them. They were reared in an era of limited expectations, when
graduate schools and careers were closed to them. Good manners,
manicures, pearls and high heels were the disguises they wore to
hide their mettle. Auntie Mame is the prototype, with her arch
double entendres and live-live-live philosophy. They were actressy,
and brimmed with theatrical enthusiasms. By Marie Brenner. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TROPHY-SHOPPING (New York) _ Jane Schub, a partner in Jules &AMP;
Jane, a small cosmetics company, drops in on Sam's Club, part of
the Wal-Mart-owned national chain, routinely, her eye always peeled
for a fashion bargain. On a recent Friday, she was as cunning as a
bobcat, prowling the aisles and pouncing on twin sets and
raincoats, sandals and mules _ anything at all that caught her eye.
Typical of a new breed of affluent fashion maven, she is as likely
to shop at off-price outlets like T.J. Maxx, which sell designer
labels, and at discounters like Target, which produce their own
wares, as she is to cruise Jeffrey or Kirna Zabete, those outposts
of downtown chic. Increasingly shrewd, such women are driven by
value, naturally _ but perhaps even more by the thrill of the
chase. By Ruth La Ferla. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-CHRISTENSEN-MODEL (New York) _ No one ever said that
life after modeling is easy. Besides the pain of makeup withdrawal
and the pangs of catwalk envy, there is also the issue of how to
make a living without simply being fabulous. Not so for the Danish
supermodel _ and runway retiree _ Helena Christensen, who since
last spring has held the impressive-sounding title of creative
director for Nylon magazine, a fashion-oriented glossy that marked
its first anniversary on Wednesday night with a party at Skirt, a
boutique in Manhattan. By Jesse Mckinley. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-PLACEMENT (Undated) _ Many envelopes will be ripped open
Sunday night at the 72nd annual Academy Awards. But not one will
contain instructions on how to display a much-hoped-for,
much-obsessed-over Oscar at home so it won't look preposterous.
Yes, this is a little-explored downside to walking away with one of
the 13-inch-high gold statuettes. An Oscar may look great on the
red carpet or on a table at Morton's during the Vanity Fair
after-party. But where can one keep it at home so it doesn't suck
all the air out of the room? By Marcia Biederman. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ I'm sorry to see the honeybees
colonies that used to populate by woods decline from parasitic
mites, not just because they have been as much a symbol of spring
for me as a daffodil or a fat robin. The bees were doing valuable
work in the orchard and in my fields and gardens, pollinating
blossoms. By Cass Peterson. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
