A6994 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CHURCH-APOLOGY-HNS &LR;      03-24 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-APOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DIOCESE PLANS ATONEMENT FOR SEXUAL ABUSE CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The sexual abuse began when Lorraine Bruz was
16, when a priest in Santa Rosa convinced her she had poor
self-esteem. It continued for about three years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bruz, now 40 and living in Sonoma County,
was among four plaintiffs who won a $1.6 million settlement from
the Santa Rosa Catholic Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Bruz will receive something more spiritually
symbolic: a formal apology from the church.
</P>
<P>
   In what is believed to be an unprecedented act of public
contrition in the Roman Catholic Church in the United States, the
Oakland Diocese will ask forgiveness of those who have suffered
sexual misconduct by clergy or other church employees.
</P>
<P>
   This cleansing of conscience, planned for about a year, is
intended as a critical first step toward healing the breach between
the church and survivors of priestly misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who've been ignored,'' said Sister Barbara
Flannery, the diocesan chancellor and a prime organizer behind the
mea culpa. ``They've been abused not once, but twice. We are
sincerely sorry for what has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Discounted and disbelieved by church officials when they lodged
complaints, many survivors watched their abusers go unpunished or
shuttled quietly from one parish to another. Stripped of their
innocence and ability to trust, survivors say they were victimized
anew by church officials who refused to acknowledge the
transgressions of sexual predators in clerical collars.
</P>
<P>
   From Los Angeles, San Diego, Fresno, they are expected to attend
the reconciliation service simply to hear church leaders utter
words never before articulated in a public arena to abuse victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, it happened years ago, but they feel rage and anger
and haven't been able to deal with it because they've been
stonewalled,'' Flannery said. ``No one has ever said they are sorry
to them, which is a sad commentary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Diocese, which encompasses 500,000 Catholics in
Alameda and Contra Costa counties, has handled a dozen cases of
clergy misconduct over the last decade, though some of the abuse
actually occurred in other dioceses, Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   While Oakland is shouldering the weight of apology, other
dioceses are being bitterly criticized for failing to extend such
an olive branch. Chief among them is the San Francisco Archdiocese,
which has weathered numerous cases of pedophilia and clergy
misconduct, paying at least $6 million in counseling costs and
legal claims.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the Catholic Church is estimated to have spent $1
billion in clergy misconduct cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of church is this? Such hypocrisy,'' said Sonia
Rubino, who was molested by a priest for eight years, starting when
she was an 8-year-old girl living in her native El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Rubino, a sales clerk who lives in San Francisco, said she
sought solace from the archdiocese but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the universal Catholic Church, they should make
amends,'' she said. ``It is a great thing that the Oakland Diocese
is doing this. It takes a lot of courage. At least in one small
place of the world they are willing to stand up for survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying clergy abuse victims as far away as Australia, Terrie
Light, regional leader of the Survivors Network of those Abused by
Priests, said of the Oakland apology: ``No one has ever heard of
anything like this. They wish it was happening where they lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Light, who said she was sexually abused when she was 7 by a San
Francisco priest, now works as a marriage family therapist in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hard time sitting in a church,'' said Light, who was
a catalyst for the Saturday service. ``The crucifix and the organ
music and all that is so psychologically painful ... (but) some
survivors say they want to attend, not because it's their bishop
speaking but at least it's a bishop. That is heartbreaking. The
church will only understand when they all meet with real victims,
when they hear of their pain and suffering and isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   During the service, Oakland Bishop John Cummins plans to
acknowledge failings to confront the ``grave evil'' inflicted on
members of the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as a church, were often negligent,'' he said. ``We do not
know of any other Catholic diocese in the country currently taking
this initiative. Yet we feel it is an important step toward healing
and reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   March has been a month of historic repentance within the Roman
Catholic Church. Two weeks ago, Pope John Paul II offered a
sweeping apology for the sins of the church throughout its history.
In what was termed a ``purification of memory'' to mark Jubilee
Year 2000, the pope asked for forgiveness for lapses and injustices
done in the name of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, various bishops and cardinals in the United States
have offered general apologies, with some specifying clergy abuse
among the transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is not accustomed to apologizing,'' said the Rev.
Daniel Danielson, pastor of the Catholic Community of Pleasanton
who helped organize Oakland's day of atonement. ``It is high time
we did it. ... At times, survivors were treated like lepers. They
were told to be quiet _ the church acted out of fear of lawsuits.
It is a scandal to the people abused and to the rest of the
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in forgiveness but it comes after the confession of
sin. We hope this is the beginning of a public change of
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a lawsuit, but the Santa Rosa Diocese, under a tentative
settlement, will be issuing a written apology to four former
parishioners as well as establishing a $500,000 therapy program for
victims of clergy misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to know how important an apology is,'' said Bruz,
one of the Santa Rosa plaintiffs. ``In some ways it feels like too
little too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
