<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NUN-SISTER-KAROL-ART-     03-24 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUN-SISTER-KAROL-ART-$ADV26-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYS TO HAVE FUN: A NUN'S TALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sun., March 26)  
(jt) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the nuns in ``The Sound of Music'' couldn't figure
out how to solve a problem like Maria, they would be completely
baffled by Karol Jackowski, who lives in the East Village, has
Margaritaville (cocktails, chips and pizza) each week with her
friends and calls chopped liver ``a major food group for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Karol, 53, has also written a book with the improbable
title, ``Ten Fun Things to Do Before You Die'' (Hyperion, $9.95).
All things considered, she sounded like my kind of sister. So I
went to her apartment, figuring we could run through the list and
she could enlighten me. But I was so enchanted by the excellent
chopped liver that I forgot to ask about fun as Sister Karol
explained it all for me _ how she started in East Chicago, Ind.,
and ended up here, wearing jeans and cooking in Calphalon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1970, there was a mass exodus from the convent,'' she said.
``We lost 500,000 in a period of six years. But I didn't want to
leave religious life _ I wanted to live it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a member of the Sisters for a Christian Community, a
Roman Catholic order of about 700 based in New Jersey that has no
convent. ``If you're self-supporting, taxpaying and taking care of
each other, you don't need that central location,'' she said.
``We're adult women. We don't need someone to approve of what we
do. It's a nontraditional lifestyle, but we still take the vows of
celibacy, poverty and obedience.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Karol works as the chief operating officer of the four
Alphabets gift stores in the city; other sisters have jobs as
varied as restaurant owner and manager of a 7-Eleven. One retired
as a vice president for marketing at Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   That's impressive, I thought. I started to ask the fun questions
but became distracted by the tour of her apartment, which includes
a lamp that says ``Ask for Imported Blue Nun by the Glass'' and a
votive stand, where she invites visitors to light a candle and make
a wish before they leave. There's also her collection of ceramic
nuns. ``They were really big in the '50s,'' Sister Karol said. ``If
you didn't have a nun for a daughter, a nun tchotchke was the next
best thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents owned a bakery in East Chicago that catered to the
local steel mills, and she had two brothers and two sisters, all of
whom ``went forth and multiplied,'' she said, giving her nine
nieces and nephews. She learned about fun from a funny grandmother
and from her own mother, who lies on the couch reading romance
novels when she visits, getting up in time to go out for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Karol is a character in her own right, not to mention a
smart one. She graduated from St. Mary's College in South Bend,
Ind., and received her M.A. in theology from Notre Dame, eventually
becoming dean of students at St. Mary's and publishing three books
with Ave Maria Press. ``Ten Fun Things to Do Before You Die'' came
from a speech she gave at the college, during which she interrupted
herself briefly to leave the podium and reappear in a gorilla suit.
In 1990 she moved to New York to earn a Ph.D. in higher education
administration at New York University, deciding when she finished
not to return to academia. ``After 20 years, I thought, `Maybe I'm
done with college,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Linda Heidinger, a former nun, is the owner of
Alphabets, and she gave Sister Karol the chance to work there
rather than return to her original order, the traditional Sisters
of the Holy Cross, in South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me to go back to more religious work,'' she said.
``But I had a richer religious life here than I had had there in 30
years. Life is more intense in New York City. The diversity here
makes for such a liberating environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I got involved with the kids who worked in the store,
most of whom were interested in a spiritual life, not a religious
life. I found that really refreshing, that they were trying to be
better persons and not knowing how to do that. With the church, on
issues like abortion and birth control, you end up fighting battles
where you're wasting your time. Here I was free of that. It was
soul to soul and what makes the most sense, not just what was good
Catholic advice.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when she switched orders and started reworking her Ten
Fun Things speech into a less Catholic, more generalized guide to
leading a fuller life. Through Heidinger, she found an agent who
sold the book for a $60,000 advance. So much for poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to support ourselves,'' Sister Karol said firmly. ``We
all know each other's financial status. The regular salaries
support the ones in the inner city who aren't being paid
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. Poverty and obedience, I understand. But how do you write a
book about fun when you're celibate?
</P>
<P>
   ``That vow is what distinguishes me from anyone who lives like
this,'' she said, waving a hand around her apartment. ``When I've
gotten close to being in relationships, I knew it was too limiting
to me. That exclusivity goes against how available I am emotionally
to people as a sister, which is the relationship I find most
divine. I'm not comfortable with having a lover or being a lover.''
She shrugged. ``Maybe I've not run into the right person.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside to celibacy is the amount of time it frees up for
writing. ``Living in the convent often meant living in silence,''
she said. ``You were thrown back on your own resources to be
entertaining. I used my free time for the imagination.'' She also
read a lot, becoming enchanted with Jungian archetypes, especially
the mermaid. Her bathroom is filled with mermaid statues and
drawings. ``It's sort of like living in both worlds, the inner and
outer, being half and half,'' she said. ``That part is like the
nun's life. I work in retail, but my life is really solitary.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
