<HEADER>
A7001 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NUN-SISTER-KAROL-ART-     03-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUN-SISTER-KAROL-ART-$ADV26-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: really solitary.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not lonely, though. We set out for the Gracie Mansion Gallery on
St. Marks Place to see an installation she was curious about (she
is a devoted art lover), and while I thought of asking the
questions about fun en route, I couldn't, since people on the
street recognized her and said hi. She visited a while with
Mansion, who also shows the artist Sally Davies, one of Sister
Karol's Margaritaville buddies. ``We're all trying to follow
Karol's advice and have fun,'' Mansion trilled as we left. And that
would be? She closed the door.
</P>
<P>
   We went on to Alphabets, where Sister Karol pointed out one of
her favorite gifts, the Wash Away Your Sins soap set with
washcloth. Then she bought some greeting cards, paying for them
with a platinum American Express card. That must be fun, though I
wouldn't know. Mine is only green.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks south we climbed the stairs to Davies' apartment,
where Ben Schneider, a manager at Alphabets, was also waiting. The
coffee table was laid out with potato chips and onion dip,
Chee-tos, Gummi Bears and M&AMP;M's. Davies presented Sister Karol with
a margarita straight from the freezer, and she sighed with
pleasure. ``This is what I have to look forward to every Friday,''
she said, sipping.
</P>
<P>
   Davies played a videotape of Sister Karol's recent interview
with Bryant Gumbel. ``Before it started, he said to me, `Sister,
what are you giving up for Lent?''' she recalled. ``And I said,
`Sex.' He almost fell over.''
</P>
<P>
   As we watched the tape, I realized that with all the talking and
eating and drinking and shopping, we had never gotten around to
discussing 10 fun things to do before we die.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel did, though, listing them at breakneck speed: ``Have More
Fun Than Anyone Else, Get Some Insight, Get Some Depth, Find a
Place to Escape Reality, Write Something at the End of Every Day,
Think About Nuns, Make Yourself Interesting, Live Alone for a
While, Treat Yourself, Live Like You Have Nothing to Lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Television being what it is, Sister Karol barely had time to
explain them, but I remembered the traits she wrote about to watch
for in fun people: ``A good appetite, interesting work, good
storytelling, slightly twisted sense of humor, fresh insight, brave
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Sister Karol qualifies as a majorly fun person.
Not only that, I finally saw that she had managed, during the
course of the day, to do what every good writer strives for: she
had showed me how to have fun, instead of telling me.
</P>
<P>
   While Davies called for the pizza, Sister Karol walked me
downstairs to get a cab. ``Goodbye, sister,'' she said warmly,
hugging me. I was touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye,'' I answered, hugging her back. As the cab took off I
thought about what it might be like. Pizza. Chopped Liver.
Chee-tos. Not so bad. All I'd need to do was convince my husband.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
