<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV26-     03-24 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A DUEL OF TROWELS, THE EARLY BIRD CROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, March 26) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE RAVER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I plan to have a huge kitchen garden this year, with trellises
for beans, peas, gourds, sweet peas and purple hyacinth beans.
</P>
<P>
   And I may plant the big stuff in long farmer rows, about 60 feet
long and 3 feet apart, because I'm tired of Cousin Janice making
fun of my six tomato plants and my little patch of Yukon Gold
potatoes. ``They're too close!'' she says every summer as I put too
many plants or seed potatoes in too small a bed.
</P>
<P>
   So this year, I'm trying her way. Tomato plants five feet apart,
in rows. She doesn't even stake them. Just lets them sprawl on
thick beds of straw. Potato plants two feet apart, heavily mulched.
Doesn't let a single sun ray hit those taters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have planted my peas and potatoes already, but I
didn't get the ground worked up last fall,'' Janice said last
Sunday. It was a rare admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yup,'' I said, thinking I could get the jump on her if I
planted my peas in compost on top of the wet ground. Or in pots, to
transplant as soon as our Maryland clay, leaden from recent rains,
lightened up a bit. Maybe both. Janice loves a hot competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greens are up, though,'' she said. Every spring, she plants
lettuce and spinach seeds in a shallow trench in some protected
place _ next to a wall with a southern exposure, say _ and puts a
board over them while they germinate. She raises the board on warm
days, lowers it on chilly ones.
</P>
<P>
   I told her we'd been eating arugula from the cold frame for
weeks, a whiff of summer in February. The trick is picking the
leaves at midday, when energy is pumping through them. And don't
wash them. Just stick them in a little plastic bag and throw them
in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to Janice got my blood running. I planted some old seeds
of Oakleaf, Black Seeded Simpson and Melody spinach in a whiskey
barrel south of the house. While the ground is warming, they'll
germinate and make their first true leaves.
</P>
<P>
   I always plant a lot of mesclun, for cut-and-come-again salads,
planting new seeds every few weeks. As the weather heats up, I
plant them in partial shade, under eggplants or broccoli or
something leafy. This year, I ordered a couple of mesclun mixes
from Renee Shepherd of Renee's Garden (831-335-7228), including her
Heirloom Cutting Mix, which features Speckled Troutback, Blush
Butter Cos, Red Ruffled Oak, Green Devil's Tongue and Sucrine. The
Cook's Garden (800-457-9703) also has some nice ones, like Nicoise,
which includes chicory, endive, dandelion, cress and arugula.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Exposure Seed Exchange (540-894-9480) has some great
lettuces, too, like Deer Tongue, which has triangular crisp leaves,
and something called Thai Oakleaf, which reportedly stands up to
the heat and has ``a distinctive almondlike flavor.'' We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   I ordered a ton of arugula from Cook's Garden, both the common
variety, Eruca sativa, and a smaller, wilder form from Italy called
Selvatica, which has finely cut leaves and is more heat-tolerant. A
wild kale mix for salads also caught my eye.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of Change (888-762-7333) has some terrific greens like a
lamb's-quarters called Magenta Spreen, whose leaves deepen from
lilac to purple and magenta; tatsoi with spoon-shaped tangy leaves;
and Osaka purple mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to plant some shallots and red onions to go with
all those salads, and radishes are also a must. Also, beets! I love
Chioggia for its pink and white rings, and Early Wonder, which
produces lots of delicious green-and-red-veined tops. I usually
order mine from Johnny's Selected Seeds (207-437-4301), which is
also plugging a beet called Red Ace. I had to try it.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd's collection of Tricolor pattypan squash is
irresistible, producing light green, dark green and gold baby
squashes. Pick them when they're just an inch and a half long,
Shepherd suggests. She eats them braised in chicken broth, onions
and fresh dill.
</P>
<P>
   She and others like Cook's and Territorial Seed (541-942-9547)
are raving about tromboncino, a light green Italian squash shaped
like a little trumpet and best trellised. It's supposed to be
tastier than a zucchini, but what isn't?
</P>
<P>
   I always have to plant Roly Poly, a beautifully mottled green
round squash with a creamy, nutty flavor, sold by W. Atlee Burpee
(800-888-1447).
</P>
<P>
   Territorial is selling green soybeans this year _ Sayamusume is
the variety _ so you, too, can steam those fuzzy pods and feast on
the sweet, nutty-flavored beans inside. Johnny's is offering one
called Butterbean.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also growing some sweet corn this year _ my old favorite
Silver Queen and a new multicolor one from Burpee called Indian
Summer, with white, red, yellow and purple kernels.
</P>
<P>
   As for peas, I'm loyal to Sugar Snaps _ the climbers, not the
short, bushy types _ and for snow peas, Oregon Giant. I usually get
my peas from Cook's, which has a wide variety of shelling peas,
including my all-time favorite, Lincoln, a tasty heirloom. I found
another favorite snap pea, Sugar Ann, at Johnny's.
</P>
<P>
   My tomatoes include Black Krim, an incredibly sweet,
mahogany-purple Russian tomato; Brandywine, a large pink beefsteak
type with intense flavor; Cherokee Purple, originally cultivated by
the Cherokees and supposedly a rival to Brandywine; and Green
Zebra, a gorgeous green-and-yellow striped tomato with a tang. All
from Seed Savers Exchange, in Decorah, Iowa (319-382-5990).
</P>
<P>
   I also want to grow a small field of Rouge Vif d'Etampes, a
widely offered French heirloom pumpkin that is said to have
inspired Cinderella's carriage. It is flame red, deeply ribbed and
very bumpy, and it was first sold in America by Burpee in 1883.
Renee Shepherd tells of chasing some teen-age neighbors down the
street last summer with some of her prize Cinderella pumpkins. ``I
felt like Farmer McGregor,''she said. ``All I needed was my
pitchfork.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd is also offering Mignonette, an alpine strawberry that
can be started from seed in pots for the terrace or in hanging
containers, or used as an edging plant in the garden. Set a little
pot of them on the breakfast table, she suggests, and graze while
you're having coffee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
