<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, March 25. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECTION (Moscow) _ In an ugly burst of negative
campaigning, Russia's state-owned television has asserted that the
leading liberal candidate in Sunday's presidential election is
supported by Jews, foreigners and homosexuals. The prime-time
attack on Grigori Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko
faction, was broadcast Thursday night by the ORT television
network. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ It was inconceivable that Pope
John Paul II, as he glided serenely though the Holy Land on a
personal pilgrimage and a secondary mission of interfaith healing,
would transform a region characterized by divisiveness and hatred.
Not even for a few days. But despite an outbreak of violence at a
Palestinian refugee camp and the verbal sniping over Jerusalem that
ruined his inter-denominational gathering, the pope has managed so
far to hover above the fray. In doing so, he has presented what
some see as a model of brotherly discourse to religious leaders
here. And he has established a soothing tone that quieted most of
the tensions and made both Israelis and Palestinians feel endorsed
by his visit. A news analysis by Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Kampala, Uganda) _ The Ugandan police said Friday
that they had found the corpses of 153 people, including women and
children, buried under a building used by the cult involved in a
fire last week in which 500 of its members died. (Summary from
wires) By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PAKISTAN (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ High anxiety has
replaced great expectations in Pakistan's capital, with people
anticipating that President Clinton will arrive here on Saturday
not just to say hello but to deliver a scolding. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned
Friday that the United Nations was in danger of losing a propaganda
war with Saddam Hussein if the ``oil for food'' program designed to
help Iraqis suffering under sanctions was not made more effective
immediately. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Harassment of gay men and women in
the American military is widespread, especially in the form of
offensive remarks, derogatory jokes and gestures, and an
overwhelming majority of service members believe their superiors
and colleagues tolerate it ``to some extent,'' according to a
Pentagon survey released Friday. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ This year's partisan battle over
the federal budget, which lurched forward early Friday when the
House narrowly passed a Republican tax and spending blueprint, has
a familiar ring to it. Republicans want a big tax cut, more money
for the military and reductions in just about everything else.
Democrats are trying to expand or at least protect spending on a
wide array of domestic programs. Each side is attacking the other
in apocalyptic terms. But it is worth noting that prosperity has
brought the parties closer on fiscal policy than either of them
usually admits. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   USAIR-UNION (Undated) _ Facing a strike deadline of midnight, US
Airways and its flight attendants' union reported modest progress
Friday as they continued negotiation in the hope of averting a
shutdown. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-OBSERVATORY (Undated) _ After a three-month review of
the risks of doing nothing, NASA decided Friday that the safest
course will be to direct the crippled 17-ton Compton Gamma Ray
Observatory to make a suicidal plunge out of orbit and back toward
Earth while they still can control its destructive return to skies
far from inhabited land. The decision disappointed astronomers, who
had hoped for a few more years of observations of the enigmatic
flashes of gamma rays that attest to some of the most bizarre and
powerful phenomena in the universe. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
