<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL RADIO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Sidebar to Web Radio) 
Compiled by DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to get an earful of radio on the Web? Turn that virtual
dial to these hot sites:
</P>
<P>
   KCRW (www.kcrw.org) is the online home of the Santa Monica
public broadcasting giant. One channel for music, which you can now
click and buy; one channel for news and public affairs programming,
and their live over-the-air feed. The site also archives the
station's prodigious catalog of locally created public affairs
programming, its frequent in-studio performances by prominent
musical acts and more. A treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Radio (www.spikeradio.com), brainchild of Australian Net
baron Chris O'Hanlon, who leveraged his Pacific Rim powerhouse of a
Web design company to create an online-only radio station staffed
with star ``iJays,'' or interactive deejays. The company is adding
Latino and Japanese music sites, and programming like the ``Church
of Fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   soundbreak.com (www.soundbreak.com) features underground dance
music and lots of goodies like a studio cam and chat room revolving
around its stable of digital jocks.
</P>
<P>
   Enigma Digital has a raft of narrowly targeted music-oriented
sites, including KNAC.com (www.knac.com), the old Los Angeles heavy
metal/hard rock FM station reborn. It has deals with two Kiss
members, and offers a variety of tracks, contests and other goodies
for fans of loud guitars, long hair and banshee singers.
</P>
<P>
   Enigma's Groove Radio (www.grooveradio.com) is home to another
L.A. FM fugitive, in this case, the Swedish Egil, whose underground
dance and club sound appeared on KROQ, MARS-FM and elsewhere before
heading Webward. Among recent offerings was a free downloadable
track by Grammy nominee Moby, remixed by Paul Oakenfold.
</P>
<P>
   Enigma also owns Luxuria Music (www.luxuriamusic.com), which
focuses on lounge and retro sounds, with fun articles on topics
such as the late Tiny Tim and offbeat getaways.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy and Doug's Farm Club, (farmclub.com) is a site where
unknown bands go to get known. Lots of resources, and for the ones
who build a big fan base, a chance to appear on the FarmClub.com TV
show with more prominent acts. Baby bands beware, however: read the
fine print.
</P>
<P>
   MusicBlitz (www.musicblitz.com) is rolling out a series of genre
music sites (such as www.reggaeblitz.com and www.bluesblitz.com)
that give away original music by moderately well-known artists such
as Taj Mahal, Presidents of the United States of America and Aimee
Mann.
</P>
<P>
   Live365.com (www.live365.com) can turn you into a station
manager. So can Shoutcast (www.shoutcast.com). They differ in such
details as how many simultaneous listeners you can have, listener
rating ability and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Launch publishes a monthly CD-ROM ``magazine'' of music,
videogame and movie previews and performances and is beefing up its
online presence (www.launch.com) with all the goodies it gathers
for the CD-ROM and with Launchcast, software that lets you program
a radio playlist from thousands of licensed tracks. It also has
licensed music videos from most of the big labels. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
