<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIDEO-GAMES-ART-650(2     03-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINTENDO'S GAME BOY CONTINUES TO DOMINATE HAND-HELD VIDEO GAME
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last month has redefined the video game business worldwide.
In Japan, Sony sold nearly a million Playstation 2 video game
consoles in the first two days on the market. And in California,
Microsoft jolted the industry with the announcement of X-Box, a
Windows PC masquerading as a video game console.
</P>
<P>
   But amid all the noise from the two giants, it's easy to forget
the $4.2 billion industry's greatest ``bit'' player of all _ the
little Game Boy.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 88 million Game Boys sold in the last decade,
Nintendo reigns as the uncontested heavyweight champion of selling
bantamweight games you can hold in the palm of your hand, boasting
more than 99 percent of the market. And a color version introduced
last year has inspired a new generation of games-to-go that
promises to extend that market domination well into the future.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no lack of challengers, big and small. The most
recent is the Neo Geo Pocket Color, from SNK, of San Jose, Calif.,
marketed as the ``Game Boy-killer.'' But the Neo, like previous
contenders, has failed to break Nintendo's iron grip on the hugely
profitable market for game players that can fit in a bookbag or
ease long car rides _ as opposed to bulkier consoles that must be
tethered to a television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game Boy represents about 30 percent of Nintendo of America's
overall revenues,'' said George Harrison, Nintendo's vice president
for advertising and corporate communications. ``We expect that
number to increase to around 40 percent in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is it that makes the Game Boy such a perennial winner?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of a better alternative,'' said Sean McGowan, executive
vice president for research at Gerard Klauer Mattison. ``In its
10-year history, competitors offered nothing that could rival the
price, compactness, library of titles, and ease of use.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Palm organizers, which enjoy an estimated lead of
millions over similar devices running Microsoft's Windows CE
operating system, the Game Boy is a carry-with-you personal
computer that engenders fierce customer loyalty and has so far
proven impervious to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is probably one of the most profitable consumer electronics
devices ever developed,'' McGowan said, estimating that total
retail sales last year topped $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That is no small feat in an age of flavor-of-the-month desktop
and notebook electronic devices. For 9 of its 10 years, the only
sizeable changes the Game Boy underwent were shedding a few inches
and ounces to make it easier to fit in a pocket or school bag, and
losing its original drab gray finish for flashier colors like red,
yellow, silver and see-through ``Atomic Purple.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant change was last year's introduction of a
color screen _ a feature that customers had been begging for from
the start. Handheld rivals like the Atari Lynx and Sega Game Gear
offered color years ago, but the novelty backfired. Their bright,
backlit screens drained batteries so fast they would often die in
the middle of a game, and both game machines fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   But Nintendo, like SNK, chose a different technology, a
reflective color LCD screen that minimizes the gadget's size,
weight and battery drain while providing high visibility in normal
lighting conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Neo Geo's screen is slightly larger than Game Boy Color's
display and offers more than double the number of simultaneous
colors, which translates into richer, more textured graphics, but
it has a long way to go before it can crack Game Boy's dominance.
Nintendo claims that a fresh set of AAA batteries will power a Game
Boy Color for about 20 hours, compared with a scant couple of hours
for older portable color systems.
</P>
<P>
   But McGowan said the ``Pokemon factor'' _ Nintendo's lock on
games based on this trading-card craze _ may have done even more to
spur sales. ``Over 25 percent of the games bought for Game Boy
Color are Pokemon-related,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Curiously, the first three Pokemon Game Boy cartridges _ Blue,
Red and Yellow _ make only nominal use of the machine's palette of
32,000 available colors (of which 56 can appear on the screen at
any given time). Even so, they became the three best-selling video
games in 1999. And Pokemon Pinball was the No. 5 best seller, after
Donkey Kong 64 for the Nintendo 64 video game console.
</P>
<P>
   Most new Game Boy games take full advantage of color, though
typically they run on older black-and-white models as well. More
than just consumer-friendly, that backward compatibility is turning
out to be a key to getting existing users to upgrade; one glance at
game packaging showing both versions is enough to make any kid cry
for the color version.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely much richer,'' McGowan said of color games.
``There is more detail, more complexity and depth to the games.
They're written differently to take advantage of the better
graphics.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in large part, he credits Game Boy's enduring success
to the developers who create the games that run on it. ``Any old
system can get better with time if developers have a motive to
squeeze more out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Game Boy's triumph, though, hasn't been without its share of
hiccups, which led to a slide from about $800 million in sales in
1991 to a low of about $175 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the decline had more to do with its rocket-like takeoff than
with any real failure, Harrison contends. ``Game Boy never really
hit a slump,'' he said. ``The product has been a consistent seller
since we first introduced it in 1989, but there have been several
sales spikes that do cause this misconception.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Video-game developers are giddy about the Game Boy market. Mike
Ribero, executive vice president of Midway Games, whose products
include NFL Blitz 2000 and Ready 2 Rumble Boxing, says his
company's revenue from Game Boy products rose 45 percent, to $10.9
million, in the first half of fiscal 2000, compared with $7.5
million in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are challenges,'' he said, ``in compressing a full game
experience from a coin-op or next-generation home system onto a
platform with more limited technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has found a way to parlay his company's expertise to
adapt arcade experience to the Game Boy's smaller screen. ``The
focus is on more fun, faster,'' Ribero said. ``They can't rely on
advanced technology and other extras like full-motion videos.''
</P>
<P>
   Such ``extras'' are standard fare on console systems like the
Sony Playstation, Nintendo 64, or Sega Dreamcast, which in power
and capacity are to the Game Boy what a desktop PC is to a Palm
Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Mike Schmitt, producer for the upcoming Tomb
Raider for Game Boy Color, says his team has managed to ``capture
the `spirit and feel' of a Tomb Raider adventure and convert it
into a completely new 2D game.'' All the original animations
depicting the game's heroine, a sort of pixel-pinup-adventurer
named Lara Croft with a huge following among young men, have been
re-rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-release screenshots and animated sequences from the game
reveal a very recognizable version of Lara standing a full 48
pixels tall _ statuesque by the standards of Game Boy, whose
characters are usually only 16 to 32 pixels high. Pixels, or
picture elements, are the dots of light on a television or monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Several coming games promise to inject the Game Boy Color not
only with the essence of their console and computer counterparts
but also with actual characters and virtual ``playing pieces'' from
those games. This will be done with an accessory called the
Transfer Pak, which Nintendo includes with its just-released
Pokemon Stadium. The Transfer Pak plugs into the Nintendo 64 game
controller and accepts Game Boy Pokemon cartridges so that all
those little monsters can populate a more graphically intense, 3-D
environment on a television screen. The Pak, which may also be
purchased separately, is expected to breathe life into other new
games as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for the competition from SNK, ``Neo Geo is getting some
recognition,'' said a New York-area video game retailer who
insisted on anonymity. ``In an average day I sell maybe 20 Game Boy
games and 2 Neo Geo games, but Neo Geo is gaining in popularity,
slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   What isn't slow about the Neo Geo Pocket Color is its graphics.
Its version of Sonic the Hedgehog, for example, plays as
lightning-fast as the older but still fast-paced Sega Genesis
version that inspired it. A fast-growing library of games suggests
that the Neo Geo has a fighting chance at getting a foothold in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan agrees. ``It's one of the best competitors to Game Boy
that's come along in a long time,'' he said. But it can't play
Pokemon, which Nintendo owns. That, McGowan is quick to remind, is
``a major reason the Game Boy is successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, SNK shipped its console-connection feature several months
before Nintendo's Transfer Pak. The first Neo Geo Pocket Color game
to offer the sharing of game-playing between a pocket game and
larger video game system is ``The Match of the Millennium: SNK vs.
Capcom.'' An optional cable connects the handheld game to a Sega
Dreamcast, letting players usher fighters in and out of that
machine's King of Fighters arena.
</P>
<P>
   But Nintendo is not on pause. ``We are not going to let Game Boy
Color fall by the wayside just because new hardware is being
introduced,'' Harrison said. Indeed, by Christmas, the company may
deliver its biggest one-two punch yet, with the much-anticipated
release of its next-generation handheld player, the Game Boy
Advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Advance will have a larger screen and higher resolution _
that is, more pixels, more colors, a faster processor. And it will
have a wireless capability that will turn it into a Web browser and
e-mail reader, and enable the kind of multiplayer online gaming now
enjoyed only by desktop PC gamers _ but on a Lilliputian scale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
