<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7028 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-CHRISTENSEN-M     03-24 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CHRISTENSEN-MODEL-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE WAS NEEDED AS A GRAMMARIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one ever said that life after modeling is easy.
Besides the pain of makeup withdrawal and the pangs of catwalk
envy, there is also the issue of how to make a living without
simply being fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for the Danish supermodel _ and runway retiree _ Helena
Christensen, who since last spring has held the impressive-sounding
title of creative director for Nylon magazine, a fashion-oriented
glossy that marked its first anniversary on Wednesday night with a
party at Skirt, a boutique on Mercer Street.
</P>
<P>
   According to its Web site, Nylon is ``the most hot magazine,''
devoted to covering ``life's passionate participants, not it's
fainthearted spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   With grammar like that, there is little doubt that Christensen's
editorial skills are badly in demand. But on Wednesday, the party
seemed more desperate for a little of the spark provided by her
previous vocation.
</P>
<P>
   The event's invitation promised ``cocktails, DJ and beautiful
surprises'' to begin at 8 p.m., but things were slow to ignite.
Christensen was running late, having just arrived from Los Angeles
with her beau, Norman Reedus, and their 5-month-old baby, Mingus.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 p.m., there were lots of normal-looking folks drinking, and
a DJ spinning 1980s music, but still no beautiful surprises.
Inexplicably, two men in Krispy Kreme T-shirts milled about with
glazed donuts and hand-scrawled signs saying, ``Negative
Calories.'' It seemed slightly cruel.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd waited, Marvin Scott Jarrett, Nylon's editor in
chief, explained Christensen's role at the magazine. ``She's not in
the office every day,'' he said. ``But she contributes to every
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   For April's ``Beautiful Issue'' (is a ``Biotechnology Issue'' in
the works?), Christensen contributed several photographs and a Q.
and A. with Brooke Shields. (Helena: ``You have a boyfriend now.''
Brooke: ``I have a boyfriend now.'')
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's wife and partner, Jaclynn B. Jarrett, who is Nylon's
publisher, expounded on their star editor's role. ``She's like a
traveling correspondent,'' Jarrett said. ``She goes places and
tells us about it, or brings back what's hot in India, Denmark,
Paris, London.''
</P>
<P>
   As of 9:30 p.m., the traveling correspondent was still out of
pocket. Outside, the paparazzi milled impatiently, taking photos of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a tan Christensen came striding up, with Reedus and
an entourage of Danish friends. While a cadre of photographers was
held at bay, Christensen, 31, said in a sidewalk interview that she
had been taking photos since her youth in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Photography is the most thrilling thing in my life,''
Christensen said with a wisp of an accent. ``It's so much more
fulfilling than being on the other side of the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she had lost any of her old talents. Moments later,
Christensen, dressed in a Dries van Noten skirt and fuchsia
cashmere top, was posing for her fellow shutterbugs, including a
Dr. Strangelove look-alike with a point-and-shoot who kept
shouting, ``Linda! Linda!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Linda?'' Christensen asked.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a crowd of well-wishers pushed forward to air kiss the
creative director. The mood changed almost immediately. The lights
were dimmed, and sure enough, the model-to-human ratio began to tip
toward the stunning. Gravity-defying necklines became the norm.
Sport-gawking ensued. The Jarretts beamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you give me,'' said one tie-wearing 20-something,
looking at Christensen, ``if I just go up to her and kiss her on
the lips?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cab fare home,'' his friend said.
</P>
<P>
   By night's end, Christensen, who sipped Champagne through a
straw, had worked her way to the back of the room, and the flashes
had subsided. It was her first drink, she said, since she became
pregnant and her five months of breast-feeding just ended. ``I
wanted to continue,'' she said, ``but he got way more hungry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1653EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
