<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7029 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-OSCARS-PLACEMENT-ART-     03-24 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-PLACEMENT-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY OSCAR? OH, THAT OLD THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, March 26)  
(lh) 
 By MARCIA BIEDERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many envelopes will be ripped open Sunday night at
the 72nd Annual Academy Awards. But not one will contain
instructions on how to display a much-hoped-for, much-obsessed-over
Oscar at home so it won't look preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a little-explored downside to walking away with one
of the 13-inch-high gold statuettes. An Oscar may look great on the
red carpet or on a table at Morton's during the Vanity Fair
after-party. But where can one keep it at home so it doesn't suck
all the air out of the room?
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the city that never sleeps well, it seems more than
a few winners get angst over housing their Oscars. What was once
the holy grail can become the monkey's paw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to keep it in an athletic sock in the bottom of a
laundry bag in my apartment in Washington Heights,'' said John
Patrick Shanley, who won the Academy Award for best original
screenplay for ``Moonstruck'' in 1988. He was worried at the time
about thieves. ``It was a really funky building,'' he said. ``There
was no lock in the front door. Instead, there was a bottle cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanley lives in Greenwich Village now, yet is still uneasy
about living with a totem of such supposed worth. He keeps his
Oscar behind his television in a tangle of wires, where it is only
partially visible.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves aren't the real issue. ``It's pretentious to even have
one,'' he said. ``They always say `the best' _ the best picture,
the best screenplay. It's sort of acknowledging you beat everybody.
It's not nice to fling it in people's faces. It won't make them
like you. And if you're alone, why would you have it out there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in a low place, it will make you feel low,'' said
Shanley, who also called the Oscar ``a tombstone'' and ``a living
rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like having it, though,'' he said. And on the night he
received it, he recalled, ``I don't know if I would have gotten
into Spago without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympia Dukakis, who won an Oscar as best supporting actress for
her role in ``Moonstruck,'' was living in Montclair, N.J., at the
time. ``When I brought it back, I left it on the kitchen table,''
she said. ``Then I had it on a little table in the corner of the
kitchen. I never decided where to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   The quandary was solved when someone broke into her house and
stole it. For $200, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
provided a replacement. When Dukakis moved to a NoHo loft last
September _ she plays the starring role in ``Rose,'' which begins
previews at the Lyceum Theater this week _ she put the new Oscar on
the top shelf of a bookcase in her home office. It sits next to a
statue of Astarte, the Phoenician goddess of sexual love, a Golden
Globe and other trophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big plaque up there. What is it?'' Dukakis said,
calling out to an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   She did not put the Oscar in a more prominent spot because ``I
tend not to display things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But an Oscar can hide in plain sight, as Donna Gigliotti has
found. Last year Gigliotti took one home as one of the producers of
``Shakespeare in Love,'' which won for best picture. The
statuette's sleek Art Deco lines happen to go with the decor of her
living room on Riverside Drive, she said, adding, ``It's a
beautiful, beautiful thing.'' Though she displays it on a table
near a sofa, guests seldom notice it. ``It's amazing,'' said
Gigliotti, who is head of production at USA Films. ``When they do
notice it, the first thing they do is ask if they can hold it. I
warn them there's an Oscar legend: If you haven't won an Oscar and
you hold one, you never will.''
</P>
<P>
   And what if the problem is having more than one? Stephen
Schwartz, the songwriter, won two with Alan Menken in 1996 _ one
for the original musical score for ``Pocahontas'' and the other for
best song, ``Colors of the Wind.'' The twin Oscars are in a trophy
case in his Connecticut home, ``where they serve as handsome
balancing sorts of bookends'' for his other awards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He lets friends play with his third, won last year for best
song, ``When You Believe,'' from ``The Prince of Egypt.'' ``I put
it in an easily accessible glass cabinet in my New York apartment,
so that all my friends who ask me about it could pick it up and
hold it,'' Schwartz said. ``The inevitable comment is always, `Hey,
it's heavier than I expected.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kopple has twice taken honors for best documentary
feature, in 1977 for ``Harlan County, USA'' and in 1991, with
Arthur Cohn, for ``American Dream.'' Her Oscars sit on a desk in
her SoHo loft as part of an artistic arrangement that includes a
large steel sculpture and a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids usually pick them up and do a he-man pose,'' she said.
``And then they want a picture taken, so we load the camera. Adults
float over and pick them up and put them down.'' Unlike some
creative people, Kopple isn't conflicted about an Oscar's everyday
presence in her life. ``An award like that gets audiences to look
at these films,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's winner for best short-subject documentary, Keiko
Ibi, said she has yet to find a place for the statuette in her
two-bedroom Greenwich Village apartment. For the moment, it is on a
high shelf in a work area ``so people won't see it so much,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first film, and I was really lucky,'' Ibi said of
``The Personals: Improvisations on Romance in the Golden Years,''
which she made while a graduate student at New York University.
``It's such a big award, it's hard to fit it in the life I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Davidson's film ``The Lunch Date,'' which he made as a
graduate-school project at Columbia University School of the Arts,
was named best live-action short film in 1991. He sent the
statuette to his parents in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to look at it every day,'' said Davidson, who
was then in his mid-20s and is now directing his first feature
film, ``Way Past Cool.'' ``Life is hard enough. I was unprepared
for it to happen. I felt I had a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The parental home was no safe haven, however. Oscar was shaken
off his shelf by the 1994 Los Angeles earthquake. Now the little
guy has ``a big hole in his head,'' the director said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's exhilarated winners might take some tips from
past recipients, not only of Oscars but of other big awards. Four
years after Lawrence Rock, the audio director of the New York
Philharmonic, won a Grammy for recording engineering, his prize, a
miniature gramophone, still spends most of its time in its box. ``I
have hauled it out to show people,'' he said. ``The problem is,
they want to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The composer John Kander has Grammys, Tonys and an Emmy, but no
Academy Award. ``If I had an Oscar, I'd keep it near the door to
defend against burglars,'' he said. ``As a weapon, the Tony isn't
worth a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   And here is a radical idea: When Susan Lucci finally won an Emmy
last year after 19 nominations as a soap opera star, she put the
award, her press agent said, ``on her living room mantel, center
stage, above the fireplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
