<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-24 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ONE IN HIS LEAGUE: PETERS OWN THE PBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excuse my self-assuredness, but you want to be Chris Peters for
a day. Trust me. I want to be Chris Peters for a day, too.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if you are male or female; straight or gay;
dark or pale; a young hip-hopper or an aged bebopper; preacher,
poet, or politician. If you are a sports fan, you would love to do
what Peters and two of his business partners recently did. In
essence, they wrote a check, slid it across a desk, shook hands in
good faith, and said the following:
</P>
<P>
   Fellas, we're buying the league.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs Rotisserie Leagues when you can buy (itals)an entire
professional sports league?(unitals) Wait until Pete Rose hears
about this. Baseball wants to ban him for life? No problem. He can
simply buy the Major Leagues, retire all No. 14s, put a slot
machine in every clubhouse and ban Bud Selig and Jim Gray from all
ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Peters is a 42-year-old dot-com wizard. He is a former vice
president at Microsoft, the company that will one day purchase the
United States and relocate the White House to the Pacific
Northwest. He is a bowling fan who was born in Akron, Ohio,
birthplace of the PBA. His family moved West when he was 2, but the
game was already snaking through his veins. That's part of the
reason he and fellow rich men Mike Slade and Rob Glaser purchased
the PBA for, sources say, $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   So now they own the PBA's logos, trademarks, copyrights, and Web
site. Almost overnight, they switched the PBA from a struggling
nonprofit organization to a stable, privately owned company. They
plan to offer the country's best bowlers stock options. They
envision marketing Parker Bohn III and Walter Ray Williams to those
who view bowlers as if they were the hilariously crazed Monday
Night Leaguers portrayed in the film ``The Big Lebowski.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies like `Lebowski' and `Kingpin' don't show what bowling
is about,'' Peters said during a telephone interview Thursday.
``Those guys are losers. The game is not like that. Today's game is
so much different than it was 10 years ago. It's a power game now.
I'm telling you, these guys are athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters talked about the strength of pro bowlers. He described
bowling balls traveling at 25 miles per hour, balls with 300 rpms,
and deceptively strong pros who often hold the ball over their
heads and roll it 700 times during a tournament. There were
references to the 50 million people in the United States who enter
bowling alleys every year. There were references to the 500,000
folks who have visited the PBA's Web site, and how bowling's
ratings are higher than the NHL's and WNBA's, despite the fact that
``the sport has had no marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even over the phone, it was obvious that bowling is Peters's
favorite sport. But that's not the only reason he and his partners
purchased his favorite league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't do this if we didn't think we could make money,''
he said. ``We don't want this to be a big charity for us. We say we
want to educate people about bowling, but a less polite name for
education is marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's amazing how much flexibility we have. In baseball,
there are so many factions. There's the umpires, the players, the
owners, and the commissioner. With us, if we want to get something
done we can just do it. We don't need anyone's permission.''
</P>
<P>
   As I talked with Peters, I had to remind myself that I wasn't
talking to one of my buddies during an
If-I-owned-a-pro-sports-league daydream riff. Amazing. He actually
is one of the controllers of the league. He is roughly the same age
as the league that he owns. Thursday, he outlined his stock-options
plan for bowlers. He said he would offer packages to the best
bowlers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him how he would explain himself to those who didn't
have stock options. What if one asked why the other guy had options
and he didn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell him, `Because he's a better bowler,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. No appeals to the Players Association. No arbitrators
overturning the ruling of a commissioner. No unproven rookie
threatening to hold out and play for another team if his contract
demands are not met. Other team? Please. It's my league, son.
You're not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I want to be Chris Peters for a day. You do, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until Marty McSorley hears about this. He is suspended for
the remainder of the NHL season for his celebrated clubbing of
Donald Brashear? No problem. Buy the entire league and reinstate
himself.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello chuckled at the buy-a-league scenario
Thursday. But he insisted that it would be impossible to do that in
football. The NFL is basically a partnership with 31 owners. So if
there were to be a sale, a billionaire would have to make
arrangements with each owner and make a sale attractive to him or
her. Aiello sounded doubtful, but I'm not. I have heard about
Microsoft's cash; I have also heard how men such as Art Modell
thirst for cash. Greedy guys can always be bought.
</P>
<P>
   Peters is not concerned about the other leagues. His true love
is bowling. He is searching for a PBA president, ``somebody who
wants to run their own league. You know anybody?''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. He can do that. He is a sports fan who owns his own
league. He can change the rules if he wants. He can require all
bowlers to wear kilts. He can put a picture of himself in every
lane, as if he were some obsessed czar.
</P>
<P>
   Peters was asked if he could see another league being bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the USTA,'' he said of the United States Tennis
Association. ``It could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
