   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY: `AND THE WINNER IS...VLADIMIR PUTIN.' (ACT SURPRISED) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN-CORONATION-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Sunday's election, Russia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even by old Soviet election standards, it has not been much of a
contest. Only the scale of Acting President Vladimir Putin's
victory Sunday is in doubt. Indeed, the most significant feature of
the election is not the railroaded result but the comprehensive way
in which the Kremlin has controlled the campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORIS BEREZOVSKY: KREMLIN PUPPETEER OR FUTURE PUTIN VICTIM? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORIS-BEREZOVSKY-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Sunday's election, Russia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Boris Berezovsky, Russia's oligarch-extraordinaire, see out
the year in jail, exile or the comfortable nook between business
and government that he currently occupies? The answer will give a
clear sign of where the country is headed under Vladimir Putin, who
is set to be elected president on March 26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 650 words; 1,000 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `CHOLO' ALEJANDRO TOLEDO: PERU'S FAIRY-TALE CANDIDATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUJIMORI-RIVAL-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Timely for April 9 election, Peru) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political fairy tales are not unknown in Peru. In 1990, a
university rector named Alberto Fujimori rose from nowhere in the
final weeks of a presidential election campaign to trounce Mario
Vargas Llosa, a world-famous novelist. Now Fujimori is seeking a
third term in an election on April 9. He has seemed assured of easy
victory. Yet suddenly he has a serious challenger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERABEAM: THE NEXT TELECOMS GIANT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERABEAM-ME-UP-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Seattle) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to ground-breaking technology and ingenious new
Internet businesses, the `digerati' who show up for Esther Dyson's
annual PC Forum are blase to the point of weariness. That makes the
buzz caused last week by Seattle-based TeraBeam Networks all the
more remarkable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEC APPEARS IN CONTROL OF OIL MARKETS. APPEARANCES DECEIVE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEC-SQUEEZED-ECONOMIST-800&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for March 27 OPEC meeting, Vienna) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oil has become a volatile substance. The world is producing
about 75 million barrels a day (b/d) of the stuff; it is consuming
about 77 million b/d. Nobody likes it that way. Producers and
consumers alike speak of their desire for stable oil prices. Yet
only in times of war or revolution has the price been wilder. Which
is one reason why, as OPEC gathers for its annual meeting in Vienna
on March 27, the hardest question is what will happen next? &QL;
</P>
