A7032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-24 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON TAKES TO IT LIKE A PRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Thompson still has strong opinions about college
basketball, but the former Georgetown coach (and Celtic player) is
getting a kick out of calling NBA games for Turner Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Like others, Thompson felt betrayed by some images of NBA
players on television _ the five-second sound bites of Shaquille
O'Neal, for instance, that portray him as a sullen, menacing giant.
Thompson has seen a little more to Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was in Miami talking with players before a recent
Heat-Lakers game and he told O'Neal that he was impressed not so
much with his size but with his incredible skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach I was telling him this,'' Thompson said. ``I mean,
forget his size, Shaq is extremely skillful. He can really play.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal thanked Thompson and went on down the court. A moment
later, O'Neal picked up Turner analyst Danny Ainge and was carrying
him around the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen it,'' Thompson said. ``He was carrying
Danny around like a little baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, when they think about Shaq, they think enigma.
But that's not all there is to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner personnel told him from the start that he would have to
work hard at broadcasting and would have to start by calling
several exhibition games to prepare for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I got the job, I thought all I would have to do was
show up at game time and start talking,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. On game day, Thompson talks with players and
coaches during their shootaround, then attends a production meeting
to talk about Turner's coverage. The network also wants him to
study tape of his broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to look like a fool, and they have been on me to
work at it,'' Thompson said. ``I've probably been interviewed since
I was 14 or 15 years old but I have never been on the other side of
the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been wonderful insight for viewers and fun for
Thompson. In Miami, he talked with Rick Fox and told the former
Celtic to tell his wife hello. Fox laughed and Thompson laughed.
Fox is married to Vanessa Williams. As Thompson tells the story,
Williams's brother attended Georgetown and was a cheerleader there.
</P>
<P>
   Right, Big John.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also tells a story about Spurs coach Gregg Popovich:
</P>
<P>
   ``Amid all the talk about Sean Elliott's return, very few picked
up the level of concern that the coach had for Elliott. You could
tell that it was more than points and rebounds that a small forward
could bring to his team. He wanted to make sure that Sean was
healthy and able to play. You could see the coach's personal
struggle over whether he should permit Sean to come back. He was
legitimately concerned and you just don't hear those stories that
much, especially in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about calling NBA games, Thompson said, is the
freedom to tell another coach's team what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big difference, coaching without the
responsibilities,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller on the bandwagon
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC airs The Players Championship Saturday from 2-6 p.m. and
Sunday from 3-6:30. Dan Hicks and Johnny Miller call the action
from Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla. Tiger Woods leads the pack. ``If you
ask me for my top 10 _ they're all Tiger Woods,'' Miller said.
``When you have a guy who drives the ball as far as he does and
makes every putt within 12 feet, you can't stop him. He just has
more horsepower right now than everyone else does and he's brimming
with confidence. That's not a guarantee _ I can see Jesper Parnevik
and Phil Mickelson playing well, and Greg Norman and Fred Couples
like this course. But they've still got to beat Tiger. If Tiger
wins here, you may as well give him the green jacket.'' . . . ESPN
Magazine baseball experts predict tight division races, except in
the AL East and AL Central. The experts did say that 18 of the 30
teams have a shot at the playoffs . . . CNN/SI analyst Ozzie Smith
named the Red Sox the 10th-best team in baseball. ``For Boston to
contend in 2000, they have to get some help for Pedro Martinez in
the rotation,'' Smith said. ``The list of other possible starters
is full of question marks. If the Red Sox can get a dominating year
out of just one other pitcher, they'll be dangerous.'' . . .
``Sports Genuises'' debuts Monday on Fox Sports Net at 6 p.m.
Hosted by Matt Vasgersian and former Patriots cheerleader Lisa
Guerrero, the show features three players competing head-to-head
for two rounds followed by a winner-take-all faceoff round.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
