<P>
   &UR; WATER: A SOLUBLE _ AND SOLVABLE _ PROBLEM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIVATIZE-WATER-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What could be more basic to life than a drink of water? Yet more
than a billion people have no access to safe water. Three times as
many lack adequate sanitation. World demand for fresh water is
expected to grow sharply, by 70 percent (for household use) by
2025. Shortages seem inevitable _ and even war. This dismal
reckoning lies behind the big world water summit held this week in
the Netherlands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAIWAN'S DARE, CHINA'S SCARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAIWAN-`ONE-CHINA'-ECONOMIST-725&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's election, which ended 50 years of Nationalist rule and
chose as the island's next president Chen Shui-bian, the candidate
of a hitherto pro-independence party, is a clear rebuff to China's
Communists, who claim Taiwan as their own. What will China do now?
The only solution remains for the two sides to decide together,
through negotiation, whether they are to be one China or two. But
as Taiwan changes and China grows ever more inflexible, that
becomes more difficult. Even if a crisis is averted this time, be
prepared for the next one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 225-word trim at 725; 1,075 words uncut) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREENSPAN'S DRIP-TORTURE STRATEGY IS DANGEROUS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RISKY-FED-RATES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pour boiling water on a frog and it will jump away; heat it up
slowly in a pot of cold water, and it will die. America's Federal
Reserve, which raised short-term interest rates by another
quarter-point to 6 percent on March 21, may need reminding of this
tale. The Fed's strategy of slowing an overheating economy by
raising rates gradually might prove just as risky for America _ and
so for the world economy, as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EXTRAORDINARY MUTATION OF AMERICA'S SUBURBS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 'BURBS-AMERICANBEAUTY-ECONOMIST-550&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for Sunday's Oscars) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``American Beauty,'' the movie favored to sweep the Oscars
Sunday night, Lester and Carolyn Burnham (played by Kevin Spacey
and Annette Bening) live in a picture-perfect house in the suburbs,
with a manicured lawn and a white picket fence. Although ``American
Beauty'' is somewhat redeemed by fine acting, the film overall
recycles a tired cliche of suburbia _ that they are vortexes of
tedium and alienation _ which has been a staple of artistic
contempt at least since John Cheever. Actually, that view is
getting less accurate by the day, as the suburbs mutate in all
sorts of extraordinary ways. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 3 trims, totaling 225 words; 1,100 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIAMI VISE: FUMING TOBACCO INDUSTRY FACES JURY _ AND
BANKRUPTCY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOBACCO-EXTINGUISHED?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
