<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-TAIWAN-`ONE-CHINA'-EC     03-24 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-`ONE-CHINA'-ECONOMIST-725&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S DARE, CHINA'S SCARE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 225-word trim; 1,075 uncut)   From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was meant to be the Pacific century, yet how suddenly the
language of commerce in the world's fastest-growing region can give
way to talk of war.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's election, which has ended 50 years of Nationalist rule
and picked as the island's next president Chen Shui-bian, the
candidate of a hitherto pro-independence party, is a clear rebuff
to China's Communists, who claim Taiwan as their own.
</P>
<P>
   They have long said they would meet any move to independence
with force, and recently added that force would also be their
response if Taiwan tried to delay talks on reunification
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   They made plain before the poll that Chen was unacceptable. The
Taiwanese elected him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Will China now make good its threat?
</P>
<P>
   Its leaders, stunned, say they will watch what Chen does and
listen to what he says. And if China does not like what it sees and
hears? Make no mistake, an exchange of shots across the Taiwan
Strait would not simply be a small skirmish in a 50-year Chinese
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   A clash between East Asia's second-largest economy and its
fourth-largest would do huge collateral damage, not least to
financial and trading interests the world over. It would draw in
America, which is committed to help Taiwan if it is attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Others, from Japan to Europe, who value their security ties to
America and profit from the stability these bring could not afford
to turn aside either.
</P>
<P>
   But high stakes can bring opportunities, as well as dangers. For
his part, Chen knows he was elected to fight Nationalist-spawned
corruption, not China. He has already said he will not declare
independence.
</P>
<P>
   This week he offered to meet China's leaders for a ``peace
summit,'' while Taiwan's parliament voted to end the ban on direct
cross-strait trade.
</P>
<P>
   China knows that taking potshots at Taiwan, let alone attempting
a full-scale invasion, and trading threats with America would
frighten away investment, putting China's own economic development
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   A blockade of Taiwan, though easier than an invasion to mount,
would be the surest bar to China's entry to the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   And if China's leaders feel pushed by their preelection threats
to demand a casualty or two, they have some: the humiliation of
Taiwan's Nationalists and their leader, the arch-``splittist'' Lee
Teng-hui, who last year infuriated China by calling for relations
to be put on a ``special state-to-state'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides insist they would prefer peace to war, yet there is a
real risk of stumbling into a conflict by misreading each other's
signals. That is where America can help, since it talks to both and
wants to see tempers cool.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only clear point of disagreement this week was one
of semantics: China wants any talks with Taiwan to take place on
the basis of its one-China principle; Chen rejects that as a
precondition, but is prepared to talk about what China means by it.
</P>
<P>
   The solution would seem obvious to any trainee diplomat: set
aside the word-play over ``one China'' and get on with the business
of reconciliation that could lead eventually to reunification.
</P>
<P>
   That may now happen. Chen takes office in May. Time, between now
and then, to switch off the megaphones and prepare for talks that
both sides say they want _ indeed that China insists on.
</P>
<P>
   So, crisis over? If only it were that simple.
</P>
<P>
   That ``one China'' difference is an incendiary one. For years
China, Taiwan and most onlookers, including America, have
subscribed to the notion that there was but ``one China.''
</P>
<P>
   They could then agree to disagree indefinitely about what sort
of China it could be: a Communist dictatorship or a democracy; one
country, two systems (as China insists) or one nation, two states
(as many Taiwanese would now prefer).
</P>
<P>
   But this sleight of diplomacy works only as long as both China
and Taiwan agree that it works. Increasingly, they do not.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure but China's, Taiwan is ``independent,'' with its
own government and currency. It used to enjoy widespread diplomatic
recognition and had a seat at the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   It is an affluent, maturing democracy; China, for all the
wrenching changes of the past 20 years, is a one-party
dictatorship. The gap is growing wider. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (225-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 725) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crisis? China acknowledges this up to a point, by offering
Taiwan even greater autonomy than either Hong Kong or Macau within
a reunified China.
</P>
<P>
   It notes, rightly, that there is no majority for independence
(its threats ensure that); but it overlooks the fact that there is
even less support for reunification. It is easy to see why.
</P>
<P>
   Binding in East Germany was hard enough for big, rich and
democratic West Germany. Small, rich, democratic Taiwan has plenty
to lose from hitching itself to bigger, but poorer, Communist-run
China.
</P>
<P>
   Egged on by China's military chiefs, its party bosses vow that
the only alternative to negotiated unity is forced unity. They may
mean it. One reason for thinking so is that, with their ideological
pretensions stripped away, they have little to wrap themselves in
but China's flag.
</P>
<P>
   To a visceral nationalist, preventing the loss of Taiwan might
seem the one thing worth risking China's economic stability for,
especially since a democratic and independent Taiwan would pose a
double threat to Communist power.
</P>
<P>
   A second reason is that the grab-Taiwan lobbyists may reckon
that casualty-averse America would soon back off in a shooting war
_ a notion America needs to disabuse them of, if such a war is to
be averted. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,075) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   China may think it can ignore the democratically expressed
feelings of the Taiwanese, but America, Europe, Japan and others
should not. It is not for these outsiders _ including those in
Congress who seem ready to fight China to the last Taiwanese _ to
urge formal independence on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, just as America must make it clear to China that force
will not be tolerated, so it must go on making it clear to Taiwan
that it cannot deliberately provoke China and then expect to have
others defend it.
</P>
<P>
   The only solution remains for the two to decide together,
through negotiation, whether they are to be one China or two. But
as Taiwan changes and China grows ever more inflexible, that
becomes more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a crisis is averted this time, be prepared for the next
one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
