<HEADER>
A7043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     03-24 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUTTER PREVENTS DRIP STAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 26, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My copper roof has turned to a nice green color, but dripping
water from a part of it has stained the concrete steps below a
green that looks like spray paint. How can I clean it, and how can
I keep it away?
</P>
<P>
   ANNETTE FLAHERTY, Southborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try a bleach solution, Zud, or muriatic acid on the stain.
The latter will etch the concrete by leaching lime out of it, and
may take the stain with it. Wear skin and eye protection when
working with bleach or acid. Even hydrogen peroxide might help. Or,
make a poultice of 1 part ammonium chloride (sal ammoniac) and 4
parts whiting made into a paste with household ammonia. Apply over
stain, let dry. Repeat if necessary. Rinse and dry. Ammonium
chloride and other chemicals can be bought at a chemical supply
house.
</P>
<P>
   You can prevent the stain one way: Put up a gutter and a
downspout on that part of the roof. Even a copper gutter will be
OK, as long as the downspout goes into the ground or a drywell. To
allow copper-laden water to run over grass could result in a dead
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My sliders are mahogany, a nice-looking wood but I am having
trouble finishing them. I don't think they were ever finished, and
they turned gray when they weathered. I sanded to the bare wood,
stained, and finished with three coats of oil-based exterior
polyurethane varnish. Now, a year later, the wood is weathering
again, but not peeling. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   MARIA JACOBSON, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know of any varnished exterior surface that stands up
to sunlight and other kinds of weather for very long. Your mahogany
sliders are an example of what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Your first priority is not to do it again. You have three
choices: 1. Let the weathering continue until all the finish is
off, then let it continue to weather. Mahogany naturally resists
decay, and if it gets wet and dries out after each wetting, it will
last indefinitely. 2. Remove the finish and let it weather. 3.
Remove the finish and treat the mahogany with one coat of a
semitransparent house stain. It will not peel, and will last for
five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to restore a 1953 porcelain sink that has two
dings and is fairly heavily abraded; the bottom is rough and
porous, the back and top edges are sill shiny. I was told by
reglazers that reglazing does not stand up very much on sinks
(bathroom or kitchen) that take a bigger beating than tubs. Is
there a reglazing that will stand up?
</P>
<P>
   TOM GOUX, Falmouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If porcelain does not stand up, any kind of epoxy coating
(the usual reglazing technique) is unlikely to stand up, either,
and the reglazers, to their credit, were very straight with you
about sinks.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven years is pretty good for a porcelain sink to last,
although I'll bet those dings occurred in the first week of the
sink. My porcelain sink was wonderful for the first week or so,
then, ding! That is why I switched to stainless steel, much less
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   So, I assume reglazing is not in the cards, but what is? You can
try this: For the dings, touch them up with appliance touch-up
enamel. You can get the right color at a hardware or paint store.
For the dull finish, there is an old homemade formula mentioned by
the handyman a thousand times. It will not restore the shine, but
chances are good that the sink will look almost new again. Wet the
dull area with hydrogen peroxide. Sprinkle cream of tartar on the
finish and leave it for an hour. Scrub and rinse. For some reason,
this treatment seems to make the finish less porous. Otherwise,
bite the bullet and get a new sink.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I saw some great self-countersinking screws that need no
predrilling at a home show some years ago. Now that I need them, I
can't find them. I have to drive screws into particleboard which is
so hard that nothing seems to work. Do you know of such screws?
</P>
<P>
   JIM WANTSMAN, North Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you were thinking of deck screws, which can be driven
without predrilling with a power screwdriver, even into
pressure-treated wood, which is Southern yellow pine, a very hard
softwood. But particleboard, especially the new superdense stuff,
needs predrilling a pilot hole for each screw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can I pressure-wash vinyl siding? The siding needs a lot of
cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   SHEILA SMITH, Walpole, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Gee, didn't the vinyl siding people say no maintenance? How
the idol has fallen. Of course your vinyl siding needs washing. Any
outside surface will get dirty (and moldy). But no, do not
pressure-wash vinyl siding or aluminum siding. This siding is put
together with interlocking joints, but if any water under pressure
gets under the siding, it will take a long time to dry out, and if
water stays there too long, it can cause decay. You can have it
done the regular way, scrubbing and rinsing with a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
