<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KREMLIN-CORONATION-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY: `AND THE WINNER IS...VLADIMIR PUTIN.' (ACT SURPRISED)  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Sunday's election, Russia)   From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It has not been much of a contest. Only the scale of
the victory is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner for the past six months, Acting President
Vladimir Putin, has produced no detailed manifesto or campaign
material, and declines to debate with other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   His most serious opponents were crushed in the parliamentary
elections three months ago. The rest, mostly marooned in the low
single figures, have ideas aplenty, but scant chance of getting
them across to the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that most excites outsiders, Chechnya's war, barely
rates a mention.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Putin's official duties in past weeks, however, look
very like campaigning. He has been touring the provinces, having
lots of carefully staged impromptu meetings with ``ordinary
Russians,'' issuing popular decrees (raising teachers' wages by 20
percent, for instance) and outlining his ideas for the future.
</P>
<P>
   These include banning food imports, bolstering the
military-industrial complex, bringing independent-minded regions
under control, and cutting overly-important, politically-connected
tycoons _ the ``oligarchs'' _ down to size.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Russia's television channels cover all this with
drooling appreciation, while ignoring the other ten candidates.
</P>
<P>
   For a trip to the troops in Chechnya, Putin arrived in a fighter
jet. This, he said, saved the taxpayer money. He also happened to
let slip shyly that for part of the way he had flown the plane
himself. ``I had a feeling very close to ecstasy,'' he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   This week he also urged voters to give him at least 50 percent
of the ballot: a second round, he argued, would waste $35 million
better spent on pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's main opponent is the perennial Communist loser, Gennady
Zyuganov. His party still has a strong organization and some loyal
governors.
</P>
<P>
   With a better leader and a fair share of airtime, the Communists
could gain more than their customary 25 percent. But Zyuganov's
grey personality and hoary simplicities turn off many voters.
Conveniently for Putin, two fringe leftist candidates also siphon
off some Communist support.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the election does go to a second round in two weeks'
time, Zyuganov looks set to be trounced, even more soundly than he
was by Boris Yeltsin in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates look even less significant. Grigory Yavlinsky,
the liberal-minded leader of Yabloko, the main center-left party,
has fought an energetic campaign. He has even dared to speak out
against the war in Chechnya, which he originally supported.
</P>
<P>
   He is in trouble with the authorities for having campaigned on
the territory of a military base, an infringement that evidently
does not apply to acting presidents handing out medals or attending
funerals.
</P>
<P>
   The other self-professed liberal candidate is the governor of
Samara, Konstantin Titov. He has been abandoned by his allies from
the Union of Right-Wing Forces.
</P>
<P>
   This free-market, pro-western party, which did better than
expected in the December parliamentary elections, now looks split.
Some of its leading lights, like a former privatization chief,
Anatoly Chubais, and Yegor Gaidar, a free-market former prime
minister, are keen supporters of Putin's.
</P>
<P>
   A few notables, such as Boris Nemtsov and Irina Khakamada, have
switched to Yavlinsky. Others are queasy, but support Putin on
tactical grounds. Titov looks set to get 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One new feature of the campaign has been an attempt by some
Moscow intellectuals to encourage a vote ``against all.'' If a
majority opts for this odd feature of the Russian ballot paper, the
poll becomes invalid.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ``against all'' seems to be running in fourth place,
with around 4 percent, a shade ahead of Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the
far-right populist xenophobe who heads the oddly-named Liberal
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ``against all'' campaign are calling for a
boycott of any western consumer-goods company which advertises on
the pro-Putin television channels.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that might still spoil the script is the war.
Putin's support has dropped by about a quarter from its peak,
perhaps because most Russians now favor a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Russian war casualties are still high, and a two-week-old battle
for Komsomolskoye, a ruined village that Russian forces claimed to
have taken in a day but have yet to subdue, has punched holes in
the sunny official picture.
</P>
<P>
   So has a report of a Chechen light aircraft discovered in
Grozny, which has supposedly been under complete Russian control
for a month. Russian officials constantly give warning of planned
terrorist outrages by Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant feature of the election is not the
all-but-certain result but the comprehensive way in which the
Kremlin has managed to control the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Putin has no real opponent. Even if he did, the
government's grip on the media, combined with a harshly and
arbitrarily interpreted election law, means that it would have been
hard for anyone else to have a fair crack at the prize. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-2DLD-WR     03-24 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-2DLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PENTAGON FINDS WIDESPREAD HARASSMENT OF GAYS IN UNIFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: EDITS and updates throughout.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG And STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon admitted Friday that there is
widespread harassment of homosexuals in the military, reporting
that 80 percent of GIs questioned around the world had heard
anti-gay remarks in the past year and that 37 percent had witnessed
or experienced harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``we simply cannot tolerate harassment in the armed
forces,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen launched an emergency
effort to combat what he called ``harassment based on perceived
sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hours before the public release of the report Cohen
announced he was establishing an oversight panel of senior military
and civilian leaders to map steps to combat the problem. He said
the panel will try to change the hostile atmosphere that gay and
lesbian troops often encounter and that by July 31 it will produce
an ``action plan'' for improving the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acted in response to a report by the Pentagon's deputy
inspector general, Donald Mancuso, who surveyed more than 71,570
men and women among the nation's 1.4 million troops.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted at 38 bases and aboard Navy ships, gauged
the troops' experiences under the Clinton administration's
controversial ``don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue'' policy that
was inaugurated in 1993 to enable homosexuals to serve more freely
in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The report said 80 percent of the respondents ``stated that they
had heard offensive speech, derogatory names, jokes or remarks
about homosexuals in the last 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   It also found that 85 percent said they believed ``such comments
were tolerated to some extent.'' Of those surveyed 37 percent
``responded that they had witnessed or experienced an event or
behavior toward a service member that they considered to be
harassment based on perceived homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of those surveyed, 57 percent, said they had ``not
had training'' in connection with the Pentagon's policy of
tolerance toward homosexuals. But 78 percent said they would ``feel
free to report harassment of perceived homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in telling reporters about the new panel he had
created, Cohen said, ``The incidents and use of abusive language
(against suspected gay and lesbian troops) are more widespread than
I anticipated. I was surprised at the numbers of people who said
they saw some evidence of harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Benecke, co-executive director of the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Network, said of the report's findings, ``We have
told the Pentagon for six years that harassment and abuse are a
serious problem. I'm glad the Pentagon has finally acknowledged it.
But the key to stopping harassment is leadership and
accountability. We hope this oversight committee is not a
substitute.'' Cohen said a major responsibility of the oversight
panel will be to ensure that all military personnel, from troops to
commanders, are versed in new Pentagon anti-harassment guidelines
issued last month. The guidelines are aimed at making sure the
administration policy on gays in the military is followed. The
policy allows homosexuals to serve as long as they keep quiet about
their sexual orientation and don't engage in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   The policy also is designed to ensure that troops who are
harassed can complain to their commanders without fear of setting
in motion an investigation into their sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen ordered the survey of the bases in the wake of the murder
last July of an Army recruit at Ft. Campbell, Ky., who was
suspected of being gay.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Army Pvt. Calvin Glover, 19, was sentenced to life
in prison for murdering the recruit, Pvt. Barry Winchell, 21, with
a baseball bat. During Glover's trial, soldiers testified that
Winchell was regularly taunted with anti-gay slurs and that
superiors did not intervene when he complained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
