<HEADER>
A7046 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-OPEC-SQUEEZED-ECONOMI     03-24 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-SQUEEZED-ECONOMIST-800&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC APPEARS IN CONTROL OF OIL MARKETS. APPEARANCES DECEIVE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for March 27 OPEC meeting, Vienna)   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 325 words; 1,225 uncut)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oil has become a volatile substance. The world is producing
about 75 million barrels a day (b/d) of the stuff; it is consuming
about 77m b/d.
</P>
<P>
   Sustained over a year, such a slim difference, less than the
consumption of South Korea, has trebled oil prices, to around $30 a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody likes it that way. Producers and consumers alike speak of
their desire for stable oil prices. Yet only in times of war or
revolution has the price been wilder. Which is one reason why, as
OPEC gathers for its annual meeting in Vienna on March 27, the
hardest question is what will happen next.
</P>
<P>
   Against all expectations, OPEC holds most of the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Low oil prices nearly bankrupted many producers two years ago,
as the revenues of the producers' cartel plunged by more than $50
billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the collusion of Mexico and Norway, neither of them
members of OPEC, Saudi Arabia arranged a concerted round of
production cuts. These are up for review in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is every sign that the producers will agree to
some rise in output, only last-minute wrangling will decide exactly
how much extra oil is produced and when. And much hangs on those
devilish details.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty arises not just because the cartel is secretive,
and its members are unruly. The real wild card is inscrutable Saudi
Arabia, which, with 2 million-3 million b/d of spare capacity, half
of the OPEC total, dominates the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   Though it might seem that the current bonanza should have made
life easy for the world's biggest oil producer, stratospheric oil
prices have actually put the Saudis in an uncomfortable position.
They are caught between forces tugging in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   From outside the cartel, consumers are clamoring for lower
prices. Within it, members want high prices.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure from consuming countries to raise output, so as to
bring prices down quickly, is strong. The shortfall has greatly
depleted global oil stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The International Energy Agency (IEA), a quasi-governmental body
representing consuming economies, reckons that OPEC must increase
production by 2.3 million b/d if oil stocks are to return to the
average level of 1990-96. If not, say analysts, prices could go
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for alarm is that high oil prices inflict pain on
consuming economies in so many nasty ways, ranging from higher
inflation to deteriorating terms of trade and a decline in
international competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which is the world's biggest oil importer, is
screaming bloody murder.
</P>
<P>
   Economists are worried that inflation, which is so far rising
only because of the oil price, might next develop its own momentum.
This means more interest-rate increases after this week's, perhaps
tipping the economy into eventual recession.
</P>
<P>
   America's trade deficit soared to a record $28 billion in
January _ $8 billion of which was spent importing oil, nearly
double the figure of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are outraged at higher prices for gasoline, and
American politicians are rising to the occasion. American antitrust
officials are looking at whether the OPEC cartel has violated
domestic competition laws.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, America's energy secretary, has been shuttling
between OPEC capitals trying to persuade producers into agreeing
``a sizeable increase in production as soon as possible _ in the
second quarter, in April.'' In other words, now.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Saudis are facing strong internal
pressure from a number of OPEC countries, such as Libya, Algeria
and Iran, that want little or no change in production.
</P>
<P>
   Some are hawks who see nothing wrong with oil at $30 a barrel,
the consumer be damned. Others are already producing close to the
limits of their capacity, and so see little benefit in raising
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget what insiders like to call ``the ghost of
Jakarta.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartel's most recent decision to raise output was taken, at
Saudi urging, at a meeting in Indonesia on the eve of the Asian
financial crisis. The subsequent collapse in prices is still fresh
in the minds of most OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
   The big international oil firms remember $10 oil too. Judging by
past behavior, months of $25-30 oil prices should have boosted
their spending on exploration and production; not this time though.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Moody-Stuart, the boss of Royal Dutch/Shell, accepts that
``it doesn't take a brave man to predict oil prices above $20 for
2000,'' but he still wants only investments such that ``they fly at
$14 a barrel, and we can sleep easy in our beds at $10.''
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that world demand for oil is anyway likely to drop
sharply in the second quarter of this year. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 800) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shokri Ghanem of OPEC's secretariat points to average figures
over the 1990s suggesting that, as the northern hemisphere's winter
ends, global oil demand declines by about 2.7 million b/d.
</P>
<P>
   So, he argues, raising output by, say, today's 2 million b/d
shortfall would flood the market with too much oil. Prices would
once again collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Most market-watchers strongly disagree. Pointing to the sharp
rebound in Asia and to suppressed first-quarter demand, the IEA
reckons that this year's second-quarter decline will be only 1.5
million b/d. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Global Energy Studies, a consultancy, thinks that
fears of a seasonal downturn are ``entirely misplaced.'' It
observes that American firms did not build oil stocks sufficiently
during the winter. To meet the demands of the spring and summer,
they must now do so at breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even a big OPEC output rise may not prevent sporadic
shortages and price shocks at American gas stations this summer,
since it takes five or six weeks for oil to travel from the Persian
Gulf to America's East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The American government's Energy Information Agency is already
warning that oil prices may spike ``to unprecedented levels.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,000, OR CONTINUE TO 1,225) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   In short, the Saudis face an unenviable choice. They know from
painful experience that OPEC is fragile and ill-disciplined, and
that they must not ``betray'' their brethren in the cartel by
simply yielding to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they also know that they must not test America's patience
too far.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia may have the oil, but America has two other weapons
that the Saudis cannot ignore: military and economic might. Even
oil producers need the American economy to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Given these diametrically opposed forces, what will Saudi Arabia
do? The opaque murmurs from Riyadh suggest that the kingdom wants
to see a more stable oil market. Some sort of compromise production
increase, of 1 million-1.5 million b/d, seems the most likely
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is decided in Vienna, Euan Baird, head of Schlumberger,
a giant oil-services firm with eyes and ears everywhere, believes
that ultimately ``Saudi Arabia wants $25 oil, and it will get it...
but it will take them a few iterations and overshoots to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the past 18 months offer a different lesson. Decreeing
stability is a mug's game. OPEC's attempts to adjust the price by
nudging output resulted in oil veering down to $10 and back up to
$30.
</P>
<P>
   Americans had better prepare for a long, hot summer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
