<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7052 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-HEPBURN-SPI &LR;      03-24 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HEPBURN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISINGLY, `AUDREY HEPBURN STORY' HAS CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Especially on the day after the Oscars, it's almost impossible
to visualize the finespun Audrey Hepburn while gazing upon the
robust Jennifer Love Hewitt. Camera tricks and acres of fabric can
only do so much. Moreover, Hewitt's spirited attempt to capture
Hepburn's accent, a challenging mix of English, Dutch and Belgian,
is a persistent obstacle to thoroughly enjoying ``The Audrey
Hepburn Story,'' which airs Monday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   It's not so bad. Good enough, certainly, to carry three hours in
prime time, and so much more polished than standard TV-movie fare
that Hewitt, who turned 21 last month, might have a future as a
producer.
</P>
<P>
   As a performer, the telegenic teen who rode a supporting role in
``Party of Five'' to pop-culture stardom and her own Fox series,
``Time of Your Life,'' will never possess Hepburn's alluring je ne
sais quoi. Call it luminescence or sparkle, glimmer or glamour.
It's not there. When Hepburn opened those enormous eyes and arched
her impossibly long neck, it was screen magic. Men forgot about the
overstuffed and underupholstered Jane Russells of the day, at least
temporarily, and women enviously copied the Hepburn style: the
short hair, the fabulous posture, the casual elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who is squinty-eyed by nature, bears a slight facial
resemblance to the late movie star, but her loving portrayal,
perhaps invevitably, smacks of the ``historical re-enactment''
footage we see so often on televised biography specials.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' is a classy production.
Bouquets go to Marsha Norman's script, which gives the viewer
credit for being smarter than a potato (couch or otherwise), and to
Steven Robman's direction, which moves artfully, even playfully,
back and forth among significant moments in Hepburn's fascinating
life.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who won a Pulitzer Prize for her play ``'Night,
Mother,'' wisely keeps Hewitt's Hepburn from having to deliver
soliloquies. Robman, a veteran of dozens of dramatic series, knows
how to set the hook to keep viewers coming back after the
commercials. (In a three-hour block of prime time, that's about 45
minutes worth of commercial time.)
</P>
<P>
   Hepburn, a paragon of '50s style and grace, is Hewitt's idol _
``the one woman that I think was everything a woman should be,''
she has gushed. As co-executive producer of this affectionate
portrait, Hewitt helped shape more than her own performance.
</P>
<P>
   She says her first exposure to Hepburn was as a young girl, when
she watched a tape of ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' with her mother.
No surprise, then, to see Robman use a recreation of the 1961 film
_ and its Oscar-winning theme song, ``Moon River'' _ as framework
for this tale of a gifted, complex woman who initially didn't grasp
the enormous impact she had on people. Not unlike Holly Golightly
in Truman Capote's story, if you'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt gamely tries to capture the enigmatic essence of Hepburn,
an indescribable quality movie buffs have loved for 50 years (as
evidenced by the many Web shrines still fawning over the woman, who
died of colon cancer in 1993.) Hewitt is more successful when
deferring to a distinguished supporting cast, which delivers enough
of a backup boost to save the film from being just another cheesy
prime-time romp.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Fisher plays Hepburn's long-suffering mother, a Dutch
baroness treated poorly by circumstance and spouse. She is the
embodiment of noble, if sometimes misguided, maternal devotion
during difficult times in the 1930s and '40s and the seemingly
charmed times afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Keir Dullea, as the reluctant father who abandons his family on
the eve of World War II, also hits a very precise target with
minimal screen time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her father's apparent rejection of all parental
obligation, Hepburn's desire to know him, a Nazi sympathizer
interned in England during the war, provides sufficient dramatic
underpinning to make ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' more substantial
than, say, a box of Junior Mints. It's a good device, though a
better choice might have been to extend the story past 1961, the
year ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' was released. Hepburn went into
semi-retirement after that to raise a family and devote time to
humanitarian causes, but the film only deals with these milestones
in a postscript. The effect, intentional or not, is to celebrate
the superficial while diminishing the significant.
</P>
<P>
   But for what it is, Hewitt can take some satisfaction in knowing
that ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' isn't an embarrassment. That,
more than anything, may be the highest praise because Hepburn, at
least according to this portrayal, always seemed most concerned not
with her own stardom but with not causing her family, friends and
loved ones undue distress.
</P>
<P>
   The Audrey Hepburn Story. Three-hour TV movie about the
Oscar-winning actress. Starring Jennifer Love Hewitt, Frances
Fisher, Eric McCormack, Keir Dullea, Peter Giles, Sarah Hyland and
Emmy Rossum. Monday night on ABC. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1705EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0192 </DOCNO>
