<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BEER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLUSION AMONG BREWERIES? EUROPEAN REGULATORS LAUNCH
INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In France they like their Kronenbourg, in Italy their
Peroni and in Holland Heineken.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans are clearly hooked on regional beer brands, but
European antitrust regulators want to know whether this is a result
of beer drinking traditions or of subtle cartel arrangements among
breweries.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, European investigators made surprise visits to
some of the Continent's major breweries, arriving unannounced to
examine documents in the Netherlands at the Dutch brewers Grolsch
and Bavaria and at Heineken's offices and in Italy, at the Italian
offices of Carlsberg SA of Denmark, and at the Italian brewer
Peroni SpA.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into whether the breweries are abusing their
dominant national positions was begun last July when the chief
antitrust regulator at the time, Karel Van Miert, himself a
Belgian, ordered investigators to seize documents at Interbrew, the
Belgian brewery that makes the national favorite, Stella Artois.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Monti, who succeeded Van Miert last year, has taken an
aggressive position in his six months on the job toward the effects
that Europe's continued market fragmentation has on competition.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the offices of brewers in Belgium were again
entered, and in January the two market leaders in France, the
Kronenbourg beer division of the big Danone food group and
Heineken's French unit, also received surprise visits from
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   France provides an illustration of the cozy relationships that
make regulators suspicious. Seventy percent of the French beer
market is controlled by two breweries _ Kronenbourg, the market
leader with 40 percent, and Heineken, No. 2 with 30 percent. Many
European countries have beer markets similarly divided between a
local champion and one or more major international brewers, and
regulators want to know whether the companies coordinate their
strategies to abuse their dominant positions.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials deny this. ``Without any doubt, we are
confident of the successful outcome of the investigation,'' said
Michael Berssenbrugge, the spokesman for Heineken in Amsterdam,
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Beer is not the only beverage European regulators are
scrutinizing over pricing practices. They have also been tough on
Coca-Cola Co. and its European bottlers. Last December Italian
antitrust authorities fined Coca-Cola $16 million after determining
that the company's discounts to selected retailers were unfair. And
in unannounced visits last July similar to those on the beer
companies, European regulators have examined Coca-Cola's pricing
practices in Austria, Denmark and Germany. The company has denied
any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts seemed puzzled by the aggressiveness of the
beer investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive world,'' said Iain Wilson, a beer
industry analyst for ABN Amro in Amsterdam, noting that while
Heineken controls roughly half the domestic Dutch market, it faces
bitter competition from three smaller breweries.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, modest levels of profitability and an oversupply of
European breweries have helped to accelerate the process of
consolidation. Heineken recently acquired breweries in Poland and
Spain; this week the British brewer, Scottish &AMP; Newcastle PLC,
announced it would pay $2.6 billion to acquire Kronenbourg from
Danone.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, consolidation among European food retailers is
creating giants like Tesco, Britain's No. 1 supermarket chain, and
Carrefour of France, whose proposed merger with another French
retailer, Promodes, would make it the largest retailer in Europe
and the second largest worldwide after Wal-Mart. Increasingly, the
breweries complain, these giants are dictating conditions to
European food and beverage companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
