   &UR; PROMISING GREECE GIVES INVESTORS HOPE FOR `EMERGING EUROPE' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `OPA!'-GREEK-ECONOMY-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple thousand years after Greece supplied a name for the
continent, Europe is about to return the favor. Next year, when the
euro likely replaces the Greek drachma, the European Central Bank
will effectively rule the Greek economy, ending a history of
inflation and financial chaos. Having tamed its Trojan-Horse
economy, Greece is ready to gallop towards an ``emerging
Europe.''...By Todd G. Buchholz, ``Worth'' magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT PAYS TO PLOD: A HARE-AND-TORTOISE RACE TO RETIREMENT
WEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BONUS-401(K)-900&AMP;SIDEBAR-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retirement savers have enjoyed a pretty good run lately _
probably even better than they think. Or so I concluded after
studying the performance of 24 leading mutual funds used in 401(k)
plans. Most investors collected a nice ``installment bonus'' on
their 401(k)-plan investments. Not because they invested
brilliantly but because they invested methodically, making regular
tax-deductible contributions....By Scott Burns, ``Worth'' magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: This 900-word story offers a SIDEBAR comparing the
even-better-than-advertised returns of 24 top 401(k) mutual funds) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: To learn more about the bonus that comes from
investing on the installment plan, see Scott Burns' previous
article, ``The Molehill-to-Mountain Myth of Retirement Savings,''
(below) from the February ``Worth.'' Story slugged
BC-BADNEWS-BOOMER-MATH-WORTH.) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MOLEHILL-TO-MOUNTAIN MYTH OF RETIREMENT SAVINGS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BADNEWS-BOOMER-MATH-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allow me to introduce the Installment Effect. That's my name for
what happens to investments when they're made or changed in
installments. Understanding the effect can mean the difference
between a well-financed old age and one that has you filling out a
job application at Wal-Mart at 84....By Scott Burns, ``Worth''
magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 375 words; 1,375 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: Cross-reference with story slugged
BC-BONUS-401(K)-900&AMP;SIDEBAR-WORTH (above), ``It Pays to Plod: A
Hare-and-Tortoise Race to Retirement Wealth.'') &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AOL-TIME WARNER'S MAIDS OF HONOR CAUGHT THE BOUQUET &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AOL-TIMEWARNER-`BOUNCE'-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 10, Time Warner shareholders from Ted Turner on down
were high-fiving one another as they watched their stock soar 39
percent, to $90 a share, after America Online announced it planned
to acquire the media giant. But they weren't the only investors
celebrating. That same day, frenetic trading drove the stock prices
of Time Warner rivals up an average of 14 percent....By Nick
Pachetti, ``Worth'' magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Columbus and San Diego _ note 3rd graf) &QL;
</P>
