<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-AIDA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSY `AIDA' LATEST DISNEY POP MUSICAL TO HIT BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFREY ERIC JENKINS  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An iron triangle has formed in the Broadway theater.
But it has nothing to do with presidential policy-making or John
McCain's loathed Washington lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   It is the rough geometric shape formed when you draw a line
between the New Amsterdam, the Lunt-Fontanne and the Palace
theaters in the Broadway district. With the opening of the Elton
John and Tim Rice musical, ``Aida,'' at the Palace last Thursday,
joining ``Beauty and the Beast'' at Lunt-Fontanne and ``The Lion
King'' at the New Amsterdam, the ``wonderful world of Disney'' has
staked its claim to the heart of American commercial theater. (Or,
as some might suggest, driven another stake into its heart.)
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Elaborate Lives'' in its first incarnation at Atlanta's
Alliance Theatre, the pop musical has been beset with weird
technical problems during development and seemed to have generated
a ``curse of the pharaohs.'' After a failed pyramid effect became
the big story from the Atlanta production, the company fired most
of the creative team.
</P>
<P>
   The directorial reins of the show were handed to Robert Falls,
the artistic wizard behind numerous reclamations of plays by
Tennessee Williams, Arthur Miller and Eugene O'Neill for Chicago's
Goodman Theatre. He had directed plays for Broadway before _ his
production of ``Death of a Salesman'' won four Tony Awards last
year _ but his work with musicals had been limited. Falls also
teamed with Tony Award-winning playwright David Henry Hwang to
polish the book written by Linda Woolverton.
</P>
<P>
   Stunningly reconceived by designer Bob Crowley, the revised
production moved to Chicago for a pre-Broadway run with the new
title of ``Aida.'' At the second preview performance, though, Aida
(Heather Headley) and her lover, Radames (Adam Pascal), tumbled out
of a box-like tomb and fell 10 to 15 feet as the set piece rose
from the stage. The actors suffered only minor injuries and a few
shows were cancelled, but the rising-tomb bit was cut.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Verdi's opera, the current Disney production is the
tale of a Nubian princess who is captured and enslaved by an
Egyptian soldier, Radames. Radames then gives his new slave to
Amneris (Sherie Rene, the Egyptian princess to whom he is
betrothed. Amneris finds the new slave to her liking and becomes
fast friends with her. But Radames also takes a shine to the
willful, adventurous Aida and troubles ensue.
</P>
<P>
   Trying desperately to be many things to many people, ``Aida''
succeeds only marginally. The musical cannot decide if it wants to
be a tragic love story _ it is not _ a wise-cracking cartoon or an
anti-imperialist tract, which is ironic when you consider Disney's
omnivorous corporate appetites.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say, however, that Aida herself fails to please.
Headley's rich, powerful voice demonstrates that she is up to the
few challenges lurking in Elton John's accessible score. When it
comes to the big musical finish, the composer writes up to her
level and Headley soars beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the same cannot be said for Pascal, an avowed pop
singer who nonetheless keeps working in musical theater. (He was in
the original production of ``Rent.'') While he admittedly looks
good without his shirt, Pascal's acting is mostly noble attitude.
His singing relies on the raspy, fluttery sound that has helped
Michael Bolton and his ilk to sell millions of records _ but it
grates on ears listening for a sweet sound.
</P>
<P>
   There are pleasures in the score, but they tend to be the joys
of nostalgia. In the song ``Elaborate Lives,'' classic John
percussive riffs _ reminiscent of the ``Yellow Brick Road'' era _
carry along Rice's flaccid top-40 lyrics. Indeed, there are moments
when the lyric rhythms echo another Rice musical, ``Jesus Christ
Superstar'' (cowritten with Andrew Lloyd Webber, it reopens on
Broadway in April).
</P>
<P>
   John writes in a variety of styles, but always with an ear tuned
to the pop charts. In ``My Strongest Suit,'' a 1960s girl-group
celebration, Amneris leads a bizarro-world fashion show complete
with catwalk and glam geometric headgear of pyramids, triangles and
cubes _ all of it designed and sewn by the princess' new best
slave, Aida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Pyramid'' features an easy-listening reggae beat that
morphs into a kitschy production number about employing architects
to build a tomb that will house the corpse of a dying pharaoh. In
the ancient economy, royal death is good for the construction
business.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers performed by the enslaved Nubians display African
musical roots. ``The Dance of the Robe'' succeeds on the strength
of its performers immersion in Wayne Cilento's choreography _ which
otherwise fails to inspire. ``The Gods Love Nubia'' is a rousing
spiritual number bound to bring to mind the work of Lebo M, a
collaborator (as were John and Rice) on ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a pretty safe bet, though, that a musical has serious
problems when you leave the theater humming the set changes.
Designer Crowley _ whose only slips include costuming the pharaoh's
ministers in heavy frock coats and making Pharaoh's headdress looks
like a bottle of champagne chilling in a bucket of ice _ diverts
our attention from otherwise lackluster proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In one splendid touch, Crowley uses a backdrop that serves as a
location where Nubian women wash clothes. The river is a zigzag
stripe of deep blue with rich red banks on either side and trees
off in the distance. When the forbidden lovers confront and accept
their feelings for one another, the life-altering moment is
reinforced as the drop is dreamily inverted. It is a lovely image
that shows their world turned upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you look in ``Aida,'' designer Crowley employs
geometric imagery: cubes, squares, pyramids, triangles. But it
isn't geometry that most concerns Disney, it's math. Can ``Aida''
be buoyed along by Elton John fans in the same way that Frank
Wildhorn's ``Jekyll and Hyde'' bubbles along? Is the third time a
charm for the troubled production?
</P>
<P>
   If Disney gets its way, Broadway's iron triangle will turn to
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Aida. Music by Elton John, lyrics by Tim Rice; book by Linda
Woolverton, Robert Falls and David Henry Hwang. Palace Theatre,
1564 Broadway (at 47th Street), New York City. Opened March 23.
Open run. Tickets $20-80; 800-755-4000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
