<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GREAT-DAMES-$ADV26-10     03-24 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREAT-DAMES-$ADV26-1000-TRIM(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOTHING LIKE A DAME, AND SHE'S ON A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, March 26)  
(jt) 
 By MARIE BRENNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A scene from a reporter's notebook, winter 1993.
There is a storm of biblical proportions and I am on my way to
interview Kitty Carlisle Hart, who clowned with the Marx brothers
and became the chairwoman of the New York State Council on the
Arts. We are to tour the boroughs; Mrs. Hart is off to visit
struggling theater companies and ballerinas in Brooklyn. The
airports have closed, and out my window in the early morning I see
herculean rain. Mrs. Hart is snappish with me on the telephone when
I call, in the hope that she will cancel. ``We never let the
weather slow us down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I arrive drenched and wilted, to be greeted by Mrs. Hart in a
lavender Ultrasuede raincoat with matching fur-trimmed boots. Her
raven hair is impeccable, and her ebullience has returned. ``Oh,
you are such a dear to come out on such a day!'' All day long, I
raced to keep up the pace. It was imperative that I not lag behind,
she told me. That night, she had 100 guests coming to her house to
greet Gov. Mario Cuomo. She was then 86 years old, the very image
of a great dame.
</P>
<P>
   Great dames _ flamboyant diva-women, who came of age before
1960s feminism _ are never defeated by their circumstances.
Tenacity, flair and fun are the traits that define them. They were
reared in an era of limited expectations, when graduate schools and
careers were often closed to them. Good manners, manicures, pearls
and high heels were the disguises they wore to hide their mettle.
Auntie Mame is the prototype, with her arch double entendres and
live-live-live philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   When I started interviewing great dames a decade ago, I viewed
them as pieces of history: Clare Boothe Luce, Pamela Harriman,
Constance Baker Motley, who tried Brown vs. Board of Education with
Thurgood Marshall. I wanted to chronicle their struggles and
astonishing survival skills in spite of their having been reared in
a world whose underpinnings were still Victorian.
</P>
<P>
   The first great dame I ever knew was my mother, Thelma Brenner.
For years, I ridiculed her dressing rituals, her need to lay out
her clothes, shoes, jewelry and scarves on the bed hours before she
dressed. I was a noisy rebel, a member of the class of '71 with the
overknowing views of my generation of young feminists. And I wore
that uniform: black turtleneck, torn jeans, long hair. My style
icon was Joan Baez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to look put together,'' my mother would tell me when I
compared her preparations to the Normandy invasion. Like the term
``great dame,'' ``put together'' is a phrase with implications.
Loretta Young twirling into our living rooms wearing chiffon and an
actressy smile. Rosalind Russell and Irene Dunne. ``Put together''
was a metaphor for an entire generation that believed in beating
back the demons by whistling in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was, I loved watching my mother dress. And now I hear
my fellow travelers of '70s feminism wondering if it was really
wise to have worked so hard. Our slob-style is long over; we are
back in suits, comparing notes on designer sales, sounding so much
like my mother and her friends. ``I am afraid our generation's
beatnik values have gone the way of the dodo bird,'' said Judith
Thurman, the biographer of Colette and Isak Dinesen.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and I used to dismiss the great dames as phonies who
needed, in most cases, a powerful man for their ascent. But right
on schedule, about the time I noticed the first lines on my brow, I
no longer viewed the dames as sacred monsters. Where once I saw the
brass and the facade, I began to see the endurance.
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to me that the great dames could become role
models for women in their 20s and 30s until just the other day,
when there it was: ``Putting it together,'' read the headline in a
fashion magazine. And suddenly, embraced by the downtown club set,
here are Babe Paley buds and Pamela Harriman clones, wearing suits
and pearls.
</P>
<P>
   They're everywhere, these new would-be great dames, born
sometime during the day-glo '60s or the Nixon administration, now
out in force in all-Manolo all the time. As in the '20s, the riffle
in a culture is often first seen in clothes. Inside the Conde Nast
offices editors are assigning variations on the theme of ``the new
formality.'' ``It's time perhaps for Tipper Gore, a nice family
girl who wears St. John Knits,'' said Anna Wintour, Vogue's editor
in chief.
</P>
<P>
   The new dames look at their mothers _ the '70s generation and
the '80s shoulder-pad brigade _ and see complete exhaustion. ``We
are the post-have-it-all generation and it doesn't look pretty,''
said Holly Peterson, an editor at Talk magazine. ``It doesn't look
pretty to drag in from the office without mascara, and look
frazzled at a party, never have sex and want to divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Ms. Peterson confided, she threw out her ``young Brown
feminist'' wardrobe of pleated pants, Shetlands and Tretorn
sneakers for a fur-collared sweater and a single pair of Manolo
Blahniks, the same look Lauren Bacall had in the 1953 classic great
dame epic, ``How to Marry a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The novelist Erica Jong has noticed this phenomenon as well.
``Suddenly, the courtesan, the woman who knows how to manipulate
men, is seen as a role model,'' she said. ``Young women want to be
seen as mythic figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jong, who is the mother of 21-year-old Molly Jong-Fast, a
novelist, has observed her daughter's friends. ``Molly will say to
me, `You were very foolish to do it all without a man.' She says,
`I want a career, but I want a man backing me up.'''
</P>
<P>
   The new dames marry younger, with bridal parties that seem to
echo Queen Elizabeth's. They attend Edwardian fancy dress balls at
the Frick Museum in tiers of see-through lace and satin, their
escorts in black top hats. Their biography of choice is Amanda
Foreman's ``Georgiana, Duchess of Devonshire,'' read for strategy
tips. Like the Duchess of Windsor, they invest in Verdura brooches
and pose on the cover of Quest magazine, promoting Palm Beach in
Lily Pulitzers the color of Key lime pie.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the new dames are sending a terse message to my
generation: They do not want to run their houses and children from
a cell phone. They have learned from our stressed-out example that
you cannot do it all. Marina Rust, a young novelist and
great-dame-to-be, said: ``This is a reaction against choices our
parents made. It's not about being Sandra Day O'Connor versus Babe
Paley.''
</P>
<P>
   The cultural historian Ann Douglas calls this period of American
life ``a serious retro time'' in which there are obvious echoes
from the '50s, the '20s and even the gilded 1880s. ``Of course, it
has to do with how much money is around,'' Ms. Douglas said, but
she noted the lack of reform movements that the previous flush eras
of American life spawned. ``In the 1880s, there were Victoria
Woodhull and Emma Willard. In the 1920s, the country was engulfed
by protests, Sacco and Vanzetti, the unions, the Scottsboro Boys.
In the 1950s, we worried about the bomb and the cold war. Now, the
political edge and the feminist edge are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The original great dames flourished in an atmosphere of grand
social purpose, as understood at the Alsop Georgetown dinners. They
could, to a woman, speak knowingly of public policy, civil rights
and cold war politics. They were as ambitious as corporate raiders
and they were determined to move up in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Before she walked into the segregated courtroom in Jackson,
Miss., in 1949, Constance Baker Motley spent a day at Lord &AMP; Taylor
searching for exactly the right dress. She was one of the first
black lawyers to appear in court in the Deep South. She used her
chic to rebuke the mural that decorated the courtroom walls: slaves
hoisting cotton bales on one side, white girls in white crinolines
on another. The politically active Marietta Tree liked to dress
like a torch singer in her '70s, but she used her earlier allure to
convince John Lindsay, then the mayor of New York, to light the
city's bridges, and in the last decades of her life she became a
city planner and designed urban projects in St. Louis and San
Antonio. Pamela Harriman started off as a courtesan with creamy
shoulders and was called ``the red-haired tart'' when she married
the son of Winston Churchill. But in her 60s, still with her creamy
shoulders, she had become a power in the Democratic party and
ambassador to France. When she died, President Clinton gave her
eulogy at the National Cathedral and celebrated her for helping him
win the White House. ``Today, I am here in no small measure because
of her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate lesson of these formidable women is endurance, and
the true test of the arc of their lives is revealed in the flourish
of Act III. Can the new dames live up to this legacy? At this
moment, I am looking at an invitation for the Bunny Hop, a
children's party to benefit the pediatrics department of Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center. It is 2000, women are in the
boardrooms and in surgeon's scrubs, yet the benefit committee,
young matrons of the city, are almost all listed by their husbands'
names _ Mrs. Thomas Glover, Mrs. Roger P. Griswold, Mrs. Anthony
Addison _ as if they are marooned in a John O'Hara world.
</P>
<P>
   Is the retro impulse limited only to the rich? Out on the
campaign trail, Karenna Gore Schiff is picking up a parallel
concern. ``I have noticed many young women are expressing anxiety
about the possibility of working and spending any real time with
their families,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In my years in the feminist sorority, remarks like this would
have you blackballed from the club. What we lacked in our first
acts in style, we like to flatter ourselves, we made up for in
substance. But dame-ism, whether in Act I, II or III, is about a
marriage of style and substance. Once, I asked Mrs. Hart to
demonstrate her exercise routine for me. She did so without
hesitation, dropping to the floor and executing a perfect set of
leg lifts in a robe trimmed with marabou. ``Who were we to start
with?'' Mrs. Hart said to me that day. ``We knew that in life, it
all comes down to discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, great dame-ism is a matter of unquenchable spirit.
Those new dames who aspire to great dame-ness would do well to wear
the Manolo Blahniks, but not to throw away the tennis shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
