<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, `AND THE WINNER IS...VLADIMIR PUTIN.' (ACT SURPRISED) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN-CORONATION-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even by old Soviet election standards, it has not been much of a
contest. Only the scale of Acting President Vladimir Putin's
victory Sunday is in doubt. Indeed, the most significant feature of
the election is not the railroaded result but the comprehensive way
in which the Kremlin has controlled the campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in The Economist's March 25 issue) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORIS BEREZOVSKY: KREMLIN PUPPETEER OR FUTURE PUTIN VICTIM? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORIS-BEREZOVSKY-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Boris Berezovsky, Russia's oligarch-extraordinaire, see out
the year in jail, exile or the comfortable nook between business
and government that he currently occupies? The answer will give a
clear sign of where the country is headed under Vladimir Putin, who
is set to be elected president on March 26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in The Economist's March 25 issue) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 650 words; 1,000 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S `VLADIMIR THE CLEANSER' IN IVAN THE TERRIBLE'S TOWN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-IVAN-TERRIBLE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOLOMNA _ Workers at Vladimir Putin's campaign headquarters in
Kolomna are so confident of success in the Russian presidential
election Sunday that they do not even have a picture of their
candidate on the wall. In Kolomna _ once Ivan the Terrible's
favorite town _ Putin is seen as the man who will clean up the mess
left by President Boris Yeltsin. Although how exactly he will do
that is, like the man himself, a mystery....By Patrick Cockburn,
The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN OPPONENTS COMPETE ON `WHO WANTS TO BE A MILLIONAIRE?' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN-REGIS-GAMESHOW-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If you think America has a bizarre way of electing its
presidents, check out Russia. Desperate for attention in an
election campaign dominated by Kremlin heir-apparent Vladimir
Putin, four of the other 11 candidates took part Saturday night in
the Russian version of the hit TV program, ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire?''...By Phil Reeves, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Monday, March 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 700 words; 975 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAMFILOVA: RUSSIA'S FIRST WOMAN PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEMALE-PUTIN-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In this weekend's upcoming presidential elections,
Russians will finally have a woman for whom they can vote. She is a
liberal reformer and former social affairs minister, 46-year-old
Ella Pamfilova. If she won the Kremlin, Pamfilova would be the
first woman to rule Russia since the Empress Catherine the
Great...By Helen Womack, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Monday, March 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN: SPOOKY PAST. RUSSIA: SCARY FUTURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-MYSTERY-MAN-ECONOMIST-775&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Vladimir Putin, Russia's acting president, seems a
strong, determined man, supported since parliamentary elections in
December by a fairly robust majority in the Duma, and standing an
almost inevitable chance of being elected in Russia's popular vote
March 26. So, then, is Putin just what the Russian doctor ordered?
Not so fast. Most of the significant things that Putin has done,
both in his short career as a political leader and in his longer
career as a spy, have been scary...By The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in The Economist's Jan. 8 issue) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 150-word optional trim at 775; 950 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VLADIMIR PUTIN: RUSSIA'S POST-COLD WARRIOR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THREE-FACES-PUTIN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Spies are good at concealing their motives.
Presumably Vladimir Putin, acting president of Russia since Jan. 1,
most of whose working life has been spent with the KGB, is no
exception. Does he come to power with the bottled-up energies of a
hitherto frustrated reformer, determined to take Russia into
Europe? Or does his heart lie in the paranoid, ruthless old world
of the Cold-War Soviet security services? Or is he in reality a
Kremlin insider, a crafty new-Russian power-broker who revels in
sleaze and arm-twisting? Any one of these three faces could be the
real Putin, the other two just political disguises...By The
Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in The Economist's Jan. 8 issue) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,025 words) &QL; 
