<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Saturday, March 25, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-DEPOT-FOUNDER _ Home Depot said Friday that Ron Brill,
executive vice president and one of the company's founders, will
retire next March. Brill was instrumental in the growth of the
Atlanta-based retailer from its earliest days, including finding
the money to finance its launch. He has held the positions of
controller, vice president of finance, treasurer, executive vice
president and chief financial officer and currently, chief
administrative officer. Brill's responsibilities for legal, loss
prevention, internal audit and investor relations will be
reassigned to other executives by March 2001. (Bond-Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).10.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-MOMS _ A new study confirms what many career-minded
working moms already know: you pay a heavy price at home for having
a good relationship with your boss. (Joyner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TEXTILE _The ``Norma Rae syndrome'' is hurting enrollment at
area textile colleges. Dwindling apparel manufacturing in the U.S.,
coupled with high-profile mill closings, is sending students
flocking to other disciplines. Most of the growth in the textile
industry is coming through industrial and technical applications,
but students (and their parents) are stuck with the misperception
that textile equals apparel. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
