<HEADER>
A7072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-VETERANS25-COX     03-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COHEN SAYS PROMISE OF VETERANS' HEALTH CARE WILL BE KEPT
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Providing lifelong health care that older veterans
were promised if they made military service a career is a ``moral
obligation'' that the Pentagon will keep, Defense Secretary William
Cohen said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The spreading unhappiness among retired members of the the Army,
Air Force, Navy, Marines and Coast Guard over not receiving health
care promised by recruiters may undermine recruitment in the modern
military, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we tell the people who are coming in that when we make
a commitment, we are going to keep it?'' Cohen said. ``Some of the
retirees are saying to potential recruits, 'Don't join because they
won't take care of you and your family.' That can have a major
impact on recruitment.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he indicated that the Defense Department would continue
to oppose a class-action lawsuit claiming the government has failed
to live up to a legally binding contract by not providing the
health care.
</P>
<P>
   In a breakfast meeting with reporters, Cohen said he was working
with chairmen of the House and Senate appropriations committees to
come up with funds to pay for the promised care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very expensive, but it's a moral obligation
and we intend to meet that obligation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon lawyers acknowledge that recruiters told young men and
women entering the military before June 1956 that a military career
would earn them free health care at military hospitals for them and
their families for life.
</P>
<P>
   The government says that without authorization from Congress,
the promises did not constitute enforceable contracts, and at least
two federal judges have agreed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for an organization that has spearheaded the
campaign to get the promised health care for retirees said
veterans' groups will lobby to support the Pentagon's request for
funds to provide the care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree wholeheartedly with the secretary,'' said Jay Bapple,
associate legislative counsel of the National Association for the
Uniformed Services. ``We wish he had been able to persuade the
president to put it in the budget. We'll support the secretary when
he goes back to Congress and asks for these funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of base closings, many military hospitals where the free
care was to be provided no longer exist, and retirees have been
shifted to the Defense Department's Tricare program, which requires
its beneficiaries to pay a portion of their medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   When retirees reach 65, they are enrolled in Medicare and
dropped from Tricare. If they want outpatient coverage, they are
forced to pay $45.50 a month for Medicare's ``Part B'' plan, and
Medicare does not pay for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep-the-promise'' bills introduced in the House and Senate
would require the Pentagon to give retirees who began military
service prior to June 1956 fully paid coverage under the Federal
Employees Health Benefit Plan, which insures civilian government
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Retired veterans who enlisted after June 1956, when the Defense
Department health care system was reorganized, would be allowed to
``buy into'' the plan, with the government paying the same portion
it now pays for retired civil service employees. No one knows
precisely how many veterans would be covered by the bills.
</P>
<P>
   According to some estimates, the legislation would cost more
than $8 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
