<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7075 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-NEWCOMERS-LADN     03-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-NEWCOMERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL OSCAR FIND ROOM FOR THE NEW?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use on Mar. 26, 2000) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences has a
well-deserved reputation for upholding traditions and playing
favorites. But you can't accuse it of old-school stuffiness this
year.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the 72nd Academy Awards' acting nominees are
first-time contenders, including the entire supporting actress
contingent. Four of the five directors are newbies as well, two for
their feature film debuts.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, of course, is whether this emphasis on the new
will result in a bumper crop of freshman statuettes. If predictions
and the results of recent years are any indications, the answer is
yes.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the dozen years following Oscar's 1927 birth have
first-time-at-bat actors and directors won as many awards as they
have over the last half-decade. Each year since 1995, at least
three of the five acting/directing awards have gone to such academy
frosh as Nicolas Cage, Kevin Spacey, Geoffrey Rush, Cuba Gooding
Jr., Anthony Minghella, Helen Hunt, James Cameron, Gwyneth Paltrow,
Roberto Benigni and that late bloomer James Coburn.
</P>
<P>
   It usually hasn't been like this _ practically from the very
beginning, in fact. The academy started playing favorites by its
third year of existence, bestowing a second nomination on actress
Gloria Swanson and a second Oscar on director Lewis Milestone. In
Oscar's fifth year, Wallace Beery and Frederic March, both previous
contestants, split the best actor prize.
</P>
<P>
   The awards' sixth year (1933) saw the first nomination for
director Frank Capra, who would dominate the category for the
decade, winning in 1934, `36 and '38. That same year, Katharine
Hepburn won her first Oscar for ``Morning Glory''; of course, she
went on to capture the lifetime record for actors with a total of
four statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went throughout the 1930s. Luise Rainer won the first
consecutive best actress Oscars; a year behind her, Spencer Tracy
repeated the feat in the men's category. Walter Brennan set the
speed record for winning three acting awards in a mere five years.
Bette Davis won two and was nominated five years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most instructively, lifetime directing Oscar champ John
Ford won one of his four awards for ``How Green Was My Valley'' in
1941, the year an obviously undeserving tyro named Orson Welles
came out with a controversial little money-loser called ``Citizen
Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Oscar preferences were set in stone by the World War II
era, newbies who could generate the right kind of extra attention
were starting to do well. The ceremonies for 1939 saw both the
fiery English import Vivien Leigh and Hattie McDaniel, the first
African-American winner, ride the sweep to victory for ``Gone With
the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next couple of decades, it helped to be exceptionally
attractive (Jennifer Jones, Ray Milland, Anne Baxter, Audrey
Hepburn, Eva Marie Saint); or atypically not so (Broderick
Crawford, Ernest Borgnine, Shirley Booth); or an exception to the
Hollywood norm (``The Best Years of Our Lives''' wounded veteran
Harold Russell, unseen-before-or-since foreign actresses such as
Katina Paxinou and Miyoshi Umeki).
</P>
<P>
   In Oscar's fourth decade, many a distinguished career was
launched with a golden boy, including Joanne Woodward's, Julie
Christie's and Goldie Hawn's, as well as Julie Andrews' and Barbra
Streisand's, who both won for their first movie appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the same criteria held through the last 30 years of the
century. In the distinguished career department, actors Robert De
Niro, Michael Douglas, Emma Thompson, Daniel Day-Lewis and Anthony
Hopkins and directors Woody Allen, James L. Brooks and Oliver Stone
were prominent winners among first-time nominees. Actors honored in
a spirit of diversity included Linda Hunt, Marlee Matlin and the
late Dr. Haing S. Ngor.
</P>
<P>
   One major trend that emerged over the last 20 years was movie
stars winning Academy Awards for their first directing efforts _
Robert Redford for ``Ordinary People,'' Kevin Costner for ``Dances
With Wolves,'' Mel Gibson for ``Braveheart.'' And of course, Clint
Eastwood won for ``Unforgiven,'' his first nomination after nearly
30 years in the business.
</P>
<P>
   But there has also been a troubling trend among first-time
winners of the '80s and '90s. The names F. Murray Abraham, Timothy
Hutton, Ben Kingsley, William Hurt, Brenda Fricker, Marisa Tomei,
Mercedes Ruehl and Mira Sorvino, among others, did not stay long
atop A-lists for casting.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, this year's first-time winners _ and there's
guaranteed to be at least one _ should be pretty pleased about the
relatively rarefied company they'll join. Being in the vanguard of
Oscar's growing determination to renew its franchise is not a bad
consolation prize, either. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
