<HEADER>
A7081 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCAR-PREDICTIONS-LAD     03-24 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PREDICTIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODDS LOOK BRIGHT FOR DARK FILM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(For use on March 26, 2000) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you haven't seen ``American Beauty,'' chances are tonight's
Academy Awards ceremony won't hold much interest for you. Having
already won honors from the Directors Guild, Producers Guild and
Screen Actors Guild, the bittersweet suburban satire stands poised
to sweep the four major categories (picture, director, actor and
actress). It would be the first film since ``Silence of the Lambs''
(and only the fourth movie in Oscar history) to pull off that
trick. (``It Happened One Night'' and ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest'' are the others.)
</P>
<P>
   The sweep would be a monumental accomplishment for a very
deserving film. It would also be somewhat of a travesty, given that
1999 produced a significant number of excellent films. To salute
one at the complete expense of all the others shows an utter lack
of imagination. But then, predictability has always been a hallmark
of Hollywood, so, in a perverse way, it makes perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my predictions for the major categories. I'd sacrifice
my Oscar pool to be wrong on a couple, just for the sake of
surprise. But I'm not holding my breath.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best picture: ``American Beauty.'' As I've already noted,
the film has won every major award, making it a virtual shoe-in for
the top honors here. It also leads the field with the most
nominations, which has guaranteed victory all but once in the last
two decades. (``Silence of the Lambs'' was the exception.) It's
simple, really. A large number of nominations indicate a broad base
of support. ``Shakespeare in Love'' led the field last year, making
its ``surprise'' victory much less astonishing in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   folo!Best actor: When he picked up his Golden Globe for ``The
Hurricane'' in January, Denzel Washington reigned as the favorite
in this category. But the barrage of criticism over the movie's
accuracy has damaged Washington's chances. His performance is the
movie's sole nomination, a bad sign. Richard Farnsworth has the
same problem.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Screen Actors Guild chose Spacey, a significant
win given that the actors bloc is by far the biggest segment of the
academy. Look for Spacey to add a matching bookend to the
supporting actor Oscar he won in 1995 for ``The Usual Suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best actress: Critical darling Hilary Swank seemed like a
sure thing until SAG voters gave Annette Bening their award. In
addition to being in the front-running film, Bening has the
advantages of her very visible pregnancy and her marriage to Warren
Beatty, who will be receiving the Irving Thalberg Award during the
ceremonies. A Bening win just makes for a better Hollywood moment
(think of Roberto Benigni's theatrics last year), never mind that
Swank gave the category's most astonishing performance.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best supporting actor: This is the evening's toughest
call. Does the award go to Tom Cruise for his career achievement
(not to mention a pretty amazing turn in ``Magnolia'')? Or to
Michael Caine, one of the most popular actors in the business, for
his sweet turn in ``Cider House Rules''? Then there's Haley Joel
Osment, the 11-year-old who carried ``The Sixth Sense'' on his
small shoulders. Kids don't usually do well in this category, but
this young man has a lot of well-placed fans. Plus, everybody has
seen his movie, something Cruise cannot boast.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best supporting actress: Toni Collette could well benefit
from ``The Sixth Sense's'' popularity as well, although people tend
to remember the spooky kid and the surprise ending and not her
performance. On the other hand, Angelina Jolie has a flamboyant
role and an outsized personality that voters seem drawn to. (Just
ask the Hollywood Foreign Press Association, which has given her
three Golden Globes.) Factor in Jolie's lineage (she's Jon Voight's
daughter) and her SAG win and you have a pretty convincing case in
her favor.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best director: Sam Mendes for ``American Beauty.'' He won
the Directors Guild award, one of the surest indicators in any
category. And he's eminently deserving of the honor.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best original screenplay: Charlie Kaufman has a lot of
support for ``Being John Malkovich,'' and M. Night Shyamalan wrote
and directed the year's most discussed movie. But this is an
``American Beauty'' pageant, and Alan Ball will emerge victorious.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!Best adapted screenplay: ``Cider House Rules'' has to win
something to justify those Miramax advertising dollars. And giving
an award to John Irving, as close as Hollywood gets to literary
respectability, will make the academy look good, even though it's
the safest and dullest choice of the bunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
