<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-DPNOMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SNAPSHOT OF THE CINEMATOGRAPHERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name of the club is Academy of MOTION PICTURE Arts and
Sciences. And there would be no MPs without the DPs: directors of
photography, also known as cinematographers. These are the artists
who decide how to light, frame and move the camera around the
images that make movies the unique storytelling form that they are.
</P>
<P>
   And this year's Oscar nominees have brought remarkable vision to
the task:
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' Conrad L. Hall: Veteran shooter Hall, a
previous winner for ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,''
orchestrated an apt mixture of visual strategies for this funny and
moving portrait of family dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The different film styles were so ingrained into the story
that they didn't clash,'' Hall says. ``We needed to see things
through the videocamera of the boy next door, because that's how he
looked at life. For the main part of the film, we wanted to have
this rigid, classic sense of composition for a lot of the scenes,
to watch the actors behave rather than go dollying around and that
sort of thing. The important thing was to get to the essence of the
characters through the lighting and the composition and the
stillness of the proscenium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The End of the Affair,'' Roger Pratt: The British Pratt's
eclectic resume ranges from Richard Attenborough's sedate
``Shadowlands'' to Tim Burton's ornate ``Batman'' to Terry
Gilliam's irate ``Brazil.'' For Neil Jordan's adaptation of Graham
Greene's classic novel, Pratt had to re-create the dreariness and
tension of wartime London, then invest it with the urgency of an
illicit romance and a sense of spiritual transcendence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not old enough to have lived through the war,'' Pratt
notes. ``The '50s were my childhood. England was still recovering,
but I had a feeling for that even darker time. England was muted:
No garish clothes, rationing, no snazzy paints for sale in the
hardware store. There was a single light bulb in the middle of
every room. It was claustrophobic. And everybody smoked. That was
the canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider,'' Dante Spinotti: Previously nominated for ``L.A.
Confidential,'' the Italian master employed all of his subtle
skills to keep this lengthy, complicated tale told mostly by
talking heads gripping and engaging from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story was all about dialogue,'' Spinotti acknowledges.
``We went in two directions. One was to try to accentuate any
existing situation through unusual lighting patterns, while still
striving for a realistic look. And we tried to achieve a kind of
false cinema verite, make it look like the movie was shot in
documentary style, although everything was controlled and
calculated according to the emotional plan that was running
throughout the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepy Hollow,'' Emmanuel Lubezki: After leaving his
distinctive mark on the films of Mexican directors Alfonso Arau
(``Like Water for Chocolate'') and Alfonso Cuaron (``A Little
Princess''), Lubezki applied a darker kind of magical realism to
Tim Burton's grisly retelling of the classic ghost story. Filming
almost entirely on sets and through clouds of studio smoke,
Lubezki's shadowy schemes convinced us we were in primeval, haunted
forests of two centuries past while sustaining an unerring sense of
earthy eeriness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' Robert Richardson: Best-known for
the virtuosic visual cacophony of his work for Oliver Stone and
Martin Scorsese, ``JFK'' Oscar winner Richardson also proved adept
at capturing the sweeping, natural beauty on Robert Redford's ``The
Horse Whisperer.'' For this postwar drama set in fog-soaked Puget
Sound, the cinematographer made compelling use of limited natural
light sources and imparted an almost magical quality to such
elements as water, air, fire and, yes, wood and snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
