<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-POPE _ KORAZIM, Israel _ Overlooking the Sea of Galilee
from the hills where Jesus Christ gave his biblical Sermon on the
Mount, Pope John Paul II delivered mass for nearly 100,000 pilgrims
from around the world Friday. The mass was one of the first large
public events of the pope's visit that seemed focused solely on
spirituality, though in a festival atmosphere, without being
subjected to the tense politics of the region. Developing. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CLINTON _ BOMBAY, India _ A busy weekend of diplomacy
looms ahead of President Bill Clinton, as he tries to invigorate
peace negotiations in South Asia and the Middle East in visits with
both Pakistani and Syrian officials. Before concluding his India
visit and turning his atteniton to those diplomatically dicey
stops, Clinton met Thursday with high-tech executives in Hyderabad,
a city where U.S. technology companies such as Microsoft and Oracle
have set up business, and then went on to Bombay to speak with
business leaders. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Expected to move by 5 p.m. EST in (i) International and
(w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-COLOR _ BOMBAY, India _ He's stood in the great
legislative cathedral of the world's most populous democracy and
felt his heart quicken at the site of a tiger in the wild. He's
glimpsed the high-tech future of one of the world's oldest
civilizations and wandered the ruins of its distant past. In the
end, though, it has been India's people that have moved and
inspired the world's most powerful man. ``For all of its
difficulties,'' said President Clinton, who leaves India Saturday
after a week-long visit, ``this is an immensely impressive
country.'' (Deans, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
