<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CREW-CHIEFS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD CREW CHIEF IS KEY IN NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Winston Cup racing, you can now make the argument now that an
elite crew chief is more important than an elite driver.
Engineering and improved aerodynamics have changed racing so
dramatically that without a near-perfect car, no driver has any
chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   And it's usually the crew chief who masterminds how a car is set
up and how the body is shaped. It's the crew chief who goes over
every inch trying to find some way to gain an edge.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't used to be that way. Once, no one made major changes
in a car during the race. If a car was loose, it was up to the
driver to slide the rear end around the corner without spinning,
not up to the crew to tighten it up. When you went into a turn, the
guy who was willing to take the greatest risks made the greatest
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Now, aerodynamics is so key that you can barely touch another
car at speed for fear of causing a wreck. Heck, drivers can
sometimes cause another car to lose it just by getting up close and
changing the air flow over the rear spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, drivers compensated for problems that developed
during the race. No more.
</P>
<P>
   On short tracks, it once was standard procedure for a fast car
to come up on a slower one, tap him once on the rear bumper and
spin him if he didn't move over. Normally, the driver of the
spinning car would regain control and move on. That's less likely
now. Cars are now more sensitive and anything that upsets them is
much more likely to put them out of control.
</P>
<P>
   That's why chassis experts have become so valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace is probably as good a driver now as he was a few
years ago, but he isn't doing nearly as well. Why? Because he lost
both Jimmy Makar and Todd Parrett, two of the elite crew chiefs in
NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Parrett's cars took Dale Jarrett to a Winston Cup
championship in 1999 and Maker may well take Bobby Labonte to one
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Jeff Gordon without his former crew chief Ray Evernham
is not nearly the force he was. Tommy Baldwin has made all the
difference for Ward Burton, who won last Sunday in Darlington, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you've got some extra millions laying around and want to
start a Winston Cup team, don't worry about getting a driver. Get
somebody who can build a winning car first.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1753EST &QL; 
