A4621 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      03-24 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 26, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBALIZATION-CONFLICTS-REVIEW (Washington) _ For seven years,
Bill Clinton has tried to offer the world's conflict-prone nations
a new commitment to globalization as the cure for an old fear of
armageddon. He made the case again last week racing through South
Asia. It proved a hard sell. Meanwhile, events in two other
flashpoints _ the Middle East and the Taiwan Strait _ were also
testing the Clinton mantra, which seemed so reasonable just a few
years ago: that sharing in global prosperity will inevitably tame
old nationalisms and make the world safer. Each of those disputes,
of course, is driven by its own history of conflict. But they all
illustrate the dangers of too simplistic a faith in the lure of the
market when nationalistic impulses flare up. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-REVIEW _ Grozny before and after. A photo essay.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-MONEY-REVIEW (WASHINGTON) _ In 1988, Bob Farmer, the top
fund-raiser man for Michael Dukakis and the Democrats, and Bob
Mosbacher, finance chairman for George Bush and the Republicans,
launched the first national programs to raise soft money _ the
large, unrestricted gifts to the two parties by wealthy
individuals, corporations and labor unions. Both Farmer and
Mosbacher have lived to regret their fiscal ingenuity and now favor
campaign finance reform. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUITS-TOBACCO-REVIEW (Undated) _ The legal system has begun
to overtake the legislative process as the vehicle to resolve
contentious debates, particularly over controversial products when
Congress is unwilling to act. Both the tobacco and firearms
litigation, for example, were highly organized assaults on targeted
industries. Previously, lawsuits had been brought by individuals
against both industries with little financial success or effect on
company policies. The use of concentrated legal firepower to set
social policy has stirred sharp debate. Some legal experts have
decried such lawsuits as abusive. Others view them as a problematic
but a needed counterbalance to the powerful control that companies
and interest groups can exert over Congress. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-SOCIETY-REVIEW (Undated) _ This year's Academy Award
nominations include a melange of comedies, dramas and absurd
flights of fancy that once again speak to the national psyche.
Judging from the contents of these films, the country appears to be
a mess. Some thoughts on what that little man of gold might be
saying about America. By Bruce Kluger.
</P>
<P>
   BOYCOTTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Even sponsors of boycotts
acknowledge these weapons have a mixed record of success and can
hurt friend as well as foe. To be sure, some boycotts succeed, as
was the case with the 1956 Montgomery bus boycott, which pressured
that city to stop requiring blacks to sit at the back of the bus.
But sometimes boycotts fail and just fade away. Although most
Americans do not realize it, the grape boycott announced by the
United Farm Workers in 1984 remains in force. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   HAIRDRESSERS-WIFEBEATING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Remember Clairol's
catchy slogan from the 1950s, ``Hair color so natural, only her
hairdresser knows for sure''? In recognition that hair stylists may
know more secrets about their clients than merely cosmetic ones,
new programs are being established by community-based organizations
and state agencies to help hairdressers identify signs of domestic
violence. These programs are trying to take advantage of the
special bond that often exists between hairdressers and their
clients. By Jeff Stryker.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-GURU-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ From 1956 to 1977, Jean
Shepherd held weeknight seminars on a New York radio station that
were part Kabuki, part commedia dell'arte, part Uncle Remus. In his
flat, nasal Indiana twang, playing all the parts, and the
occasional kazoo, he oozed into the darkened bedrooms of East Coast
America on the battery power of cheap Japanese transistor radios.
The meandering stories he told were usually about him but they also
seemed to be about us. What was he? Social commentator? Cult
leader? Or just a manic kid from a blue-collar background
discovering his subversive id. Excerpts from a recent radio
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EXTRADITE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The initial rulings against
Chile's Gen. Augusto Pinochet caused some former U.S. officials to
wonder whether they too could some day be extradited _ let us say,
if the United States lost its position as the world's sole
superpower _ and put on trial any time that any judge in the world
accuses them of human rights violations. Imagine, for instance,
that Oliver North is arrested while vacationing in Switzerland and
then extradited to Lebanon for his role in the U.S. bombings of
Libya in 1986. By Jayson Blair.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN-REVIEW (Moscow) _ Vladimir Putin's most serious
effort since assuming the leadership of Russia has been prosecuting
the brutal military operation in Chechnya, intended to prove that
he is the firm hand that can rebuild a strong Russian state. But
far more complex and difficult tests await him on that very score.
His real challenge will be the appointments, the policies and
economic reforms he undertakes to bring Russia back from the brink
of disintegration. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   HAVANA-REVIEW _ In eloquent stasis, Havana awaits a new era. A
photo essay.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORY QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: &LR;
</P>
