<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-EDUCATION25-COX     03-24 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDUCATION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE CHOOSES THE CLASSROOM AS HIS BATTLEGROUND WITH BUSH
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACOMB, Mich. _ See Al run. See Al run to be the education
president.
</P>
<P>
   That was Vice President Al Gore's assignment Friday during his
day-long visit to L'Anse Creuse Middle School North in this
blue-collar suburb of Detroit: to convince swing voters that he
will do more to improve education than his presidential rival, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process, Gore appeared to having the most fun ever in
his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call me Al,'' he told 13-year-old Dan Lindeman upon
arriving at the school. Lindeman had a double row of spikes in his
hair, but Al never mentioned the do.
</P>
<P>
   Al lectured Diane Persha's history class about the industrial
age, with special attention to the cotton gin and telegraph, but
refrained from taking credit for either invention.
</P>
<P>
   Al rejoiced that Friday meant pizza for lunch, and he gobbled
down the pepperoni, listed on the cafeteria menu as ``Hungry
Howie's.''
</P>
<P>
   Al even joined an exercise in Sally Hannert's drama class in
which the actors were allowed to speak only gibberish as they
portrayed a father scolding his daughter about bad grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wub woo bub bub wub, wub,'' he said to the delight of the
sixth-graders in the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting ready for our debates with George Bush,'' Gore
spokesman Chris Lehane immediately quipped, alluding to Bush's
reputation as intellectual slacker.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's visit to the middle school in this predominantly
white bedroom community _ which coincided with Bush's visit to
Central High School in Little Rock, Ark., whose desegregation made
history _ underscores the importance of the education issue in this
year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no higher priority for our future than giving our
children the best education in the world,'' Gore said as he kicked
off a series of visits with students, teachers and parents that his
campaign is calling ``School Days.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the kind of attention education is getting from Gore
and Bush has not been seen in a presidential campaign since 1964,
when President Lyndon Johnson was trying to expand the federal role
in what is still mostly a function of local and state government.
</P>
<P>
   Polls consistently show that education is a big issue,
particularly with women, the most important voting group in the
last two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Democratic Party has long been the party most
trusted by voters to improve education, Bush is close to stealing
the education issue from Gore. A recent poll by the Pew Research
Center found 44 percent of voters think Bush would do ``the best
job'' on education, while 41 percent thought Gore would.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is very surprising, given the Democratic Party's
traditional edge on this issue,'' said Andrew Kohut, the center's
director.
</P>
<P>
   Education reform, however, is a subject on which Bush has shown
passion and knowledge. While he views education as largely the
prerogative of local government, the governor is planning a series
of speeches on the ``common ideals'' that should guide education
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore is following the same tactic against Bush that he used
so effectively in vanquishing Bill Bradley, his rival in the
Democratic primaries. Gore tries to be first out of the starting
blocks with his own proposals, at the same time pounding away at
his rival's record.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he did with Bradley's health care proposals, Gore is
probing for the weak spots in Bush's education record. So far,
Gore's attention has rested primarily on a 1999 study that 76
percent of Texas schools report a need to upgrade or repair their
facilities _ among the worst states in national rankings. The study
was conducted by the National Education Association (NEA), the
nation's largest teachers union, which has endorsed Gore's
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to reform a school that's falling down,''
Gore said at a campaign stop in Ohio on Thursday en route to
Michigan. ``That is why we need a new national commitment to
rebuild and modernize public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be talking about the mess in Texas,'' Lehane
said Friday. ``We're not talking about the people of Texas. We're
talking about that they deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
   One cornerstone of Gore's campaign is a plan to spend $115
billion over 10 years on a host of education programs, including
universal pre-school, expanded after-school programs, modernizing
schools and reducing class sizes by providing local school boards
with more money to hire teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Social Security and federal health care programs,
education is the single largest spending proposal he has made.
</P>
<P>
   L'Anse Creuse was a near-perfect backdrop for his modernization
proposal. Founded in 1966, the school has an enrollment of 905. But
is becoming overcrowded as Macomb County has grown into Michigan's
third most populous county. Along the way, it has gained fame in
political circles as the home of many ``Reagan Democrats'' with an
independent voting streak.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed spending $5.5 billion in federal education
spending over five years, but his policies are linked mostly to
accountability through locally designed and administered tests.
</P>
<P>
   He would take federal money away from poorly performing schools
and give the money instead to parents in the form of vouchers that
could be used at private or parochial schools. Gore opposes
vouchers outside the public school system, as does the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has proposed letting families put $5,000 per year into
a tax-free education savings account for each elementary or
secondary school student. Currently the law allows $500 per year
for college expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
