<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BLACK-SPIRITUAL25-COX     03-24 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-SPIRITUAL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black religious leaders examine King's vow on 'Promised Land'
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the last night of his life, the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr. delivered an apocalyptic sermon, vowing that black people
would get ``to the Promised Land.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 4, the 32nd anniversary of his assassination, an
intriguing mixture of black religious leaders from across the
nation will gather in Atlanta to discuss whether King's vow will
ever come true.
</P>
<P>
   The first Spiritual State of Black America conference, a
three-day program sponsored by the Interdenominational Theological
Center, will consist of seminars, moderated discussions and sermons
by some of the most powerful preachers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But what separates this conference from the rest is its
electrifying mix of speakers. Leaders from the black Muslim
community, the black church and black political organizations will
debate one another over their vision of the Promised Land.
</P>
<P>
   ITC President Robert Franklin said he organized the conference
because King's vision still challenges America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use (the conference) as a kind of moral checkpoint
for examining the spiritual state of black America, but also the
spiritual and theological condition of the larger nation,''
Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   Conference speakers include Hugh Price, president of the
National Urban League; Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP; Imam
Warith Deen Mohammed, head of the American Muslim Society and son
of the founder of the Nation of Islam; Minister Ava Muhammad,
Southern regional representative for the Nation of Islam; and
Bishop John Hurst Adams from the AME Church.
</P>
<P>
   Any conclusions or solutions to issues raised at the conference
will be compiled into a report that will eventually be released to
the public, Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   The report, he says, will hopefully note signs that King's vow
is not far off _ the Promised Land is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our poorest communities,'' Franklin said, ``you
still see violent behaviors, substance abuse, HIV infection and a
high level of despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-527-7719 Spiritual State of Black America
conference
</P>
<P>
   A three-day event sponsored by the International Theological
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404 527-7719
</P>
<P>
   John Blake write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
