<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-MOVIES25-COX     03-24 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MOVIES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents need to help their youngsters find films that are
healthy and fun
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sabreen Muwakkil and her husband have watched ``The Green
Mile,'' a nominee for Best Picture when the annual Academy Awards
are handed out Sunday. They liked the film adaptation of Stephen
King's death row novel, but Muwakkil won't let her teenage children
see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's R-rated, we generally don't let them go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Ellen Italiaander took her young children to
see ``Stuart Little,'' a visual effects Academy Award contender
based on an E.B. White story about a 3-inch-tall mouse. She was
shocked when the movie's cute critters let loose with a couple of
expletives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy going to the movies,'' said Italiaander, the mother of
six children under 9 years old. ``But I think moviemakers do a bad
job of creating films that are just healthy and fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Muwakkil, a Muslim who worships at Atlanta's Masjid Al-Islam,
and Italiaander, a member of The Temple, a Reform Jewish
congregation, are trying to raise their children in homes based on
sound religious faith and practice. Both, like millions of other
parents, struggle with how to help their offspring deal with
popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think movies have a huge impression on children,'' said
Italiaander. ``There's enough stress out there without going to see
something inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect of a film may go far beyond whether there's cursing,
sex or violence, say people who review films for religious
publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do all films contain a message?'' asks Ed McNulty, a
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) minister in New York state who
publishes a film review magazine called Visual Parables. ``They do
in the sense that there's a worldview that underlies them. The
question is what message? Sometimes the messages are anything but
what people of faith would prefer.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore ``Ted'' Baehr, publisher of Movieguide magazine and
head of the Christian Film and Television Commission in Los
Angeles, says viewers can find the message of the movie in its
conclusion. ``Does virtue and decency and honesty triumph over
adversity?''
</P>
<P>
   Baehr does not advocate goody-two-shoes movies with no tension.
``If you take the bad person out, there's no conflict,'' he said,
but added that greed and violence should not win in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Not all people of faith _ nor all Christian movie reviewers _
have the same opinions of the same films.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``The Tigger Movie,'' a brand-new, apparently innocent
animation of the adventures of A.A. Milne's popular gang including
Pooh, Piglet, Baby Roo and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to have a powerful message that there's family
everywhere that's caring,'' said McNulty.
</P>
<P>
   But Phil Boatwright, who reviews films from an evangelical
Christian point of view as The Movie Reporter and lives in Thousand
Oaks, Calif., says he thinks Tigger advocated ``a new family
structure'' that ``goes hand-in-hand with same-sex marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts off the responsibility of family,'' he said. ``It's
kind of like we're restructuring our society.''
</P>
<P>
   A controversial film such as ``Dogma'' invites even stronger
disagreement. To McNulty, who teaches a workshop called ``Sitting
in the Dark Looking for the Light,'' the film ``was really
preaching against the phony cheap gimmicks to sell Jesus to the
masses.'' McNulty rated ``Dogma'' one of the top 10 films of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Baehr's group classified the film as ``Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Baehr was equally unimpressed with some of the nominees for Best
Picture. His organization gave its annual $25,000 Epiphany Prize
for the Most Inspiring Movie of 1999 to ``The Winslow Boy,'' which
did not make the academy's cut. He said the movie, about a
barrister defending a young man accused of theft, presents a
``Christian worldview of justice'' with the theme that ``the
powerless must be protected against the powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even films with important messages that are inspiring to adults
may be inappropriate for children, Baehr said. His favorite example
is ``Schindler's List,'' the 1993 Academy Award winner about the
Holocaust that included graphic images from concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some tough movies like 'The Green Mile' that are
just about topics that children at certain stages of development
will not understand fully,'' he said. And parents should not rely
on their children's assurance that they are ready for a deep film.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes this so complex is that kids always want to say
they can handle it,'' Baehr said, ``but they don't have the
apparatus to connect all the dots.''
</P>
<P>
   Before children _ or teenagers or even adults _ can make
adequate discernment about the messages they are receiving from
culture, they must be grounded in the values of their own faith and
family, said Boatwright. ``As you develop your spiritual life,
you're going to be able to see the faults and inadequacies.''
</P>
<P>
   Boatwright, Baehr and McNulty all recommend that parents try to
see films before they let their children, even teenagers, see them
and that the family discuss each movie and what it means.
</P>
<P>
   Muwakkil said she and her husband already are doing that with
their children, a son who is a sophomore at Morehouse College and
daughters who are a sophomore and a junior at Clara Muhammad School
in east Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we talk about a movie just to see what kind of effect
it might have on them or to see their viewpoint,'' she said.
``We'll discuss any good that was in it. And we always try to
discuss stereotypes or any other things we don't approve of.''
</P>
<P>
   Italiaander describes herself and her husband, who attends the
Orthodox synagogue Congregation Ariel, as ``very conservative as
parents.'' She said she plans to try to see every movie before she
allows her children to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``In society today, there's a lot going on out there. I want to
make sure my children have all the right information from me and my
husband, not from TV and not from the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
