<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7099 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-OSCARS25-COX     03-24 1927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-OSCARS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judging the Oscars from
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five critics from various religious points of view offer their
thoughts on this year's nominees for Best Picture, focusing on the
moral, ethical and spiritual implications of each film.
</P>
<P>
   The critics rank the finalists in relation to one another, with
1 being the highest and 5 the lowest, judging each movie's moral
message and how well it is conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Baehr, an ordained Episcopal priest and former
filmmaker, is chairman of the Christian Film and Television
Commission and publisher of Movieguide magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Boatwright reviews films for The Movie Reporter and the
Dove Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cunneen is film critic for the National Catholic
Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McNulty, a minister in the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.),
publishes Visual Parables, a film review journal.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Stopp is editor in chief of ``Gynergy,'' the newsletter
for the department of religious studies at Agnes Scott College.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN BEAUTY (R)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey plays a man caught in midlife limbo with a crush on
his daughter's friend and a life that is disintegrating.
</P>
<P>
   CIDER HOUSE RULES (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Stars Michael Caine as Dr. Wilbur Larch, who delivers babies and
performs illegal abortions in a Maine orphanage, and Tobey Maguire
as Homer Wells, his protege, who runs off to learn about the world
in the adaptation of a John Irving novel.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN MILE (R)
</P>
<P>
   Adaptation of a Stephen King prison novel in which Tom Hanks
plays a 1930s death row guard whose latest prisoner, a mysterious
hulk played by Michael Clarke Duncan, has mystical healing powers.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER (R)
</P>
<P>
   Russell Crowe plays Jeffrey Wigand, a real-life cigarette
industry consultant who blows the lid off the tobacco industry; Al
Pacino stars as the ``60 Minutes'' producer dogging the story.
</P>
<P>
   SIXTH SENSE (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Eight-year-old Cole (Haley Joel Osment) can see restless
phantoms with their skulls blown open, raising questions about the
relationship between the dead and the living world.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Baehr, Movieguide
</P>
<P>
   THE GREEN MILE
</P>
<P>
   This fascinating ``Holy Fool'' story contains many Christian
references. It is filled with moments of grace, respect, love,
forgiveness, and talks about divine topics, including the Last
Judgment. It also has some direct references to Christ, God and
Christian behavior, mixed, regrettably, with some strong
profanities.
</P>
<P>
   Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   THE INSIDER
</P>
<P>
   Told with conviction, intensity and adroit acting, this tale of
whistle blowing and tobacco companies has some moral elements
concerning telling the truth, product liability and the ethics of
TV journalism. It also has some mild humanist and politically
correct elements that give too much power to big government.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN BEAUTY
</P>
<P>
   Redefines beauty as ugliness, converts a middle-aged businessman
into a pot-smoking pedophile who tries to rape his daughter's
friend, makes a peeping Tom the hero, bashes the military, and
portrays a very fractured family.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   THE CIDER HOUSE RULES
</P>
<P>
   Endorses abortion. As William Norman Grigg noted in The New
American, it is ``a satanic inversion of the Christmas story'' that
takes a fascist, National Socialist approach to morality and the
sanctity of life, an approach that Adolf Hitler and his
trench-coated mass murderers would love.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   THE SIXTH SENSE
</P>
<P>
   Lies about the afterlife and promotes spiritism, a demonic,
occult worldview that God has explicitly and strongly condemned in
his Word, the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Phil Boatwright, The Movie Reporter, The Dove Foundation
</P>
<P>
   Green Mile
</P>
<P>
   This may be the year's best film with its reverence for things
seen and not seen, and the main character's regard for human life.
A profound movie that respectfully raises questions concerning
God's power and man's ability to do great good or great evil. What
moved me was the element of self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Sense
</P>
<P>
   With many elements of Hitchcockian-suspense, director M. Night
Shyamalan gives audiences the best spook-fest of the tepid crop of
horror films out of this past summer. Some unsettling imagery, but
rather than being so graphic it caused us to use our imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Insider
</P>
<P>
   The film is about journalistic integrity _ a phrase that has
lost a great deal of meaning over the past decade. Jeffrey Wigand
(Russell Crowe) is a man who, although he loses everything, stands
up for what he believes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Cider House Rules
</P>
<P>
   Well-crafted, but it is Hollywood's definition of right and
wrong, not the Bible's. Negative stereotypes of Christians and
conservatives that are becoming very hackneyed in film. Christians
are portrayed as unfeeling holier-than-thous, while the lawbreaking
doctor is, down deep, the sensitive and judicious caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   American Beauty
</P>
<P>
   Brilliantly acted, with stinging dialogue, but the film, besides
containing so much objectionable material, also seems bent on
ridiculing and debasing U.S. suburban life. It is the most
depressing film I have seen in quite some time. Those attempting to
develop a spiritual walk may find the lack of spirituality and the
despicable behavior disturbing and unsatisfying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cunneen, National Catholic Reporter
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Sense
</P>
<P>
   Deserves praise for avoiding the cliches of the ghost story and
not confusing the hard-to-explain with the sacred. Good writing,
acting and directing work together to suggest our responsibility
for each other, even across the barrier of death. The conclusion is
stunning, while avoiding sensationalism, reinforcing the hopeful
sense that its suffering characters can help one another.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Cider House Rules
</P>
<P>
   Powerfully moving in its orphanage sequences, dominated by an
idealistic doctor who breaks ``the rules'' in performing abortions
on women in need. But its Dickensian growing-up story is weakened
by a cliche romance and its condescending treatment of
African-American migrant workers. Making the young man's decision
to continue the doctor's work depend on an instance of incest only
weakens the movie's ``argument'' in favor of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Insider
</P>
<P>
   Aims a sharp critique at the tobacco industry, particularly for
its dishonesty about prior knowledge of the harmful effects of
smoking, but awards its highest praise for the man who discloses
the inside information he possesses _ and suffers the consequences.
 &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   American Beauty
</P>
<P>
   Satirizes our consumer impulse for endless acquisition and the
way in which the hunger for success often poisons the possibilities
of marriage. Because its targets are so exaggerated, however, most
viewers will feel a challenge to their values and may find it hard
to accept the young drug dealer as the bearer of its moral vision.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Green Mile
</P>
<P>
   Moved audiences with its prison story of good against evil, but
its oversimplifications simply exploit the emotions we already
bring to the theater. It is hard to take a movie seriously that
shows bodies twitching at executions but never questions capital
punishment.  &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Ed McNulty, Visual Parables
</P>
<P>
   American Beauty
</P>
<P>
   I like that it started out as what I expected it to be, a witty
satire of some of the shallow suburban values and lifestyles. I was
surprised or pleased that it took a 90-degree turn toward a
celebration of the beauty of life despite its unhappy or sordid
conditions. The triumph is Kevin Spacey and his daughter who emerge
affirming life and its beauty, but the tragedy is the mother, who
makes the wrong choice _ success drive, superficial riches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   The Insider
</P>
<P>
   I had to admire the filmmakers who dare to indict a powerful
American industry that contributes to the death of thousands of
citizens each year. I see it as a social justice film that if the
prophets Amos and Jeremiah were preaching today, they might have
made that film.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   The Green Mile
</P>
<P>
   I see this as a wonderful tale of human decency and divine
miracle, taking place in a very unlikely place, the death row of a
prison. I admire the Tom Hanks character, the chief guard, who
tries to treat even the most depraved of the prisoners with dignity
and respect and then he in turn receives healing grace. It doesn't
have the Hollywood happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Sense
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised by the choice of this film which, in turn, has a
surprise ending to it. It's a film that affirms that there is a
life beyond what our five senses can detect. It's a film that
affirms the importance of human relationships and, unfortunately,
one character doesn't learn that until pretty late. I was intrigued
_ there have been several films along this line that there is a
justice in our universe that must be satisfied if a dead victim is
to truly rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Cider House Rules
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's controversial for some because of its stand on
abortion, I think the film explores well the sense of call or the
responsibility to help others in life. I think especially it
affirms the somewhat tenuous bond that join an older and a young
man in a father-son relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Stopp, ``Gynergy,'' the newsletter for the department
of religious studies at Agnes Scott College
</P>
<P>
   American Beauty
</P>
<P>
   The strongest film. The plot accurately reflects the depravity
and tragic injustices in the busy culture of modern America. Backed
by strong leading and supporting actors, the film exposes the dark
side of suburbia while allowing the viewer to make her own
judgments of the actions taken by the characters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Green Mile
</P>
<P>
   A close second to American Beauty and will probably win, if for
no other reason than the prestige associated with Stephen King and
the amazing cast. The characters suffer a bit from stagnation, and
the believability of John Coffey's (Michael Clarke Duncan) healing
power is questionable. Overall, the film is strong and offers a
powerful anti-death penalty sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Cider House Rules
</P>
<P>
   A blatantly pro-choice film, presents strong social arguments
for keeping abortion legal but falls short in the running for Best
Picture. The underdeveloped character Candy weakens the movie, and
the lack of discussion of religious-based objections to abortion
serves as the film's death sentence for winning Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Sense
</P>
<P>
   Depicts the story of a little boy haunted by ghosts and his
relationship with his mother and psychologist. The moral message in
this film is an interesting twist on the old golden rule since the
people the child learns to help are dead. Although the performance
of Haley Joel Osment is incredible, the film itself is rather weak
and leaves too many unanswered questions to win Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Insider
</P>
<P>
   The anti-establishment rhetoric is tedious and the viewer is
left with unsatisfactory resolution in the end. Although it
successfully portrays the evils of the tobacco industry, this film
falls short of Oscar-worthy material and is simply not as strong as
the other nominees.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
