<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7100 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WHITNEY-REVIEW26-COX     03-24 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mix of high-tech art, international flavor at heart of Whitney
Biennial
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 2000 Whitney Biennial gets the new century off to
a good start. The work of the 97 artists is serious, thoughtful,
inventive and carefully crafted. If this graciously installed
exhibition lacks the boisterousness of past biennials, a sense of
maturity is not a bad trade. And most welcome of all, it doesn't
stick its finger or its rear end in your face, which goes to show
you that art _ and the biennial _ can be provocative without being
shrill and confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   (Hans Haacke's critique of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
response to the Brooklyn Museum of Art's ``Sensation'' exhibition
is the exception, and it looks so ``last century.'')
</P>
<P>
   The biennial aims to survey what is being made in America. Its
observation: everything, from abstract painting to installation to
Internet art (included for the first time.) Still, this is
definitely the year of technology. In addition to Net art, there is
an abundance of video, digital and computer presentations. One of
the most intriguing, even though the point isn't quite clear, is
Cambridge, Mass.-based Krzysztof Wodi-czko's ``Aegis: Equipment for
a City of Strangers.'' The contraption is a pair of winglike LCD
monitors worn on the shoulders. They show images of the wearer that
talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the year of the figure. That's inevitable, what
with the preponderance of photography and video. But even most of
the nonrepresentational objects have figurative references as
opposed to being an investigation of form and color. In the case of
Chakaia Booker's wall relief ``Homage to Thy Mother (Landscape),''
one of the most strikingly beautiful pieces in the show, the
material _ car tires cut and shredded into a variety of shapes _ is
highly symbolic. The New York artist sees many references to
African-Americans in the tires, from their color to their
resilience. In one of many interesting juxtapositions, Booker's
piece is installed across the room from works by Alabama artist
Thornton Dial, who takes a similar approach to materials.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial abounds with inventive treatment of both au courant
themes and venerable genres. Ghada Amer, an Egyptian native living
in New York, makes elegant ``paintings'' by stitching patterns on
canvas that comment on the place of women in Islamic culture.
Atlantan Chris Verene comments on women in this culture in his
photos of men in camera clubs who take soft-porn pictures of
misguided women.
</P>
<P>
   (Both he and fellow Atlantan Kojo Griffin more than hold their
own here. Unfortunately, many of the videos and films, including
those of Atlantans Robin Bernat and Ruth Leitman, weren't
re-viewable during press previews.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the demographics are broader _ both in geography and
generation _ than in the past, don't expect a regional flavor. Most
of the work selected by the six-person curatorial team comes out of
either a more interior source or a larger art world consciousness.
In fact, with 21 artists born outside of the United States, the
biennial exudes an international character. Iranian-born New Yorker
Shirin Neshat has contributed a riveting two-screen video about
Islam and individualism, with a touch of romance. Art may be the
melting pot that America never quite was.
</P>
<P>
   Not every piece is a gem, of course. In some cases, the object
can't carry off the conceptual burden imposed upon it.
Nevertheless, this biennial makes a persuasive and surprisingly
coherent case that contemporary art of all description is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Biennial
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m.-6 p.m. Tuesdays-Wednesdays and Fridays-Sundays; 1-9 p.m.
Thursdays. Through June 4. $10; $8 senior citizens, students.
Whitney Museum of American Art,
</P>
<P>
   945 Madison Ave., New York.
</P>
<P>
   For timed reservations (add $2) and information, 1-877-944-8639
or www.whitney.org.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A winner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
