r a BC-WRITER-INDICTED-TEX     03-24 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITER-INDICTED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE-CRIME WRITER INDICTED ON DRUG CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By SUSAN GILL VARDON 
And MIKE LEE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH RICHLAND HILLS, Texas _ True-crime writer Barbara Davis
has been indicted on four felony drug counts in connection with a
Dec. 15 raid by police that left her 25-year-old son dead,
officials said this week.
</P>
<P>
   The charges relate to the designer drug gamma hydroxybutyrate,
or GHB. Davis, 48, of North Richland Hills, a Fort Worth suburb, is
charged with possession of a controlled substance; possession of a
controlled substance with intent to deliver; manufacture of a
controlled substance; and attempted manufacture of a controlled
substance, said Terry Barlow, a Tarrant County assistant district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Davis did not return a telephone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Tom Carse, who is representing Davis in her
wrongful-death lawsuit against the North Richland Hills Police
Department, said he isn't surprised by the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to the opportunity of pursuing vigorously our
claims against all potential parties arising out of Troy Davis'
death and vigorously defending Barbara,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of one or all of the charges, Davis could serve as
little as two years in prison with a $10,000 fine, or as much as 99
years or life in prison, plus a fine of up to $100,000. The various
counts carry different penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a grand jury heard cases against Davis and North
Richland Hills police officer Allen Hill, who shot and killed Troy
Davis during the raid. The grand jury determined that there was
insufficient evidence to charge Hill in connection with Troy Davis'
death.
</P>
<P>
   North Richland Hills Police Chief Tom Shockley said on Thursday
that Hill, who has been on paid leave since the shooting, also was
exonerated by an internal investigation and probably will return to
work next week.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was among the tactical team officers who broke through the
Davises' door after getting a tip that they were growing marijuana.
Police have said that Troy Davis was pointing a gun at the officers
when Hill shot him in the chest. The officers used a ``no knock''
warrant, meaning they entered the house without warning.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they found three marijuana plants, enough GHB for
600 doses, and 16 guns _ including a pistol that they said was in
Troy Davis' hand. They said they also found a loaded AR-15 assault
rifle. The guns are legal, and Barbara Davis has said she believed
that GHB was legal.
</P>
<P>
   One of the counts against Davis states that she possessed the
ingredients for making GHB, as well as the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration outlawed GHB,
which is known as a ``date rape'' drug. It has been illegal in
Texas since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Davis is best known for writing ``Precious Angels,''
which portrays Darlie Routier as a coldblooded killer who stabbed
her two young sons to death in 1996 in a Dallas suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Davis made a turnaround during an appearance on the television
talk show ``Leeza,'' declaring that she believes that Routier is
not guilty. Davis also announced plans to write a new book.
</P>
<P>
   Hill will return to work as a motorcycle traffic officer after a
vacation, Shockley said. He will not return to the tactical team in
the foreseeable future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shockley said he reviewed the internal investigation report
after the grand jury decision was announced Monday. He said he
determined that Hill had not violated department policy when he
shot Troy Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been such a tragic event, and it's certainly not what any
of us wanted to happen,'' Shockley said. ``But we've got to go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Shockley had suspended Hill in June, six months before the
shooting, for exposing himself during a group photograph taken at a
training seminar, police records state.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
