<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7105 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-BEAUTY-LADN &LR;      03-24 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-BEAUTY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTY' IN THE EYE OF THE BEHOLDER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use March 26, 2000) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pre-Oscar gnashing and thrashing has been even more
cacaphonous than usual this year. Laments over who got robbed,
complaints about who's campaigning too lavishly, tortuous formulas
for predicting how the academy is going to vote and why _ there was
endless babble about everything.
</P>
<P>
   Everything except, perhaps, what it might actually mean.
</P>
<P>
   1999 was generally agreed to be one of the finest recent years
of cinema. Consequently, the 72nd Academy Awards' best picture race
has been considered, until very recently, one of the most closely
competitive ever. The five films vying this time around are wildly
different in approach and subject matter, so it is not surprising
they all have their passionate champions _ and, with the possible
exception of one of them, severe critics.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the leading nominee, ``American Beauty,'' has
been looking increasingly likely to win most of the eight races
it's entered in tonight, it's still conceivable that any of the
contenders could still win best picture. There's not the sense of
inevitability that attended the ``Titanic,'' ``The English
Patient,'' ``Forrest Gump'' and ``Schindler's List'' coronations,
nor of the two-picture shootout we got last year between
``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Saving Private Ryan,'' or when the
1995 competition pitted ``Braveheart'' against ``Apollo 13.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of these reasons, it's too bad that most Oscar
commentary has focused so narrowly on what's going to win. The more
interesting take for this uniquely thoughtful movie year is, what
will the academy's choice say about the Hollywood establishment it
represents: the tastes, the prejudices, the ethics and the
imaginative vision of the people who make most of our movies?
</P>
<P>
   Each of the nominees represents a different, complicated
statement on how the best in American film should be defined. Let's
look at what those qualities are _ and, just for wicked fun on this
day of all overhyped days, let's also acknowledge the complaints
about each film, and to what extent they succeed at overcoming
them.
</P>
<P>
   As the moralists among us delight in mentioning, only an
industry as corrupt as Tinseltown could consider something like
``Beauty'' as its finest achievement. The film essentially starts
with a sad moment of shower masturbation, then quickly and
gleefully pours themes of infidelity, pedophilia, voyeurism,
recreational drug use, professional blackmail and violently
repressed homosexuality right down the sewer after it.
</P>
<P>
   That the film is cleverly written, superbly acted, photographed
with outstanding grace and wonderfully scored is a strong defense
in most people's books, but actually a liability to those who think
it glamorizes the aforementioned vices. But while indulging and
even exploiting its illicit thrills, the movie is really about
transcending unhappiness and discovering genuine personal
fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap, false epiphanies are the real sins of too many Hollywood
movies. By recognizing ``American Beauty,'' academy members let
slip that they, like the characters in the film, desperately want
something truer.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line is ``The Cider House Rules,'' a film its creators
probably can't believe has gotten such an easy ride. After all, the
abortion-rights stance of John Irving's 1940s-set, coming-of-age
story couldn't be more offensive to the anti-abortion contingent,
but there's hardly been a peep about the film from the religious
right. Nor, for that matter, has the civil rights community
attacked the film's blithe pathologizing of an African-American
family just to make a key plot decision easier for its white
protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of protest is due in great part to the movie's
studiously non-confrontational style. It goes out of its way to be
sensitive, nostalgic, forgiving and filled to bursting with
adorable, wide-eyed orphans. ``Cider House'' is in line with a
decades-old Hollywood tradition of presenting divisive, somewhat
muddled liberal beliefs in the safest, most artistically
conservative manner possible. It's the kind of film that makes a
statement while striving not to alienate a single potential
ticket-buyer _ which, whatever you feel about the ethics of it, is
definitely an art in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same can be said for ``The Green Mile,'' which sets its
critique of the death penalty more than half a century in the
buffering past, and in a place and time where its own bizarre,
condescending racial attitudes could conceivably be more
permissable.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Green Mile'' is a Stephen King story, too, and thus a
fantasy. Its serious ideas about injustice, redemption and an
aching eternal punishment that lies somewhere in between are
wrapped in thick religious metaphor. Combine that wihth the film's
lengthy, portentous pace and its starring duo, towering Michael
Clarke Duncan and iconic Tom Hanks, and you've got the kind of
mythmaking effort that earned the industry its Dream Factory
nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'' was the only one of this year's highly praised _
then seriously denounced _ true-life stories to make the final
five, even though it plays as loose with the truth as ``The
Hurricane'' and ``Boys Don't Cry'' were accused of doing. It stands
for all the best and worst aspects of filmmakers' tendency to shape
reality to their needs for dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the reason Michael Mann's expose of Big Tobacco
malfeasance and the compromise of TV journalism outpaced the others
is its pit bull commitment to chewing over the tough task of acting
honorably in a complicated world. Sure, there were definite good
and bad guys in ``The Insider,'' but there were more imperfect
mortals whose agendas and loyalties did not easily distill into
standard Hollywood rights and wrongs. That could well be why this
movie never found a wide audience; but by honoring complexities of
circumstance and motive, ``The Insider'' expanded the scope of the
true expose movie, and brought at least some new elements of truth
to the prestigious and often pompous genre.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the one that everyone likes, ``The Sixth
Sense.'' It's the only nominee that's not about anything real
(which, let's face it, is the kind of thing studios are most
comfortable and most often successful with); just a perfectly
wrought ghost story with an exquisitely engineered surprise ending.
</P>
<P>
   Although worlds away in style from such fellow box-office
blockbusters as ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' and
``The Matrix,'' ``Sixth Sense'' nevertheless represents the same
kind of pure escapism into an imaginary universe. The drab, mundane
world the movie's clairvoyant kid lives in even seems specially
shot to look like Hollywood's idea of the average moviegoer's
existence. Haley Joel Osment's awe and emotional response to the
fantastic things he sees parallel an audiences' reaction to being
manipulated by entertainment craftspeople who, more and more in
recent years, like to be thought of as wizards.
</P>
<P>
   So which one's going to win tonight? That's all we care about,
right, along with what everybody's wearing. But we can, as the ad
line says, look closer. The big choice will tell us a lot about how
the industry feels its skills at spinning surface illusions should
be employed in the new century. Will it boldly illuminate deeper
truths or entertainingly distract us from life's tougher
realities? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
