<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-FOR-SALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SELLING 2,200 E. TEXAS ACRES AT FORMER AMBASSADOR
UNIVERSITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the multimillion-dollar auction doesn't work out, maybe
Ambassador University can be offered as an ultra-extravagant gift
in the Neiman Marcus Christmas catalog.
</P>
<P>
   On April 4, the Worldwide Church of God will seek a Texas-size
bid for the Texas-size property _ a leafy, 2,200-acre former
university campus that includes a golf course, landing strip, radio
station and 46-acre lake.
</P>
<P>
   Now a shuttered ghost town, Ambassador University closed in 1997
after 33 tumultuous years. The campus is fenced off from
surrounding property, and visitors can walk undisturbed for hours
through its buildings and pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   Located in the East Texas Piney Woods three miles outside Big
Sandy, which lies north of Tyler and has a population of 1,258, the
campus comes stocked with such diverse things as farming equipment
and five Steinway pianos.
</P>
<P>
   The property will be sold off in 17 parcels, with the developed
campus of 698 acres sold as one of the auction lots. Some of the
other parcels are small enough to be developed as ranchettes.
Bidding is expected to take five days for all 10,000 items to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's incredible diversity, first-class educational
buildings, two lakes, a golf course, an airstrip and first-class
library with rare books,'' said Bernard Schnippert, chief financial
officer of the Worldwide Church of God. ``I don't know many
colleges that have those things plus beautiful scenery. While
you're on the campus you could be anywhere in the world; the
scenery is very diverse. The views are incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The campus was one of the centerpieces of the Worldwide Church,
founded by the radio and TV evangelist Herbert W. Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Since his death in 1986, the denomination has lost more than
half its 150,000 members. Armstrong's successors, Joseph Tkach; and
his successor's son, Joseph Tkach Jr., moved the church from its
fringe apocalyptic beliefs to those more in line with mainstream
evangelical denominations.
</P>
<P>
   But many members couldn't stomach the radical change and bolted.
They clung to original Worldwide beliefs that it was the only
Christian church and that the Holy Trinity is a pagan doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador College, later a university, was where believers
could safely send their children for higher education so they
wouldn't have to mix with youths of other religious backgrounds,
alumni said. It expanded to 1,100 in the early 1990s after the
closing of an affiliated California college of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Classes were coed, but there was little tolerance for typical
campus hijinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was somewhat like a military situation, like a military
school,'' said Dixon Cartwright, a 1969 Ambassador graduate and
faculty member in the early '90s. ``There were curfews, there were
rules about relationships between the sexes and dating. You
couldn't get physical. But most who went there didn't have a
problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador had a sister campus in Pasadena, Calif., which closed
as a college in 1990 but has served as the church's headquarters.
It is under contract to be sold. Millions had been poured into the
two campuses as showpieces of Armstrong's empire.
</P>
<P>
   The church's influence went far beyond its relatively small
membership through its magazine, ``The Plain Truth.'' Then there
was its ``The World Tomorrow'' radio and TV broadcasts, which
featured Armstrong's son, Garner Ted Armstrong, before he left the
church in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group is now solidly within the heart of
neo-evangelism,'' said Mark Toulouse, dean of Texas Christian
University's Brite Divinity School and a professor of American
religious history. ``Whether they can define a place within that
culture remains an open question. I would not be optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador's stormy past remains an emotional issue for many
former students and faculty.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have remained in the downsized church, a sprawling
college campus is just no longer required.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to maximize its value,'' Schnippert said. ``We would
love to see someone use the property consistent with its heritage
and make sure in some way it benefits the public.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who still adhere to Armstrong's original
teachings, the auction is seen as severing the last connection to
their former church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like it's an effort to take away any memory of the
old Worldwide Church of God,'' said Big Sandy Mayor David P. Smith,
a 1977 Ambassador graduate who has left the fold. But Smith said
the church has a ``a real financial need for the money the sale
will generate.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger over the sale has led to at least one attempt to sabotage
the auction.
</P>
<P>
   Faxes ostensibly urging East Texas businesses to bid on the
property demanded a $500 ``donation'' for a pre-auction tour while
threatening to blacklist any company that didn't cough up the
offering. Church leaders denounced the faxes as a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a chance the auction could be pre-empted by a
last-minute sale of the entire property, church leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions are continuing with several groups, they said. One
group is said to want to establish an all-male military school
based on traditions of the Citadel, which now admits women. Other
religious schools have also expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1817EST &QL; 
