u i BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-NYT &LR;      03-24 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANIS ANXIOUSLY AWAIT CLINTON'S ARRIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-INDIA, INDIA-TB) 
(js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ High anxiety has replaced great
expectations in this capital, with people anticipating that
President Clinton will arrive on Saturday not just to say hello but
also to deliver a scolding.
</P>
<P>
   This is to be Clinton's final stop on a long-awaited visit to
southern Asia. For months Pakistan's military rulers, who took
power without violence in a coup on Oct. 12, feared that Clinton
would shun them entirely, as their rivals in New Delhi had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, after five friendly days of talking, toasting and
sightseeing in India, Clinton will now make a meager five-hour stop
here, enough time to meet with Pakistan's chief executive, Gen.
Pervez Musharraf, and to address the nation on television.
</P>
<P>
   Given some of what Clinton has been saying in India, Pakistanis
may prefer that he had gone straight home. ``Reality is finally
sinking in that this is the 21st century, the New World Order, and
that nations with strong economies will get America's attention,
and that does not include Pakistan,'' said Rifaat Hussain, a
professor of international studies at Quaid-i-Azam University in
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the difference in Washington's perceptions of India and
Pakistan seems to be the difference between a potential market and
a potential disaster.
</P>
<P>
   India, a resolute democracy, is home to a booming software
industry and a rapidly multiplying middle class. Pakistan, with
democracy delayed, is nearly bankrupt, relying on a steady
intravenous drip of restructured loans from international lenders.
Social upheaval appears an increasing possibility, with poverty and
corruption pushing even more people toward Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the president's national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, said Clinton would carry a message of hard realities,
telling Musharraf that Pakistan was ``a country in trouble'' and
that a nuclear-arms race with India would be a ruinous folly.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, India and Pakistan exploded tit-for-tat tests of
nuclear weapons, with New Delhi the first to hit the button. Last
summer, the countries squared off in fierce battles in the
mountains of Kashmir, the territory that the two have fought over
since they emerged from the British Empire in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   As neighbors, India and Pakistan share more than a common
boundary. They can watch each other's television stations. And this
past week, Pakistanis scornfully viewed what seemed a love fest
between their Indian enemies and America's president.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sliding succession of indelible imagery. Clinton was
cheered wildly in India's parliament. He danced to folk music with
the woman of a Rajasthani village, and he reveled at the sight of
tigers in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal and national victory for the Indians,'' said
Najam Sethi, editor of a weekly newspaper, The Friday Times.
``There's only one superpower in the world, and that superpower has
come to them. When we see the Indian TV screen, we see such fawning
over Clinton: `Here, look, this is where Clinton sat!' And, `Here,
this is the kind of soup he ate!'''
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, the president appeared to be tilting toward India's
side on Kashmir. In a widely quoted interview with ABC News,
Clinton said, ``I believe there are those within the Pakistani
government that have supported those who engage in violence in
Kashmir.''
</P>
<P>
   To many here that seemed an endorsement of one of New Delhi's
most constant accusations, that Pakistan has complete command over
groups of Islamic militants that are creating bloody havoc in
Indian-controlled Kashmir. The Pakistanis, to the contrary,
routinely claim to supply only moral and political support to the
``holy warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf had some reason to hope that Clinton would say
something quite different. Recently, the president had called the
subcontinent ``the most dangerous place in the world today,'' a
nervous observation that might well have preceded a U.S. move to
involve itself in a coaxed settlement, something that Pakistan
wants and India does not.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, while Clinton did urge India to negotiate with
Pakistan, he said emphatically, ``I have certainly not come to
south Asia to mediate the dispute over Kashmir.'' And the president
made no mention of well-documented human-rights violations by
India's extensive army and paramilitary presence in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be accepted that Washington's old policy of
friendship with Pakistan is no more,'' wrote a columnist for a
Pakistani daily, The News.
</P>
<P>
   Often, America had employed Pakistan as reliable helpmate in the
Cold War. After the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan in 1979,
Islamabad was used as the conduit for billions of dollars in
military aid to the mujahadeen resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some of those same warriors have shifted the focus of
their jihad to India and America. Among them is Osama bin Laden,
whom the United States considers responsible for bombing two of its
embassies in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   bin Laden's name will surely come up in Clinton and Musharraf's
talks on Saturday. The accused terrorist is believed to be living
in Afghanistan, where the ruling Taliban militia is his host.
Washington has been disappointed in Pakistan's reluctance to use
its influence with the Taliban to press for bin Laden's expulsion
or arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Another certain item on the president's agenda will be a
timetable for Pakistan's return to democracy. On Thursday,
Musharraf announced that three rounds of local elections would be
held from December to July 2001. But he gave no indication of when
a full restoration of civilian government would occur _ and
Washington immediately expressed dismay.
</P>
<P>
   The general has chosen to display optimism about his meeting the
president. The two men may well hit it off. If Clinton can come
across as a hail fellow well met, so can Musharraf, a person with
an easy manner around Westerners. His brother is a doctor in
Chicago. His only son is an actuary in Boston for the state of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But the two leaders are scheduled to meet one-on-one for only 40
minutes, a brief time that could be taken up simply defining what
each means by troublesome terminology like ``terrorism'' and
``democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf, however, has expressed confidence that when Clinton
meets him in person he will find a trustworthy, altruistic soldier
_ and not an enemy of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to tell President Clinton our point of view,'' the
general said. ``I am confident that I will be able to convince
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
