<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSHEE25-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Mideast, pope has work cut out for him
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roman Catholic Christianity came to the Holy Land following
crusaders carrying swords. That was 800 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Pope John Paul II visits that sacred soil carrying an
olive branch. He wants to reconcile Jews and Christians, Muslims
and Christians and make peace among various Christian communities
there.
</P>
<P>
   That is a task worthy of the Vicar of Christ and fraught with
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   In the Holy Land, the past is present in ways most Americans
cannot understand. Age-old scars are fresh wounds. Righting the
perceived wrongs of centuries drives much contemporary
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   For many Palestinians, the 12th-century crusades to free the
Holy Land of Muslim control are as fresh as last week's news.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim-Christian conversation beyond mere platitudes will be a
major victory for the pope, whose predecessors enthusiastically
supported the marauding crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   But his toughest challenge may be reconciling warring factions
of Christians. Six different Christian communities share
responsibility for the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, which marks
the likely place of Jesus' crucifixion in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Latin Catholics _ as the Roman Catholic Church is known in the
Middle East _ Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Syrian, Egyptian Copt and
Ethiopian Christians eye one another suspiciously _ and have for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Latin Christianity is a relative newcomer. The church had little
significant presence in the Holy Land until the 12th century.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the church ran into Orthodox churches that had been there
since the first century and moved in on them.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Church built its own shrines cheek by jowl with those
of the Orthodox community. A Roman Catholic chapel stands next to
the central Greek Orthodox sanctuary in the Church of the Holy
Sepulcher. Another flanks the Orthodox chapel at the traditional
site of the Crucifixion in a different part of the building. The
19th-century Latin Church of St. Catherine stands immediately next
to the sixth-century Orthodox Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Such redundancy is a sign, in stone, of the difficulty of
finding significant common ground with other Christians in the Holy
Land.
</P>
<P>
   And the pope's hope to ease Jewish-Christian tensions is equally
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Charges of Christian complicity in the Holocaust frame his visit
to Israelis. They want an apology. But things are never that simple
for the church.
</P>
<P>
   Another Holy Land church is an unlikely symbol of that problem.
The Church of the Beatitudes near the Sea of Galilee marks the
traditional site of Jesus' Sermon on the Mount. The pope is
scheduled to offer Mass nearby today. The building, an Italianate
jewel of beauty and tranquility, was built in 1938 by Mussolini. He
was a partner with Hitler in the atrocities of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the complex web of history and faith in the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pope is in a place where miracles happen.
</P>
<P>
   stevegushee(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
