</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-MOMS0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rapport with boss affects women's job stress level
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new study confirms what many career-minded mothers
already know: Women with families pay a heavy price at home for
having a good working relationship with the boss.
</P>
<P>
   The plum assignments, carte-blanche flexibility and open-door
access to your supervisor often have trade-offs in the form of late
nights in the office and weekend homework, and that cuts into
family time, says Debra Major, co-author of the Old Dominion
University study. Major is an associate professor of psychology at
Old Dominion in Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have mutually high expectations for one another,'' Major
said. ``You expect your boss to go to bat for you and to give you
high-profile assignments. In return, your boss expects you to be
available and do what it takes to get ahead, and sometimes those
things spill over into your family time.''
</P>
<P>
   While managers often believe they treat their workers equitably,
many acknowledge that they give flexibility and promotions to those
with whom they've forged personal and professional alliances, Major
said.
</P>
<P>
   The study polled 206 women in a variety of jobs _ from
secretaries to teachers to doctors _ in the Hampton Roads area of
Virginia. Major said she was surprised by the findings because she
and colleague Karyn H. Bernas, a doctoral student at the
university, expected to find that women had less problems with
on-the-job stress if they had good a relationship with their boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it says is that there are trade-offs,'' Major said.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, those career women are ``in a better position
to negotiate how the work gets done'' as opposed to women who are
on the ``mommy track'' _ a term used to describe working mothers
whose careers have been derailed because they have families _ or
scrutinized closely when they ask for time off to attend their
child's school play, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace expert Connie Glaser called the study's finding
``quite interesting. But I wouldn't trade having a good boss for
any other kind of compensation on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaser is the author of ``When Money Isn't Enough,'' due out in
paperback April 1, about women who are redefining what it means to
be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems a small price to pay because there's a greater price
to pay for working for a boss you don't get along with. That's
going to undermine your self-esteem, and that's going to really
play out at home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that women with hearty personalities _
those who view challenges as opportunities and believe their
actions and behavior determined what happens in their lives _ fare
better on the job. Not surprisingly, too, women who had the
emotional support of their families did better at work and at home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
