<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT25-COX     03-24 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT CASE FACES WEEKEND CRUNCH AS RULING LOOMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Microsoft Corp. and government antitrust
lawyers, the moment of truth arrived Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The software giant put a last-minute settlement offer on the
table after U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson reportedly
warned that he has written a verdict in the landmark case and plans
to issue it Tuesday unless the two sides report substantial
progress toward a full settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers believe Jackson almost certainly would find
Microsoft guilty of flouting the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   If an eleventh-hour deal struck, it is likely to be crafted by
Judge Richard Posner of the U.S. 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Chicago, whom Jackson enlisted last November as a mediator in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are prepared to go to Chicago this weekend to review
such a deal with Posner, but no talks were scheduled by Friday
evening. Neither Microsoft nor the Justice Department would
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's last-minute offer would put a variety of
restrictions on its future business conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The company would agree to abide by uniform licensing of its
flagship Windows operating system for all comers. That means all
personal computer makers would pay the same price for the software,
with no further volume discounts for such long-time partners as
Compaq and Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has also offered to open up its proprietary Windows
source code so that other software firms will face no disadvantage
in writing their own ``hooks'' into the operating system for
applications that might compete with Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, however, whether this conduct-based
remedy will satisfy the Justice Department and the 19 state
attorneys general who have so far successfully prosecuted the case
in Jackson's courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Washington agrees to a deal that imposes sweeping
restrictions on Microsoft's business practices, it is by no means a
sure bet that the attorney generals in such key states as Iowa, New
York, and Connecticut will go along with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys general in Florida, Ohio, Maryland and Kansas are
no longer pressing for a structural remedy that would break up
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-line faction is holding out for splitting Microsoft
into at least two separate units. One would market Windows, and the
other applications such as Microsoft Word.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have strong incentive to settle.
</P>
<P>
   In cutting a deal, Microsoft would avoid the risk of Jackson
ordering a breakup at a later stage in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the trauma of forced breakup or a protracted appeals
process, devastating ``findings of fact'' already issued by Jackson
could be used in 108 class-action suits currently pending against
Microsoft. If the case is settled, those findings recede in legal
value for other litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The government, on the other hand, would avoid a lengthy legal
appeals by Microsoft. The Justice Department also faces the risk
that if a Republican president is elected this November, it would
take a radically different approach and refuse to press an appeal.
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican presidential
nominee, is on record as opposing a breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it may prove difficult to find common ground, despite the
mounting pressures to do so.
</P>
<P>
   University of Baltimore law professor Bob Lande, who has
followed the case closely, noted that Microsoft will not settle
unless it is allowed to accept a ``nonstructural'' remedy that
keeps it intact.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department antitrust chief Joel Klein told Congress on
Wednesday that the remedy ``ought to be commensurate'' with
Microsoft's practices, which Jackson has already ruled to be
monopolistic and harmful to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how the Justice Department can accept a
nonstructural remedy,'' Lande said. ``I don't see how Microsoft can
accept a structural remedy. Posner's task is to try to split the
baby in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Microsoft, which touched 115 earlier Friday, fell 3/16
to 111 11/16 in late Nasdaq trading. The stock gained 8.4 percent
Thursday following widespread reports of renewed settlement
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
