<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS     03-24 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MINISTER ACCUSED OF WAR CRIMES DEPORTED TO U.N. TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The State Department said Friday that a Rwandan
clergyman who spent nearly three years in a Laredo jail was
extradited to Africa to face genocide charges before a United
Nations tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a former Seventh-day Adventist pastor,
is the first person arrested on American soil to face such a trial,
said Don DeGabrielle, an assistant U.S. attorney. Other
extraditions from the United States have returned the accused to a
nation, not an international court.
</P>
<P>
   The International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda is being held in
Arusha, Tanzania, an African nation on the Indiana Ocean that
borders Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has accused Ntakirutimana of leading attackers
armed with machetes, grenades and guns in a murderous April 1994
rampage that killed dozens of people who were hiding in his church.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana is a
Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are all condemned to die! It is all over for you!'' the
pastor said, according to a witness who later hid among the
corpses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ntakirutimana's lawyer nor his son, a physician who
practices in Laredo, could be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly man's lawyer, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey
Clark, has said that his client would not receive a fair trial
because Rwandans questioned by Ntakirutimana's counsel could face
violent reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has maintained that his client is being unjustly accused
as a result of tribal hatred.
</P>
<P>
   DeGabrielle said U.S. Marshals and a physician flew with
Ntakirutimana from Laredo to Houston Thursday morning. From there
he was to continue to Amsterdam and then to Tanzania.
Ntakirutimana's age has been given variously as 73 to 75.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials were not certain how soon he would
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright signed a
warrant authorizing Ntakirutimana to be extradited, following four
years of legal appeals that led all the way to the U.S. Supreme
Court. In January, the high court declined to hear his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The former minister was first arrested in September 1996 after
legally emigrating here with his wife to live with their son. He
has been in and out of jail in Laredo since.
</P>
<P>
   The trials in Arusha are only the third such international
forum. Others include the ongoing tribunal at The Hague,
Netherlands, addressing allegations of genocide in the former
Yugoslavia, and the trials against Nazi criminals in Nuremberg,
Germany, following World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
