A7136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      03-24 0281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, March 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pockets of moderate rain will develop across the Gulf States on
Saturday as a slow cold front combines with a compact jet-stream
disturbance to lift moist air from the Gulf of Mexico. These
patchwork rains, some with thunder, will stay mostly in a corridor
from North Texas across the lower Mississippi Valley to the
southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow, broken line of generally light showers will accompany
the northern end of the cold front quickly across the eastern Great
Lakes and into western New England later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the front, cool winds from the northwest
averaging 15 to 30 mph will prevail across the upper Mississippi
Valley. Gusts to 40 mph are possible in spots. Rain showers will
dampen parts of the northwest Great Lakes, with snow showers near
the Minnesota-Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Daring Rescue
</P>
<P>
   Canadian helicopter pilots plucked sailors from the turbulent
Atlantic on Friday after their ship sank on Thursday about 400
miles northeast of Bermuda. Seas up to 12 feet high hindered rescue
efforts. Protracted winds associated with a sluggish low-pressure
system over the middle Atlantic persistently blew over a long
stretch of water, causing increasingly rough seas. The low was
orphaned by the steering winds of the jet stream, which were
rerouted far to the north by a blocking high-pressure system off
Northern Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
