<HEADLINE>
WORKS IN PROGRESS OF THINKERS AND RETHINKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
(With NEW-IDEAS-MONEY, NEW-IDEAS-BALKANS, NEW-IDEAS-FLOWERS) 
(lb) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the most raked-over historical fields to the latest
technology, scholars and researchers continually manage to ask new
questions, rethink old verities and produce fresh insights. Some
ideas may turn into breakthroughs and others may turn out to be
dead ends, but the journey is rarely boring. Here is a handful of
works in progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1834EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH25-COX     03-24 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush invades Clinton territory
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   White House wannabe George W. Bush on Friday took his campaign
to Little Rock, a southern capital that might be able to give
Austinites a glimpse of what happens when an ex-resident becomes
president.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A Bush presidency would not mean we're all going to
be federal judges or ambassadors. It would not mean a quick,
federally-funded fix to our traffic woes. And it probably won't
mean a second presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, the experience has been predictable. Folks who
liked Gov. Bill Clinton think President Bill Clinton has been good
for Little Rock. Folks who thought Gov. Bill Clinton was Slick
Willie are glad he is becoming a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The empirical data are not quite as polarized. Little Rock
business leaders say the economy is humming along nicely, but they
think it's part of the national uptick. Arkansas gets healthy doses
of federal aid, but it always has.
</P>
<P>
   As for hard-core evidence that the city has produced a
president, so far there's not much, short of indictments and
subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, seven months prior to the election, it's tough to
gauge how a Bush presidency might affect the city. But experts say
it will, and part of the story could be what, or who, we would
lose. ``If (Bush) becomes president it will really impact this
city,'' said Herb Berkowitz of the Washington-based Heritage
Foundation, which has studied presidential transitions. ``I would
suspect that hundreds of your neighbors would move to a place
called Washington D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about potential impact on Austin, Bush is quick to
remind that he's not really from these parts. Though he's lived in
public housing here since January 1995, Bush says he's not the
Austinite that Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really more identified with Austin than I have been. He
was raised in this part (of the state). I was raised out in
Midland,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But he is convinced that Austin, and Texas, would benefit if he
leaves town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have a positive effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Mayor Kirk Watson, a good Democrat, does not want Bush to
become president. But the mayor can see the upside to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage would be that he is familiar with Austin,'' said
Watson. ``He is familiar with what we need and you would hope that
because of that familiarity he would be in a position to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hazelwood, president and chief executive officer of the
Greater Austin Chamber of Commerce, said a Bush presidency would
produce ``natural interest in where the president comes from, and
the president is going to be returning here periodically.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, however, is where ``here'' will be. The Texas
White House probably would be the 1,600-acre ranch Bush recently
purchased near Crawford, west of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I win,'' said Bush, ``I anticipate spending time here
with Laura and my family at our place up in Central Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   For the national press corps, that would mean quality time in
the festive Waco area, much like the press corps of the 1960s
bivouacked in the Hill County during Johnson's frequent trips to
his ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't think much of hanging around Johnson City, but
they learned how to buy barbecue and beef jerky,'' said George
Christian, who was Johnson's press secretary. ``They loved it, for
awhile. They thought it was real wild west stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in Little Rock, the biggest bricks-and-mortar evidence of the
Clinton presidency is still to come. The city is getting a
presidential library, though not everyone is thrilled about it.
Plans to name a street for Clinton were scaled back after someone
suggested ``Impeachment Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for us having a national root canal on our local
politics, I don't think it's benefited us one iota,'' Chris
Carnahan of Little Rock said of having a former local resident in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, of course, as executive director of the Arkansas
Republican Party, has a bad attitude about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Little Rock compares the Clinton presidency to
dental discomfort. From day one, the Clinton candidacy raised the
profile of a city previously best defined by the 1957 integration
crisis at Central High School, where Bush had a campaign event on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Harvel, head of the Little Rock Chamber of Commerce, said
the city has benefited from the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people across the nation know about Austin,'' he
said. ``Not everyone knew about Little Rock. Now, everyone knows
where Little Rock is. Now, no one asks what state it's in.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas Democratic Party Chairman Vaughn McQuary says the
attention has been positive for Little Rock, if not for all Little
Rockians (Little Rockers? Little Rockites? Pebbles?).
</P>
<P>
   ``The never-ending Whitewater investigation has devastated a lot
of good people here in Arkansas for no reason other than they were
friends of the president,'' said McQuary, who blames vindictive
Republicans. ``As far as being able to go back to the good ol' days
of Lyndon Johnson and getting projects into your state, I don't
think this president or the next president or the next president
after that will be able to do those types of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous president agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president should stay out of that,'' ex-President
George Bush said of nudging federal money and projects homeward.
``It's different than the LBJ days. I don't think you can, on
public expenditures of money, leave yourself open to the charge
that you are paving your own state, as opposed to a congressman who
is expected to do that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But a president can find ways to help the homefolks, Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, we had the Republican National Convention in
Houston because people saw that would please me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas already has some high-profile examples of what it means to
have a native son in high places. The LBJ Space Center near Houston
is a product of the Lyndon B. Johnson administration.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has two presidential libraries: Johnson's at the
University of Texas and Bush's at Texas A&AMP;M University. The
Electoral College will decide whether a George W. Bush presidential
library will be needed, but the president of a Dallas college
sounds interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No discussion has taken place with the governor, but with
Laura Bush being an alumna of SMU we would be receptive to
discussions about the opportunity,'' said Southern Methodist
University President R. Gerald Turner. ``But this is obviously
premature.'' You may contact Ken Herman at
kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
