<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-24 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN FEEL RICH WITH RIGHT VALUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Marry Tom Arnold?''
</P>
<P>
   The money mania that spawned a hit game show and a
stomach-turning ratings stunt has gotten so out of hand, Roseanne's
ex-husband now has a Web site devoted to helping him get dates.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian, however, is not promising potential brides a pot
of gold _ just the chance to marry a relatively famous,
twice-divorced actor with a low sperm count.
</P>
<P>
   Since I am not making any of this up, I think it is fair to say
that, as a nation, we have counterbalanced the dizzying heights of
the bull market with all-time lows in values.
</P>
<P>
   But who can blame us?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INSTANT-WEALTH STORIES ABOUND &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems just about every day there's a story in newspapers or
magazines, on television or the World Wide Web about the latest
batch of twentysomething workers who took a chance on an Internet
start-up and struck it rich with stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Or there's the gossip about the stay-at-home mom in the
playgroup of your boss' cousin's best friend who brings in $50,000
a month day trading while her kids nap.
</P>
<P>
   Or the billboards that urge you to spend a dollar twice a week
on the chance to win $4 million or more in the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of pressure to get rich quick has many of us thinking
we are failing in this economy when we don't have seven-figure bank
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of instant wealth and instant information, the idea
of keeping up with the Joneses has led to a national sense of
inadequacy more debilitating than the old-fashioned neighborhood
envy.
</P>
<P>
   We worry that we don't make enough, don't invest correctly and
don't know the right people so we can invest correctly, say in a
hot IPO for a B2B start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, we worry that when this economic era is an entry in
the encyclopedia as the second Gilded Age of the 20th Century, we
won't have an answer for our children when they ask us: ``Why
didn't you make a million in the bull market?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FINANCIAL SECURITY IS RELATIVE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I was concentrating on taking care of those things
that were of value to me: my family, my health and enjoying my
job,'' says Kurt Goedecke, a financial planner with the Lutheran
Brotherhood. ``Getting rich is not one of my values.''
</P>
<P>
   One trick to feeling satisfied with where you are financially at
a time when playing the stock market has become the national
pastime is to figure out your values and stick to them.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of financial security is a relative feeling. How many
times have you read about people who grew up dirt poor but didn't
realize the magnitude of their family's poverty until they were
adults? Their parents provided them with a sense of well-being that
had nothing to do with income and material goods.
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse your net worth with your self-worth. By defining
yourself in terms that reflect what is truly important to you, you
immunize yourself from the effects of ``affluenza.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to inoculate your psyche is to share what you do
have. Being able to give away some money and time to organizations
or charities that reflect your values will increase your sense of
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Only the truly impoverished _ people with bankrupt inner lives _
have nothing to give someone else.
</P>
<P>
   If you try all of that and you still feel like you are missing
out, take comfort from one last vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a child asks you what you did in the bull market, that's a
good time to discuss risk,'' says Robert Weinberger, a clinical
psychologist and owner of Weinberger &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Come to terms with how much risk you are willing to take. If you
can't bear the thought of losing half your principal investment or
more on an Internet stock, then you are not going to be a
high-flier in this market.
</P>
<P>
   Accept that although you could have taken a lot of risk, you
chose to go for less immediate results, so that in the long term
you didn't suffer from big losses.
</P>
<P>
   That's not failing to capitalize on the bull market. It's just
merely deciding to not worry about getting rich and, instead,
concentrate on not becoming poor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
