<HEADLINE>
STOCK TRADERS' BEHAVIOR IS FERTILE FIELD FOR STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
(lb) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do bond and securities traders trade the way they do? That's
the question Caitlin Zaloom, an anthropologist at the University of
California at Berkeley, is trying to answer. Zaloom wants to know
how technology is affecting the money managers who make decisions
that direct capital flow around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, she says, she is trying to understand how traders
make certain kinds of decisions at a given moment in the trading
pit. ``For example, how, without the tools of calculation available
outside the pit, do they decide when to buy and sell?'' Zaloom
said.
</P>
<P>
   She is comparing the intensely personal interaction between
traders of 30-year Treasury-bond futures at the Chicago Board of
Trade, the world's leading futures exchange, to the thoroughly
computerized tools used in a securities trading room at a private
investment bank in London.
</P>
<P>
   Zaloom's first stop was Chicago, where she was able to observe
the action firsthand as a clerk. The Board of Trade operates under
what is known as the ``open outcry auction market'' system. Instead
of relying on today's disembodied trading systems, it relies almost
entirely on face-to-face relationships to trade tens of millions of
Treasury-bond futures around the world every month.
</P>
<P>
   The trading pit is octagonal with steps descending toward the
middle, allowing all buyers and sellers to see one another. Buy and
sell orders are placed by ritualized hand gestures. The hierarchy
is literal: People who are new or who are not perceived as
particularly adept are relegated to the bottom of the pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any given moment, you can watch the personalities and the
emotionality of decision-making in times of intense activity,''
Zaloom said.
</P>
<P>
   Traders take a step up by unspoken consensus, when the senior
traders see that they can handle more trade volume and more
financial risk. None of the traditional measures like education or
connections guarantee success in the pit.
</P>
<P>
   The only measure of success, Zaloom said, is the ability to make
money in the moment. And how that is accomplished ``is discipline _
the ability to admit that you're wrong and sell when the market is
going against you, not convincing yourself it'll turn in your
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pit traders Zaloom interviewed said that when they
found themselves thinking in the ways they were trained to think _
as lawyers, for example _ it hampered their ability to trade. ``To
be deliberative is to miss the market,'' she said. ``The market
doesn't exist outside this exact moment in time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if immediacy is the prime factor in the futures pit, she
said, deliberation is at the core of decision-making for fund
managers, like those she has been studying in London. She is still
waiting for permission to observe their daily operations firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to these people is incredibly complex,'' she said.
``They want to keep their decision process to themselves because
it's how they make money.''
</P>
<P>
   She says that embedded in the computerized, predictive tools
these financial institutions use ``is a model of human behavior
that assumes the market will act in a certain way; it will produce
an outcome that will happen again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Trade, on the other hand, depends on a a pit
trader's social savvy. Zaloom likens it to a poker game, where
traders learn how to read the other players and the feel of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Zaloom finds the contrast fascinating. Fund managers champion
the use of computers, she says, ``because they provide a level of
rationality. They get rid of personalized relationships; thus they
believe the market will become a more rational, efficient
institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to rephrase the question as `Where do those emotional
relationships go?' It doesn't make sense that they disappear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
