<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, March 25 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Harassment of gay men and women in
the American military is widespread, especially in the form of
offensive remarks, derogatory jokes and gestures, and an
overwhelming majority of service members believe their superiors
and colleagues tolerate it ``to some extent,'' according to a
Pentagon survey released Friday. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT23.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Under pressure from two
federal judges, lawyers for Microsoft and the government are
scrambling to see whether they can settle their antitrust case
within the next few days, and Microsoft presented a new settlement
proposal on Friday. Lawyers for the Justice Department and 19 state
attorneys general were studying it, trying to decide whether it was
serious enough to warrant crash settlement negotiations over the
weekend. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-UNDERCOVER-COPS (New York) _ To curb drug dealing and the
violence it spawns, New York City has embarked on an ambitious and
expensive narcotics enforcement drive, known as Operation Condor,
that for the past two months has put 500 additional police
officers, some in uniform and some in plainclothes, on the streets
to stage undercover drug stings and roust dealers from corners in
high-crime neighborhoods. Police officials say the expansion of
narcotics operations has been a great success, noting that Condor
has produced a 36 percent increase in narcotics arrests. But
critics dispute this portrayal of Operation Condor, saying that the
aggressive tactics being employed to arrest people for often minor
crimes have only increased tensions in a city where many black and
Hispanic citizens already view the police with suspicion or fear.
By Laurie Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Kampala, Uganda) _ The Ugandan police said Friday
that they had found the corpses of 153 people, including women and
children, buried under a building used by the cult involved in a
fire last week in which 500 of its members died. (Summary from
wires) By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECTION (Moscow) _ In an ugly burst of negative
campaigning, Russia's state-owned television has asserted that the
leading liberal candidate in Sunday's presidential election is
supported by Jews, foreigners and homosexuals. The prime-time
attack on Grigori Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko
faction, was broadcast Thursday night by the ORT television
network. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ARGERICH-PIANIST (New York) _ Few people who have heard the
tempestuous, Argentina-born pianist Martha Argerich perform ever
forget it. She is a colossal technician, a powerfully intuitive
musician, and an electrifying performer. But Argerich is the most
enigmatic figure in classical music today, by turns passionate,
disarming and chaotic. A profile. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ This year's partisan battle over
the federal budget, which lurched forward early Friday when the
House narrowly passed a Republican tax and spending blueprint, has
a familiar ring to it. Republicans want a big tax cut, more money
for the military and reductions in just about everything else.
Democrats are trying to expand or at least protect spending on a
wide array of domestic programs. Each side is attacking the other
in apocalyptic terms. But it is worth noting that prosperity has
brought the parties closer on fiscal policy than either of them
usually admits. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
