<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ AND DELL NOTEBOOKS SPARKLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Beta testers and computer industry professionals
who've been using Windows 2000 for a while all seem to agree on one
thing _ the new operating system from Microsoft really shines on
notebook computers.
</P>
<P>
   That's a refreshing change from its predecessor, Windows NT 4.0,
which was abominable on a portable PC. From its lack of
plug-and-play capabilities to its arcane networking setup to its
nonexistent power management, NT 4.0 was a laptop user's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   To check whether the praise is justified, I've been living with
a pair of notebooks with Windows 2000 installed. I've been pleased
with the plug-and-play features and the stability, though I can't
say these machines haven't locked up on me. And configuring the
operating system to talk to a corporate network can still be
daunting for an everyday user.
</P>
<P>
   The notebook PCs, meanwhile, are pretty slick. Both are
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _ Armada M700, $3,499, Compaq Computer Corp.: This is the bigger
brother to the Armada M300, the ultra-portable PC that won my
Attaboy Award for best notebook in 1999. (See
www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/tech/415820.) It's also the worthy
successor to the popular Digital Hi-Note line, which Compaq
acquired when it bought Digital Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The M700 falls into a category somewhere between ultra-portables
and full-sized notebooks. It's aimed at road warriors who want a
full-sized keyboard and screen but still want to shed some weight.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried had a 500-megahertz Intel Pentium III chip; 64
megabytes of memory, which I later bumped up to 128; an
11.2-gigabyte hard drive; built-in 56K fax modem; a DVD-ROM drive;
8 MB of video memory; an ATI Rage Mobility graphics adapter; and a
14.1-inch active-matrix screen.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's specifications indicate this notebook is about 5
pounds, but that's with a smaller, 13.3-inch screen. Mine felt more
like a solid 6, particularly with the DVD installed. It also comes
in a very solid magnesium case.
</P>
<P>
   The M700 uses a trackpoint-style pointing device _ it looks like
a pencil eraser jammed between the G and H keys _ which may be
falling out of favor. While I don't mind it, I showed this notebook
to a lot of folks who looked at the nub and said, ``Eeew, I don't
like that.'' Most of them expressed a preference for the touchpad
that lets you use a finger to move the mouse cursor _ which is the
pointing device used on the smaller M300.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is expansive and comfortable to use, with a
spacious wrist-rest that also houses the computer's speakers. My
only complaint here is that some useful keys _ such as the Delete
key _ are shrunken. There's plenty of room for more full-sized
keys, and I don't know about you, but I make enough typing errors
that a big, fat Delete key is a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Battery life was about average _ I usually got close to 2 1/2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The M700 was a fast computer _ particularly once I added an
additional 64 MB of memory. Windows 2000 really is happiest with
128 MB, I believe, just as Windows 98 really gets jumping at 64 MB.
The memory-chip moguls must love Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first Windows 2000 notebook I tried. I learned here
that, while the operating system will let you swap out devices such
as DVD and floppy drives, you have to disable the devices first. I
also learned that not disabling the devices is a good way to lock
up this supposedly stable operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But other than through my own boneheadedness, Windows 2000
didn't crash on the M700. Nor did any of the applications I was
running, some of which are prone to nasty behavior on some Windows
98 machines.
</P>
<P>
   I did have some problems finding the right settings to make it
talk to the Chronicle's corporate network. The settings dialogues
are different enough from both Windows NT and 98 that I had to
resort to trial and error.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latitude LS, $2,600, Dell Computer Corp.: This is Dell's
second shot at an ultraportable notebook. The first, a variation of
the Sharp Actius, was a nice machine _ but this is better.
</P>
<P>
   The Latitude LS is a classic ultraportable, with that category's
natural benefits as well as failings. It's thin and quite light,
but it achieves its small size by using external drives and losing
the serial port. That means if you need to install software or will
be accepting data disks on the road, you'll need to carry the
floppy and CD drives along.
</P>
<P>
   My test unit came with a 400-MHz Pentium III processor, 128 MB
of memory, a 6-GB hard drive, a built-in 56K fax modem, an Ethernet
jack, external CD and floppy drives, a NeoMagic graphics adapter
with 2.5 MB of video memory and an 11.1-inch active-matrix screen.
</P>
<P>
   It weighs in at just under 4 pounds; a larger optional battery
kicks the weight up substantially. It is about three-fourths the
size of a traditional notebook computer, about an inch thin and is
packed into a stylish silver-colored magnesium case.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is slightly undersized, but comfortable to use.
Like the M700, some keys are smaller than others, including the
Delete key. It uses the touchpad as a pointing device, and it's a
nice implementation.
</P>
<P>
   The Latitude LS has just about every connection you'd need
except for the aforementioned serial port. An optional port
replicator is available for $199.
</P>
<P>
   Battery life was excellent, with the Latitude reliably getting
over three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the active-matrix screen can only handle up to
800-by-600 resolution in normal mode. Sure, you can set it at
1,024-by-768 in a so-called ``virtual desktop,'' but this is
maddening to use. The screen image slides from side to side and top
to bottom to give you the impression you're getting more real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000 performed well here, except for one problem. A
couple of times the system would not come out of hibernation
properly, locking up. Restarting the Latitude cured the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I really enjoyed using this notebook, though I wish Dell had
found a way to have swapable drives built into the case. I really
dislike lugging external drives. Maybe on version 2.0?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
