<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO TELL IF YOUR PROCESSOR IS A CELERON OR A PENTIUM II 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I bought a new PC with Windows 98. The processor is
an Intel Celeron. While booting, the configuration reads Celeron.
But in the Windows system settings, it reads as a Pentium II
processor. How do I determine if the vendor has really given me a
Celeron or if he has given me a lesser-performing processor and
tampered with the CMOS settings to read as a Celeron?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, if the vendor tampered with the BIOS to force the
computer to show a Celeron processor when you actually got a
Pentium II, you're getting the better end of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Celeron processor was released after the Pentium
II, it's not quite as powerful. A Celeron is really a Pentium II
chip, but with less built-in cache, which is a memory buffer that
speeds the transfer of data into and out of the processor.
</P>
<P>
   When Windows 98 was originally released, Celeron processors were
not around. As a result, Windows doesn't recognize them. Instead,
they appear as Pentium II chips. But your BIOS is probably giving
you accurate information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a printer and a scanner that use USB ports, so I
bought a hub to add more USB connections. Then I bought an MP3
player that uses USB. When I plug it into the hub, I am told there
is not enough power. What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are two types of USB hubs _ powered and unpowered.
Unpowered hubs get their ``juice'' from the computer itself.
Powered hubs rely on an AC adapter.
</P>
<P>
   Some USB devices require more power than others. For example, a
USB printer has its own power supply, but an MP3 player may require
more power than it gets from its batteries in order to transfer
files from the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Or, it may be a device such as Microsoft's IntelliMouse
Explorer, which includes a tiny camera and an LED. Those devices
each require a relatively large amount of power, and a powered hub
is required.
</P>
<P>
   Some vendors, including Microsoft, are now selling keyboards
with USB ports on them, which seems like a clever idea except that
the keyboards don't usually have their own power supply. That means
the keyboard is an unpowered hub, and will not support all USB
devices.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do is plug the MP3 player directly into one of the
USB ports on your PC. Most PCs now have at least two USB plugs, so
you can then plug your unpowered hub into the second port.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a new cable modem, and I understand there's a patch I
can get that will make my connection even faster. Where can I get
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Try www.speedguide.net/Cablemodems/cablepatches.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   What most of these patches do is change settings in the Windows
registry to improve the way your PC connects to the Internet. You
need different settings if you have a high-speed connection than
the defaults, which in Windows are set for traditional modems.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some fixes from Microsoft on that page, including
one for a bug in Microsoft's TCP/IP component.
</P>
<P>
   As always, use these patches with caution _ and your mileage may
vary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
