<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING AND TALKING MAY MEAN CRASHING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's the hottest, newest, most-talked-about employer
liability issue of the moment: employees who conduct business on
their company cellular phones while driving.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone does it _ that's why companies issue cellular
phones _ but the liability question inevitably comes up when folks
get so carried away with the phone conversation that they run into
other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are having to pay damages, Rodney Glover, a lawyer
with Gardner, Carton &AMP; Douglas in Washington, D.C., told those
gathered this week for a seminar sponsored by the Houston Human
Resource Management Association at the George R. Brown Convention
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Glover scared the group with a story about how financial
services firm Smith Barney ended up settling a cellular phone case
for $150,000 in addition to the firm's liability insurance coverage
after one of its brokers hit a motorcyclist while trying to dial a
client. The motorcyclist died after the broker ran a red light.
</P>
<P>
   The news caught many of the human resource managers by surprise.
An informal survey of about a dozen managers revealed that most had
never even considered that potential liability of DWT.
</P>
<P>
   Only one manager said the subject had come up at the branch
manager level, but hadn't gone anywhere beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   But don't mention the company, the manager said with a nervous
laugh. He didn't exactly want it getting around.
</P>
<P>
   For most companies, though, it's not on the radar screen. And
that could be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ISSUE BECOMES MORE SENSITIVE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a sensitive issue for companies, especially in light of
recent news on the dangers of driving while talking on a cellular
phone. One study compared the practice to drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   And there is growing resentment against drivers who talk on
their cellular phones. Parents who have lost their children because
of cellular phone accidents are campaigning for laws to prohibit
their use in moving vehicles. And cars are sporting bumper stickers
that read: ``Hang Up and Drive!''
</P>
<P>
   But companies, eager to boost productivity, often encourage
employees to use the cellular phones to make sales calls.
</P>
<P>
   It's often an implicit requirement, said Dennis Herlong, a civil
trial lawyer who handles a variety of employment cases in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Like the human resource managers, lawyers haven't exactly been
sitting around thinking about cellular phone liability.
</P>
<P>
   But since the question came up, Herlong said he recommends that
companies set firm policies that prohibit employees from using a
cellular phone while driving. Employees should be required to pull
over when they need to use the phone. Otherwise, employers should
be held responsible for accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't feel comfortable turning people loose with a cell
phone,'' Herlong said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would Margie Harris, an employment lawyer in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to install a speaker into employees' cars so
drivers don't have to hold a car phone. When you dial a phone, your
concentration is diverted, said Harris, who has been known to talk
on her phone while driving but saves her dialing for stoplights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COMMON SENSE MAY CLASH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several of Houston's largest companies were surveyed on the
subject _ and many managers responded with something like ``huh?''
But at least one, Apache Corp., the energy company, is talking
about the talking-while-driving issue.
</P>
<P>
   Apache recently included a warning in one of its periodic safety
bulletins to its field staff about studies linking the increase in
accidents with cellular phone use. The bulletin urged employees to
use common sense when using their cellular phones in a vehicle,
said Tony Lentini, vice president of public and international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also looking into whether it should establish a
cellular phone driving policy but there are a few issues to resolve
first, such as how to enforce it and how should the company treat
phones that have hands-free speakers, Lentini said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lawyers often find a problem behind every rule, and
Glover, the seminar's speaker, pointed out that telling employees
to pull over before they make a call from the car could create
another liability.
</P>
<P>
   After all, what happens if an employee is attacked at a rest
area?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7151 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-BMW-ART-$A     03-24 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-BMW-ART-$ADV26-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BMW X5 4.4i: GOSPEL OF BMW, TRANSLATED ANEW  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)   (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Driving the BMW X5, you might titter an aha! _ as if you've
caught somebody failing to practice his preaching. It's the feeling
you'd get after sitting through a fiery sermon on demon rum, then
bumping into the reverend in a barroom, tossing back shots of
tequila.
</P>
<P>
   For years, BMW has spread the gospel of Ultimate Driving
Machines, by which it meant high-performance cars with rear-wheel
drive, low-slung suspensions, crisp manual shifters and glued-down
road manners.
</P>
<P>
   Even while competitors like Mercedes-Benz jumped head-first into
the sport utility market, BMW stood back with smug detachment. But,
just as it succumbed to pressure from self-indulgent Americans and
added cup holders, it has now joined the truck parade with the 2000
X5.
</P>
<P>
   The company would prefer that you not call the X5 an SUV, but a
``sports activity vehicle.'' While it differs considerably in some
ways from other rugged-outside, soft-inside vehicles, in the end it
is perhaps not so different after all. However much the company
would like you to consider the X5 a new concept in transportation,
it walks and quacks much like a duck, er, truck.
</P>
<P>
   In truck fashion, the X5 sits relatively high, and it puts power
on the road through all four wheels. It weighs a hefty 4,828 pounds
and will tow three tons. The doors are heavy and trucklike, and
though the climb inside is less steep than in most big SUVs, you
still pull yourself up into the cabin. The driver looks down on
ordinary cars, including other BMWs.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other premium-priced sport utilities, the X5 has a
one-piece structure, not a body on a separate frame, plus a
sophisticated independent suspension. Some parts are shared with
BMW cars. Unlike most 4-by-4 trucks, it doesn't have a low gear
range for off-roading.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, BMW went to extreme lengths to lower the
center of gravity; this was deemed crucial in minimizing the tippy
feel of sport utilities and in providing a semblance of BMW's
sporty driving dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   This effort, coupled with a body structure nearly as rigid as a
BMW sedan's and perfect front-rear weight distribution, indeed
makes the X5 the best-handling sport utility around. But, as the
SAV label suggests, the utility is missing. You couldn't take it up
a rocky trail if you wanted, and its cargo space _ 16 cubic feet
with the rear seat up _ is smaller than a Taurus' trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Such a design was no accident. BMW is responding to consumers'
wishes for an SUV that's actually a car with attitude _ that looks
as if it could roam the Serengeti but is more at home in Saddle
River.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the company needed a vehicle that wouldn't cannibalize its
5-Series wagons or the true off-roaders of its Land Rover
subsidiary (which Ford has agreed to buy). So the X5 is either a
trucklike car or a carlike truck, and it has the pluses and minuses
of both.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the concept of a Bimmer SUV is appealing, so
expectations are high. Starting last fall, queries came from
friends, colleagues, strangers: Have you seen it? Have you driven
it? How much? I picked up the test vehicle on 43rd Street; by the
time I reached 57th I'd fielded admiring questions and thumbs-up
signals at five stoplights.
</P>
<P>
   But the hip 20-somethings who seemed most impressed aren't
likely to buy a vehicle with a sticker of $55,315. (The base price
of the 4.4i, the V-8 model, is $49,970.) There are reports that the
German head of a publishing company is driven to work in one.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a chauffeur-driven X5 will amuse anyone who has had
much seat time, for the stiff suspension that helps the X5 handle
adroitly results in a jarring ride. It is one thing to be
jackhammered in an M roadster just above the pavement; it is
another thing altogether to experience buckboard motions in a
vehicle high off the road.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ride is a negative, the X5 handles well enough to
make you a believer. The all-new unit body exudes quiet strength;
the chassis is taut and responsive; the rack-and-pinion steering is
heavy _ perhaps too heavy _ and the huge brakes are superlative.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Several runs on an autocross course, part of the Ultimate
Driving Experience program that seeks to lure new BMW customers,
left no doubt about the X5's stability and abilities. It performs
much like a BMW car, which is to say very well.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is essentially the same 4.4-liter V-8 used in BMW's
big sedans, in this case with 282 horsepower and 324 foot-pounds of
torque. Although not quite as fast as the 342-horsepower V-8 in the
Mercedes ML55 _ the reigning hot rod of SUVs _ it is close enough,
especially considering that the ML55 costs $15,000 more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The X5's five-speed transmission is a gem, too, although its
Steptronic self-shifting feature isn't as much fun as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   A V-6 model, due in late spring for $40,000 and up, will also
offer a five-speed manual.
</P>
<P>
   Either version has a full-time all-wheel-drive system that
ordinarily sends a third of the power to the front wheels and
two-thirds to the rear, an effort to preserve the BMW rear-drive
feel. The system also relies heavily on traction controls, applying
the brake to a slipping wheel and feeding torque to tires with
grip.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system _ the Mercedes M-Class's is similar _ works well
on moderately bad roads but is less practical in severe conditions
where wheel spin is desirable. Nor are the X5's big, soft tires
helpful in wintry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The X5 comes with a lot of technological bells and whistles,
including dynamic stability control, which helps to prevent skids,
and dynamic brake control, which reinforces the driver's effort in
panic stops. A hill descent feature borrowed from Land Rover holds
the vehicle to a steady, slow speed on steep downhill grades.
</P>
<P>
   The X5's cabin is rich, with wide panels of poplar and enough
leather to warrant an animal-rights protest. The steering wheel has
controls for the cruise control, stereo and optional car phone.
Buttons remember the preferred settings, for three drivers, of the
seats, shoulder belt, steering wheel and mirrors. The driver has a
huge left footrest.
</P>
<P>
   The early-production test vehicle seemed generally tight and
quiet, with a couple of exceptions. There was more wind noise than
you'd expect, plus a persistent, highly annoying squeak _ akin to
fingernails scraping a blackboard _ from the shoulder-belt anchor
next to the driver's left ear.
</P>
<P>
   The two-part cargo door has a glass liftgate plus a fold-down
tailgate; a one-piece design would be more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Safety features include front and side air bags and
head-protection bags above the doors. The X5 is highly rated in
government crash tests, and its bumpers are situated low for
collision compatibility with cars.
</P>
<P>
   All this adds up to an impressive package, on paper, yet the X5
lacks the purity of form and function that enthusiasts expect from
BMW. Perhaps that is the price of competing at a time when small
companies feel the need to offer more things to more people, in a
world where style is supreme. For the X5 is, ultimately, an
off-road fashion statement for people who don't go off road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Just what people were asking for, for better or
worse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
