<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ELECTION-ART-(     03-24 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECTION-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S STATE TV AIRS NEGATIVE REPORTS ON PUTIN RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's state-owned television has broadcast reports
that the nation's leading liberal challenger to Vladimir Putin is
supported by Jews, homosexuals and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The three prime-time reports by the ORT television network were
clearly intended to exploit the anti-Semitism, homophobia and
suspicion of foreigners that still pervade Russian society, as well
as Russians' enthusiasm for conspiracy theories.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, broadcast Thursday night, indicated that the forces
behind Putin were trying to make sure that he would win more than
50 percent of the votes cast Sunday. He needs that many to avoid a
run-off, which would be held April 16.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate against whom the broadcasts were aimed, Grigori A.
Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko faction, is generally
held to have no chance in the election. But though Yavlinsky, who
is part Jewish, is running a distant third, he is the candidate who
stands to siphon the most votes from Putin. He therefore poses the
greatest danger to the acting president's chances of winning a
mandate on the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to score a decisive victory, Putin on Friday implored
Russians to go to the polls and pick a leader who could restore the
country's prestige and command its nuclear arsenal. The Russian
Orthodox Patriarch Aleksy II also urged a high turnout.
</P>
<P>
   But the televised reports had a different tone. Kseniya
Ponomaryova, the deputy head of Putin's election headquarters, said
she saw nothing wrong with the reports, which she said the campaign
had not orchestrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``ORT has shown that gays support Yavlinsky, and that there are
grounds to consider that his campaign is financed by persons who do
not have Russian citizenship,'' she said. ``What can I say about
it?''
</P>
<P>
   But others said the reports made a mockery of the Kremlin's
pledge to take the high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin promised no dirty tricks during the presidential
campaign,'' said Grigory Arbatov, a long-time specialist on
Russia's relationship with the West. ``But now they turning all the
propaganda against Yavlinsky during the last days of the campaign.
Putin's whole style reminds me of a policeman in the provinces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government formally owns 51 per cent of the ORT
channel, whose reports are seen throughout Russia. Boris Berezovsky
_ the tycoon, master political intriguer, Putin supporter and
Yavlinsky foe _ is also a major owner and has an played an
influential behind-the-scenes role at the network.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, ORT has not hesitated in the past to join the
political fray. Before parliamentary elections in December, Sergei
Dorenko, the host of one of the network's most watched news affairs
shows, conducted slashing attacks against Yevgenni Primakov, the
former prime minister, and Yuri Luzhkov, the Moscow mayor, both
Putin rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless criticism was one reason Primakov and Luzhkov
fell way behind Putin in the opinion polls and decided not to take
part in the presidential campaign. But Thursday night's broadcast
was exceptional even by ORT's standards.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of ORT's reports charged that Yavlinsky was bankrolled by
powerful Jewish businessmen, specifically Vladimir Gusinsky, the
head of the NTV, Russia's only independent television network. He
is one of Russia's most prominent Jewish citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky has dual Russian and Israeli citizenship. ORT's report,
however, emphasized his Jewish background. It showed Gusinsky at a
banquet with Hasidic leaders who were wearing black fedoras and
yarmulkes.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky has made no secret of his view that Yavlinsky is the
best candidate for Russia. But ORT suggested darkly that Yavlinsky
was secretly being financed by ``Israeli citizens.'' It was a
striking attack in light of Putin's vows to battle anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   The network also charged, without producing any evidence, that
Yavlinsky's campaign was receiving financial support two German
think tanks. Its most eye-catching report was about gay Russians
who ostensibly are backing Yavlinsky.
</P>
<P>
   There is little tolerance in Russia for homosexuals and they
have not been a visible or important factor in the nation's
political life. So the report that a gay organization had organized
a press conference in the ``Blue Heart Club'' created a stir.
``Blue'' is Russian slang for ``gay.''
</P>
<P>
   The ORT report cautioned that the press conference might be part
of a disinformation campaign, but not until it had first broadcast
the effusive declarations of support for Yavlinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ORT and RTR, Russia's other state-owned television network,
attended the event. NTV said it was not invited and that the entire
episode appeared to have been staged.
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly the only mud that has been slung at Yavlinsky.
ORT has also charged that he secretly underwent plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, ORT's coverage of Yavlinsky was more restrained.
It continued to criticize him, but also broadcast a letter from
Yavlinsky denying that his campaign had received foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
   The two German think tanks featured in the ORT report also told
the Russian press they were not underwriting Yavlinsky's
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   For all its unsavoriness, the logic of ORT's attacks on
Yavlinsky is clear. Yavlinsky is only expected to receive between 5
and 10 per cent of the vote. Many of his supporters, however, are
from Russia's emerging middle class. They could help Putin achieve
the majority he is seeking in the first round of voting if they
were induced to back the acting president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Igor Malashenko, a senior executive at Berezovsky's media
conglomerate, said there several explanations for ORT's broadcast.
Berezovsky, he said, might be going out of his way to demonstrate
his loyalty to Putin. And Putin's campaign team, he said, is
anxious to avoid a run-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not terribly excited by the election,'' Malashenko
said. ``So they want to demonstrate that there is some sinister
conspiracy against Putin _ basically, a Jewish conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Otto Latsis, a political analyst at the newspaper Izvestia, said
he doubted that Putin has personally authorized the broadcasts and
described them as despicable and foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever made the decision was trying too hard,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
