<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AMERICAN-BEAUTY-WRITE     03-24 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BEAUTY-WRITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR NOMINATION PUTS SPOTLIGHT ON `AMERICAN BEAUTY' SCRIPT
WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Ball now knows why some celebrities ``go nuts.'' Since he
his Academy Award nomination for Best Original Screenplay for
``American Beauty,'' he has spent so much time talking about
himself that he has to keep reality in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing what it's like, in terms of being a celebrity _ but
not quite really a celebrity _ but to get a lot of attention and be
interviewed a lot and photographed a lot,'' Ball said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand why famous people go nuts. You develop a
persona that's like the best version of yourself that you present
every time you're interviewed,'' he said in a telephone interview a
few days before the big night. ``This is like a two-month thing for
me and it will be over. But after a while, for big movie stars,
they probably begin to believe that persona.''
</P>
<P>
   As a build-up to the Academy Awards ceremonies March 26, Ball
said that his ``job for the past three weeks has become just being
me,'' in interviews with television stations, magazines and
newspapers. Ball admits that he's getting an unusual amount of
attention for a screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, he said, is that American Beauty started with a
``spec script,'' written with hopes of being sold. ``It was my own
idea,'' he said. Most movies start with a producer or a star, not a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   When he was in high school, Ball said that dreamed ``of going to
the Oscars, but as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up the acting dream and spent more than a few Oscar
nights with friends ``drinking martinis and screaming at the
television. It's such a bizarre spectacle. It's like a Fellini
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' a black comedy that focuses on the material
excesses of society while exploring the disintegration of a
seemingly successful suburban family, opened in October, at the
same time that the TV comedy he created, ``Oh, Grow Up'' premiered
on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The film became a critic's darling, while the series was
canceled after a few episodes, leaving him somewhat embittered
about television. But he said that the show's failure _ which he
blames partly on the network _ probably kept him more balanced with
the wild success of ``American Beauty,'' which has grossed more
than $100 million in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything had been successful, it would have been
difficult to keep my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the irony of the reasons for the show's cancellation _ the
resignation of Jamie Tarses who as ABC Entertainment president had
championed the show, and the success of ``Who Wants to be a
Millionaire'' _ are not lost on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting that I had this amazingly positive
experience and this horribly devastating experience. I will never
be glad that the show was canceled for `Who Wants to be a
Millionaire.' That show panders to people's basest instinct, which
is one of things, ironically, that `American Beauty' is questioning
_ that money will give meaning to your life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was angry that the network ``strung us along for so long.
They had decided to pull the show and didn't tell us. I was pouring
my heart into the show and we did some really good episodes, but a
couple of them never aired.''
</P>
<P>
   All the attention surrounding the Oscars hasn't kept Ball from
writing, which is ``what keeps me sane. I just need to write.''
</P>
<P>
   He's working on another screenplay that is ``very very different
from `American Beauty.' I'm always asked, `How do you top `American
Beauty'? You don't try to. You do something different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm doing. I think if I allowed myself that
everything I do has to be of the same magnitude, I might just shoot
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also working on the pilot for a proposed HBO series about a
family that owns a funeral home. Ball expects to direct the pilot
in July if the pay cable network picks it up. Despite his
experience with ``Oh, Grow Up,'' he said that he likes the medium
and looks forward to the freedom that a cable network can offer a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Ball said he has spent the last few weeks traveling from one
awards ceremony to another, picking up trophies along the way.
``It's like going to the prom on a weekly basis,'' he said. But
he's been trying to put the Academy Awards ceremony out of his
head, at least until he has to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Even though old friends (and suddenly new ones) keep telling him
he's going to win, he doesn't want to think about the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of my hands. It's possible to ignore it, at least
momentarily. I don't know what obsessing would do for me. I'll be
nervous enough the day of the ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   However the Oscars turn out, he's said that he's happy about
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great for my career. Now I'm in a place where I can
pick and choose and call my own shots and that's rare. I'm also
aware that it may not last. My next movie could be a flop, and
that's all they'll remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he's not yet a member of the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences, Ball couldn't vote for himself, which he said
that he would have done. He said, with a sincerity that is
surprising for a writer better known for a biting sense of irony
and sarcasm:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that it sounds so corny and insincere, but being
nominated itself is really such an honor, especially this year
because it's been such a good year for American movies. I can't
believe my name is on the same list as Charlie Kaufman (`Being John
Malkovich'), Paul Thomas Anderson (`Magnolia'), M. Night Shyamalan
(`The Sixth Sense') and Mike Leigh (`Topsy-Turvy').''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he'll be nervous on March 26, not only about the
awards and a possible acceptance speech, but just being around the
movie stars who will be surrounding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I met Kevin Spacey, I was practically a babbling idiot,''
Ball said. But now that he's being recognized, ``People I always
admired and respected want to meet me. I'm just usually bowled over
and gush at them shamelessly.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that obligatory Hollywood moment, Ball will be doing his
star gazing while looking his best. He'll be wearing a Prada tuxedo
that the design company is giving him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stock must have gone up. When I went to the Golden Globes,
I wore Armani and they gave me a 30 percent discount.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Handelman writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
