<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-THYSSENKRUPP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THYSSENKRUPP MAKES UNSOLICITED OFFER FOR VODAFONE SUBSIDIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British mobile telephone giant Vodafone AirTouch
PLC said Friday that it had received an unsolicited offer from
ThyssenKrupp AG, Germany's largest steelmaker, for the car parts
and engineering unit of Mannesmann, which Vodafone recently agreed
to acquire for $183 billion in the biggest hostile takeover of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   The offer by ThyssenKrupp for Mannesmann's
automotive-engineering subsidiary, called Atecs, was considered a
surprise, partly because Vodafone and Mannesmann had been planning
to sell Atecs through a public stock offering in June. Vodafone
said the ThyssenKrupp proposal would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal were struck, ThyssenKrupp would become an industrial
powerhouse with a vastly strengthened car business, which is more
profitable than its steel business.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company would disclose how much ThyssenKrupp's offer is
worth, though analysts said that Atecs could be valued at about $10
billion. The Financial Times, which first reported ThyssenKrupp's
overture to Vodafone Friday, said the German company had offered 9
billion euros, or about $8.7 billion. The Atecs stock offering has
yet to priced.
</P>
<P>
   ThyssenKrupp said in a statement: ``Against a background of
rapidly changing markets, ThyssenKrupp is firmly convinced that
joining forces would create a leading international supplier.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann is against selling its industrial unit to
ThyssenKrupp. A spokesman for Mannesmann said ``Atecs Mannesmann
and ThyssenKrupp don't fit together.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts disagreed, though, arguing that a
ThyssenKrupp-Atecs tie-up would be a natural fit and a quicker and
cleaner way for Vodafone to dispose of Atecs than by offering
shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone, the world's leading mobile telephone company, pursued
Mannesmann aggressively because it saw the German company's highly
successful mobile phone business, the biggest in Germany, as a
crucial strategic acquisition. Vodafone had no desire to keep
Atecs, which Mannesmann had been planning to divest anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ThyssenKrupp itself is a result of a hostile offer.
ThyssenKrupp's co-chief executive, Gerhard Cromme, led a hostile
bid for Thyssen about two years ago when he was the chief executive
of Hoesch-Krupp. The merger was eventually agreed upon in a
friendly transaction after it had created an uproar among Germany's
steelworkers.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of ThyssenKrupp dropped 2 percent to 25.60 euros, or
$24.83 in Frankfurt while Vodafone also fell less than 1 percent to
368.25 pounds, or $581.84 in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
