<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-24 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: `HATRED IN ACTION' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ronald D. Rotunda, a law professor at the University of
Illinois, was an ethics adviser to Kenneth Starr. The other day he
made an extraordinary attack on federal judges in Washington.
Writing on the Op Ed page of The Wall Street Journal, he said
judges appointed by President Clinton had dealt improperly _
politically _ with cases important to him. The headline was,
``Another Clinton Victim: The Integrity of the Federal Courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotunda's main target was U.S. District Judge James Robertson. I
know Robertson, and I know his high reputation for integrity, so I
decided to look into Rotunda's charges. I found that they were a
farrago of untruths.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson handled the 1998 tax fraud prosecution of Webster
Hubbell and three others by the independent counsel. Rotunda
charged that the judge had acted improperly to delay and prevent a
trial of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transcript reads as if Robertson had decided that the case
was not going to trial,'' Rotunda wrote. ``He just had not decided
why.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcript to which the professor refers begins with
arraignment of the defendants on May 8, 1998. Their lawyers said
they would file motions challenging the legal basis of the
prosecution. Robertson allowed them just three weeks to do so.
</P>
<P>
   David Barger, an assistant to Starr, asked the court to set an
early trial date. Robertson said he would consider that at a status
conference on June 2, four days after the motions were due. At that
conference Barger suggested a trial date ``around Oct. 5.''
Robertson said, ``Oct. 5 is your date.''
</P>
<P>
   No unbiased person could read that transcript and think that the
judge set out to delay or prevent a trial. In fact, he set an
unusually tight schedule for a case involving four defendants and
complex documentary evidence. And the schedule was satisfactory to
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the motions were filed, Robertson dismissed the
prosecution on the ground, among others, that the Fifth Amendment
barred the use against Hubbell of business records he had been
forced to produce. The Court of Appeals reversed that decision _
but imposed tough requirements on the prosecution to prove that its
evidence was constitutionally untainted. In the end Starr accepted
a plea of guilty to a misdemeanor tax offense, with Hubbell paying
a $25 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rotunda had what he called ``another eyebrow-raiser.''
Clinton appointees to the D.C. District Court, he said, held
``monthly caucuses from which other federal judges were excluded.''
The implication was that they plotted.
</P>
<P>
   Here again the truth is otherwise. The newer judges had lunch
together a few times. They were not ``caucuses,'' they did not
occur monthly and no court business was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Rotunda failed to mention that the charge of improper
meetings had been examined by the acting chief judge of the Court
of Appeals, Stephen F. Williams, a Reagan appointee, and dismissed
last November as ``frivolous.'' ``Reasonable observers do not take
so cynical a view of the judiciary,'' Williams wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also dismissed another charge repeated by Professor
Rotunda: that the chief judge of the District Court, Norma Holloway
Johnson, had improperly taken the Hubbell case and others out of
the random assignment system and given them to judges appointed by
President Clinton. The court's rules permitted such special
assignments for difficult cases, and Williams noted that the judges
who got those cases had less crowded dockets.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is now looking at the assignment issue again, at the
request of a congressman. But whatever he does cannot affect
another Rotunda falsehood.
</P>
<P>
   Rotunda wrote that the rule allowing non-random assignment of
difficult cases in Washington had been changed last month ``in a
stunning rebuke'' to Johnson. There was no rebuke. The D.C. court
simply changed its rules to conform with a resolution adopted a
year ago by the Judicial Conference of the United States. The
court's new rule was proposed by another judge attacked by Rotunda,
Paul L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Rotunda engage in the cowardly business of making
false, political charges against judges? I can only assume that, in
working for Starr, he was infected by the right's hatred of Clinton
_ and its frustration that not even a majority of the Senate voted
to remove him from office. And why would the editors of The Wall
Street Journal publish such vile trash? Hate, again, must be the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1854EST &QL; 
