<HEADLINE>
POPE REPEATS 2,000-YEAR-OLD MESSAGE TO 100,000 PILGRIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT OF THE BEATITUDES, Israel _ Standing on a hill overlooking
the Sea of Galilee on Friday, Pope John Paul II urged more than
100,000 pilgrims to act on Jesus' revolutionary message to become
gentle peacemakers and to return evil with good.
</P>
<P>
   Monico Villarreal, a 45-year-old Waxahachie, Texas, truck driver
on a pilgrimage with 150 other Texans, said he was overwhelmed and
amazed to be standing on the Mount of the Beatitudes, hearing the
age-old message of the Sermon on the Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I'm seeing something that had not happened for 2,000
years,'' said Villarreal, one of 31 members of the St. Joseph's
Catholic Church in the town near Dallas attending the event.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's message was based mainly on Jesus' famous sermon,
delivered near the same spot centuries ago and recorded in the Book
of Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of
heaven,'' Jesus declared to the large crowd gathered from Galilee,
the Decapolis, Jerusalem, Judea and across the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of religious unity, which has been a hallmark of John
Paul's historic visit to Israel, continued as the pope celebrated
Mass. Christian, Jews and Muslim groups gathered to see and hear
the pontiff. Flags and banners were displayed from Canada, the
United States, Great Britain, Croatia, Spain, Uruguay, Russia,
Chile, Poland, Hungary, Australia and many other nations.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, in a climactic moment of his weeklong pilgrimage to
the Holy Land, said new life will come to Christians if they follow
Jesus' teachings.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange message to some, the 79-year-old pontiff
declared. ```Blessed are you!' he says, `all you who are poor in
spirit, gentle and merciful, you who mourn, who care for what is
right, who are pure in heart, who make peace, you who are
persecuted! Blessed are you!' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strange that Jesus exalts those whom the world generally
regards as weak. He says to them, `Blessed are you who seem to be
losers, because you are the true winners: the kingdom of heaven is
yours!'''
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/ In the audience were thousands of young people who
participated in a worldwide event to mark the coming of the new
century.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his infirmities and age, John Paul has become a hero to
the young.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were smeared with mud from the rainy
conditions, and sleepy from all-night prayers, young people played
drums, sang and shouted ``John Paul II, we love you,'' and ``Viva
el papa'' as the pontiff waved from a popemobile driving him
through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The youths broke into loud applause when John Paul arrived at
the red-carpeted platform underneath a 45-foot-high black tent. A
huge picture of a young Jesus and a large cross holding a figure of
Christ dominated the altar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to care,'' said delegate Eric Hernandez,
20, who attends Eastfield Community College in Dallas. ``I admire
him, too, because despite his problems, he keeps talking to us.''
</P>
<P>
   When John Paul called for a spiritual change of heart, he
addressed himself to the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``You young people will understand why this change of heart is
necessary,'' he said, ``because you are aware of another voice
within you and all around you. ... It is a voice which says
`Blessed are the proud and the violent, those who prosper at any
cost, who are unscrupulous, pitiless, devious, who make war and not
peace, and persecute those who stand in their way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul said the secret to following the Beatitudes is
devotion to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the Beatitudes,'' the pope said. ``Looking at him you
will see what it means to be poor in spirit, gentle and merciful,
to mourn, to care for what is right, to be pure in heart, to make
peace, to be persecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   To the diverse crowd, the pope said: ``Please take my prayerful
greeting to the whole Greek-Melchite community. I greet the members
of the Latin community, including the Hebrew-speaking faithful, the
Maronite community, the Syrian community, the Armenian community,
the Chaldean community. ... I extend a special word of thanks to
our Muslim friends ... and to members of the Jewish faith and the
Druze community.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Monsanto, an architect from Waxahachie who was escorting a
group of young people, said the pope's message will encourage all
to make the new century a time of spiritual growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong word for us, and I hope we follow it,'' said
Monsanto, who is a permanent deacon in the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the pope of the millennium,'' said Cesar Gomez of
Panama, who brought his wife and three of his children to the
event. Pointing to the young people, he said, ``Here you see the
future of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Octavio Ocon, 15, of San Francisco, said of John Paul:
``He has a great soul.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
