<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-1STLD-W     03-24 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF PILGRIMS ATTEND POPE'S SEA OF GALILEE MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete writethru; UPDATES with Barak meeting and visits
to sites near the Sea of Galilee; adds new details; restructures.
) 
 (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT OF THE BEATITUDES, Israel _ Standing where Jesus Christ is
said to have told followers, ``Blessed are the meek, for they shall
inherit the earth,'' Pope John Paul II warned a youthful multitude
on Friday against heeding what he called ``contradictory''
beatitudes lurking in the modern Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the voice which says, `Blessed are the proud and
violent, those who prosper at any cost, who are unscrupulous,
pitiless, devious, who make war, not peace, and persecute those who
stand in their way,''' the pope said, speaking to thousands of
pilgrims from a platform overlooking the shimmering Sea of Galilee.
``And this voice seems to make sense in a world where the violent
are often triumphant and the devious seem to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope described this as ``the choice between good and evil,
between life and death,'' and asked which voice the young people
would obey.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's version of the Sermon on the Mount was his first
public Mass in Israel, part of a week-long pilgrimage to retrace
the steps of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   His trip, the first official visit by a pope to Israel, has had
extraordinary political resonance in Israel as well as in
Palestinian-controlled territories, where the pope held a Mass and
visited a refugee camp on Tuesday. The pope's visit has also been
enormously important to Christians who constitute a tiny minority
in Israel and had never experienced an outdoor Mass like this.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 100,000 pilgrims arrived here as early as 3 a.m.
and gathered on grassy slopes left muddy from overnight rain.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed to have traveled from everywhere and included not
only Palestinians from Israel and the West Bank but also Lebanese
Christians who were allowed to cross the tense border from southern
Lebanon. There was also a scattering of U.N. peacekeepers,
recognizable by their blue berets.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nazrin Touba, 33, who works in an orphanage in Nazareth, arrived
in a bus with other Arab Christians at 3 a.m. Touba, who was pushed
up against a fence by the exuberant crowd, explained why she and
her friends had come to the Sea of Galilee, when the pope is
scheduled to come to Nazareth Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're afraid we might not be able to see him in Nazareth,''
she said. ``The security may be so strict that we won't be able to
go at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pilgrims came from Romania, Guam, the Philippines, Italy
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Marina Danese, 33, an Italian homemaker from Milan, said she had
left her family behind in Milan, Italy. ``I could see the pope
anytime I want in Italy,'' Danese said, ``but I could never again
see him in the place where Jesus lived.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the Mass site, blue-and-white Israeli flags fluttered near
the Vatican's yellow-and-white banners. Red-white-and-black
Palestinian flags were scattered among the crowd, along with a
banner that read, ``The uprooted people of Kfar Bire'm welcome John
Paul II.''
</P>
<P>
   The banner mentioning Kfar Bire'm, a village occupied by the new
state of Israel in 1948, came down halfway through the Mass, which
was tightly controlled by Israeli police officers. Israeli
officials described the papal visit as the largest security
operation in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   A black canopy was pitched over the pope's altar and platform,
and bulletproof glass shielded him on both sides as he spoke. The
Vatican almost always rejects such measures. The only other time
the Vatican allowed bulletproof screens near the altar was in
Detroit in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, the pope met with Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who
outlined the status of Israel's peace negotiations with the
Palestinians and Syria and asked for the pope's assistance in
learning about the fate of Israeli soldiers missing in action,
including a tank crew in 1982 and a pilot captured in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the pope's visit has ``immense historical
importance,'' the prime minister added, ``I believe it might help
make the atmosphere much better in the world, in relations between
Jews and Christians and in regard to the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since the pope arrived in Israel from Jordan on Tuesday, both
Jewish and Palestinian leaders have pushed their competing claims
over Jerusalem. The argument even seeped into an interreligious
meeting meant to promote harmony among Jews, Christians and Muslims
that ended after a Jewish rabbi and a Muslim cleric clashed and the
cleric left abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said that if such
problems are real, he could hardly avoid them. ``It would be a
fiction to walk on the clouds and not on the earth,'' Navarro-Valls
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday was reserved for stops at sites near the Sea of
Galilee associated with the ministry of Jesus and his disciples.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The frail 79-year-old pope held up remarkably well on the fifth
day of his weeklong pilgrimage. He delivered his homily in a
strong, distinct voice and even negotiated 30 steps with the help
of his cane to pray at a chapel after his lakeside meeting with
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The pope stopped to pray at Tapgha, the limestone church built
on the site where Jesus was believed to have performed the miracle
of feeding the multitude of 5,000 with five barley loaves and two
small fishes, according to the Gospel of John.
</P>
<P>
   At the Church of the Primacy, the pope kissed the sprawling rock
where tradition says a resurrected Jesus shared a festive meal of
fish with his apostles.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Gospels, after that meal Jesus asked Peter to
succeed him as leader of the church.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, the pope arrived at Capernaum to the tolling of bells
from a nearby Greek Orthodox church. He prayed at the ruins of what
was believed to be the house where Peter lived. As the pope prayed,
a group of Vatican prelates surrounded his armchair and sang ``Tu
es Petrus,'' the Latin rendition of the words Jesus is supposed to
have used to select Peter as the first pope.
</P>
<P>
   The pope was given an oil lamp dating to the time of Christ and
a stone from the house by the Stanislao Loffreda, 68, the
Franciscan archaeologist who discovered the ruins in 1968, five
years after the pope, then a young bishop in Krakow, made a
pilgrimage to the Holy Land. After the meeting, Loffreda said the
pope told him, ``If your health permits it, keep digging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
