r p BC-POL-TICKER25-COX     03-24 2451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Strong support for Coelho from Gore
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore said today his campaign chairman, Tony Coelho, is doing
a ``terrific job'' and suggested Coelho would remain with his
presidential campaign despite a criminal investigation into past
financial dealings. Asked if he was concerned about the possibility
of criminal wrongdoing, Gore refused to elaborate on his statement,
saying, ``He's doing a great job and he will keep on doing so.''
George W. Bush, asked today about Gore's problems regarding Coelho
and an investigation of White House e-mail, said: ``The best way to
make sure we get rid of all these investigations is to change
administrations.''
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO CENTRAL HIGH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was at Little Rock's Central High School today,
urging a national commitment to battle ``a tremendous gap of
achievement between rich and poor, between white and minority.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that four decades after the racial standoff there was
resolved by federal intervention, ``We have a great challenge of
our own. Access is universal, but excellence is not.'' Central
High's front steps were the scene of a national standoff in
September 1957 when Arkansas Gov. Orval Faubus ordered the National
Guard to prevent nine black students from entering the building
under a desegregation plan. President Eisenhower responded by
sending in the Army to open up the school.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE FOR CAMPAIGN CASH
</P>
<P>
   Despite heightened voter interest in fund-raising reform, both
candidates have stepped up their chase for the big bucks. Al Gore
was in Houston today to scoop up more than $500,000 in ``soft
money'' for the Democratic National Committee. Meanwhile, George W.
Bush has hit the money circuit with events Thursday in Palm Beach,
Fla., and today in Little Rock, Ark. His appearances are expected
to net $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-PRIVATE DIFFERENCES
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Republican Party relentlessly criticized Democrats
for taking big donations from foreigners during the 1996 election,
its lawyers argued in a filing with the Federal Election Commission
that excaped public attention last year that such contributions
should be considered legal: ``Foreign national donations to party
committee non-federal accounts are legally permissible.'' The quiet
reversal has left Democrats crying foul. ``What it looks like
they're doing here is selective outrage at best and utter hypocrisy
at worst,'' said Democratic spokeswoman Jenny Backus. ``It has
always been the policy of the RNC not to accept foreign national
contributions,'' said Republican spokesman Mike Collins.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY CAN SWING BOTH WAYS
</P>
<P>
   The rosy economy seems a double-edged sword for George W. Bush.
With continued low employment and the stock market moving above
11,000 again, Bush is finding plenty of Republicans with a lot of
cash. But these good times also are boosting Al Gore's presidential
hopes, and Bush wants voters to think about other issues as well as
their pocketbooks: ``The pundits _ they keep saying we're going to
have a tough time winning because the Dow Jones industrial average
is high, but that doesn't lift the spirit of America. And it
shouldn't obscure the fact that some kids can't read in our
society. It doesn't say anything about the military and our
preparedness to keep the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN'S BACK, AND OUT FOR BEAR
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Senate less than a week, John McCain is also back to
making his point that campaign finance rules need an overhaul.
McCain says he'll vote against confirming Republican Bradley Smith,
a Federal Election Commission nominee who opposes campaign finance
reform. McCain told reporters he would do everything he could to
defeat Smith on the grounds that he is against tightening
fund-raising rules. Smith is strongly backed by senior Senate
Republicans, including Majority Leader Trent Lott and Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky, perhaps the Senate's strongest opponent of
campaign financing reform.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORT, BUT TEPID SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   John McCain cast himself as a vigorous campaigner for the
Republican congressional majority and insisted he is ``not
interested in harming'' George W. Bush's candidacy. But in an
hourlong interview with the New York Times, McCain acknowledged
several times that he was walking a ``very careful line'' in trying
to be loyal to his party while still remaining true to the
insurgent cause that attracted millions of new voters to the
Republican primaries this year. McCain said he wants to fight to
change the Republican Party from the inside. And he said the
difference between an endorsement of Bush and his assurance this
week that he would support his party's nominee was a difference in
``the degree of enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN CLAWING TO KEEP DELEGATES
</P>
<P>
   As Michigan Republicans began meeting to choose delegates for
the Republican National Convention, some backers of John McCain
worry that George W. Bush's supporters will get the seats that
should go to them. McCain spokesman Todd Harris suspected Thursday
that Gov. John Engler _ one of Bush's biggest advocates in the
state _ may be trying to get Bush supporters into some of the
delegate spots that McCain earned by winning Michigan's GOP
presidential primary last month. McCain picked up 52 of the state's
58 convention delegates. Engler spokesman John Truscott said there
was no move afoot to challenge McCain supporters vying for delegate
spots.
</P>
<P>
   POLES APART ON NEEDING POLLS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush often says he doesn't need polls to tell him how
to run his campaign, but polls conducted by the GOP have been
steering Bush's latest attacks on Al Gore. ``This is a man who will
say anything to get elected,'' has been a recurring theme in Bush
speeches. That's because the line was tested and shown to be
effective in a Republican poll taken last month, according to ABC
News. In a speech in Florida last week, Bush repeated the line four
times in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE POISED IN REFORM PARTY STRUGGLE
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the case to a divorce, a federal judge in Lynchburg,
Va., said he'll rule Monday on who controls the Reform Party in a
bitter feud that pit two factions against one another. ``What we
have here in this case are honorable people who are divided in
beliefs on which way the party should go,'' said U.S. District
Judge Norman Moon. Jack Gargan, the party chairman ousted at a
raucous meeting last month in Nashville, and Pat Choate, the man
who replaced him, now run parallel chairmanships complete with
dueling ``official'' party Web sites and plans for rival nominating
conventions. Each side claims ownership of $2.5 million in federal
funding, most of which is held in the custody of the court. The
party's presidential nominee also will receive $12.6 million for
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   BOTH SIDES DRINK FROM THE TROUGH
</P>
<P>
   Congress is unlikely to change laws governing White House
reimbursement for campaign travel despite election-year criticism
of Hillary Clinton's modest payments for using Air Force planes in
connection with her campaign for the Senate. Congressional
Republicans ordered a special inquiry to examine the first lady's
reimbursement for travel to New York state in her Senate race
against Rudy Giuliani. But Rep. Jim Kolbe (R-Ariz.), chairman of
the House Appropriations Committee's panel on White House
operations, conceded that Congress has little inclination to
overturn the reimbursement scheme that effectively subsidizes
political travel by Republicans and Democrats both when they serve
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   HARD LINE ON OIL PRODUCERS
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential candidate Pat Buchanan promised to
slap new tariffs on oil-producing nations that systematically
withhold their product. In San Francisco, Buchanan charged a global
conspiracy to inflate oil prices, and pledged to cut financial aid,
including World Bank and International Monetary Fund loans, to any
country he deemed part of a plot to ``withhold oil and gouge the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SECURITY A STATE BUDGET ITEM
</P>
<P>
   Texans have spent $1.3 million so far this year on security for
George W. Bush while he campaigned for president. The amount is
more than four times the $286,000 that it cost to protect Bush and
his family in 1998, when he was not a presidential candidate for
president. As of Monday, the state has spent $3.9 million on
security for the Bushes in the 15-month period beginning in January
1999, according to new figures from the Texas Department of Public
Safety. Costs to Texas should decrease now that the Secret Service
has taken over security for Bush. The DPS still protects his
family, however.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY INSECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, accustomed to the Democratic Party's upper hand on
Social Security, bitterly derided George W. Bush as Bush staked his
own claim on that issue. Any school child could ``go to the
blackboard and demonstrate how his numbers don't add up,'' Gore
contended. Battling in Cincinnati for the favor of senior citizens,
who reliably vote in powerful numbers, Gore alleged that the only
way Bush could pay for his proposed tax cuts would be through
massive budget deficits or Social Security cutbacks. Bush, in
Orlando, Fla., countered that Gore was naive to think he can save
the program for future retirees simply by throwing money at the
Social Security Trust Fund. ``People need to ask, `Who's the
reformer in the race' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS FINDING BUSH SLIPPAGE
</P>
<P>
   Now that the smoke from the nomination battles has cleared, Al
Gore has opened up a small lead over George W. Bush in a new
national survey. The latest Pew Research Center poll (4 percentage
point margin of error) found Gore up 49-43 percent. The 6-point
edge is Gore's largest in matchups for the fall election, but other
polls indicate that the race to be a virtual dead heat, and in at
least two recent national surveys Bush was leading Gore. A common
thread running through all the polls, however, has been a drop in
support for Bush since the primaries began.
</P>
<P>
   THE CANDIDATES _ IN A WORD
</P>
<P>
   Voters are starting to tell pollsters George W. Bush is
``cocky'' and ``arrogant.'' Some 31 percent of respondents in the
Pew Research Center survey chose a negative term when asked the one
word that best described him, compared to 12 percent who thought of
a negative term first a year ago. While the majority of references
to Bush were positive, the most frequently mentioned negative words
were ``arrogant,'' ``dislike,'' ``untrustworthy,'' ``wimp,''
``bad'' or ``cocky.'' The most frequently mentioned negative word
for Al Gore was ``boring,'' and ``dull'' was second, tied with
``politician'' _undefined as to positive or negative. Next on the
negative list for Gore came ``dishonest'' and ``incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER ENTHUSIASM FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's supporters are more likely to feel strongly
about their support than are voters who favor Al Gore, according to
the latest poll for Hotline, the online political tip sheet. The
poll, taken March 16-19 by Democratic pollster Jef Pollock and
Republican pollster Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, found that 59 percent of
Bush supporters held that position strongly, as against 49 percent
of Gore backers. The poll also found that voters who said John
McCain was their first choice for president were evenly split when
asked to choose between Bush and Gore. The poll's margin of error
was 3.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   TURNING BACK THE CLOCK
</P>
<P>
   The race for the White House is turning into a race against the
past. Al Gore is running as much against former President George
Bush as he is against George W. Bush, working feverishly to remind
voters that the last Republican president presided over a recession
and record budget deficits _ and arguing that the son would bring
back the father's sins. But the campaign against the elder Bush may
not be the sure-fire winner it was eight years ago. Many voters
have forgotten hard times, but remember what it was like to have a
devoted family man in the Oval Office, and the elder Bush is more
popular now than when he left office. The younger Bush counts on
that sentiment, and runs as much against Bill Clinton as against
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKY HERE_ FREE AIR TIME
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and gubernatorial candidates will be provided with
five minutes of free air time this year on the 18 television
stations across the country owned by the Belo Corp. Expanding an
initiative it began in 1996, Belo, which also publishes the Dallas
Morning News and the Providence Journal, will turn over a
five-minute block of news programming to each qualified candidate
during the final 45 days of the campaign. In the pilot project four
years ago, six of Belo's stations provided 73 candidates with more
than six hours of free air time.
</P>
<P>
   SCRAMBLE IN SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Sanford, a Republican from South Carolina, became a
well-known figure around the state earlier this year because of his
maverick support for John McCain. But rather than exploit his
popularity, he is, at least for the moment, according to the New
York Times, leaving politics in keeping with a promise to serve no
more than three terms. The prospect of filling a rare open seat has
attracted seven Republicans to the June 13 primary. Leading
contenders: H.B. Limehouse, a former transportation commissioner,
and state Rep. Henry Brown. The winner will likely face Andy Brack,
the Charleston County Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   YOU KNOW WHO YOU'RE MESSING WITH?
</P>
<P>
   A campaign staffer for Al Gore threatened a Nashville police
officer during a DUI arrest, saying she worked for Gore and would
report the officer to the U.S. district attorney, police police
say.
</P>
<P>
   Anupama Rangappa, 25, was charged on March 11 with driving under
the influence and refusing to take a breath-alcohol test, the
report says. The Tennessean newspaper said she is from Virginia,
but has been working as a scheduler in Gore's campaign headquarters
in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY KEEPING STAFF PRESENCE
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley's campaign announced that it will maintain a staff
presence as the ex-candidate, who is on vacation, closes down his
campaign. A statement from Bradley's campaign headquarters in West
Orange, N.J., said Rick Wright has been named chief of staff for
the Bill Bradley for President Committee. Bradley has not released
his delegates.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
