<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-HNS &LR;      03-24 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES PAKISTAN TO RETURN TO DEMOCRATIC ELECTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ President Clinton, completing the Indian legs of
his South Asian journey Saturday, moved on to Pakistan to press its
military ruler for a timetable for national elections and a return
to democratic government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried about the future of Pakistan,'' said Clinton's
national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger. A senior
administration official even suggested that Pakistan's economy is
so precarious that the Islamic nation might ``fail.''
</P>
<P>
   After about five hours in Islamabad, the Pakistani capital,
Clinton was to fly on to Geneva, where he will meet Sunday with
President Hafez el-Assad in hopes of getting peace talks restarted
between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In the wrap-up to a five-day state visit, the president focused
Friday on ``New India,'' dropping by HI-TEC City in Hyderabad and
talking to business leaders at the nation's biggest stock exchange
in this city of 15 million on the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said $4 billion in private business deals were struck on
the sidelines of his trip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said one was a gas supply agreement worth
$75 million between Enron Gas Marketing Company Private Ltd., an
arm of the Houston-based energy giant, and Ispat Energy Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The gas will be used for a power-generating plant in Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of his trip to the world's most populous democracy,
Clinton expressed just one regret: ``I desperately wanted to ride
on an elephant's back. I've always wanted to do that.'' Clinton
told reporters that his staff, afraid he would look silly atop a
pachyderm, talked him out of getting aboard one of the mammoth's.
He was chagrined that some of those aides themselves went for
elephant rides.
</P>
<P>
   By stopping in Pakistan, a move some in the administration
opposed, Clinton faced not only the nation's five-month-old
military dictatorship but also one of the knottiest and bloodiest
regional confrontations _ the clash between India and Pakistan over
the disputed province of Kashmir. The face-off, with its almost
daily skirmishes, became graver in May 1998 when first India and
then Pakistan tested a nuclear weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Although Indian leaders earlier in the week upbraided Clinton
for calling the Kashmir dispute perhaps the most dangerous in the
world, a new government-sponsored survey shows many average Indians
share his view. The Indian Office of Research reported the
three-quarters of the respondents in a poll earlier this month feel
it likely that Kashmir will lead to a war between Indian and
Pakistan ``in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's visit to New Delhi, the Indian capital earlier
this week, 40 Sikhs were killed in a village on the Indian side of
the Kashmir cease-fire line. India blamed terrorist groups, at
least one of which it said was based in Pakistan. The Pakistan
government denied having any role.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, aware that he cannot act as intermediary for unwilling
parties, planned to ask the Pakistani Army general, Pervez
Musahrraf, who came to power last October in a coup, to consider
direct talks with India on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The White House insisted that Clinton's stop was meant to
encourage the Pakistani people to persevere in the face of an
unelected government, and Clinton planned a television broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can turn our back on the Pakistani people
with whom we've had a very strong relationship,'' Berger said. He
referred to close U.S. ties to Pakistan, and especially its
military, during the Cold War. While India aggressively proclaimed
its non-aligned status and sometimes courted Moscow, Pakistan
generally was a faithful U.S. ally.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Berger said, ``it's a country that's in trouble and really
needs to put all of its energy into self-renewal, not territorial
conflicts. They don't have the luxury of that.'' He said Clinton
will ``convey some hard realities to Musharraf and to talk directly
to the Pakistani people about the hard choices they face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the nature of persuasion,'' Berger said, to say to
Musharraf ``that you'll have a stronger basis generally on which to
address these problems if people can see a clear road map back to a
democratic government.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf announced Thursday that local elections will begin
late this year, marking a move away from martial law, and he said
that broader elections would follow, but he did not spell out a
timetable for returning the national government to elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, another regional dispute will be on Clinton's agenda.
He will seek to convince Assad to renew his nation's direct talks
with Israel on a peace deal _ which would require settlement of
such thorny issues as an end to Israel's occupation of the Golan
Heights and security guarantees for the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, which were conducted in Shepherdstown, W.Va., broke
off in January when the Israeli and Syrian sides could not even
agree on which of the issues, the Golan or Israeli security, would
be discussed first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best-case result,'' Berger said, ``is that we have a sense
after the meeting that there is enough common ground ..., that if
we actually resume negotiations, that you could envision them
ending in success.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton flew about, ABC News reported his weeklong sojourn
was the most expensive presidential trip ever _ costing an
estimated $50 million. Ninety percent of the tab, the network
reported from Washington, was the almost 80 airplanes used to
airlift the president, his entourage, his vehicles and
communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six of the Air Force's largest transports, more than a
third of the service's C5s and C17s, were on the flight roster, ABC
said. The network compared it to the humanitarian relief effort for
the Mozambique flooding, in which only about a dozen of the giant
planes were employed.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the wide-ranging international forays by Clinton,
the nation's most-traveled president, already have drawn complaints
from Republicans in Congress, and the current trip, with its fair
share of sight-seeing, seems likely to renew their displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his visit to Hyderabad with a stop at Mahavir
Hospital where he helped to vaccinate a child against polio, which
because of a massive immunization program, has ebbed as a threat in
India. One thousand cases of polio were reported in India last
year, a dramatic drop over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   In January, in what the White House described as the biggest
single public health effort in history, more than 149 million
Indian children were vaccinated against polio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called for a similar sustained effort against AIDS,
malaria and tuberculosis, because, he said, infectious diseases are
a threat from which ``no nation is immune.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
