<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-3COM-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MAY BE BORING, BUT THE MODEM STILL LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The modem industry had one of those handwriting-on-the-wall
moments last week as the market leader, the 3Com Corp., announced
that it was getting out. The company said it wanted to concentrate
on higher-growth markets like broadband communications and Internet
telephony, implying that plain old modems, which let computers send
and receive data over wires, had become a boring commodity.
</P>
<P>
   And yet worldwide modem sales nearly doubled in 1999, to 120
million units. That's not high growth?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of paradoxes in the modem market right now,''
said Ernie Rapiere, an analyst with VisionQuest 2000, a market
research firm based in Moorpark, Calif. Rapiere noted that sales of
modem chip sets, the active ingredients of outboard modems and of
modem cards, games and set-top boxes with built-in communications
capabilities, grew ``as much in 1999 as in any year in the past
10.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that prices were falling at the same time, so
fast that higher unit sales did not necessarily translate into
higher revenue or even profitability.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of that price pressure comes from new computers'
learning to do a modem's work without needing modem chip sets.
``The sub-$700 PC and sub-$2,000 notebook went heavily to
host-based modems,'' said Rapiere, using the industry term for
software-only communications arrangements. Sales of host-based
modems quintupled in 1999, to 30 million units, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Software-only modems have existed for years, but until recently
the burden they put on a computer's microprocessor degraded
performance too much for most users. Today's much faster processors
have speed to spare, Rapiere said. ``Unless you're trying to do a
lot of complex things all at once, you're probably not going to
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   To exit the business, 3Com said it would form a joint venture
with Accton of Taiwan and NatSteel Electronics of Singapore that
would buy 3Com's desktop analog modem business, including the U.S.
Robotics brand, and its operations making modems for use in laptop
computers. Together, they had given 3Com some 60 percent of the
market, according to Instat, a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The handoff gives competitors an opportunity to gain share, said
Frank Manning, president and chief executive of Zoom Telephonics in
Boston, which sells modems under the Zoom and Hayes brand names.
``What 3Com's doing is taking their valuable shelf space and
selling it off,'' he said. ``Do I think analog modems are a highly
lucrative part of our business? No. But it's very dangerous to just
focus on the high-growth areas and abandon customers when a segment
slows down.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning said there were still ways to differentiate modems,
through better firmware (the programming embedded in the chip set),
better packaging and customer support. A new industrywide technical
standard called V.92, due later this year, will make possible new
features like call-waiting, higher upload speeds and faster
connection setup. ``People think modems are more of a commodity
than they actually are,'' he said. ``There actually is room for
doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Branded modem sales were flat in 1999, at about nine million,
according to VisionQuest; many more were sold bundled into PCs. But
Manning said it was too soon to say broadband services like DSL and
cable had killed off analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is way ahead of the rest of the world in
cable modems and DSL, but it's still true that most people can't
get them,'' Manning said. ``The base Internet functionality five
years from now will still be an analog modem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
