A7193 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS &LR;      03-24 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESORT TOWN SEEKS TO CONTROL SPRING BREAK MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas _ On the heels of a national trend,
this Gulf of Mexico beach resort is becoming increasingly fed up
with the trash, traffic and truculence imported by thousands of
Spring Break visitors.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 disgruntled residents, merchants and winter visitors
at a community meeting Wednesday essentially said the time has come
to put the brakes on breakers.
</P>
<P>
   They voiced their outrage with the annual early spring pause in
classes at colleges and high schools, which they say has become
exceedingly lawless and potentially dangerous despite ever-growing
numbers of police officers being deployed to control it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has let things go to the point that it's
uncontrollable,'' South Padre Alderman Eddie Dwyer said. ``Public
safety is just totally ignored so we can make a buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Their complaints echo those of other resort communities
throughout the country that are attempting to market Spring Break
to another type of clientele _ those who are not so much young as
young at heart.
</P>
<P>
   That has been done successfully in Port Aransas, where some
unruly students overturned a car and roughed up the driver a decade
ago, forcing the city to take action. Now, young parents and
children play in the surf.
</P>
<P>
   Some South Padre Island residents who attended the meeting said
they are sick of cleaning up the rubbish after accommodating unruly
students. They, too, want to appeal to families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have fun with Spring Break,'' said George Ferguson,
a 31-year resident. ``The last eight years, it's getting worse. Our
city officials have just practically given the town over to the
Spring Breakers.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this year has been the worst yet. He was almost struck
twice while walking in a pedestrian lane. Then he was hassled by
students when he politely asked them to move a car blocking
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, South Padre Mayor Ed Cyganiewicz downplayed community
frustrations at boisterous student behavior, saying Spring Breakers
typically are more defiant during bad weather, such as the type
that struck the island this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have to start with the positive,'' he said. ``I've
been involved in this 15 years. We've had thousands and thousands
coming down, and we've had (few) deaths and no serious injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone believes a low fatality rate is a good measure
of success for a spring holiday. Dwyer pointed out that 49 units at
one condominium development had to be evacuated after kids began
throwing televisions, VCRs, mattresses and other objects out the
windows during a brief power outage.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer, who owns a restaurant on the island, said he believes any
economic benefits of Spring Break very well may be offset by the
costs of damage control.
</P>
<P>
   The city of South Padre Island, with some 2,100 residents, has
done no study on the economic benefits of Spring Break in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smaller businesses haven't really put the pencil to it,''
Dwyer said. ``They think the revenue goes up, but the other
expenses are astronomical.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer called for more responsibility on the part of businesses.
As an example of the problem, he pointed out an advertisement for
fake IDs in a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have got to take responsibility for their businesses,''
he said. ``We have bartenders serving people after they're
inebriated.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer said it is the air of lawlessness that appears to attract
the students, many of whom are traveling now to countries like
Mexico for Spring Break in search of a lower drinking age and other
lax laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The businesses you're going to lose by cracking down on these
kids are the ones we don't want around here anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With cities like Atlanta, Galveston, Texas, Daytona Beach, Fla.,
and Virginia Beach, Va., trying to find strategies to put the
brakes on break, South Padre Island will be looking to them for
help, Dwyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to reach out and get help from these other
communities, instead of, as the city government has done in the
past, sweeping this under the rug,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer said he believes he has enough support on the City Council
for the first time in many years to rein in Spring Break. There
will meetings on the subject April 5 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have the kids come down here, but they're going to have
to understand that we have laws, too,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
