<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7194 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-CREDIT-CARDS-$ADV     03-24 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CREDIT-CARDS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLY NOW. BUT LEARN THE INTEREST RATE LATER.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, consumers have found plenty of reasons to
complain about companies that issue credit cards. High interest
rates. Less time to pay bills (and hefty penalties for being a day
late). Fees for exceeding credit limits. Balances computed in new
ways, to the customer's disadvantage. New, sometimes more onerous
terms when accounts are sold to another company.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is another: difficulty in shopping for the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, federal law has required that issuers disclose
interest rates and other key conditions to potential card holders.
But recently, various companies have taken to listing a wide range
of rates for one or more of their cards and not committing to one
until they have conducted a credit check.
</P>
<P>
   It is akin to a rental car company asking for all sorts of
information before it tells you how much it costs to rent a midsize
car in Phoenix _ and then making you wait two weeks to find out.
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying that the practice is illegal; indeed, it seems
patently reasonable to base the cost of credit on a borrower's
creditworthiness. But critics contend that listing multiple
potential rates _ a practice called risk-based, or tiered, pricing
_ is not what Congress intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a radical shift'' in card marketing, said Ken
McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action, an advocacy
group based in San Francisco. ``Banks don't quote rates until it's
clear whom they are dealing with. It looks like the free
marketplace is being shuttered, replaced instead with targeted
offers based on your credit history.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say that tailoring rates to creditworthiness may be
a result of a welcome democratization of credit, in which consumers
with black marks like garnishments or liens on their records are no
longer necessarily rejected. ``Even people like that now can get a
credit card,'' noted Janis Smith, spokeswoman for the Comptroller
of the Currency.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators say they have not received enough complaints
for this issue to register; the 1,620 complaints last year over
national banks' disclosures of credit card terms were mostly about
rate increases on existing accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a consumer is at a disadvantage when applying for a card
without knowing its exact terms. Comparison shopping becomes
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Aria cards, Visa cards that Providian Financial
offers only via the Internet. ``You apply _ and then we tell you
what you qualify for,'' Laurie Cole, a spokeswoman for Providian,
said of the four types of Aria cards, which have interest rates of
7.99 to 23.99 percent. ``In order to offer credit to such a broad
spectrum of people, we need to know something about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said that Providian's direct-mail solicitations, to people
who have been at least minimally screened, offer only one rate, but
that balance transfers still need to be, as she put it,
``customized.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo also bases rates on its judgment of risk after an
introductory 5.9 percent for six months, the rate rises to 12.75,
16.15 percent and 18.15 percent. It typically takes two or three
weeks after applying to learn which rate will be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, Smith said, is that consumers cannot assume that all
issuers are alike _ or that they can skip reading the fine print.
``More and more banks are setting individual terms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A consumer who is stuck with an unattractive rate, however, has
an option: canceling the card. He should not let it sit in his
wallet; besides accumulating possible annual fees, the card
represents potential borrowing power that could give other lenders
_ say, for a mortgage _ distinct pause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
