<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BUSH-EDUCATION-$     03-24 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-EDUCATION-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH AND GORE ON EDUCATION: A KEY SIMILARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 26)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As they stumble over each other to use schools as
campaign backdrops, Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush are as far apart on education as a Democrat and Republican can
get.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would devote $115 billion of the federal budget surplus
over the next 10 years to provide universal access to preschools,
create smaller high schools, improve teacher quality and aid school
reconstruction. Bush opposes big federal education programs,
offering a modest $5.5 billion over five years, and telling voters,
``I'm not running for national superintendent.'' He promises
greater local control over federal education dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But in one crucial education area, the two prospective
presidential nominees are remarkably similar.
</P>
<P>
   Both favor rigorous standardized tests at key grade levels
coupled with sanctions _ including loss of federal funds _ for
low-scoring schools that fail to show improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are using this idea of accountability to show
they are centrists on education, an issue that ranks high among
voter concerns in most polls.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, testing and sanctions are part of his bid to define
himself as a ``compassionate conservative'' _ upping minority test
scores in Texas through state-imposed discipline on schools.
Although the core of accountability was in place when Bush was
first elected governor in 1994, he lists the rise in test scores
among Texas minorities as one of his key accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   For schools in poor districts that fail to bring up test scores,
Bush would take away federal money earmarked for them to assist
needy, underachieving students. Known as Title I funding, the money
would go directly to parents under the Bush plan. They could use it
for private school tuition or transfer their children to other
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   To Gore, testing and sanctions allow him to position himself as
a hard-nosed centrist, unlike the Republicans' image of liberal
Democrats who throw money at social problems with little care on
whether there is measurable progress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants all states to impose high school exit exams _ 26 have
them so far. States and school districts that turn around ``failing
schools'' in poverty zones should get federal dollar bonuses, Gore
says.
</P>
<P>
   Schools with plummeting test scores should be shut down and
reopened with a new principal, intensive training for teachers and,
ultimately, removal of low-performing instructors, Gore says.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore administration is spending $134 million this
year trying to turn around low-performing schools that have
significant Title I low-income student enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   School districts failing to show progress by this September risk
possible loss of their share of the administration's $7.9 billion
Title I budget.
</P>
<P>
   Under Department of Education regulations, schools receiving
this money must permit their students to transfer to other public
schools or to special charter schools within the local public
school district.
</P>
<P>
   But therein lies a key difference between the two candidates.
Bush would permit vouchers for private school, but Gore would not.
The Democrats are reluctant to risk offending public school
teachers, an important part of the Democratic support base. The
American Federation of Teachers and the National Education
Association gave $482,000 in unregulated ``soft money'' to
Democrats in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Public school principals and superintendents for the most part
have embraced high-stakes standardized testing as the best way to
ward off their biggest fear: vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   But the carrot-and-stick world of accountability has many
detractors among education specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're training a generation of Jeopardy contestants,'' said
Peter Sacks, author of a book called ``Standardized Minds: The High
Price of America's Testing Culture and What We Can Do to Change
It.''
</P>
<P>
   The book cites teacher surveys over the past decade by
researchers at UCLA and the University of Colorado showing the vast
majority of teachers feeling heavy pressure to improve test
results. The Colorado survey reported the most common complaint
from teachers: ``Too much teaching to test content and test
format.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If tests displace everything else in school, then all kids
learn is how to take tests,'' said Gary Orfield, a Harvard
education professor. ``There ought to be serious examination of the
assumptions behind this movement, but it's not happening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Testing and sanctions defenders say the system, while not
perfect, has worked well enough to guarantee that students emerge
from classrooms having actually learned something.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Carnine, a University of Oregon education professor who
has advised Bush, said that ``school failure has always been an
adult problem. Rhetoric aside, people didn't care if poor kids
learned or not. That's changed with accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Chester Finn Jr., a testing advocate who is president of the
Washington-based Thomas B. Fordham Foundation, says the best models
are high school advanced placement (AP) exams, where students cover
a subject such as American history or biology in depth. At the end
of the course, they take a test that earns them college credit or
permits skipping introductory courses if they score high enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's have tests worth teaching to,'' he said. ``If it can be
done in AP, it could be done in 4th grade. Then you'd have a proper
curriculum, tests to prove progress and we'd be a lot better off.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7197 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS     03-24 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MINISTER ACCUSED OF WAR CRIMES DEPORTED TO U.N. TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The State Department said Friday that a Rwandan
clergyman who spent nearly three years in a Laredo jail was
extradited to Africa to face genocide charges before a United
Nations tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a former Seventh-day Adventist pastor,
is the first person arrested on American soil to face such a trial,
said Don DeGabrielle, an assistant U.S. attorney. Other
extraditions from the United States have returned the accused to a
nation, not an international court.
</P>
<P>
   The International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda is being held in
Arusha, Tanzania, an African nation on the Indiana Ocean that
borders Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has accused Ntakirutimana of leading attackers
armed with machetes, grenades and guns in a murderous April 1994
rampage that killed dozens of people who were hiding in his church.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana is a
Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are all condemned to die! It is all over for you!'' the
pastor said, according to a witness who later hid among the
corpses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ntakirutimana's lawyer nor his son, a physician who
practices in Laredo, could be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly man's lawyer, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey
Clark, has said that his client would not receive a fair trial
because Rwandans questioned by Ntakirutimana's counsel could face
violent reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has maintained that his client is being unjustly accused
as a result of tribal hatred.
</P>
<P>
   DeGabrielle said U.S. Marshals and a physician flew with
Ntakirutimana from Laredo to Houston Thursday morning. From there
he was to continue to Amsterdam and then to Tanzania.
Ntakirutimana's age has been given variously as 73 to 75.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials were not certain how soon he would
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright signed a
warrant authorizing Ntakirutimana to be extradited, following four
years of legal appeals that led all the way to the U.S. Supreme
Court. In January, the high court declined to hear his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The former minister was first arrested in September 1996 after
legally emigrating here with his wife to live with their son. He
has been in and out of jail in Laredo since.
</P>
<P>
   The trials in Arusha are only the third such international
forum. Others include the ongoing tribunal at The Hague,
Netherlands, addressing allegations of genocide in the former
Yugoslavia, and the trials against Nazi criminals in Nuremberg,
Germany, following World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAQ-U.N.-485&AMP;ADD-NYT     03-24 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN EXHORTS U.N. COUNCIL ON `OIL FOR FOOD' FOR IRAQIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned Friday that
the United Nations was in danger of losing a propaganda war with
President Saddam Hussein of Iraq if the ``oil for food'' program
intended to help Iraqi civilians suffering under sanctions is not
made more effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The humanitarian situation in Iraq poses a serious moral
dilemma for this organization,'' Annan told the council. ``The
United Nations has always been on the side of the vulnerable and
the weak, and has always sought to relieve suffering, yet here we
are accused of causing suffering to an entire population.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at a special daylong Security Council session to review
the organization's work in Iraq, during which the United States was
on the defensive against criticism that it is blunting the positive
impact of the program by blocking more than 1,000 import contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to such criticism, James B. Cunningham, the deputy
U.S. representative at the United Nations, announced Friday that
the United States was lifting its holds on 70 contracts worth at
least $100 million in the Iraqi sanctions committee, which reviews
Iraqi orders. The United States also formally introduced its
resolution doubling to $600 million the value of oil equipment Iraq
may import every six months. Since December, there have been no
limits on the oil Iraq can export.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham offered several proposals for better supervision in
Iraq, so that U.S. suspicions about the ultimate use or
destinations of certain imported goods, including electrical,
scientific, telecommunications and oil equipment, could be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its current problems, Cunningham said, Iraq's oil
exports and food imports are reaching the levels that prevailed
before Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, which led to
international sanctions and the Persian Gulf war in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In a long speech accompanied by statistical material circulated
to council members, Cunningham continued to place much of the blame
for shortcomings in the oil sales plan on Saddam's government,
which, he said, refuses to expedite orders, share information or
allow inspections at many sites.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also took the Iraqis to task, saying people living under
sanctions are ``often victims both of their own government and of
the measures taken against it.'' The only way to end that, he
added, is for Iraq to comply with council decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The council is waiting to see if Saddam will allow the return of
weapons inspectors, the key to ending sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   But Annan expressed anguish over the position the United Nations
now finds itself in, with an uncooperative Iraq on one side and an
intransigent United States on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in danger of losing the argument, or the propaganda war
_ if we haven't already lost it _ about who is responsible for this
situation, President Saddam Hussein or the United Nations,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During Friday's debate, several council members tried to shift
from past blame to future efforts to make the ``oil for food''
program work.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock of Britain, speaking to reporters before
Friday afternoon's session, said there were numerous things the
council could do without further debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can speed the procedures in the sanctions committee,'' he
said. ``We can inject more cash into the U.N. program in Iraq. We
can start to stop the smuggling that is going on, the illegal oil
sales. We can increase the number of monitors looking at the
program's delivery in Iraq, and if we do that, we can bring down
the number of holds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, French and Chinese were most critical Friday of
the U.S. and British on Iraq. Sergey Lavrov, the Russian
representative, accused the United States and Britain of killing
more than 140 people and wounding hundreds more in attacks over the
no-flight zones in northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any explanation that these strikes were not directed at
civilians does not hold water,'' Lavrov said. He called for an
early suspension of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Peter van Walsum, the Dutch representative and chairman of the
council's Iraqi sanctions committee, said that despite differences,
there was a council consensus that Iraq still has to convince the
world that it does not have dreams of creating prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq is the only country in modern history that has not only
attempted to develop all categories of weapons of mass destruction
_ nuclear, biological and chemical _ but has actually used such
weapons, both against a foreign enemy and against its own
citizens,'' van Walsum said. ``In doing so, Iraq has placed itself
in a league of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, two issues lying at the heart of the debate on
Iraq had rarely been raised. One is the scarcity of verifiable
information beyond what is physically visible to United Nations
officials in Iraq _ whose appointments Baghdad can control in the
sense that it can reject nominees for relief positions, and whose
movements are frequently circumscribed.
</P>
<P>
   All health and poverty figures the United Nations has to work
with are provided by the Iraqi government. Journalists cannot
report freely in the country, and the international news agencies
there must use Iraqi citizens for day-to-day reporting, which
usually amounts to no more than repeating what officials say in the
government-controlled press. Families of critics face wholesale
retaliation, diplomats based in Baghdad say.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi government decisions are often opaque, some United Nations
officials say. In some ministries, there appears to be little
planning for social development using what funds are available to
the government from its own resources.
</P>
<P>
   In the virtual absence of independent information-gathering in
Iraq, critics of Saddam say, the effects of sanctions can be
manipulated to influence public opinion inside and outside the
country, as a few speakers noted Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Butler, a diplomat in residence at the Council on
Foreign Relations, who was chief arms inspector in Iraq from 1997
to 1999, argues that sanctions worked when they were first imposed
after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got an immoral and utterly determined regime _ and
people are very frightened of Saddam _ sanctions might work
initially, depending not on how severe they are or how the
leadership reacts to them,'' Butler said in an interview Wednesday.
``They did, in the Iraq case, concentrate their minds for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However, given this immorality and ruthless determination, the
longer the time sanctions are applied, the less and less effective
they become, to the point where they invert in their effectiveness
for two reasons,'' he said. ``One, they get busted through a black
market and two, the leadership is able to parlay this into a reason
for staying in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's exactly where Saddam is now,'' he said. ``Today
the regime is absolutely prospering through its black market
operations _ and the longer they go on, the leakier things become _
and he is successfully deploying them propagandistically. He's
saying, `Only I can protect you from all those bad people out
there, and that's why you've got to stick with me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
