<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POPE-ISRAEL-ASSESS-2T     03-24 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ISRAEL-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: POPE'S TRIP TO ISRAEL IS SEEN AS AGENT OF CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also POPE-HOLYLAND) 
(lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ It was inconceivable that Pope John Paul II, as he
glided serenely though the Holy Land on a personal pilgrimage and a
secondary mission of interfaith healing, would transform a region
characterized by divisiveness and hatred. Even for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   But despite an outbreak of violence at a Palestinian refugee
camp and the verbal sniping over Jerusalem that ruined his
interdenominational gathering, the pope has managed so far to hover
above the fray. In doing so, he has presented what some see as a
model of brotherly discourse to religious leaders here. And he has
established a soothing tone that quieted most of the tensions and
made both Israelis and Palestinians feel supported by his visit.
</P>
<P>
   That is a feat, considering the political agendas that have gone
unsatisfied. Many Israelis wanted the pope to apologize for the
Catholic Church's silence during the Holocaust; he didn't. Many
Palestinians wanted him to explicitly endorse the Palestinian
refugees' right of return to their homes in Israel; he didn't do
that either.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as if they were embarrassed in his presence by how much they
had been demanding, there has been no outcry from either side about
what has not been said so far. The pope spent Friday, the fourth
day of his six-day visit here, with his own faithful, celebrating a
giant outdoor Mass on the Mount of Beatitudes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the pope has reaffirmed stances he took previously:
recognizing Israel and the enormity of the Holocaust on the one
hand, and giving his blessing to Palestinian nationalist
aspirations on the other.
</P>
<P>
   But by doing so in person and in this place, he underscored his
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By saying right here on Palestinian soil that he was praying
for the Palestinians who are homeless, the pope abridged the whole
Palestinian story,'' an editorial in Al-Hayat al-Jadida, a
Palestinian daily, said.
</P>
<P>
   When do Israelis hold their tongues? They did so this week,
impressed into silence. On Wednesday the pope brought together
about 50 high-ranking Orthodox Jewish and Catholic clergymen for an
unprecedented meeting, after which his public appearance with the
chief rabbis of Israel was suffused with an unusual warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, when his visit to the Yad Vashem Holocaust
memorial did not produce the long-awaited official apology from the
Church, they were practically silent.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Rabbi Yisrael Meir Lau issued a statement about what he
wished the pope had said. But it was decidedly neutral and
expressed no explicit disappointment. Earlier in the day, in an
unusually conciliatory comment, the rabbi said he did not expect
``one pope to condemn a predecessor,'' seemingly abandoning his
previous insistence that Pius XII's failure to speak out against
the Holocaust be denounced.
</P>
<P>
   The three major Israeli daily newspapers, which often emphasize
the negative, ran solemn, moving headlines Friday morning about the
pope's memorial to the victims. Maariv said, ``With sorrow, with
sadness, with silence.'' Haaretz said, ``The message is greater
than the words.'' Yedioth Ahronoth called it ``The pope's
kaddish,'' using the Hebrew word for the Jewish mourning prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis have been won over by the many stories that circulated
this week about the pope's childhood friendships with Jews and acts
of kindness toward Jews after the war. They had not expected to
feel such a heady affirmation in his visit. No one could have
imagined that elderly ultra-Orthodox rabbis would have bounded to
their feet, as they did on Wednesday, to surrounded him as if he
were a celebrity and try to bond with him as fellow Eastern
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Palestinian refugees on Wednesday said that the pope
seemed to understand their plight, many Israelis said Friday that
he stepped inside and grasped their tremulous emotions about the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he sounded almost Jewish,'' said Szewach Weiss, a
Polish-born Holocaust survivor and chairman of the Yad Vashem
Council, who was exhilarated. ``He gets it. Definitely. He is
building a bridge between Jews and Catholics over the river of
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally breathless, Haim Ramon, an Israeli Cabinet minister
speaking for the government, declared: ``This is a milestone in the
relationship between Judaism and Christianity.'' He continued:
``The majority of steps toward reconciliation, in my opinion, have
already been taken by this pope. The image of the Roman Catholic
Church in Israel is better today than it was three or four days
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's effect on the Palestinians was not as powerfully
curative. His day in Bethlehem ended up highlighting the gulf
between Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and his most
desperate constituents, the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   A violent confrontation erupted between the Palestinian police
and the residents of the Deheisheh refugee camp shortly after the
pope left on Wednesday. It revealed the schism between the
authorities and the people who feel that their cause _ the right of
return _ may be sacred but that they are neglected and may be sold
out during the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But the visit also made many Palestinians proud, since the pope
embraced their suffering and treated their aspirations for
statehood as legitimate and logical. ``The pope and Palestine''
read the posters, banners and bumper stickers. It seemed to make
Palestine a more tangible place, their place, some said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent his very first day here with us, not the Israelis,''
said Maher Abu Nidal, a vendor. ``The Israeli security forces had
to hand him over to us, and we Muslims protected him like he was
our own. He was most welcome here in Palestine. I felt very proud.
We accepted him, he accepted us, like it was the most natural
thing. Also, the world watched and learned.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Potential tensions still lie ahead. On Saturday, he visits
Nazareth, where the cornerstone of a mosque has been laid in the
shadow of the Basilica of the Annunciation, raising tensions
between Christian and Muslim Arabs and between the state of Israel,
which approved the mosque, and the Vatican, which disapproves.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday is the pope's interfaith trifecta day, when he stops
at Christian, Jewish and Muslim holy sites in the walled Old City,
which is at the heart of the dispute over Jerusalem's status.
Arguments over Jerusalem broke down the attempted interfaith
meeting on Thursday. There is no meeting of minds on this core
issue, and nothing that the pope can do except duck when the
subject arises.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every other respect, the pope's presence here has been
perceived as a potential agent of change. The fact that he has
wanted for so many decades to make this pilgrimage, and that he
undertook it when he was old and frail as a kind of apex of his
papacy, has affected the way he has been received. It has given the
visit a sense of undeniable magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, the debate about Jewish-Christian relations has been
almost therapeutic, and not only because it distracted attention
from the many political scandals. The pope's visit to Yad Vashem
focused attention on what binds Israelis: that which they cannot
forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good that the pope did not ask for forgiveness,'' David
Grossman, the novelist, wrote in a column on Friday. ``No one can
ask for forgiveness for the Holocaust in the name of others, and no
one is entitled to forgive in the name of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the pope's presence at Yad Vashem, inside the deepest
dimension of Jewish suffering, and the acts that he performed,
personally as a man, resonate far more strongly than could any
official declaration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
