<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON BUSINESS  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Free Lunch, Indeed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer is warning shareholders not to attend its annual meeting
on an empty stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Admission tickets for the April 27 meeting include this note:
``Due to space limitations, we will be serving lighter refreshments
at this year's annual meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, said Brian McGlynn, a Pfizer spokesman, when
attendees would be treated to a sumptuous spread of smoked salmon
and other goodies. But attendance started rising a few years ago,
and the company cut back to serving a continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   A record crowd is expected to pack the ballroom of the Grand
Hyatt Hotel in New York this year because of Pfizer's pending
merger with Warner-Lambert, so the pickings will be even slimmer.
Thus the note, McGlynn said, ``so people won't be disappointed and
say, `I was expecting more of a meal.'''
</P>
<P>
   John Wilcox, vice chairman of Georgeson Shareholder
Communications, a proxy solicitation firm in New York, said the
note was unusual, but the move to lighter fare was not. Besides
wanting to save money, companies have second thoughts about the
merits of drawing crowds of individual shareholders with giveaways
like meals and product samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encouraging small investors to come simply to get a meal
doesn't really contribute to the purpose of a meeting,'' Wilcox
said.
</P>
<P>
   --DAWN GILBERTSON &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
