<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DANGELO-MUSIC-REVIEW-     03-24 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGELO-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LADIES' MAN, PLEASING AND TEASING 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were shrieks and squeals of joy when D'Angelo
finally took off his shirt during his encore at Radio City Music
Hall on Monday night. With his pumped-up shoulders and chiseled
abs, D'Angelo is one of the reigning sex symbols in
rhythm-and-blues, singing respectful come-ons in a voice that can
be sweetly imploring or insouciant and assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can provide everything you desire,'' he vowed. Yet offering
himself up as a sensual fantasy is only the most conventional facet
of what he's up to. D'Angelo seeks nothing less than a grand
reunion of African-American music to satisfy body, mind and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   His heart is in music, not hitmaking. Tracing African-American
musical connections wherever they lead, D'Angelo would rather delve
into the mysteries of the groove than trim his songs to fit radio
formulas. Like the seduction he promises, D'Angelo's music takes
its time and pays attention to the possibilities of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   On his two albums, D'Angelo is often a one-man studio band.
Onstage, he made a large group just as flexible and audacious as
the music he created on his own. At a time when hip-hop has
decimated bands, D'Angelo still prizes live musicians as the key to
making music that strives for synthesis rather than pastiche. He
looks back toward a line of funk visionaries; his new album,
``Voodoo'' (Virgin), makes no secret of his admiration for James
Brown, Sly Stone, Stevie Wonder, Marvin Gaye, George Clinton and
Prince, for starters. Like them, he knows how to make a tune bump
and grind, shimmy and strut, and he's happy to make people dance.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't simply recreate old sure-fire moves. D'Angelo
keeps tinkering: pulling the vocals far from the beat, piling up
dissonant jazz harmonies for the horn section, hinting at
Thelonious Monk in a bass line, double-timing funk into gospel. His
first song on Monday night, ``Devil's Pie'' _ about the temptations
of materialism _ distilled its groove down to an eerie combination
of Ahmir Thompson's ticking cymbal, Pino Palladino's sparse bass
riff and a high, shivering tremolo note from Samuel Jones on
guitar. Later, performing the title song from his 1995 album,
``Brown Sugar'' (EMI), D'Angelo turned it inside out, pushing its
chorus into the background to toy with syncopations and
countermelodies.
</P>
<P>
   In his two-hour set, D'Angelo embodied all sorts of soul
archetypes. He was a nasal down-home connoisseur of ``Chicken
Grease'' and a high-stepping soul man, bounding across the stage.
He was a gospel preacher answered by tambourine-shaking backup
singers. He was an infuriated betrayed husband, smashing a
microphone stand to the stage amid hard-rock guitars; he was an
imploring suitor in falsetto, begging a lover to cheat on her
boyfriend with him just once more. During the song, he lay on the
stage and let a woman from the audience stroke his chest and back,
igniting a feminine uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, D'Angelo was a brilliant band leader. The
two-hour set traveled to Memphis, to New Orleans, to Minneapolis,
to Augusta, Ga., to Chicago and to Detroit. The music transmuted
itself through 50 years of rhythm-and-blues, up to a hip-hop cameo
from Busta Rhymes. It was overarching ambition realized through the
meticulous details of horn lines, backup vocal strategies and
rhythm-section blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   While D'Angelo's calm charisma held every fan's attention, his
own attention was on the music. Immediately after he took off his
shirt, he sat down to his electric piano to play abstruse jazz
chords. Sure of his groove and determined to stretch it, he wasn't
courting applause: he was slipping one more experiment into the
flux.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
