<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-PRISONS-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-24 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$3 BILLION NEEDED TO REPAIR AGING PRISON UNITS, TEXAS OFFICIALS
SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Five years after the Texas prison system
completed the largest construction program in the nation's history,
top prison officials said Friday they will need as much as $3
billion more to fix up aging units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some old units,'' said Texas Board of Criminal
Justice member John David Franz of Hidalgo. ``The thing is we can't
wait for five years and allow some of these units to fall into a
state of disrepair to where they're uninhabitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Franz, who chairs the board's facilities committee, made his
comments in a report to the board, which concluded its bimonthly
two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wayne Scott, executive director of the Texas Department
of Criminal Justice, said after the meeting that he has no
intention of going to the Legislature next year with hat in hand
asking for $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I wouldn't get it,'' Scott said. ``It's going to
be highly unlikely to get a large, large appropriation for this up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, state law prohibits the agency from seeking more
money than it needs in a two-year budget cycle, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Franz called the financial needs ``depressing'' and said the
board and the Legislature will be faced with tough decisions in
coming years over whether it will be more economical to refurbish
the old units or tear them down and build new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in a dangerous state today,'' Franz said.
``There won't be anything in a hazardous condition next year. But
it's coming. We're trying to be proactive and figure out how we're
going to fund the refurbishing, the renovation of some of these
older units. Or maybe the Legislature wants to build more new
prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he put the price tag at fixing up 26 of the system's
older units _ some of which are more than 100 years old _ at $3
billion over the next six years, Scott and other administrators
said the cost would be much less.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's price tag was $1.2 billion over the next four
legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, that smaller figure is close to the $1.7 billion Texas
spent adding new prisons to house 95,000 more prisoners in a
fast-track construction program that ended in 1995. The new cost
estimates, officials said, represent what it will take to repair
water and sewer lines, repair roofs and ventilation systems, and
otherwise fix up older units.
</P>
<P>
   The Huntsville Unit, the prison system's first facility, is 152
years old, and 10 other units are at least 75 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not anything you want to hear, but it's something we
expected,'' said board chairman Alfred M. ``Mac'' Stringfellow of
San Antonio. ``It's not by our choice. It's just something we have
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said the agency's first step will be to analyze short- and
long-term prison repair needs for each two-year budget cycle. He
estimates TDCJ will need about $350 million during the next
legislative session for the most urgent repairs, a figure that is
10 times what the department normally spends on facility
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prison system is a growth industry unfortunately,''
Stringfellow said. ``As long as there are criminals in this state,
we've got to have a place to lock them up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
