<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7214 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH25-COX-1STLEDE     03-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH25-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Changes throughout
 &HT;    Bush invades Clinton territory
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   White House wannabe George W. Bush on Friday took his campaign
to Little Rock, a southern capital that might be able to give
Austinites a glimpse of what happens when an ex-resident becomes
president.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A Bush presidency would not mean we're all going to
be federal judges or ambassadors. It would not mean a quick,
federally-funded fix to our traffic woes. And it probably won't
mean a second presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, the experience has been predictable. Folks who
liked Gov. Bill Clinton think President Bill Clinton has been good
for Little Rock. Folks who thought Gov. Bill Clinton was Slick
Willie are glad he is becoming a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   As for hard-core evidence that the city has produced a
president, so far there's not much, short of indictments and
subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to gauge how a Bush presidency might affect Austin.
But experts say it will, and part of the story could be what, or
who, we would lose. ``If (Bush) becomes president it will really
impact this city,'' said Herb Berkowitz of the Washington-based
Heritage Foundation, which has studied presidential transitions.
``I would suspect that hundreds of your neighbors would move to a
place called Washington D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he's lived in public housing here since January 1995,
Bush is quick to remind that he's not the Austinite that Lyndon B.
Johnson was. Still, he is convinced that Austin, and Texas, would
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have a positive effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Mayor Kirk Watson, a good Democrat, does not want Bush to
become president. But the mayor can see the upside to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage would be that he is familiar with Austin,'' said
Watson. ``He is familiar with what we need and you would hope that
because of that familiarity he would be in a position to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hazelwood, president and chief executive officer of the
Greater Austin Chamber of Commerce, said a Bush presidency would
produce ``natural interest in where the president comes from, and
the president is going to be returning here periodically.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, however, is where ``here'' will be. The Texas
White House probably would be the 1,600-acre ranch Bush recently
purchased near Crawford, west of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I win,'' said Bush, ``I anticipate spending time here
with Laura and my family at our place up in Central Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in Little Rock, the biggest bricks-and-mortar evidence of the
Clinton presidency is still to come. The city is getting a
presidential library, though not everyone is thrilled. Plans to
name a street for Clinton were scaled back after someone suggested
``Impeachment Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for us having a national root canal on our local
politics, I don't think it's benefited us one iota,'' Arkansas GOP
executive director Chris Carnahan of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Little Rock compares the Clinton presidency to
dental discomfort. From day one, the Clinton candidacy raised the
profile of a city previously best defined by the 1957 integration
crisis at Central High School, where Bush had a campaign event on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Harvel, head of the Little Rock Chamber of Commerce, said
the city has benefited from the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people across the nation know about Austin,'' he
said. ``Not everyone knew about Little Rock. Now, everyone knows
where Little Rock is. Now, no one asks what state it's in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father said the benefits are more indirect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president should stay out of that,'' ex-President
George Bush said of nudging federal money and projects homeward.
``It's different than the LBJ days. I don't think you can, on
public expenditures of money, leave yourself open to the charge
that you are paving your own state, as opposed to a congressman who
is expected to do that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But a president can find ways to help the homefolks, Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, we had the Republican National Convention in
Houston because people saw that would please me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas already has some high-profile examples of what it means to
have a native son in high places. The LBJ Space Center near Houston
is a product of the Lyndon B. Johnson administration.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has two presidential libraries: Johnson's at the
University of Texas and Bush's at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   The Electoral College will decide whether a George W. Bush
presidential library will be needed, but the president of a Dallas
college sounds interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No discussion has taken place with the governor, but with
Laura Bush being an alumna of SMU we would be receptive to
discussions about the opportunity,'' said Southern Methodist
University President R. Gerald Turner. ``But this is obviously
premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
