</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BIENNIAL 2000 AT THE WHITNEY MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial notebook on Friday,
March 24:
</P>
<P>
   Hans Haacke's ``Sanitation'' lives in a small room on the third
floor of the Whitney Museum, whose Biennial 2000 exhibition opened
Thursday. Frankly, almost naively political, ``Sanitation'' caused
a fracas even before the opening. The work will strike many viewers
as an uncompromising if overblown attack on the cultural criticisms
of Rudolph Giuliani, Patrick Buchanan and Pat Robertson. Their
comments on contemporary art are placed on the wall in a typeface
that is meant to recall the dictates of the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trivializing the Holocaust, as some critics have
charged, Haacke tries to lay bare the seeds of cultural repression,
and he does so in a context that explicitly evokes the
constitutional protection of free speech and the separation of
church and state. But not even controversy _ not even Marylou
Whitney jumping ship _ can make ``Sanitation'' visually
interesting. Getting in and out of its crowded room is more
complicated than the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this Biennial does not take its tone from
``Sanitation.'' The show is jumpier, funnier, more playful, more
inventive. A Biennial takes a lot of explaining, an accounting for
how the artists were chosen and why. You learn to approach the
exhibition labels reluctantly, so earnest and self-justifying do
they often seem. The last thing you expect from a gathering of this
kind _ a summa of contemporary art over the past two years _ is
flirtatiousness. Yet that's what you get. Like John Currin's
tuberous female nudes, this Biennial is coy and brazen at once.
Like Lisa Yuskavage's equally tuberous female nudes, it is
self-regarding, self-revealing, and self-desiring without ever
seeming narcissistic or self-centered.
</P>
<P>
   The team of six non-Whitney curators who selected the works in
this exhibition have commented on its international flavor, the
presence of artists who work in America but come from somewhere
else. There's also a reportorial edge here. Chakaia Booker's ``It's
So Hard to Be Green'' is a monumental wall-construct pieced
together from discarded tires. It is impossible to see this work in
a self-contained way. It reaches back to the junkyard sources of
those treads and tubes, that vulcanized scent. The same with the
towering installations by Rita Bannerjee and Sarah Sze. One is
inorganically organic, the other almost bio-mechanical. Their
shapes are transcendent, but their contents are allusive, worldly,
pieced together from the detritus of living.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, this Biennial will be read as a referendum on
contemporary art _ a report for some on importance or unimportance,
for others a survey of shock. But when shock ends, play begins, and
taboos, whether sexual, political or formal, whether old or new,
become ironic conventions. You can see that happening everywhere:
in Kojo Griffin's thuggish teddy bears, in Vik Muniz's ``The Raft
of the Medusa'' drawn in Bosco syrup on a light-table, in Josiah
McElheny's fashion narrative in blown glass, in Kurt Kauper's
hyper-realist ``Diva Fictions.''
</P>
<P>
   The very idea of the museum _ an institution with complex taboos
of its own _ appears to fracture at this Biennial. Years ago the
Whitney introduced film and video works to the Biennial. Now it
adds Internet art. With a mouse-click or two, you can immerse
yourself in Ben Benjamin's ``Superbad'' or Lew Baldwin's
``Red-smoke.'' Even with the addition of Internet art, it will take
real willfulness to sustain any controversy arising from this
Biennial. That may turn out to be just one of its many pleasures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
