<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL ST. UNIMPRESSED BY PRICE RISE IN OIL PATCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With per-barrel prices continuing to flirt with $30 and gasoline
going for $1.75 a gallon in some parts of the country, many people
are in a lather about oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, those people aren't on Wall Street.
Based on movements in the stock prices of the integrated oil
companies, you would think that oil was selling for $16 a barrel
and headed lower. As a stock group, the Exxon Mobils and Texacos of
the world are down for the year so far.
</P>
<P>
   Big Oil may start doing better soon, though, because in a few
weeks these companies will start reporting first-quarter earnings.
The consensus is that those numbers are going to be big.
</P>
<P>
   William L. Randol, senior petroleum analyst at Banc of America
Securities, took some time last week to talk about why investors
continue to shun the oil stocks, and about why they should take
another look. Following are excerpts from the conversation: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Oil prices have about tripled in the last year or so, but the
stocks haven't done a thing. Why is that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The stock-price charts of these companies all look the same:
flat in early 1999, a big run on the heels of the OPEC agreement to
limit production, then flat and finally down this year. All this
time the price of oil kept making new highs.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason the stocks haven't done better is that
investors don't seem to be giving any credibility to the new highs.
Another problem has been the infatuation with the Internet and
technology stocks. Cyclical industries in general have suffered
because of that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But isn't the operating environment for these companies very
good? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In many ways the fundamentals for oil stocks have never been
better.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the commodity is higher than anyone would have
thought. We think oil will settle this year at around $25 a barrel.
Companies can do very well with prices at that level, because they
cut their costs dramatically as oil prices fell in the 1980s and
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies can do OK with oil prices at $18 a barrel, and
break even at $15 a barrel. So anything in the low- to mid-$20
range is fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Refining margins are also improving and will improve further
into spring and summer, because gasoline inventories are very low
and demand is very strong. Natural-gas prices are high. And even
the chemical business is doing well. So everything is clicking on
all cylinders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Just what does an increase in oil prices mean to the bottom
line for these companies? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. People forget just how sensitive earnings are to the
commodity price.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies, like Occidental Petroleum, Conoco and Texaco,
are the most sensitive to oil price changes, while the larger
companies, like BPAmoco and Exxon Mobil, are the least sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   For example, we figure a $1 rise in the price of a barrel of
West Texas oil raises earnings per share by 32 cents at Chevron. At
BPAmoco, the same increase boosts earnings per share by 12 cents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So how much are the price increases we have seen going to
bolster earnings? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Last year, operating earnings for the seven major oil
companies were just under $25 billion. Assuming oil prices average
$25 a barrel this year, the comparable figure should be just under
$40 billion. That's a gain of about 55 percent to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If oil prices average $21 a barrel next year, which is our
current assumption, in 2001 those earnings numbers should flatten
out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many people don't expect oil prices to remain at or near
these levels for very long. OPEC, which has an important meeting
this week, is under a lot of pressure to raise production. Do you
think that will happen, and that prices will soften? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The base case we have right now is that OPEC will recommend a
one-million-barrel-per-day increase in output, of which OPEC's
share would be 700,000 barrels and Mexico's would be 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think that will be enough to cause prices to decline
much this year. In fact, I am beginning to think my 2001 forecast
of $21-a-barrel oil is too low.
</P>
<P>
   Unless non-OPEC production rises dramatically soon, which we
don't think will happen, prices will stay well above $20 a barrel
next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which of these stocks do you like? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We like companies with three attributes: good production
growth, strong management and attractive valuations.
</P>
<P>
   In the last regard, some of the underachievers have P/E ratios
that are less than 12 times earnings, like Conoco.
</P>
<P>
   Based on those three criteria, we like Chevron, Conoco and
BPAmoco. We also have a strong buy on two refiners, Valero Energy
and Tosco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
