s f BC-INVEST-CONSUMER-GOODS     03-24 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CONSUMER-GOODS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECTOR THAT COULD USE A SHOULDER TO CRY ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble. Nabisco Holdings. Coca-Cola. Anheuser-Busch.
These are all prestigious, blue-chip names. So why are their shares
in such a funk?
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, companies like these that make soap,
crackers, beer and other consumer packaged goods have been the
scourge of Wall Street, losing as much as one-third of their value
while money pours into New Economy darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble got everyone's attention earlier this month,
when, on the heels of a rare earnings warning, its stock plummeted
more than $27 in a single day, chopping off 31 percent, or about
$36 billion, of its market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Dial said its quarterly earnings would be 10
percent lower than last year's, and investors responded by driving
down the share price by 23 percent in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors are behind the deluge. Raw materials prices are on
the rise. And with inflation low, many of these companies have lost
their power to increase prices.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the entire consumer products sector has been punished,
regardless of individual companies' performance under current
conditions. ``The great disconnect here is between the businesses
and their stocks,'' said Daniel Peris, an analyst for Argus
Research. ``It just doesn't matter how good a particular food
company is.''
</P>
<P>
   For investors, then, the issue is how to sort out the companies
that can handle the stresses from the companies that cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Consider beverage stocks. Coca-Cola has announced plans for a
major revision of the way it does business and is expected to
reduce its earnings projections next month. Its price-to-earnings
multiple for this year has tumbled from more than 46 in January to
32 as of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Anheuser-Busch has a better pricing structure and
more potential customers than at any time in the last 10 years,
according to John A. Faucher, an analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities.
Yet its multiple for 2000 has fallen by about a quarter, to 17.5 on
Friday. Anheuser-Busch shares closed at $57.3125 on Friday, 36
percent below the 12-month target of $90 set by Susan M. Byrne,
manager of the Gabelli Westwood Equity fund which holds the stock.
</P>
<P>
   For food companies, too, the problems of a few are tarnishing
the whole group. With supermarkets consolidating and wielding more
power in their relationships with manufacturers, investors have
shied away from well-run companies like Nabisco Holding and
Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies are better positioned to deal with it than
others, and the market is treating them as if they were all the
same,'' said Nomi Ghez, a food analyst for Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Peris, for example, said Bestfoods, a company whose brands
include Hellmann's mayonnaise, Knorr soups and Skippy peanut
butter, has consistently met earnings targets over the years and
has a coherent strategy. It closed at $42.875 on Friday. Campbell
Soup, by contrast, has had trouble increasing sales of its flagship
products because of changing lifestyles and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   And its chief executive, Dale F. Morrison, resigned on
Wednesday. Yet with a closing price of $30.50 on Friday, its stock
trades at at a multiple of 16 based on 2000 earnings estimates,
about the same as that of Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   The market's punishment has been ``indiscriminate,'' said Paul
Wayne, co-manager of the Kayne Anderson Rising Dividends fund,
which holds Bestfoods stock. He thinks the share price should rise
at a 15 percent to 30 percent rate over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Peris also lists Colgate-Palmolive and Kimberly-Clark, both P&AMP;G
competitors, as companies ``that are pumping on all eight cylinders
right now.'' He suggests that investors buy the good companies
while they can. ``When an entire sector is being pushed down, then
you have an opportunity to get good stocks at low prices,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ghez likes Nabisco, which has increased its cash flow and market
share under a new management team. ``They have delivered on
everything we expected the company to deliver,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, will anything change in the foreseeable future to get the
stocks moving? Just 10 years ago, most of them could be counted on
for steady, predictable earnings growth at rates of about 15
percent a year. Life is cyclical, so what may cause consumer
products to cycle back into the picture?
</P>
<P>
   Some companies may need to revise their strategies and start
selling off businesses that are not very profitable, said Emanuel
Goldman, a global consumer products analyst for Merrill Lynch.
``Today, when it's so hard to raise prices, you want to be sure
you're in the right businesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the theory that consolidation could set a fire
under consumer stocks. Merger talks between Heinz and Bestfoods
that collapsed in September would have created a food giant with
powerful global distribution, said John M. McMillin, a food analyst
for Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is to follow Coke's example, steering growth
expectations lower. ``My philosophy is that stocks will not turn or
improve until the fundamentals and earnings improve,'' said David
Garza, an analyst for Roxbury Capital Management, a fund manager in
Los Angeles, who has invested in consumer products companies in the
past. ``These companies are selling toothbrushes and toothpaste and
soft drinks. There are little games they can play to get us to buy
a little bit more. But long term, they cannot get dramatic
growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
