<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-NYT &LR;      03-24 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AIDES SAY THEY DIDN'T REALIZE SERIOUSNESS OF E-MAIL
PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House officials learned almost two years ago
of a major computer problem that resulted in the mishandling of the
administration's electronic mail. Now, as they defend themselves
against accusations that they illegally concealed the situation
from investigators, presidential aides are arguing that they lacked
the computer knowledge to really understand how important the
problem was.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, this matter involves complex technical issues,''
said the White House counsel, Beth Nolan, in a statement to
congressional investigators that she is scheduled to deliver next
week. ``Of course, my staff and I are lawyers with laypersons'
understanding of the technical complexities of electronic messaging
and archiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of e-mail messages sent to White House officials
from outside the office's network from 1996 to 1998 were not
properly stored in a computer archive. Specialists who have
reviewed the problem say it was caused by an unintentional error
when someone mistakenly capitalized the name of a computer server,
writing MAIL2 instead of Mail2. As a result, when the White House
received subpoenas from various investigative agencies and searched
the archive for relevant e-mails, many messages were overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery of the overlooked e-mail messages assumed on a new
degree of seriousness this week as the Justice Department disclosed
it had started a criminal investigation into whether the White
House intentionally kept the messages from investigators and
threatened computer specialists not to disclose the problem to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, Congress and the independent counsel's
office had all issued subpoenas to the White House seeking
information dealing with campaign fund-raising improprieties, the
Monica Lewinsky case and other matters. The White House had not
informed any of them of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for sure what is contained in the affected
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly no one saying, `The jig is up. We've been
caught,''' remarked Judge Royce C. Lamberth, who is handling a
civil case in U.S. District Court in Washington that touches on the
e-mail controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The case was filed against the Clinton administration by
Judicial Watch, a conservative legal group that is a fierce
antagonist of the White House. Larry Klayman, who heads Judicial
Watch, contends that the e-mail messages could be explosive, even
though they were written to White House officials and not by them.
Klayman told Lamberth at a hearing Friday that the correspondence
could include important evidence from former White House officials.
</P>
<P>
   But a Justice Department lawyer, James J. Gilligan, who sought
to delay Klayman's lawsuit while his office investigates, argued
that it was unlikely anything incriminating would turn up on the
messages. The Internet is not secure, he said, and people outside
the White House would be unlikely to provide any evidence in e-mail
form.
</P>
<P>
   One computer specialist from Northrop Grumman who was hired to
maintain the White House e-mail system has testified that a
colleague told her the e-mail dealt with a variety of
administration controversies, from campaign fund-raising practices
to the Lewinsky case. That colleague, however, testified before the
House Government Reform Committee on Thursday that he said no such
thing.
</P>
<P>
   At that hearing, which was called by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind.,
computer experts tried repeatedly to describe the computer problem
in everyday English. But they quickly started rattling off terms
like e-mail archiving and the design flow problem that left
onlookers confused.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, who is expected to testify on the issue next week, said
in a statement that her predecessor, Charles Ruff, knew of the
problem with e-mail years ago but did not really understand the
extent of it, or its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Mr. Ruff understood the technical problem at the time, he
did not think that the error had an effect on previous searches or
that it might affect future searches of e-mail records,'' Nolan
wrote. ``As a result, Ruff had no reason to believe there was any
need to notify investigative bodies of this error.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigative counsel for Burton's committee, Jim
Wilson, was not buying the White House defense. ``It may be a
difficult problem, but the onus was on them to come to an
understanding of what the problem was, and they didn't,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
