<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAR-SMART-SUVS-ART-$A     03-24 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-SUVS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPENSIVE SPORT UTILITIES FALL SHORT OF EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo has moved as NYT22 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By CHERYL JENSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luxury sport utilities built on the underpinnings of trucks, as
most are, tend to disappoint owners more than luxury cars _ and
also more than a new breed of carlike ``crossover'' SUVs, according
to two recent studies.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer satisfaction studies _ by Strategic Vision and J.D.
Power &AMP; Associates, two California-based research companies _
suggested that high expectations might be a factor in buyers'
dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luxury cars tend to provide some of the industry's
highest-quality offerings,'' said George Owens, manager of product
research at J.D. Power. ``People who are coming from luxury cars
are continuing to bring with them luxury-car expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   While most sport utilities, including luxury models like the
Cadillac Escalade and Lincoln Navigator, have bodies fixed to truck
frames, crossovers like the Lexus RX300 and BMW X5 use one-piece
unit bodies like most cars'. Crossovers also have suspensions and
steering systems much like those of cars, compared with the rugged,
often less sophisticated, systems of trucks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a report comparing the RX300 with traditional sport utilities
and luxury sedans, Daniel Gorrell, vice president of Strategic
Vision, said old-style SUVs did not deliver the attributes buyers
sought and fell short of meeting owners' emotional needs.
</P>
<P>
   These buyers want a luxury vehicle that makes them feel in
control, is able to handle anything, adds to the fun in their life
and gives a sense of freedom, he said. ``Yet these vehicles deliver
less well on these dimensions than luxury cars or the RX300,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   These truck-based luxury sport utilities scored lower than
luxury cars in quietness, engine performance, ease of entry and
exit, and particularly on fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 and 1999 initial quality studies by J.D. Power
indicated that consumers liked their luxury cars better, in
general, than their luxury trucks.
</P>
<P>
   One group in particular _ those who traded in luxury cars _ is
even less happy with their fancy trucks. These consumers'
complaints mostly related to the quality factors that the industry
calls ``fit and finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Several manufacturers have crossovers in the works, including
Buick, Pontiac, Porsche, Saab and Volkswagen. Gorrell said
crossovers ``represent the birth of a significant new segment that
can offer customers the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who has also seen some disenchantment, but doesn't
think it is a big problem, is George Petersen, president of
AutoPacific Inc., another consulting firm. Luxury SUVs provide
outstanding satisfaction, Petersen said, adding: ``But it's not the
same level of satisfaction as a luxury car, and it's a different
kind of satisfaction. They are still based on trucks and don't have
the same level of finesse as luxury cars.'' Owners take that into
account, he said, ``because, by golly, they are trucks.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 1941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
