<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-ART-N     03-24 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN CONGRESSIONAL BUDGET FIGHT, SOME COMMON GROUND
EXISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's partisan battle over the federal
budget, which lurched forward early Friday when the House narrowly
passed a Republican tax-and-spending blueprint, has a familiar ring
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want a big tax cut, more money for the military and
reductions in just about everything else. Democrats are trying to
expand or at least protect spending on a wide array of domestic
programs. Each side is attacking the other in apocalyptic terms.
The policy and political repercussions could be substantial.
</P>
<P>
   But it is worth noting that prosperity has brought the parties
closer on fiscal policy than either of them usually admits.
</P>
<P>
   Without debate or rancor, Republicans and Democrats have more or
less agreed that the surplus being generated by Social Security _
$1 trillion over the next five years and $2.3 trillion over a
decade _ should go to pay down the portion of the debt held by the
public, currently about $3.5 trillion. (The fine print would also
allow the money to be used to help create private investment
accounts within Social Security, a Republican goal that has been
put on the back burner at least until after the election.)
</P>
<P>
   There is common ground on other issues as well. Republicans are
proposing a substantial increase in spending on education, seeking
to neutralize an issue that long played to the advantage of
Democrats. Both parties want to provide money to add a prescription
drug benefit to Medicare, though they differ on the scale any such
program should have.
</P>
<P>
   And the unanimous votes this month in both the House and the
Senate to repeal the earnings limit on Social Security recipients
provided some hope that compromise might be possible on other tax
issues, like the marriage penalty paid by many two-income couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be doing a little bit more celebrating for what we
have been able to achieve as Republicans and Democrats alike,''
said Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, the chairman of the House Budget
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the differences, in both ideological and dollar terms,
are more than enough to create political friction on the campaign
trail this year as well as in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The House budget blueprint, passed by a largely party-line vote
of 211-207 early Friday after more than 12 hours of often rancorous
debate, would cut taxes by at least $150 billion over five years
and perhaps as much as $240 billion, and increase total government
spending authority by 3 percent, to $1.85 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has locked up the Republican
presidential nomination, wants a $483 billion tax cut over five
years _ more than his party is willing even to try getting through
Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who will be Bush's opponent in the fall,
says that the approach taken by Republicans in Congress would risk
a return to budget deficits and imperil efforts to shore up Social
Security and Medicare _ and that Bush's plan is even worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will soon take up a budget plan similar to the one
passed by the House, though it has been bottled up for the past
week in the Senate Budget Committee by conservatives who are
pressing for bigger tax cuts and less spending.
</P>
<P>
   Once both chambers have settled on and reconciled their budget
plans _ nonbinding resolutions that provide a framework for the
development of specific spending and tax bills _ the really
difficult work will begin.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the appropriations committees that set spending
levels for everything from fighter planes to farm aid and school
lunch programs will begin their work. If the past few years are any
guide, they will find it difficult if not impossible to remain
within the limits set out in the budget outline.
</P>
<P>
   The budget provides for a 6 percent increase in military
spending, to $307.3 billion, but essentially freezes nonmilitary
spending at $289 billion, requiring cuts in most programs once
inflation is taken into account. Most of the rest of the budget
goes to pay Social Security and Medicare benefits and interest on
the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the past several years, the Republican-controlled
Congress has approved nonmilitary spending increases well above the
inflation rate. In part, that is because of pressure from President
Clinton. But it is also because Republicans themselves have found
it hard to vote for spending cuts or freezes in popular programs at
a time when the budget surplus is swelling.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been to make it difficult for Republicans to pass
the appropriations bills needed to keep the government operating,
leading to an end-of-session rush to cut deals and get out of town,
even if it requires using budgetary gimmicks to make the numbers
add up. Such a prospect looms again this year, when members of
Congress will be particularly eager to get home to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The failure by Republicans to set realistic spending targets
``has delayed, rather than expedited, action on appropriations
bills and other fiscal legislation,'' Jacob J. Lew, the White House
budget director, said in a letter sent to congressional leaders
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is exacerbated by a split within the Republican
Party. House leaders had difficulty rounding up the votes they
needed to pass the budget early Friday because a group of
conservatives had threatened to vote against it on the ground that
it did not have enough safeguards against last-minute deals to
increase spending.
</P>
<P>
   Yet moderates and members of the appropriations committees
warned that the spending levels in the budget plan were already
unrealistically low, and that passing appropriations bills would
become even more difficult if conservatives insisted on further
cuts or more debt reduction.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
