<HEADER>
A7255 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-BARISH-AR     03-24 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-BARISH-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH BRIAN M. BARISH AND JOHN D. FREEMAN: AHA DIVERSIFIED
QUITY FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photos has moved as NYT26,27 to NYT photo clients.
Graphic of AHA Diversified Equity is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888
603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two heads are often better than one. And when it comes to the
task of managing a portfolio of large-capitalization value stocks,
which have badly lagged behind the broader market lately, the extra
brain power may come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the $138.8 million AHA Diversified Equity fund, run
jointly by Brian M. Barish, senior vice president of Cambiar
Investors, a money management firm in Englewood, Colo., and John D.
Freeman, president of the Investment Research Co., a money manager
in Rancho Santa Fe, Calif. Each oversees about one-half of the
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the two managers have never met each other, don't
talk to each other, and neither has expressed much desire to do so.
But they sound alike. Asked about their relationship, they replied
with identical words: ``He does his thing, and I do my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund, marketed to members of the American Hospital
Association, has posted exceptional returns. It gained 23.4 percent
a year, on average, for the three years through March 17, more than
double the 11.3 percent for its large-cap value category, according
to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   (The minimum investment is $1 million, but the AHA, whose
members include hospitals and other health care groups, may
introduce a share class with a lower minimum.)
</P>
<P>
   The rationale behind the approach? ``Using two value-oriented
managers with different investing styles, we hope to decrease the
volatility that naturally occurs in equity funds over time,'' said
R. John Evans, chief financial officer of the AHA The tobacco-free
portfolio is rebalanced at least once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two managers have different approaches to
stock-picking. Freeman, 44, uses a computer-based mathematical
model. Barish, 32, picks stocks using what he calls a modified
value approach.
</P>
<P>
   But Barish doesn't pile into industries with the highest
dividends or the lowest price-to-earnings or price-to-book ratios.
Instead, he said, ``we look for companies that sell at low
valuations relative to their peer group in industries that we think
have favorable prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   That means a strong tilt towards telecommunications, technology
and health care sectors, rather than the chemical, airline and
railroad stocks that many value investors own.
</P>
<P>
   Barish typically looks for stocks that trade at 20 percent to 40
percent discounts to their 52-week highs _ and for catalysts that
can push up the price.
</P>
<P>
   Six analysts work with Barish, preparing spreadsheets of 20
industries. They use a variety of multiples based on historical and
projected numbers, including price to cash flow, price to sales and
price to earnings. But they want the 30 to 35 stocks in their part
of the portfolio to trade at a minimum 30 percent discount to
industry averages.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting management is important. Barish figures that he travels
at least 10 days a month, visiting companies in his portfolio. He
unearths information about new products, capital expenditures,
marketing plans and alliances, among other things, looking for
catalysts.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Freeman never talks to management. ``We look at the
traditional variables that apply across the entire universe,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike Barish, he wants companies that sell for discounts to
their peers, based on price-to-earnings and price-to-cash-flow
ratios. In general, he wants price-to-earnings multiples to be 10
percent to 20 percent below those of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index, and historical price-to-sales and
price-to-cash-flow multiples at a 20 percent to 30 percent discount
to the index.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman and his two analysts also measures the gap between cash
flow and earnings _ the bigger it is, the better the earnings'
sustainability, or quality. ``It helps us to avoid short-term
earnings disappointments,'' he said. He also looks for analysts'
forecasts of stable or strengthening earnings.
</P>
<P>
   All that information is used to choose his 170 to 200 stocks,
matching the sector weightings of the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman likes Caterpillar, the heavy-equipment manufacturer. He
bought shares on March 2 at $31.42, based on a price-to-cash-flow
multiple of 7.5, versus an industry average of nearly 10. Another
plus was the quality of the company's earnings; he predicts a
three-year growth rate of 9.2 percent, annualized.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar shares closed on Friday at $39.50, or 13 times his
earnings forecast of $3.07 a share for the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Barish likes Watson Pharmaceuticals, a generie drug maker in
Corona, Calif. At the end of 1998, its stock traded at $60; he
bought shares last September, after prices fell to $35. ``On the
supply side, an enormous number of patent-protected drugs will lose
their protection in the next four years and become subject to
generic competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects Watson's earnings to grow 15 percent to 20 percent,
annualized, over the next three years. The stock now trades at
$38.4375, or 19 times his earnings forecast of $2 a share for this
year; his 12-month price target is in the low $50s.
</P>
</TEXT>
