</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAIR-UNION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 US AIRWAYS, FLIGHT ATTENDANTS IN 11th-HOUR TALKS TO AVERT STRIKE  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 1, 2, 24, 25 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Facing a strike deadline of 12:01 a.m. Saturday, US Airways and
its flight attendants' union reported modest progress Friday as
they negotiated late into the night in the hope of averting a
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's management repeated Friday that if no agreement
was reached by the deadline, US Airways would suspend operations
beginning Saturday to avoid being whipsawed by the attendants'
planned partial strike.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting unorthodox tactics, the union's 10,000 flight
attendants have warned of a partial strike that would disrupt 49 of
the airline's busiest routes. Company officials fear that the
partial strike, which the union calls Chaos _ Create Havoc Around
Our System _ would tie the airline in knots and strand thousands of
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday in Washington, Patricia Friend,
president of the Association of Flight Attendants, said that the
union was continuing preparations for a strike, adding, ``We've
been able to settle a large number of issues, mostly the smaller
issues, but the larger issues of pay and pension remain
unresolved.''
</P>
<P>
   The union's leaders and Rakesh Gangwal, the airline's chief
executive, were still negotiating late Friday in an undisclosed
Washington hotel with the assistance of Ernest W. DuBester,
chairman of the National Mediation Board. Officials from both sides
said that the talks were difficult because the airline is intent on
reining in its operating costs, the highest in the industry, while
the attendants want a large raise because they have not had an
across-the-board pay increase in four years.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants have been bargaining with the airline
since 1996 and they became free to strike at 12:01 a.m. Saturday
when a federally mandated cooling-off period expired. Under federal
law, President Clinton has the power to order the airline and the
attendants to continue normal operations for 60 days, but officials
for both sides said they doubted he would do that because neither
side had requested such intervention.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to step in, several labor leaders said, it would
upset the AFL-CIO, which was unhappy when he intervened in 1997 to
abort a pilots' strike at American Airlines, a move that unions
felt weakened the pilots' leverage.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a shutdown of the nation's sixth-largest airline,
whether through a strike or the company's pre-emptive action, was
sowing tension and chaos in airports around the nation Friday as
thousands of passengers rushed to change their reservations or seek
refunds on their tickets. On a typical day, US Airways operates
2,500 flights carrying a total of 150,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a considerable amount of nervousness out there,'' said
Michael Pingrey, owner of Act Travel, a Washington-based travel
agency. ``We're working hard to get people on other flights, but
it's getting tougher and tougher. Everyone has been trying to get
onto other flights, but all the other flights are booked up now.''
</P>
<P>
   A shutdown would do the greatest harm to the East Coast, where
US Airways, with 36 percent of the regional market, has the largest
market share. The cities expected to be hit hardest are Charlotte,
N.C., where the airline has 320 daily departures, accounting for 90
percent of airport traffic, and Pittsburgh, where it has 264 daily
departures, representing 86 percent of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Airlines has said that if US Air's New
York-Washington-Boston shuttle was suspended, it would add several
planes to the route, while Amtrak said it would add cars to its
trains to carry additional passengers between New York and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways has arranged for other airlines and Amtrak to honor
its tickets if its operations are shut down. The airline advises
customers holding electronic tickets to call US Airways or a travel
agent, or to go to a US Airways counter, to get their tickets
reprocessed so that those tickets can be accepted at other
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Baggaley, an airline analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said
that a shutdown would cost the airline $15 million to $20 million
in losses per day. But he said that the airline has more than $1
billion in cash on hand to help weather a shutdown, including a
$500 million credit line it recently drew down.
</P>
<P>
   To control its costs, US Airways is pressing the attendants to
accept a formula similar to one accepted by its other major unions,
a formula that would link the attendants' pay to the average of
their counterparts at the nation's four largest airlines plus 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But US Air's attendants have bridled at this, egged on by union
leaders who say that the formula put forward by management would
cut their pay and benefits. Resistance to the formula has been
fueled further by resentment toward the lofty compensation received
by US Air's top executives. Stephen M. Wolf, the chairman, received
$34.2 million last year in salary, bonus and stock option grants,
several times that of his counterparts at the top four airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that when they receive their large salaries
and bonuses and when the airline continues to prosper in a strong
economy, they expect us to take a pay cut and accept concessions,''
said Christopher Spangler, a $32,000-a-year flight attendant based
in Pittsburgh. Attendants' pay starts at $17,145 and rises to
$36,918 after 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials assert that their pay offer is generous
because it links the attendants not to their counterparts at
struggling companies, but to their counterparts at the industry
leaders: United, American, Delta and Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   US Air officials added that if the union accepted the parity
formula it would go far to restrain the airline's costs. These
officials added that if the attendants were to receive a higher
formula, then the airline's other major unions _ the pilots,
mechanics and passenger-service workers _ might demand to have
their contracts reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about who is right or wrong or who wins or
loses,'' said Lawrence Nagin, executive vice president and general
counsel at US Airways. ``It's about this company being competitive
and doing what's right for our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   One sticking point has been the attendants' assertion that
management was pressuring them to accept the same version of the
parity formula as the pilots, and not a formula tailored
specifically to the attendants. But late Thursday the airline
announced that it was presenting different versions of the formula
to address the union's concerns while still enabling the airline to
restrain its costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
