<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-NASA-OBSERVATORY-     03-24 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NASA-OBSERVATORY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA WILL RETURN CRIPPLED OBSERVATORY TO EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a three-month review of the risks of doing nothing, NASA
engineers and scientists decided Friday that the safest course
would be to direct the crippled 17-ton Compton Gamma Ray
Observatory to make a suicidal plunge out of orbit and back toward
Earth while they can still control its destructive fall so that it
comes down far from inhabited land.
</P>
<P>
   The decision disappointed astronomers, who had hoped for a few
more years of observations of the enigmatic flashes of gamma rays
that attest to some of the most bizarre and powerful phenomena in
the universe.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration feared that one more failure by navigation
instruments would leave the huge $670 million spacecraft
uncontrollable, and that on its re-entry into the atmosphere it
might scatter debris over populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington, Dr. Edward J. Weiler, NASA's
associate administrator for science, announced that the Compton
observatory's last day in orbit would be June 3, over nine years
after it was deployed by a space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safest option is clearly to bring it down in June,''
Weiler said. ``We will lose valuable science. But the bottom line
is: There can be no trade-off between science and the least chance
of loss of life.''
</P>
<P>
   If the spacecraft wound up making an unguided return, he
estimated, there would be a 1-in-1,000 chance of a human fatality.
</P>
<P>
   Flight controllers at the Goddard Space Flight Center in
Greenbelt, Md., said the spacecraft's re-entry into the atmosphere
would be aimed for the sky over a remote 900-mile-long stretch of
the Pacific Ocean. The center of the re-entry area is on the
equator about 2,500 miles southeast of Hawaii, about 120 degrees
longitude.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the craft should burn up in the atmosphere, 30 to
40 pieces of the titanium structure, each weighing as much as 40
pounds, could survive as potentially lethal shrapnel, NASA said.
</P>
<P>
   The Compton observatory's trouble began in December, when one of
the three gyroscopes used for guidance and navigation failed. If a
second gyroscope were to fail, the flight controllers would be
unable to control the spacecraft reliably. And the Goddard
engineers figured there was a 10 percent chance of losing another
gyroscope within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, NASA officials said, they had little
choice but to bring the mission to a safe ending as soon as
possible. In the late 1970s, when the Skylab space station, an even
larger vehicle, came down out of control, debris fell over the
Indian Ocean and parts of western Australia, although with no
injuries and very little damage.
</P>
<P>
   Martin E. Frederick, associate chief of the Goddard guidance and
control center, said that nearly all systems on the Compton
spacecraft would be shut down on May 26, in preparation for the
four-stage re-entry maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   For the first step, braking thrusters will be fired to lower
Compton's orbital altitude to 220 miles from 316. The next two
firings, several days apart, will reduce the altitude to 90 miles.
On the fourth firing, the spacecraft will begin its fiery plunge
through the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neil Gehrels, the Compton mission's chief scientist, said
astronomers ``will be quite disappointed with this decision,'' but
he added: ``We're not done. We have 62 days left, and we're going
to make the best use of every one of those minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
