A7271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-KLAN-GRAVE-HNS     03-24 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KLAN-GRAVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF JASPER VICTIM UPSET OVER KKK STICKER ON GRAVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ohio) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ The family of Jasper dragging death victim
James Byrd Jr. said Friday that they are upset by a glossy
magazine's photo of a Ku Klux Klan imperial wizard who placed a KKK
sticker on Byrd's grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely needs to stay away from that gravesite,'' said
Byrd's sister, Clara Taylor, of Houston. ``That won't be
tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 49-year-old black man, was killed June 7, 1998, when he
was chained by the ankles to a pickup and dragged for three miles.
His dismembered body was found on a road in front of a black
cemetery east of Jasper. Three white men were convicted of capital
murder and two were sentenced to die for the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The April edition of Details magazine shows a photograph of
19-year-old James Roesch, imperial wizard of the Knights of the
White Kamellia, and his wife, April, standing beside Byrd's grave
in Jasper City Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said Roesch, who moved to Jasper after Byrd's
death, left a small sticker on the headstone that said, ``A Ku Klux
Klansman Was Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Boatner, another of Byrd's sisters, said she saw the
sticker on the grave but refused to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost sacrilegious,'' Taylor said. ``The nerve of him
to do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Roesch, who works as a logger, could not be reached for comment,
and a phone message left with a Details magazine spokeswoman was
not returned.
</P>
<P>
   The Conde Nast publication, promoted as a lifestyles magazine
for Generation X readers, recently announced it was closing. Plans
are to relaunch it as a monthly men's fashion magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's grave has been vandalized before. Last year someone pried
loose a stainless steel name plate that had been attached to the
concrete vault that covers the grave. After that, Byrd's name was
engraved in a stainless steel slab that covers the vault and a
black granite headstone was erected at the head of the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said she and other family members are considering what
actions to take. ``A restraining order is a possibility,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she wants to find out more about the circumstances of
the article and added that she believed Roesch was ``just doing it
to get publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles said authorities are looking
into the matter, but the KKK sticker was gone by the time officers
got there. Rowles said officers will file charges of desecrating a
grave against anyone found defacing Byrd's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper has been the scene of several small Klan rallies as well
as rallies by black power groups since Byrd's death. The rallies
were mainly put on by members from other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said they knew of no organized Klan activities
before Roesch moved to town from Kettering, Ohio, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
