<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-WOMEN-COACHES0325     03-24 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOMEN-COACHES0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gender gap: Legion of male coaches dwindling
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The idea of returning to his native state was so
tempting for Bill Fennelly five years ago that he paid little
attention to the fact that Iowa State was regarded as one of the
worst coaching jobs in women's college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he turned the Cyclones' program into one of the
nation's best, Fennelly, who had modest success at the University
of Toledo for more than a decade, felt he was fortunate to have the
opportunity to move up. As it turns out, he is, and for quite a few
other reasons than what he originally had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he will be one of four men coaching teams in the women's
Sweet 16. Louisiana Tech coach Leon Barmore, who announced his
retirement effective at the end of the season, could meet Fennelly
and Iowa State in the final of the Midwest Regional if both win
today.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's conceivable that three male-coached teams could
reach the Final Four for the first time, Barmore's impending
departure comes at a time when male coaches in the sport are seeing
their numbers decline in the upper echelons.
</P>
<P>
   Because parity has not risen to the top in women's basketball,
it helps to be at one of the big schools if you want to win a
national championship. Only two men can make that claim: Barmore in
1988, and Connecticut's Geno Auriemma in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Of 69 positions in the six major conferences, only 13 are held
by men. Two of those leagues _ the Pac-10 and the Big Ten _ don't
have any. The ACC has one.
</P>
<P>
   While a number of other women's collegiate sports are dominated
by male coaches _ particularly volleyball, soccer, swimming and
diving, and track and field _ basketball long has been a
battleground over gender-based hiring issues.
</P>
<P>
   The four men whose teams are still alive _ Fennelly, Barmore,
Auriemma and Georgia's Andy Landers _ all of have coached women's
basketball for 20 years or longer. But because of political
pressures placed on major schools to hire women, and because of the
development of the sport in producing former players who have
gotten into coaching, younger men appear less likely to follow in
their footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something a young man can go into thinking, `if I
work hard, in about 10 years I can get a big job,' `` Fennelly
said. ``It's going to be harder for a lot of guys. There are a lot
of (women) players who want to get those jobs. I just think it's an
evolution in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly one third of Division I women's coaches are women, but
the percentages of men go up as the level of competition goes down.
Men are still the vast majority of girls' coaches at the high
school, youth and AAU levels, where the pay and the prestige are
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years after the establishment of the women's college
game, females who benefitted from Title IX playing opportunities
are becoming the candidates of choice. Many earned their coaching
stripes as assistants for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural progression of our mission to encourage girls
to play,'' said Beth Bass, executive director of the Lilburn-based
Women's Basketball Coaches Association. ``It's natural for them to
be introduced into coaching that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Tech assistant coach Lisa Stockton, a standout
player at Wake Forest in the mid-1980s, has taken Tulane to six
straight NCAA appearances, and her name is frequently mentioned
when openings at major schools occur.
</P>
<P>
   Among those reportedly being wooed by Michigan State is Xavier
coach Melanie Balcomb, whose father was an assistant to the
legendary Pete Carril at Princeton. Another leading prospect for
moving up in the ranks is Evansville coach Kathi Bennett, the
daughter of Wisconsin men's coach Dick Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the subject is a touchy one on the other side of the
spectrum. The appointment of Fennelly's Big 12 rival, Paul
Sanderford of Nebraska, was held up for several weeks in 1997
because of pressure from state legislators to consider women
candidates. Even Fennelly wasn't originally considered by Iowa
State, which eventually extended its search to include men.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been very many (men) in very visible Division I
jobs in recent years,'' Landers said. ``If that's the trend, then
that's the trend. If it's not, then I've misread the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the SEC, considered the top conference in women's basketball,
gender hasn't been much of a concern. Five of its 12 coaches are
men, although four of them have been at their schools from between
eight to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia assistant coach Michael Shafer has been on Landers'
staff the last five years, and has been involved with the Lady
Bulldogs' program since attending first Landers' camps at the age
of 14. The son of former Georgia associate athletics director and
current Mississippi AD John Shafer, the younger Shafer, now 28, has
moved up from a graduate assistant to a full-time aide with
substantial recruiting responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   His prospects, should he want to take the next step, are
uncertain, to say the least. Shafer was reluctant to be
interviewed, and according a team spokesman, he hasn't thought much
about becoming a women's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of them who like what they do but they'll
always be a well-paid assistant coach or they'll have to take a
step down,'' Fennelly said. ``I get a letter a day from players who
want to get into coaching. I think it's good; this is the women's
game after all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why it's still an issue and a concern for (male
coaches),'' said Bass of the WBCA, which has set up an advisory
board for male coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like what women have had to go through for many years.
They're going to have to be better than the average candidate. And
they've got to be twice as good as a female candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
