<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 227.
WASHINGTON, March 24 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Security
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 100 to 0, a bill that would
allow senior citizens, ages 65 through 69, to receive full Social
Security benefits if they decide to continue working after reaching
retirement age. Supporters, including President Clinton, said the
bill would help seniors struggling to make ends meet. There were no
opponents to the measure. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Insurance
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 95 to 5, a $6 billion spending
measure to overhaul the nation's crop insurance system. The plan
puts $5 billion toward revising the current risk management program
and $1 billion toward researching new programs. Supporters said the
insurance plan reduces dependence on government disaster relief
programs. Opponents said the bill contained too much spending. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Waste
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 253 to 167, a bill to create a
permanent nuclear waste storage site at Yucca Mountain, Nevada. The
measure would allow 40,000 tons of radioactive waste around the
country to be transported to the site 90 miles north of Las Vegas.
Supporters said removing waste from temporary storage sites was
long overdue. Opponents, including President Clinton -- who intends
to veto the measure, say the plan is not environmentally sound. A
``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Oil
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 382 to 38, a bill that makes it
U.S. policy to work with other oil importing nations to stop price
fixing by some oil exporting nations. Supporters said the bill
forces the president to take a tough stance on oil producers.
Opponents said the scaled-back version was weak and should contain
language instructing Clinton to cut military and economic aid to
countries that fix oil prices. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Budget
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 184 to 233, a five-year budget
plan that contained fewer tax cuts and more debt reduction monies
than a similar plan that later passed. The measure would have
provided prescription drug benefits for Medicare recipients.
Supporters said the bill would offer adequate tax relief while
reducing the nation's debt. Opponents said the tax cuts were not
large enough. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: Budget2
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 211 to 207, a five-year, $1.8
trillion budget plan. The measure, which would cut taxes $240
billion over five years, increases spending for defense, education,
and prescription drug benefits for Medicare recipients. Supporters
said the bill ensures fiscal discipline while freeing up money for
tax relief. Opponents said the tax cut was too large. A ``yes''
vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
