<HEADER>
A7287 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV26-N     03-24 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST WITH MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For AOL-Time Warner, Triumph of the Hard Sell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America Online, of course, is a master of the hard sell, from
stuffing mailboxes with free trial offers to forcing subscribers to
click through ads before they can get their e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Those skills apparently served the company well this year, after
investors fled in the wake of its proposed merger with Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks after the huge deal was announced on Jan. 10,
America Online shares fell steadily. By Feb. 22, they stood at
$49.625, compared with $73.75 before the merger announcement,
wiping out more than $100 billion of the combined market value of
the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   The drop, which was attributed to America Online investors'
disdain for Time Warner's slow growth rate, led some people to
speculate that AOL might have to increase the price it had agreed
to pay for Time Warner _ or that even the merger itself might be at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   But through that rough stretch, America Online and Time Warner
executives said that they remained committed to each other and that
the terms of agreement were set. The selling of the deal went on,
publicly and privately. Reporters who called to ask about the deal
were apt to find themselves on conference calls with senior
executives from both companies. At the same time, America Online
and Time Warner officials fanned out to meet face to face with
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The companies turned on ``a full court press,'' said John
Schreiber, an assistant portfolio manager at Janus Capital, which
will be among the largest holders of the combined company. ``They
made lots of joint appearances and tried to get everybody
introduced to both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of delay, top Wall Street analysts began to crank
out positive reports on the proposed deal, complete with the
requisite punditry. ``America Online/Time Warner: Perfect
Time-ing,'' Goldman Sachs chirped in one cheery report.
</P>
<P>
   Lo and behold, the stocks of America Online and Time Warner
began to rally. By the close of trading on Friday, AOL shares stood
at $71, just below their level before the deal was announced. At
that price, the combined company has a market value of more than
$350 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And talk that the merger might not happen has faded.
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber, who sees the stock as still undervalued even after
its recent run-up, said, ``It just takes these things a while to
get understood and communicated.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL shareholders are fortunate that their company is a smooth
communicator.
</P>
<P>
   _Alex Berenson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patent No. 6,003,018, For Asset Allocation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people have devised winning investment strategies _
although it helps to have a bull-market wind at your back. But
Richard Michaud and his son, Robert, have gone a step further. They
have received a United States patent for theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The government awarded patent No. 6,003,018 to the pair for what
they call ``the first serious improvement in portfolio construction
and asset allocation technology in almost 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Building on the pioneering efforts of Harry Markowitz, the Nobel
laureate from the University of Chicago, the Michauds say numerous
portfolios provide optimal combinations of return and risk _ not
just one, as many academics and investors had long supposed. That
means that a portfolio might not need as much adjustment as it
traditionally has in order to achieve an optimal mix of assets.
That, in turn, could cut trading costs by as much as 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Herculean leap in the state of the art,'' contended C.
Michael Carty, a managing director in New York of New Frontier
Advisors, a Boston-based company founded last year to exploit the
patented technique.
</P>
<P>
   But while the patent appears to be the first in its niche _
identifying optimal portfolio allocation strategy _ the Patent and
Trademark Office issued nearly 600 patents last year alone for
computer-related business methods, some of them involving
investments.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Michauds' method, the ROM Optimizer, met the four
official tests of patentability _ that it be new, useful,
nonobvious (that is, not just slightly incremental) and fully
disclosed _ the government does not insist on take-it-to-the-bank
proof that an investment strategy makes or saves money. It's a
matter of persuading patent examiners of, in effect, plausible
practicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our examiners determine that it would do what it says it
does,'' said Brigid Quinn, an agency spokeswoman, ``based on a
written description.''
</P>
<P>
   _Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
