<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7289 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV2     03-24 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUBBLE CAN'T BE PIERCED IN STAGES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all those who doubt that a speculative bubble hangs
dangerously over the economy _ and the doubters number in the tens
of millions _ Robert J. Shiller's new book is sobering. He
describes a market so out of control that the run-up in the Roaring
'20s looks like a molehill, compared with the Mount Everest of the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Shiller, a Yale University economist, called his book
``Irrational Exuberance,'' borrowing the phrase coined by Alan
Greenspan in December 1996. The Federal Reserve chairman has tried
ever since to soften stock prices, but investors _ that is, nearly
half the population _ have laughed in his face. The Fed notches up
interest rates and stocks rise anyway, as if they were an addiction
like cigarettes or liquor, just as much in need of a warning label.
</P>
<P>
   Posting such a label _ in this case, coming right out and saying
that we are in a stock market bubble _ would be the sort of
government intervention that Greenspan resists. But stocks today
are greatly overvalued _ perhaps by more than $7 trillion, Shiller
says _ and even free-market economists wonder about the efficacy of
the Fed's interest rate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us believe that the speculation has gone so far that
there is no easy or painless way out,'' said one such economist on
Wall Street, Albert Wojnilower. ``The question is whether to
acknowledge this and open the floor to other solutions. That is
what Greenspan would be doing if he declared that speculation is
driving up stock prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said in 1996 _ and he continues to say today _ that
irrational exuberance (italics)might(end italics) be driving up
stock prices. But he has never stepped over the line and bluntly
stated that it is. Instead, he has kept one foot firmly planted in
the camp of those who regard the market's performance as rational.
</P>
<P>
   Rising productivity and the prospect of rising corporate
profits, he says, bring investors tumbling sensibly into stocks in
anticipation of future gains.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has acquired enormous prestige for his astute
nurturing of the economy in recent years. But he is in danger of
dissipating that prestige by insisting on rational monetary policy
_ the notching up of interest rates _ to discipline an irrational
situation. Why should investors be deterred from borrowing money at
6 percent or even 10 percent, Wojnilower asks, when they believe
that stocks bought with the borrowed money will go up 20 percent by
year-end? Getting interest rates high enough to stop that fervor
would bust the economy.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen if Greenspan declared bluntly that irrational
exuberance controls the market and is running roughshod over all
the sensible reasons for owning stocks? For one thing, such
frankness would encounter resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, in an election year, prefers to view
the market as reflecting corporate America's strength and
profitability. And most Wall Street traders like Greenspan's
current ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   But public recognition of the bubble might finally propel
America into vigorous debate about ways to control the market
fever.
</P>
<P>
   There are a half-dozen remedies besides higher rates. On
everyone's list is tightening margin requirements. Investors could
be required to put up 60 percent or 70 percent of the purchase
price of a stock, instead of the present 50 percent. Greenspan
objects that small investors, the biggest users of margin debt,
would be forced more than big investors to pull back. But they
would also be saved from painful losses in a market sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   Bank regulators could put up another obstacle to the purchase of
securities on credit. They could require banks to increase the
capital that backs such loans, which by one measure rose to $23.4
billion in February from $18.1 billion just last November. The
government, in effect, would be allocating credit, a role shunned
in Washington today.
</P>
<P>
   A transaction tax on all stock trades, of the sort once proposed
by James Tobin, the Nobel laureate in economics, would slow
trading. So would an old Warren Buffett idea: a 100 percent capital
gains tax on stocks held for too short a term, say less than a
year. That would encourage people to invest for the long term, more
cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called suitability rules could also be extended. These
require brokers to check that a customer's investment goals are in
line with his income, net worth and the like. A broker is bound by
the rules to discourage a grandmother from sinking all her savings
into a profitless Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Suitability rules do not now cover day traders and online
investors, though formal proposals already exist to extend them.
</P>
<P>
   Remedies like these might sap the speculation without bringing
down the economy. But even proponents worry that it is already too
late to prevent a damaging market crash or a painful sell-off _ the
denouement in the past of speculative bubbles that have gone
unrecognized for so long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
