<HEADER>
A7291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-POLITICS-ART-(TR     03-24 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AREQUIPA JOURNAL: PRESIDENT'S FORMER WIFE IS RUNNING HER OWN
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AREQUIPA, Peru _ When Peru's Congress got in President Alberto
Fujimori's way, he abolished it. When three judges wanted to uphold
a constitutional ban on his running for a third term, Fujimori
simply had them fired. Not even the most vicious terrorist group in
Latin America could resist him.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to toughness, Fujimori appears to be no match
for his former wife. Susana Higuchi, who as first lady became the
object of international attention six years ago when she said she
was being held prisoner and screamed out state secrets from a
fourth-story window of the presidential palace, has now taken their
domestic spat on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi, divorced from Fujimori four years ago, is running a
strong campaign for Congress, and many pollsters predict she will
win even though she is attached to a minor left-leaning political
party. She carries a symbolic broom on the stump and calls for
social justice and an end to what she calls ``the dictatorship''
led by her former husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to say enough is enough with this immoral, corrupt
system,'' Higuchi recently told an auditorium full of women who
were attending a seminar here about women's issues. ``There are
journalists _ obviously bought off _ who ask if I am still angry at
President Fujimori. And I say yes! What kind of political bossism
is this?''
</P>
<P>
   As the 250 women gasped in horror, she said that Fujimori had
treated Abimael Guzman, the imprisoned leader of the
Maoist-inspired Shining Path terrorist group, better than he had
treated her. ``He sent him a cake for his birthday!'' she said. (In
an interview later, she said that Fujimori never did the same for
her during their 22-year marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi, a 49-year-old civil engineer and businesswoman, still
has the political stature of a first lady. She is the object of
long profiles in the political magazines, and her news conferences
are often better attended than those of presidential candidates.
She says little to muffle the widely held speculation that her
ambition is to get the ultimate revenge on Fujimori by becoming the
first woman to serve as Peru's president.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As her campaign caravan moved through the streets and markets of
this enchanting Andean mountain city of pearl-white colonial
churches, people shrieked and applauded as if she were a movie
star. Some threw flower petals over her and handed her bouquets of
white carnations, while others exploded firecrackers in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Alberto a spanking,'' cried out one middle-aged man as
her campaign van passed. Later, a woman pressed against her van
window as the vehicle became snarled in traffic to plead with her
to get back together with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori refuses to criticize her candidacy, and his
intelligence service _ which has helped upend other politicians _
has so far laid off Higuchi's campaign. Fujimori appeared at the
recent funeral of Higuchi's father and walked beside his former
wife and their eldest daughter, Keiko Sofia, during the funeral
procession.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, even while Higuchi sharply criticizes her former
husband's governing style, she has helped him a bit lately by
publicly denying recurring rumors that he has cancer and that he is
not a native Peruvian but was born in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   She has also dropped her old habits of complaining about
Fujimori's bedside comportment and questioning his commitment to
Roman Catholicism. Nevertheless, Higuchi said in an interview that
there is ``zero'' chance for a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters here asked her to comment on press reports about
irregularities in Fujimori's campaign, including an accusation that
his backers forged 1 million signatures to get him on the ballot,
she simply said, ``He never keeps his word.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if her criticism of the president is somewhat more
muted these days, opposition leaders say her campaign for Congress
is putting a spotlight on the dark side of Fujimori's personality
and hurting his chances for re-election on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvian press has taken to calling the saga of the couple's
relationship ``La Show Susana'' and ``Fujidrama.''
</P>
<P>
   The marriage between the former first couple showed its first
public signs of deterioration in 1992, when Higuchi said that some
of Fujimori's relatives were skimming off aid given by Japan. By
1994, the relationship had soured so much and Higuchi's criticisms
had become so strident that she said Fujimori's bodyguards had
locked her in a room in the presidential palace. Higuchi called
reporters in the middle of the night to complain, and later went on
a hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi announced her intention to run for president against her
husband in 1995, but the electoral tribunal disqualified her.
Congress enacted a bill prohibiting presidential relatives from
running for president in what became known as the ``Susana Law.''
</P>
<P>
   That is all history now, but Higuchi's campaign has revitalized
speculation about the former first couple's love lives.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Fujimori told his favorite television talk
show host, Laura Bozzo, that he did not have a girlfriend but that
he was looking for one. He said he needed at least 10 dates to fall
in love.
</P>
<P>
   As for Higuchi, she said in an interview that she has no
interest in meeting other men and that she has dedicated her life
to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am too busy with my work,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2019EST &QL; 
