<HEADLINE>
POPE TELLS YOUTHS TO KEEP THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORAZIN, Israel _ Overlooking the Mount of Beatitudes where
Jesus once gathered his disciples, Pope John Paul II presided
Friday over a Mass devoted to youths that brought together an
estimated 75,000 worshipers from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice unusually strong and clear, the ailing, 79-year-old
pope called for faith in Jesus in an age in which young people are
tempted by violence, greed, and ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``His call has always demanded a choice between the two voices
competing for your hearts, even now on this hill, the choice
between good and evil, between life and death,'' he said. ``Which
voice will the young people of the 21st century choose to follow?''
</P>
<P>
   The pageantry of the event, beginning with the Pope's grand
entrance through a crowd waving national flags and welcoming
banners into a natural amphitheater overlooking the Sea of Galilee,
seemed lifted from another century.
</P>
<P>
   Among the tens of thousands of worshipers were students from
Germany and Poland, immigrant workers from the Philippines and
Nigeria, parishioners from Mexico and Costa Rica, and pilgrims who
had flown in from Detroit and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half were from an international movement known as the
Neo-Catechumenal Way that grew out of the slums of Madrid a quarter
century ago and has flourished especially in Europe and Latin
America. The movement, a politically conservative evangelical wing
of the Catholic Church, advocates adult catechism and baptism and
helping the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Waymel, 22, an adherent of the Way from St. Louis Parish
in Denver, said, ``The words of the pope are very encouraging for
youth today, and a very important alternative to the messages they
hear every day in movies, the Internet, the streets, shallow
messages that in the end shatter their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrims also included Palestinian Christians, a dwindling
minority in the Holy Land, sprinkled among the Europeans and
Americans. Many were seeing the Galilee for the first time in their
lives, because Israeli checkpoints usually block their access from
traveling from Palestinian-controlled areas to most places in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live two hours from here, and I have never been allowed to
come here,'' said Wafa Arga, 19, of Bethlehem. ``We hope that the
Pope's presence here will help show the world what we live with
here as Palestinians and as Christians. We hope his visit will push
forward the peace process in a way that we can someday get on with
our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the pageantry were some very obvious security measures, as
Israeli police and army deployed in an operation of unprecedented
scale.
</P>
<P>
   The pope delivered his sermon from behind a bulletproof glass
shield. Israeli bomb squad units fanned out around the site. And
Israeli police carrying machine guns ringed the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Some Vatican officials have privately criticized the security
measures, saying they appreciated the Israelis' concern but found
the show of force excessive. When the pope travels Sunday to
Nazareth and Monday to Jerusalem's Old City, both flashpoints of
conflict, security is expected to grow even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   The Korazin gathering took place on a rocky hillside, its
terraced slopes blanketed in green grass and wild flowers. This
countryside, with red anemones and blue iris sprouting among the
gray, craggy rocks, was the setting for many of Jesus's parables.
</P>
<P>
   The pope recalled that it was on the same site that Jesus
gathered his 12 disciples for the Sermon on the Mount. One of them,
Peter, a fisherman believed to be from the village of Capernaum at
the foot of the mount, would be handed the responsibility of
building the church.
</P>
<P>
   The aging pontiff, who Catholics believe is the spiritual
successor to Peter, seemed particularly animated and forceful in
delivering his sermon on this site.
</P>
<P>
   He told the gathering that the Sermon on the Mount, which
begins, ``Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom
of heaven,'' represents for Christians a new understanding of the
Hebrew Bible's Ten Commandments, a message that the fufillment of
God's Law comes ``through love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
