<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S EDUCATION IDEAS CONTESTED AT ARKANSAS HIGH SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-EXCERPTS) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Visiting a high school here that was a
historic battleground in the fight to integrate public schools in
the South, Gov. George W. Bush faced open skepticism Friday from
several educators and a student leader who questioned his proposals
to improve education for minority and disadvantaged children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush traveled to Central High School, where federal troops were
deployed in September 1957 to escort nine black students past
rioters, to say that while minority children were no longer denied
access to institutions of learning, they were too often denied the
same quality of education that more privileged peers received. The
Texas governor said that he wanted to change that.
</P>
<P>
   But a few of the 10 participants in a panel discussion that he
staged in the school's library wondered aloud about the efficacy of
his prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The school's principal, Rudolph Howard, said that Bush's
advocacy of greater local flexibility in the use of federal
education funds would not necessarily do enough to help financially
strapped public schools meet the demands of paying teachers higher
salaries and repairing crumbling buildings. Vice President Al Gore
has proposed additional federal money for both of those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Howard began to make that case to Bush in the panel discussion,
then toughened and expanded his criticism in a conversation with
reporters afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want something very tangible in place that would be
encouraging for those of us who have to carry the ball,'' Howard
said, adding that Bush's push for more local control and his plea
for high standards were ``pie-in-the-sky, hopeful kinds of things
that we have existed on for years and years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to hear him say he's going to commit to something,''
the principal added. ``All these catch phrases are horses that are
not going to trot anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Williams, the student council president, said that
Bush's support of programs to allow students to use public money
for private education would divert resources and energy from public
schools and make it harder to provide the children who remained
there with an adequate education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really agree with the concept of it,'' Williams, who
is 18, told the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges illustrated the difficulty that Bush, the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee, may encounter in
convincing some Americans that his vision for public schools is the
right one and that it is tailored with the neediest students in
mind. Those claims are cornerstones of Bush's presentation of
himself as a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, polls have shown that on the issue of education
Americans trust Democrats more than Republicans. But Bush is trying
to turn that around, and some polls released over the last two
weeks suggest that he and Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee,
are on relatively equal footing on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance at Central High School, where 57 percent of
the roughly 2,000 students are black, demonstrated his confidence
in his ability to sell his ideas and his willingness to hash them
around even with likely critics.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was clearly after powerful political theater, not
polite public dissent, in staging the event at a place that he
called ``a symbol that prejudice may run deep, but goodness runs
deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   His scripted remarks at the start of the panel discussion took
in the sweep of the civil rights movement and included the comment
that the continuing gap in the achievement of white children and
black children perpetuated a divided society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the cause,'' Bush said, ``the effect is
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our common ground,'' he added, ``is found in our common
schools. And we must make those schools worthy of all our children.
This, I believe, is the next advance in the cause of equality, the
next frontier of civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's education proposals call for some enhanced
federal financing, they turn more strongly on giving states and
local school districts additional discretion and authority in how
they use existing federal money. Bush also envisions financial
incentives and punishments to motivate schools whose students test
poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Sustained failure would mean forfeiting some federal assistance,
which would be rechanneled so that parents could use that money to
help pay for private educational options or so that more charter
schools could be established.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists at Central High School largely concurred with
Bush's call for higher educational standards, his vision of an
accountability system and his advocacy of local control.
</P>
<P>
   But several seemed to want a much greater financial commitment
from the federal government, which Bush seemed wary of making.
</P>
<P>
   He told a middle school principal who had raised the issue of
teachers' salaries: ``I just caution you not to expect the federal
government to be paying teachers more money.'' Bush said that was a
local prerogative, which he strongly recommended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
