<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS TAKE DIM VIEW OF DAYLIGHT SAVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Ruben Escandon will wake up Sunday at the same
time he does every day _ 6:45 a.m. _ but he's not happy about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be dark, and I'm going to have to eat my
breakfast with the lights on,'' said Escandon, 52, a parking lot
attendant. ``I'll probably get to work before the sun comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clocks and watches all across Mexico will move ahead one hour at
midnight Saturday, the country's version of daylight saving time,
better known here as summer hours. But a growing number of Mexicans
would prefer to keep their timepieces set just the way they are.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from 75 countries, including the United States,
where daylight saving is observed on the first Sunday in April,
Mexico adopted the spring-forward/fall-back schedule in 1996 as a
way to conserve energy and to keep their work schedules
synchronized with key foreign markets and time zones.
</P>
<P>
   But the time change has created a surge of complaints, from
worried parents to proud citizens, who argue that summer hours
endanger children and hurt national pride.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Mexican states have formed a mini-revolt over
summer hours, threatening to pass laws that would supersede the
federal government's program and keep them fixed on standard time.
This year, the states of Morelos and Aguascalientes have joined the
list of provinces opposed to summer hours.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the time change has also trickled into this
year's heated mayoral campaign in Mexico City, where council
members have vowed to keep the capital on standard time. Santiago
Creel, a mayoral candidate from the center-right National Action
Party, has called for a citywide referendum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest beef over summer hours has come from parents who say
their children will be forced to walk or ride from crime-ridden
neighborhoods to school before sunrise for three months of the
school year. On Monday, the sun will be up just before 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some children carry flashlights to school,'' said
Olga Camares, 29, a mother of three daughters. ``At least they
should wait for summer hours until the school year is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics of the change offer a conspiracy theory: Summer
hours is yet another sign of US habits infiltrating Mexican
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials contend the plan is a more rational use of
sunlight, and they credit the summer program for reducing the
country's electricity demand, especially during peak evening hours,
because the sun sets later.
</P>
<P>
   Government figures show that electricity demand has declined by
1,500 megawatts from 7 p.m. to 10 p.m. Although the change has
increased demand in the pre-dawn by roughly 10 million lightbulbs,
it has cut evening demand by three times that amount, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, supporters of the shift argue, less demand on the
country's power plants means less fuel to keep them running, and
less pollution. Mexico's Energy Secretariat estimates the summer
hours initiative saves 2 million barrels of petroleum a year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexico's summertime clock is only five years old, the
country has flirted on and off with the idea for decades. The
northern state of Baja California first adopted the schedule in
1942.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government took up the idea in the mid-1990s.
Officials surveyed business leaders and citizens and studied the
possible consequences of the 60-minute change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea was considered very carefully,'' one energy official
said Friday with a sigh of exasperation. ``We even looked at
whether it would affect people's health to wake up earlier or stay
up later.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some Mexicans welcome the change, especially the
prospect of a longer and brighter evening, which will last until
the final Sunday in October, when clocks are set back to standard
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel better to have the extra daylight,'' said
Yudi Corvera, a 34-year-old Mexico City writer. ``It's the sign
that spring and summer are finally here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
