<HEADLINE>
CROWD ON MOUNT OF BEATITUDES: `JOHN PAUL II, WE LOVE YOU!' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORAZIM, Israel _ They came from as far away as Venezuela,
Uganda and the Philippines on Friday with water bottles, rain coats
and high spirits to listen to Pope John Paul II celebrate Mass on
the mount where they believe Jesus gave his famous sermon nearly
2000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., tens of thousands of young Roman Catholics from all
over the world covered a muddy hillside the size of two football
stadiums overlooking the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   They stood in groups or sat together on plastic tarps covering
the wet ground. They sang hymns, played guitars and waved flags,
transforming the hill into a cacophony of sound and hodgepodge of
color and as they waited for the pontiff to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so marvelous to be here,'' said Crispin Chanda Witika of
Zambia, ``To see such an event, it's the work of God for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old pope may have waded into the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict during the first few days of his weeklong visit to the
Holy Land. But to the 100,000 people gathered to receive John
Paul's blessings on the Mount of Beatitudes, his presence was
purely spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two thousand years ago, Christ died, and today we're
celebrating Mass here. It's a gift from God,'' said Carmen Sanchez,
24, one of 200 pilgrims from Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:15 a.m., the papal party's first helicopters roared
overhead, and the bustling crowd fell silent. Fifteen minutes
later, the assembly burst into cheers and applause when John Paul
appeared in his Popemobile. Slowly, the vehicle made its way down a
narrow path that ran through the center of the crowd. The pope
passed Lebanese, French, Venezuelan, Japanese and U.S. flags as he
rode toward the altar.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Paul II, we love you!'' the crowd chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Mass, clouds cast shadows on the green hills
around the Sea of Galilee, and once or twice light rain fell on the
crowd. But few of the pilgrims seemed to notice. It was here,
according to the Bible, that St. Peter lived and Jesus performed
the miracle of the loaves and fishes.
</P>
<P>
   And it was here, Christians believe, on a stunning cliff
overlooking the Sea of Galilee that Jesus gave his famous Sermon on
the Mount, telling the poor in spirit that theirs is the kingdom of
heaven, the meek that they shall inherit the earth and the
peacemakers that they shall be called children of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something very beautiful about this place,'' said
Rachel Sim, a 21-year-old from England. ``It's a natural
amphitheater. You're brought up with stories. They are almost like
fairy tales. They're almost not real.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you see this place, you feel that it's true. You feel
uplifted.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephan Galleitner of Frankfurt, Germany, agreed. ``It's very
important to me to walk on the same ground as Jesus did, to breathe
the same air,'' Galleitner said. ``He gets even more real. He's
already present, but now it's more concrete than before.''
</P>
<P>
   A chaperon who led a group of young people from Ireland was
impressed with the historical significance of Friday's Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the kids, I don't think they realize how important it
is,'' said Mary Power. ``It's a spiritual trip, but it's history as
well. He's only the second pope to come here.'' The only other pope
to visit Israel was Paul VI in 1964. His stopover lasted 11 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's three-hour Mass began with hymns sung in Arabic. John
Paul delivered his sermon in English. The Gospel was chanted in
Greek. And just before Communion, the pontiff uttered, ``asalam
aleikum,'' Arabic for ``peace be upon you,'' and 100,000 people
turned to each other in unison and repeated his words in dozens of
languages.
</P>
<P>
   During his sermon, John Paul exhorted the multitudes of young
people gathered before him to live by the Ten Commandments and by
the words of Jesus. He told them not to be afraid to be Christian
and to spread the news of the Gospels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, at the dawn of the third millennium, it is your turn to
go out into the world to preach the message,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people hunched over short wave radios or plugged ear pieces
into small transistors to hear the sermon in their language.
</P>
<P>
   ``His message was for us to bring the message of God to the
world,'' said Cornelia Bier a resident of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   After the sermon ended, dozens of priests filed down the
Popemobile's path and dispersed through the crowd to minister
Communion to the faithful. An Israeli-Arab choir sang, and the
throng of people fell into silent reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the Mass ended, and the people moved in a wave
toward the street, where many boarded buses bound for Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a simple man of peace,'' said Lena Alam, a Maronite
Christian and an Israeli Arab, as she left the celebration. ``He
brings us closer to God.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
