<HEADLINE>
STABILITY IN CENTRAL AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 26, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By H.D.S. GREENWAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ What a difference a decade makes. In the
1980s, when I last visited Central America, it was a caldron of
discontent and armed rebellion. The Sandinistas, who had taken over
from the Somoza dictatorship of the right, were hard at work
imposing their own dictatorship of the left while battling the
``Contras'' whom the CIA of the Reagan administration were arming
against them.
</P>
<P>
   In El Salvador, the ``Muchachos'' of the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front were challenging the US-backed government
in a bitter guerrilla war. In Guatemala an even more vicious civil
war was to claim an estimated 200,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are still problems,``but at least we are no longer
killing each other,'' says Costa Rica's former president and Nobel
laureate, Oscar Arias. It was Arias who got the warring parties in
El Salvador and Nicaragua together and brokered a peace leading to
elections and national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Arias how he could possibly have thought that he, as the
leader of such a small and powerless country, could pull off such a
deal. He said that a country that has not had a standing army for
nearly half a century had the moral authority to end the wars, and
he has been working ever since to persuade the world to reduce the
arms trade and abolish armies. So far only Panama has followed
Costa Rica's example.
</P>
<P>
   But in the '90s, Guatemala ended its civil war, and death squads
no longer ply their trade in the cities and in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   In Nicaragua, President Arnoldo Aleman of Anastasio Somoza's old
Liberal Party has made a cynical pact with Daniel Ortega of the
opposition Sandinistas to alter the constitution and ``diminish
pluralism,'' as Christiana Chamorro, the daughter of Nicaragua's
previous president put it, so that they can run the country
together in ironic harmony.
</P>
<P>
   In El Salvador, the former guerrillas have more fully embraced
the democratic process, however, and recently emerged as the
largest party in the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The United States military, intelligence services, and fruit
companies no longer intervene in this region to protect their
interests _ or oppress the people, depending on your politics. But,
as the great purchaser of Central American goods, the United States
still looms large. Tourism is booming in the region. In Panama,
tourists are assured that Panamanian coins are the same size as US
coins and therefore slot machine-accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Costa Rica, where political stability has made it a
favorite for foreign investors, computer parts are fast gaining on
agriculture for exports dollars _ now accounting for 38 percent _
promising a day when silicon chips will trump bananas in these
long-suffering republics between the North and South American
continents. The Cold War seems very far away and long ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
