<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT, JERRY SPRINGER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use on or after March 27; fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Used to be, if your career was in need of a little
rehabilitation, you went on Leno. He'd pitch you a few fat
whiffleballs; you'd self-deprecatingly belt them out of the park;
America loved you again.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the first couple of episodes of the second season
of ``The Dick and Paula Celebrity Special,'' Dick and Paula's New
England-based chatfest is the new stop for the repentant celeb. No
less than the Blair Witch and Satan wind up on Dick and Paula's
couch, talking up their good works, be it participating in a 10K
walk for testicular cancer (the Blair Witch; say thank you, Tom
Green) or directing Charlton Heston in local community theater
(Satan).
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick and Paula'' comes from Tom Snyder, the guy who developed
``Dr. Katz: Professional Therapist'' and, like that series, the wit
is drier than an empty martini glass and so deadpan it makes Steven
Wright look like Carrot Top. Similarly animated in what Snyder
calls Squiggle Vision, which sort of just simulates motion, the
craftsmanship is rudimentary enough to make ``Pokemon'' look like a
Pixar product. The show takes us backstage, where Paul Revere is
forever haunting the green room (and forever getting bumped from
the show at the last minute), to the stage before the show begins,
where the warm-up comic barely rouses the studio audience; he, at
least, occasionally detects a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have acquired the taste, it's funny stuff. The
Blair Witch shows up tonight, but not to discuss her movie (a nasty
lawsuit pending). Next week, Satan shows up to mark the third
animated incarnation (following the ``South Park'' movie and ``God,
the Devil and Bob'') in which the Prince of Darkness is depicted as
a good idea man who's a little taken aback at how others have taken
his concept and run with it. Dick and Paula themselves are the
usual fatuous glad-handers, but they're not too obnoxious about it;
maybe Paula can sub for Kathie Lee when she walks. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The show: ``The Dick and Paula Celebrity Special.'' &QL; 
What: Animated comedy transpiring on the set of a small-town talk
show. &QL; 
Where: FX. &QL; 
When:!off 10:30 p.m. Mondays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
