<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPENING TO IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 27, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Secretary of State Madeleine Albright proposed last week to
dismantle the ``wall of distrust'' between Tehran and Washington,
her true audience was the divided leadership in Iran. Because of
the power struggle there between reformers and hardliners, her
appeal might not be heeded for some time to come. Nothing was lost
by her initiative, however, and much may be gained.
</P>
<P>
   It is a privilege of America's present power and wealth that the
vicar of the nation's foreign policy can acknowledge past American
errors in Iran without having to worry about a loss of pride or
prestige. Thanks to the conclusion of the Cold War and a peculiar
American insouciance about the past, Albright had no difficulty
saying certain things Washington had been told Tehran needed to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   Without quite apologizing, she evoked the coup d'etat that the
CIA arranged in 1953 to overthrow the nationalist regime of
Mohammad Mossadegh and install Shah Reza Pahlavi. ``The coup was
clearly a setback for Iran's political development,'' Albright
said, ``and it is easy to see now why many Iranians continue to
resent this intervention by America.''
</P>
<P>
   Her wording was cleverly descriptive, and though it stopped well
short of an apology, the mere recital of unpleasant facts belied
the premise of Iranian hardliners who preach that the Great Satan
cannot and will not acknowledge the evil it has perpetrated against
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   To her credit, Albright went further, admitting that for a
quarter century the United States backed ``the Shah's government''
while it ``brutally repressed political dissent.'' If there is to
be a dialogue between Washington and Tehran, this is a confession
the Iranian side needed to hear. It also has the virtue of being
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Saddam Hussein's regime had to say that Albright was
lying when she expressed regret for America's support of Iraq in
its 1980-88 war against Iran. Saddam's flacks said the United
States had backed Tehran. This mendacious commentary from Baghdad
should be a reminder of the benefits that may come from a US-Iran
dialogue, should the reformers win the Iranian power struggle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
