<HEADER>
A7317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CANAL-BOS &LR;      03-24 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CANAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE PASSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 27, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By H.D.S. GREENWAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY _ Many of the buildings of what was until a few
weeks ago the last of the American empire lie empty. The Panama
Canal, and the five-mile zone on either side with its clipped
lawns, administration buildings, and trim bungalows, passed to the
Republic of Panama on Dec. 31. The vast complex of Fort Clayton,
once the headquarters of the US military's Southern command, the
modern hospital, and Balboa High School await a new development
incarnation the Panamanians are planning.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Panamanians are pleased that the Yankees have gone home.
Some fear that a corrupt government could rob the canal of its
assets and allow it to deteriorate. After all, they say, that is
what happened to the transcontinental railroad that parallels the
canal. It was turned over 12 years ago, and today no trains run and
the tracks are covered with grass.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States there are even more dire predictions from
alarmists who say that the Hong Kong company that will improve the
port facilities will lead to a Chinese takeover.
</P>
<P>
   This worrying about the canal's future reminds me of the fuss I
encountered in Cairo 44 years ago when Gamal Abdal Nasser seized
the Suez Canal from the British. Englishmen said that the
``Gippies'' could not possibly manage the canal on their own. They
predicted that the sands of the desert would soon fill in what was,
until the building of the Panama Canal, the greatest feat of
hydraulic engineering known to man. In fact, the Egyptians have run
the canal without interruption ever since, except for when the
British and French attacked them in a vain attempt to get the canal
back.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of who owns the Panama Canal has been settled more
amiably. In 1977 President Jimmy Carter agreed to hand it to Panama
at century's end, and the turnover has been both gradual and
successful. More than 700,000 vessels have passed through the great
locks between the Pacific and the Caribbean Sea since they opened
in 1914, and today ships sail on in stately tandem as they always
have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
