<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7318 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TEXTILE0325-COX     03-24 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXTILE0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Textile schools face shortage of students, industry changes
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Recruiters for area textile colleges might be
wondering whether someone keeps popping ``Norma Rae'' into the VCR
on Career Day.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Field's 1979 character as an impoverished mill worker in
North Carolina gripped the country with its bleak portrayal of
textile manufacturing. And the bad rap lingers, even though the
industry has changed dramatically in the 20 years since Field's
Oscar-winning role.
</P>
<P>
   Despite significant technological innovations, universities are
still having a hard time luring students into textile careers.
</P>
<P>
   For years, recruiters have blamed falling enrollment at textile
schools on headlines about plant closures and rising imports. News
about the loss of jobs in the labor-intensive apparel sector has
overshadowed the industry's thriving sectors, such as research and
design, said Fred Cook, chair and professor of Georgia Tech's
School of Textile and Fiber Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the word `textile' is mentioned, the first thing that
pops into a student's mind is clothing. We see that time and time
again in recruiting,'' Cook said. ``This is a huge industry that
covers the entire fiber spectrum, but that generally is not how the
public perceives us.''
</P>
<P>
   According to recruiters, there's plenty of high-paying
opportunities. The industry is still alive in the Southeast, where
textile companies have invested billions of dollars to create
highly automated plants. And that means jobs have shifted away from
low-paying mill work to more lucrative positions focusing on
engineering and production processes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could graduate three times as many students as we do each
year and have absolutely no problem placing them,'' Cook said.
``We've got 22-year-olds with very little experience making $40,000
and up to start. It's the best supply-demand situation that I know
of in favor of the student.''
</P>
<P>
   But that message has failed to trickle down to high schools, he
said. And that's putting a dent in enrollment at schools like
Georgia Tech's textile school, which has lost nearly half its
student body.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech will start the fall with 135 textile
undergraduates, down from 230 students five years ago. It remains
the country's second-largest public textile school after North
Carolina State University's College of Textiles.
</P>
<P>
   Other public textile colleges also report declining enrollment.
One factor, some say, is that students are more bewitched than ever
with the get-rich-quick lure of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not `dot-com,' and that's part of the problem,'' said
Walter Thomas Jr., department head and professor of Southern
Polytechnic State University in Marietta, Ga. And this year's
recruitment season doesn't show much promise, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a recruiting dinner last week in LaGrange, which is a
big textile city, and 25 people showed up, including parents and
teachers,'' Thomas said. ``Usually, we get about 75 to 125 people
at that dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Polytechnic's small apparel and textile engineering
technology department graduates about a dozen students a year.
Total enrollment is down to 80 students from 135 three years ago,
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, starting salaries for textile majors in general
have gone up considerably. The average salary for a Georgia Tech
textile engineering graduate last year was $42,500, for example.
That's up from $30,400 four years ago. In the past three to four
years, starting salaries for Southern Polytechnic textile graduates
have gone up an average of $8,000, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in pure textile majors means companies are hiring
more graduates from other disciplines, such as chemical, electrical
and mechanical engineering, and then training them for a company's
specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for textile (graduates) is great...but the textile
industry has become so sophisticated that we're recruiting across
all majors,'' said Richard Dillard, director of public affairs at
Spartanburg, S.C.-based Milliken &AMP; Co. Technical and liberal arts
majors alike are welcome, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milliken, which operates about 15 plants in Georgia, represents
some of the diversity in the textile industry. Its products range
from colorants in Crayola Washable Markers to the orange spacesuits
that shuttle astronauts wear. The company also makes carpet, table
linen and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   It's the commercial textiles that go unnoticed by most students,
recruiters said. The industrial applications, including such
textile products as automotive air bags and flame-resistant
firefighter coats, offer a wide range of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The textile industry is not just cotton farmers in the
South,'' said Sara Johnson, a senior majoring in textile and fiber
engineering at Georgia Tech. ``I got interested in this because
there's so much growth in industrial textiles. I knew I would never
be without a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old has a job lined up at Michelin Tire Corp. in
Winnsboro, S.C., where she'll be monitoring cabling equipment at a
tire cord facility.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a dwindling number of students like Johnson, forcing
most textile colleges to make significant changes to keep their
schools viable.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State University's College of Textiles is beefing
up its global focus. The school is teaching students how
international business is conducted, and there's more of an
emphasis on learning foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are completely cognizant that the textile industry is
becoming more global,'' said David Buchanan, interim dean of the
textile college. ``The days that a student would come here and go
back to his hometown to work are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Polytechnic is becoming more international, too. Last
year, the school started an exchange program with Mexico and sent
nine students to study there. Next year, it's adding China to the
program.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia Tech, some significant changes could be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Textile Manufacturers Association in Atlanta is
creating an endowed chair for the textile school. The position
ideally will be filled with a longtime industry executive who would
bring real-life experience into the school, said Roy Bowen III,
association president.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the school is developing a long-range plan that
addresses the declining enrollment, Georgia Tech's Cook said.
Considerations include research and recruiting strategies and
possible changes to the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   The textile school's faculty has dropped along with enrollment.
The school presently has 12 faculty members, down from 15 five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been told we won't be allowed to add any faculty until
we get the student ratio back up,'' Cook said. ``One of our
considerations is if we can legitimately continue offering three
degrees in textiles.''
</P>
<P>
   One controversial consideration is dropping the word `textile'
from the school's name. Cook said he thinks the word conjures up
too many negative associations. Instead, he'd like to see a name
that puts the focus on fiber. ``I'm a firm believer in marketing
strategy,'' Cook said. ``If the old image doesn't work anymore you
develop a new image.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy to get rid of a word that has been on the
school's sign for 103 years, admits Cook, who emphasized that the
name change is only a consideration at this point.
</P>
<P>
   The industry will likely fight such a name change. At the same
time, there's room for a better description of the wide-ranging
industry, said Thomas at Southern Polytechnic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us have a concern about what the proper name is for
what we're doing,'' Thomas said. ``When you think of all the
textile applications there are _ from apparel to filtration systems
to materials for aircraft _ all of it involves taking fiber and
making a product out of it. That's really where we have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
