<SLUG> BC-HACKERS-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BRITISH MEN ARRESTED IN INTERNET THEFT OF 26,000 CREDIT CARD
NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Canada)  (Eds.: This story has been added to the front page of the business
section) 
(rk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The FBI said that it had assisted British and Canadian
law-enforcement officials in the arrest of two 18-year-old British
men in connection with the theft of more than 26,000 credit card
numbers over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The two were arrested on Thursday by the Dyfed-Powys Police
Service in Wales and charged with violating the United Kingdom's
Computer Misuse Act of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI spokesman said the names of the suspected computer
intruders were being withheld under the terms of the British law.
</P>
<P>
   An individual claiming responsibility for obtaining and
publishing the credit card data had in recent months been in
frequent contact with U.S. and European journalists. He had claimed
the break-ins were aimed at exposing the lack of security in
commercial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI estimated that losses connected with the intrusions
could exceed $3 million. The Philadelphia field office of the
agency assisted in the investigation, but Jim Davis, a spokesman
for the FBI, said he could not describe the agency's role because
it might jeopardize the British case against the pair. He said it
was unlikely that charges would be leveled against the pair in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself ``Curador,'' the young computer intruder has
spoken by telephone to reporters and claimed to be on a crusade to
eradicate computer security weaknesses in online shopping services.
As part of his vendetta against as many as nine small electronic
commerce sites earlier this year he had begun begun posting
thousands of stolen credit card numbers, addresses and expiration
dates to public Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The theft and the distribution of the card numbers echoed
another recent extortion attempt against a Connecticut-based online
music retailer. In that incident an anonymous computer vandal stole
about 300,000 credit card numbers from CD Universe and then began
posting them on a Web site when the retailer refused an extortion
demand and went to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card industry officials estimate that in 1999, 6 cents of
every $100 charged was fraudulent and that in the same period
credit card fraud totaled $956.2 million in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A Visa official said Friday that U.S. credit card fraud has
declined dramatically in the last seven years, falling from 17
cents per hundred dollars in 1992, for the nation's largest credit
card association.
</P>
<P>
   However, computer security experts said the new incident posed
troubling challenges for Internet retailers because the young
computer vandal had written a simple program that systematically
was able to search tens of thousands of Web sites looking for a
specific vulnerability in a Microsoft Internet Web server.
</P>
<P>
   The vulnerability was identified last year by Microsoft Corp.
and other computer security experts in the company's Internet
information server, but many computer sites have not yet patched
the flaw and are vulnerable to the attack.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been a bitter debate within the computer security
world over the wisdom of openly publishing information on computer
security vulnerabilities. Many computer security specialists argue
that the free publication of vulnerability information encourages
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But others respond that open publication of such flaws is the
only way to motivate slow-to-move system administrators to plug
holes that can be easily exploited by intruders.
</P>
<P>
   In the new case, a person who stated in a telephone interview in
February that he is an 18-year-old British computer hacker,
repeatedly posted the stolen numbers anonymously to different Web
sites. At the beginning of February the individual, who identified
himself as Curador had posted the numbers at least three times on
different Web sites. But the Web hosting services, including
Geocities and Tripod, took the information off of the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites Curador claimed to have stolen credit cards from
were: www.shoppingthailand.com; www.promobility.net;
www.ltamedia.com; www3.ntd.co.uk; www.visioncomputers.com;
www.ascp.org; www.salesgate.com; and www.feelgoodfalls.com.
</P>
<P>
   When notified that the credit cards numbers were posted on the
Web Hosting Services last month several of the service providers
said they had contacted law-enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conversation with a reporter last month, the
British teen-ager Curador predicted his arrest. ``There will be a
knock on the door and I will be arrested,'' he said. However he
claimed to be untroubled by the possibility: ``A couple of days
later I'll escape.''
</P>
<P>
   He also asserted in the interview that he had illegally ordered
the prescription drug Viagra and mailed it to the office of William
Gates, the Microsoft chairman. The claim could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that unless he continued to demonstrate the
vulnerability of many Web sites, computer security would not be
improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping I can have an impact,'' he said. ``I realize it
won't happen overnight. But at least they will begin to password
protect their sites, that wouldn't be too much to ask.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
