<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COWBOY-POEMS-NYT &LR;      03-24 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-POEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POEM ON THE RANGE: COWBOY LAUREATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: verse excerpts should be italicized)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since books of cowboy poetry began to appear in the 1890s,
the lyrical verses have evoked a sense of lost romance and a
disappearing way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy poetry's roots date from the end of Civil War, writes
Dave Stanley, a teacher of folklore history at Westminster College
in Salt Lake City, in a new anthology, ``Cowboy Poets and Cowboy
Poetry'' (University of Illinois Press), edited by Stanley and
Elaine Thatcher. Grazers and herders began arriving in the open
grasslands of the West with cattle from Texas and Mexico after
native populations had been driven from the area. Poems were
traditionally recited around the campfire during great cattle trail
drives or roundups, in bunkhouses and line camps, and in bars and
saloons.
</P>
<P>
   The folk historian Alan Lomax says that as trail drives moved
herds from Texas northward ``a variety of poem and song traditions
were recalled, modified, reinvented, and regionalized.'' He
particularly cites ``the verbal art of sailors and soldiers,
largely English and Irish in origin, which combined with the songs
and hollers of black cowboys and the corrido, or Mexican folk
ballad, tradition of the vaqueros.''
</P>
<P>
   A cowboy's work was taken seriously and often treated with
sentimentality, writes James S. Griffith, formerly the coordinator
of the Southwest Folklore Center of the University of Arizona. D.J.
O'Malley's poem ``A Cowboy's Death'' describes a cowboy's fatal
accident:
</P>
<P>
   'Twas a sad death for man to meet
</P>
<P>
   Out on that lonely lea;
</P>
<P>
   His relatives in Texas live,
</P>
<P>
   No more his face they'll see;
</P>
<P>
   But we hope the Father greets him
</P>
<P>
   With a smile upon his face,
</P>
<P>
   And seats him by his right hand
</P>
<P>
   Near the shining throne of grace.
</P>
<P>
   But anything short of death could be considered a subject for
humor, says Griffith. Consider O'Malley's ``D-2 Horse Wrangler,''
about a tenderfoot narrator who after a bucking accident asks for
special treatment:
</P>
<P>
   They picked me up and carried me in.
</P>
<P>
   And rubbed me down with a rolling pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's the way they all begin.
</P>
<P>
   You are doing well,'' says Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``And tomorrow morning if you don't die,
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you another horse to try.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh won't you let me walk?'' says I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes' says he, ``Into town.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy poetry is essentially oral. Reciting it aloud seems to
work in two ways, Stanley says. Many of the poems need personal
interpretation to save them from being tedious. And since much of
the subject matter of cowboy poetry _ riding horses, rounding up
cattle, breaking broncs and drinking in saloons _ occurred in
settings inhospitable to written texts, recitation was the way to
share experiences. ``It's as if all these poems had been composed
on horseback and later, grudgingly, committed to paper and ink,''
he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the formal center of cowboy poetry is the ballad,'' the
medieval form used in many of the oldest folk songs in English,
Stanley writes. ``The ballad _ which contrasts the symmetrical and
the asymmetrical, the even and the odd, voice and silence _ creates
a nice kind of tension that drives the language, as in ``The Glory
Trail'' by Charles Badger Clark. (The poem is sometimes called
``High-Chin Bob,'' after the proud cowboy in the verse who ropes a
mountain lion and is doomed to have it follow him forever.)
</P>
<P>
   'Way high up the Mogollons,
</P>
<P>
   Among the mountain tops,
</P>
<P>
   A lion cleaned a yearlin's bones
</P>
<P>
   And licked his thankful chops,
</P>
<P>
   When on the picture who should ride,
</P>
<P>
   A-trippin' down a slope,
</P>
<P>
   But High-Chin Bob, with sinful pride
</P>
<P>
   And mav'rick-hungry rope.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Cannon, founding director of the Western Folklife Center in
Elko, Nev., says that while cowboy poetry is sometimes humorous,
``it is often born of loss, remembrance and grief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there was no home to return to,'' he said, ``even
early cowboy poetry from the 1800s is a song of exile from the
American promise of the West,'' like the 1860s poem ``The
Blizzard,'' by Eugene Ware:
</P>
<P>
   A requiem in a lonesome land,
</P>
<P>
   In a mournful minor key:
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how long the river,
</P>
<P>
   The river will reach the Sea!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0332 </DOCNO>
