<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS &LR;      03-24 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFER GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 26, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy being an industry apostate. The tobacco giants
reacted furiously when the Liggett company turned state's evidence
in 1997, admitting for the first time that nicotine is addictive
and that tobacco companies had been marketing to youngsters. Now
Smith &AMP; Wesson, one of the most venerable names in firearms
manufacturing, has enraged others in the industry by agreeing to
important safety measures for the manufacture and sale of its
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The adoption by Smith &AMP; Wesson of principles for the responsible
manufacture and sale of guns should be seen as a model, not a
betrayal, by other firearms companies. It is past time for
manufacturers of the only unregulated consumer product in the
nation to take voluntary steps to ensure that their product is as
safe as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Springfield, Mass., company said last week that all its
handguns would be shipped with safety locks beginning immediately
to reduce accidental shootings. All new issues would include a
second, hidden serial number to make guns easier to trace. Most
significant, the company pledged within three years to develop
handguns equipped with so-called smart-gun technology _ allowing
the guns to be fired only by their owners. Boston announced
Wednesday that the city would give preferential treatment to
companies working on smart-gun technology in awarding police
contracts; a significant number of officers killed in the line of
duty are shot with their own weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson also said that it will require its authorized
dealers to follow uniform guidelines in distributing its guns: not
to sell at gun shows unless buyers have been properly screened, not
to deal in high-capacity magazines or assult weapons, to require
those placing multiple orders to wait 14 days after the first gun
is released to pick up the others.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms estimates
that of the 100,000-plus licensed gun dealers in America, just 349
of them account for 50 percent of the guns eventually used in
crimes. The vast majority of legitimate gun dealers should have no
problem complying with the Smith &AMP; Wesson principles.
</P>
<P>
   That Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to these changes under threat of a
lawsuit does not diminish their importance. These are reasonable
steps by a responsible company that wants to become part of the
solution to gun violence. Unless they adopt similar standards,
other manufacturers will continue to be part of the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7329 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-`HOLLYWOOD'-LOTTO-TEX     03-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`HOLLYWOOD'-LOTTO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLLYWOOD' HENDERSON _ SUPER BOWL STAR, PHILANTHROPIST, LOTTO
WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By THOMAS TERRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was with little of his trademark flair that
Thomas ``Hollywood'' Henderson celebrated his $28 million Lotto
jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The former star Dallas Cowboys linebacker strolled into a
7-Eleven, ordered a sausage-and-egg biscuit, washed it down with a
pint of milk, then munched some of those little white doughnuts for
dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now in the early '70s that would be cocaine and champagne,'' a
chuckling Henderson, 47, wearing gym shorts and a diamond Rolex
watch, said outside his upscale Austin condominium on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   His heady, drug-flowing days are apparently long gone, and his
recent years have centered on inner-city good works. But flashes of
the high-rolling times came back with a roar for Henderson when he
bought a fistful of lottery tickets at Nau's Drug in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   One carried the winning number to a $28 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows your mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got drafted by the Dallas Cowboys in 1975. I won the Super
Bowl in 1977. The only thing bigger than winning this lottery was
16 years ago (when) I changed my life and became a clean and sober
man. I am probably the most prepared person to win $28 million that
I know of.''
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials said the former Cowboy has not yet claimed his
prize but had passed a preliminary validation test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he's coming in next week,'' said Lottery Commission
spokeswoman Leticia Vasquez. ``He hasn't given us a date, but he
did tell us he hasn't slept very much. People have been calling him
at his house all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Henderson produced a unique validation number from the
winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson estimates that he has spent about $20,000 on Lotto
tickets over the past decade. On Wednesday, he bought $100 worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew that I was going to win,'' he said. ``I (just)
didn't know when I was going to win. I only played when it was
$20-30 million _ spend one or two hundred dollars at two or three
different stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson was on the golf course when his former wife called on
his cellular phone. She had heard that Nau's, a popular Austin
pharmacy where she knew he bought tickets, had produced a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ex-wife had the numbers,'' Henderson said. ``She tortured
me by saying, `Do you have any tickets with a five on it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Yeah, what are the numbers?' And she said, `I'm not
telling you. Look at the tickets and tell me each one that has a
five on it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through about five tickets starting with fives, then I
got to the ticket where I went through six numbers, and she goes,
`Oh my God!' ''
</P>
<P>
   His winning numbers were 5, 8, 17, 35, 38 and 41.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has not always been so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   He was a linebacker for Dallas from 1975 until the Cowboys cut
him in 1979 because of drug problems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, he was arrested in California for smoking crack with
two teen-aged girls. According to police, he sexually assaulted one
of the girls, threatened both with a gun and held them against
their will. He served two years and four months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson credits the example set by Cowboys coach Tom Landry in
helping him turn his life around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not listen to Tom Landry, but I heard him,'' Henderson
said. ``I wish Tom Landry was here to see this, because he would
say to me: `Let's see how you handle this, Thomas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I give him the credit ... Landry taught me quality control.
Through my recovery from drugs and alcohol ... I have his voice,
his message, what he stood for, loud in my head today, (in) my
philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has been involved in various Austin charities and said
his lottery winnings will allow him to give more. Two years ago, he
went on a week-long hunger strike in a drive to raise money for a
running track in impoverished east Austin, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   With his profile raised by charitable endeavors, Henderson
decided he wanted to do more for the community and announced that
he would run for a spot on the Austin City Council.
</P>
<P>
   But he soon discovered that he was ineligible because of his
prior felony conviction.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lotto officials, the winner selected the immediate
cash option, meaning the $28 million jackpot is worth a little more
than $14 million before taxes. Henderson said he is exploring ways
to limit his tax liability on the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, he's not in a big rush to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take everything under advisement,'' he said.
``I'm not in any hurry. I've got plenty of money already. ... I'm
just going to continue to do the charities that I do, take care of
my children and buy my momma a Town Car.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is the most famous Texan to hit a jackpot, according
to Vasquez, the Lotto spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really come full circle,'' a former Cowboys teammate,
receiver Drew Pearson, told The Associated Press. ``He had it all
when he was playing for the Cowboys; that's when he became
Hollywood. Then he got into trouble and got mixed up with the drugs
and lost it all. He hit rock bottom.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
