<HEADLINE>
MAN KILLED IN HOTEL RESTAURANT IN MEXICO IS TWICE MISIDENTIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Authorities acknowledged Friday that they twice
misidentified a man killed in a shooting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours after the shooting in a hotel restaurant here,
law enforcement authorities identified the man in written
statements as Cuauhtemoc Herrera Suastegui, who was a senior aide
to Mexico's attorney general. He resigned in January after becoming
the target of a drug investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Herran Salvatti, Mexico's top drug prosecutor, discussed
Herrera's supposed demise on a late-night television newscast, only
to realize he was in error, when forensic doctors sent him a photo
of the corpse from the morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Herrera because I've worked with him, and that wasn't
him,'' Herran Salvatti said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera was shot in the back but survived. His defense lawyer
and a woman who had been with him were also shot; they also
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Herran Salvatti said that Mexico City detectives first erred
when they found a document identifying the victim as Army Capt.
Cuauhtemoc Najera, and announced the victim as Cuauhtemoc Herrera.
</P>
<P>
   Correcting that mistake, they then identified the corpse as
Cuauhtemoc Najera. But that was also incorrect. Just before
midnight, authorities finally identified the shooting victim as
Sergio Jorge Chavez, Herrera's driver.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Del Villar, the Mexico City district attorney, said
Friday that five men had been detained but that police were still
seeking another man whom Herrera and a Canadian tourist have
described as the gunman who burst into the Imperial Hotel, firing
at Herrera and his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Herrera attracted special attention because
William E. Ledwith, a senior Drug Enforcement Administration
official, pointed to him as an example of corruption in Mexican
anti-drug units during a Feb. 29 congressional hearing in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera, while serving as the No. 2 official in an elite federal
narcotics investigations unit that worked for Mexico's attorney
general, failed a lie detector test administered by U.S. officials
in September 1998, and other evidence emerged to suggest that
Herrera was collaborating with traffickers, Ledwith said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those warning signs, Herrera was not dismissed from the
attorney general's staff. Instead he was transferred to a
diplomatic post in Spain, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Herran Salvatti said Friday that after authorities discovered
Herrera's name on documents confiscated from drug traffickers in
Cancun, Herrera became the target of a drug investigation in
mid-1999, about the time he returned to Mexico from Spain. But
although he was, officially at least, the target of a criminal
investigation, Herrera continued to hold a job on the attorney
general's staff, although in a lowly post.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned voluntarily on Jan. 14. He had been scheduled to
meet with an aide to Herran Salvatti Friday, to respond to
prosecutors' questions, Herran Salvatti said.
</P>
<P>
   From his hospital bed Friday, Herrera told detectives that he
asked for the meeting with prosecutors in order to ask for their
help in clearing his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
