<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7333 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-PORTFOLIOS-ART     03-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PUTIN AND MARKETS, THE HARD PART STARTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of Moscow Stock Exchange index is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Fedorov, the former Russian finance minister and
one-time head of the state tax service, knows an expatriate Russian
couple who put a large chunk of their money into Russian stocks in
December. Since then, they have doubled their stake and bought a
house.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Americans, who have probably been avoiding
volatile Russian stocks, the couple's good fortune means that much
of the easy money has been made.
</P>
<P>
   The market rally has come as the Russian economy is rebounding
from its plunge during the financial crisis of August 1998, when
the ruble was devalued and the government defaulted on its foreign
debt. The Russian economy grew 3 percent last year _ a pace that is
expected to continue, if not accelerate, this year.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround was spurred by a tripling of oil prices, which
also bolstered government revenue, and the ruble's devaluation,
which made domestic companies more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Investor interest is also perking up. For example, cash flow
into the $68.6 million Lexington Troika fund, which invests in
Russia, was a heavy $9.1 million for the first two months of the
year, according to Lipper estimates. The Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
office here, headed by Rair R. Simonyan, a Russian investment
banker, will be host for a conference for foreign investors in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, the head of the Russian Federal Property Fund,
which controls the remaining government stakes in Russian
companies, met with potential investors in London and New York.
</P>
<P>
   This year's rally, however, may have more to do with the New
Year's Eve resignation of the unpredictable Boris N. Yeltsin as
president. The Russian Trading System Cash index jumped 17 percent
in the wake of the announcement and is now up 39 percent for the
year. The stability that people see coming with the expected
election Sunday of the acting president, Vladimir V. Putin, has
also helped.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts here say the stock-market rally was powered by
local investors just waiting to sell when foreigners piled back in.
In any event, much of the good news is already in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Once the election ballots are counted, a new uncertainty may
emerge: Will Putin be a reformer, and, if so, can he make the
changes he wants? The needed tax, regulatory and legal reforms are
daunting. There is corruption to deal with, and the rich and
powerful oligarchs. Putin has been difficult to gauge; no one can
say what he will do about these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Kim, Morgan Stanley's strategist for Russia, said
people were still uncertain about who, precisely, the new policy
makers would be and what reforms would be carried out. ``It is
always implementation that has failed,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov, now an author, said, ``once oil prices go down and
devaluation effects go away, things will be tough for Putin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More stability will not carry the market,'' he added,
referring to investors' hope that Putin's strong hand will prove
enough to keep stocks rising. ``By the end of the year, there will
have to be other actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri V. Vasiliev, the former head of Russia's version of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, has a long list of what the
country needs, including laws and regulations that treat investors
and companies equally, lower taxes and improved collections.
</P>
<P>
   Now the head of a shareholders rights organization, backed by
institutional investors with $10 billion in Russian stocks,
Vasiliev said, ``Today, rules are so unclear that there are so many
opportunities for bribery.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the financial crisis, he said, investors looked at Russia
through ``rose-colored glasses'' and bought everything; after the
crisis, Russia was viewed through ``black glasses'' and nothing was
bought. Now, he said, investors need to ponder opportunities here
through ``clear glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   That means ``deep investment analysis'' of companies is
necessary, he said, especially concerning the honesty of executives
and any links to the oligarchs or organized crime. Foreign
investors face not only the risk of a tumbling stock market, but
also of maneuvers by Russian executives that could undermine the
value of a company or dilute the value of a stock.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of analysis, he allowed, ``is not easy, of course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
