<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRAIN ON MARS TOO ROUGH FOR SMALL PROBES, NASA PHOTOS INDICATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most terrain of scientific interest on Mars is too rugged for
the small landing craft NASA has been sending, extensive new
photographs indicate. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; For more than two years, planetary geologist Ken Edgett has
been among the first experts to examine the steady stream of
photography dispatched to Earth by NASA's Mars Global Surveyor, a
small camera-equipped probe that has been circling the Red Planet
since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mars Global Surveyor is showing us just how rugged most of
the interesting parts of Mars are,'' said Edgett, a staff
researcher at Malin Space Science Systems, the San Diego-based
company that built and operates the probe's cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks very, very rugged, lots of sharp edges, points and
hills,'' said Edgett. ``We are dealing with a planet where it has
not rained for billions of years, if ever. Rain on the Earth tends
to smooth, erode and flatten down things. This has not happened on
Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   The doomed, 640-pound, 3 1/2-foot tall Mars Polar Lander and the
other small probes that NASA has been planning to launch are no
match for the planet that Global Surveyor is revealing, Edgett
said. Plans to launch a similar lander that would reach Mars in
2001 have been at least temporarily suspended in the wake of the
Polar Lander loss.
</P>
<P>
   Edgett also raised the issue during the annual Lunar and
Planetary Institute conference in Houston earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mars Global Surveyor has completely revolutionized (our
understanding of) Mars,'' Edgett said. ``However, most of the
revolution is still under way. A lot of the data has not been
released to the general science community. Once it's released, it
may take a good decade of people sifting through that data before
it really sinks in.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the space agency plans to release the results of its
investigation into the Dec. 3 loss of the $221 million Polar
Lander, which was attempting to reach Mars' unexplored south pole.
The findings promise to alter the cost, pace and design of future
Mars probes.
</P>
<P>
   A $273 million mission, Global Surveyor maneuvered into orbit
around Mars in September 1997. Because of a mechanical problem the
probe was unable to begin its two-year mission of mapping the
planet's terrain until early 1999. Findings from the mission's
science teams are just beginning to make their way into prominent
science journals.
</P>
<P>
   Global Surveyor's cameras can detect objects as small as a
school bus. In contrast, features captured by NASA's Viking probes
of the late 1970s had to be as large as football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Edgett said his greatest concern for the future of Mars
exploration is that the rugged terrains in the imagery collected by
the Global Surveyor are the features that are of highest scientific
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression from what I've seen is that we should be
designing landers for the landing sites.'' said Edgett. ``If a
community of scientists decides, here is where we will find
evidence of life but that spot looks really nasty to land, we darn
well should design something to land there anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise we will be forced to land at places as flat and
smooth as an airport runway,'' he said. ``Those places are very
rare, and they are far away from the kinds of places that would be
of scientific interest.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Among Mars' most prominent geological features, he notes, is
the 2,500 mile long Valles Marineris, a canyon system that drops to
a six-mile depth in places. Global Surveyor's cameras have revealed
a distinct layering of the canyon walls, including the the upper
most crust.
</P>
<P>
   The layering of Valles Marineris, if it can be accessed with
robotic probes, would offer scientists an unexpectedly thorough
chronological record of Martian climate change. Hidden among the
structures are evidence of volcanic activity, Earthquakes and
meteor impacts. They could reveal whether Mars once harbored oceans
and possibly life.
</P>
<P>
   On Earth, the oldest rocks are about 3.9 billion years-old,
about 600 million years younger than the estimated formation of the
solar system, creating a gap in what geologists can examine to
explain this planet's earliest evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The better preserved features on Mars offer the potential to
fill in the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might mean that we want something that can land on the wall
of Valles Marineris or that can land on the top and walk, crawl or
snake down,'' said Edgett.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in late 1996, Global Surveyor was part of the first
salvo in a wave of low cost missions that NASA hoped to launch to
Mars every 26 months. Each salvo was to include a lander and an
orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Pathfinder, the Global Surveyor's companion lander, reached
Mars with equal success July 4, 1997, returning close up images of
rocks scattered on an ancient watershed north of the planets'
equator.
</P>
<P>
   The second salvo in that wave, NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter as
well as the Polar Lander mission, failed.
</P>
<P>
   The $151 million Climate Orbiter mission was lost last Sept. 23
as it was maneuvering into orbit around Mars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
