u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV26-B     03-24 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBTS IN THE CYBER-CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 26, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 11 years, Tom Valovic was writer and then editor of perhaps
the liveliest trade publication to cover the dawn of the digital
age. Telecommunications magazine was established in the late 1960s
in suburban Boston and grew to prosperity, eventually competing
against vigorous weeklies such as Communications Week and Network
World, owned by McGraw Hill and IDG. It has remained independent
long past the point at which a lesser magazine would have been
swallowed up, thanks to family ownership and its engaging tone:
even ISDN jokes were permitted (It Still Does Nothing).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was Valovic himself who wrote the article that fairly
can be said to have broken the story of the decade in June 1991:
``A Giant Step Towards Internet Commercialization?'' It began, as
usual, with a tip _ an e-mail tip, no less _ from Brian Kahin,
director of Harvard University's Information Infrastructure
Project. Valovic scrambled to pin it down, and in due course,
announced to the waiting world:
</P>
<P>
   ``According to several sources, ANS (the backbone operator of
the Internet) is expected to make a major announcement concerning
the creation of a separate for-profit subsidiary chartered to
develop the T3-based Internet backbone for commercial use. If this
does happen, it will have significant impacts for further Internet
commercialization.''
</P>
<P>
   The world was underwhelmed. In those days, the
telecommunications industry was a hyper-regulated world of Baby
Bells and switch manufacturers seemingly far removed from the
computer industry, where the networking drive was taking place (the
academic computer industry at that!). The rest of the world had
other things on its mind. So Valovic went on gathering more little
items for print, tracking the Net's ``elaborate progressions,''
until convergence of telecommunications, computers, publishing, and
entertainment was among the foremost topics on the Communal Mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would boost the Internet during the day, and come home and
have my doubts at night,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The result of his evening pensees is ``Digital Mythologies: The
Hidden Complexities of the Internet.'' Published by Rutgers
University Press, Valovic's essays describe the rise of the hype
surrounding the Internet and surveys the counter-literature of
skepticism that it has spawned. It is an uncommonly thoughtful
book. Once again, the reporter has gotten a first-rate scoop.
</P>
<P>
   It was five years ago that technology pundit G. Pascal Zachary
coined the term Cyber-Church to characterize the quasi-religious
fervor that has gripped enthusiasts of the new communication
technologies. No one has come up with a better phrase. The
exuberant phase of revelation is mostly over. The new phase is one
of Second Thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Bill Joy, chief scientist of Sun Microsystems, recently
made headlines with a piece in Wired magazine that warned darkly
against uncontrolled progress in genetics, nanotechnology, and
robotics. Sinners confessing is a classic way of getting rubes into
the revival tent.
</P>
<P>
   John Seely Brown, director of the Xerox Palo Alto Research
Center (in which many aspects of computer-user interface were
designed), has teamed up with Paul Duguid of the University of
California at Berkeley to write ``The Social Life of Information.''
They argue that technological ``tunnel vision'' _ a narrow focus on
ends _ has pushed into the background important social
considerations that now must be redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Evolution of the Wired Life,'' Charles Jonscher of
Harvard University's Program on Information Resouces Technology
argues that it is more important than ever to understand the
difference among data, information, and knowledge. The history of
the wired world he offers is most engaging.
</P>
<P>
   But only Valovic provides a revealing map of how the climate of
opinion got from there to here.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he describes the role of The Well, a dial-up
computer conferencing system organized by Stewart Brand more than a
decade ago in California that proved to be very influential in
framing the terms in which the new technology was to be discussed.
Well subscribers chose to participate in a wide range of
discussions _ chat rooms, we would say today _ and durable
connections formed there among thinkers, doers, and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   He vividly limns the rise of Wired magazine from (more or less)
the ashes of the Whole Earth Catalog. (The remarkable Stewart Brand
was among Wired's founders; Kevin Kelly, its executive editor, had
been a Whole Earth editor.) Despite Wired's self-professed disdain
for media empires, he writes ``Wired and Big Media seemed to be
made for each other.'' Wired's stable of freelance writers _ Steven
Levy, Paulin Borsook, Mitchell Kapor, Howard Rheigold, Jon Katz,
Brock Meeks, John Markoff, and others gradually moved out to
influential magazines, newspapers, foundations, and, of course, the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Wired (and its countercultural counterpart, Mondo 2000) ``laid
the foundation for a new technocratic set of values that gained
mindshare not on the basis of being rigorously examined and then
accepted but rather unquestioningly swallowed whole on the basis of
its trendy cachet,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nebulous cloud of assumptions that pervaded Wired's
message tended to belie the notion that science and technology _
with their natural propensity for order, accuracy, and precision _
were involved here. No, there was something else present, a leap of
faith perhaps, or possibly a kind of cultural mutation that
operated conveniently out of the range of the expected set of
journalistic descriptive powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Valovic is no technophobe, as is to be expected of someone who
served as editor in chief of a high-tech trade magazine for five
years. Indeed, he is an expert on bringing seemingly disparate
worlds into communication with one another. (A market research
manager now for International Data Corp., he also teaches courses
at Northeastern University.)
</P>
<P>
   But he insists that context is important to such discussions _
and that context means attention to the concrete. A good portion of
his book is devoted to exploring the pathologies of the online
life, the weird dissociation that often accompanies extensive
virtual schmoozing. He is a persistent, patient advocate for
traditional concerns, for investing in children, spouses, gardens;
for balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the media seemed to have gotten caught up in the
Internet craze, almost in a pop-culture sense, and became prone to
repeating a single idea: that the new technologies were going to
profoundly change our lives in the realms of business, education,
health care, or just about any other realm that could be thought
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this was true enough on the surface of things, it also
became apparent that these breathlessly delivered renditions were
usually devoid of any real specifics. . . . Where were the
specifics of these transformations? How do we get past all the
marketing hype and constantly-invoked mythologies of digital
process and into something more tangible, more grounded in
day-to-day reality?
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, if we don't know what these changes will really
amount to, how can we possibly say that we think they are important
or exciting or wonderful?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
