<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE ULSTER PARTY LEADER CHALLENGED BY FOE OF PEACE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The Northern Ireland peace agreement
faces a showdown vote Saturday as members of the Ulster Unionists
decide whether to keep David Trimble as their leader or return
their party to its harder-line past.
</P>
<P>
   The 850-member party council is to vote on a leadership
challenge by the Rev. Martin Smyth, 68, a former grand master of
the Orange Order, the militant Protestant group. But the decision
will turn not on the delegates' views of the two men but on their
increasing level of discomfort with the peace pact, which Trimble
embraces and Smyth opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth's bid looms as another setback for the already stalled
peace negotiations, but Trimble, 55, said he was ``relaxed'' about
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was coming and it's part of the whole question of
change, generation change within the party, and is part of the way
in which the party is renewing itself at the moment, and some
people aren't comfortable with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In persuading his party to take part in new political
arrangements under which Protestants, long the dominant force in
Ulster politics, share power with the Catholic minority, Trimble
has transformed its stance from a rigid one of surrendering as
little authority as possible to one that accommodates compromise.
In 1998 he shared the Nobel Peace Prize with John Hume, leader of
the Social Democratic and Labor Party, the largest Catholic group.
Trimble's party is the largest Protestant party in the province.
</P>
<P>
   But his moderate stance has cost him the support of party
members who have either opposed the settlement from its signing in
April 1998 or have grown disenchanted by what they perceive as its
favoritism toward the republican movement. Republicans, most of
whom are Catholic, want to see Northern Ireland with closer ties to
the Irish Republic, while the largely Protestant unionists want
Northern Ireland to remain part of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord sought to balance these contrasting aspirations
and bring political stability to the province, where more than
3,600 people have died in three decades of sectarian violence. It
created a new power-sharing assembly as its centerpiece with
Trimble as first minister and members of the rival Sinn Fein party,
the political representatives of the Irish Republican Army, in
executive posts.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, the new home rule government abruptly ended
after only two months when the IRA failed to start disarming and
London re-established its authority over Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The British suspended the new administration to forestall
Trimble's almost certain ouster by his party if the government
continued without any weapons turnovers. Britain believes Trimble
to be essential to progress in Ulster, and Prime Minister Tony
Blair left no doubt Friday which candidate he favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a very clear choice for people, and the Ulster
Unionist Party will make its mind up, but I have got a very great
deal of respect for David Trimble and the enormous courage he has
shown in trying to give people a peaceful future in Northern
Ireland,'' he said in a statement from Lisbon, where he was
attending a European Union summit conference.
</P>
<P>
   Many unionists were angered last week when Trimble suggested
during a St. Patrick's Day visit to Washington that he would be
prepared to go back into government with Sinn Fein with no prior
disarmament as long as the IRA gave guarantees of its intention to
destroy its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth said this statement prompted his challenge and showed that
under Trimble, the party was straying too far from its principles.
There should be ``no guns outside the door, no guns under the
table, no guns on the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, 72 percent of the party council's members voted
to support the agreement, but last November, only 58 percent backed
Trimble's decision to enter government with Sinn Fein. If Smyth can
improve on that 42 percent dissident figure, Trimble's leadership _
and most likely the entire peace agreement _ is probably doomed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
