<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HOLLYWOOD-LOTTO-HNS &LR;      03-24 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-LOTTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NFL PLAYER'S BEST HIT: $28 MILLION TEXAS JACKPOT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Moved in ``a'' and ``s'' categories) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Thomas ``Hollywood'' Henderson already knew he
was lucky. The former All-Pro Dallas Cowboys linebacker had
survived the NFL, crack addiction, suicidal urges and prison.
</P>
<P>
   And he already considered himself a rich man, at least compared
to the inner-city Austin kids he is devoted to helping.
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson, 47, had powerful new proof of his good fortune
and wealth Friday: a Texas lottery ticket that will bring him about
$14.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have money. I've got a nice home, a big truck and
some cars. The only thing that's going to change about me is it's
going to add some zeros to my account,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   He defied the game's 15.8 million-to-1 odds with six winning
numbers out of 50 in Wednesday's drawing, capturing the biggest
Lotto Texas jackpot of the year and one of the larger unshared
pots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the odds of winning are like one in 17 million. But
what are the odds of me winning?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson bought $100 worth of tickets for Wednesday's $28
million jackpot and allowed the computer to choose the winning
numbers _ 5, 8, 17, 35, 38, 41.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials said that because Henderson chose the lump sum
``cash-option'' payment, his prize will actually amount to
$14,491,235. After taxes, he'll get a check for $10,433,690,
spokesman Keith Elkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, God. Thank you very much,'' he told Austin's
KXAN-TV Thursday night when he first disclosed he held the winning
ticket. After that interview, he said he celebrated alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a one-man party. I went to 7-Eleven and got a sausage
biscuit with egg, some little white donuts, some whole milk and a
large bottle of water. That was the celebration spread,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in bed by 11 o'clock, but I didn't go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said his all-important charitable work with
underprivileged kids just got easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't have to beg so much any more,'' he told KXAN. ``I
won't have to fast any more,'' as he once did to raise money for a
youth sports facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been rich, I've been poor. I've been bad, I've been good.
For the last 16 years I've been clean and sober. I've been trying
to make a difference in my children's lives and the lives of
kids,'' Henderson said. ``I've tried to be a good steward in my
community. I've tried to be an activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine said to me tonight, `It's karma. You just got
the big bonus in karma for the work you've done,''' said Henderson,
who counsels substance abusers as well as heading up his nonprofit
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted the friend's assessment. How else could the Austin
native explain his trip from humble roots to fame, from sports hero
to inmate, from rehabilitated role model to the super-wealthy?
</P>
<P>
   A surprise first-round draft pick out of Langston College in
Oklahoma, the three-time Super Bowl veteran played for the Cowboys
from 1975-79, when he was fired by the late Coach Tom Landry due to
cocaine addiction. When he eulogized Landry just five weeks ago, he
called him ``the greatest man I've ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson finished out his playing career with Houston, Miami
and San Francisco. But in 1984, his football days behind him, he
hit a low point. He began serving 28 months in a California prison
for felony convictions of sexual assault and bribery. The charges
stemmed from a crack-hazed encounter with two Long Beach teen-age
girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received a sexual favor from one for letting them smoke
crack with me. Sex for crack. That is the way it was,'' he said in
a belated apology to his Cowboys teammates in 1997. He also penned
an autobiography, ``Out of Control.''
</P>
<P>
   But even after his prison stint and years as an anti-drug
campaigner, Henderson wasn't through paying for his crimes. This
year, a disappointed Henderson _ ineligible to hold office _ was
forced to abandon plans to run for Austin City Council because he
was never pardoned nor had his criminal record expunged.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his troubled past, in the capital city Henderson is
well-known and admired for his nearly single-handed development of
a sports center for East Austin youths. He went on a hunger strike
in 1997 to raise money for the outdoor track and field facility,
and he has spent copious amounts of time building and maintaining
it. But it's still a work in progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need hurdles, high-jump apparatus, pole vault apparatus. I
called and got a price the other day. It's $15,000,'' he said, and
with a laugh added: ``Oh, well. I'll be writing a check.''
</P>
<P>
   To do the Thursday interview with KXAN, he dropped by the store
where he bought his ticket _ Nau's Enfield Drug, an old-fashioned
pharmacy and hangout in the Clarksville neighborhood one mile west
of the Capitol. The store is about three blocks from his
fashionable condo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won $28 million in my neighborhood. In my neighborhood,'' he
repeated. ``It's going to stay in Austin because I'm not leaving
Austin. This is my hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he figured out he had the winning ticket Thursday and
spent a listless day staring at his ticket and preparing to go
public with his secret.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Henderson was hard to find and less eager to talk,
apparently weary of media and well-wishers' calls.
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson did contact the Texas Lottery Commission on Friday
to get informal confirmation that he was the winner. He told
officials that next week or later, after consulting with an
attorney and financial adviser, he plans to surrender the ticket in
return for his multimillion-dollar check.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
