<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-REYNOLDS-H     03-24 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REYNOLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
VERO BEACH, Fla. _ When Shane Reynolds received the official word
Friday that he would be the Astros' opening-day starter April 3 at
Pittsburgh, he didn't exactly jump for joy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because that isn't his nature. Or maybe it's
because he has had the honor four previous times. Then again, it
could be something totally different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to pitch against the other team's No. 1 starter?''
Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing the opening-day assignment pretty much assures Reynolds
will be matched with the ace _ or at least one of the top pitchers
_ from opposing teams during the early part of the season, until
rotations start getting off kilter.
</P>
<P>
   It makes getting off to a hot start that much more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference,'' Reynolds said. ``I'm sure anyone
would rather face someone besides the No. 1 starter on other
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Being slotted in the No. 1 position didn't seem to bother
Reynolds in 1999, when he was 4-1 with a 2.65 ERA the first month
of the season. His .650 career winning percentage for April is his
second-best for any month.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker chose Reynolds over Jose Lima despite Lima
having posted better statistics in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lima was 21-10 with a 3.58 ERA, while Reynolds was 16-14 and
3.85. The fact Reynolds has started every opening day since 1996
factored heavily into Dierker's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting on opening day is an honor, but it's also a
challenge,'' Dierker said. ``You get so excited, and you have to
keep your emotions under control. I think Shane has a better chance
to do that because he's started on opening day before.''
</P>
<P>
   By starting on opening day for the fifth time, Reynolds will
match J.R. Richard and Mike Scott for the most opening-day
assignments in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice honor, but it's not the only thing in the world,''
Reynolds said. ``It's not the reason I work as hard as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   An argument could be made that not all of Reynolds' opening-day
assignments have been based on merit. In 1996, Doug Drabek was
scheduled to pitch the first game but Reynolds was pushed up a day
when Drabek suffered a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile would have been the likely choice to open in 1998
after winning 19 games the previous season. Reynolds got the nod
because Kile signed a free-agent contract with Colorado after the
1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson's departure following the 1998 season helped
Reynolds' cause in 1999, just as the Mike Hampton trade opened the
door this time. But while Reynolds may not have delivered the best
season among his mound mates every year, he has been the club's
most consistent pitcher over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny how things work out,'' Reynolds said.
``There were many different reasons for me starting on opening day
so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Pirates manager Gene Lamont has tabbed righthander Jason Schmidt
as his opening-day starter; how Pittsburgh's rotation will line up
for the remainder of the series is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Lima will start the second game of the Pittsburgh series,
followed by Chris Holt.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Octavio Dotel in position to start the first
regular-season game at Enron Field, when the Astros host the
Philadelphia Phillies on April 7. Dwight Gooden would make his
first start in the second game of that series.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden also is in line to start the inaugural game at Enron
Field, Thursday's exhibition against the Yankees _ one of his
former teams.
</P>
<P>
   Lima will start against New York the following night, and Holt
is scheduled to start the final game of the exhibition season April
1 against the Texas Rangers, also at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Where starting pitching looked like a weakness _ or at least a
question mark _ at the beginning of spring training, it has been
one of the most pleasant surprises of the Grapefruit League season.
</P>
<P>
   The five pitchers who will make up the Astros' season-opening
rotation have a combined spring ERA of 3.31. If they carry that
type of success into the season, maybe people will stop asking how
the team plans to manage without Hampton, who won 22 games in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Holtie is going to have a great year, and with Shane
and Jose they're going to be fine,'' Hampton said. ``One person
doesn't make that much of a difference on a team, I don't care who
you are. It still takes 25 guys to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've still got a powerful lineup, and they've still got
good pitching, so they're going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
