<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-MINERS-ART-710     03-24 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MINERS-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MINERS, ANGRY OR NOSTALGIC, PREPARE TO VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT29, NYT30 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHAKHTY, Russia _ The air is so choked with dust deep in the
October Revolution Mine that only the beams from the coal miners'
head lamps are visible in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   That group of 12 miners is wrestling with a roaring grinding
machine that works its way like an iron mole along the seam. It
gouges chunks of sparkling coal from the wall and spews the shards
onto a conveyor.
</P>
<P>
   All the earth would have to do is shrug, and the lives of 206
Russian miners on the day shift would be extinguished. Yet the
miners consider themselves lucky to have jobs, even though they are
owed wages dating from September.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started paying us again, because now is the time of
election fever, but we will see what happens after the election,''
said Stanislov Gribonov, who has worked underground here for 20 of
his 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   The coal miners are one of the country's most identifiable labor
groups, and because their labor is essential to life itself in the
Russian winter, they played a crucial role in the political
struggles that attended the demise of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   And with their strikes and marches on Moscow, they enlivened the
election campaigns when Boris Yeltsin fought the powerful tide of
labor discontent over his economic reforms. The miners were
especially motivated because wages, pensions and social benefits
were often the first victims of privatizing industries.
</P>
<P>
   As Russians prepare to go to the polls this weekend to elect
Yeltsin's successor, the miners here, 600 miles south of Moscow,
find themselves, like many Russians, trying to decide whether to
support the front-runner, Vladimir Putin, the acting president, or
to cast a protest vote for one of the other 10 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin gives us hope,'' Gennady Zhikharev, 36, said. ``He gives
us hope that he can finish the war in Chechnya, that he can raise
up the economy. At least he has shown us he can do something in
Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are also anger and disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in power have cheated us a lot, and Putin is just
continuing in the tradition of Yeltsin,'' Gribonov said, as he and
fellow miners took a break from grinding coal to talk with a
visitor this week. As Gribonov spoke, he shifted on the kneepads
that the miners wear as they scramble on all fours in the cramped
tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Zyuganov,'' Gribonov said about the Communist Party
leader, Gennady Zyuganov, ``because what is important to me is that
me and my two daughters will be healthy and that they will have a
chance to grow up and get into a good institute and have a good
life.''
</P>
<P>
   In this mining center there is plenty to be angry about. The
coal industry has been ravaged by economic collapse. The wage
arrears here are among the worst in the country, and working
conditions make it seem heroic each time these miners don their
helmets and sling their battery backs and respirators on their
belts for another descent into the warren of tunnels 1,200 feet
below ground.
</P>
<P>
   On the road from Rostov-on-Don to Shakhty, beyond a landscape of
barren wheat fields, slag piles rise like low mountains in a line
that follows the coal seam deep underground. Half the 26 mines
operated by Rostovugol, the former state coal combine, have closed,
and the work force has declined, from 100,000 to 28,000. Production
dropped from a peak of 20 million tons a year in the 1980s to fewer
than 5 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   State subsidies for investment in new equipment have largely
disappeared, forcing the mines to barter with both suppliers and
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Today the company receives hard currency for only one-third of
its sales. The rest is barter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am voting for Zyuganov,'' Valery Klimovich, 32, said. ``It
was 100 times better under the communists, because we could travel
about our country almost for free and we could take our vacations
at the sea at any resort.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Orlov, 48, agreed, saying, ``For simple workers, life
under the communists was better, more stable, and we lived
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Sakhabiyev said he was voting for Vladimir Zhirinovsky,
the hard-line nationalist who talks of setting up a police state
and bringing back the KGB. ``He says the right things,'' Sakhabiyev
said. ``He would use the iron fist.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Klimovich's view, the economy is like a tree and the roots
are the mines. His metaphor resembled the catechism of the
state-planned economy.
</P>
<P>
   After he had described the leaves of the tree as factories and
their fruits as products, he explained that in the Yeltsin era the
roots have withered for lack of money. He said the government was
``severing the roots while pouring water on the leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   The miners expressed little faith or understanding of the market
economy and questioned whether such a system would be able to
deliver the modest prosperity that they enjoyed in times past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really understood this market economy,'' Gribonov
said, ``unless it is just a means to degrade the country's
resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
