<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-EXAMINER-NEWSPAPE     03-24 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-EXAMINER-NEWSPAPER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THE OLD MATH MAY NOT APPLY IN SAN FRANCISCO 
FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Until last week, it seemed likely that The San
Francisco Examiner would be an orphan of the information age.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. no longer had any use for The Examiner, its
first property and onetime flagship, once the company bought the
paper's thriving rival, The San Francisco Chronicle, for $660
million last year. Dwindling circulation, red ink and potential
antitrust concerns more or less forced Hearst to sell, and The
Examiner had been on the block since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, there should have been a host of bidders salivating
over such a well-known if struggling title serving a city full of
the wealthy, well-educated readers whom advertisers covet.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the city is awash in venture capital, no small
amount of it pouring into new-media ventures meant to reach that
very audience. And major newspaper chains like Knight Ridder own
papers in suburbs and nearby cities that might fit well with The
Examiner, whose readership is concentrated in San Francisco proper.
</P>
<P>
   Yet The Examiner was shunned like a silver dollar in the middle
of Market Street traffic. Several of the big newspaper companies
looked at its books, but none were among the final bidders. To get
The Examiner off its hands, Hearst agreed to pay expenses _ as much
as $16 million this year and $25 million in 2001 and 2002,
according to court filings _ to Ted Fang, whose family publishes 12
free local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner's near-death experience illuminates the kinds of
risks that newspaper companies are willing _ and unwilling _ to
take today. Knight Ridder, Tribune, The New York Times, Belo and
McClatchy have recently tolerated losses of $8 million to $20
million a year on Internet ventures with unproven business models,
according to company filings and presentations to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Moroney, president of Belo Interactive, and Ross Jones,
chief financial officer of Knight Ridder, say that building Web
sites is a research-and-development cost. ``People are increasingly
going to be going to the Internet for a local content experience,''
Moroney said. ``We need to be there.'' For Jones, The Examiner, cut
off from the joint operating agreement, is ``not a complete
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something between a newspaper and a start-up,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   These companies have all bought newspapers in metropolitan
markets in the last six years, but all passed on The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Does his willingness to go where they feared to tread make Fang
a visionary, or a fool? In some measure, he is whistling past ``the
graveyard full of mastheads,'' as the newspaper analyst John Morton
put it. Local business interests bought, but could not sustain, the
Cleveland Press (it closed its doors in 1982) and the St. Louis
Globe-Democrat (it folded in 1985).
</P>
<P>
   Judging by circulation figures, the odds this time are just as
steep: The Examiner sells an average of 107,100 copies daily, less
than one-quarter of The Chronicle's 457,000. ``I am aware of the
pressure of history on this project,'' Fang said last week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What made The Examiner so unappealing to the industry giants
with the experience and resources to better the odds? Morton offers
the old newspaper math as an answer.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest costs of producing a daily are labor and
newsprint. Publishing The Examiner at roughly its current size,
110,000 copies of 70 broadsheet pages, six days a week, would
consume some $20 million in paper annually at today's newsprint
prices. Even at half the size, it would take $12 million of paper,
Morton estimated.
</P>
<P>
   As for labor, by the industry rule of thumb of one journalist
for each 1,000 copies sold, the paper's newsroom needs 100 people,
half the size of the current staff. To get and keep them, a new
owner must pay enough to overcome the region's high cost of living
and compete with new media fishing in the same talent pool, like
Salon.com, Quokka Sports, The Industry Standard or Marketwatch.com.
With salary and benefits, figure $75,000 to $100,000 a head, or
$7.5 million to $10 million annually, Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are computers to buy, presses to run, trucks to drive. In
those areas, a buyer's existing resources can help hold down costs.
Still, several million dollars a year would be needed, Morton
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and the cost of getting out the paper starts at $25
million a year _ the maximum size of the Hearst subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, The Chronicle and The Examiner have combined their
circulation and advertising departments in a joint operating
agreement and split the income, which, after they paid their
newsrooms, could be taken as profit. It is unclear how The Examiner
can independently match that income, estimated at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising brings in 75 percent to 80 percent of revenue at
most newspapers. But high-margin classified ad volume has come
under pressure in recent years from Internet competitors like
Monster.com. And how many display advertisers will want to sell
their wares through the smaller of two general-interest
metropolitan dailies?
</P>
<P>
   Neither is there much room to increase circulation revenue. The
San Francisco Bay area, with 5.4 million people, is home to 19
daily newspapers, many of which dominate their chosen slices of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Given these cloudy prospects, some critics say Hearst's deal
with Fang is a sham, meant to stave off antitrust action by the
Justice Department while limiting Hearst's costs and shielding The
Chronicle from serious competition.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the old math may not apply. ``I am one of those
weirdos who happen to believe that if The Examiner is spun off it
has a chance,'' said Tim Redmond, executive editor of The Bay
Guardian, an alternative newspaper that has railed editorially for
three decades against the joint operating agreement. ``I'd make it
a tabloid, focus tightly on the city, create flashy front pages,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pan Asia Venture Capital, the Fang family company, has a history
of buying failing local newspapers and reviving them by cutting
costs and emphasizing community news. ``It took the local touch my
family brought to these newspapers to make them work,'' Fang said.
</P>
<P>
   Dailies are not weeklies, of course. Still, The Examiner need
not go toe to toe with The Chronicle to survive as a daily, judging
by the experience of the The Palo Alto Daily News, which lives
profitably in the shadow of The San Jose Mercury News by giving
away 26,500 copies and keeping its operations lean _ just 30
employees in all.
</P>
<P>
   Or Fang could find a deep-pockets patron that would subsidize a
newspaper that reflects its views, as the Unification Church does
with The Washington Times. Fang's father, John, came to San
Francisco from Taiwan to be editor of The Young China Daily, backed
by Chiang Kai-Shek's Nationalist Party. He later struck out on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   The family's alternative weeklies, known for fiercely partisan
coverage, have been credited with tipping tight city elections
toward candidates they favored.
</P>
<P>
   But Fang rejects the mouthpiece model for The Examiner. ``I
don't want to be funded by someone with an agenda,'' he said. And
he said he had no plans to convert to free distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to think outside of the box, but we intend to run
The Examiner as a paid, subscriber-based morning newspaper,'' he
said, seizing a chance that none of the giant chains was willing to
take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      03-24 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, EARNEST STUDENT AND NATURAL TEACHER, WITH A SWEET TOOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE-EXCERPTS) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACOMB, Mich. _ Vice President Al Gore was sitting around with a
group of students when Sally Hannert, the drama teacher, plucked
him out to participate in a theatrical exercise. A look of mild
panic froze his face, but he gamely plunged in.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Stephanie White, 12, were to play a father and daughter
discussing her bad report card. But they could not use words, just
gibberish, while another student, Rachel Burke, 11, had to guess
the plot through their gestures and tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``NNNNAAAARRRRVOOOO,'' the vice president said. Rachel
interpreted the indistinct slur of vowels and choked consonants as
the plight of a girl afraid of being attacked by a bear. Still, she
perceived Gore as a benevolent figure and decided what he was
saying was this: ``Everything will be OK. I'll take care of it. I'm
the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie rated him later as clueless, but a great success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't know what was going on,'' she told a reporter. ``But
it was really fun to play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   From the drama class to a discussion on the Industrial
Revolution to the cafeteria, where he wolfed down two slices of
pepperoni pizza, two chocolate chip cookies and half a brownie, the
vice president delved into suburban school life Friday, showing
himself off as dutiful student and natural pedagogue _ and, his
campaign hoped, as being in touch with ordinary Americans and more
concerned about education than his Republican rival, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In the first ``school days'' of his campaign _ he promises one
every couple of weeks and pledges to continue them if he is elected
president _ Gore is using the novelty of a presidential candidate's
spending an entire day in school to draw attention to his
commitment to education.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Pew survey, voters said that Bush cared more about
this vital issue than did Gore. But Gore aides believe that as Gore
and his proposals become better known, he will catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can demonstrate to you during the course of this
campaign that I have the perspective and heart to do the job,'' the
vice president told a group of students, teachers and parents in
the course of his day, which ran from a 7:45 a.m. hallway chat with
school custodians to a 2 p.m. rally in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   The site was not random. The school, L'Anse Creuse Middle School
North, sits smack in Macomb County, a landmark bellwether electoral
district northeast of Detroit where Reagan Democrats first emerged
and were then coaxed back to the Democratic fold by Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Voters here _ many of them white, Roman Catholic, blue-collar
and socially conservative _ represent one of Gore's greatest
challenges. They voted for Sen. John McCain of Arizona in the
Republican primary this year and are being wooed by Bush, whose
father won them over in 1988 and 1992. Gore needs to keep them and
sought his way to their hearts Friday through their children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore uttered nary a word about the Bush family Friday, trying to
focus instead on the concerns especially of suburban mothers here,
from stopping school violence to nurturing their inner selves. He
emphasized the importance of parental involvement and used the day
as he used his town meetings in the primary season _ to convey that
he is not a scripted politician but a real person, and a sensitive
one at that.
</P>
<P>
   In a soft-focus, FM-radio voice, he told students at every
opportunity to be focused and disciplined, as if sharing a campaign
secret from his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be true to yourself, be honest, keep a good sense of what's
important in your life, set priorities and if it is important
enough for you to reach a goal, you can reach a goal,'' he said in
response to a student who asked him how to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The day was given over also to small revelations about the vice
president, who, many people here said, once seemed cold and remote
but now seemed like one of them.
</P>
<P>
   His day began after a sleepover on Thursday night at the home of
a teacher, Claudia Amboyer, 52, and her husband, Donald, a former
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Amboyer fed the vice president chocolate cake
(``Don't most men like chocolate cake?'' she asked later) and on
Friday morning cooked him scrambled eggs and bacon. She told him
that she sold antiques and was interested to hear that Gore's
father had also sold antiques. She described the experience as
``wonderful and unnerving,'' telling reporters that she did not see
any Secret Service agents but that a Winnebago mysteriously arrived
in her driveway and stayed the night.
</P>
<P>
   She and the vice president rode to school together Friday
morning in a cavalcade of suburban vans. Gore helped guide a civics
discussion that moved from the Industrial Revolution to global
warming to child labor laws. The parents of some students work in
the auto industry, but as Gore questioned the students, he found
few who were interested in doing work like their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Their aspirations, they told him as he toured a
technical-education room, were different: veterinarian, lawyer,
marine biologist. One girl said she wanted to be an author, to
which Gore responded: ``You must be a good writer. Do you know
Annie Proulx? Get a book called `Shipping News' and look at the way
she writes.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, he wanted his listeners to know that he came as a
student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned in my work setting up the reinventing-government
program,'' he said, ``that the most important insights and lessons
by far actually come from the people who are doing the hands-on
work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
