<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7364 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     03-24 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG OUTING IMPROVES ROSE'S SHOT AT STARTING ROTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The battle for the fifth starting spot in the
Red Sox' rotation continues to rage.
</P>
<P>
   Friday it was Brian Rose's turn. The big righthander registered
4 1/3 innings of one-run ball in a 7-1 victory over the Texas
Rangers. Rose gave up five hits and walked three, but pitched out
of trouble and remains in contention with Juan Pena and Bryce
Florie for the job. Of the three hurlers, only Florie would be kept
as a reliever, which means it's doubtful both Rose and Pena will
start the season with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Rose has started five spring games, giving up four earned runs
in 14 1/3 innings (2.52 ERA). Pena has a 1.32 ERA in five
appearances covering 13 2/3 innings. The Sox have options left on
both pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as though I'm getting a little stronger,'' said Rose.
``One more start and spring's over. Everyone would like to know,
but I've got to go out with the same frame of mind. I feel like I
pitched well this spring. I feel as though I put myself in position
to help the team out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible another starter could get hurt or the Sox could
put veteran lefthander Jeff Fassero in the bullpen (manager Jimy
Williams says Tim Wakefield is in the starting rotation), but
barring either scenario, Rose or Pena appears bound for the minors
after a good spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're two young arms and they were both on the shelf last
year,'' said the manager. ``You never have enough pitching, but we
can only take 25 and both of them are still in the hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are still at a whopping 39 players and will leave for
Arizona next Thursday. Williams said the fourth and fifth starters
would stay behind when the team goes to Phoenix for the final two
exhibition games before opening the season in Seattle. He said the
Sox might take five extra players to Arizona and make final cuts
there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frye shagging flies
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Frye played left and right field and made a nice catch of a
Frank Catalanotto fly in the second inning. The dugout greeted Frye
with a standing ovation and several ``We're not worthy'' bows. Frye
appears to be in a battle with Donnie Sadler, who plays some
outfield. Frye wasn't particularly happy with the assignment and
said, ``It's not my favorite spot, but it's a spot. I felt all
right. But it's boring out there. It's way too boring.'' Frye had
two hits, as did Jose Offerman . . . The Sox pounded six hits in
scoring five runs in the third inning. Nomar Garciaparra, Mike
Stanley, Darren Lewis, and John Valentin all doubled in the inning
. . . Carl Everett had his second outfield assist when he threw out
Rangers leadoff man Royce Clayton going for a double in the first .
. . John Valentin has a nasty bruise on his left biceps, courtesy
of a Ramiro Mendoza pitch Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gaetti makes impression
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gaetti started at first base and played six innings. He
rejected any speculation that he'd retire even if the Sox decide to
keep him. ``The knee is sore, but it's coming around,'' he said.
Gaetti fielded everything cleanly and looked good making throws to
second base. Clearly, he's a Williams favorite . . . Lewis stole
his seventh base . . . Another day off for Marty Cordova (ribs).
He's not scheduled to go to Clearwater, Fla., with the team
Saturday for its game with Philadelphia. He hit live batting
practice Friday and is scheduled to do so again Saturday. Rod Beck
has a stiff neck and did not pitch. ``He's day-to-day,'' said
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. Williams said Beck underwent an MRI .
. . Pedro Martinez is scheduled to pitch against the Phillies and
wants to throw 70-75 pitches . . . Former outfielder Jim Eisenreich
is a scout with the Kansas City Royals and has seen the Sox three
times this week, but he says there's nothing afoot on the trade
front. ... There's a grass-roots campaign afoot to change the zip
code of Hernando, Fla., home of Ted Williams. The Hernando zip is
34442. Williams's lifetime batting average was .34441 and that zip
is unassigned. Sounds like a job for the postmaster general.
Williams used to weigh his bats at the post office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
