<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-FIRE-BOS-1ST-LEDE-WRITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY AVERTED IN BOSTON COLLEGE DORM FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 THROUGH  
 (Eds:   Restores dropped time element in lede.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ A fast-moving fire in a Boston College dormitory
early Friday sent students fleeing to the roof and banging on their
windows for help.
</P>
<P>
   Six students and two security officers were sent to city
hospitals for treatment for smoke inhalation. None of the injuries
was considered life-threatening, and five of the eight were
released Friday. The other three were expected to be released
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   What could have been a tragedy became instead a frightening
lesson in fire's deadly potential. Fire, smoke, and heat alarms
worked in the Cardinal Medeiros dormitory for freshmen; Newton
firefighters responded almost immediately, and rescue was prompt
for about a half-dozen students trapped either on the roof or in
their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God was good to B.C.,'' college spokesman Jack Dunn
said as he gazed at the charred north wing of the three-story
dormitory. The wing houses 37 students, all of whom have been
displaced by the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze has been traced to a faulty plug strip in a
third-floor room, according to State Fire Marshal Stephen Coan and
B.C. officials. The plug strips are widely used by students on
college campuses, channeling power for computers, printers, CD
players and other appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said the 37 students are expected to be able to return to
their rooms within two weeks. In the meantime, they have been taken
in by other students who volunteered to house them until repairs
are completed.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said damage was ``significant'' but he could not provide a
cost estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's fire, however, will not soon be forgotten by the
freshmen in the Medeiros dormitory's C wing, one of three wings in
a townhouse-style complex at Hammond and Tudor streets.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Breaux, a 19-year-old freshman from Lafayette, La., said
he figured the fire alarm at 5:17 a.m. signaled ``just another
drill.'' But then he hustled outside and saw wisps of smoke, then
flames, coming from the adjoining C wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a few minutes, I saw people at their windows, trapped,''
Breaux said. ``They were banging on their screens; they might as
well have been in a jail cell. One kid said he couldn't see his
door from his window, and that's only about 10 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters lifted ladders to those windows as well as to two
students who had fled to the sharply pitched dormitory roof, and
rescued everybody. One student, who suffered neck burns, was
discovered unconscious in his room by firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said everyone in the dorm had been accounted for by 5:40
a.m. ``The issue wasn't getting students out, but the fast-moving
action of the fire,'' which had heat that reached 1,100 degrees,
Dunn said. The evacuation proceeded without panic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Jan. 19 dormitory fire at Seton Hall University in East
Orange, N.J., where three students were killed and 58 were injured,
prompted Boston College to re-evaluate its fire precautions, Dunn
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
