<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-RAY-PROFILE-ART-2TAKE     03-24 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAY-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT RAY: STARR'S SUCCESSOR COULD BE EVEN MORE OF A MATCH FOR
CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT36 was sent March 23 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr's replacement, the man with the power
to prosecute the president after he leaves office _ and,
potentially, to affect the outcome of a close U.S. Senate race in
New York _ goes about his business here in almost perfect
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've been noticed yet,'' says Robert Ray, the
39-year-old career prosecutor who took over as independent counsel
last October and appeared on national television for the first time
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Every evening, he commutes to his parents' house in the Virginia
suburbs, where he has been bunking back in his old room for the
last five years. On weekends, he takes the train home to his wife
and three children in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   While Starr used to receive boxes of letters _ several thousand
every week _ Ray typically gets just three or four, and answers
them himself. But though America has moved on, Ray is just getting
started. And it is Starr's unfamous, unassuming junior successor
who not only seems to understand the politics of prosecution in a
way Starr never did, but also shows signs that he could become a
more even match for the president than the widely reviled Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office this week, Ray did not come off as
particularly zealous. ``Somebody has to do this,'' he said when
first asked about his job. He also said, ``It's time to bring this
to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point he left the impression that he might like to run
for political office himself someday, a rather remarkable
suggestion from someone in his position and surely a hopeful sign
for the Clintons. After Starr's experience, one would not have to
be a Princeton history major, as Ray was, to conclude that
indicting Bill Clinton might not be a launching pad to a career in
public service.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ray, the eldest son of a former Carmelite nun, Peggy, and a
retired Army colonel, Robert, also spoke of his work as a duty, a
reason to make certain personal sacrifices and as a service to his
country with a seriousness that might just as reasonably give
President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, goose bumps. And the new
independent counsel made absolutely clear that he had in no way
ruled out prosecuting the president after he left office, in
connection with the same issues that led to his impeachment last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process has to be vindicated,'' Ray said, adding that he
means by that that ``no person is above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That issue has been raised since the beginning of the
Republic,'' he said, ``such as during the Civil War over whether
Lincoln acted over and above the law in suspending habeas corpus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose President Nixon had decided he didn't have to deliver
the tapes,'' he said. ``There's a basic question about whether the
criminal justice system will be allowed to work, and principles
don't get protected in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, like much of what Ray said in the interview, might or
might not be taken to mean that he intends to go beyond what even
Starr apparently thought appropriate. Starr reportedly did not
believe that the president, having been impeached, should be
prosecuted after leaving office, and it is Ray who has reopened the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he released the first of three final reports on
various investigations involving the Clintons that have gone on for
more than five years and cost upwards of $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having cleared the Clinton White House of any illegality in
the improper acquisition of some 900 FBI files, Ray continues to
oversee investigations into two more matters involving Clinton: the
Arkansas land deals known as Whitewater and accusations of abuse of
power in the firing of some longtime employees of the White House
travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on these issues are due this summer. Both also involve
Mrs. Clinton, as she campaigns for the Senate against New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York. It was Giuliani, as U.S.
attorney in Manhattan, who gave Ray his first real job, as a
federal prosecutor, though Giuliani left the office before Ray ever
went to work.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Ray spoke of justice in the almost 90-minute
interview, he also mentioned fairness, and he seemed to take a
swipe at his predecessor when he said, ``We all know what the
consequences are of the improper use of power.''
</P>
<P>
   But he would not say directly what he thought of the job Starr
had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not really for me to say,'' Ray said. ``That's for
history.''
</P>
<P>
   And though he has signaled that he had learned from Starr's
mistakes, especially in public relations, he does seem to have
adopted Starr's determination to flout public opinion as he sees
fit.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Ray not only began expanding an office that most
people thought was already packing up, but also plucked one of his
two new staff members from the politically charged committee run by
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., one of Clinton's most aggressive critics.
</P>
<P>
   Does Ray care how that looks? ``Sure, those things are
factors,'' he said, ``but it's more important for me to have people
with experience with the issues I'm dealing with, and I don't think
it's a bad thing to have people with some political experience.''
</P>
<P>
   When he feels overwhelmed by the size of his responsibilities,
Ray said, he finds it helpful to think of his father's experience
in Vietnam, where he served two tours of duty and nearly died after
his plane crashed into a mountainside.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of service to it,'' he said, ``that affects
me today. And I always think, `Don't panic; It's nothing like
combat. Relax.'''
</P>
<P>
   Physically compact, temperamentally careful and very earnest,
Ray comes across a little like the boy every mother in the parish
secretly hoped her daughter would grow up and marry.
</P>
<P>
   He spent six years putting away drug dealers and organized crime
figures as a federal prosecutor in New York, and had a reputation
for toughness. A couple of times, judges dressed him down for what
they considered cowboy tactics in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Ray did not become a prosecutor because he enjoyed the thrill of
legal research. ``I wanted to try cases; I love the excitement of a
trial, I love being before a jury,'' he said, becoming much more
animated at the mere thought of courtroom action.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Again, though, he tempered that remark by following it with a
comment about how much he liked to finish one case and move on to
the next. ``The task you're given has a beginning, a middle and an
end. That's my attention span,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His politics are also hard to pin down. He made two
unsuccessful, nonpartisan runs for the local school board in
Brooklyn, in 1993 and 1996, as an opponent of the ``Rainbow
Curriculum,'' best known for its connection to the book ``Heather
Has Two Mommies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a child in second grade that was going to be exposed to
material I didn't feel was appropriate,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Though his side lost that battle at the ballot box, he said his
concerns were later taken into account. ``It's funny how life works
out,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his involvement in the board battle with the
``children's slate,'' a group generally aligned with social
conservatives, Ray was a registered Democrat until recently. Now he
is an independent, he says, because ``appearances count.''
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton, to which he had applied in emulation of his
boyhood role model, Bill Bradley, he wrote an admiring senior
thesis on John F. Kennedy and the Peace Corps. In a recent article
in an alumni publication, one of Ray's college roommates remembered
him as a ``Kennedy-worshiping liberal Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray speaks with great pride about his grandmother, Rose Ray,
whom he describes as a local Democratic Party leader _ ``kind of a
power broker''_ in Brooklyn in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   And asked if he saw himself running for office again at some
point, he smiled and did not say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I better stay out of that for now,'' he replied. ``I
thought it was a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani interviewed Ray and hired him 1989, he says
Giuliani's race with Mrs. Clinton has nothing to do with him. But
as he also said: ``You can pretend you live in a political vacuum,
but life is not that way. Pretending things don't exist is not good
judgment. Nobody said this was going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray was born in Frankfurt, West Germany, where his father was
stationed, and his father's military career took him away from home
for years at a time. Ray's wife, Kristen, comes from a military
family, too. And Ray said that was the way they saw his service in
Washington _ where he thought he was assigned temporarily five
years ago, when he came here to handle trial work for Donald C.
Smaltz, the special prosecutor investigating Mike Espy, Clinton's
first secretary of agriculture, who was acquitted on all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Every Friday night, Ray takes a three-hour train ride back to
New Jersey, where the family moved from Brooklyn two years ago, and
spends Saturday shuttling his children, ages 10, 12 and 14, to ball
practice and the Boy Scouts while his wife, who works retail six
days a week, is selling glassware.
</P>
<P>
   (The only positive in this arrangement, he says, is that he has
time to catch up on his reading, though his favorite writer now is
still the same today as when he was in high school, John
Steinbeck.)
</P>
<P>
   Showing less ego than may be common among big-deal prosecutors,
Ray told how he and his future wife first got together, when both
were students at Jefferson High School in Alexandria, Va.: ``She
made me a cake for my birthday when I was a junior, and the rest is
history. Her great line was, `Would you like a cake?' I said, Yes
and put it in my locker. My mother said, `You idiot! What did she
give you with the cake?' I said, `Oh, two forks. I guess she wanted
to have some with me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though sources in his office have indicated that they hope to
issue the two outstanding reports on the Clintons by this fall and
announce whether to indict the president as soon as possible after
he leaves office, Ray says he sees himself ``working in some
cubbyhole long after the public part of this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems confident that both he and the Republic will survive
the final chapter of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are people worried about me?'' he asked. ``Yeah. Am I worried
about myself? Sure. But it's important we get it right, and that's
why I'm here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
