<HEADER>
A7380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      03-24 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: NEW PROTESTS BY TEACHERS
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of teachers marched through Paris to demand
higher spending on education and to demand the resignation of
Education Minister Claude Allegre. Similar demonstrations took
place in Marseille, Toulouse and Toulon. The protests, which closed
most public schools for a day last week, has added to pressure on
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to shake up his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: AGENT ACCUSED OF TREASON
</P>
<P>
   Officials said an agent of its domestic Federal Security
Service, arrested last week on charges of passing political
information and names of Russian agents to Britain, had been
charged with high treason. The unidentified agent was arrested as
he left for Estonia, whose own officials, the Russians charged, had
joined Britain in recruiting the spy. The British declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MI5 SLIPUP
</P>
<P>
   The police revealed that a laptop computer with confidential
information about Northern Ireland was stolen from an officer of
the MI5 secret service on March 4 when he put it on the platform of
a London subway station momentarily to help passers-by. The police
asserted there was no threat to national security because the
information was heavily encrypted, and there was no evidence the
thief knew the machine belonged to MI5.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PRESSURE ON PARKS
</P>
<P>
   Visits to Canada's national parks are forecast to double in 15
years to 28 million, according to a new government study. Faced
with growing pressure by tourists, Sheila Copps, the minister
responsible for the country's 39 national parks, vowed ``no new ski
hills, no new golf courses'' and proposed limits on fishing,
hiking, camping and snowmobiling in the most popular parks. Copps
has fought to limit development in Banff National Park, crown jewel
of the 115-year-old system.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: CLERIC WARNS REFORMERS
</P>
<P>
   A prominent member of the conservative Muslim clergy warned
reformers who won a landslide victory in February elections not to
try to ease Islamic social taboos. ``It is not like the new
deputies can pass any laws they like,'' Ayatollah Mohammed Yazdi
said in a sermon at Tehran University. ``The young people who you
think voted for you have no right to demand laws to allow them to
dance in the streets, or the annulment of any Islamic mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: POLICE STILL DEFIANT
</P>
<P>
   The police continued to defy a court order requiring them to
remove black squatters who have invaded hundreds of white farms.
The police said they needed specific instructions from the
government before moving against the squatters, who are led by
veterans of Zimbabwe's war of independence from Britain. President
Robert Mugabe has spoken out in support of the squatters.
</P>
</TEXT>
