<HEADLINE>
SHORT ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Hoop, but Net Is Crucial For This Tournament Champ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA crowns its basketball champion next week, but the
powers that be in venture capital have pronounced the University of
California at Irvine the victor in a business-plan competition
among college and graduate school entrepreneurs, a competition
worth $5 million to the winning company.
</P>
<P>
   In a contest it called February Madness, executives of Hummer
Winblad Venture Partners, including a founding partner, Ann
Winblad, compared business plans from 64 schools, then took
meetings with the ``Sweet 16.'' Their investment went to
MyDrugRep.com.
</P>
<P>
   Quang X. Pham, the company's founder, intends to use the
Internet to make drug marketing more efficient. Instead of having
representatives go door to door trying to meet with harried
doctors, he plans to offer a Web site where doctors can learn about
new and existing drugs, order samples, and read sales information.
The Web site will make commissions on the drug sales it generates.
``This replaces the whole sales channel over time,'' Winblad said.
``It'll be a bits-driven business versus a knock-on-the-door
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Knocking on doctors' doors is something Pham knows about as a
former representative of Genentech and Merck. Pham, 35, left
Genentech last year to attend the executive MBA program at the
University of California at Irvine Graduate School of Management.
</P>
<P>
   Winblad predicted that in this tournament, there would in a
sense be 5 or 10 winners, all likely to eventually receive
financing from venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   _Matt Richtel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the Future of Mice and Music &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strauss Zelnick, chief executive of BMG Entertainment, came to
Silicon Alley recently to boast that his business had nothing to
fear from the World Wide Web. His speech, ``How a Major Music
Company is Aggressively Embracing the Net and Expects to Win the
Digital Wars,'' came amid reports that the Napster software was
making free downloads of music easier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   As a book collector, Zelnick explained, he would not want just a
photocopy of a classic. He is confident that his customers will
feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   By Christmas, paying customers will be able to download music at
www.bmg.com, he told the New York InfoTech Forum. ``This revolution
is a good thing for BMG music,'' he said. ``It's wrongheaded to
characterize the Internet as a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of students, meanwhile, are voting against him, with
their mice. Geoff C. Gardner, a physics major at Purdue University,
has used Napster to install more than 500 songs on his computer,
and hasn't bought a CD in more than five months, saving hundreds of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick's response? ``There is no question that Napster is a
wholesale copyright violation, pure and simple. It can't be
allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   But if that's the law, how to enforce it? ``It's like
jaywalking,'' Gardner said. ``Everybody does it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Julie Dunn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Software as a Lifesaver &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rus, a marketing executive for Autodesk Inc. in San Rafael,
Calif., gets a thrill refining his company's mapping software for
clients whose needs range from checking utility lines after
earthquakes to tracking elk migration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really cool stuff,'' he said. Even cooler is that because
of his serendipitous affiliation with Roots for Peace, a group of
California vintners working to remove land mines, Rus is also
refining the software into a humanitarian tool.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Croatian minesweepers are using the donated software
to pinpoint mines in the town of Dragalic, in a field that children
traverse as a shortcut to school. United Nations officials, whom
Rus met in Croatia in January, believe that the software can speed
up land-mine removal there and in other countries. More than 1,000
people in Croatia have been killed or maimed by mines since
hostilities ceased in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _Andrea Adelson
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
