<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HEPBURN-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      03-24 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPBURN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT AUDREY, NOT EVEN CLOSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Mon., March 27; ``today'' refers to that date.) 
(Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1{ stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should Jennifer Love Hewitt's phenomenal career turn out to be
enduring, in the distant future she'll refer, with the appropriate
desultory chuckle, to this past year as ``a learning experience.''
Among the lessons: Don't believe it when your small circle of
sycophants insists that you're a one-woman entertainment industry.
Don't leave a successful show for a spin-off with no discernible
idea propelling it (e.g., the tank job ``Time of Your Life''), even
if you're offered an executive producer's credit. And never, ever
believe you can play a beloved pop-culture icon just because you
think she's kinda cool.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other lessons _ among them, if you're trying
an accent, hire a competent dialect coach _ but they're hardly
worth wading through, pretty much like Hewitt's latest project, the
arduously protracted telebiopic ``The Audrey Hepburn Story.'' It's
not as godawful as early rumors suggested, but it sure could've
done with an editor capable of shaving an hour out of this
three-hour leviathan.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt assumes the title role (as well as a co-executive
producer's credit _ warning!), one in which she is thoroughly
miscast. Hepburn carried herself with legendarily elegant feline
grace, never showing the slightest hint of perspiration even when
doing broad comedy (though she was plenty skittish off-camera);
Hewitt skitters about like a frantic puppy who'd be adorable if it
would just !ital!quit hopping up and down in your face.
</P>
<P>
   Hepburn had luminous, saucer-like eyes; one of Hewitt's more
charming moves is scrunching her eyes up so that they're tiny but
gleaming _ when she goes for the wide-eyed effect, she looks as
though she's picking up radio waves from distant worlds; to depict
cool refinement, the actress simply goes blank.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt plays this young woman born into aristocracy about as
you'd expect from someone who recorded a pop song titled ``Let's Go
Bang'' in her midteens. The filmmakers' way of coping with the fact
that Hewitt and Hepburn don't exactly appear separated at birth is
to cast the roles of Gregory Peck, Humphrey Bogart and William
Holden with performers who don't look remotely like their
characters, either.
</P>
<P>
   The film's hackneyed framing sequence begins on the set of
``Breakfast at Tiffany's,'' only because the filmmakers must've
decided that's the one Hepburn film everyone has heard of. Truman
Capote (imagine Philip Seymour Hoffman imitating Jerry Lewis) is on
the set sniffing at her abilities, and though everyone else, of
course, is utterly charmed, Hepburn decides she must win over
Capote, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cut, at random, to cheering fans, which inspires a series of
flashbacks to her past life, for no other reason except that's how
these movies work. Heaven forbid that Hepburn would've been
concentrating on her !ital!work on the set of a film that earned
her an Oscar nomination, so obviously she has plenty of time for
lurid navel-gazing _ heck, she even has time to remember a
flashback within the context of another flashback.
</P>
<P>
   Her father was a Nazi sympathizer, but she herself is part of
the resistance movement in Holland (though her first question as
German tanks rumble down her street is a pouty, ``What about my
ballet lessons?''). Pop abandons the family, leaving mom (Frances
Fisher) to fend for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually comes the numbingly dull, peripatetic trek through
Hepburn's career and a fairly sanitized depiction of her personal
life. Men say such things as, ``It is useless for you to try not to
be seen _ you are too beautiful'' and ``Audiences love her _ so do
I.'' As her husband Mel Ferrer, Eric McCormack (Will on ``Will &AMP;
Grace'') is the one actor around who handles his role without
looking utterly at sea. The one vaguely alarming moment in her
career _ she's thrown from a horse while shooting a film _ is
depicted here merely as a radio news item, but there's a long
play-dress-up sequence.
</P>
<P>
   For a three-hour movie, a heck of a lot is omitted.
Thoughtfully, her Oscar win (for ``Roman Holiday'') is mentioned,
but her other four nominations are ignored, as is her Tony win. The
last 30 years of her life, when Hepburn had the bad taste to grow
old and, therefore, not of interest to Hewitt's fans or ABC's
target demographic, are dismissed with a couple of title cards. Her
years of work for UNICEF _ in which she was often plunged into
danger (which, memo to the filmmakers, is a good thing when making
a drama) in Third World countries _ is similarly, and shockingly,
shrugged off. On the upside, we're spared the spectacle of Hewitt
in old-age makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and obviously, by film's end, Hepburn indeed wins over
Capote. The viewing audience _ well, that likely will be another
story. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The show: ``The Audrey Hepburn Story.'' &QL; 
What: Hollywood biopic. &QL; 
The stars: Jennifer Love Hewitt, Frances Fisher, Eric McCormack. &QL; 
Where: ABC (Channel 7). &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
