<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NY     03-24 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STEPHEN KING'S WEEK OF TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK RICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Al Jolson in blackface in ``The Jazz Singer'' to
persuade America that talking pictures were no passing fad. It took
Uncle Miltie in drag for the TV set to usurp radio in the nation's
living rooms. Is Stephen King's ``Riding the Bullet,'' the first
hit book distributed exclusively through the Internet, speeding the
end of the Gutenberg age and the dawn of a fully digitalized
cultural world?
</P>
<P>
   Even before the King e-book was so much as announced, Microsoft
had bet on the death of paper. In lavish ads heralding its new
``book-like'' device, Microsoft Reader, it touts ``the best
estimates of Microsoft researchers and developers'' about the
post-print future: E-books will start outselling printed books in
2009; newspapers will abandon paper editions in 2018; Webster's
will alter its first definition of ``book'' to refer to writing
read on a screen by 2020. Jack Romanos, the CEO of Simon &AMP;
Schuster, King's publisher, likens the fallout of ``Riding the
Bullet'' to the invention of the paperback in the 1930s. ``What
shocks me,'' he says, ``is the number of people who are willing to
read for entertainment on screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine's cover take on the King phenomenon this week sees
an even broader canvas for e-culture: the Net is becoming a
``global talent show'' in which any amateur novelist, musician or
filmmaker can take to the Internet to ``get discovered and attain
stardom.'' Were this actually true, it's a prescription either for
the greatest democratization of the arts in history (Time's view)
or a dumbing down that may make the advent of public-access cable
TV look in retrospect like the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   In my informal sampling of futuristic prognostication, only Lyn
Blake of Amazon.com, a key player in her company's free
distribution of ``Riding the Bullet,'' tried to bring this latest
wave of Net hype back down to non-virtual earth, saying that she
sees no end in sight for the printed book. But Blake does note that
even Amazon, the shrewdest of Web retailers, completely
underestimated the demand for King's novella, with the result that
its famously prompt customer service record was blighted by a rare
snafu.
</P>
<P>
   If Amazon can't unfailingly read the Internet's future _ at
least as far as books are concerned _ why should anyone else try?
Maybe it's easier to take a pass and conclude that ``Riding the
Bullet'' is just a one-week wonder proving merely that people will
always clamor for a brand-name product that is (largely) given
away, especially if the book that must be read on screen is a scant
66 pages. After all, only eight months ago another brief (if not
brief enough) ghost story, ``The Blair Witch Project,'' was alleged
to revolutionize the movie biz, triggering an avalanche of hit
independent movies that would be promoted like wildfire by Internet
buzz. There hasn't been a repeat occurrence since.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if you look at ``Riding the Bullet'' in the context of all
the other sweeping changes in the cultural marketplace just since
New Year's, the future doesn't seem that foggy at all. The
prognosticators writing the ad copy at Microsoft, painful as it is
to concede, may be right. If books aren't abandoning their analog
containers for digital ones, they're about the only mainstream
media product that is not.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, facing an aging readership, not to mention the Net's
potential theft of their best brains and classified ad profits, are
running to the Web as fast as stockholders can carry them. In the
past couple of months, the country's top dailies have almost all
been leapfrogging onto an accelerated Internet track. The
multimedia-crazed Chicago Tribune is swallowing up the once
impregnable old-media lion The Los Angeles Times. The New York
Times has switched to continuous news on its Web site and is trying
a joint Webcast with ABC News. Donald Graham, publisher of The
Washington Post, has relinquished day-to-day operation of his paper
in part to focus on Internet strategy. In magazine publishing,
recent print issues of e-centered titles like Red Herring, Fast
Co., Business 2.0 and The Industry Standard have rivaled or
exceeded the daunting 470-page heft of Vanity Fair's Hollywood
issue. Even Harper's Bazaar, a magazine without a Web site, is
reduced to making up for lost Internet time by doing a ``wired''
print issue it hopes will pass for ``young.''
</P>
<P>
   A still speedier, and more revealing, indicator of the rapid
migration of mass media to the Web can be found in music. At
Christmas, few had heard of Napster, a free software program
invented by a 19-year-old college dropout that allows anyone with a
PC to trade music over the Internet (in easy-to-download MP3 files)
with every other Napster user at no cost. But as any parent of
teen-agers now knows, Napster has proliferated like a virus _ so
rapidly that kids are swapping entire CD collections on line and
overloading university computer networks, much as orders for
``Riding the Bullet'' crashed Net booksellers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported this week that Indiana
University (among many others) had to ban Napster upon discovering
that within weeks of catching on it was generating 60 percent of
all electronic traffic between the campus and the Internet. Alec
Foege, a People magazine writer who is doing a book on the
phenomenon, says that by summer panicked record labels will be
selling downloadable music directly on the Web, hoping to co-opt
Napster rather than merely pray that copyright litigation might
stamp out the wholesale pirating of their wares. Movie studios may
eventually have to bow as well: illegally bootlegged Hollywood
features are already circulating in the hackers' underground and
would be ubiquitous were gargantuan video digital files not too
cumbersome for all but the fastest Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the culture of Napster pertinent to the future of
print is not just the velocity of its acceptance but the ease with
which its enthusiasts have broken their supposedly entrenched
listening habits, ditching CD's for a less tangible medium. It's
one thing if teen-agers abandon newspapers, not a strong habit
among the young to start with, for Web news sources. But weren't
teen-agers said to be as enamored of the CD as an object as they
were of its music?
</P>
<P>
   Now it turns out they can do very well without the packaging,
cover art and liner notes. Writing in the online magazine Feed,
Julian Dibbell, a former rock critic, describes how easy it was to
overcome years of CD fetishism to embrace instead the same
collection in the form of a ``weightless, borderless cloud of
data'' residing on his computer's hard disk. Wouldn't it be as easy
to abandon the physical object of the book if it can be recast in a
weightless vehicle that is handier and more visually commodious
than the current, early e-books, which make reading even the
relatively short ``Riding the Bullet'' such an eye-straining chore?
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Kirshbaum, who runs trade publishing at Time Warner,
says that the book business faces an aging audience just as
newspapers do, and, like newspapers, must hunt down new customers
wherever it can. ``To get the kids and get the readers of the
future, we've got to go to the space they're in,'' he says, and
that space could be any number of non-paper venues _ not just
e-books, Palm Pilots or computer screens but video game consoles,
now frequented by young audiences more than movie theaters, let
alone libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave those of us who still love bindings, crisp
paper and dust jackets? Books will not go the way of eight-track
tapes as long as there are still people around who were raised on
them. That's a large market to be serviced and one that still
includes many, if not most, current teen-agers. But as the
cybernovelist Bruce Sterling put it while speaking at this month's
South by Southwest Interactive Festival in Austin, Texas, a
3-year-old child today finds the computer ``as banal as a fork or
running water.'' Such a child may well grow up on pixels, not
paper, and by the time he or she enters junior high school and
starts consuming books in large volume, it will be 2009 _ the very
year, according to the seers at Microsoft, that electronic books
will overtake print as the reading medium of choice.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that such a kid will read Stephen King to the
exclusion of Dickens. The child who grows up with the Internet may
well imbibe a more heterogeneous cultural mix than my generation,
the often-passive patsies of three look-alike TV networks. Either
way, what is certain is that sentimental sermons by us old print
fogies aren't going to turn back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
