<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CASE OF SLIPPING STANDARDS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ There were terrible losses and impressive
victories. There was an NCAA investigation and an academic
suspension. The coaches were vilified and glorified. The players
were awesome and awful, dominant and dormant, sometimes from one
minute to the next. There was a February funk and a March charge.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was one of the strangest UCLA seasons in memory, and for
that reason it was not strange at all.
</P>
<P>
   Under fourth-year coach Steve Lavin _ but not always because of
him _ the Bruins have turned tumult into routine. They are
consistently chaotic. Names and events change, but turmoil
persists. Some years,it's drug-related suspensions. Some years,
it's injuries. Some years, it's NCAA violations.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it was the fall-quarter academic suspension of Matt
Barnes and the 24-game NCAA suspension of JaRon Rush. It was the
29-point loss at Arizona State and the overtime victory at
Stanford. It was six losses in seven games followed by an
eight-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But remove the names and events, and the bottom line is a UCLA
team with four high school All-Americans and several future pros
won 21 games, lost 12, finished fourth in the Pac-10 and reached
the Sweet 16 of the NCAA Tournament. That is not cause for alarm;
nor is it cause for celebration. It's very, very . . . solid.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the Bruins spin it _ and there's nothing they do
better than spin _ it's nothing more than solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Lavin said he was proud of us and I'm proud of us,
too,'' junior forward and co-captain Rico Hines said. ``Everybody
counted us out. Nobody thought we'd make the Sweet 16. Everyone
thought we'd be in the NIT. We pulled together when we could have
thrown in the towel.''
</P>
<P>
   All true, or course. But what the Bruins fail to mention is that
everything good about the season was rooted in something bad.
</P>
<P>
   They were thrilled with their late-season turnaround, but they
shouldn't have been in that position (13-11 after the Arizona
roadtrip) in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   They were pleased with the intensity and efficiency of their
practices in the final month, but the workouts should have been
like that all along. It was as if they were shamed into practicing
better.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin called this his most rewarding season and mentioned
several memorable victories: North Carolina, Purdue, USC, Stanford
and Maryland. But those look good only when compared to
embarrassing losses to Colorado State, Washington, Oregon, USC and
Arizona State. And since when does a home victory over USC qualify
as significant? Either the standards are declining or the
competition's closing, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin also was pleased with the late-season development of
center Dan Gadzuric and point guard Earl Watson, and rightly so.
But neither player should have been as confused or ineffective as
he was early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Even their demise was self-inflicted. A day after the 80-56 loss
to Iowa State in the Sweet 16, Watson and Lavin talked about being
emotionally drained. ``We played the NCAA Tournament two times,''
Lavin said. ``To get in the NCAA Tournament, we had to win six
consecutive, Russian-roulette games.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that predicament: six losses in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   School officials believe Rush's suspension cost UCLA victories
over Colorado State, Washington and Cal. But the Bruins didn't need
Rush to beat Washington. They simply needed better fundamentals,
better judgment, better preparation and better execution. If Lavin
had run January practices with the urgency and efficiency he ran
March practices, the Bruins would have coasted into the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches and players are aware of what we have to do
starting Oct. 15,'' Watson said. ``We'll just start where we left
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for UCLA fans is the last month showed the
coaching staff is capable. The bad news is it took until the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   What does the future hold? It looks a lot like the present.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lavin took over in 1997, the win total has steadily
declined: 24, 24, 22, 21. The Pac-10 win total has dropped: 15, 12,
12, 10. Pac-10 placement has plummeted, as well: first, third,
third, fourth.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to panic. The Bruins will continue to recruit
talented players and provide reasonably good coaching. They will
play a difficult schedule and send players to the NBA. They will
win 18-22 games a year, challenge for an occasional Pac-10 title
and make the Sweet 16 every few years.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the coaching staff improves dramatically _ or changes
are made _ the Bruins will not average 25 wins a year like Arizona
and Kentucky and Duke and Kansas. They will not win the Pac-10
title every two or three seasons, and they will not be a consistent
Final Four threat.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, the Bruins have become wholly consistent. They
are consistently good, with a flash of greatness here and a dash of
ineptitude there.
</P>
<P>
   The question the coaches and administration must answer is this:
Is consistently good good enough?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
