<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7397 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-ART-2TA     03-24 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY OF TROOPS FINDS ANTIGAY BIAS COMMON IN SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anti-gay attitudes and harassment are commonplace
in the U.S. military, especially in the form of offensive remarks
and gestures, and an overwhelming majority of service members
believe their superiors and colleagues tolerate it ``to some
extent,'' according to a Pentagon survey released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, ordered after a gay soldier was beaten to death last
July at Fort Campbell, Ky., suggested that despite repeated efforts
to prohibit such behavior, including new directives by the four
armed services late last year, disparaging and even hostile
attitudes toward gay men and women remain a pervasive part of
military culture.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of service members questioned by the Pentagon's
inspector general reported hearing anti-gay remarks during the last
year, and 33 percent said they heard them often or very often.
</P>
<P>
   Even more troubling to Pentagon officials, 37 percent said they
had witnessed or experienced some form of harassment based on
sexual orientation in the last year. Often the harassment involved
offensive remarks or gestures, but in more than half of those
cases, service members said they had witnessed or experienced that
harassment in the form of graffiti, vandalism, threats, unfair
discipline, discrimination in training or career opportunities or
even physical assaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report shows that military leaders must do more to make it
clear that harassment based on sexual orientation violates military
values,'' Secretary of Defense William Cohen wrote in a memorandum
sent to the civilian and military leaders of the services Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators surveyed a random sampling of 71,570 officers and
enlisted personnel at 38 military bases and aboard 11 warships and
submarines in the United States and overseas. The survey did not
question people at Fort Campbell, where Pfc. Barry Winchell was
bludgeoned to death last July with a baseball bat. The Army's
inspector general is conducting a separate investigation into why
commanders there ignored reports that soldiers had openly taunted
Winchell about his presumed sexual orientation for months.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's findings surprised many senior officials at the
Pentagon, who had publicly played down the extent of harassment
only a few months ago. Scrambling to respond, Cohen appointed a
committee of civilian and military officials to review the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen ordered the committee, which will be headed by the under
secretary of the Air Force, Carol DiBattiste, to report back to him
by the end of July with plans for dealing with what the Pentagon's
spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, acknowledged was ``a disturbing
amount'' of harassment in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's findings have focused new attention on the Clinton
administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, which Congress
put into law in 1993 after a fierce political battle. The policy
allows gay men and women to serve in the military as long as they
keep their sexual orientation to themselves and do not engage in
homosexual acts, but still bars openly gay people from serving in
uniform. Although meant to make it easier for gays to serve,
thousands have been discharged in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are also sure to intensify the political debate
over homosexuality and the military, which Vice President Al Gore
has already made an issue in this year's presidential campaign by
vowing to allow gay men and women to serve openly. Gov. George W.
Bush, his Republican opponent, has expressed support for the
existing policy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's national security adviser, Leon S. Fuerth, said this week
that society's views had evolved and that gay men and women now
deserved the chance to serve their country openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a posture that makes it impossible for very good
people to serve without living in fear that something private about
themselves will be divulged and held against them,'' Fuerth said in
an interview with reporters. ``In our society that is changing, and
our military has always been a reflection of the society as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, in his memo Friday, said it was impossible to say whether
the survey's findings reflected larger social attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rush, the deputy under secretary of defense for planning,
who announced the survey at the Pentagon Friday, cited the finding
that 80 percent of service members reported hearing anti-gay
remarks in the last year and added: ``There is nothing out there
that we have seen that says how often would you hear such jokes or
names, or other types of offensive speech, in the broader civilian
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Cohen said that harassment ``seriously undermines
the good order and discipline that is critical to an effective
fighting force.'' And the survey suggested that good order and
discipline were under assault in units around the country and in
all the services.
</P>
<P>
   While 80 percent reported hearing ``offensive comments'' about
gays, even more _ 85 percent _ believed that the comments were
tolerated within their units.
</P>
<P>
   Even in more serious incidents, the survey's findings suggested
that anti-gay behavior appeared to be widely accepted, despite the
Pentagon's most recent directives, which explicitly prohibited
harassment based on sexual orientation, just as policy now
prohibits harassment based on race or gender.
</P>
<P>
   Of all respondents, 5 percent believed that harassment based on
sexual orientation was tolerated by superiors in the chain of
command and 10 percent said it was tolerated by colleagues in their
unit.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe in detail one incident of harassment, 22
percent said that a more senior person had also witnessed the
behavior, and in 73 percent of those cases, they said that person
did nothing immediately to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The findings varied by service. In the Marine Corps, for
example, more than 45 percent of those questioned reported hearing
offensive comments often or very often, compared to only 23 percent
in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Rush attributed the differences to differences in age, education
and training within the services. Marines, generally, tend to be
younger and less educated than personnel in the Air Force, which
requires greater technical expertise. Also, lower-ranking enlisted
personnel were far more likely to hear or witness anti-gay
attitudes than officers.
</P>
<P>
   While Pentagon officials expressed disappointment in the
findings and said more worked needed to be done, a spokesman for
the Marine Corps, Maj. David A. Lapan, played down the results. He
cited the finding that only 5 percent of those questioned believed
that harassment was tolerated by superiors and said the Marine
Corps had not experienced an increase in complaints of harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not necessarily concerned with the results,'' Lapan
said, ``because we're not seeing indicators like increased
complaints of threats or mistreatment that would indicate the
policy is not working.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rush and other officials pointed to one positive finding: About
78 percent of those questioned said they felt free to report
anti-gay harassment to their superiors without fear of retribution,
while 22 percent did not feel free to do so.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the survey found that of those who
said they had seen or experienced harassment within the last year,
only 16 percent actually did report it to a superior.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for gay men and women in the military seized on the
findings as validation of what they had been saying for years.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Smith, a spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign, the
largest gay political organization in Washington, said the findings
showed that repeated directives issued by the Pentagon had failed
to stop harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to change until the uniformed military
leadership, from the Joint Chiefs of Staff on down, send clear and
unambiguous signals that this type of harassment will not be
tolerated under any circumstances,'' he said. ``To date, we have
not heard those messages from the uniformed military leadership.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, a
legal-aid organization based in Washington, reported that anti-gay
harassment had more than doubled last year. The group reported 968
incidents of verbal abuse or physical assaults. The group also
reported that 1,034 gay men and women were discharged because of
their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osborne, one of the group's executive directors, said
the findings released Friday were a direct result of the inherent
inequities in the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a law that treats an entire class of people as
second-class citizens,'' he said, ``it suggests that you can treat
them that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
