<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7411 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLO-OWENS-RAMSEY-ART     03-24 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-OWENS-RAMSEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO GOVERNOR CUTS HIS TEETH ON JONBENET MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He pushed hard for gun control measures, which failed,
and for educational reforms, which passed. But when Colorado's
legislative session has ended, the lasting impression of Gov. Bill
Owens, a first-term Republican, could be of a battle he fought
outside the House and Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons not entirely clear, Owens has injected himself into
the murder investigation of JonBenet Ramsey, the 6-year-old girl
who was found beaten and strangled in the basement of her home in
Boulder more than three years ago. While Boulder investigators
placed the girl's parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, under an
``umbrella of suspicion'' early on, Owens has made it clear that he
believed that the police were looking in the right direction to
solve the murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference last October, he said the Ramseys should
stop hiding behind lawyers and advisers and return to Colorado from
their home in Atlanta to answer questions. The Ramseys, contending
an intruder killed their child, responded in their new book, ``The
Death of Innocence,'' criticizing Owens as acting on political
impulse alone.
</P>
<P>
   Owens shot back this week, repeating his call for the Ramseys to
face investigators and telling ABC's ``Good Morning America'' that
``the focus on this case is really on Patsy Ramsey.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else involved with the case has come so close publicly to
naming a possible suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have been talking about it,'' state Sen.
Michael F. Feeley, a Democrat who is minority leader, said of
Owens' sparring with the Ramseys. ``It has been the subject of a
lot of discussion around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his appearance on ``Good Morning America,'' Owens has
declined to discuss the matter. His spokesman, Dick Wadhams, said
the governor challenged the Ramseys in October because his youngest
child, Brett, was born the same year as JonBenet, ``and as a father
of three kids, he felt very strongly that from day one the Ramseys
did nothing to cooperate with the authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys waited four months after the killing to meet with
investigators for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The governor only returned to the subject of the Ramseys,
Wadhams said, because they devoted two pages of their book to
criticize him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some in Colorado said Owens' comments about the Ramseys
reflected more political concerns than parental ones.
</P>
<P>
   Owens was presiding, after all, in a state where the worst
school shootings in American history happened last year. In the 11
months since 15 people died at Columbine High School, virtually
nothing has changed in Colorado. Almost all of Owens' gun control
initiatives, including requirements for background checks at gun
shows and a safe-storage law for guns kept in the home, died in the
Legislature at the hands of his own party, which controls both
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, statewide polls were showing that
most Colorado residents favored tighter gun control measures,
leading one group to begin a campaign to have the gun-show measure
turned into a ballot initiative in November. Owens said he would
support it.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was a planned strategy or not, taking on the Ramseys
gave the governor a new _ and nonideological _ chance to flex
Colorado's criminal justice muscles even though a grand jury
completed 13 months of work last fall without indicting anyone in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first said those thing about the Ramseys,'' Feeley
said, ``my first reaction was, How dare you? But I've changed my
thinking. He has met with investigators and prosecutors in the
case, and I believe he has been told that there is an awful lot of
evidence pointing to the Ramseys, but there are also holes to
create reasonable doubt. As a result, he is going after them the
only way he can, through the court of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeley added: ``I believe he has read the public correctly on
this. After I blasted him for injecting himself in this the first
time, calls to my office ran against me 9 to 1. He had a pretty
good feel of this. I think it's been a political plus for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Hero, a professor of political science at the University
of Colorado, said Owens' willingness to express his views about the
Ramseys also provided ``a kind of easy national visibility, at the
same time raising some issues that are bothersome to many
Coloradans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any political downside to it,'' Hero said. ``This
was a major crime. This is his way of saying we here in Colorado
have a sense of justice and what's happened so far is an offense to
our state and city.''
</P>
<P>
   While Owens has relinquished the floor on the Ramseys, his views
seemed likely to gain momentum soon.
</P>
<P>
   In a book to be released next month, ``JonBenet: Inside the
Ramsey Murder Investigation,'' Steve Thomas, a former Boulder
detective assigned to the case, has laid out his version of events,
rejecting the intruder theory and asserting that the Ramseys knew
more about what happened than they told police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Owens is aware of a lot of the behind-the-scenes
issues in this case,'' Thomas said in an interview. ``I think he
shares our frustrations over the propaganda from the Ramseys, and
he has been offering some bottom-line comments, making it clear
that their version of events does not stand alone as the last word.
I happen to agree with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
