<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GOES TO BUSH COUNTRY TO RAISE CASH FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vice President Al Gore cannot count on Texas for
electoral votes in November, but he can still bank on it for
Democratic money.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was to attend a reception and dinner Friday
night in Houston that would raise more than $600,000 for the
Democratic National Committee, capping a week of fund raising in
Washington, Cincinnati and Detroit expected to raise an additional
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has called for an overhaul of campaign finance laws
and challenged Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, to mutually halt the raising of
large, unregulated donations of ``soft money,'' has shown no signs
of letting up his own prodigious fund raising. Gore is helping the
Democratic Party to raise $35 million in soft money during the next
few months to finance a spate of television commercials intended to
highlight the party's differences with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's back yard may seem an unusual place for Gore to raise
money, given the governor's popularity here and his strong ties to
the state's business community and to wealthy donors who make soft
money donations. But last year, in Dallas, Gore raised about
$500,000 during a reception and luncheon at the Fairmont Hotel as
part of a swing through Texas that raised $1 million for his
campaign, said Jess Hay, a Dallas businessman and longtime Gore
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   This is Gore's first money-raising trip to Texas for the
Democratic committee this year; he made none last year, party
officials said. President Clinton has raised $1.5 million for the
party in Texas over that time, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can raise that kind of money by going into a
guy's home state against him, that's kind of unusual,'' said Ben
Barnes, a former Democratic lieutenant governor of Texas who is now
a lobbyist and is involved in technology venture capital projects
in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush, noting that both events
were being held at the homes of lawyers, said, ``Al Gore is an
obstacle to meaningful lawsuit reform because he's beholden to
powerful personal-injury trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Houston event for Gore, according to officials at the
Gore campaign and the Democratic National Committee, was to be a
$1,000-a-person reception at the home of Denman Heard, a Houston
lawyer. Later, at a dinner held at the home of Lee Godfrey, a
prominent litigator who has previously played host at similar
events, 33 people expected to donate $15,000 each were to dine on
crabmeat parfait, quail stuffed with squash, and pecan pie.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is then to return to Washington, plans to make remarks
at both functions. Attendees were expected to include Steve Susman,
one of Godfrey's law partners; F. Kenneth Bailey Jr., a prominent
Houston plaintiff's lawyer; Garry Mauro, a former Democratic land
commissioner of Texas, and Edward G. Rendell, the former mayor of
Philadelphia who is now general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
