<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-ROUND20325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Psyched Sutton in TPC control
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton started the week leading
the PGA Tour in psychology, insisting that to praise Tiger Woods
unnecessarily is to be defeated on the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six holes later, Sutton is still leading The Players
Championship at 6-under-par 138, by one shot over non-winner Omar
Uresti and Tom Lehman, and Sutton is still beating Woods.
</P>
<P>
   On the treacherous TPC at Sawgrass, which is getting firmer and
faster after two days of drying wind, that's no easy mission. Proud
of his patience during Friday's round, when he made a 12-foot putt
for bogey at the 18th hole after driving into the water, Sutton
said, ``The only person I can control is myself and I'm out of
control half the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Uresti, one of several players in contention who could gain a
potential last spot in the Masters _ not to mention $1,080,000 with
a victory _ regrouped for a second-round 68 after a potentially
disastrous start. Finishing two holes from Thursday's first round,
Uresti hit a ball in the water at the par-3 island 17th, reloaded
and made a 4-foot putt for a bogey. He took just 23 putts in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, it happens,'' he said, pondering the weekend.
``I'm only 31... so I feel like I've quite a few years left.''
</P>
<P>
   South African Fulton Allem, known for his opinions and a hatred
of slow play, shot the low round of the tournament, a 7-under 65,
after an opening 75 and is two shots back at 140.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who double-bogeyed No. 4, birdied the par-5 ninth to
finish a second consecutive 71. He's tied for fifth at 2-under 142,
along with Len Mattiace and Ernie Els, four behind Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything under par is good,'' Woods said. ``It's becoming
quite a challenge out there. I'm very pleased with my position. I'm
in the hunt with a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion David Duval is at 4-over 148, 10 shots back
after a 73 that included a triple-bogey on the par-3 eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, who won here in 1983, said course conditions have the
potential to go ``over the edge'' as they did last year, when shots
would not hold on baked greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times out there right now where we're switching from
offense to defense,'' he said. ``You've got to be smart enough to
know when to hit the accelerator and when to hit the brake.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
