<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN: MOISO, RUSH MIGHT GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ UCLA coach Steve Lavin acknowledged Friday
that sophomore forwards Jerome Moiso and JaRon Rush might turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those would be the two, for different reasons,'' Lavin said.
``Over the next couple weeks, they'll have to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush must make restitution on the $6,525 he took from a sports
agent and his former AAU coach that resulted in NCAA violations and
a 24-game suspension. He also has legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso has first-round talent and might creep into the lottery.
Scouts question his toughness but love his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the position, because of his size and ability, to make
the jump,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible personnel change involves reserve forward Matt
Barnes, who said Thursday that he's considering playing football
and joining the basketball team late. He was a gifted receiver in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be real surprised,'' Lavin said. ``That's always something
he has entertained. It's in his mind because he loves football. But
he knows he came here to play basketball and that's his future. I
don't think he wants to do anything that would set him back from
the pack. If he plays football, he'll be playing catch-up the rest
of the (basketball) season.''
</P>
<P>
   __ They're welcomed back: The only staff changes will come if
one of the assistants (Michael Holton, Jim Saia and Steve Spencer)
gets a head-coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin has no plans to replace anyone on his much-maligned staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people have forgotten is the first year . . . they hired
us with the understanding that we were a young staff that would
grow with the program,'' Lavin said. ``(Firing someone) is not a
very good model for loyalty, it kills your continuity and it sends
an odd message when you have that level of success and you're
rolling heads. The worst is when you lose in the first round and
roll heads. That's shifting the blame (from the head coach).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a critical part of the success we've had, with three
Sweet 16's in the last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Help arriving? The Bruins signed one recruit in November,
power forward T.J. Cummings from the Chicago suburbs, and they
could have used him against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough kid in terms of blocking shots, playing hard,''
Lavin said. ``He's a blue-collar Midwestern kid. His strengths
early in his career will be defense and rebounding. As he develops,
he'll be more like his dad. He'll be an offensive threat, as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings' father is longtime NBA veteran Terry Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Add recruiting: The Bruins are not recruiting a point guard
to join the team next season. Earl Watson, who will be a senior,
played extremely well in the final month, and the Bruins believe
Ryan Bailey is a capable backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way our kids finished out the season, there's not a point
guard in the country that could come in as a freshman and leapfrog
over Earl and (Bailey),'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ The lineup: The Bruins will need all the talent they can
muster. Most of the talent returns for Stanford, Arizona, Cal,
Arizona State and USC, and the Bruins' nonconference schedule is
brutal.
</P>
<P>
   They open in the Coaches vs. Cancer tournament, a four-team,
two-game event with St. John's, Kansas and Kentucky. They play
Georgia Tech in the Wooden Classic. They visit DePaul and Purdue
and host North Carolina and Villanova. They also play Hawaii, Cal
State Northridge, UC Irvine and UC Santa Barbara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
