<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CHINESE-RESTAURANTS-$ADV26-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL CHINESE FOOD GO THE WAY OF PIZZA?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOEL M. KOTKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ It is a long way from any kind of Chinatown
to the Fashion Square Mall in this upscale Phoenix suburb. But to
Richard L. Federico, the usually-packed flagship restaurant in the
P.F. Chang's China Bistro chain, nestled close to Nordstrom's and
convenient to the multiplex, is more representative of Chinese
food's future than are the tens of thousands of mom-and-pop Chinese
restaurants that pepper the Main Streets of America.
</P>
<P>
   If he is correct, mass marketing, Wall Street financing and
professional management will finally have broken through in what
has long been a chain-resistant segment of the retail economy. Like
independent department stores, local burger joints and dozens of
other entrepreneurial businesses, the independent ethnic restaurant
may soon find itself, if not headed for extinction, well on the way
to marginalization.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Chinese food has been one of the last redoubts.
Donna Gabaccia, a historian at the University of North Carolina who
examined the mainstreaming of ethnic food in her 1998 book, ``We
Are What We Eat,'' said Chinese food presents unique obstacles to
mass marketing compared with, say, Italian or Mexican cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Individually owned Chinese restaurants were among the first to
offer fast orders, takeout and delivery, she noted, leaving little
room for a franchise fast-food approach to take hold, as it did in
hamburgers, chicken, pizza, tacos and other categories. And the
complexity of Chinese food preparation, whose tools and techniques
have little in common with European cuisine, makes it less
susceptible to standardization.
</P>
<P>
   Federico, president and chief executive of P.F. Chang, dismisses
those concerns. ``In this business, the attitude was that there was
a Chinese restaurant on every corner, and the idea was you could
not penetrate the Chinese segment,'' he said. ``But they said the
same thing about Italian 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Professionally managed companies made inroads long ago into
other ethnic food categories, with mass chains like Chili's
(Mexican and Tex-Mex, 637 restaurants) and Olive Garden (Italian,
464). In many suburban and Sun Belt communities, chains like these
often became the standard-bearers for their categories, sometimes
by default. Their success told Paul M. Fleming, founder of P.F.
Chang and now a consultant to the chain, that ``authentic'' roots
were far from a prerequisite for success in ethnic food.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, 45, had a background in chain restaurants, notably as
owner and operator of several Ruth's Chris Steak House locations.
On a business trip to Los Angeles, he once enjoyed a meal at the
swank Mandarin Restaurant in Beverly Hills, but afterward could not
find similar quality food in Phoenix, his hometown. He got in touch
with Phillip Chiang, owner of the Mandarin, in 1992 and asked him
to lend some culinary expertise to a new chain.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming started with Chiang's recipes and ingredient-buying
instructions, but he made some adjustments that he hoped would
enhance the food's appeal to a more mainstream market. He
concentrated on the most familiar menu selections, lowered the oil
content a bit and aimed to hold prices to an average bill of $17 a
person.
</P>
<P>
   He also developed an extended wine list, unusual in Chinese
restaurants, and chose a sleek modern decor that avoided Chinese
cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming believed that starting in a suburban mall rather than in
a cosmopolitan urban setting would be a better way to test the
concept for an eventual national rollout. ``Phoenix may not be a
recognized center for Chinese cooking,'' Fleming said, ``but it is
a good barometer for the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1993 with a name that melds Fleming's initials and a
version of Chiang's surname that Middle America could readily spell
and pronounce, P.F. Chang's took off, and soon expanded to Southern
California, the Boston area and to Westbury, N.Y., on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are now 39 open nationwide and 13 in development. In 1996,
with the chain growing and more managerial expertise needed,
Fleming brought in Federico, 46, a veteran of the Bennigan's and
Macaroni Grill chains of Brinker International, to run the
operation with a new chief financial officer, Robert T. Vivian.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming remains on the board, and Chiang continues as a
consultant and minor shareholder. The new executives took the
company public in December 1998 at $12 a share; the stock closed on
Friday at $32.75.
</P>
<P>
   As Gabaccia might have predicted, the toughest challenge in
expansion was transmitting cooking expertise to new chefs and staff
members, especially because the chain had no intention of
restricting itself to places where native Chinese workers could be
recruited.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility for maintaining chainwide food quality falls
on P.F. Chang's executive chef, Paul M. Muller, a German-American
native of Oakdale, N.Y., with experience in the kitchens of the
distinctly non-Asian Waldorf Astoria Hotel in Manhattan and the Old
Ebbit Grill in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Having been schooled in Chinese cuisine under Chiang's
direction, Muller puts new chefs through six to eight months of
training before giving them restaurants to run.
</P>
<P>
   Only 8 of the 39 head chefs at P.F. Chang's restaurants are
Asian. ``The skills can be taught to gwei-lo's for sure,'' Muller
said, using a Cantonese slang expression for Caucasians. ``It just
takes a different mentality and a kind of passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the chain approach say the mentality and passion are
not so easily cloned, just as knowing how to daub paint doesn't
make someone a pointillist. Theresa Lin, a of Chinese-food critic
and a restaurateur based in Los Angeles, said P.F. Chang's and
ventures like the New York-based China Grill could compete
effectively only where mainstream diners have not been exposed to
the work of native Chinese chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of businesses are good at marketing, but when the
mainstream people discover the real authentic food, they will go
for it,'' said Lin, who was born in Taiwan and now owns three
upscale restaurants in Las Vegas, Miami and Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Federico concedes that at the luxury end of the spectrum, Lin
may well be right. P.F. Chang's may never be the first choice of
sophisticated diners who enjoy sampling Chinese fare in meccas like
Manhattan, San Francisco, the Flushing neighborhood of Queens or
the San Gabriel Valley east of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But as his chain expands across the country, Federico said he
believes the great majority of consumers will come to think of the
food at places like P.F. Chang's, not the traditional, mom-and-pop
eateries, as setting the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, for a lot of people of my kids' generation,''
he said, gazing out at the crowd in the Scottsdale dining room,
``this will be the real definition of a Chinese restaurant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
