<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA GRAHAM BOARD SEEKS TO REMOVE DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The board of the Martha Graham Dance Company voted
7-5 on Thursday to remove Ron Protas, Graham's heir and handpicked
successor, as artistic director of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Protas was groomed by Graham to direct the troupe after her
death in 1991. Graham also left him her ballets. The company has
received good reviews in recent years for performances in New York
and internationally. But the fund-raising difficulties of Graham's
last years continued under Protas' direction.
</P>
<P>
   Protas agreed two years ago to step down as director in June
2000, when Janet Eilber, a former Graham star, was to join the
troupe as artistic director with his agreement. It appears that the
sudden board vote may have been precipitated by Protas' unexpected
reluctance in early March to accept Eilber as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the succession agreement, Protas became the director
of the Martha Graham Trust, which he set up to license the Graham
dances. Michael Quinn, the lawyer who represents Protas and the
trust, suggested Friday that it might be difficult for Protas to be
removed as artistic director of the company, given that he owns the
copyrights to the dances.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Nederlander, chairwoman of the 22-member board, which
is based in New York, was not present at the meeting and did not
return a request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Mason, a board member since 1973, who voted to remove
Protas, said Friday: ``I believe Ron is responsible for Martha
getting her work together so that by the end of her life everything
was poised for the future. But I'm afraid the time has come. Our
hope is to work out with him and his attorney the best next way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Preston, executive director of the company, said Friday
that the troupe ``would proceed at this time to operate without an
artistic director.''
</P>
<P>
   Eilber, who has served as artistic director designate for the
last two years, withdrew in February after the board failed to
raise money for her salary this year. When a board member proposed
a plan, at a meeting in early March, to raise the funds, Protas
said that he disagreed with some of Eilber's plans and felt that
the appointment had been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Eilber, who lives in Los Angeles, said Friday that she would
have to remain there with her family for another year. In a letter
to the board dated Feb. 22, she offered to continue working long
distance as principal artistic adviser with Christine Dakin and
Terese Capucilli, two current lead Graham dancers who are associate
artistic directors in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is the end,'' Quinn said Friday. ``Whether
or not the board had the power to do this as a board, Ron holds all
the copyrights in the dances and the rights in the use of Martha
Graham's name as a trademark. As the owner of the Martha Graham
trademark and copyrights, he not only has the right but the duty
under the law to oversee the quality of the company and its
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Protas has agreed to allow the company, now on a national tour,
to continue performing the dances through April 29, when the tour
ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
