<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRISTOL-POLE0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park wins pole with record run
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _Six drivers bettered the qualifying-lap record
at Bristol Motor Speedway Friday, but no one could outrun Steve
Park's No. 1 Chevrolet all day.
</P>
<P>
   Park had the fastest car in two practice sessions, then backed
it up by taking the pole for Sunday's Food City 500. He dashed
around the half-mile concrete track in 15.184 seconds or 126.370
mph.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first pole of Park's three-year Winston Cup career and
the first for his car owner, Dale Earnhardt, who qualified 11th,
just ahead of the other car in the Earnhardt garage, the No. 8 of
son Dale Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Park was rewarded by a congratulatory chat and a rare
wide grin from his intimidating boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hard guy to please at times,'' Park said of Earnhardt.
``Sometimes if you get just half a smile from him you know you're
doing good. If you do something wrong, you're usually out on the
farm on a tractor, bailing hay with him in the hot sun.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't be bailing together this week, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a proud father, really,'' Park said. ``This is his
first Winston Cup pole. He's put a lot of time, effort and money
into developing this team, not only for myself but for his son.
He's seen it grow from a grass field to what it is today. The first
pole for DEI (Dale Earnhardt Inc.) is something that I'll always
remember and he'll always remember.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that he's going to start out front, Park is prepared to
have his boss running hard behind him. Last year, in a
controversial move, Earnhardt bumped Terry Labonte from behind on
the last lap, knocking Labonte out of control and winning the fall
race here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to run fast enough to keep him behind me on
that last lap,'' Park said. ``I'll be expecting a bump and maybe be
on the defensive. I think Terry thought he was going to get away
from him last year and Dale's a fighter, he doesn't give up.
</P>
<P>
   It was expected that Rusty Wallace's qualifying lap record of
15.333 seconds set last year would be obliterated after several
drivers broke the record testing earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace qualified sixth at 15.328 seconds (125.183 mph). His
brother, Kenny, took the outside pole in 15.242 seconds although he
slightly damaged the right rear of the No. 55 Chevy when he brushed
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon qualified third and Mike Skinner was fourth as Chevy
took the first four spots.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton, fifth, was the top qualifying Pontiac and Rusty
Wallace had the top Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
