<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MASS-ROBINSON-ART-NYT     03-24 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-ROBINSON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BY CONFESSION IN BID FOR KENNEDY'S SENATE SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT36 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Put yourself in the shoes of Jack E. Robinson III.
</P>
<P>
   Faster than you can say your own name, your fledgling campaign
for Edward M. Kennedy's U.S. Senate seat has been clobbered by
embarrassing accusations that you are sure came from the senator's
camp: a rush of stories about your driving record, your legal
history and, most mortifying of all, your love life.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference to announce your candidacy, you find
yourself forced to declare: ``I am not a womanizer. I am not a
groper.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how tempting it would be to fight back by dragging up
the scandals that roiled your opponent's past.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in an interview at the elegant home office that is so
far his campaign's only place of operations aside from its Web
site, www.robinson2000.com, Robinson suggested, ``Perhaps, the
senator should issue `The Kennedy Report' to tell us exactly what
happened at Chappaquiddick.''
</P>
<P>
   In that highly unlikely event, the report would be the second
confessional exercise of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a 39-year-old businessman, sixth-generation Republican
and first-time candidate, has already posted ``The Robinson
Report'' on his campaign Web site. Perhaps the most notable effort
at a pre-emptive political strike of the Internet era, it lists and
explains every incident in his life that he thought might be fodder
for attacks.
</P>
<P>
   It includes an ex-girlfriend's restraining order against him,
which was dropped, he writes, because he had phone-record proof
that she was the real harasser, and a drunken driving charge that
was dropped after he passed a Breathalyzer test. He also thrice
flunked bar exams in other states before passing in Massachusetts,
has had some lawsuit tangles and was once arrested for failing to
pay a speeding ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there have been some embarrassing incidents, and we
believe sources close to the Kennedy campaign have basically
launched this attack,'' said Robinson, a bachelor. ``So I decided
to try to put an end to all these extraneous issues by just
releasing everything I could think of in my entire life that could
even possibly be used against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's spokesman, Will Keyser, dismissed as ``completely
ridiculous'' Robinson's suggestion that the damaging information
had originated in the senator's camp.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not mollified Robinson. ``You know, there's a
candidate in this race who was actually convicted of a crime, and
it's not me,'' he said. (After Kennedy's 1969 plunge off a
Chappaquiddick bridge, which killed his car's passenger, Mary Jo
Kopechne, he pleaded guilty to leaving the scene of an accident and
was given a two-month suspended sentence.)
</P>
<P>
   But the reasons for Robinson's frustration and anger just keep
growing. Amid the rush of accusations, he was unceremoniously
disowned this week by the Republican governor of Massachusetts,
Paul Cellucci, and the state Republican Party, a rejection that
Robinson called ``unheralded in American history'' and a ``typical
Beacon Hill back room double-cross.''
</P>
<P>
   And almost every day, local papers have carried a new source of
embarrassment, leading some to comment that Kennedy may finally
have a rival with a past as problematic as his own.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, it was an unidentified woman's account in The Boston
Globe that Robinson had subjected her to unwanted advances after a
heavy-drinking dinner date, including French kisses that led her
and her friends to refer to him as ``Jack the Tongue.'' Robinson
denies the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, it was reports that he left the scene of an
accident that occurred while he was giving a radio interview on his
cell phone. Robinson, who was not accused of being at fault, has
said he was pulling forward to get out of traffic's way, not
fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of what he calls ``fallacious and fraudulent
allegations'' has utterly obscured Robinson's campaign message: He
presents himself as a John McCain-style reformer who wants a
radical overhaul of the country's education and campaign finance
system, a less radical overhaul of the health care system and a
more concerted foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reform the system, and I don't believe the
senator's capable of doing that,'' he said. ``He is the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusations have also obscured what is otherwise a quite
distinguished resume. Raised in Boston's Roxbury section, son of
two entrepreneurs who divorced when he was 5, Robinson attended
Brown University and received law and business degrees from
Harvard. He was the top executive of an airline and wrote a book,
``Freefall: The Needless Destruction of Eastern Airlines''
(HarperCollins, 1992). In the mid-'90s, he shifted to the
cell-phone industry and founded a company doing business in the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was running now, Robinson said he had four goals in
his life, and he had accomplished the first three: to graduate from
Harvard; to be president of an airline by the time he was 30, which
he made by about a week, and to be economically self-sufficient by
40. The fourth, he said, was to be a U.S. senator from his home
state, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   He has been living out-of-state for a dozen years, in Manhattan
and then Greenwich, Conn., he acknowledged; but he has voted here
since the mid-'90s, he said, and was moving his possessions back
this week to the stone Tudor-style house on Boston's graceful
Arborway where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Some Massachusetts political analysts say that Robinson's
candidacy is so laughable that the Republican Party should be
ashamed for not being able to field a candidate credible enough to
keep Kennedy busy at home instead of off gaining votes for other
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But for Robinson, this is the fight of his life, he said,
tougher and nastier than anything he has ever encountered.
</P>
<P>
   He is putting out a ``clarion call for help,'' he said, and
plans to battle on no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party be damned, full speed ahead,'' he said, ``because I
don't want the next generation of politicians to live through what
I just lived through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
