<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEAD SHIFTS IN POLL
</P>
<P>
   After a series of tough primary battles, Gov. George W. Bush
appears to have lost his edge over his likely Democratic opponent,
Vice President Al Gore, in the race for president, a national
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted last week by the Pew Research Center for the
People and the Press, 49 percent of the registered voters surveyed
said they would vote for Gore in the general election or were
leaning toward supporting him, up from 40 percent last December.
Only 43 percent said the same for Bush, down from 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore scored especially well among the sort of voters that Sen.
John McCain of Arizona courted in his campaign, including
independents, older men and people who live on the East Coast.
Bush's standing also declined among white Catholic voters, who are
now evenly split between Bush and Gore, Pew said; in December, Bush
held a two-to-one advantage. The survey's margin of error is plus
or minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP'S ADS ATTACK MICHIGAN SENATOR
</P>
<P>
   Michigan has one of the closest Senate races in the United
States, as Rep. Debbie Stabenow, a Democrat, challenges Sen.
Spencer Abraham, a freshman Republican seeking re-election. But the
heaviest political advertising right now is not by either
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Federation for American Immigration Reform,
which seeks strict limits on immigration, has paid for heavy radio
and print advertising criticizing Abraham's record as chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration. The ads assail
the senator's support for a bill that would increase sharply the
number of visas available for companies to bring in foreign
high-technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   The senator continues to push for the legislation, which is
intended to alleviate a labor shortage that is making it harder for
companies to start new projects and that is pushing up wages for
American workers in the computer sector.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON SENATE RACE IS GETTING EXPENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats vying in Washington state for the right to take
on Sen. Slade Gorton, the Republican incumbent, have demonstrated
an ability to generate campaign funds, but in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of solicitations, Deborah Senn, the state insurance
commissioner, recently reported that she would soon pass the $1
million mark.
</P>
<P>
   Her opponent in the Democratic primary, former U.S. Rep. Maria
Cantwell, is worth at least $12 million and has indicated that she
is willing to dip into her personal fortune to make the race.
Cantwell, who became an Internet company executive after she lost
her congressional seat in the 1994 Republican tide, announced in
January that she would run for Gorton's post. The senator himself
is attempting to amass even more than the $5.4 million he raised
for his 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A HUG FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   While he was raising money in Detroit on Thursday, Vice
President Al Gore showed up in a taped segment on NBC's ``Tonight
Show With Jay Leno.'' Angela Ramos, who has hugged the major
presidential candidates at Leno's behest, was shown greeting and
embracing Gore at the New York Sheraton Hotel on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos had hugged Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, Sen. John McCain
and former Sen. Bill Bradley while they were campaigning in
California before the March 7 primary there. NBC and the Gore
campaign finally arranged a get-together this week.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gov. George W. Bush nor Vice President Al Gore has
public events scheduled Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
