<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALAMIN0325-COX     03-24 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jamil Al-Amin's attorney wants restrictions lifted
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Attorneys for Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin filed a
petition in the district court of Montgomery demanding that the
Muslim cleric be allowed to spend more than one hour outside of his
cell and be allowed to pray along with other Muslims who are locked
up.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Sanders, who is representing Al-Amin in Montgomery, along
with attorney J.L. Chestnut, complained to Montgomery County
District Judge Lynn Bright that Sheriff D.T. Marshall has violated
Al-Amin's right to religious expression by refusing to let him
attend Friday's prayer service with other Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Since being captured Monday in White Hall, Al-Amin has been in
solitary confinement for 23 hours a day. The only time he is
allowed out of his 10-by-10 foot cell is to go to court or for the
one hour he can leave his cell to bathe or exercise.
</P>
<P>
   During court appearances, he has worn a stripped prison uniform
with orange slippers. He is not allowed to wear any religious garb,
including his Kofu.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Montgomery County Sheriff's Department is maliciously
impinging on Al-Amin's civil rights and human rights to religious
freedom without any reasonable or legitimate penological purpose,''
said Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin did get a chance to meet with his wife, Karima Al-Amin
and his brother, Ed Brown, for about 30 minutes Friday morning.
Because they drove from Atlanta early Friday morning, the two were
able to visit Al-Amin. The normal visiting day for those in
solitary confinement is Saturday from 3:30 to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The two immediately drove back to Atlanta after the visit
without commenting to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin is facing murder charges in Atlanta for the shooting of
Fulton County Deputy Ricky Kinchen. Kinchen, along with his partner
Aldranon English, were shot March 16 while trying to serve Al-Amin
with an arrest warrant. Kinchen died the next afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's attorneys said they were anticipating that the Fulton
county grand jury might indict Al-Amin Friday, starting the
extradition machinery rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury met on its regular schedule Friday but did not
indict Al-Amin. Fulton County prosecutors would not comment on
whether the grand jury considered Al-Amin's case Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders wanted Al-Amin to be able to attend Jaamu, which is a
religious collective prayer held on Fridays, the Muslim Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Haverland, director of the Montgomery County Detention
Facility, where Al-Amin is being held, said Muslim prisoners have
never requested permission to pray together on Fridays and that
they generally pray alone.
</P>
<P>
   Haverland said there about 20 Muslim prisoners in the detention
center's 429-person population.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he is a prisoner, he will be treated just like any
other inmate,'' said Haverland.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because he is a Muslim, the food hasn't been an issue,
because we don't serve any pork products. They eat turkey baloney,
turkey ham and turkey turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Haverland said his most famous inmate is presenting no special
concerns to the center's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been a problem since he came here,'' said Haverland,
adding that Al-Amin has been eating. ``I think he has more
important things to worry about right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
