<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-PUPPETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IRREVERANT POKE AT RUSSIAN POLITICOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A playboy president cruises Moscow's streets looking
for prostitutes and finds them in parliament. A sadomasochistic
communist, decked out in leather, begs to be hit _ hard. A virgin
liberal refuses to participate in group-sex with other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Russia's top three presidential hopefuls were
recently portrayed on national television _ on a weekly puppet show
that spoofs Russia's political leaders and has become one of the
nation's most popular television programs.
</P>
<P>
   The show, called ``Kukly'' or Puppets, has stood out in a
political season notable for its lack of humor. As most media have
slavishly praised Vladimir V. Putin, the heavy favorite to win
Sunday's election, Kukly has mercilessly lampooned the acting
president, along with the rest of Russia's elite.
</P>
<P>
   Irreverently ridiculing Russia's rich and powerful, by showing
their vanities, quirks, and idiosyncrasies, is a something Kukly
has been doing for five years. Equal opportunity humor, with
anybody in power as fair game, has earned the show a loyal
following.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Shenderovich, the show's 42-year-old creator, said the
program seeks to keep Russia's leaders accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society needs to keep the authorities under control, and I
like to think that what we do is in the interests of society,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For many aspiring politicians, being spoofed on Kukly is a sure
sign that they have hit the big time. Others, however, are not
amused.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Putin supporters sought to have criminal charges
brought against Kukly for ``insulting the president.'' And on the
floor of Russia's parliament, some lawmakers said they were
``deeply appalled'' by the show's humor.
</P>
<P>
   Shenderovich brushed off the criticism with a sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I understand that some people may be offended by
what we do,'' he said. ``But at the same time they need to
understand us. Politicians are public figures and are subject to
public evaluations of their activities.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made a few appearances. One 1998 episode
showed puppets of Clinton and former President Boris Boris Yeltsin,
both facing impeachment. In the show, Yeltsin called Clinton to
offer advice about how to deal with his unruly foes: shoot up the
legislature and put your opponents in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make the point that the American president can be
held accountable for his actions and removed from office. Our
president, on the other hand, can do just about anything,''
Shenderovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The episode with Putin and the prostitutes is rooted in a
historical Russian reference. Soviet founder Vladimir Lenin was
known to call his opponents ``political prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shenderovich used the metaphor to expose what he sees as
hypocrisy among the political elite.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov appeared as a puppetdecked out
in leather and chains and wielding a whip, who tried to seduce the
novice Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit me!'' Zyuganov demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What for?'' Putin asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'll hit you! And then you'll hit me again! Let's wear
each other out! In front of everybody, publicly!'' Zyuganov said.
</P>
<P>
   When Putin refused, parliamentary speaker Gennady Seleznyov
stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand anything. You're just very young,''
Seleznyov said. ``Later, close to election time (and in private),
he'll give in to you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, liberal presidential candidate Grigory
Yavlinsky, who is running third in the polls, appeared as a
sanctimonious virgin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all disgust me individually as it is. But I absolutely
refuse to take part in this group thing,'' Yavlinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The Seleznyov puppet responded: ``You little political prude.
Been preening for five years, and won't give up a thing to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The segment, Shenderovich said, was meant to demonstrate that
Yavlinsky was the only candidate really opposing Putin. At the same
time, it was a subtle dig at Yavlinsky, a prickly loner.
</P>
<P>
   Kukly broadcasts on the private NTV television station, the only
national network that has openly criticized Putin.
</P>
<P>
   NTV's stand has drawn the wrath of pro-Kremlin media. This week,
ORT television has attacked NTV and its owner, Vladimir Gusinsky,
accusing him of being an Israeli provocateur.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attacks, Shenderovich said he wasn't afraid of
censorship under Putin. ``The most important thing,'' he said, ``is
not to show fear, because the authorities can sense this. We must
act like we are in the right, because we are right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
