<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 LEADING RABBIS VOICE APPRECIATION FOR JOHN PAUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Pope John Paul II stood in silent meditation on Thursday
inside Yad Vashem, the Holocaust memorial in Jerusalem, he created
a visually riveting moment symbolic of a major theme in his
22-year-old pontificate: the establishment of healthy relations
between Roman Catholics and Jews. Those who have followed the
pope's statements know it as a concern to which he has returned
again and again.
</P>
<P>
   In an apostolic letter in 1989, for example, he reflected on the
``anti-human'' events of World War II, declaring that ``there is
one that will forever remain a shame for humanity: the planned
barbarism which was unleashed against the Jewish people.'' Two
years ago, the Vatican issued a document on the Holocaust that
repented inaction of many Catholics in the face of Nazi genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, particularly Jews, remain disappointed that the
pope has declined to go so far as to apologize for the silence of
his predecessor Pius XII during the Holocaust. That aside, are not
John Paul's statements of contrition and remembrance having a
cumulative effect, working a gradual but profound change in
Catholic-Jewish relations?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, said Rabbi Eric Yoffie, president of the Union of American
Hebrew Congregations, which represents nearly 900 Reform synagogues
in the United States and Canada. ``I think it's an absolute
revolution,'' Yoffie said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A similar response came from Rabbi Ismar Schorsch, chancellor of
the Jewish Theological Seminary, an institution of Conservative
Judaism, in New York. ``I think there's been enormous progress,''
he said. ``One just need compare the visit of Paul VI to Israel to
the visit of John Paul II. They are worlds apart.'' (Pope Paul VI,
in a very brief sojourn on Israeli soil three decades ago, never
uttered the word ``Israel.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie spoke by telephone from his native Worcester, Mass.,
where he had gone to give a speech about Catholic-Jewish relations.
In that speech, at Assumption College, a Catholic institution, he
said he was distressed that in responding to the pope on previous
occasions, some Jewish leaders seemed to focus more on what the
Vatican had not done (particularly with regard to Pius XII) than on
efforts to improve interfaith relations. ``When my friend
apologizes to me for a sin he has committed,'' he said in the
speech, ``the appropriate response is for me to thank him, to
welcome his repentance and to express my desire to continue our
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he thought that unlike those leaders, whom he did
not identify, Jews of many congregations felt positively about the
progress in Catholic-Jewish relations.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say in his speech that Reform Judaism had fallen
behind in teaching its youth about important changes that had
occurred since the Second Vatican Council, in the 1960s, an event
whose emphasis on interfaith engagement is the foundation that John
Paul has built upon. The Reform movement, Yoffie said, will revise
religious-school textbooks to reflect ``accurately and
sympathetically'' the church's position on Jews and Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Yoffie remains troubled by the case of Pius XII. He
made that clear in his speech, while also saying he recognized that
some Catholics felt quite differently, believing that Pius actually
encouraged secret efforts to help Jews. Yoffie said Catholics and
Jews might soon have to recognize that they were at an impasse on
this issue. And he said he regarded the possibility that the church
might move to declare Pius a saint to be a religious matter
internal to the church.
</P>
<P>
   But as a way to frame the discussions about canonizing Pius, he
proposed that Catholic and Jewish theologians sit down together to
talk about the standards for righteous conduct in a time of evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we to assume at such a time that anyone who is not totally
evil can be called righteous?'' Yoffie said in the speech. ``Or are
we to assume exactly the opposite: that anyone fighting evil in an
evil time has to be particularly good? The relevance of these
questions to the Nazi era is immediately apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Schorsch, he noted that the present pope had experienced
the Nazi era directly, as a young seminarian in Poland. John Paul
grew up with Jewish neighbors and schoolmates. Jews, who numbered
more than 3 million in prewar Poland, ``were not an abstraction to
him, as they must have been to so many Italian popes,'' Schorsch
said. ``The Nazi trauma'' is a source ``of his empathy for Jews,''
the rabbi said, and of ``his courage in taking the church so far in
its progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Schorsch said he regarded John Paul's visit to Yad Vashem as a
climactic ``expression of a personal mission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pattern of efforts of reconciliation,'' he added,
``is unmistakable and cumulative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
