<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SMALL STATUES AND TALL TALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Should a movie that claims to be a true story get an
Oscar even though it's not true? If you think not, you have plenty
to root against Sunday. But you would be missing the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you can quibble with ``Music From the Heart,'' in which a
white violin teacher and black principal in Harlem battle hostile
parents and lazy teachers to introduce classical music to students
in a violence-ridden cultural wasteland. In reality, it was a
peaceful, highly regarded school with a white principal, supported
by enthusiastic parents and teachers. The real students were
putting on operas before the violin teacher arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the tobacco-industry whistle-blower in ``The Insider''
might not have been threatened as shown in the movie. A scene of
his being tailed by a shadowy figure is pure invention. A bullet
was indeed found in his mailbox, as shown, but an FBI investigator
and the whistle-blower's wife at the time say he planted it
himself. Mike Wallace of ``60 Minutes'' says he's misquoted and
misrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   And sure, ``Hurricane'' may distort the legal case and include
pure fantasies. The real Rubin Carter was not robbed of the
middleweight boxing title by a racist decision. (He lost fair and
square.) The movie's racist detective obsessed with framing Carter
for murder never existed, as the director freely concedes.
</P>
<P>
   But why nitpick? Why criticize producers who would otherwise
spend all their money on ordinary fiction? The more ``true
stories'' they pay for, the more they spread Hollywood's wealth
across America. And the more creative they become, the more hope
for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   I once despaired of selling my life to the movies. My reporting
had never saved a life, rescued a city or put me in mortal danger.
An article against recycling had angered some environmental groups
and provoked a lot of angry letters, and a carton of smelly
garbage, but that didn't seem to be enough for a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, I know better. With the right director, someone
who understands Hollywood's concept of ``higher truth,'' I could be
sitting at next year's Oscar ceremony watching scenes from my
life's story. Call it ``The Heart of the Cyclone.''
</P>
<P>
   Fade in to suburban schoolchildren being forced by their
teacher, a stern but beautiful brunette, to sort bottles into
recycling bins. One child coughs and collapses, followed by others.
Watching from the parking lot is Joao Tierneiro, a tall, elegant
ebony-skinned Brazilian-American journalist.
</P>
<P>
   He befriends one student, a sad but savvy homeless child. They
steal a bottle from the recycling bin and discover it harbors
deadly bacteria. Tierneiro, nicknamed Cyclone for his writing
speed, stays up all night typing and carries his scoop to New York
Times executives planning the next day's front page.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is run by the ruthless director of advertising, who
barks orders: ``We need room on A1 for that puff piece on the auto
industry. Kill the Middle East story _ those countries aren't
buying full pages.'' He sneers at Cyclone's article. ``Recycling
industry threatens millions? Kid, their ads pay your salary.''
</P>
<P>
   He crumples the article and orders it buried in The New York
Times Magazine, where it is slashed to 8,000 words by an editor
bigoted against Brazilians. But even that doesn't satisfy Big Can,
the unholy alliance of recycling companies and environmentalists.
In a blood-curdling pre-dawn scene, Cyclone is awakened by a death
threat, the sound of glass ominously splintering inside a recycling
truck outside his apartment. He stumbles to the window in time to
see two mysterious hooded figures speeding away on the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclone goes into hiding in the cardboard box of the homeless
student. The boy carries the article to their last hope, the Nobel
Prize committee. The judges are about to give Cyclone the first
combined prize for medicine and peace when the meeting is
interrupted by the two hooded figures, now revealed as
environmentalists with the Natural Resources Defense Council. The
thugs hold shards of contaminated glass to the necks of the judges,
who dutifully change their votes.
</P>
<P>
   In despair, Cyclone visits the boy's teacher. Romance ensues.
She lets the students skip recycling one day for another
after-school activity that they learn from Cyclone. It's a sport
from his homeland never before seen by the suburbanites, soccer,
which quickly becomes so popular that it replaces recycling. All
the students recover their health, and the homeless boy moves in
with Cyclone and the teacher. They all gleefully toss bottles into
the regular garbage as the credits roll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
