u f BC-USAIR-DISPUTE-BOS &LR;      03-24 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAIR-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AIRWAYS NEGOTIATORS TRY TO AVERT STOPPAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS AND GREGG KRUPA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Airways management and flight attendants negotiated into the
night late Friday in an effort to reach a settlement in a contract
dispute, and avoid a shutdown of the airline, which would cripple
travel along the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The airline sent letters Friday to all 42,000 employees
regarding reporting to work in the event of a shutdown, and said
that ``almost all employees will be busy with activities related to
the shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO president, John Sweeney, issued a statement saying
he hoped an agreement could be reached, but said the US Airways
demand for concessions from flight attendants was ``not only
unacceptable; it is absolutely unconscionable.'' He added that the
labor federation was ready to assist the flight attendants in any
way it could.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials were preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning for a complete shutdown of the air carrier,''
said Thomas Kinton, aviation director for Massport, which operates
Logan International Airport in Boston . ``We're hoping that does
not occur. We hope that the parties can come to some kind of mutual
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, such as Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, the airline
has well over 50 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   While other major carriers have said they would honor US Airways
tickets on a space-available basis, Kinton said many airlines had
little space available out of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern we have, obviously, is that there is not a lot of
excess capacity in the aviation system. There are not a lot of
extra airplanes that can be put into a market to take care of that
kind of demand, nor are there a lot of excess seats available in
the market. A lot of the carriers who fly in and out of here are
close to booked if not overbooked.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a little softening in negotiations when the company
agreed to discuss alternative formulas for reaching parity plus 1
percent with the big four airlines _ United, American, Delta and
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Other unions representing USAir workers have agreed to that pay
scheme, but the flight attendants say that the company's offer
would result in an erosion of their pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   To remain competitive, grow domestically and internationally, US
Airways management has said it must control operating costs _ which
are the highest in the industry in part because after a series of
mergers in the 1970s and 1980s, workers were able to keep the best
parts of many different contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the more than 9,000 flight attendants have been working
without a new contract for three years and want raises and better
pensions. While the airline has lost money in the past two quarters
and will probably be in the red for the first two quarters of this
year, it turned a profit of more than $1.5 billion in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, management said it would shut down the airline, the
busiest carrier along the East Coast, rather than subject
passengers to the uncertainty of flights in the face of wildcat
walkouts threatened by flight attendants starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Airline analysts said a shutdown would cost the airline at least
$15 million a day; flight attendants have put the figure at $30
million. US Airways said it would pay the salaries of employees
other than flight attendants for as long as possible. It has more
than $800 million in cash and has drawn down a $500 million line of
credit.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to payroll, the airline also has to continue to
pay for airplanes _ it is under contract with Airbus Industrie to
accept about one new plane every week _ and continue to rent space
at airports.
</P>
<P>
   A shutdown would cause massive disruptions in travel in the
Northeast, where US Airways operates a Boston-LaGuardia-Washington
shuttle as Philadelphia and Pittsburgh as hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Massport's Kinton said that he was contacted Friday by the
federal Department of Transportation. ``They are going to be
contacting certain airports _ Boston is one of them _ over the next
two days to get a report on the disruptions that may be occurring
at this airport. So they want to be kept abreast of any of the
problems. They want to know how we are coping.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a shutdown, President Clinton can create an
emergency board that would investigate and report on the labor
dispute and make recommendations for a settlement. The creation of
a board would stop any strike or lockout, generally for 60 days.
Aviation officials said it is not considered likely that Clinton
would act immediately, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Kinton said that in the event of a shutdown, extra Massport
staff would be in front of ticket counters at Terminal C where
Delta Airlines is located and Terminal A where the Delta Shuttle
and Continental are located.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect those two terminals to feel the brunt of this
shutdown, should it occur, because, obviously, the Delta Shuttle
and Continental have frequent service to the New York and Newark
area, and Terminal C, where Delta airlines has frequent service to
Florida,'' Kinton said. ``The Florida markets will be heavily
impacted with the US Airways shutdown of service here in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline is expected to staff its ticket counters at Terminal
B to accommodate passengers and have its mechanics do maintenance
work on the fleet if the planes are grounded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TURNER-GRANTS0325-COX     03-24 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-GRANTS0325-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner grants helping preserve
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _When the latest recipients of Ted Turner's global
giving were announced earlier this week, public attention focused
on the showiest package of grants _ more than $6 million to help
fight the spread of AIDS in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But also included were funds for a cause dear to Turner's heart:
the environment. Grants went to identify areas in need of
international protection and to promote energy conservation in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's philanthropic interests, clearly, are not limited to
fighting disease, poverty and war. His lifelong enjoyment of the
outdoors as a yachtsman, rancher and fisherman has led to a deep
appreciation of the environment. And that appreciation has been
deep enough to prompt him to reach into his pockets to try to help
protect the environment around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything happens to the environment, there's not going to
be any human race,'' Turner said in an interview. ``We depend on
the environment. It's absolutely imperative that we have a healthy
environment if we're going to have a healthy human race.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest grants were announced Thursday by the U.N.
Foundation, set up to disburse Turner's gift of $1 billion over 10
years to United Nations projects. It was the sixth round of grants
awarded since the foundation was created just over two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, public attention has been paid to grants aimed at
eradicating polio, controlling population growth, giving loans to
poor women and reintegrating child soldiers into their homes,
schools and villages.
</P>
<P>
   But every round of grants has also included money for
environmental projects, such as controlling ``invasive species'' in
the Galapagos Islands or protecting wildlife parks in the
Democratic Republic of Congo while the country is at war.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is by design.
</P>
<P>
   After Turner, the Atlanta businessman who founded CNN and is
vice chairman of Time Warner, announced in 1997 that he would
donate $1 billion to U.N. projects, he decided that, to have the
greatest impact, he would focus on three areas: improving the
health of children, controlling population growth while empowering
women and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the foundation has given away more than
$237 million of Turner's money. About 18 percent _ more than $42
million _ has gone to 31 environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
   Among the grants so far:
</P>
<P>
   $1.5 million to assess coral reef degradation around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   $4 million to protect native species in the Galapagos Islands
from ``invasive species'' such as pigs and rats.
</P>
<P>
   $500,000 to develop an electronic U.N. Atlas of the Oceans to
track threats to the marine environment.
</P>
<P>
   At this pace, by the end of the 10 years the foundation will
have awarded $180 million of Turner's wealth to efforts to protect
the environment around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Turner has been using his gift to induce the U.N. to
improve in areas he finds important. For example, cooperation among
different U.N. agencies has often been difficult to achieve in the
past; the U.N. Foundation seeks to change that by frequently
awarding grants to proposals developed by two or more U.N. agencies
working together.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the approach with the environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. has been relatively weak in the environmental area,''
Turner said. ``But they do have an environmental component, and we
want to encourage that component. And that's why we're making these
grants.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's grants focus largely on slowing global warming
and preserving diverse species, two areas that were agreed upon as
important by participants in the 1992 U.N.-sponsored Rio Earth
Summit, said Nicholas Lapham, a program officer with the U.N.
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the U.N. Foundation is accountable only to its board _
and board chairman Ted Turner _ it can make grants that other
organizations might deem too risky.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the foundation gave $2.9 million over four years
to the U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization,
known as UNESCO, to help five wildlife areas survive the current
multi-nation war in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The parks are home to some of the world's rarest large mammals,
such as the northern white rhinoceros, Grauer's gorilla and the
okapi.
</P>
<P>
   All the parks are designated by UNESCO as World Heritage sites,
worthy of international protection. Four of the five are in the
eastern part of Congo, and staff members, who are employees of the
Congolese government, have not been paid since 1998, said Natarajan
Ishwaran, a senior program specialist with UNESCO World Heritage
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they continue to show up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to see how dedicated these people are to the
sites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Threats to the parks abound, said Terese Hart, an official with
the Wildlife Conservation Society. She works at one of the parks,
the Okapi Wildlife Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the guards have control over less than half of the
reserve,'' Hart said. ``There is heavy poaching in these areas.
Particularly notable is killing of elephants _ at least 11
elephants were killed just in January and February. There is also a
fair amount of small-scale mining.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, rebel groups are thought to have actually set up
military operations on protected park land, said Ishwaran.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's money will be used to pay park employees' salaries and
for equipment, training and monitoring of the species in the
reserves, he said. After the war has ended, tourist revenue from
the parks will be needed to help rebuild the economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Most other donors were not interested in making environmental
investments in a war zone, Ishwaran said. ``The main reason is the
risk,'' he said. ``There are so many groups, you don't know who is
loyal to what. There can be a lot of accidental things, because you
don't know who is fighting each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But the risk did not deter the U.N. Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you know, the U.N. Foundation, like the U.N.
itself, is about risk, to a degree,'' said Turner. ``When the U.N.
sends peacekeepers into a place like Kosovo, they take a risk. I
mean, life is about risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Now other donors are beginning to follow the U.N. Foundation's
example, Hart said. The U.S. Agency for International Development
and the European Union have begun targeting money for the parks in
Congo, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he is working to develop an even more important
environmental proposal _ one that he cannot do through the U.N.
Foundation. The foundation always works through United Nations
agencies, which are governed, in large measure, by the world's
nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Turner said, he is working through the Turner
Foundation, a domestic philanthropic organization he set up years
ago, to launch a ``major initiative to get nuclear weapons back on
the global agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been downplayed since the end of the Cold War, he
said, but there is no greater threat to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that the United States and Russia have 6,000
warheads on hair-trigger alerts pointed at each other around the
clock all the time, and it's a very dangerous situation,'' Turner
said. ``There could be an accident or somebody could go mad and
push a button somewhere and annihilate us all. You know, just when
we thought it was safe to come out of our bomb shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
