<HEADLINE>
GIVING AWAY THE ENDING AT THE OSCARS? SHOCKING.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had been weeks, or at least days, since journalists last
found themselves besieged by accusations of Peeping-Tomism,
prurience, piling on or general tawdriness. But on Friday, some
were at it again.
</P>
<P>
   Flying in the face of accusations that it was spoiling
everyone's fun, The Wall Street Journal published the results of a
poll on which actors and movies are likely to win Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a list of critics' picks or consensus of such
informal oddsmaking like office pools, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   No, Journal reporters gathered the putative picks of 356 of the
5,607 voting members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences, the people whose votes award the Oscars. The ceremonies
are Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   To academy officials, this was the equivalent of someone
releasing exit-poll results before the voting precincts had closed.
Once word of what the newspaper was up to got out, Bruce Davis, the
academy's director, told his membership in a letter quoted in
Friday's Journal that the poll was ``a threat to the Academy Awards
process.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, though, publication of the results could not
discourage voting for the Oscars, which finished at 5 p.m.
Thursday, long before the Weekend Journal came out on Friday. But
it sure could poke a hole in the suspense that keeps people up _
and tuned in _ on Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood was indignant, in its way, at The Journal's
undertaking, questioning the poll's methodology and the newspaper's
intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything goes in journalism these days, even at The Wall
Street Journal,'' sighed Anita Busch, editor of The Hollywood
Reporter, in an interview on Friday. Journalism, she added, ``has
gone into a yellow age.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickee Adams, director of corporate communications for Dow
Jones, the paper's publisher, defended the poll. ``It is not a
scientific study. It's a best and educated guess _ a fun look at
some of the top six awards.''
</P>
<P>
   But would The Journal turn the same level of scrutiny on the
process by which journalists are awarded Pulitzer Prizes? ``As with
any story that may or may not appear in The Wall Street Journal, I
cannot give you a response on that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So, what, exactly, did The Journal's poll find?
</P>
<P>
   That ``American Beauty'' was the clear favorite for Best
Picture. Respondents gave Denzel Washington a thin lead over Kevin
Spacey for Best Actor and Hilary Swank a wider lead over Annette
Bening for Best Actress. Michael Caine got double the number of
votes as Haley Joel Osment in the Best Supporting Actor category,
and Angelina Jolie seemed the favorite for Best Supporting Actress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
