<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON ADMITS `DON'T ASK' POLICY ISN'T WORKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon acknowledged Friday that its ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy for gays needs to be carried out better,
after an extensive survey revealed widespread hostility to
homosexuals on bases and aboard ships and submarines.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon inspector general's report found that 85 percent of
the servicemen and women surveyed believed that antigay comments
were tolerated on their base. The report called offensive comments
about gays commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven percent said they had personally witnessed or been
the target of harassment because of perceived homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Based on surveys of 71,500 members of the Army, Air Force, Navy,
and Marine Corps, the report declared that the Clinton
administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy has not worked.
President Clinton himself had recently said the policy, enacted in
1993, was now ``out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, ordered by Defense Secretary William S. Cohen in
December after the bludgeoning death last July of a gay Army
private at Fort Campbell, Ky., now puts the onus on base commanders
to end the verbal and physical abuse of gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This behavior is not acceptable and can't be tolerated in the
military,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon told reporters
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen announced he would form a committee of military and
civilian officials to create measures that would improve how the
policy is carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspector general's report convinces me that additional
actions are necessary to address the problem of harassment of
service members who are alleged or perceived to be homosexual,''
Cohen said in a memorandum to the services.
</P>
<P>
   The policy says gays and lesbians may serve in the military, as
long as they keep their sexual orientation to themselves. The
policy bars those who are openly homosexual from the military and
says harassment or violence toward other service members will not
be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   The defense secretary also said in his memo: ``The report shows
that military leaders must do more to make it clear that harassment
based on sexual orientation violates military values.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey's findings, which were conducted on 38 US bases
and aboard 10 Navy ships and one submarine:
</P>
<P>
   --Most of the harassment was done by junior enlisted men to
other junior enlisted men.
</P>
<P>
   --Some 73 percent who said that when a ``senior person'' had
witnessed harassment, the senior person did nothing to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   --Eighty percent said they had heard offensive speech or jokes
or derogatory names or remarks about gays in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   --The offensive behavior was reported most frequently in the
Marine Corps and least frequently in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   --Nine percent said they had witnessed physical assaults of
gays.
</P>
<P>
   --Less than 50 percent said they had received training on the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   --About 50 percent of all service members surveyed said they
believed the policy was at least moderately effective at reducing
harassment of gays; 46 percent believed it was not effective.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director of Servicemembers Legal
Defense Network, which has helped represent about 2,200 service
members since the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy was enacted,
called the findings ``very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need commanders in the field to stop the harassment when
they see it and hold people accountable when they see it,'' Osburn
said. ``The commander in the field now has support from the very,
very top of the Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Osburh said his group has received 982 reports of incidents of
harassment against gays in the service in 1999, up from 400 the
year before, a 142 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying for a long time that antigay harassment is a
huge problem in the military,'' he said. ``The position of the
Pentagon for the last few years was that it wasn't a problem. Today
they quite clearly changed their position.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat, said he
hoped that ``Secretary Cohen's comments set a tone for the whole
military chain of command.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anti-gay harassment will disappear when it's no longer
tolerated,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials Friday acknowledged that the current policy
gives no specific guidelines to those in the military on what would
be considered offensive and what needed to be reported to
superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is, I think, always a judgment for the service member,''
said Frank Rush, deputy undersecretary of defense for planning in
personnel and readiness. ``But this may be something that needs to
be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rush grew defensive when asked about the lack of policy
directives, saying: ``What we've been focusing on today
specifically, (is) on the issue of offensive speech, which is
always going to be a problem with junior members, and harassment. .
. . There are a number of areas where we are always dealing with
harassment of one type or another, whether it has to do with sexual
orientation or whether it has to do with other matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted from Jan. 24 to Feb. 11. The committee
examining the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy will report to Cohen
by July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
