<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MAGEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARREN MAGEE, 91, A LAWYER IN UNPOPULAR CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warren Egbert Magee, a lawyer who represented Nazi war
criminals, corrupt politicians, and Sen. Joseph McCarthy, died on
Feb. 25 in Washington. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Magee represented the last seven Nazi war criminals condemned to
death at the Nuremberg trials and then hanged after World War II.
Another client was Baron Ernst von Weizsaecker, state secretary to
the German Foreign Office and the Nazis' ambassador to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949 Magee failed to save Rep. Andrew May, D-Ky., who was
chairman of the House Military Affairs Committee during World War
II, from a prison sentence for bribery and corruption, though
President Harry S. Truman later pardoned him.
</P>
<P>
   Magee acted for the anti-communist crusader McCarthy, R-Wis., in
the $2 million libel suit that McCarthy brought against Sen.
William Benton, D-Conn., charging that Benton had slandered him by
calling for his removal from the Senate. But in 1954 McCarthy
dropped his action.
</P>
<P>
   Magee's willingness to represent unpopular defendants stemmed
from his enjoyment of testing the law's limits, his daughter,
Dianne M. Nordyke, told The Washington Post. ``He was a lawyer
first,'' Nordyke said.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Washington, Magee graduated in 1929 from what is now
American University's Law School and was admitted to the District
of Columbia bar in 1930. After working at the Justice Department,
he entered private practice in 1938, forming what later became the
firm of Magee &AMP; Bulow. He retired in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946 and 1947, Magee tried to save the last major Nazi war
criminals from death for crimes against humanity, sentences imposed
by the International Military Tribunal in Nuremberg, Germany. Those
condemned to die, all former senior officers in the SS, included
Oswald Pohl, blamed for the destruction of the Warsaw Ghetto and
the killing or deportation of more than 56,000 Jews; Otto
Ohlendorf, responsible for the murder of some 90,000 people; and
Paul Blobel, convicted of ordering the deaths of 60,000 Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Magee delayed their executions until 1951 with a barrage of
appeals in the U.S. courts. In one instance, by arguing that the
United States was bound to respect the new West German
Constitution, which banned the death penalty, he won a reprieve
after the condemned men's wives had paid what they were told would
be their last visit.
</P>
<P>
   On June 6, 1951, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to grant any
further stays of execution. The next day the seven prisoners were
hanged in the courtyard of Landsberg prison in Bavaria. They were
the last of the 275 World War II criminals executed by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 Magee was back in Nuremberg to represent von
Weizsaecker, one of 21 Nazi diplomats and officials accused of
lesser war crimes. Magee argued that his client had sought to brake
the excesses of his Nazi superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Von Weizsaecker was sentenced to seven years' imprisonment, but
Magee later succeeded in getting this reduced to five years.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Hitler's Pope: The Secret History of Pius XII''
(Viking, 1999), the British historian John Cornwell paints a
reasonably creditable picture of the baron, saying his great fear
was that moves against the Italian Jews would be an unbearable
strain on the pope's promise of impartiality toward the war.
</P>
<P>
   Magee's propensity for representing unpopular and difficult
clients made him a natural choice to represent McCarthy in his 1953
libel suit against Benton, who had called McCarthy a corrupt liar
who deserved to be expelled from the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1976 book ``Men Against McCarthy,'' Richard M. Fried of
Illinois University, paraphrasing von Clausewitz, said that the two
senators regarded the court case as ``politics carried on by other
means'' and sought to politicize the hearings. Benton even
suggested calling Winston Churchill to testify.
</P>
<P>
   As that year's presidential election campaign heated up, Judge
Matthew McGuire of the District of Columbia U.S. District Court
decided to delay his ruling on disputed points in the case ``for
some little time,'' which meant until after the election. When
Benton lost his Senate seat that November, McCarthy decided there
was no point in pursuing the litigation, which risked doing him
more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   Magee appeared in several other unusual cases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 he represented the publisher Douglas MacCollum Stewart
on perjury charges arising from an accusation that he had accepted
money from the German charge d'affaires in Washington in the early
days of World War II to finance a magazine urging the United States
to keep out of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950 he represented Louis P. Lochner and Frank E. Mason, who
had compiled the book ``The Goebbels Diaries,'' based on the
presumed papers of the Nazi leader Joseph Goebbels, papers that
Russian troops in Berlin had ordered a junk book dealer to remove
from the ruins of the Propaganda Ministry in 1946. The U.S.
government contended that the papers were war loot and that any
profits made from a book based on them should go toward war
reparations.
</P>
<P>
   Magee is survived by his second wife, Leslie Magee, and two
children from his marriage to Sue Mayfield Wren, who died in 1946.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FISHNET-$ADV26-NY     03-24 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FISHNET-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IDEA THAT ALMOST GOT AWAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine years after patenting a helicopter-deployed fishing net,
Kent Thomas finally went fishing last month in New Zealand's Bay of
Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a veteran helicopter pilot, used a specially designed
net to encircle a cloud of fish called trevally. The fish had
little to fear, though, because the net's closure mechanism failed.
Thomas had been waiting six months for the right fishing conditions
while his net sat idle at an airfield; unknown to him, grass had
grown through some of the lines and snarled them.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointments and delays don't faze Thomas, an entrepreneur
who has nursed his idea for an environmentally friendly fishing net
with persistence, self-sacrifice and a willingness to change
course.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it failed to capture any fish, the ``drop net''
developed by Thomas' Ocean Friendly Co. of Signal Hill, Calif., is
described by some people in the fishing world as a breakthrough.
Moreover, fishing regulators, who helped finance the net, consider
it an economically and environmentally promising alternative for an
industry facing restrictions on more and more declining species.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first real innovative fishing technique in
decades,'' said James M. Meehan, a tuna biologist for the National
Marine Fisheries Service, which imposed curbs last April on coastal
catches of shark, Atlantic tuna and marlin.
</P>
<P>
   When dropped from a helicopter, the net forms a sort of
mid-ocean aquarium. A 38-foot-wide hexagonal ring of floats
supports a strong, light cylindrical net weighted at the bottom.
Five tons of fish may be caught when the three-story cylinder is
twisted closed.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier tests, the net had closed properly, but in empty
water. The latest test failed to trap fish permanently, but it did
show how they would react inside the enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unknown,'' Thomas, 54, said in a telephone interview
from New Zealand. ``They were just swimming; they didn't have a
clue!''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy growing up on California's Santa Catalina Island, he
saw firsthand the collapse of sport fishing as commercial fleets
depleted the waters of bait fish. After serving in Vietnam as an
Army helicopter pilot, he flew commercially, spotting fish for tuna
boats.
</P>
<P>
   Wasteful methods _ the indiscriminate killing of juvenile fish
and protected species along with the desired catch in mile-long
purse seine nets _ galvanized him.
</P>
<P>
   He designed a net to improve a boat's yield of a single species.
Traditional nets kill the fish they snare, but the drop net keeps
them alive, allowing unwanted fish to be sorted out and returned to
the sea.
</P>
<P>
   And though the net's potential volume is less than that of
traditional nets, its live catch is suitable for aquariums, sea
farming or demanding sushi chefs, and thus has higher value.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was endorsed by the executive director of the
Inter-American Tropical Tuna Commission in La Jolla, Calif., which
sets fishing limits in the eastern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Friendly got a $170,000 federal research grant for the
project, one of the few backed annually by the Commerce Department.
Reducing the ``bycatch'' _ unintended netting of dolphins, sea
turtles and other species _ is a top concern of the agency's
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just funding the best of the best,'' said Joseph M.
Bishop, a Commerce official. ``Japan is at the cutting edge,''
using infrared imaging devices to seek the birds and dolphins that
are a telltale sign of tuna, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Friendly's prototype nets, finished in September 1998 by
Ocean Spar Technologies, a Seattle maker of sea cages, met a chilly
reception from American fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas thinks that an unwillingness to try new methods unraveled
a pledge by a Tacoma, Wash., shipowner to permit a crucial sea
trial of the drop net from one of its tuna trawlers. When the
company stopped returning his calls, Tom Meneghini, an Ocean
Friendly vice president, met the boat as it pulled into dock in
Guam in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way that drop net is coming aboard,'' the boat
captain told him, according to a report Ocean Friendly filed with
the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing company's president, Joseph S. Martinac, said a
trial was aborted over potential liability issues as well as the
skipper's reluctance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Ocean Friendly scrambled for another option, and the money to
pay for a demonstration, Commerce officials agreed to let the net
be tested outside American waters. Thomas settled on New Zealand,
where migrating fish often school close to land; he calculated that
a helicopter could carry a net a few miles from shore; no reluctant
boat captains would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Tangled lines did not figure in his thinking, however. Nor did
running out of money. When the grant ended in September, Thomas
tapped some of his 28 private investors. For his personal needs,
his sister lent him $400. He raised $4,000 by selling his
Volkswagen van.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always concerned he's going to starve to death,'' said
Leon La Porte, a commerce official. ``We funded him as far as we
can,'' he said, adding that Thomas has resisted fresh rounds of
venture capital to avoid ceding control.
</P>
<P>
   Other governments may help. The Green Party of New Zealand wants
the minister of fisheries to consider support for Ocean Friendly
and has scheduled a presentation. Indonesia, which granted Ocean
Friendly fishing licenses, has also asked for a presentation from
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this is certain. ``I'm having difficulty getting a
read on the potential for support from the governments of New
Zealand and Indonesia,'' Meneghini said. ``They are long shots, in
my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   During the years that Thomas has been proving his concept, new
methods for managing fish resources have been emerging _ a change
that could benefit his company. Besides the familiar Norwegian
salmon farms, aquaculture is taking hold in countries like the
Philippines, Australia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Gary F. Loverich, chairman and senior engineer of Ocean Spar,
says the drop net _ which his company made for $18,000 _ is a
reasonable fit with aquaculture, particularly for countries short
of cash. ``You don't have to buy big boats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loverich figures that Ocean Spar will soon be making Ocean
Friendly nets. ``This would not have happened without Kent,'' he
said. ``He's got a PhD in tenacity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
