<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SAID TO OFFER PLAN TO SETTLE ANTITRUST CASE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft presented a proposal in an attempt to settle the
antitrust case filed by the Justice Department and 19 states
against the company. Lawyers were studying the plan to decide
whether it was promising enough to warrant weekend negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the government said Microsoft agreed to
restrain some of its business practices but the document contained
so many technical details that they could not analyze it quickly.
Judge Richard A. Posner, chief judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals
in Chicago who is acting as a mediator in the case, has urged the
two sides to resolve the case quickly.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS, BUT NASDAQ RISES AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   A volatile week on Wall Street ended quietly, as the Dow Jones
industrial average fell slightly and the technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index crept closer to the record it set earlier in March.
The Dow was down 7.14 points, to 11,112.72, while the Nasdaq rose
22.42 points, to 4,963.03. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
rose 0.11 point, to 1,527.46. The real action Friday was in the
bond market, with the price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond
falling, sending the bond's yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from its price, up to 5.99 percent from 5.91 percent on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN BEER PRICES INVESTIGATED
</P>
<P>
   European investigators looking into the retail price of beer
made surprise visits to five breweries, including Grolsch and
Heineken in the Netherlands and Italian brewer Peroni, to
investigate documents that may shed light on how the industry sets
its prices.
</P>
<P>
   STEELMAKER BIDS FOR CAR-PARTS UNIT
</P>
<P>
   British mobile-telephone giant Vodafone AirTouch said that it
had received an unsolicited offer from ThyssenKrupp, Germany's
largest steelmaker, for the car-parts and engineering unit of
Mannesmann, which Vodafone recently agreed to acquire for $183
billion. Analysts said a deal for the car-parts and engineering
unit could be worth $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON LAUDS INDIA'S TECH INDUSTRY
</P>
<P>
   India's information technology industry, the core of the
country's steady economic growth, was saluted by President Clinton,
who, on the final full day of his visit to the country, was
promoting trade between India and the United States, and more U.S.
investment in India.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS DECLINE 2.3 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Orders for durable goods declined by 2.3 percent in February,
the second consecutive monthly decline and the largest in 10
months. The figure was lower than analysts had expected, but was
still 7.3 percent higher than a year earlier, indicating that the
recovery by the manufacturing sector of the economy from the global
financial crisis of 1997-99 remained on track.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON MOBIL CHALLENGES ARCO SALE
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil said that it sued to block the sale of Atlantic
Richfield Co.'s Alaskan oil fields to Phillips Petroleum,
contending that it had the right of first refusal to purchase some
of the assets. The lawsuit seeks a preliminary injunction that
could delay BP Amoco's proposed $33 billion purchase of ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AMERICAN AUTO TRADE PACT
</P>
<P>
   South America's two largest countries, Brazil and Argentina,
reached an agreement on the trade of automobiles. The five-year
accord will establish an equal balance of imports and exports
between the two nations, in addition to a shared tariff of 35
percent on imports from outside the Mercosur trade bloc, which
includes Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   IBM DEVELOPING TV INTERNET CHIP
</P>
<P>
   IBM said it was developing technology to provide Internet access
on television sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
