<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEW-IDEAS-BALKANS-1ST     03-24 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-IDEAS-BALKANS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLAR STRESSES COOPERATIVE ASPECT OF BALKANS' HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct historical inaccuracy in 9th graf by deleting the
three words ``were created. They.'' That part of the sentence now
should read ``and Albania went on...'' Sentence also has been
re-punctuated.)  
(mk) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Karen Barkey is far from alone among scholars in
trying to untangle the Balkans' tumultuous past and present.
Shelfloads of books and articles have been written on the region's
ancient ethnic and religious hatreds as well as on the modern
machinations of today's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkey, a sociologist at Columbia University, argues that
the region's history is much more cooperative than many of the
current explanations suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about the Balkans as a powder keg, the Balkans
and ethnic nationalism and ethnic cleansing,'' she said, ``but
there is a lot that is nonethnic and much more interesting, such as
the traders, the way in which society ordered itself, even with
religion and the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkey is of Turkish-Jewish origin, a native of Istanbul,
Turkey, and is now at work on a book about the historical roots of
the Balkan conflict. She believes it is crucial to rethink the
structure of the Ottoman Empire in the 18th century, a pivotal
period in the region's history.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 18th century, Barkey said, the Ottomans had developed
a vertically organized society in which every level looked to the
state. If conflicts arose, for instance, the peasants, traders or
local officials involved would confer with the person above them,
following a chain of command that ultimately led to Constantinople.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 18th century, Barkey argues, those vertical lines of
association began to fracture because of a reorganization of the
empire's system of rule and taxation, which transformed the way in
which people did business. People started turning to other members
of the same group or class to resolve disputes. Neighbors sorted
out problems with neighbors. Civic associations formed. Traders
dealt with their difficulties through a proliferation of trade
associations and networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an unbelievable mixing of people, the creating of
low-level, autonomous, free associations,'' Barkey said. ``People
started creating slowly a civil society in the 18th century that
was kind of removed from the state.''
</P>
<P>
   She believes that if these groups of traders, merchants and
multireligious networks had become more powerful, a more diverse
Balkans would have been the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Barkey said, although more tolerance developed, it did
not lead to greater civic cooperation. War with the Hapsburg and
Russian empires along with ideas of self-determination that were
imported from Western Europe produced a fractious legacy. When the
Ottoman Empire broke up after World War I, a number of insecure
nations like Serbia, Greece, Romania, Bulgaria and Albania went on
to fight for territory among themselves, which in turn led to
further divisions and warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these groups that were so interethnic and understood each
other and their differences,'' she said, ``they became the losers
in many ways. Understanding didn't win out. What wins out is the
war, the warriors, the warlords emerge and that kind of defines the
Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkey takes issue with policy analysts and historians who, she
believes, focus too much on nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my work is to show that the Balkans cooperated and
lived together and produced social capital for a long time. We have
to emphasize that as well as understand the conditions in which
they became antagonistic to each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
