<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-CULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BODIES FOUND FROM UGANDA CULT; MURDER IS SUSPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HENRI CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MBARARA, Uganda _ The Ugandan police said Friday that they had
discovered the bodies of 153 people buried in shallow graves on a
patch of land belonging to the same doomsday cult involved in the
mass deaths of hundreds of its followers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The people were murdered, and among the dead were at least 59
children, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were killed,'' said Eric Naigambi, the deputy spokesman
for the police. ``With 153 people, how could it be anything else?
They are trying to figure out how they were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, hundreds of followers of the group, the Movement for
the Restoration of the Ten Commandments of God, died in a fire in a
makeshift church at their headquarters in Kanungu, on the
southwestern edge of the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the fire appeared at first to be a mass suicide, motivated
by prophecies about the end of the world, evidence is mounting that
the fire, which took at least 330 lives, may have been murder.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators went to the site of Thursday's discovery, about 30
miles from Kanungu, in search of additional information on the
group, which had a base in the town as well, according to local
news media here in the regional capital. ``They had reasonable
suspicions that there were mass graves around that place,''
Naigambi said.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived, the investigators noticed a foul odor and
immediately began digging, the local news media said. They found at
least two mass graves, one with 105 bodies and the other with 48
bodies, according to local news media.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the victims appeared to have been strangled, while
others may have been slashed, the police told Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second discovery of more dead bodies in the week
since the fire. On Tuesday, the bodies of six people were pulled
from a pit latrine in a building next to the site of the fire. The
six people, who could not be identified, also appeared to have been
slain, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Already staggered by the scale of the investigation, the
country's police now have an even more complicated case to piece
together.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investigators have not found any survivors of the fire
last week, which has left the police and the public with, at best
educated hypotheses, and at worst wild conjecture, as they try to
figure out what happened in the makeshift church on that morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of followers of the cult, which promotes a return to
life according to the Ten Commandments, assembled in the hillside
chapel on March 17, perhaps for a morning of prayer, perhaps for a
morning that they were told would mark the end of the world as they
knew it.
</P>
<P>
   They were lured into one room, and no one is known to have made
it out. A raging fire swept the room, apparently killing everyone
inside. Amid the charred detritus of the building and its
occupants, the police were able to count 330 people dead. But an
untold number are believed to have been burned to ashes, so the
exact toll may never be known.
</P>
<P>
   As the police have learned more about the cult, they have begun
looking at the case more as a murder investigation and less as a
suicide. ``We feel the leaders of this cult murdered their
followers,'' the police department's deputy regional commander,
Stephen Musoke, said Friday in an interview here.
</P>
<P>
   Founded about a decade ago, the movement imposed a rigid
lifestyle on its adherents, encouraging them to give up sex even
between married couples, and demanding that they sell off all their
possessions and contribute the proceeds to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   It is the last finding that has emerged as most troubling to
police, who suspect that the cult's leaders may have been fleecing
their flock. ``It looks like they have been robbing the people,''
Musoke said.
</P>
<P>
   That theory has led police to suspect that the cult's leaders
may have eluded or escaped the fire. ``We think that some of the
leaders may be off somewhere enjoying this wealth,'' Musoke said.
``We are really looking for these people using all of our available
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top of their list is Joseph Kibwetere, 68, who helped
found the sect, and became the spiritual and financial force behind
it. Active in the region's Roman Catholic life for many years, he
was a teacher and a supervisor in Catholic schools. But he broke
with the Catholic Church in the late '80s and was eventually
expelled by the local bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the cult's membership have ranged from 1,000 to
5,000. And it is only the most troubling tip of a problem the
government faces with religious cults, which have been growing in
popularity in recent years. The government has tried to crack down
on those that have emerged as threats to security, including two
shut down recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
