A7466 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-24 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HELP THE STUDENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ The first thing the UCLA basketball
players scoped out after checking in at their hotel here Tuesday
afternoon wasn't the minibar or anything in a miniskirt. It wasn't
the room-service menu, the game room, the pay-movie selections or
the shopping mall across the street.
</P>
<P>
   For starting point guard Earl Watson and six of his teammates
who also were enrolled this quarter in a ``History of the European
Economy in the 20th Century'' course, their priority was locating
computers on which they could compose the 10- to 12-page research
papers that had to be faxed to their professor by Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State's suffocating defense two nights later wouldn't
strike as much terror in Watson as did the sight in the hotel of a
solitary computer that all the Bruins were going to have to share.
Next to divvying one computer among seven guys, Watson has to admit
sharing one basketball among five players is a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Watson was wise enough not to even try. He and a couple of other
players located a Kinko's that was open all night and paid to use
the computers until four in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, after spending most of their afternoon at The
Palace for practice and mandatory media interviews, Watson and
senior forward Sean Farnham sat at opposite ends of a hotel room,
taking a 100-question multiple-choice exam in astronomy under the
fierce gaze of a member of the Bruins' academic staff.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the dark side of Bracketville. Come tournament time,
the NCAA loves to parade its participating players _ um, excuse us,
make that !ital!student-athletes _ as paragons of higher education.
For all the lip service paid to academics via endless
student-athlete references and the florid public-service spots
during the network telecasts of the games, you'd think State U's
monster rebounder was also a Renaissance man.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the NCAA could do a lot more to help the basketball
player who is sincerely trying to be a student. It certainly
couldn't do much less.
</P>
<P>
   It sends players across the country with 48 or 72 hours' notice
for the first two rounds of the tournament, their class schedules
(or in the case of the Bruins, their final-exam schedules) be
damned. It parades them in front of television cameras and
reporters for hours on end and schedules their games so some end
well past midnight, local time.
</P>
<P>
   The players are too keyed up the day of a do-or-die tournament
game to get much quality studying in and they're too spent
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA can make its athletes account for every dollar in their
pockets. Yet there has been no concerted campaign to keep track of
every hour of study and class time lost in the name of promoting
and playing in the revenue-rich postseason extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' said UCLA junior swingman Todd Ramasar, ``I
think the term during the NCAAs should be athlete-student.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get no argument from Farnham, who said, ``During the (NCAA
postseason) everything is focused on athletics. People are coming
up to you and asking who's going to win and boosters who fly in for
the games want to wish you luck and there are a lot more demands on
your time, in general. No matter how hard you try, academics is
going to fade to number two. That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramasar redshirted this season after undergoing shoulder surgery
in October. He felt overburdened this week just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of uptight, kind of stressing out and I'm not even
playing,'' Ramasar said when stopped in a hallway at the Bruins'
hotel Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He did look a little fidgety just standing there. Ramasar had
inhaled a continental breakfast and was hurrying back to his room
to get ready for two history essay exams stacked one on top of the
other, starting later in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of his teammates, Ramasar had gotten back to the
hotel at about 2 a.m. after the Bruins' 24-point loss to Iowa
State. He stayed up for three more hours studying. His eyes were as
red as the lettering on Iowa State's jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's left eye was nearly swollen shut Friday. He admits he
started to panic after he absorbed an elbow to the eye in UCLA's
blowout win over Maryland last Saturday that required four stitches
and led to laser eye surgery two days later.
</P>
<P>
   People who didn't know any better thought he was alarmed he
wouldn't be able to play against Iowa State. That wasn't it. Watson
was worried he wouldn't be able to see well enough to prepare
properly for his exams.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was my scariest thought,'' Watson said. ``I was thinking,
`How am I supposed to study when I can't see anything?' On
Wednesday my vision was still blurry and I had really bad
headaches.''
</P>
<P>
   He considered asking his professors if he could postpone his
exams until next week, when the student body is on spring break.
Watson decided against it, reasoning, ``If I was a professor, I'd
say if you can play basketball, then you can take your exams.''
</P>
<P>
   Copernicus couldn't keep Watson out of the Midwest Regional
semifinal. On Wednesday he sat in a room with Farnham and took his
astronomy exam, as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Watson and the others would get a welcome reprieve from their
economics professor. After explaining the computer crisis at the
hotel in an e-mail to the professor, the players were granted an
extension on their papers.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of worrying about finishing them this week, they get
to spend their spring break writing at length on such topics as,
``The great Depression and its effect on the German economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, basketball players at UCLA certainly do lead charmed lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we not been able to get an extension on our papers,''
Farnham said, ``you would have seen the whole team at Kinko's
before and after the (Iowa State) game trying to finish them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating for us,'' he added. ``We want to handle
our business. Sometimes there's just circumstances out of our
control.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has the power to help. It could lean on a sponsor to
lend laptop computers to the participating teams, if nothing else.
It should do something, lest people start to think NCAA stands for
Not Caring About Academics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
