<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON MAINTAINS CONTROL OF EMOTIONS AND ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ In almost every round at the Players
Championship, adversity is unavoidable. Players who remain
resilient have a chance to win. Players who succumb to frustration
find themselves hopelessly behind.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton reached a crucial crossroad midway through Friday's
round, when back-to-back bogeys threatened to send him tumbling off
the leader board. But instead of collapsing, Sutton regrouped with
three consecutive birdies. And at the midway point of a demanding
tournament, Sutton remained the man to catch.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting his second consecutive 69, including a 32 over his
final nine holes, Sutton held a one-stroke lead at six under par
for the tournament (138) after Friday's second round of the TPC at
Sawgrass. Tom Lehman and Omar Uresti, both of whom shot 68, were
tied for second place at five under par, while Fulton Allem, who
had the tournament's best round (65), was in fourth place at four
under par.
</P>
<P>
   Only nine players remained under par in an event that has forced
some of the world's best players to reach for a pain reliever.
Tiger Woods, who shot 71, was tied at two under par with Ernie Els
and Len Mattiace, while Lee Janzen and Scott Dunlap were tied at
one under par.
</P>
<P>
   It will be an interesting weekend with names like Sutton,
Lehman, Woods, Els and Janzen chasing the biggest purse in golf
($1.08 million) on a course that demands excellent play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great test,'' said Sutton, who answered a bogey
at No. 18 with birdies at Nos. 1, 2 and 3. ``There are times where
we are switching from offense to defense. You've got to be smart
enough to know when to hit the accelerator and when to hit the
brake. I think that's what makes this course great. It's easy to
hit the accelerator constantly, or to hit the brake constantly.
It's hard to know when to hit each one.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, this tournament showed no mercy for those who were
not playing well, even though the wind was much calmer than it was
during Thursday's first round. Prominent names who missed the
six-over-par-cut included Jesper Parnevik (seven over), Darren
Clarke (seven over), Phil Mickelson (10 over), Jose Maria Olazabal
(10 over), Sergio Garcia (10 over), and Duffy Waldorf (14 over).
The defending champion David Duval made a costly double bogey on
No. 18, and fell to four over par for the tournament, 10 strokes
behind Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Even the leaders had their precarious moments. Woods (one
under), who has yet to break 70 in 14 rounds at Sawgrass, was
nearly victimized by the island green at No. 17. On Thursday, Woods
hit his tee shot at 17 into the water, which led to a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a gust of wind grabbed his 8-iron tee shot from 145
yards and sent it left of the pin. The ball landed on the green,
but trickled down the slope and came to rest at the edge of green,
just an inch from tumbling into the water. Balancing himself on the
ledge, with his heels hanging over the water, Woods used a 3-wood
to putt up the hill, then made an 8-footer to save par.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Woods escape without a bogey, but he did not fall
into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Stevie to grab me if a gust of wind came,'' said Woods,
referring to his caddie, Steve Williams. ``I'm proud of my round
today because as well as I hit the ball, I didn't think I deserved
to be even par.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods had to scramble, and he made his second double bogey
of the tournament at the par-4 No. 4. He caught a bad break on that
hole, when his drive landed in a sand divot. Woods' next shot was
short and right of the green, then his chip from a terrible lie was
still 30 feet short of the hole. Woods lagged his putt to four
feet, but he missed the 4-foot bogey attempt and walked away with a
double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Woods ended the day with a birdie at the par-5, 583-yard ninth
hole. After a huge drive, Woods hit a monstrous 3-wood from 255
yards that nearly reached the green, then chipped to 8 feet and
made the putt. That left Woods in his best position ever at the
Players Championship starting a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm right in the hunt with a chance to win,'' said Woods,
hoping to win for the fourth time in seven starts this year. ``And
I'm very pleased with how I'm hitting the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Sutton, who bounced back after hitting his tee shot into
the water at No. 18. After taking a drop, his next shot from the
deep rough almost landed in the water again, stopping a foot from
the bank. But Sutton chipped to 12 feet, then made the putt to save
bogey. After making the turn, Sutton made a 12-footer for birdie at
No. 1, and 18-footers for birdies at No. 2 and No. 3. As a result,
Sutton will start the weekend in front, with some impressive names
close behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any difference,'' said Sutton, when asked if
he noticed the names on the leader board. ``I can only control
myself, and I'm out of control half the time. I'm going to do the
best I can with me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
