<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS' CLEAVES PROVIDES INSPIRATION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Michigan State trailed Syracuse by 10
points Thursday night, and Mateen Cleaves was so angry that he
stormed into the locker room's bathroom and herded the Spartans
freshmen out of their usual halftime hiding place. His teammate,
the starting power forward A.J. Granger, smiled about the scene
Friday, but made it clear no one was laughing at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He charged in and screamed at them to `get out here now, you
guys need to hear this, too,''' said Granger, explaining that the
young reserves usually try to get as far away from the team's
intense point guard as they can during tight games. ``He's the type
of guy to lead the charge in the locker room, and it's better than
just hearing it from the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   So in a voice as gravelly as the abrasive style he plays,
Cleaves, the senior point guard, laid down the law: missed shots
are one thing; not getting back on defense is an unacceptable other
thing. It was vintage Cleaves, and it powered the Spartans to an
explosive 75-58 victory over Syracuse and a spot in the Midwest
Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   When he spent the preseason and the Spartans' first 13 games on
the injured list with a stress fracture of his foot, Cleaves
demonstrated unwavering leadership. While his teammates practiced,
he sat on the side of the court working out on a combination
bicycle and rowing machine. ``He'd be there for an hour sweating
more than us,'' Granger said.
</P>
<P>
   When the top-seeded Spartans meet second-seeded Iowa State on
Saturday night in the regional final, Cleaves will take on a
less-heralded but just as maniacal point guard in Jamaal Tinsley of
Brooklyn. Asked who would win a playground one-on-one between
Cleaves and Tinsley, Iowa State's all-American forward Marcus Fizer
slumped in his chair and just sighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that would decide that game is who got
dehydrated first and passed out,'' Fizer said. ``I'd like to watch
them go at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the nation will see 10 players on the floor and two
teams that absolutely believe that NCAA tournament games are won
and lost on the defensive end. The Spartans have won eight straight
games overall by holding opponents to 54.4 points a game and 36
percent shooting. The Cyclones are just as suffocating: they held
opponents to 41 percent shooting from the field over 35 games, and
stifled UCLA _ a team that had scored 105 points last week against
Maryland _ in Thursday's 80-56 regional semifinal victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a game of individual matchups,'' Iowa State coach
Larry Eustachy said. ``It is our team versus their team. Neither
team got to where we are without a collection of great players, and
these are two great teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Cleaves was injured, Michigan State coach Tom Izzo
said, he improved the Spartans both on and off the court. His
impact was especially strong on his teammates and close friends
from Flint, Mich., Charlie Bell and Morris Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo said: ``When he was out, Charlie had to learn how to handle
the ball and create his shots, and Morris learned that this was his
team; he was the one to take the big shots. The great thing was
that Mateen was right there on the bench, in the locker room, on
the side of court reinforcing these things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans went 9-4 without Cleaves _ losing to Texas,
Arizona, Kentucky and Wright State. It was excruciating for
Cleaves, who had spent the spring and summer working on his
strength and shooting. He still cringes about losses he believes he
could have turned into victories, but he has been single-minded
since his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to look at the past,'' Cleaves said. ``I put my
mind and focus on the task at hand. If I run my team now, we can
win the title with three more victories.''
</P>
<P>
   But first Iowa State and Tinsley stand in his way. The muscular
guard barely missed a triple-double against UCLA _ he had 14
points, 11 assists and nine rebounds. Eustachy says the blossoming
during the tournament of Tinsley, a New York summer league legend,
has as much to do with his buying into Iowa State's structure as it
does with pure talent.
</P>
<P>
   The coach concedes he likes Tinsley's chances against Cleaves.
``He has an unconventional way of creating havoc,'' Eustachy said.
``He doesn't get enough credit for his discipline, thinking,
switching, finding the right post and running the offense. He can
play with the other guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
