<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CARWASH-SLAYING-TEX     03-24 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARWASH-SLAYING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHER SAYS SLAYING SUSPECT MISLED HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MITCH MITCHELL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ William Harris said his brother, murder suspect
Robert Wayne Harris, misled him and apparently police about how the
slayings at the Mi-T-Fine Car Wash in Irving took place Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At first, William Harris said, he believed his brother's account
that he had snapped while arguing with a carwash manager when he
asked for his job back. Now, William Harris said, his brother's
account doesn't match the evidence _ and his brother didn't tell
him about his connection to Sandra Estes Scott, in whose slaying he
is also the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   William Harris said that he is unsure about what happened at the
carwash and about his brother's lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I knew him,'' William Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him to look me in the eye and tell me the truth,
because I wanted to know,'' William Harris said. ``I was defending
him, and I wanted to know what happened so I would know what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The carwash victims were all shot in the head, and one had his
neck cut, according to medical examiner reports. Crime scene
experts said that the head wounds were consistent with calculated
killings, not with shootings that happen during a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harris, 28, was charged Friday with five counts of
capital murder and one count of attempted capital murder in the
carwash slayings, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   He is also is expected to face murder charges in the slaying of
Scott, 37, said David Tull, an Irving police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's body was found Wednesday morning after Robert Harris
told investigators where to find her, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was transferred Friday from the Irving Jail to the Lew
Sterrett Justice Center in Dallas. As he was being escorted into
the jail, Robert Harris quietly said he was sorry when asked if
there was anything he had to say to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harris is accused of fatally shooting five carwash
employees and critically wounding another. The dead are Dennis Lee,
48; Rhoda Wheeler, 45; Benjamin Villasenor, 32; and Roberto Jimenez
Jr., 15, all of Irving; and Agustin Villasenor, 36, of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Ramos, 36, of Irving was in critical condition Friday
night at Parkland Memorial Hospital in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   William Harris said that he has spoken to a relative of one of
the victims, and that the families are praying for each other.
</P>
<P>
   But the agony experienced by the families touched by these
shootings has caused William Harris to search his memories for
missed opportunities that might have prevented Monday's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been tormenting myself,'' he said. ``I've felt guilty.
I've been looking for what I could have done differently that might
have made things different. I tried to help him, but maybe it was
the wrong kind of help.''
</P>
<P>
   The shame her husband feels is shared by her whole family,
Beverly Harris said. Beverly Harris said that she has been on both
sides of the situation. Her cousin was slain years ago, and Beverly
Harris said she remembers the pain that she and her sister felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on that side, and I've been on the other side,''
Beverly Harris said. ``The side of the accused is much worse. It's
one of the worst feelings you could ever have. You wonder if there
was anything you could have done, if you should have prayed harder,
if you should have witnessed to him more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for me has been watching'' her husband, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since getting out of prison in May, Robert Wayne Harris kept
most people in the dark about his life, William Harris said. He
said that he may have never really known his brother _ that he
remains unable to unlock whatever secrets his brother kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only memories I have of him are good memories, childhood
memories,'' William Harris said. ``I hold onto those. Those are
precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members were poor when they were children. Many of the
houses in the Dallas suburb where they lived are now boarded up and
condemned. William Harris was 10 when their parents separated after
moving from Lubbock. The father returned to Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   The family went from having what they needed to live an ordinary
middle-class life to being very poor, William Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom didn't work,'' William Harris said. ``It was like she
didn't have the will to do what it took to raise two children.''
</P>
<P>
   They ate syrup sandwiches, he said, and they had to borrow money
to keep the gas and lights from being cut off. Sometimes, one of
the boys would go next door to bring water home to bathe in, Harris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harris liked to work, his brother said. When he did odd
jobs around the neighborhood, he would give his mother half the
money and split the rest with him, William Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   William Harris said he and his brother had grown apart during
the past 11 years, most of which Robert spent in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got out, he got a driver's license, he got a job at
the carwash, and he got a 1980 Oldsmobile,'' William Harris said.
``He got a promotion at his job. They were small accomplishments
for most people, but it was a great deal for him.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Domingo Ramirez Jr. and Diane Smith contributed
to this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
