women are driven by value, naturally - but perhaps even more by the
thrill of the chase. At an open air market in SoHo, Susan Lazar, a
New York fashion designer, closes in on a $17 silk kerchief halter.
(Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
NUN-SISTER-KAROL -- If the nuns in ``The Sound of Music'' couldn't
figure out how to solve a problem like Maria, they would be
completely baffled by Sister Karol Jackowski, 53, who lives in the
East Village, has Margaritaville (cocktails, chips and pizza) each
week with her friends and calls chopped liver ``a major food group
for me.'' Life is more intense in New York City,'' said Sister
Karol, who has also written a book with the improbable title, ``Ten
Fun Things to Do Before You Die.'' ``The diversity here makes for
such a liberating environment.'' (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
NITEOUT-CHRISTENSEN-MODEL -- Since last spring, the Danish
supermodel Helena Christensen has held the impressive-sounding
title of creative director for Nylon magazine, a fashion-oriented
glossy that marked its first anniversary on Wednesday night with a
party at Skirt, a boutique in Manhattan. According to its Web site,
Nylon is ``the most hot magazine,'' devoted to covering ``life's
passionate participants, not it's fainthearted spectators.'' (Miles
Ladin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
OSCARS-PLACEMENT-2 -- Many envelopes will be ripped open Sunday
night at the 72nd annual Academy Awards. But not one will contain
instructions on how to display an Oscar at home so it won't look
preposterous. When visitors want to look, John Patrick Shanley has
to shine a light on his Oscar, which lives behind the television.
``I used to keep it in an athletic sock in the bottom of a laundry
bag in my apartment in Washington Heights,'' said Shanley, who won
the Academy Award for best original screenplay for ``Moonstruck''
in 1988. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
OSCARS-PLACEMENT-1 -- Many envelopes will be ripped open Sunday
night at the 72nd annual Academy Awards. But not one will contain
instructions on how to display an Oscar at home so it won't look
preposterous. Olympia Dukakis squeezes her trophies, including an
Oscar, onto a shelf in her home office. ``I tend not to display
things,'' said Dukakis, who won an Academy Award as best supporting
actress for her role in ``Moonstruck.'' (The original Oscar was
stolen; for $200, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
provided a replacement.) (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- FREUD-BOOKSTORE --
Sometimes a bookstore is just a bookstore. But as today's Freudians
should know, it can also be a publisher, a Website and a gathering
place, like the newest venture by analyst, academic, editor and
psychoanalytic entrepreneur Michael Moskowitz. His store, Other
Books in Chelsea, is just one of the tools he uses in his mission
to rescue psychoanalysis from the academic isolation and bitter
scholarly skirmishes that have dogged it for the last 20 years by
bridging the divide between clinicians and theorists. (Barbara
Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
BIZ-3COM-B&AMP;W -- Frank Manning, chief executive and president of
Zoom Telephonics in Boston, which sells modems under the Zoom and
Hayes brand names. ``Do I think analog modems are a highly
lucrative part of our business?'' he asks. ``No. But it's very
dangerous to just focus on the high-growth areas and abandon
customers when a segment slows down.'' (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LONGVIEW, Texas -- March 24, 2000 -- BELLY-DANCERS-3-COX
-- The belly dancing course at the Panther Park Community Center in
Longview attracted more students than anticipated, and what was
originally supposed to be one class became three. Amy Easley,
foreground, and Gabriela Cotton practiced during a recent belly
dancing class at the center. (Bahram Mark Sobhani/The Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LONGVIEW, Texas -- March 24, 2000 -- BELLY-DANCERS-2-COX
-- Belly dancing is not your mother's two-step. It's not even her
Lambada. Actually, it's better because it's all about being a woman
- in a way that Shania Twain can't touch. But she probably could
learn a few things, and the belly dancing course at the Panther
Park Community Center in Longview has the answers. Jessica
Winchester practiced her hip movements during a recent class.
(Bahram Mark Sobhani/The Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LONGVIEW, Texas -- March 24, 2000 -- BELLY-DANCERS-1-COX
-- The belly dancing course at the Panther Park Community Center in
Longview attracted more students than anticipated, and what was
originally supposed to be one class became three. Damiana led a
recent belly dancing class at the center. (Bahram Mark Sobhani/The
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HOUSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- BARBER-FAMILY-HNS --
Whenever the Ortuno family gets together, you could say it's a
hair-raising experience. The extended family of barbers at
Peluqueria Acapulco Unisex No. 1 and Acapulco Barber Shop No. 2
includes, from left, Marisela Ortuno, Gloria Rodriguez, Janete
Ortuno Castro, Manuel Ortuno, Mayda Ortuno, Ezequiel Ortuno, Amado
Ortuno, Laura Fraire and Laticia Ramirez, seated in the barber
chair. (Andrew Innerarity/The Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MOSCOW -- March 24, 2000 -- RUSSIA-ELECTION -- In an ugly
burst of negative campaigning appearing just days before the
presidential election, Russia's state-owned television has aired
television spots charging that the nation's leading liberal
candidate, Grigori Yavlinsky, is supported by Jews, foreigners and
homosexuals. At top, two men claiming to be homosexual proclaim
their support for Yavlinsky. At bottom, video from a dinner hosted
by a financial backer of Yavlinsky showing members of Moscow's
Orthodox Jewish community in attendance. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MONUMENT BEACH, Mass. -- March 24, 2000 --
OSCARS-RICHARDSON -- He's jumped out of airplanes and filmed with
bullets whizzing by his head, but the thought of going to Sunday
night's Academy Awards, where he's nominated for an Oscar for his
work as director of photography in ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' fills
him with fear. So Robert Richardson plans to hole up at home on
Cape Cod, watching the telecast with his family. (Barry Chin/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BELMAR BEACH, N.J. -- March 24, 2000 -- SPRING-FLOATER --
Pat Gargiulo and her daughter Kim Leonard sit by the shore as a
group of people walk their dog Friday afternoon. Dry and
unseasonably mild weather covered most of the East on Friday
reinforcing the arrival of spring earlier this week. (Dith Pran/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOUND BROOK, N.J. -- March 24, 2000 -- VIDEO-GAMES -- Al
and Shelley Gomolka of Bound Brook, N.J., with their son Jacob, 4,
watch President Clinton's state of the union address as his son
Joshua, 9, plays on his Nintendo Game Boy. Nintendo reigns as the
uncontested heavyweight champion of selling bantamweight games you
can hold in the palm of your hand, boasting more than 99 percent of
the market. While there has been no lack of would-be rivals, the
Game Boy engenders fierce customer loyalty and has so far proven
impervious to competition. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- USAIR-UNION-2 -- Lisa
Holcombe and her husband Jamie, center, both flight attendants for
US Air for some 35 years combined, are among dozens of US Air
employees picketing outside the departure area at Logan airport,
Thursday. US Air, the nation's sixth largest airline, is facing a
possible walkout by flight attendants at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday
unless negotiators, meeting with federal mediators in Washington,
can resolve a three-year contract dispute. (John Tlumacki/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- USAIR-UNION -- US Air, the
nation's sixth largest airline, is facing a possible walkout by
flight attendants at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday unless negotiators,
meeting with federal mediators in Washington, can resolve a
three-year contract dispute. Passengers wait on line at the ticket
counters at USAIR at Boston's Logan Airport late Thursday. (John
Tlumacki/The Boston Globe)
</P>
