</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MOSCOW -- March 24, 2000 -- RUSSIA-ELECTION -- In an ugly
burst of negative campaigning appearing just days before the
presidential election, Russia's state-owned television has aired
television spots charging that the nation's leading liberal
candidate, Grigori Yavlinsky, is supported by Jews, foreigners and
homosexuals. At top, two men claiming to be homosexual proclaim
their support for Yavlinsky. At bottom, video from a dinner hosted
by a financial backer of Yavlinsky showing members of Moscow's
Orthodox Jewish community in attendance. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MONUMENT BEACH, Mass. -- March 24, 2000 --
OSCARS-RICHARDSON -- He's jumped out of airplanes and filmed with
bullets whizzing by his head, but the thought of going to Sunday
night's Academy Awards, where he's nominated for an Oscar for his
work as director of photography in ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' fills
him with fear. So Robert Richardson plans to hole up at home on
Cape Cod, watching the telecast with his family. (Barry Chin/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BELMAR BEACH, N.J. -- March 24, 2000 -- SPRING-FLOATER --
Pat Gargiulo and her daughter Kim Leonard sit by the shore as a
group of people walk their dog Friday afternoon. Dry and
unseasonably mild weather covered most of the East on Friday
reinforcing the arrival of spring earlier this week. (Dith Pran/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOUND BROOK, N.J. -- March 24, 2000 -- VIDEO-GAMES -- Al
and Shelley Gomolka of Bound Brook, N.J., with their son Jacob, 4,
watch President Clinton's state of the union address as his son
Joshua, 9, plays on his Nintendo Game Boy. Nintendo reigns as the
uncontested heavyweight champion of selling bantamweight games you
can hold in the palm of your hand, boasting more than 99 percent of
the market. While there has been no lack of would-be rivals, the
Game Boy engenders fierce customer loyalty and has so far proven
impervious to competition. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- USAIR-UNION-2 -- Lisa
Holcombe and her husband Jamie, center, both flight attendants for
US Air for some 35 years combined, are among dozens of US Air
employees picketing outside the departure area at Logan airport,
Thursday. US Air, the nation's sixth largest airline, is facing a
possible walkout by flight attendants at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday
unless negotiators, meeting with federal mediators in Washington,
can resolve a three-year contract dispute. (John Tlumacki/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- USAIR-UNION -- US Air, the
nation's sixth largest airline, is facing a possible walkout by
flight attendants at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday unless negotiators,
meeting with federal mediators in Washington, can resolve a
three-year contract dispute. Passengers wait on line at the ticket
counters at USAIR at Boston's Logan Airport late Thursday. (John
Tlumacki/The Boston Globe)
</P>
