<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 03/24/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- NY-SUPERS-INTERNET -- In
class, building supers learn about Web-linked software that has
helpful categories like ``Leak in Faucet.'' Frank Fischedick, top,
trains supers to use EdificeRex, a Web site billed as the world's
first Internet portal for residents of specific co-ops and
condominiums. The service has been introduced in 300 high-end
apartment houses managed by the Insignia Residential Group, a
division of the largest real-estate services company in New York.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- NY-DORISMOND-WAKE-2 --
Anger and grief mingled as thousands of mourners filed past the
coffin of police shooting victim Patrick Dorismond on Friday, and
some protesters called for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's resignation
over his controversial response to the death. Two unidentified
women held Haitian flags as they watched the scene outside from a
window of the Andrew Torregrossa funeral home in Marine Park,
Brooklyn. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- NY-DORISMOND-WAKE-1 --
Anger and grief mingled as thousands of mourners filed past the
coffin of police shooting victim Patrick Dorismond on Friday, and
some protesters called for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's resignation
over his controversial response to the death. A small group of
demonstrators stood across the street from the funeral home
conducting Dorismond's wake in Marine Park, Brooklyn; holding a
sign at right is Marie Pyrol, a cousin of Dorismond's mother. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- MASS-ROBINSON -- Jack E.
Robinson III, Republican Senate candidate from Massachusetts, isn't
waiting for the media to skewer him. Robinson, a 39-year-old
businessman, sixth-generation Republican and first-time candidate,
has already posted ``The Robinson Report'' on his campaign Web
site. Perhaps the most notable effort at a pre-emptive political
strike of the Internet era, it lists and explains every incident in
his life that he thought might be fodder for attacks. (Jared
Leeds/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) DENVER -- March 24, 2000 -- COLO-OWENS-RAMSEY -- For
reasons not entirely clear, Gov. Bill Owens, R-Colo., has injected
himself into the murder investigation of JonBenet Ramsey, the
6-year-old girl who was found beaten and strangled in the basement
of her home in Boulder more than three years ago. This week, Owens
repeated his call for the Ramseys to face investigators and told
ABC's ``Good Morning America'' that ``the focus on this case is
really on Patsy Ramsey.'' No one else involved with the case has
come so close publicly to naming a possible suspect. (Kevin
Moloney/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNITED NATIONS -- March 24, 2000 -- IRAQ-U.N.-2 -- At a
special daylong Security Council session Friday to review the
organization's work in Iraq, James B. Cunningham, the deputy U.S.
representative at the United Nations, announced that the United
States was lifting its holds on 70 contracts worth at least $100
million in the Iraqi sanctions committee, which reviews Iraqi
orders. The United States also formally introduced its resolution
doubling to $600 million the value of oil equipment Iraq may import
every six months. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) AREQUIPA, Peru -- March 23, 2000 -- PERU-POLITICS-2 --
Susana Higuchi, right, campaigning in Arequipa for a seat in Peru's
Congress along with Adelita Arratia, another congressional
candidate. Higuchi, who has been denouncing President Alberto
Fujimori, from whom she divorced four years ago, is running a
strong campaign for Congress, and many pollsters predict she will
win even though she is attached to a minor left-leaning political
party. (Ana Cecilia Gonzales-Vigil/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A -- ``In many ways the fundamentals for oil
stocks have never been better,'' said William L. Randol, senior
petroleum analyst at Banc of America Securities. ``The price of the
commodity is higher than anyone would have thought. We think oil
will settle this year at around $25 a barrel. Companies can do very
well with prices at that level, because they cut their costs
dramatically as oil prices fell in the 1980s and the 1990s.'' (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNITED NATIONS -- March 24, 2000 -- IRAQ-U.N. -- At a
special daylong Security Council session Friday to review the
organization's work in Iraq, Peter van Walsum, the Dutch
representative and chairman of the council's Iraqi sanctions
committee, said that despite differences, there was a council
consensus that Iraq still has to convince the world that it does
not have dreams of creating prohibited weapons. Van Walsum said
Iraq's violent track record placed the country ``in a league of its
own.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SHAKHTY, Russia -- March 24, 2000 -- RUSSIA-MINERS-2 --
A miner with a bag of coal after finishing his shift at the October
Revolution mine some 600 miles south of Moscow earlier this week.
Each miner is allowed to take home some coal for personal use. As
Russians prepare to go to the polls this weekend to elect a new
president, the coal miners in this region find themselves, like
many Russians, trying to decide whether to support the acknowledged
frontrunner, Acting President Vladimir V. Putin, or to cast a
protest vote by supporting one of the other 10 candidates.
(Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SHAKHTY, Russia -- March 24, 2000 -- RUSSIA-MINERS --
Miners inside The October Revolution Mine some 600 miles south of
Moscow. As Russians prepare to go to the polls this weekend to
elect a new president, the coal miners in this region find
themselves, like many Russians, trying to decide whether to support
the acknowledged frontrunner, Acting President Vladimir V. Putin,
or to cast a protest vote by supporting one of the other 10
candidates. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) AREQUIPA, Peru -- March 23, 2000 -- PERU-POLITICS --
Susana Higuchi, former wife of President Alberto Fujimori of Peru,
waved her now famous broom during a campaign stop in the municipal
market earlier this week. Higuchi, divorced from Fujimori four
years ago, is running a strong campaign for Congress, and many
pollsters predict she will win even though she is attached to a
minor left-leaning political party. Higuchi, who carries a symbolic
broom on the stump, is calling for social justice and an end to
what she calls ``the dictatorship'' led by her former husband.
Second from right is Adelita Arratia, running for local office on
Higuchi's ticket. (Ana Cecilia Gonzales-Vigil/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- OBIT-VENTURELLI-B&AMP;W --
Helen Venturelli, a champion of better benefits for widows of
police officers and firefighters killed on the job, died March 15
at Westchester Square Hospital in the Bronx. She was 86 and lived
in the Bronx. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- March 24, 2000 -- VIDEO-GAMES-2 -- The last
month has redefined the videogame business worldwide. In Japan,
Sony sold nearly a million Playstation 2 videogame consoles in
their first two days on the market. In California, Microsoft jolted
the industry with the announcement of X-Box, a Windows PC
masquerading as a videogame console. But amid all the noise from
the two giants, it is easy to forget the $4.2 billion industry's
greatest ``bit'' player of all - the little Game Boy. (The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- USAIR-UNION-4 -- US Airways
flight attendants picketed outside Terminal B at Logan Airport on
Friday. US Airways Group Inc. and the union representing its 10,000
flight attendants huddled Friday in 11th-hour talks aimed at
averting a threatened shutdown of the sixth-largest U.S. airline
this weekend. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- USAIR-UNION-3 -- US Airways
flight attendants picketed outside Terminal B at Logan Airport on
Friday. US Airways Group Inc. and the union representing its 10,000
flight attendants huddled Friday in 11th-hour talks aimed at
averting a threatened shutdown of the sixth-largest U.S. airline
this weekend. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- March 24, 2000 -- GAYS-MILITARY --
Anti-gay speech and harassment is commonplace in the U.S. military,
especially among young enlisted troops, according to a Pentagon
inspector general's survey released Friday. Deputy Under Secretary
for Planning Frank Rush pondered a question from the press during a
briefing on the results of the survey. (Susana Raab/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
CAR-SMART-SUVs -- The Lexus RX300, built like a car. While most
sport utilities, including luxury models like the Cadillac Escalade
and Lincoln Navigator, have bodies fixed to truck frames,
crossovers like the Lexus RX300 and BMW X5 use one-piece unit
bodies like those found on most cars. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
ABOUT-CARS-BMW-2 -- BMW would prefer that you not call the X5 an
SUV, but a ``sports activity vehicle.'' While it differs
considerably in some ways from other rugged-outside, soft-inside
vehicles, in the end it is perhaps not so different after all. (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
ABOUT-CARS-BMW-1 -- Responsive and plush, the BMW X5 lacks the
utility and off-road prowess of an SUV. However much the company
would like you to consider the X5 a new concept in transportation,
it walks and quacks much like a duck, er, truck. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
TROPHY-SHOPPING-3 -- A new breed of affluent fashion maven has
arrived. She is as likely to shop at off-price outlets like T.J.
Maxx, which sell designer labels, and at discounters like Target,
which produce their own wares, as she is to cruise Jeffrey or Kirna
Zabete, those outposts of downtown chic. Increasingly shrewd, such
women are driven by value, naturally - but perhaps even more by the
thrill of the chase. From J. Chuckles, a fashion hunter bagged
zebra mules ($34.99), white pants ($32), a silky black halter top
($19.99), a tailored double-breasted topper ($59) and white bag
($19.99). (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
TROPHY-SHOPPING-2 -- A new breed of affluent fashion maven has
arrived. She is as likely to shop at off-price outlets like T.J.
Maxx, which sell designer labels, and at discounters like Target,
which produce their own wares, as she is to cruise Jeffrey or Kirna
Zabete, those outposts of downtown chic. Increasingly shrewd, such
women are driven by value, naturally - but perhaps even more by the
thrill of the chase. An ensemble from Broadway Generation features
a fake crocodile jacket by Fubu ($49), a silk fitted shirt ($13.29)
and khaki low-rider pants ($19.99). (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
TROPHY-SHOPPING-1 -- A new breed of affluent fashion maven has
arrived. She is as likely to shop at off-price outlets like T.J.
Maxx, which sell designer labels, and at discounters like Target,
which produce their own wares, as she is to cruise Jeffrey or Kirna
Zabete, those outposts of downtown chic. Increasingly shrewd, such
women are driven by value, naturally - but perhaps even more by the
thrill of the chase. At an open air market in SoHo, Susan Lazar, a
New York fashion designer, closes in on a $17 silk kerchief halter.
(Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
NUN-SISTER-KAROL -- If the nuns in ``The Sound of Music'' couldn't
figure out how to solve a problem like Maria, they would be
completely baffled by Sister Karol Jackowski, 53, who lives in the
East Village, has Margaritaville (cocktails, chips and pizza) each
week with her friends and calls chopped liver ``a major food group
for me.'' Life is more intense in New York City,'' said Sister
Karol, who has also written a book with the improbable title, ``Ten
Fun Things to Do Before You Die.'' ``The diversity here makes for
such a liberating environment.'' (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
NITEOUT-CHRISTENSEN-MODEL -- Since last spring, the Danish
supermodel Helena Christensen has held the impressive-sounding
title of creative director for Nylon magazine, a fashion-oriented
glossy that marked its first anniversary on Wednesday night with a
party at Skirt, a boutique in Manhattan. According to its Web site,
Nylon is ``the most hot magazine,'' devoted to covering ``life's
passionate participants, not it's fainthearted spectators.'' (Miles
Ladin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
OSCARS-PLACEMENT-2 -- Many envelopes will be ripped open Sunday
night at the 72nd annual Academy Awards. But not one will contain
instructions on how to display an Oscar at home so it won't look
preposterous. When visitors want to look, John Patrick Shanley has
to shine a light on his Oscar, which lives behind the television.
``I used to keep it in an athletic sock in the bottom of a laundry
bag in my apartment in Washington Heights,'' said Shanley, who won
the Academy Award for best original screenplay for ``Moonstruck''
in 1988. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
OSCARS-PLACEMENT-1 -- Many envelopes will be ripped open Sunday
night at the 72nd annual Academy Awards. But not one will contain
instructions on how to display an Oscar at home so it won't look
preposterous. Olympia Dukakis squeezes her trophies, including an
Oscar, onto a shelf in her home office. ``I tend not to display
things,'' said Dukakis, who won an Academy Award as best supporting
actress for her role in ``Moonstruck.'' (The original Oscar was
stolen; for $200, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
provided a replacement.) (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 24, 2000 -- FREUD-BOOKSTORE --
Sometimes a bookstore is just a bookstore. But as today's Freudians
should know, it can also be a publisher, a Website and a gathering
place, like the newest venture by analyst, academic, editor and
psychoanalytic entrepreneur Michael Moskowitz. His store, Other
Books in Chelsea, is just one of the tools he uses in his mission
to rescue psychoanalysis from the academic isolation and bitter
scholarly skirmishes that have dogged it for the last 20 years by
bridging the divide between clinicians and theorists. (Barbara
Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
BIZ-3COM-B&AMP;W -- Frank Manning, chief executive and president of
Zoom Telephonics in Boston, which sells modems under the Zoom and
Hayes brand names. ``Do I think analog modems are a highly
lucrative part of our business?'' he asks. ``No. But it's very
dangerous to just focus on the high-growth areas and abandon
customers when a segment slows down.'' (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LONGVIEW, Texas -- March 24, 2000 -- BELLY-DANCERS-3-COX
-- The belly dancing course at the Panther Park Community Center in
Longview attracted more students than anticipated, and what was
originally supposed to be one class became three. Amy Easley,
foreground, and Gabriela Cotton practiced during a recent belly
dancing class at the center. (Bahram Mark Sobhani/The Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LONGVIEW, Texas -- March 24, 2000 -- BELLY-DANCERS-2-COX
-- Belly dancing is not your mother's two-step. It's not even her
Lambada. Actually, it's better because it's all about being a woman
- in a way that Shania Twain can't touch. But she probably could
learn a few things, and the belly dancing course at the Panther
Park Community Center in Longview has the answers. Jessica
Winchester practiced her hip movements during a recent class.
(Bahram Mark Sobhani/The Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LONGVIEW, Texas -- March 24, 2000 -- BELLY-DANCERS-1-COX
-- The belly dancing course at the Panther Park Community Center in
Longview attracted more students than anticipated, and what was
originally supposed to be one class became three. Damiana led a
recent belly dancing class at the center. (Bahram Mark Sobhani/The
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HOUSTON -- March 24, 2000 -- BARBER-FAMILY-HNS --
Whenever the Ortuno family gets together, you could say it's a
hair-raising experience. The extended family of barbers at
Peluqueria Acapulco Unisex No. 1 and Acapulco Barber Shop No. 2
includes, from left, Marisela Ortuno, Gloria Rodriguez, Janete
Ortuno Castro, Manuel Ortuno, Mayda Ortuno, Ezequiel Ortuno, Amado
Ortuno, Laura Fraire and Laticia Ramirez, seated in the barber
chair. (Andrew Innerarity/The Houston Chronicle)
</P>
