<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROKER-COCAINE-NYT &LR;      03-24 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKER-COCAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKER ADMITS SELLING DRUGS ON FLOOR OF STOCK EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., also filed in ``f'' category) 
(mk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Time Warner and Citigroup are among the
typical things bought and sold at the New York Stock Exchange. But
one broker pleaded guilty on Thursday to selling cocaine to
undercover officers on the trading floor, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest, and three others, resulted from a sting in which an
undercover officer took a clerical job on the exchange floor and
was able to buy drugs, packaged in stock exchange envelopes, from
four people from July to September of last year, the Manhattan
district attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The broker, Frank Geneva, 45, of Staten Island, N.Y., an
employee of B.R. Doyle &AMP; Co., pleaded guilty to charges of drug
possession and drug selling. He faces up to six years in state
prison when he is sentenced on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   The police also arrested two messengers for the stock exchange,
Sandra Corson, 37, of Staten Island, and Shawn Moore, 34, of
Manhattan, and a telephone clerk, Hector Almonte, 59, of Queens
County, N.Y., who worked for another brokerage, Asiel &AMP; Co. Their
cases are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Diamond, a lawyer for Geneva, said that his client became
addicted to cocaine and then started selling the drug around 1997.
Geneva did not know the other three people and made his sales
independently, Diamond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was selling to a few friends,'' Diamond said. ``It was just
a handful of people, to supplement his own use.''
</P>
<P>
   Geneva had worked at the exchange for 20 years and lives in a
modest home on Staten Island, Diamond said. He would not say where
his client bought the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Zito, a spokesman for the New York Stock Exchange, said
the market cooperated with investigators, allowing the police to
post an undercover officer on the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it was an isolated incident,'' Zito said.
</P>
<P>
   The four who were arrested were among the sea of 3,300 workers _
along with the undercover officer, Detective Rodney Rodriguez _ at
the exchange. The two stock exchange employees who were arrested
were among the 148 messengers who take confirmation slips from
traders on the floor to the booths where brokers work. The job of
the messenger is a dying art form, since many brokerages are
replacing the paper slips with e-mail messages, Zito said.
</P>
<P>
   The two brokerages could face an investigation and fines from
regulators who work for the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The stock exchange conducts pre-employment drug testing, but
does not test employees. But Zito said the exchange has a
zero-tolerance drug policy and had banned all four people after the
arrests and the exchange's internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you cross the line on our trading floor, no matter who your
employer is, you will no longer be allowed in this building,'' Zito
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
