<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-1STLD-W     03-24 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAUDS TECHNOLOGY AS KEY TO INDIA'S ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Updates and rewrites completely.)  
(See also CLINTON-PAKISTAN, INDIA-TB) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDERABAD, India _ President Clinton saluted India's
information-technology industry Friday, the core of the country's
steady economic growth and a supplier of brain power to Silicon
Valley in California.
</P>
<P>
   This was the last full day of Clinton's visit to India, and
after having dealt with tricky strategic and political questions,
it seemed appropriate that the president should concentrate on the
economy, the area where there is probably the most commonality
between the United States and India.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, trade between the two countries is relatively
small, $12 billion last year compared with $94.9 billion between
the United States and China. But it is the potential for dramatic
growth, especially with an expanding middle class with a taste for
American consumer goods, that excites the administration and
American businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is India's largest trading partner. But India,
because of its high tariffs and largely state-run economy, accounts
for less than 1 percent of American global investments. Clinton,
accompanied throughout his India trip by Commerce Secretary William
Daley, made clear that he hoped that would change.
</P>
<P>
   After touring booths that displayed information technology and
receiving an Indian driver's license through the Internet, the
president spoke at a software center, popularly known as HITEC
City, an acronym for the Hyderabad Information
Technology-Engineering Consultancy. Computer companies including
Microsoft, Oracle and Toshiba have set up shop here, alongside new
Indian giants and smaller start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In extolling Indian achievements in information technology,
Clinton cited computer superstars like Vinod Khosla, who helped
build Sun Microsystems, and Vinod Dahm, who created the Pentium
chip.
</P>
<P>
   India is ``fast becoming one of the world's software
superpowers,'' Clinton said, proving that ``in a globalized world,
developing nations not only can succeed, developing nations can
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Internet users in India is expected to grow 10
times in the next four years, he added. The worth of India's
information-technology exports have catapulted, to $4 billion from
$150 million 10 years ago. The Indian government projects that by
2008 the exports will grow to $85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Most important for India, Clinton said, the significant effects
of Indian computer engineers on the American industry is beginning
to pay back at home. ``We're moving from brain drain to brain
gain,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A group, IndUS Entrepreneurs, whose members include the leading
Indian software engineers in Silicon Valley, estimates that 30
percent of the software engineers there are of Indian origin. Most
were educated at Indian technology institutes and went to the
United States to give an impetus to Silicon Valley. But now, with
the Indian economy growing at 6 percent a year, and with 10 percent
growth within sight, some Silicon Valley veterans are beginning to
return.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also struck one of his favorite themes about the
Internet, that it can be used to lift the poor. India, he told his
audience, accounts for 30 percent of the world's software
engineers, but also 25 percent of the world's malnourished. Thus,
he said, India is in a special position to show how its brains and
inventiveness in the new technologies could improve health care and
education across the nation's villages.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``good economics,'' Clinton said. If for example,
villages had computers with educational software, and printers,
that would create a potential for a revolution in education in a
country where almost 50 percent of the population is illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean, among other things,'' he said, ``that the
world's most populous nation would have the world's largest number
of educated people and, therefore, in no time would have the
world's largest economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2231EST &QL; 
