<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-HNS &LR;      03-24 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Even the beholders who get to play aren't
trying to convince us this one will be a beauty.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wisconsin vs. Purdue. Round Four of ugly, almost-brawl ball.
</P>
<P>
   The two Big Ten brutes have traveled west to play for the fourth
time this season, and like their other three contests, Saturday's
NCAA Tournament West Regional final is not likely to be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat up on each other one time, then we beat up on each
other a second time, then we beat up on each other a third time,''
Purdue point guard Jaraan Cornell said. ``Now, here we go. We're
just going to beat up on each other again.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Cornell may have taken ``beat up on each other'' a bit
too far when in the heat of battle he allegedly threatened to break
Wisconsin guard Mike Kelly's jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know about his reputation, and maybe I have come out trying
to say, `He can't guard me,' and that has taken me out of my
game,'' Cornell said. ``I let my emotions get the best of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell denies he made the jaw threat, but Kelly was quite clear
in his memory of the incident, though he said he understood the
frustration Cornell was feeling at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hacking him pretty bad, and the refs weren't calling
it,'' said Kelly, who holds Wisconsin's single-season and career
steals records. ``I was all over his arms and got a couple of
steals that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense rests its case, your honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There you go there you go,'' said Cornell, who scored just
nine points on 3-of-19 shooting in the Boilermakers' two losses to
Wisconsin this season. ``That's the way they play. They're taught
to hack. I can't fault them, though. They're just playing tough
defense and doing what they can get away with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't let that bother me, even when the refs won't let it go
on the other end. I've got to control my emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence the belief that today's game will be brutal _
aesthetically and physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm sure it'll be ugly,'' Wisconsin coach Dick Bennett
said. ``These are two of the hardest-playing teams you can find,
and I'm sure we'll both get after it. Purdue plays at least as hard
as if not harder than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett credits Purdue coach Gene Keady with bringing toughness
into the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gene Keady may have the patent on intensity _ getting
people to play hard,'' Bennett said. ``That has been a cornerstone
of their program and his coaching forever. When you play a team
coached by this man, you tighten your belt buckle, you pull up your
socks, you lace your shoes very tight, and know that there will be
no quarter given and none asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, on the other hand, should be credited with bringing
another gear into the conference _ reverse. The Badgers' brand of
basketball is a slow, grind-it-out style that frustrates opponents
and leads to wins, especially in a tournament setting where
Wisconsin's foes are not accustomed to its tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Badgers, Purdue is not one of those teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing Purdue, we'll lose that advantage because they know
what to expect,'' Bennett said. ``They have seen it before three
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-seeded Purdue (24-9) reached the Elite Eight with wins
over Dayton, Oklahoma and Gonzaga, while No. 8 seed Wisconsin
(21-13) advanced with victories over Fresno State, Arizona and LSU.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers lost two of their previous three games with
Wisconsin, putting up some of their worst numbers of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue hit only 36.2 percent of its shots but won the first
matchup of the teams 63-52. In Game 2, the Boilermakers managed
only 45 points and shot a horrendous 28.6 percent from the floor,
their worst shooting effort of the season, in a 10-point defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin jumped out to a 14-4 lead and never trailed in the
third meeting two weeks ago in the quarterfinals of the Big Ten
tournament. That game's highlight was a head-to-head collision
between Kelly and Purdue's Carson Cunningham. Both took stitches
but returned to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of teams we are,'' Kelly said. ``We need hard
hats. It seems like when you match up with those guys, you come out
with a lot of bruises and bumps _ even stitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre thing about the collision was that it occurred on an
inbounds play away from the ball, and Kelly wasn't even guarding
Cunningham at the time.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams know each other's personnel and schemes so well
that Keady said his staff had little preparation to do for the
game. Sometimes, he said, you can ``over-know'' an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play a team for the fourth time, they know everything
about you, and you know everything about them,'' Wisconsin forward
Andy Kowske said. ``It really emphasizes execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no surprises. They know our defense. The last three
games we surprised our opponents with the kind of defense we put on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin held LSU to a season-low 48 points in the West
Regional semifinal, and Cornell said he could see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting there watching the game and thinking, `They (the
Tigers) don't have a clue,''' he said. ``You can't put the ball on
the floor like LSU was doing. That's what Wisconsin wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep moving and keep the ball moving to find the
open man, and he has to take the shot. You can't put it on the
floor. That's playing right into their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, fluid offensive execution is the last thing either team
expects in this one. Purdue had an 8:51 stretch without points at
Wisconsin, and the Badgers had a 10-minute stretch in West
Lafayette, Ind., in which they managed just two points. The last
time the teams played, there were 49 fouls called, and the teams
shot 63 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``While you're playing, your adrenaline is flowing, so it's not
a real brutal experience,'' Cunningham said of the teams' penchant
for physical battles. ``It's definitely physical, but it's fun. We
like contact. We like aggressive, hard-nosed basketball. I think
Wisconsin does, too. We're just ready to get it on.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2233EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
