<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-WRESTLE-490&AMP;ADD-NY     03-24 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WRESTLE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MOVES AGAINST EXTREME WRESTLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ New Jersey's governor and a leader of the
Assembly joined forces Friday against a violent form of pro
wrestling in which contenders use chairs, kitchen implements and
other sharp items to draw blood from one another and squeals from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here, Gov. Christie Whitman, a Republican,
and the Assembly's Democratic leader, Joseph Doria, said they would
propose legislation to regulate what is known as extreme or
hard-core wrestling. Their main concerns, they said, were to
prevent young children from attending the matches and to give local
officials some say in whether the matches should take place in
their towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extreme wrestling is a grotesque and depraved activity,'' said
Doria, who is also the mayor of Bayonne, where matches are held
almost every week. ``It's a blood sport with no redeeming value for
our children.''
</P>
<P>
   The two officials said they planned a bill that would bar
children under 16 from attending matches and would establish a
licensing mechanism for the matches within the State Athletic
Commission. Communities would be able to appeal the commission's
permits for such events.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations would not affect the more popular mainstream
matches of the World Wrestling Federation and World Championship
Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the new legislation would apply to only a small
percentage of wrestling going on in the state. And she said that
although she had not seen any extreme wrestling herself, she had
received letters and e-mail messages from parents urging her to
take some action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't seek to outlaw it completely,'' she said. ``But we do
want to prohibit children from seeing it. It is one thing for
consenting adults to attend these events and it is quite another to
allow impressionable children to sit ringside as participants set
out to maim and attack each other with objects such as razors and
chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The advent of extreme wrestling matches in New Jersey is an
unintended result of the state's decision three years ago to
deregulate wrestling altogether and remove it from the State
Athletic Commission's supervision. That move was made, Whitman
said, only after the mainstream wrestling groups stopped insisting
that they were a sport requiring strength and skill, but were a
form of entertainment that was staged and choreographed.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schapiro, co-owner of Jersey All-Pro Wrestling, which
stages groups of matches weekly in Bayonne and other places that
feature one or two extreme events complete with chairs, pots and
pans, tables and barbed wire, said that such events had grown
rapidly with deregulation and the growing audience for wrestling,
which seems to demand more and greater thrills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real blood in these matches even though they are
choreographed,'' he said. ``But we do it because the fans want to
see blood. It's the fans' appetite for bloodier matches that drives
this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Shapiro, who packs up to 300 people into Charity Hall for
his matches in Bayonne when the hall is not being used for church
bingo, said that the more extreme matches had lost much of their
allure and lately were ``falling flat.'' Thus, he said, he could
easily phase them out and live with any of the proposed
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The age restriction will be a problem because we have a fan
base that goes from 10 years old and up,'' he said. ``But I think I
can live with the regulations they are proposing. Plus, people
don't want that stuff as much now, and want more acrobatics in the
ring.''
</P>
<P>
   While he expected his matches to survive regulation, he was not
so sure about groups like CZW, a southern New Jersey company that
promotes extreme wrestling almost exclusively. Officials of the
company could not be reached for comment on the proposed
legislation, but their Web site carried a drily written account of
one of their recent matches featuring performers with such names as
Wifebeater and Mac Smack.
</P>
<P>
   ``CZW champion Zandig fought Kronus to a no contest,'' the
account began. ``The bloody match ended when Wifebeater and Mac
Smack interfered. They taped Zandig onto the ring ropes, then
whipped him with barbed wire and then used two Weedwhackers to
slice his back and arms open. Then Wifebeater poured salt, lemon
juice and lighter fluid onto his cuts. Finally they set him on fire
before CZW security stopped the attack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
