<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7484 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-24 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAM HOME AT SECOND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the questions on the Cal State Northridge sports
information department's athlete questionnaire is, ``Where might
you be 10 years from now?'' Adam Kennedy answered, ``Playing
professional ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question goes, ``If you weren't in college, where might
you be?'' Kennedy wrote, ``Playing pro ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a few years since Kennedy, then the Matadors'
All-America shortstop, revealed his uncomplicated soul so
concisely. And the years don't seem to have changed him one bit.
For him, baseball isn't merely a game, isn't only a career. It's a
place, a destination.
</P>
<P>
   So when Kennedy, a 24-year-old rookie second baseman, went from
the St. Louis Cardinals to the Angels in a three-player trade on
Thursday, the fact he's coming home was not the main reason he
proclaimed himself ``happy as I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my second worry,'' he said of playing in Anaheim, close
to his parents and his boyhood home in Riverside, and not far from
his friends at Matador Field. ``I'm trying to win a job on a
big-league roster, and playing to compete in October (in the World
Series). Being at home is great, but (playing) is my biggest
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the Angels, one reason general manager Bill
Stoneman's first significant transaction is a smart one.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, now numbering four, the Angels have put
uniforms on too many players who were thrilled to come to Southern
California for the beach, the girls or the cameras. They were the
ones who always looked comfortable in their well-tanned skin, as
long as they didn't have to scrape it in the process of breaking up
a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy sounds different. He's thrilled to come to Southern
California because this is where he'll get a chance to play
major-league baseball every night.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't getting that chance with the Cardinals, who acquired
veteran second baseman Fernando Vina from the Milwaukee Brewers
over the winter and demoted Kennedy to their minor-league
spring-training camp last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even really calmed down (since hearing about the
trade),''Kennedy said Friday afternoon on a cellular phone from a
Chili's restaurant in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   He'd hopped on an early Friday-morning flight from South
Florida, where the Cardinals train. By afternoon, he was fielding
practice ground balls in a No. 2 Angels uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Now he'll have a week of Cactus League games to convince Angels
manager Mike Scioscia he's a better choice for opening-day second
baseman than Scott Spiezio or Trent Durrington. The Angels begin
the season April 3 at Edison Field against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman seemed to be convinced before he made the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was the keystone in the Thursday deal that brought
18-game winner Kent Bottenfield to the Angels and sent center
fielder Jim Edmonds to the Cardinals. Stoneman said he wouldn't
have agreed to a straight-up Bottenfield-for-Edmonds deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Adam Kennedy is ready to play at the major-league
level,''Stoneman said. ``We intend to throw him right into the
mix.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels think Kennedy is the best all-around of the three
second-base candidates. He'll outhit Durrington and outfield
Spiezio. That fits the Kennedy portrait scouts have painted since
his Northridge days, when he was the Matadors' first three-time
All-America baseball player and the first player to lead the nation
in hits in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After the college junior was drafted by the Cardinals with the
20th pick of the first round in June 1997, the club's scouting
director described him as ``the best pure hitter in the draft'' and
a sure-handed, quick-footed infielder with a good head for
baseball. Two weeks later, Kennedy accepted a $650,000 signing
bonus, less than the going rate for a first-rounder, because he
wanted to get on with his pro career.
</P>
<P>
   Moved to second base after St. Louis traded for 23-year-old
shortstop Edgar Renteria, Kennedy was a .300-10 homers-20 steals
kind of player at Triple-A Memphis in 1999, and was named the
Cardinals' Minor League Player of the Year. A nice honor _ but only
a step toward the place Kennedy wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the big leagues. On opening day. And in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, as a competitor, you're trying to win wherever
you're at,'' Kennedy said. ``I'm trying to win every game. That's
the way I was raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Destination: the lineup card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
