<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-WEST-NYT &LR;      03-24 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATCHUP OF HARD KNOCKS ON HARDWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ They are Big Ten Conference rivals, but in
the case of Wisconsin and Purdue, familiarity breeds hostility, not
contempt. The last meeting between the Badgers and the
Boilermakers, a 78-66 Wisconsin victory in the quarterfinals of the
Big Ten tournament, surpassed the lofty standards of physical play
in the conference. It produced 49 fouls, 63 free throws, two cuts,
seven stitches and numerous bruises in a variety of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue guard Carson Cunningham needed four stitches, and
Wisconsin guard Mike Kelley required three stitches to close wounds
from a head-on collision.
</P>
<P>
   Such accidents can happen in any game, but these teams have a
recent history of taking intensity to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about like a football game,'' Purdue center Greg McQuay
said. ``Maybe worse. It was brutal down in the low post with all
the elbows flying. We all had scratches and bruises.''
</P>
<P>
   If that game was a preview of Saturday's West Regional final of
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, expect an
even more action-packed sequel. There will be no secrets in either
team's half-court games or the strategies of the two coaches,
Wisconsin's Dick Bennett and Purdue's Gene Keady, who both cited
Vince Lombardi as a profound influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation of how much more can we know about them after
three games,'' Keady said. ``Sometimes you can over-know
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   A sense of urgency exists for both programs. Wisconsin has not
survived this far into the NCAA tournament since 1941, when it won
the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue has reached the Round of Eight for the second time in
Keady's 20 seasons at the school, but has yet to make the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's patience and depth wore down Gonzaga in a 75-66 victory
Thursday night. As they hope to do against the Badgers, the
Boilermakers shut down the 3-point shooting of Gonzaga (5-20) and
capitalized on 20 offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jaraan Cornell broke out of a shooting slump to lead
Purdue with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams that have given us fits are the ones with a senior
point guard like Cornell,'' Bennett said. ``He's good. We've got to
keep him in check and hope that affects the rest of their
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's defense suffocated Louisiana State, forcing 23
turnovers. The Badgers shot only 38 percent, but hit four 3-point
shots at key moments in the second half to win easily.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jon Bryant led them with 16 points and Mike Kelley had
five steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three games in the tournament, we surprised opponents
with the defense we put on them,'' center Andy Kowske said.
``That's not going to be the case with Purdue. We both know what's
going to happen out there. They're going to be in our face, and
we're going to be in theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers won two of the three games against Purdue this
season. On Jan. 26, they won, 55-45, as both teams combined for 45
fouls. On Jan. 15, Purdue routed Wisconsin by 72-52.
</P>
<P>
   They met again in the tunnel between Thursday night's semifinal
games at the Pit. The Badgers congratulated Purdue on their victory
over Gonzaga; the Boilermakers wished Wisconsin luck against LSU.
It is that grudging respect that should result in another physical
battle that may or may not be closely watched by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they call it close, there's going to be foul trouble on
both teams,'' Keady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a push,'' Bennett said. ``I don't want the
officials to swallow the whistles, so to speak. I want them to let
the kids determine the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
