<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DORISMOND-WAKE-ART     03-24 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DORISMOND-WAKE-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWDS MOURN VICTIM OF POLICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT27, 28 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than a thousand mourners filled a funeral home
in Brooklyn on Friday night to pay respects to Patrick Dorismond,
the 26-year-old security guard killed by a plainclothes policeman
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens carried or wore the Haitian flag, and members of his
family of renowned Haitian musicians sang for him. Across Flatbush
Avenue, picketing protesters demanded justice for the fourth
unarmed black man to be killed by the police in the last 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Andrew Torregrossa Funeral Home in Marine Park,
Dorismond lay in a coffin lined with white satin, underneath an
arch with his name written in white and green carnations. Several
women, overcome with grief, let out hoarse, muffled cries and had
to be escorted out.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Dorismond, the victim's older brother, said his brother
had gone to a better place, in contrast to whoever killed him. ``If
he has a guilty conscience, that's his torture for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond was shot on March 16 after a plainclothes police
officer approached him outside a bar in midtown Manhattan and asked
if he knew where to buy marijuana. Dorismond reacted angrily, and
in the ensuing scuffle one of the officer's backups, Detective
Anthony Vasquez, shot him in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez has said through his lawyer that the shooting was
accidental.
</P>
<P>
   The wake Friday night was attended by Haiti's consul general to
the United States, Therese Guitos, and by Alan Hevesi, the city
comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of New Yorkers who are decent caring
people offer their most profound sympathy and understanding for
your loss,'' Hevesi told the Dorismond family. ``This is an awful,
awful day.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the funeral home, about four dozen peaceful protesters,
surrounded by dozens of police officers in powder-blue
windbreakers, chanted and carried signs, mostly in Haitian Creole,
denouncing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Some of the signs compared the
mayor to a ``loup garou,'' a Haitian demon who seeks the blood of
babies.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Dorismond has inflamed political and racial
tensions in the city, not just because of the shooting itself but,
critics say, because of the way the Giuliani administration has
handled its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the incident, Giuliani and Police Commissioner
Howard Safir released Dorismond's police record, including a sealed
court record of an incident when he was 13. They did not
immediately release Vasquez's disciplinary record _ which included
his shooting a neighbor's Rottweiler and pulling a gun in a 1997
bar fight.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including Hillary Rodham Clinton, Giuliani's opponent
in the race for the U.S. Senate in New York, accused city officials
of blaming Dorismond for his own death. But the mayor said that he
was merely pointing out that Dorismond had acted violently in the
past and might have acted violently in the moments that led to the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond was a security guard for the 34th Street Partnership
and had two children. He was never convicted of a crime as an
adult. His arrests for punching a man in an argument over drugs in
1993 and for pulling a gun during a traffic dispute in 1996
resulted in disorderly-conduct charges, for which he did community
service, and no jail time. The case against him in 1987, when he
was 13, was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   His death was a bitter blow to Haitian Americans, still reeling
from the brutalization by the police of Abner Louima, who in 1997
was sodomized with a stick in a Brooklyn precinct station house
after being arrested in a case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   And Dorismond's death comes soon after the verdict on Feb. 25 in
the Amadou Diallo case, where four plainclothes police officers
were cleared of criminal charges after firing 41 shots at the
unarmed Guinean street peddler, hitting him 41 times.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after that verdict, Malcolm Ferguson, 23, and also
black and unarmed, was killed by plainclothes officers in the
Bronx, three blocks from where Diallo was shot. The other unarmed
black man killed by the police recently was Richard Watson, who was
shot in the back last September.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At Dorismond's wake, Delroy LaRoc, a friend of Dorismond since
1989, when they attended high school together, remembered making
music with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be the beat and I would be the lyrics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaRoc recalled how his friend recently celebrated receiving his
tax refund by taking him out to a $90.07 dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ate so much food, you just gotta love him,'' he said. ``The
next day he got up and went to work, and after work he never came
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's death left one mourner, Felix Serieux, 12, of East
New York, afraid and perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sad,'' said Felix, a seventh-grader. ``It makes
afraid for my own life, you understand. ```Say no to drugs.' They
tell you that in school, to say no. So what happens now? Do you
have to say yes?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
