<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RAPIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPIST IS EVALUATED IN EFFORT TO CONFINE HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A rapist who was captured this week after a
nationwide manhunt has undergone a court-ordered psychiatric
evaluation as part of the state's effort to have him committed to a
treatment center as a violent sexual predator, a state official
involved in the case said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joseph S. Conte of Superior Court, who conducts New
Jersey's commitment hearings, ordered the examination Thursday of
the rapist, Raymond Alves, at the request of the state attorney
general, John J. Farmer Jr., the state official said. No date has
been set for a hearing on whether he should be committed, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Alves, 57, a convicted rapist, has been held without bail in the
Bergen County Jail since his arrest on Tuesday night, 12 days after
his bungled release from a state prison enraged law-enforcement
officials in northern New Jersey and touched off a nationwide
search.
</P>
<P>
   He spent nearly all the time he was hunted as a fugitive on a
meandering bus journey through the East, South and Southwest.
Law-enforcement authorities captured him in the rural hamlet of
Annandale in western New Jersey after receiving a tip that he
planned to take a commuter train there, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   After Alves was freed on March 9, William H. Schmidt, the Bergen
County prosecutor, called him a threat to public safety because of
his conviction for raping one teen-age girl in Bergen County and
throwing another off a railroad bridge in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt also denounced prison officials for freeing Alves
without providing his office with a 30-day notice, which is
required under New Jersey's law dealing with the release of sex
offenders, commonly known as Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt has said he would have used the 30 days to start civil
commitment proceedings against Alves.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain a commitment under state law, the authorities must
prove that Alves suffers from a mental abnormality or a personality
disorder that makes him likely to commit another violent sexual
crime unless he is confined for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, commitment hearings are closed to the public
unless a sex offender waives his privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   Alves is now charged with only a minor felony that carries an
18-month prison term: violating the sex-offender law by lying about
the address he was to have after after prison. A bail hearing is
scheduled in Superior Court here on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
