<P>
   &UR; FEATURE Stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT-GOBER-ART (Washington) _ Robert Gober, 46, is among the
best known of the American artists who established careers during
the late 1980s and 1990s, a time when AIDS, identity politics and
culture wars produced a surreal, gothic, dystopian sensibility in
art. His work is much in evidence this spring, both in the
traveling survey ``Robert Gober: Sculptures and Drawings'' at the
Hirshhorn and in the 2000 Biennial that opened at the Whitney
Museum of American Art in New York last week. In the Hirshhorn show
in particular it is art that feels resonant with a recent past but
in tune with art shaping up in a new decade. By Holland Cotter.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-PHILHARMONIC (Prague, Czech Republic) _ The Czech
Philharmonic, led by its chief conductor Vladimir Ashkenazy, will
give the first of three concerts this Sunday at Avery Fisher Hall
in New York City, having just completed two weeks of touring in
Florida and California. These concerts, the orchestra's first in
New York since 1996, consist mostly of Bohemian or Czech music and
are part of Lincoln Center's Prague Festival, which celebrates the
10th anniversary of the Velvet Revoution and began Saturday with a
symposium on the cultural history of Prague. By James R. Oestreich.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEAU-TRAVAIL-FILM (New York) _ Dressed in a leather jacket and
jeans, the director Claire Denis, whose latest film, ``Beau
Travail,'' opens on Friday, has a casual sophistication. At 49, she
is petite, intense, reticent and, on occasion, disarmingly honest.
The daughter of a French civil servant, Ms. Denis grew up in
Cameroon in West Africa during the final days of the colonial
empire. ``Beau Travail,'' the story of a troop of French Foreign
Legionnaires, is set in present-day Djibouti, in East Africa. By
Nancy Ramsey. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE-OF-THE-WIND-VIDEO (Undated) _ Anthony Howarth's ``People
of the Wind'' (Milestone, $33.95), takes a look at the Babadi tribe
of Iran as they drive a million sheep, goats and pack animals into
great boulder fields, across icy turquoise rivers, upward into
mountain passes and down to vast expanses of pasture. By Peter M.
Nichols. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-HAMLET-BALLET (New York) _ As far as Russian czars go,
Paul I is not exactly a household name in the West or a likely
subject for a ballet. Unlike his mother, Catherine the Great, he
was not even worth a costume drama with a film superstar (Marlene
Dietrich in ``The Scarlet Empress''). Serious historians, however,
are familiar with his turbulent life and reign in the 18th century,
and the verdict is not positive. But to the Russian choreographer
Boris Eifman, Paul was a young idealist whose spirit was broken by
the murderous court milieu that turned him into a tyrant. That, he
said, is why his new ballet, ``Russian Hamlet (the Son of Catherine
the Great),'' focuses on the youthful Paul, still to be czar. By
Anna Kisselgoff. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAVA-PUPPET-THEATER (Cirebon, Java) _ In Java, the world's most
populous island and the political and cultural center of Indonesia,
the traditional drama still mainly survives the way it has for
centuries: by popular demand. Itinerant puppeteers, known as
dalangs, travel from village to village, performing the ancient
tales of gods and demons, heroes and fools, for anyone with the
wherewithal to hire them. In most cultures, puppets imitate human
actors; in Java and the neighboring island of Bali, the reverse is
true. The traditional dramas have always been performed with
puppets; indeed, the Indonesian word for puppet, wayang, is used to
denote the various forms of the drama. When a piece is performed by
people, for example, it is called the wayang orang _ literally, a
human puppet show. By Jamie James. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NIETZSCHE-THEATER (New York) _ Has Richard Foreman, 62, found
his alter ego at last? Could it be that the poor mad philosopher
Friedrich Nietzsche is the perfect analogue for the playwright and
director, who for more than 30 years has been breaking the
boundaries of theater to combine the surreal, the disordered, the
mysterious and, sometimes, the just plain nutty? This year is the
centenary of Nietzsche's death, and he is the subject of Foreman's
new play, ``Bad Boy Nietzsche!,'' currently at his
Ontological-Hysteric Theater at St. Mark's Church in Manhattan. By
Dinitia Smith. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NOISE (New York) _ Every so often, a critic feels
compelled to write a crabby column about the rudeness of audience
members. Such columns seldom do much good, but at least the critic
feels better. The traditional disruptions, like coughing, will
always be with us. But although colds afflict us all, the kind of
unabashed hacking that you hear from people who don't even seem to
be trying to control themselves has to be a passive-aggressive
expression of boredom. Some irritants are particularly exasperating
because they are so preventable. Why would a woman choose to adorn
her wrist with a clinking set of bracelets when she goes to the
opera, so that every time she fidgets in her seat or tinkers with
her Met Titles she becomes a human wind chime? Crinkling plastic
bags drive me nuts. The cell phone represents a new level of
intrusiveness. So far this season, it has been the rare concert or
opera I've attended during which at least one didn't ring. By
Anthony Tommasini. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ZAMPA-OPERA (New York) _ ``Zampa,'' the pirate king in Ferdinand
Herrold's opera, introduced to wild acclaim at the Opera-Comique in
Paris in 1831, remained a fixture in French, Italian and German
opera houses throughout the 19th century. Today the overture is the
sole excerpt that enjoys any name recognition, and that only
barely. A whirlwind potpourri of infectious tunes from the opera,
it displays orchestration of a zest and finesse that recalls Weber,
Mendelssohn and Berlioz. On April 3, at Alice Tully Hall, a concert
revival by L'Opera Francais de New York _ with narration written
and delivered by the composer's descendant Alexander Herold
replacing the original spoken dialogue _ restores the subsequent
action in what is said to be the opera's first New York airing in
more than a hundred years. By Matthew Gurewitsch. (Moved). WITH
PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-MAINSTREAM (Undated) _ Jazz is a music of unmistakable
personalities. Though ensemble interaction between these
personalities remains one of the music's glories, the expression of
individual identity has always been the essence of jazz, with
players cultivating solo sounds as singular as fingerprints.
Increasingly, though, classic recordings by these consummate
individualists are being deployed as a sort of mood music,
background noise for everything from Broadway drama to television
hucksterism to coffee bar drinking. Some view this as a sign of
jazz's mainstreaming, its wider dissemination. Still, how
distressing it is to hear music conceived as the purest
distillation of individuality rendered so anonymously. By Barry
Singer. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-IMPRESARIOS (New York) _ These days, in the brave world of
new music in New York, versatility is the key word. Limor Tomer, a
Juilliard-trained pianist and former music history teacher at New
York University, is one of a small but avid group of advocates who
are presenting music that falls between the cracks of genres. It is
music that won't fill 600-seat auditoriums but may be the
wellspring for mainstream music to come. Call Tomer and her ilk
downtown Diaghilevs, mini-impresarios, or settle for a less
grandiose term, music curator. By Eric V. Copage. (Moved). WITH
PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ Design has abandoned Socrates
for Nietzsche. This is the take-away idea at the first edition of
the National Design Triennial at the Cooper-Hewitt Museum. No more
pure geometric shapes. No more strict correspondences between form
and function. No more efforts to refine materials and production
methods to their pure Platonic essence. Instead, we behold room
after room of dancing stars. Fluid shapes. Appetizing colors.
Laughter in the dark. Flesh. Organized by the curatorial team of
Donald Albrecht, Ellen Lupton and Steven Skov Holt, this is the
first of a series of surveys to be conducted every three years by
the Cooper-Hewitt, the Smithsonian Institution's New York venue for
the study and exhibition of design. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRAUN-PHOTOGS (Undated) _ The interplay of aesthetic and
commercial concerns in the 19th century is vividly set forth in
``Image and Enterprise: The Photographs of Adolphe Braun,'' at the
Rhode Island School of Design in Providence through April 22 and at
the Cleveland Museum of Art from June 18 through Aug. 27. The first
American show to examine Braun's career, it features 100 of his
photographs, along with related material. By Vicki Goldberg.
(Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROMAN-GLASS-ART (New York) _ A stunning variety of glass objects
in daily use in sixth century Rome incorporates virtually every
glass-working technique known today, as can be seen in ``Roman
Glass: Reflections on Cultural Change,'' an exhibition at the Bard
Graduate Center for Studies in the Decorative Arts in Manhattan,
through June 11. The 200 pieces date from the first century B.C. to
the sixth century A.D. and were selected from the university of
Pennsylvania Museum in Philadelphia by Stuart Fleming, the show's
curator. It is the first exhibition of the museum's collection of
ancient glass since the museum opened a century ago. By Rita Reif.
(Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-WONDERLAND (Undated) _ The scene in the opening episode of
ABC's ``Wonderland'' is harrowing. A pregnant doctor in the
emergency room of a hospital patterned after New York's Bellevue
intervenes when a violently unhinged patient tries to harm himself
with a syringe. In the scuffle that follows, the syringe pierces
the doctor's stomach. ``It's a powerful scene,'' said Lloyd Braun,
co-chairman of the ABC Television Entertainment Group. ``Like any
series that pushes the envelope _ and this one clearly does _ there
may be some people who will find the show too intense. But we
repeatedly talk at the network about how important it is to take
risks with programming. Without question, this show represents a
risk.'' The risk, of course, is that a drama about psychiatric
patients and their doctors will prove simply too unsettling to
network audiences accustomed to sitcom humor and twentysomething
angst. By Bernard Weinraub. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOUNTAIN-OF-YOUTH (New York) _ ``The Fountain of Youth,''
written and directed by Orson Welles, the pilot for an anthology
series, and rarely seen, will be presented at the Museum of
Television and Radio along with an Edward R. Murrow interview and a
very funny 1956 ``I Love Lucy'' episode with Welles as guest star.
(The program begins on Friday and runs through May 7 at the museum
in New York and through May 31 in Los Angeles. By Caryn James.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
