<SLUG> BC-CD-MAIL-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ADMITS FRAUD IN JOINING CD CLUBS THOUSANDS OF TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second time since November, a New Jersey man has pleaded
guilty to defrauding mail-order music clubs of thousands of compact
discs by using false names and addresses to exploit the clubs'
introductory offers.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Joseph Parvin, 60, said that between 1993 and 1998 he
received 26,554 compact discs addressed to 2,417 customer accounts
at 16 post office boxes and slight variations on the address of his
house in Lawrenceville. He got the discs from BMG Music Services
and Columbia House Music Club, both based in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty Friday before Judge Alfred M. Wolin in U.S.
District Court in Newark to one count of mail fraud, and faces up
to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine when sentenced June 13.
</P>
<P>
   Parvin's lawyer, William F. Maderer, said Parvin also ran a
legitimate business registering and selling Internet domain names.
</P>
<P>
   In November, David Russo, 33, of Aberdeen Township, pleaded
guilty to cheating the same two mail-order companies out of more
than 22,000 CDs valued at $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Russo, who is to be sentenced by Judge Joseph A. Greenaway of
U.S. District Court in Newark, sold the discs at flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the men took advantage of the companies' offer of
free CDs in exchange for agreeing to future purchases. Columbia
House, for example, now offers 15 free CDs if a customer agrees to
buy just 5 at full price over a two-year period, said Maura
McLoughlin, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney in the case, Scott S. Christie, said the
independence and the magnitude of the two schemes suggested that
others may be doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no evidence we know of that connects Russo
and Parvin, which makes you wonder how prevalent this kind of thing
is,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
