<SLUG> BC-CT-LIEBERMAN-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR IS POSSIBLE VICE PRESIDENTIAL CONTENDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ In New York there is the colossal battle
known as Hillary vs. Rudy. In the Senate race in New Jersey, the
winner of a hugely expensive fight for the Democratic nomination
will face the survivor of a four-way clash among obscure
Republicans. But in Connecticut, things are so quiet that voters
could be forgiven for not realizing that Sen. Joseph Lieberman is
actually up for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a two-term Democrat, has sky-high approval ratings,
overflowing campaign coffers and, as yet, no opponent. The one
Republican who has expressed any interest in mounting a challenge,
Mayor Philip Giordano of Waterbury, has been discouraged from doing
so by two of the most important members of his party, Gov. John
Rowland and the state Republican chairman, Chris DePino.
</P>
<P>
   So when Lieberman's name comes up these days, it is not in terms
of the Senate race in November but the result of a recent bubble of
speculation about him as a possible running mate for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In a more substantive way, though, the lack of a U.S. Senate
contest in Connecticut is allowing Lieberman to do actual work,
like crisscrossing the state last week to visit schools and push
for a major new education bill. ``This bill actually dramatically
increases federal support of education, by $7 billion,'' he told
the 40 students in the senior class at Bridge Academy, a charter
school in downtown Bridgeport, last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the visit encapsulated Lieberman's current
political state: his confidence, his popularity and his bipartisan
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Bridge Academy, with 160 students, was founded three years ago
with the help of federal money made possible by a bill Lieberman
sponsored with a Republican senator, Dave Durenberger of Minnesota.
Lieberman arrived at the school to thunderous applause, smiled
proudly as students told him of the school's success and spoke
earnestly of the need for more federal money to replace a start-up
grant that ends this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to hear it,'' Lieberman said of the recent
speculation, which includes a column urging his selection as a vice
presidential candidate in the Capitol Hill journal Roll Call last
week and a recent article in the conservative Weekly Standard.
``But I don't expect it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A list of possible vice presidential contenders in the magazine
Campaigns and Elections also puts him on the Democratic short list.
</P>
<P>
   Far-fetched as a spot on the national ticket may be, the fact
that Lieberman, 58, an observant Jew who does not work on the
Sabbath, is mentioned at all is testimony to his stature, both in
the Democratic Party and in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for his increased prominence was his willingness to
become the first Democrat to condemn President Clinton publicly for
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, a stand that reinforced
Lieberman's reputation as one of the Senate's stronger moral
voices.
</P>
<P>
   But much of his rise has to do with his reputation as an
independent-minded New Democrat whose religious observance is
appreciated by some of his more conservative colleagues across the
aisle and whose policy interests have at times diverged with the
majority view in the Democratic Party. For example, he speaks
favorably about school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want you to agree with them on everything,''
Lieberman said over tea and a cheese omelet at a Bridgeport diner
last Friday. ``They want to feel that you are doing what you feel
is right. Part of what I have tried to do is be independent and not
walk the political party line if I didn't think the party happened
to be right in that case. And this state is very supportive of that
kind of representation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
