<HEADLINE>
GAS PRICES NOT DETERRING
 DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY MARY JO PITZL AND DAVE
 WALKER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Phoenix area gas prices have increased an average of
a penny a day this month, but motorists aren't budging from behind
their steering wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Local transportation officials say they have no evidence that
people are driving less, although the current $1.58-per-gallon
average for gas has made the drive more bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Bejarano, a shift leader at a downtown Pizza Hut, said
she first started hearing complaints from her delivery drivers two
weeks ago. Now, the drivers, who pay for their own gas, are asking
for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very upset because the gas price is so high,'' she
said. ``They put $5 in, and it doesn't get them nowhere. It very
definitely makes a great difference in their pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   AAA Arizona has been tracking the steady climb in gas prices.
But spokeswoman Laura Rightenburg says she's seen no change on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, on my drives to and from work, even though we've
been preaching a lot of fuel conservation, I'm not seeing anybody
changing their driving behavior,'' she said. ``Unless, of course,
there's a police officer next to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
