<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GRAU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITA GRAU, 84; HEADED EFFORT ON BEHALF OF CUBAN CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polita Grau, a daughter of a prominent Cuban political family
who helped to spirit thousands of children out of Castro Cuba,
which later jailed her for 14 years as a CIA conspirator, died
March 22 at a nursing home in Miami. She was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Grau, politically engaged since adolescence, spent four separate
periods in exile in Miami because of her work. There, many admired
her as a patron of the Catholic Church-sponsored Operacion Pedro
Pan to give Cuban children a non-Communist education.
</P>
<P>
   She came to Miami from her native Havana for the first time
during her senior year in high school, graduating there from a
local parochial school.
</P>
<P>
   She was a niece of Dr. Ramon Grau San Martin, a professor of
physiology who served as Cuba's provisional president in 1933 and
'34 and as president from 1944 to 1948. During his first term,
Grau, a bachelor, made his niece, then known as Maria Leopoldina
Grau, his official first lady at state events.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Grau had been a central figure in the student rebellion
against President Gerardo Machado (1925-33), a nationalist who grew
increasingly autocratic. Ms. Grau was involved in the campus
rebellion as a member of radical and liberal student groups.
</P>
<P>
   Born into a wealthy family, she at first also supported the
movement that sent the dictator Fulgencio Batista into exile in
1959. But her enthusiasm for the ensuing Castro regime did not last
when it instituted its program of nationalizing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   With her brother, Ramon Grau Alsina, she helped send some 14,000
children to Miami in the early 1960s. They were the offspring of
parents who feared their Communist indoctrination or were involved
in the anti-Castro resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Operacion Pedro Pan smuggled them out of Cuba with the help of
the State Department. Once in the United States, they were placed
by the church in camps or foster homes; some of them were never
reunited with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Grau and her brother were arrested in 1965 and accused of
plotting to overthrow Fidel Castro, who was then Cuba's prime
minister. They were convicted for their role in Pedro Pan and of
having had dealings with the CIA, which denied the connection.
</P>
<P>
   They both got 30-year sentences, but Ms. Grau was freed in 1978
when Castro released a large number of political prisoners as part
of a relaxation encouraged by President Jimmy Carter. Ramon Grau
was freed in 1986 and followed her to Miami, where he died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grau's survivors include a daughter, Hilda Aguero, six
grandchildren, and one great-granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7612 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a SNOWBIRDSARECRUCIALIN     03-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS
</HEADLINE>
 SNOWBIRDS ARE CRUCIAL IN (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY MAUREEN WEST AND
 SHAUN MCKINNON 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - It's an uncivil tug-of-war between Arizona and other
states, and befuddled retirees are the rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know what the heck to do,'' said Beverly Houwman
of Minnesota, who along with an esti mated 180,000 other U.S.
snowbirds will spend April 1, the official U.S. Census Day, in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Should they list Arizona, where they consume state resources, or
their hometowns in the Midwest and elsewhere, where they have emo
tional roots?
</P>
<P>
   Depending on which state these snowbirds declare as ``home'' on
census forms, Arizona could gain or lose upward of $720 million
over the next decade in federal tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There is no in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Census forms have no provision for dual-state residency, though
that is how a growing number of Americans live, especially
retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Winter Visitors Associ ation in Apache Junction gets
daily calls from snowbirds confused about which state to list as
``home'' in this year's census. And Census Bureau offices in
snowbird-exporting com munities, like Fargo, N.D., also are swamped
with calls from Arizona and Florida retirement communities.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which finds itself feeding these retirees in senior
centers, pro tecting them with paramedic services and paving the
roads they drive on, wants them to write down Arizona as their
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been telling snowbirds that if they are in the Valley
April 1, they should fill out the form here,'' said Dan Austin,
president of the Arizona Winter Visitors Association. ``That is
what we have been told by the census office.''
</P>
<P>
   But faraway towns and states are asking their wandering retirees
to list them as their home. Minnesota officials have shown up at
Arizona events, such as last month's Minne sota Picnic in Mesa,
handing out leaflets and message-embossed pen cils, telling
wandering Minnesotans to list their old home on the census.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 300,000 retired winter visitors stay in Arizona.
Although January and February are the peak months, about
three-fourths of them still are here April 1. Of those, as many as
180,000 are U.S. residents.
</P>
<P>
   Many retirees stay from October through May, but still declare
some where else as their home on the census forms. They may fear
having to pay the extra freight here: Car tags and insurance, for
example, are often more expensive in Arizona. But the census forms
are confidential and not used for determining residency status,
even for illegal immigrants who are counted.
</P>
<P>
   Each person counted in a state translates into more federal
dollars and more representatives in Con gress. Every extra Arizonan
counted adds $3,500 to $4,000 in federal funds over the next 10
years, accord ing to various estimates. That money goes to health
care, transportation and social service programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Arizonans 65 and over make up about 14 percent of the
population, the same as the national average, the number of
retirement age residents here would grow to nearly 19 percent if
all Ariozna snowbirds were counted, according to Tom Rex of the
Arizona Center for Business Development.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe senior services suffer in Arizona and other Sun
Belt states because they serve more elders than indicated by past
census statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to any senior center during the winter and you will find
winter visitors eating lunch for free,'' said Anne Lindeman,
executive director of the Arizona Governor's Advisory Council on
Aging. Some of it evens out, she adds, when Arizona-based retirees
travel northward in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Delia Garcia Kim, Arizona's census director, said the state
isn't actively campaigning to persuade winter visi tors to consider
this their official home. But ``in all fairness to the community,
if they're spending a significant amount of time here, they're
using community resources,'' she said. ``They may not think of this
as their home, but in reality, if they're spending time here, it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``significant amount of time'' generally is defined as six
months and a day, or more than half the year, Garcia Kim said. When
asked, state officials will tell visitors this: If they're here on
or about April 1, they should mark Arizona as home.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona cities with large winter visitor populations also have
kept their efforts low-key, but encourage people to consider the
services they use when they're in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever you use the most govern ment services or spend the
majority of your year is where you should answer the census from,''
Peoria spokesman Kelly Corsette said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hall, field operations man ager for the Census Bureau's
Phoe nix office, said the general rule when filling out a census
form is to base the information on a person's ``usual address,''
where he or she lives most of the time. For most people, that's not
difficult, but for winter visitors the issue gets confusing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Lundberg, a retired lawyer who divides his time evenly
between Fargo and a home in Mesa, has no doubt about what he wants.
If he has to choose ``home,'' which seems to be the case this year
with the census, it's North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our low population, we have a heck of a time hanging on
to people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg has been checking his mailbox each day to see whether
his census form from North Dakota has been forwarded. But census
forms aren't forwarded because they are addressed to the residence,
not the individual. Still, many travelers have their mail forwarded
anyway, by family, friends or a private mail service. Lundberg did
receive a cen sus form, but it was addressed to his Mesa residence.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in late April and continuing through July, census
workers will begin visiting homes that didn't return forms.
</P>
<P>
   A major effort is planned for RV camps in Arizona's deserts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
