<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TPC-HNS &LR;      03-24 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Mulligans are fine on the first hole. But
you don't get many in life. And Fulton Allem would like to have
avoided this particular do-over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 43-year-old South African, who might as well have been
enjoying early retirement given his thorough lack of success the
past six years on the PGA Tour, had to tee it up again in his
personal life, going through a divorce that he called pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   As he recounted it in great detail Friday, ``They're all
pathetic, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Allem's comments came after an incredibly good round.
</P>
<P>
   His 7-under-par 65 scorched the Tournament Players Course at
Sawgrass and propelled him into solid contention at the midpoint of
The Players Championship. Hal Sutton leads at 6-under 138 after his
second consecutive 69.
</P>
<P>
   But at 4-under 140, Allem is right in the hunt _ unexpectedly
so. His sudden bolt of greatness caught just about everybody off
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Allem has been so far off the radar since his magical season in
1993 that he was considered lost. He has not had a top-three finish
since '93, when he won twice, including the Colonial in Fort Worth.
The first of his three career wins was the Independent Insurance
Agents Open at The Woodlands in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Allem fired verbal darts at his ex-wife, slow play on
tour, Tiger Woods and cursing _ which by the way, is one of his
favorite pastimes.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear that his protracted stretch of pitiful play on
tour was directly related to his divorce _ in Allem's mind, at
least.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the golf course, but my mind was nowhere near golf,''
Allem said of those bad years. ``I tried to play through it all,
and it leads to frustration, then it leads to losing your
confidence. Fortunately, I got my mulligan. It's a pity it didn't
happen 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Allem added: ``I couldn't care less what my ex-wife does. She
just must take care of my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Allem's story of despair is a tough one. But it's no more
shocking than the fact he was fined and suspended last year for
cursing aloud at the PGA Tour event in Reno, Nev., and that he
openly berates fellow pros for playing too slow.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his brash, sometimes crude nature, a few of Allem's
cohorts on tour would rather see anybody else have a good day on
the course. He's not the most popular figure on tour, partly
because he has a little Charles Barkley in him. He says what he
thinks, and the consequences don't concern him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them like me, and some of them think I'm a jackass,''
Allem said. ``What can I tell you? Nobody's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sutton said: ``If you don't want to hear how things really
are, don't talk to Fulton.''
</P>
<P>
   Now living near Orlando, Fla., Allem has started a new life with
his girlfriend. But the divorce from his first wife, Colleen, left
him bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was leading the Colonial (in '93) going into the last
round,'' Allem said. ``My ex-wife and two kids were flying back to
South Africa, so they weren't going to get to watch the final
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won the tournament, and I knew I'd be able to call South
Africa if I waited a few hours. I called, and she answered. I was
so excited. I said: `Hi, sweetheart, I just won the golf
tournament.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She said: `I don't love you anymore. I want a divorce. I'm not
coming back to the United States.' That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair tried to patch things up. Allem won the World Series of
Golf later in '93.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she came running,'' Allem said. ``There was money. She
came running. Then we spent the next four or five years between
misery and happiness. Eventually, she left with some ski instructor
from Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Colleen now lives with the kids. As always, there are two
sides to this story. But for Allem, all that matters is the
present, not the past.
</P>
<P>
   His separation from Colleen was the start of the lean times for
Allem, who never finished higher than 109th on the money list from
1994-99.
</P>
<P>
   Since then? Allem has become notorious for other things, like
his intolerance of slow play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's wrong,'' Allem said. ``Bob Estes, I played
with him the first time and wrote it right across his scorecard:
`You are too slow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We should all try to play the game within the rules. Etiquette
is not a small city in France. You have 40 seconds. Don't stand
there and mess around, because it's not fair to everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   And Allem will vent his frustration when things don't go his
way. He was fined and suspended for a week last year for cursing
near an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods, who is four shots out of the lead and only two
behind Allem, doesn't intimidate Allem in the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not unless he's got a gun,'' Allem said. ``I know a lot of
them (other players) are (intimidated). But I'm going for the
gusto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the kid is great. He's the best player, bar none. But
you have to go out there and enjoy the challenge, not go out there
and say: `I wonder how I'm going to beat this guy.' If I look at
his record and look at my record, ain't no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he can make mistakes. You might hole a 6-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Allem birdied five of his first seven holes,
including a 35-foot bomb on the par-4 14th. He then eagled the
par-5 second hole when his 2-iron cozied to within five feet of the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of luck involved shooting 65 on a course like
this in these conditions,'' said Allem, who added his putting was
crucial. ``For the last 10 years, all I've done is hit the ball and
putt like an absolute idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were mitigating factors. And Allem hopes never
to repeat the personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
