<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CREATES SCHOLARSHIP FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times announced Friday that it had
established an endowment fund to support and supplement a college
scholarship program that it created last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The fund recently received $1 million from the Starr Foundation,
a nonprofit organization in New York City that supports educational
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The Times announced last spring that its affiliate The New York
Times Co. Foundation would award scholarships of $12,000 a year for
four years to each of six high school seniors from New York City
who had surmounted daunting personal challenges to attain academic
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of readers asked how they could help the winners and the
other finalists. In response, The Times set up a public fund, which
last year financed 15 additional scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   By converting the fund to an endowment, the foundation will be
able to use income from investments to pay for more scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   This month the program awarded five scholarships of $12,000 a
year, financed by the foundation, as well as a sixth, also of
$12,000, paid by a grant from the Ochs-Sulzberger family, the
controlling shareholders of the Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   Seven scholarships of $6,000 a year are being financed from
public contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
