<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7620 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ASIA-WEB-INVESTOR-ART     03-24 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-WEB-INVESTOR-ART-3TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MANY ANALYSTS CAN SAY THEY WERE ONCE COMMUNISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: (Italics) used twice in 4th graf) 
(ART ADV: Graphic of ranking internet underwriters is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ On a sultry Sunday evening earlier this month,
Taiwanese death-metal rock music echoed from a party in a hillside
apartment far above the ribbon of headlights snaking through the
skyscrapers below. The living room was emptied of all but a couch,
a table and a couple of pairs of socks balled up in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Over the din, a dozen young Internet entrepreneurs swapped
business plans and financing tips, gushing over the millions they
hoped to make when their companies went public.
</P>
<P>
   Such soirees were unheard of a year ago, as was Matei Mihalca,
an Internet analyst from Merrill Lynch who was the host of these
festivities. His unbridled enthusiasm, and his embrace of the Net
culture, have quickly made him a favorite among Asia's new cyber
jet set. That and the fact that he can help make them all very,
very rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ehr-fei! You  &UR; (italics)have(end italics) &LR;  to meet these
guys!'' Mihalca shouted across the room, charging toward Ehr-fei
Liu, a Merrill technology banker, two Web design executives in tow.
``They already beat their revenue forecasts for the year. This is a
real growth story! Huge. I mean  &UR; (italics)huge!(end italics) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This company is all about opportunity!'' Then the cell phone in
his pocket rang, and Mihalca walked away, lost in the next big
opportunity, leaving the three men behind to exchange awkward
hellos.
</P>
<P>
   Asia is sick with dot-com fever. But no one has the bug so badly
as American investment banks hoping to take Asia's new Internet
companies public. Asian economies, left for dead two years ago when
the tumbling dominoes of a currency crisis brought the region's
growth to an abrupt halt, are being reinvented overnight. Or, at
least, Asia's stock markets are.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 50 Internet concerns in countries like China, India
and Singapore are likely to go public this year alone, more than
double the number that did so last year. Fueling that boom is the
rising number of people in Asia going online, projected to more
than triple over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations like those attract opportunists. So for investment
banks that largely missed the technology boom in the United States
over the last five years, lagging behind the powerhouses Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter and Goldman Sachs, Asia has become a place to
reinvent themselves, too.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch is among them. The technology practice of Merrill,
one of the world's biggest brokerage firms, pales when compared
with its peers over that period. Merrill ranks seventh worldwide in
the number of Internet businesses it has taken public, according to
Thomson Financial Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that Merrill has been slow to foster the oversized
personalities necessary these days to attract high-profile,
big-name clients. It has no technology analysts, for example, with
the renown _ and entree _ of Mary Meeker, who helped put Morgan
Stanley's practice on the map.
</P>
<P>
   But with Asia awakening to the Internet, Merrill sees the
possibility for a fresh start. ``The idea was: It's a land grab,
and we wanted to be there,'' said Adam Quinton, Merrill's former
head of Asia-Pacific research, who now helps coordinate
telecommunications research in New York.
</P>
<P>
   So last year, Merrill began the task of grooming Mihalca into an
Internet celebrity. He seems the unlikeliest of candidates _ a
30-year-old former Communist from Romania with no technology
background to speak of and little finance expertise. Even his
mother is surprised at the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something of a paradox that somebody who was raised in a
Communist state went on to work for a Wall Street firm,'' said
Doina Bochis, who still lives in Romania. ``He was always so
literary, like me, with a very strong, developed mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is eager, and willing, to avail himself of a public and a
business culture chasing dot-com fantasies. Mihalca is a tireless
traveler who visits as many as 25 companies a week and often takes
the lead in wooing potential clients into Merrill's fold. If he is
successful, it will mean millions of dollars in lucrative initial
public offering fees for his firm, and a bigger salary for him.
</P>
<P>
   His hunger to put Merrill Lynch and himself on the map, though,
raises a fundamental question for investors in both Asia and the
United States who rely on analysts like him to be their trail
guides through the vast plains of the Internet's Wild Wild East:
When does boosterism end and critical analysis begin?
</P>
<P>
   Even in the United States, the line between research and
salesmanship _ that is, between the traditional roles of stock
analyst and investment banker _ has blurred. Here, it has all but
been erased.
</P>
<P>
   Mihalca has no quibble with that. ``In many places, people think
this is a conflict,'' he said. ``I see it as working together.'' If
he doesn't believe in a company, he added, he simply won't
recommend taking it public.
</P>
<P>
   Such boldness concerns those who see Asia's Internet market as
immature and driven mostly by hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember reading a report from a guy talking about
philosophy and love, and that's because analysts are at a complete
loss,'' said J. Mark Mobius, who as managing director of Templeton
Asset Management has spent years searching the world for
undiscovered companies.
</P>
<P>
   It is more difficult finding sound investments in Asia, because
there is little in the way of a venture capital community to ferret
out the best ideas, he said. The danger is that untested businesses
will be sold to a ravenous public, with only investment bankers as
a buffer against speculative excess.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell if Merrill's gamble on Mihalca will pay
off. So far, he has yet to make any headline-grabbing stock
predictions like those of his American colleague Henry Blodget, who
made his name more than a year ago by predicting that Amazon.com
would hit $400 a share months before it did.
</P>
<P>
   And it may not be long before Mihalca follows in the footsteps
of other Merrill up-and-comers who have left for venture firms or
dot-com companies. He has been approached by a handful of
start-ups, and rivals say privately that in the past he has talked
about making a switch.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
