<DOCNO> NYT20000324.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7622 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ASIA-WEB-INVESTOR-ART     03-24 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-WEB-INVESTOR-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HONG KONG: a switch.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Opportunism, after all, is not just for institutions. ``Now that
there is attention being paid to this one sector, there is a
pedestal to step on,'' said Jay Chang, who competes with Mihalca as
an Internet analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in Hong Kong.
``So, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1:15 p.m. on March 8, a Wednesday, and the last day of a
technology conference Merrill had put on for Asian investors.
Mihalca was nowhere to be found. A dozen or so journalists were
milling around the ballroom lobby of the Island Shangri-La Hotel,
eagerly awaiting his arrival at a news conference. Mihalca,
nicknamed ``the mad scientist of Internet analysts'' by colleagues
because of his quirky ideas, was found napping on a couch. The
reason? He had spent all night writing a research report on an
Internet portal company that Merrill was hoping to take public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an experiment in selling,'' Mihalca said of the report
after he showed up in the lobby, quaffing a cup of coffee as he
rubbed sleep from his bloodshot eyes.
</P>
<P>
   For an analyst, Mihalca talks a lot about selling: selling
stocks to investors, selling companies on Merrill, selling himself
to all of them. In February 1999, just when the cyberworld in Asia
was beginning to take off, Merrill needed a bold and articulate
spokesman to better its image among journalists and potential
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective I gave him was to raise his profile in the
corporate world as quickly as possible,'' Quinton said. ``If
someone wanted to interview someone who was knowledgeable, he would
be the person the media turned to.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that his relevant experience was limited. He was a
fluent Mandarin speaker and well-versed in Asian culture and
politics, a necessity in countries where government and business
are so closely intertwined. And he showed an early affinity for
writing; his father was a journalist in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief stint at the United States Chamber of Commerce in
Taiwan, Mihalca was hired by Merrill in 1997 as an analyst. He was
not a natural fit at first, so was hired on a temporary basis,
Merrill executives said. But he showed promise, particularly as a
skilled networker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to know more people in Taiwan in one year than I did
in 10,'' said Peter Kurz, the director at Merrill in Taiwan who
hired him. ``He is disarmingly honest, and people trust him for
that reason.'' After first covering the semiconductor industry, he
was appointed head of Asia-Pacific Internet research last year.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, Merrill began its Mihalca campaign. He was
introduced to reporters at major media outlets, some of whom he
knew already from his stint freelancing for The Asian Wall Street
Journal. Merrill took out newspaper advertisements touting his
research and included his e-mail address. He made himself a regular
visitor to the CNBC studios on the 25th floor of the Asia Pacific
Finance Tower in central Hong Kong, eight floors above his own
humble cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promote myself,'' he said unabashedly in a recent interview.
Last month, he moderated an hourlong panel on CNBC Asia about the
Internet there. That was a result of an elevator conversation with
a ``Squawk Box'' anchor, Bernard Lo.
</P>
<P>
   And he always returns reporters' calls. When America Online and
Time Warner announced plans to merge in January, for instance, he
was disturbed at midnight by a reporter seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy about that,'' Mihalca said. ``You have to put
yourself in the customer's shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   But who, in fact, are Mihalca's customers? Some may still think
that analysts are the eyes and ears of investors, or at least their
brokers. But in truth, analysts like Mihalca labor to suit the
companies their bankers court.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Rosenthal, a fan and president of MeetChina.com, a
business-to-business Web site in China, said of Mihalca: ``I see
him as a salesman. He is out there getting the business.'' Mihalca
recently offered to broker an introduction between MeetChina
executives and a potential partner interested in setting up a joint
venture. He is also a trusted confidant; after an investor meeting,
Mihalca said he gently suggested that a MeetChina executive refrain
from talking about his colleagues' wives.
</P>
<P>
   Mihalca connects with young entrepreneurs in tradition-bound
Asia because he, like many of them, is an outsider. On a recent
Sunday morning, Mihalca, along with his Taiwanese wife, Ching-Fang
Hu, and Rajesh Jain, an Indian entrepreneur who recently sold his
Internet company for $115 million, took the ferry from Hong Kong
island to Kowloon for breakfast. The two men had met only once last
October, but they greeted each other with smiles and a hearty bear
hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Matei, we talked for three hours at a Bombay
hotel,'' Jain said over a breakfast of Egg McMuffins (a favorite of
Mihalca's) and coffee. ``I met someone who was as excited as I was
and really understood what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Such exuberance is rare on Wall Street. One colleague teased
that David Komansky, Merrill's chief executive, would grow pale if
he knew about the all-nighters Mihalca spent at the office. Mihalca
waves goodbye with two hands, and the floor shakes under his gait
as he runs down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think there is something neurologically wrong
with him,'' joked Duncan Wooldridge, a Merrill senior economist in
Hong Kong. ``One of the great things is that his excitement and
enthusiasm are contagious. He likes to talk about ideas. If you
don't have free time, don't go by his desk.''
</P>
<P>
   But can Mihalca adapt his style to more traditional clients,
particularly as the Internet sector matures? His discomfort with
established society became apparent hours after his meeting with
Jain. Mihalca and his wife were invited to the exclusive Hong Kong
Jockey Club for a private party held by Champion Technology, a
multibillion-dollar communications concern. It was Derby Day, the
equivalent of the Kentucky Derby in the United States. Clearly
Mihalca was not on familiar terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice carpet,'' he said sarcastically, pointing to the burst of
purple and orange on one of the floors. The guest list was a who's
who of Hong Kong's diplomatic corps and business society. They had
arrived in private cars, while Mihalca took a cab because he missed
the train. His khakis and tweed jacket looked pedestrian compared
with other guests' tailored suits and dresses. And while Champion's
chairman, Paul Kan, held court with older, more polished investment
bankers, Mihalca was briefly introduced when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   To him, the business culture of the jockey club's patrons was a
curiosity to be studied and understood. Theirs is a social
structure being displaced by newer entrants. And to comprehend
where society was going, one had to understand from where it had
come.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
