<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7623 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ASIA-WEB-INVESTOR-ART     03-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-WEB-INVESTOR-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HONG KONG: had come.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Sure, I felt more comfortable this morning with Rajesh,'' he
said later, during the cab ride home. ``But you have to understand
this world, too. You can't turn your back on them just because it
is not comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihalca was born on April 5, 1969, an only child, and lived in
the small Romanian mountain town of Baia Sprie, 100 miles from
Bucharest. Food was scarce under the tyranny of Nicolae Ceausescu,
and the lights in young Matei's house ran on a car battery.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers his mother, a hospital psychiatrist, treating
``depressed people who swallowed detergent and stuff.'' (His
stepfather, Mircea Bochis, an artist, married his mother 24 years
ago.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a lone cowboy,'' Mihalca said. And at times that has cost
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had problems in school because he spoke against the
system,'' his mother recalled. ``He presented himself openly as an
anti-Communist. I always said, `Shut up! Be quiet!'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his views, Mihalca joined the Communist Party in 1988.
If he hadn't, he said, he might have missed the opportunity that
has defined his career: a chance to study Chinese in Beijing in
1989, as one of a handful of students plucked from the University
of Bucharest for a summer exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   Turmoil seems to chase him, or he, it. Then just 20, he arrived
at the Beijing Language Institute on June 7, days after the
massacre at Tiananmen Square. Armored vehicles rolled past his
dormitory-room window. Many foreign students had returned to their
embassies, and as their mail piled up in the dorm lobby, he spent
his summer skipping classes, reading Western magazines and learning
to ride a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, back in Baie Sprie, he and his family huddled
around a television set and watched the Ceaucescu government
crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Mihalca returned to Beijing and was later accepted into a
doctoral program at Harvard University to study history and East
Asian languages. He spent five years there but never finished his
dissertation. In Cambridge, too, he had a difficult time getting
along. Nikolas Gloy, a Harvard friend and next-door neighbor, said
Mihalca openly criticized the research of fellow students and
corrected the grammar of native Chinese speakers.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed to reflect, Mihalca acknowledges that those were
not happy days. ``Being a Romanian guy studying Chinese in America
did not work that well,'' he said. He paused for a moment, deep in
thought, the memory seemingly raw. ``In a way I am like my father,
somewhat cold. I do not feel the need to be sentimental about my
past.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone best understands Mihalca, it is probably his wife, Hu.
The two met in Taipei in 1997, where she was editor in chief of
Playboy Taiwan, for which she now consults.
</P>
<P>
   Having a dialogue with society is important to her husband, she
said. And at Merrill Lynch, he gets the attention he craves. ``He
has a childish side _ like a baby, naughty,'' she said. ``He needs
a lot of love. He is like a complicated child who is always
thinking, and it is hard to get to the heart of where his mind
is.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still early in the race to take Asia's Internet industries
public. Among investment banks, Lehman Brothers, an also-ran in the
United States, has captured much of the attention here so far with
two high-profile offerings last year. One was for Chinadotcom, the
other for Pacific Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ravi Sarathy, Lehman's chief Internet analyst and an early
dot-com celebrity in Asia, played a key role in attracting that
business.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Wall Streeters, he has since departed to create
his own online start-up. But he remains a consultant to Lehman
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the banking business here are as peculiar. Some
analysts are also entrepreneurs. Eric Gan, who works for Goldman
Sachs Japan, is also co-founder of eAccess Ltd., an Internet
service provider in which Goldman has invested, said a spokeswoman
for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Internet stocks keep going up, there seem to be few
complaints about such arrangements. The real test will come when
companies begin to stumble. Then, the true Internet stars will
shine, the analysts and bankers who can separate the novas from the
black holes.
</P>
<P>
   Clients and investors say Mihalca's strength is understanding a
concept _ and, even better, marketing it. But as the investing
world comes to focus more on revenue and profits, the ability to
sell a story will hold less appeal. Then the plodding, less
glamorous, but more incisive analysis will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   That may prove uncomfortable to Mihalca and others like him who
are making young Asian entrepreneurs rich today, but will be
duty-bound to chastise them if they fail to execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were to happen, it would be a personal disappointment,''
Mihalca said. ``You invest a lot of time and energy and personal
commitment.'' But by then, he added, he may have a large-enough
staff to help him work through the numbers. ``How I delegate the
nitty-gritty to our team members,'' he said, ``is something I will
have to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   He is acutely aware that if Asia's Internet companies fail to
deliver, his 15 minutes in the spotlight are up. But in this
market, where everything is a ``buy,'' he does not seem to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pick companies that go up in flames, well, it is
everyone who goes up in flames,'' he said. ``Then it is not about
you anymore. The story is fairly sound. If the Internet as a whole
doesn't work out, it is not my problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
