A7631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-STOCK-TRADES-NYT     03-24 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STOCK-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRADING STOCK FOR THE BEST PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, March 25:
</P>
<P>
   A technological revolution is shaking up Wall Street, and
federal regulators are scrambling to keep up. The explosive growth
of electronic brokers is bringing investors lightning-quick,
low-cost execution of trades. But with the benefits of this new
form of competition come threats that some investors may not get
the best price for their stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission worries that the pillars
of American stock trading, the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq,
are moving sluggishly to meet the challenge posed by the growth of
electronic communications networks. These electronic brokers use
sophisticated software programs that match buyers and sellers. By
contrast, the floor exchanges and Nasdaq rely on slower, costlier
human intermediaries to complete many trades.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic brokers can match buyers and sellers perfectly well
when there are lots of buyers and sellers hovering around. But for
stocks that are only infrequently traded, human intermediaries
serve the valuable function of smoothing what would otherwise be
erratic swings in price, for example by purchasing shares during
periods when buyers are nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Intermediaries provide something else that electronic brokers
cannot: price improvement. Specialists on the floor exchange, after
analyzing their roster of offers to buy and sell at specified
future prices, often offer customers prices better than those that
were posted at the time their orders arrived. Electronic brokers
merely search for the best current price.
</P>
<P>
   With the growth of trading on several electronic networks comes
fragmentation, or splitting of trades among different exchanges,
dealers and electronic networks.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of fragmentation is that investors get more choices
of where to trade stocks. The downside is that some markets will
offer better prices than others in ways that will not be clear to
individual investors. Current rules require brokers to provide
customers the best price available anywhere. But the rule is often
violated.
</P>
<P>
   A troubling example of fragmentation comes from dealers who
match buy and sell orders from their own customers without
directing them to floor exchanges, Nasdaq or anywhere else. They
probably represent a bigger threat to the floor exchanges than do
electronic brokers. The question lingers how well these dealers are
serving their customers.
</P>
<P>
   To address some of these problems the SEC chairman, Arthur
Levitt Jr., has proposed that traders disclose customer offers to
buy and sell stocks on a central electronic display for everyone to
inspect simultaneously. He also called for electronic linkages so
traders can send orders wherever the price is best _ to floor
exchanges, Nasdaq or electronic networks. Both recommendations
should be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   But another idea, designed to encourage brokers to be aggressive
in offering customers better prices, should be embraced more
cautiously. Under current rules, if a specialist on the floor of
the stock exchange offers to pay $20 for a stock, up from $19, in
hopes of attracting trades, other dealers can hold their own
customers merely by matching the new $20 offer. That squashes the
incentive to make aggressive bids.
</P>
<P>
   To attack this problem, the commission has issued for comment a
controversial plan that would require that trades go to the broker
who first posts the best price. This time-based rule would reward
aggressive offers.
</P>
<P>
   Big brokerage houses like the idea. But the New York Stock
Exchange fears that a time-based rule could destroy the way the
specialists and brokers interact on the floor of stock exchanges,
undermining the most competitive arena of stock trading. That is
why Levitt started with the easier calls _ electronic display and
links _ and proceeds cautiously before rewriting rules that dictate
where trades take place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2347EST &QL; 
