<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT &LR;      03-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS HEAT UP AND THEN HOLD ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once Latrell Sprewell ducked out of the locker room
after halftime to offer a visual on assertiveness Friday night, the
New York Knicks perked up just long enough to tuck away a
crestfallen Atlanta Hawks team that was auditioning its young
talent for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Hawks' best player, Dikembe Mutombo, only played in
the first and third quarters, the Knicks still had hiccups on their
way to a 95-83 victory Friday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   This was not exactly the send-off of the Knicks' dreams, not
when their sloppiness enabled the Hawks to cut a fourth-quarter
16-point lead to eight, but the Knicks managed to set themselves up
for their five-game West Coast trip with a needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   By scoring 15 of his 30 points in the third quarter, by giving
his languid team a boost with defensive energy, Sprewell made sure
the Knicks (42-26) would not slip against an easy opponent.
</P>
<P>
   After the Hawks cut the Knicks' lead to eight with four minutes
remaining, Sprewell came up with a three-pointer and a steal that
led to another basket to provide his team with breathing room.
Allan Houston ended the game with 27 points, while Patrick Ewing
ended with eight points in 34 minutes against Mutombo (three
points, 24 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks arrived as a team that in no way resembled the one
that faced the Knicks in the playoffs last season. On their way to
the worst season since the 1970-1971 team, the Hawks have been a
dysfunctional mess, punctuated on March 17, when the organization
severed ties with Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
   He was the very player they believed could give them a lift
against the Knicks, but the erratic Rider delivered only headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Only on occasion have the Hawks taken a break from their
troubles and found success. Twice the Knicks have provided relief
for them. In their two previous meetings, both in Atlanta, the
Hawks leaned on Mutombo's sharpened elbow to intimidate the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Circling Ewing, Mutombo averaged 15 points and 22 rebounds in
those two games. With his ominous positioning in the paint, Mutombo
turned the Knicks into jump-shooters who were too timid to confront
him with a driving layup.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, coach Jeff Van Gundy wanted his team focused on
being the aggressor Friday night. Not only as a way to grab the
victory but also to set them up mentally for their West Coast road
trip, which will begin in Portland, Ore., on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 0-2 against a team like we are against Atlanta,
and you have problems historically against teams that rebound and
have size in the paint like Atlanta does, you don't think about the
trip,'' Van Gundy said before the game. ``But also, if you do think
about it, you get depressed. It's going to be quite a challenge. As
I told our team today, our West Coast trip starts now.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the start he imagined Friday night. Although the
Knicks began the game driving inside to test Mutombo, they shook at
the sight of him, changed their shots and missed a stream of
layups. On the other end, the Hawks were driving inside on Ewing
and then Camby for uncontested layups and popping open jumpers over
the loose coverage of Houston and Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   This slack mentality by the Knicks extended into their ball
handling as well. After consecutive turnovers by Houston and Kurt
Thomas, the Hawks stopped trading baskets with the Knicks and
grabbed a 43-38 lead with five minutes left in the first half. At
that point, the Hawks were shooting 55 percent and outrebounding
the Knicks. And most of this damage was done with Mutombo on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks, the Hawks have been in future mode, wanting
to look at young players such as center Lorenzen Wright. He was
playing well in the second quarter, so coach Lenny Wilkens kept him
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second quarter, the Knicks finally awoke to the fact
that Mutombo was off the floor and made a 14-6 run to close out the
half. Strangely enough, they junked driving to the basket, even
with Mutombo out of their way, and rode the hot touch of Houston to
take a 52-49 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell provided the jolt. With 15 energetic points in the
third, he pushed the Knicks out to a 78-66 lead entering the
fourth. From the second-half tip, Sprewell's force was uncorked. He
raced down the court for a dunk off the fast break while being
fouled in the process and then turned a steal into another
opportunity for his team.
</P>
<P>
   By pushing the ball and passing crisply to the open man, he was
the energy boost the Knicks needed.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell brought everyone along for the ride. Even Larry
Johnson, who has been mired in a slump for two weeks, found his
rhythm. It did not matter if Ewing and Mutombo were getting nowhere
as they banged heads inside; the Knicks had intensity on defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
