<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETH-POPE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURIAN'S RESEARCH INTO BIBLICAL TIMES GETS POPE'S ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the Tabgha
Monastery by the Sea of Galilee on Friday, young people sang
``Kumbaya,'' and nuns and priests filled the chapel.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Magruder, president of Truman State University in
Kirksville, Mo., sat in a folding chair, awaiting Pope John Paul
II.
</P>
<P>
   The pope came through the door, approached the altar and prayed.
Then it was time for the ceremony that had drawn Magruder thousands
of miles.
</P>
<P>
   A Benedictine monk handed the pope two books that Truman State
University Press had published about the lost town of Bethsaida, an
ancient fishing village nearby. Scholars believe it was the home of
the apostle Peter and other disciples of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church considers Peter the first pope; Jesus told
Peter he was the rock on which he would build his church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter. Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   A frail John Paul II repeated the name of his predecessor and
smiled at Magruder's small delegation from the Bethsaida
Excavations Project, based at the University of Nebraska-Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Magruder, a Methodist, said his heart would forever cherish
Friday's brief meeting and his travels along the Sea of Galilee.
The area around Bethsaida is where the New Testament says Jesus
performed miracles, including feeding thousands of people with a
few fish and loaves of bread, curing a blind man and walking on the
sea's water to strengthen the faith of his followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been overwhelming,'' Magruder said by telephone from
a kibbutz hotel, where his window overlooks the Sea of Galilee.
``All my life I have heard of these places, and it never occurred
to me that I would ever go. We're seeing Jerusalem, Bethlehem, the
Sea of Galilee, (the place) where Jesus said the Beatitudes. All
those things _ they're just pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The road to Galilee for Magruder began a decade ago when he was
a vice president at Northeast Missouri State University, now called
Truman State.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Mark Appold asked Magruder whether the school could
join other universities in digging out the lost town of Bethsaida,
just north of the Sea of Galilee on the east bank of the Jordan
River. Magruder approved.
</P>
<P>
   Appold now takes Truman students to Israel, Jordan and Syria
every summer. They work with the Bethsaida Excavation Project's
founder, Israeli archaeologist Rami Arav, an adjunct professor at
Nebraska-Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   The students sift dirt and move rocks. Lots of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   They discover pottery shards and fishing hooks. They hold in
their hands clues to what the world looked like 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting because it's like a treasure hunt and you never
know what you're going to find,'' Appold said of the dig.
</P>
<P>
   The excavations have revealed an old city gate believed to
predate Jesus' birth by several centuries, a statue of an Egyptian
god, a small Roman temple and a large house with a courtyard. The
researchers also found a Roman key. A replica of the key also was
given to John Paul II on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The finds aren't complete, but archaeologists and historians are
using the pieces to unravel the history of this town that had
disappeared from maps for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Arav decided to investigate a mound just east
of the Jordan River called et-Tell to see whether it was the site
of Bethsaida.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars now say it was. Now Bethsaida is marked on Israeli
maps, and Truman State University's books on Bethsaida are sold in
the Israel Museum. And the Truman State students participate in the
discovery of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible just to think about how old the place you
were standing is,'' said senior Kenny Boyce, a nondenominational
Christian from Raymore who participated in the dig. ``All the
things that had taken place there _ it was amazing. We got to go
swimming in the Sea of Galilee every day we were on the dig.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyce is working toward a physics degree with a minor in
philosophy and religion. ``It was a chance to explore my faith a
little and see the historical places associated with my faith. I
felt a deeper connection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's also what the trip has given Magruder _ a chance to live
the words in his Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Magruder plans to visit the archaeological site and
witness the placing of a marker honoring Truman State and the other
colleges in the Bethsaida Excavations Project.
</P>
<P>
   Magruder said he has been moved by the pope's emphasis on peace
between people of different faiths, especially between Catholics
and Jews and between Jews and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   In reading one of the pontiff's books during his Israeli trip,
Magruder found a piece of wisdom which he said will ``be on my lips
often.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethnic and cultural differences should never be seen as
justifying conflict,'' John Paul II wrote. ``Rather, like the
various voices in a choir, these differences can exist in harmony,
provided there is a real desire to respect one another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
