<HEADLINE>
NEW SCHEDULE DRAWS REACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ The newly configured 2000 Irwindale Speedway
schedule could be one of feast or famine, according to several
drivers who competed at the track last year.
</P>
<P>
   The speedway _ which begins its second season at 7 tonight with
a full slate of NASCAR races, including the $15,000 Home Depot
Super Late Model 100 _ has eliminated its heat races and will have
longer feature events.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the top guys, it's not a big deal,'' said Rip Michels of
Mission Hills, who will compete in tonight's Grand American
Modified class race. ``We rarely were in the heats. But for the
guys trying to qualify, it will make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The track's trophy dashes _ for the fastest six qualifiers _
will remain in place. But instead of qualifying heats, the track
will have a lesser main event for the slower qualifiers, with the
top finishers being added to the main event.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something was not right, you could change things and check
for leaks during the heat races,'' said John Watkinson of Santa
Clarita, a Grand American driver. ``I think (the change) is
political.''
</P>
<P>
   Track competition director Chris Morgan says the elimination of
the heats and lengthening of the feature event will save wear and
tear on the cars and add to the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes for better racing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's Super Late Model winner will receive $3,000 with the
last-place finisher receiving $200, double the entry fee. More than
60 cars are expected to vie for the 30-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Late Models, Grand American and Super Stocks will also be
competing.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket office opens at noon, the gates at 5 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-24-00 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
