<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7643 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PLAYGROUND-SAFETY-2TA     03-24 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYGROUND-SAFETY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY, ACCESSIBILITY BECOME FOCUS FOR KC AREA PLAYGROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY ALAN BAVLEY AND RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The metal slide and
other playground equipment in Montgall Park, at 22nd Street and
Kansas Avenue, were getting uncomfortably warm Friday in the midday
sun.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In the hot Kansas City sun, those heat up and burn hands and
feet,'' said Denise Dowd, an emergency room doctor at Children's
Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Underfoot, mixed in with the sand and pea gravel around the
equipment, half-buried pieces of broken glass glinted menacingly.
They are a sure source of lacerations for any child running
barefoot, Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   Playground hazards like these are common to the parks and
schools of central Kansas City, where antiquated equipment and
years of neglect put children at risk. But safety experts from
Children's Mercy and community leaders said Friday at a news
conference at Montgall Park that they hope to eliminate many of
these perils.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Montgall Park this spring, and eventually
focusing on other parks, they plan to replace broken-down
playgrounds with newer, safer equipment. And by encouraging local
residents to get involved in the design and construction of the
playgrounds, Children's Mercy intends to use the improvements as a
catalyst to revive inner-city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody plays a role in this. It's a neighborhood effort,''
said Lenita Johnson, manager of the Center for Childhood Safety at
Children's Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Unsafe playgrounds have been recognized in recent years as a
serious problem in neighborhoods across the country, particularly
in urban cores. And many communities in the Kansas City area and
elsewhere, including suburbs that generally have more resources for
playground improvements, have been working to eliminate such
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Mercy project, called Safe Places, is modeled
after a similar program in New York's Harlem neighborhood, where
Harlem Hospital Center has worked to improve more than 30
playgrounds over the past decade. During that time, the incidence
of accidental injuries among children there has been cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want children out exercising, not playing in abandoned
buildings and in the street, and not sitting in front of a
television,'' said Barbara Barlow, the physician who organized the
Harlem playgrounds program.
</P>
<P>
   Although city tax money will pay for some of the Kansas City
park improvements, Children's Mercy is seeking private donations to
buy new equipment for playgrounds. A Safe Places fund has been set
up at the Greater Kansas City Community Foundation to accept
donations.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 study by the Consumer Federation of America found that
nationwide, 87 percent of all public playgrounds lacked adequate
protective surfaces. Climbing equipment was too high in 62 percent
of playgrounds, and 58 percent had swings placed too close
together.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Children's Mercy researchers have identified these
kinds of playground hazards as a significant cause of childhood
injuries, especially in the inner city, Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   From August 1997 through September 1998, the emergency room at
Children's Mercy treated 146 children for playground-related
injuries. Fourteen had to be hospitalized. The total cost of
treating their injuries was $205,294.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the injuries occurred in playgrounds in Kansas
City's 3rd City Council district, which covers roughly the area
bounded by Ninth Street on the north, 41st Street on the south,
Troost Avenue on the west and the city line on the east.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the hospital of 42 playgrounds at parks, schools and
community organizations in the 3rd District found more than a dozen
had hazardous or outmoded equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The problems included equipment in which a child's head could
become trapped; broken swing chains, metal bolts projecting from
climbing equipment, an unstable climbing dome, broken glass,
chipped paint and cement play surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   With neighborhood residents pitching in to help, two new
playgrounds will be built in Montgall Park in late April.
</P>
<P>
   One playground is designed for children about 2 to 5 years old;
the other, for older children up to about 12. Equipment will be
made of vinyl, and both playgrounds will have spongy rubber play
surfaces that will be poured into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably about the best surfacing you can get,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The city is adding a walking trail, two drinking fountains and a
baseball diamond. But Children's Mercy is seeking donations to
cover the $64,000 cost of playground equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy has been working on the project with the
Washington Wheatley Neighborhood Association, which represents
residents living around Montgall Park. Parents and children in the
neighborhood helped choose the playground equipment and their
preferred colors.
</P>
<P>
   Local social service organizations such as the Seton Center
Family and Health Services, schools and the city parks and
recreation and police departments also have lent their support.
</P>
<P>
   And as plans for the new playgrounds have progressed, they have
already stimulated community interest in new projects, Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a local artist plans to work with young people in
the neighborhood to paint murals, a way to cut down on graffiti.
And several residents have expressed interest in starting a Little
League team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great opportunity to revitalize the
neighborhood,'' said Rachel Asaro, director of Seton Center, which
is a block from the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to now, we've been afraid to use the park because of the
crime element. This is a way for the community to take hold and
make this a safe place,'' Asaro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision is to see children out here playing safely. Older
adults coming out and seeing the beauty of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy expects the new playgrounds to be very
well-used. The Washington Wheatley neighborhood has more than 3,000
residents. Another 11,000 people in nearby neighborhoods are also
likely to use the park. About 25 percent of the population of those
neighborhoods is under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Other Kansas City area communities also are addressing the
problem of unsafe playgrounds:
</P>
<P>
   - Independence is halfway through a roughly six-year, $620,000
program to upgrade the city's playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the last two to three years we have removed a lot of
outdated playground equipment,'' said Jim Fisher, who oversees the
city's playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, because funding wasn't readily available, those
playgrounds were not replaced right away. Independence officials,
however, felt such steps were necessary to protect children from
potentially hazardous equipment and the city from lawsuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
