r a BC-PLAYGROUND-SAFETY-2nd     03-24 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYGROUND-SAFETY-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY, ACCESSIBILITY BECOME FOCUS FOR KC AREA PLAYGROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY ALAN BAVLEY AND RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Installation for six
brand-new playgrounds is underway and expected to be completed by
May. Another six playgrounds are planned in another two years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   New playgrounds feature shorter slides and
handicapped-accessible equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to new playgrounds funded by a one-eighth cent sales
tax, city officials have also started a matching grant program that
provides partial funding to neighborhood groups that also help pay
for more playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things would've, should've, could've been taken care of
years ago,'' Fisher said. ``Playground safety has been around a
long time, but it hasn't been a household term until the last few
years. Now, people are paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   - Overland Park has been spending between $50,000 and $100,000
annually to remove and replace outdated or unsafe playground
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Such ongoing efforts are necessary in the city's 50 playgrounds,
explained Parks and Forestry Manager Greg Ruther, because safety
standards and guidelines change almost every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have older equipment out there that was current when it
was purchased, but like everything else, that changes,'' Ruther
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three city staff members certified in playground inspection also
make monthly checks on playground equipment, he said, looking for
things like protruding screws, damaged equipment or thinning mulch
around structures. Those areas most in need get highest priority.
Another focus is making all playgrounds handicapped-accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten more aggressive in the last couple of years,''
Ruther said.
</P>
<P>
   - Lee's Summit has started regular playground equipment
inspections, replacement and modernization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all our playgrounds have gone through a cycle in
changes in the last few years,'' said Parks and Recreation
Administrator Tom Lovell. ``We yanked all the equipment out,
replaced all the equipment and materials. The old jungle gyms you
used to find in playgrounds? You won't find those anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the city is spending roughly $90,000 on new
playground equipment at three parks: Hartman, Lowenstein and
Summit.
</P>
<P>
   As in Overland Park, officials in Lee's Summit still know there
is equipment in their parks that does not meet current guidelines,
said Lovell, but that the city is only within a few years until all
that is gone also.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make adjustments as rapidly as'' standards change,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
