<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WOLVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS IN PAINFUL LOSS TO TIMBERWOLVES, 116-115 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As the Nets desperately chased the
Timberwolves around the court trying to foul, to somehow prolong a
game that they needed to win, the horn sounded, ending the game.
The next sound was Kevin Garnett's booming voice, screaming in
search of Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' he shouted. ``Give me some love.''
</P>
<P>
   That Marbury could do, hugging his former Minnesota teammate and
friend. But what Marbury could not do was smile, not after the Nets
saw an emotional comeback ruined in the final seconds of overtime
Friday night as they fell to the Timberwolves, 116-115, at
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With Orlando winning Friday night, the 11th-place Nets slipped
four games from the eighth and last playoff spot in the Eastern
Conference, with 14 games to play.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett methodically pounded nails into the Nets' playoff hopes.
He hit seven of his first eight shots and finished with 38 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the first meeting of the two teams since Marbury forced his
way out of Minnesota, Marbury had 39 points and the victory.
Garnett had 27 points and 18 rebounds in that game, but he shot
just nine for 33.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, Marbury had the burden of traveling back to
Minnesota, but it was his friend Garnett who seemed most affected
by the reunion. While Marbury was booed regularly, Garnett seemed
to shrink under the emotion of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I rushed a couple of shots, probably didn't take as
much time as I should have,'' Garnett said before Friday night's
game. ``At the same time, they came to play. Last time was more
emotional, just because I hadn't seen Steph in a long time. When
you take that out of the equation, I'm a lot more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you step on the floor with an ex-teammate things
are going to always come back. It won't probably be as high-profile
or high-intensity, but it will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   That performance got the Timberwolves to rethink their approach
to the game, diversifying their attack rather than running
everything through Garnett. Since that game, Garnett had shot 55.3
percent and the team had won 13 of 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was probably a blessing in disguise,'' Minnesota
coach Flip Saunders said. ``After that we really ended up
diversifying our offense more. We do not run nearly as much stuff
through Kevin, and Kevin's been a lot more efficient. If you look
at our last game, he scored 40 points with 23 shots. We've done
some things to take some pressure off him. Wally Szczerbiak has
come in and played well. We have a lot more team balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett added: ``It woke us up, man. It woke us up to the point
that we're not as good as we think we are. We've got to come out
and bring it every night.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little danger of Garnett's slipping into that sort of
shooting night this time as he dropped in his first shot and then
rarely missed after that. He hit seven of eight from the floor in
the first quarter, piling up 14 points as the Timberwolves built a
30-21 lead after one period.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves built the lead to as many as 14 points in the
second period, but the Nets, despite allowing Minnesota to shoot
62.5 percent in the first half, continued to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 11 with less than two minutes left in the half, the
Nets got a breakaway dunk by Jamie Feick on a steal by Marbury, and
then Marbury added a pull-up 3-point field goal on the next trip.
</P>
<P>
   That cut the lead to 6, and the Nets went into the locker room
down by just 56-48.
</P>
<P>
   In their second-half comeback, the Nets made big shots, with
Keith Van Horn, Kerry Kittles and Marbury taking turns converting
in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   The game went back and forth for the final minute of regulation,
with the lead changing hands six times.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 1 point with 7.7 seconds left when Marbury fouled
out, Lucious Harris entered the game. Kittles attempted a short
jumper, and as the ball bounced off the rim, Harris darted into the
lane, leaping inside and above the 7-foot Garnett to tip in the
go-ahead shot with 2.2 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett then drew a foul at the other end as he and Burrell
battled for position. He converted one of two shots with the clock
not moving to send the game into overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
