<HEADLINE>
NEW CONTRACT URGED FOR ASSOCIATED'S UNION WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ About 300 supporters
of Associated Wholesale Grocers Inc.'s union workers gathered
Friday near the food wholesaler's Kansas City, Kan., headquarters,
calling for a new contract for more than 600 employees.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friends, family members, and area union activists picketed and
chanted on Kansas Avenue, across the street from Associated's
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was held with just eight days remaining on a
three-year agreement between Associated and Teamsters Local 955.
The local represents Associated's warehouse and transportation
department employees.
</P>
<P>
   Associated gave those workers a 60-day layoff notice on Feb. 1,
saying it was outsourcing those operations to private companies on
April 2 unless a new contract could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   A similar notice was delivered to nearly 700 Associated
employees at its Springfield division.
</P>
<P>
   Associated, an 850-member store food cooperative, said it needed
work-rule changes to boost productivity and efficiency in the face
of competition from Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and other national chains.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters officials have contended they have made proposals to
increase efficiencies for the cooperative but have been rejected at
every turn.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, supporters of Associated's employees made their
viewpoint known.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question is, how can (Associated) negotiate in good faith
when they have already given the workers a 60-day notice?'' asked
Beverly Welling, whose husband has worked in the garage of
Associated's transportation department for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Welling said her husband and other employees are not interested
in working for another company that would handle Associated's
transportation department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have 30 years in and a retirement plan with the
Teamsters, he wouldn't consider working in a new nonunion
environment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perryman Refrigerated Lines, which has a tentative agreement to
operate Associated's transportation department in Kansas City,
Kan., on April 2, employs owner-operators who are nonunion.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Goodman, a union driver for Fleming Companies Inc., said
he was supporting the work force of a competing company in efforts
to sustain a middle-class standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Associated) is a profitable company that the union has helped
build up through the years,'' said Goodman, a 14-year driver for
Fleming. ``Now, the company has achieved superiority in the
marketplace, and they want to throw the union aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Kansas Gov. Joan Finney also attended Friday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know you are right, nothing can stop you,'' she told
a cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Associated reiterated Friday that it is seeking to resolve the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to the negotiations,'' said Jerry Garland,
Associated's senior vice president of marketing. ``But time is
running short. We're disappointed the Teamsters have only met with
us six times since Feb. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Associated and Teamsters officials met March 16-17 in Clinton,
Mo., and a follow-up session was held on Wednesday. Bobby Davidson,
president of Local 955, said the union presented a new proposal to
pay drivers based on hours and mileage, but it was soundly
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get there, but it's difficult when they reject
everything that's put on the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baker, Associated's chief negotiator, said the two sides
have made little progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at their proposal for the drivers versus our
tentative contract with Perryman, and it was woefully inadequate,''
Baker said. ``It fell far short of the savings we would gain from
Perryman.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the company was hoping the union would present a
written proposal on Tuesday, when daily negotiations begin as the
contract deadline approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk about these issues in theory and concept, but the
union needs to get to the specifics as AWG has done in our proposal
that has been on the table for six weeks,'' Baker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
