<HEADLINE>
KCP&AMP;L SUBSIDIARY JOINS E-COMMERCE VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City Power &AMP;
Light Co. subsidiary has become a partner in a venture that aims to
boost the use of e-commerce in purchasing supplies by electric
utilities in the U.S. and abroad.
<TEXT>
<P>
   KLT Inc., KCP&AMP;L's deregulated subsidiary, and the St.
Louis-based utility Ameren UE, have become partners with bex.com on
an electronic site that will allow electric utilities to combine
their buying power and shop for everything from paper clips to
heavy machinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This...exchange for the electrical utilities industry
effectively brings an old economy market into the new economy,''
said Greg Orman, president of KLT.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of KLT's investment was not disclosed, although KCP&AMP;L
spokesman Tom Robinson described it as ``small.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is expected to begin operating in the second
quarter. Other utilities also might become partners, said Erin
Lutz, a spokeswoman for bex.com based in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz said the electronic platform will allow electric utilities
to amass more buying power. In addition, it is expected to smooth
the purchasing of supplies by putting in one place everything from
quotations to payment.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1996, bex.com operates e-marketplaces specializing in
business-to-business transactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
