<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-24 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-MAIL-KAN &LR;      03-24 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-MAIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPRING DIP INTO THE MAILBAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The time has come,
the walrus said, to speak of many things, mostly of how long it has
been since Uncle Fearless turned the column's reins over to his
valued contributors. Dipping into the ol' mailbag, the first
contribution is from a guy wondering about the stock market's
recent whuppin' of Procter &AMP; Gamble.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When P&AMP;G announced quarterly profits were going to be lower
than expected...P&AMP;G shares dropped $28 (and when) computer trading
kicked in (it caused) the fourth-largest one-day dip in (Dow Jones
industrial average) history. What if the market had said, `OK. So
what?' What would the impact to shareholders have been if there had
not been this large sell-off?''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Wondering: There are two answers to your question, both
simple. If the market had ignored P&AMP;G's transgression, P&AMP;G
investors would be a lot richer today, at least on paper. It's a
meaningless hypothetical, though. The market never says `OK. So
what?' when companies mislead Wall Street on earnings prospects.
The punishment is always certain and swift, because analysts will
forgive earnings disappointments a lot sooner than they will being
played for fools.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of being played for fools, another reader had some
questions about how those demonizing the tobacco industry to enrich
themselves could do so without disinterested bystanders asking
obvious questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it illegal for a child to smoke because it might kill
him, yet OK for a mother to kill him in the womb? Why is it I can
sit in a bar in some states, consume (beer), then drive anywhere,
yet...I have to step outside into the weather (to) smoke? Why is it
in this supposedly free country an immigrant (co-worker) from
Russia would comment, `I guess I'll have to go back to Russia to
enjoy the freedom of smoking,' (which) made me ashamed to admit I
served in the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Questioning: Having no good answers to your questions, some
advice will have to do. As one veteran to another, never be ashamed
of your military service. This type of contribution may be out of
fashion, but it's still a highly honorable aspect of your life.
Meanwhile, there are worse things than being harassed as a smoker.
Living in Russia would top my list in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the military, one reader wrote a letter to the
editor to point out that the cost of maintaining a U.S. defense
presence in the Middle East means gasoline taxes are really too
low.
</P>
<P>
   ``America acquiesces to the role of Mideast military policeman
at a taxpayer expense that exceeds $100 billion, according to the
Center for Defense Information. If we Americans insist on having
our SUVs and car-centric ways, we should pay the true ongoing cost
of this increasing Mideast oil flow dependency.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Geopolitics: If the military existed solely to protect
U.S. energy interests in the Middle East, this view would make more
sense. The military, however, exists to protect myriad American
interests that go far beyond defending against foreign attackers. A
secure supply of petroleum is but one of those interests.
Maintaining a military is part of the geopolitical overhead cost
that goes with being a powerful nation.
</P>
<P>
   Keep them cards and letters comin', hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
